<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-herskowitz </SLUG>
 column-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   Timing isn't right &QL; 
for Jordan to leave
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SO Phil Jackson has confirmed what he had been saying all along: He
is out of there, gone as the bearded guru of the Chicago Bulls,
content to be an ex-coach for at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   The search to replace him began Tuesday, but it isn't likely the
Bulls will find a more perfect fit than the coach with the big
shoulders in the City of Big Shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   How much credit Jackson deserves for shaping the NBA's last
empire isn't clear, but he is surely due more than most observers
will give him. He kept the Bulls hungry, kept them together, and
best of all, he let them be whoever they were. The Bulls seemed to
enjoy his occasional references to Eastern philosophy, his yen for
Zen.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves with a record that defies criticism, six world titles
in this decade. He coached for nine seasons, not a number that
would offend those who favor term limits. But he left in his own
good time.
</P>
<P>
   Now the fans of the team, and the fans of grace and glory, can
only pray that Michael Jordan doesn't follow him into the twilight
zone. The strong conviction here is that Michael will not. It never
made sense to us that he would connect his plans, his future, to
the whims of his coach. Yes, they have been friends and comrades,
but they were never joined at the hip. They didn't use the same
hairstylist.
</P>
<P>
   He's still got game
</P>
<P>
   Would a new coach treat Jordan with any less respect or
gratitude? Would he use him as a decoy so the Bulls could get the
ball to Luc Longley?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, as you may recall, Michael was able to separate himself
from Phil once before, when he went off to make the world safe for
minor-league baseball. His sudden goodbye, in 1993, wasn't
described as a mere retirement. It was analyzed like the breakup of
the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   I don't believe he is ready to put us through that again. You
saw his face this week on the cover of Time. There is Mike the
legend, Mike the symbol of the NBA's wealth and international
reach, and Mike the growth industry, known on Wall Street as Air
Jordan. If he quit this time, never to return, what would be the
impact on all the companies that hitched their wagons to his
frequent-flier club? What would become of all those kids who want
to be like Mike? Where do they go to retire?
</P>
<P>
   They would learn, as all of us eventually must, that life goes
on.
</P>
<P>
   But the best guess is that Jordan will remain with the Bulls and
play one or two more seasons, even without Jackson &LR; v R-$+&AMP;$,,
R'-+WH05kW-YHT.nR,
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
