<HEADLINE>
BRAVES BEAT YANKEES, 7-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Orlando Hernandez has been a hungry learner since
joining the New York Yankees, absorbing the English language,
adapting his style of dress and his humor to that of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, the Atlanta Braves taught him a lesson on the
sophistication of advance scouting.
</P>
<P>
   Sorting through Hernandez's assortment of arm angles and
pitches, the Braves consistently attacked him in the same way and
chased him from the mound after three and two-thirds innings as
they beat El Duque and the Yankees, 7-2, before 54,775 fans at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez forced home on walks two of the six runs he allowed
and lost his first decision, in his fourth big league start. Tom
Glavine, who makes a habit of winning the day after the Braves
lose, pitched eight innings and gave up both Yankee runs.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the Yankees flew to Atlanta, where they will
begin a two-game series on Wednesday night, with the Yankees' David
Cone (9-2) pitching against Kevin Millwood (9-3).
</P>
<P>
   The baseball that Hernandez played in Cuba was highly
competitive and refined, judging by his quick transition to the
major leagues. But the conditions were relatively spartan there,
and in the international competition in which Hernandez thrived;
teams did not possess the scouting resources teams have in the big
leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was signed by the Yankees too late in spring training
to pitch in exhibitions, to give the Braves a chance to see him in
Florida. But in preparing for Hernandez, the Braves could have
relied on the reports of advance scouts or videotape. Chipper
Jones, their third baseman, referred to the use of videotape on
Tuesday afternoon in discussing his preparation for Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   After the Cuban right-hander's first two starts, an American
League advance scout said he could find no discernible pattern in
Hernandez, that he was unique because he could throw his curveball
for strikes consistently. But it appeared on Tuesday night as if
the Braves had identified a method of attack against Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   They often ignored his fastball and his changeup, pitches
Hernandez likes to throw outside the strike zone in the hope
opposing batters will hack at them. But when Hernandez threw his
curveball _ the one pitch he consistently throws for strikes _
Atlanta batters usually swung, like dive-bombing hawks. With a part
of his camouflage gone, Hernandez became more and more passive in
his approach, eventually capitulating.
</P>
<P>
   The first three Atlanta hitters made out on curveballs, Curtis
Pride taking a called third strike and the other two putting the
ball in play as Hernandez got through the first inning with only 10
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But the left-handed Ryan Klesko singled to left with one out in
the second and the right-handed Javy Lopez leaned over the plate
and whacked a sidearm fastball into the right-field corner, Klesko
stopping at third. Hernandez spun a curveball to Michael Tucker,
who slapped it to left-center, to score Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez still had a grip on this game _ the score was tied,
1-1, for Derek Jeter had homered in the Yankee first against
Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, however, walked Ozzie Guillen, Atlanta's No. 9
hitter, to open the third inning. Pride pulled a curveball through
the first-base hole, Guillen hustling around second and sliding
into third. Hernandez tried a curveball with a 2-2 count on Keith
Lockhart, who chopped it to second, allowing Guillen to score.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, it was as if Hernandez had recognized
Atlanta's approach, for he threw mostly fastballs and changeups,
and Atlanta's hitters wouldn't bite. When Hernandez walked Lopez to
put runners at first and second with nobody out, a collective
grumble began encircling Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker struck out on three pitches, but when Andruw Jones swung
at the first pitch _ a curveball _ and grounded it to third, Scott
Brosius fumbled the ball, the error loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez then walked Guillen to force home the Braves' third
run. With Pride at the plate, Hernandez and his catcher, Jorge
Posada, seemed at odds several times on what to throw. Pride twice
called for time before one pitch, and Posada swiped at the dirt
with his bare hand, apparently in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez then walked Pride, forcing home another run, and
Atlanta led, 4-1. Lockhart struck out, but Chipper Jones lined a
fastball to center, two runs scoring.
</P>
<P>
   El Duque was done for the night, having allowed six hits, four
walks and six runs in three and two-thirds innings. Glavine cruised
through the final innings to make his record 10-3. Atlanta rolled
to its 51st victory, matching the Yankees' total.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez hardly seemed disheartened afterward, answering
questions contritely, admitting that he did not throw enough
strikes, seeming confident that he could make adjustments in his
next start against the New York Mets on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learn from my losses, not my wins,'' he said. ``I'm not
worried or disappointed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
