<SLUG> BC-BBO-ARATON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FORGET ABOUT IT, GEORGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, re-editing throughout) (sw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Another night, another event, another thumbs-up
referendum on the state of George Steinbrenner's baseball team and
the stadium it reluctantly calls home.
</P>
<P>
   After 53,000 showed up at Yankee Stadium on Monday night,
another 54,775 braved the mist, the traffic, the parking and the
prices on Tuesday night to watch a suddenly erratic Orlando
Hernandez lose his first major league game, by 7-2, to Tom Glavine
and the Turnersville Braves. Big deal, Steinbrenner huffed, albeit
good-naturedly, in the Yankee clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a natural setup, with the World Series,'' he said.
``What will we do with the Phillies next week? That's more of a
test.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell us another one. Keep setting obstacles in the Bronx and
daring New Yorkers to cross them. Face it, big guy, they will build
a nuclear test site in Manhattan before they build you a ball park.
You blew it. You put together this splendid team, brimming with
homegrown stars and smart acquisitions, and nurtured by a calm,
street-smart city native.
</P>
<P>
   You say you learned that you ``can't go undefeated in
baseball,'' which you proved by not overreacting after losing in
the playoffs last October. Now New York loves your talented Yankees
for what they stand for, for their international flavor. Fans are
visiting the Stadium at a near-record pace that will only improve
with the kids out of school. By the end of the season, your cries
and those of the mayor for a park on the West Side of Manhattan
will sound like so much whistling in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   In your advancing age, you have become too smart for your own
good, even if you did get yourself stuck in two hours' worth of
traffic after landing at Newark International Airport from Tampa,
Fla., on Monday night in the middle of rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw what some of these people have to go through to get to
the games,'' Steinbrenner said. ``You have to love the Yankees to
do that, and they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Spotting a couple of children in Yankee caps in the next car, he
recounted, ``I rolled down the window and said, `Don't worry, they
ain't starting until I get there.'''
</P>
<P>
   He's still the Boss, but these children, Steinbrenner said,
didn't even know who he was, and why would they? While busily
romancing Mayor Rudolph Giuliani these past few years, he has
surrendered the spotlight, allowed his players to be the only stars
of his baseball team, and they have authored the most feel-good
story of the decade in New York sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any bad apples, no one barking at the manager,
and that's why people like this team,'' Darryl Strawberry said. ``I
know that we have a feeling like the Chicago Bulls have _ the
unity, knowing how to play, how to win, that you don't panic. We've
won a World Series, been together a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the Braves visit baseball's 24-hour supermarket for rich
teams sometime this summer, the Yankees are more charismatic,
deeper and have the superior bullpen. As the 20th century nears its
end, we have reached the point where Steinbrenner's franchise is
one of the game's most reliably stable, the one El Duque and Hideki
Irabu chose over all others. The Yankees are closer to what the
Dodgers were until Rupert Murdoch took over in Los Angeles and the
era of television executives bypassing the general manager to make
multiplayer trades commenced.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Foxies have fired a Dodger manager, for the first
time in 45 years, and jettisoned an accomplished general manager
along with him, there is a whisper circulating that they want to
ditch the elegant Dodger uniforms next, for ones that would be
easier to market to ``X-Files'' America. By the time Murdoch is
done, Steinbrenner's respect for history and tradition will be
compared to Wimbledon's. Sooner or later, he will realize he isn't
getting the Manhattan stadium, that it would be insane to go to New
Jersey, that luxury boxes, a Metro North train stop, improved
access and parking will solve his worst riddles. He will embrace
the Bronx, reinvent himself as a Robin Hood of sports.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Steinbrenner will continue to insult New York
by comparing it to Cleveland and Baltimore, limp tourist towns that
fill their parks to watch underfinanced opponents playing on life
support. New York doesn't buy that scam as easily, never has. Or as
Strawberry said: ``New York fans always come out for the teams that
can almost compete with us.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 107,000 came to the Bronx to watch the Yanks and the
Braves split two games the last two nights, despite Steinbrenner's
insistence that ``people do not come up here for midweek night
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Go tell that to the Mets. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
