<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASORDA SAYS TENURE DEPENDS ON FACTORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Tom Lasorda has always had interest in one day
being the general manager of the Dodgers. But since he is now 70,
he might prefer that his GM days are short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   That issue was just one of many topics that Lasorda touched on
in his second day on his new job. He said he plans on making some
personnel changes and has talked to other clubs, but he wouldn't
pinpoint the areas where the team needs improvement. Also, he
vehemently denied a report that he was trying to get former manager
Bill Russell fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, age is a factor,'' said Lasorda on Tuesday. ``I feel
great, but we have to get someone a lot younger in here. I'm just
trying to get this team in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I am doing the job because they asked me to. If
they ask me at the end of the season to stay, I'm doing a good job
and I'm feeling well, I'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Avila visits: Dodgers vice president Ralph Avila, who
oversees operations in the Dominican Republic, was expected to make
a short visit to Los Angeles. But after the death of Al Campanis on
Sunday, Avila will attend the funeral Friday, help out Lasorda and
team president Bob Graziano and probably won't depart until this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Avila, who is in his 28th season with the organization, arrived
in L.A. on Monday afternoon following a 12-hour flight from Taiwan,
where he was helping the Sinon Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason that I wanted to stay here was for Al's
funeral,'' said Avila, who has been instrumental in signing such
players as Ramon Martinez and Raul Mondesi. ``But in the meantime,
I can help Tommy or Graziano in any capacity they need.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Wilton's OK: Wilton Guerrero wanted out as a Dodger. But
after being recalled from Triple-A Albuquerque on Monday, the
23-year-old infielder has changed his tune.
</P>
<P>
   After learning he was being demoted to Triple-A on May 16, he
was very upset and asked for a trade. A member of the Dodgers
organization also said that infielder Alex Cora was promoted from
Triple-A in early June because Guerrero refused to come back.
</P>
<P>
   While Guerrero admitted that he let his emotions get the best of
him, he also said he didn't refuse to return to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it was tough. But I had to get used to it because it
was out of my control,'' said Guerrero, whose comments in Spanish
were translated. ``But it was hard. Yes, I was emotional, but I am
here now. I was mad and (the trade comments) were the first thing
that came to my mind. I'm just trying to forget about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Scioscia looks ahead: Dodgers coach Mike Scioscia has dreams
of one day managing on the major-league level. And now that it
doesn't seem likely that it will happen in Los Angeles, he will
likely be open to looking elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't pick where you want to manage,'' he said. ``But when
the opportunity comes and you like the environment, that's your
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Etc: Former Dodgers general manager Fred Claire is holding a
press conference this afternoon at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel in
Pasadena.... Third baseman Bobby Bonilla, who was placed on the
15-day disabled list with a intestinal infection Saturday, is
continuing to improve. He is expected to be at Dodger Stadium
today.... Albuquerque coach Jon Debus will manage the Dukes until a
replacement is named.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
