<HEADLINE>
GROUP MOVES TO BLOCK REFUSAL TO LIST GOSHAWK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Citing more than 300 scientific reports that back them up,
environmentalists moved Tuesday in federal court to reverse the
federal government's refusal to list the Northern goshawk as an
endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what she called the ``best available science,'' U.S.
Fish and Wildlife Service Director Jamie Rappaport Clark said she
believes her refusal Monday to protect the goshawk will _ on the
third try _ stand up in court.
</P>
<P>
   Twice before, a federal judge in Tucson has struck down similar
refusals by Clark's agency to place the goshawk on the endangered
species list, and twice the judge has ordered the federal
government to redo its studies.
</P>
<P>
   Clark called her agency's most recent study the first analysis
of goshawks throughout the West. She said her biologists were
unanimous in their recommendations. Their review showed there are
nearly 3,200 goshawk territories in the 11 Western states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the best available data provided to our scientists,
we found no conclusive evidence of a declining population trend for
the goshawk in the forested West,'' said Clark, a biologist who
took over the agency last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would put any one and every one of those biologists on the
stand to defend their recommendations,'' she said during a
nationwide conference call with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   They'll likely get their chance, said Kieran Suckling, executive
director of the Southwest Center for Biological Diversity, which
immediately filed notice in federal court of its intent to block
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen a more outrageous squashing of an endangered
species than this decision,'' said Suckling, whose Tucson group and
six other environmental organizations first petitioned the
government to list the goshawk in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Suckling said he has compiled 360 studies documenting the
virtual disappearance of goshawks from forests in Southern
California and western Oregon and Washington, as well as their
decline in Arizona, New Mexico and Idaho near Yellowstone National
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Suckling also disagreed with Clark's assertion that goshawks are
not dependent on old-growth forests, those few remaining areas not
already logged at least once that are favored by many endangered
species.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is just incredible. There are literally dozens of studies
that show that goshawks are closely associated with old-growth
forests. That is so off the wall that I don't think we'll have any
trouble convincing a judge that this decision was just politics,
through and through,'' Suckling said.
</P>
<P>
   Fish and Wildlife also refused to list the goshawk as endangered
in 1992 and 1996. Both times the agency was overruled by senior
Judge Richard Bilby of the U.S. District Court in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent ruling last year, Bilby chastised the Fish
and Wildlife Service goshawk decisions as ``arbitrary, capricious
and unlawful'' and ``an abuse of (Fish and Wildlife's)
discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said her decision not to list the goshawk was based, in
part, on new guidelines by the U.S. Forest Service designed to
prevent logging _ especially clear-cuts _ from eliminating goshawk
habitat.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the Arizona Game and Fish Department argued in a
150-page report that those Forest Service guidelines actually would
devastate forest habitats in Arizona, especially north of the Grand
Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish predicted that the Forest Service policy would
enable timber companies to eliminate old-growth and result in
forests of small, young, fire-prone trees.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a University of Arizona ecologist, Martin
Taylor, concluded in a report that, since the Forest Service
guideline took effect in 1992, ``goshawk populations have declined
sharply in the south and central West,'' and the goshawk should be
protected as endangered. &QL; 
 &UR; Steve Yozwiak can be reached at 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
