<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIES FLATTEN RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-PHILLIES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How soon we forget from whence Derek Lowe has come. Maybe we
simply expect too much.
</P>
<P>
   Inexperience again haunted the Red Sox rookie righthander in a
3-2 loss to the Philadelphia Phillies Tuesday night at Fenway Park.
Seeking his first victory since June 23, 1997, Lowe was given a 2-0
lead in the fifth inning. But it wasn't to be as he coughed up
three runs in the sixth. Like butter sliding down a stack of
pancakes, Lowe melted. And now he is 0-6 in nine starts this
season. It all happened so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   First he gave up a solo home run to Scott Rolen, which is no
disgrace. But after getting the next two batters, he allowed four
straight batters to reach. Two of them scored.
</P>
<P>
   That's unacceptable, even for a 25-year-old pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that,'' said Lowe. ``That's obvious. I didn't shut
them down and we lost. All I can do is blame myself. I'm the one
that's doing it. Blame me.''
</P>
<P>
   No need to do that. Most nights it takes more than two runs to
win at Fenway. Philadelphia's Mark Portugal had as much to do with
the result as Lowe. The Sox got to him for two runs in the fifth,
but that was all he gave them in his first complete game in almost
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Troy O'Leary and John Valentin touched Portugal for back-to-back
doubles for one run, and with one out, Valentin scored on a
perfectly executed squeeze bunt by Mike Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox threatened in the sixth, putting runners on second
and third with one out. Midre Cummings led with a single, and after
Reggie Jefferson struck out, Nomar Garciaparra doubled off the
wall. So what did Portugal do? He listened intently to pitching
coach Galen Cisco in a brief mound conference, then struck out both
Mo Vaughn and O'Leary, the heart of the Red Sox lineup these days.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Sox couldn't touch him. He retired nine of the
next 10 batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope (Lowe) paid close attention to what Portugual did after
Nomar got a double,'' said Sox pitching coach Joe Kerrigan. ``He
didn't fool around with Vaughn and O'Leary up. He shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Derek is developing and growing. But I think we have to teach
him that mentality, especially if your team scores. Mostly, that
comes from experience. But it starts by having the right mentality.
Keep the momentum in your dugout. That's what you have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   After Rolen's home run brought the Phillies within 2-1, Lowe got
two outs. But then he walked Bobby Abreu and hit Kevin Jordan with
a pitch. Abreu came home on a single by Mark Lewis, and Desi
Relaford brought home Jordan with a single to left.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe finished the inning, but despite strong bullpen work by
newly acquired Carlos Reyes (two innings) and Rich Garces, the Sox
lost the second game of this unusual four-game series, which
continues tonight in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Lowe must step it up a notch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is about wins,'' he said. ``You can have a good ERA,
but the bottom line is getting wins, and I don't have one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
