<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
21-YEAR TERM IN '97 BEATING, RAPE AND ARSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA HARKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Libby Siegling could contain her anguish no longer.
</P>
<P>
   Her wails grew louder in Maricopa County Superior Court on
Tuesday as she struggled to describe the suffering her daughter had
endured. Last year, Brian Christopher White raped and beat her
daughter and stomped on her head over and over again, leaving
imprints of his shoes on her face.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting near Siegling was her daughter, Melissa, who once
dreamed of being a chef.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Father's Day, she had to have help making pancakes,'' said
Siegling, whose choked-up speech had broken down into yells and
gasps.
</P>
<P>
   Siegling apologized to Judge Barbara Jarrett three times as her
crying became more uncontrollable.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both the victim's and the defendant's families _ both
men and women _ sobbed throughout Tuesday's sentencing hearing.
</P>
<P>
   White buried his face in his handcuffed hands, one of which
clutched a a wadded white tissue. His close-cropped dark hair
showed scars of the head injuries he'd suffered as a child.
</P>
<P>
   White's family and fiancee testified that he'd never been
violent before. And White himself told the judge that he'd taken
out on Melissa the rage built up inside him from his abusive
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   But Jarrett called the crime ``cruel, heinous and depraved.''
She sentenced him to 21 years in prison and lifetime probation for
attempted first-degree murder, attempted sexual assault and arson _
for burning Melissa's car.
</P>
<P>
   White met with Melissa last June when he walked into a
``swinger's'' club called Encounters, in an industrial area near
30th and Clarendon avenues.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa, a waitress at the Phoenix club, recognized White from
junior high school. Witnesses told police they saw Melissa talking
to an obviously drunk man with whom she later left in her car.
</P>
<P>
   When White demanded sex, Melissa refused and pulled into a
parking lot, court records say. There he sexually assaulted her and
strangled her, then stomped on her head and body as many as 50
times, her mother said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   White drove her to the 10800 block of West Campbell Avenue and
dumped her in an area covered with gravel and prickly-pear cactus.
Still, Melissa lived.
</P>
<P>
   A man who took his dogs out for a walk in the early morning
heard her groans and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   After almost slipping away three times, she came out of a coma
after two weeks in the hospital. Since then, Melissa has undergone
numerous surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, she walked haltingly before the judge and read some
statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still cannot understand why someone would do something like
that to me,'' said Melissa, 21, who cannot remember any details of
the night. ``I struggle daily to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   She began to cry, but no tears came because her ducts no longer
function. She's lost feeling in her left leg, and has lost much of
her ability to retain memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to hold on so tight to my memories,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Siegling said, she drills Melissa on questions to answer
for job interviews, but her daughter can't remember the questions
from day to day.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa works 16 hours a week at a discount department store,
the only job she's been able to get, her stepfather said. He said
he quit his job at Intel due to depression.
</P>
<P>
   He's also had to prevent his wife from killing herself, he said.
</P>
<P>
   White's lawyer, Michael Hruby, asked that his client be given
the minimum sentence of 15 years. White's sister, mother and
stepfather tearfully testified to the abuse the boy suffered at the
hands of his drunken parents. As they spoke, White cried, rocked
back and forth in his chair and hung his head.
</P>
<P>
   Before being sentenced, White, 23, told the judge he was sorry.
He didn't ask for mercy, but blamed his problems on alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the crime, he said, his older brother told him
that he had assaulted him as a child. That pushed him over the
edge, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to live anymore,'' White said. ``I was trying to
drink myself to death. . . . She didn't deserve anything I did to
her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Melissa to know I will spend the rest of my life trying
to make up for what I did.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Victoria Harker can be reached at 444-8058 or at
victoria.harker &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
