A3651 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSY-ECON-OUTLOOK-LAD     06-24 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSY-ECON-OUTLOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA ECONOMY TO CONTINUE ON A ROLL, UCLA SURVEY SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- California's economy, robust enough to shrug off
a withering financial calamity in Asia, should continue on a strong
growth curve through 2000, according to a widely watched survey.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly projection by the UCLA Anderson Forecast, to be
released today, predicts that job gains in the state through 2000
will rival the strongest spurts of the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   And it concludes that, during the first five months this year,
Southern California's economy grew at a brisker clip than Northern
California's for the first time in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Particularly heartening to us is the strong expansion in
Southern California, which is now growing apace with the San
Francisco Bay Area,'' said Tom Lieser, the forecasting project's
executive director and author of the California report.
</P>
<P>
   Through 2000, the number of jobs in the state will grow at a 2.8
percent rate by about 370,000 annually, gains in real income will
average about 4 percent, and the unemployment rate will fall to 5.4
percent, the university's economists predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Every sector should add jobs, with especially strong
performances turned in by the apparel industry, businesses services
and the tourism and amusement industries.
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that government figures indicate employment in
the entertainment industry stopped expanding in 1997 and so far
this year as corporate jobs were shed to cut costs. But official
surveys, such as the monthly poll conducted by the state and
federal government, underestimate what is happening outside the
corporate realm, the UCLA report says.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA economists estimate that employment in motion pictures and
television has reached 170,000 jobs, with an additional 20,000
likely over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tone of this forecast is very much the tone we had back in
April,'' said Ted Gibson, chief economist for the California
Department of Finance. ``It's a perfectly reasonable outlook, and
it's one that has a good chance of coming true.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA said the public sector's balance sheet is the best way to
gauge private sector performance. By that measure, things are going
well, as evident in the state government's $4.4 billion surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The state is even weathering the roiling financial crisis in
Asia, the UCLA report noted.
</P>
<P>
   While exports to six Asian countries fell a combined $1.8
billion during the past four quarters, that drop was more than
offset by gains in exports to Mexico, the Netherlands, Australia
and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weakness of export trade with Asia (has) been surprisingly
mild in reports for the second half of 1997, when the turmoil was
perhaps most intense,'' Lieser said. ``The concern over Japan is
(still) warranted because if anything could kill California it
would be a worsening of our business with Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kyser, chief economist at the Los Angeles County Economic
Development Corp., said the Asian economic cycle could still do
some damage in the Golden State before running its course. So far,
the crisis has caused more financial pain in the Central Valley
farm industry and Northern California's high-tech sector than in
the Southland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Asia is unfolding in slow-motion fashion,'' Kyser
said. ``Right now, though, everything looks good for California.
We've had a whole lot of green lights, but I have seen an
occasional yellow caution out there we have to be very aware of.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some highlights of the UCLA Anderson Forecast as the
state heads into the next century:
</P>
<P>
   --Despite a harsh winter, construction employment rose by 10
percent over the past 12 months. About 60,000 new construction jobs
should be added over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   --The apparel industry continues to add jobs despite pressure
from lower-wage areas, primarily Mexico. These jobs, which are
concentrated in the Los Angeles area, should grow by 5 percent this
year and next.
</P>
<P>
   --While the aerospace industry has experienced job losses, it
still attracts lots of subcontract work and should continue to gain
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   --The growth of high-technology electronics jobs, which grew by
19 percent between 1995 and 1997, has rapidly slowed. The forecast
is for annual growth rates of 3.4 percent, 2.3 percent and 1.7
percent from now through 2000.
</P>
<P>
   --Business services are the giant of California industries, with
more than 1.1 million jobs. The number of these jobs will expand by
nearly 6 percent over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   --Wholesale and retail trade will be a strong growth sector.
Total employment will rise 2.7 percent through 2000.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
