<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BUSY ON PHONES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Will the Los Angeles Lakers once again upstage the
Clippers, even on draft day?
</P>
<P>
   No other team was busier Tuesday than the Lakers, according to
several sources, who said the team was enthusiastically working the
phones in an attempt to work a deal by today's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver, the site of the draft, was buzzing with talk that the
Lakers were offering Eddie Jones, Nick Van Exel and Elden Campbell
to the Grizzlies, if point guard Mike Bibby is available at the No.
2 spot.
</P>
<P>
   According to a source, the Lakers have made a similar offer to
the Clippers, who own the draft's top pick. Vancouver general
manager Stu Jackson denied that a trade would be made with the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lakers would never do that for the No. 2 pick,'' Jackson
said. ``Someone's sabotaging the Laker organization if they would
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers did not respond to several messages seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have also reportedly offered Campbell and Van Exel to
the Washington Wizards for small forward Juwan Howard.
</P>
<P>
   A deal of some sort seems likely, because of the Lakers' desire
to rid themselves of Van Exel, who has been in and out of the
doghouse for the past three seasons. The Boston Celtics have
reportedly turned down an offer of Van Exel straight up for
ex-Laker Travis Knight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some possibilities to move up (in the draft), and it
has to make sense,'' Lakers general manager Mitch Kupchak said.
``Obviously, we've run across nothing to date that makes sense,
because we haven't done anything.''
</P>
<P>
   In order for Vancouver to swing the deal with the Lakers, they
would need the Clippers to pass on Bibby with the top pick and
instead select Pacific center Michael Olowokandi. That seemed at
least a 50-50 prospect Tuesday, as the Clippers have taken a more
serious look at Olowokandi, who is considered to have the most
potential of any player in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers brought Olowokandi in for a second workout last
weekend, dragging him all the way across the country from a Friday
workout in Boston. This has fueled growing speculation that they
will pass on Bibby, who seemed certain to be the pick for several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, for one, continued to lobby for the idea that
Olowokandi is just too good for any team _ including the Clippers _
to pass up. Of course, some of this might be the normal smoke
screens teams try to put up to hide their player preferences. But
the Bibby camp does appear to be nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby's agent, David Falk, had lunch with Clippers owner Donald
Sterling on Tuesday and Falk has made it known he wants Bibby in
Los Angeles. It's doubtful they would have met if the Clippers had
already decided to select Bibby.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers definitely don't want to upset Falk. He also
represents Michael Jordan, Howard, Alonzo Mourning and Allen
Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   Falk instructed Bibby not to answer questions regarding specific
cities during a Tuesday press conference, an order that was not in
place on Monday, when Bibby freely answered questions in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers just might feel that Olowokandi is too much to pass
up, even if it takes a year or two for him to develop. Especially
when free-agent center Isaac Austin is not certainty to return next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Elgin Baylor, the Clippers vice president of basketball
operations, said he has received a lot of phone calls regarding the
top pick. And in Sacramento, there were reports the Kings offered
Chris Webber and the No. 7pick in exchange for the Clippers' top
pick.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to a lot of intrigue for a draft that is devoid
of a franchise player, or even a consensus No. 1 pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a unique draft,'' Boston coach Rick Pitino said.
``Normally, you know 1 through 5 or 1 through 8. But 10 could be as
good as 1 and 12 could be as good as 2. I see a big dropoff after
13.'' &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
