 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, June 24.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-REPORT (Geneva) _ AIDS infection rates worldwide are far
worse than previously believed, particularly in parts of Africa
where as many as one in four adults has the virus, according to a
U.N. report. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (Beijing) _ At home, President Clinton's fortunes
may wax and wane, but here on the eve of his first state visit to
China, he is already a star. Not only in the official press but
also among elements of the intelligentsia, he is being lionized as
a great statesman who had the wisdom to change his mind about
China. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PIRACY (Shanghai) _ The authorities have begun a crackdown
on many of the illegal activities that are ordinarily tolerated
these days, like the sale of pirated video and music compact disks.
The fight against piracy of software, music and movies, an issue
that loomed large in China-U.S. relations a few years ago, has been
pushed in the background and is unlikely to be raised seriously
during President Clinton's visit, even though it remains as rampant
a problem as ever. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-U.S.-ASSESS (Washington) _ The Clinton administration has
tried to minimize its direct involvement in Asia's economic crisis,
pulling strings at the International Monetary Fund, sending out
envoys to cajole foreign leaders and avoiding the lead role
Washington took when it saved Mexico from economic implosion in
1995. But as President Clinton prepares to leave for China, the
Asian crisis, in the words of one of Clinton's top aides, is
becoming ``worse and worse every day,'' and it is becoming far more
difficult for the leader of the world's largest economy to deal
with it at a distance. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ALBANIANS (Klina, Serbia) _ In recent days the rebels have
changed their strategy and begun to attack and kidnap Serbian
civilians in an apparent effort to drive them out of their villages
in the overwhelmingly Albanian province of Kosovo in southern
Serbia. Until now the rebel group, the Kosovo Liberation Army, has
avoided attacking Serbian civilians, despite the deaths of scores
of ethnic Albanian civilians, including more than 20 children. But
in the last few days, five Serbian villages and many small hamlets
and farms in the agricultural region around Klina have been seized
by armed rebels. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FEATHERED-FOSSILS (Undated) _ Paleontologists examining
fossils from animals bearing feathers think they have found the
most persuasive evidence yet that birds evolved directly from
small, meat-eating dinosaurs. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   REPORTERS-PROSECUTORS (Undated) _ It is one of the least talked
about corners of journalism: the relationship of reporters and
their prosecution sources. But the debate in recent days over how
much and what kind of information the independent counsel Kenneth
W. Starr gave reporters about his investigation of the president
has put an uncomfortable spotlight on the ties between journalists
and prosecutors, which often lead to information, and sometimes, to
misinformation. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FIRES (Miami) _ Desert-like dryness and heat have led to one
of the worst outbreaks of wildfires in Florida in more than 50
years. The blazes have destroyed more than 100 homes and
structures, damaged an estimated $10 million in commercial timber
and left a smoky haze in cities such as Jacksonville, Daytona
Beach, Tallahassee and Orlando. The dry conditions have caused an
additional $100 million in damage to corn, hay, soybean,
watermelon, peanut, cotton and tobacco crops. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MISSILES _ Inside a command bunker at a launch center in
southern China, U.S. military monitors watched a Chinese rocket
streak toward space carrying a $200 million American communications
satellite. But 22 seconds after liftoff on Feb. 15, 1996, the Long
March rocket exploded, showering fiery debris, burning fuel and
chaos on a nearby Chinese village, where by American accounts as
many as 200 civilians were killed. For five hours, Chinese
authorities barred them from rushing to the crash site, purportedly
for their own safety. When the Americans finally reached the area
and opened the satellite's battered but intact control box, a
supersecret encoded circuit board was missing. Now congressional
investigators are asking whether there could be any explanation for
the missing technology other than that the Chinese took it. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ASSESS _ What Tuesday's ruling means for the future of
Microsoft and its Windows operating system. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   SMALLCAP-MARKETPLACE _ A rising tide lifts only big boats. Ask
any investor who owns small-capitalization stocks. He will tell you
that the old saw about bull markets levitating all stocks no longer
holds true. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   TEMP-EXECS _ Not everyone wants the typical trappings that come
with lengthy tenure in the upper reaches of corporate America. Many
executives, no longer enamored of steady management jobs, are
signing up to be, in effect, temps. By Adam Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   GM-MEXICO (Matamoros, Mexico) _ GM's shift of production from
Flint and Saginaw to this border city facing Brownsville, Texas,
was part of a sweeping 20-year transfer of its U.S auto parts
industry south across the border. Since 1978, GM has built more
than 50 parts factories in Mexico, which today employ 72,000
workers, making its auto parts subsidiary, Delphi Automotive
Services, Mexico's largest private employer. Many other American
companies, of course, have also moved plants to Mexico. By Sam
Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   FORECAST-AD-COLUMN _ Remember the disk jockeys who shouted,
``And the hits just keep on coming!''on the old Top 40 radio
stations? Well, the rosy predictions for domestic advertising
spending just keep on coming from a leading industry forecaster. By
Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ American Express plans to buy blocks
of airline seats to Europe on Continental and Virgin Atlantic for
resale to corporate clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD-SMITH (Undated) _ Details of Anna Deavere Smith's new
institute at Harvard. By Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   SENEGAL-SINGER (Undated) _ Arts Abroad: A look at the Senegalese
singer Youssou N'Dour.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd imagines a conversation
inside Al Gore's head.
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Frank Rich looks at the real Ozzie and
Harriet Nelson and their effect on American culture.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBO-ARATON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column: Have
the Yankees and Dodgers switched places? The once tumultuous Bronx
Bombers seem like the picture of stability, while the Dodgers, long
the emblem of tradition and order, are going through upheaval. By
Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COOKING-SCHOOLS (New York) _ A pile of carrots, turnips, onions,
shallots, lettuce leaves and potatoes lay on a stainless-steel
table at the French Culinary Institute's teaching kitchen. My
mission, on this first day of La Technique, the institute's basic
course for amateur chefs, was to turn those vegetables into
textbook examples of the basic French cuts. My goal was to test the
basic-skill courses offered by New York's top cooking schools: the
French Culinary Institute, Peter Kump's School of Culinary Arts and
the culinary arts division of the New School. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   COOKING-CIA (New York) _ It used to be that if you wanted to
become a chef, you were expected to go to cooking school in Paris.
There you learned classic technique, the organization of the French
kitchen, and discipline under the critical eye of French
instructors. And when you returned to America, you were practically
guaranteed to land a job at a top restaurant. But over the last
decade, the culinary world changed. Cuisines fused, and American
kitchens were transformed from French food factories into dens of
creativity. Nowhere is the break with the past clearer than in a
comparison of the most influential school in the United States, the
Culinary Institute of America in Hyde Park, N.Y., with its
counterpart in France, Le Cordon Bleu in Paris. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   COOKING-GRADS (New York) _ By the time Matthew Laux completed a
two-year program last March at the New England Culinary Institute _
after paying nearly $40,000 for an education that encompasses all
aspects of the food service industry _ he had earned his reward: a
job at Trois Jean, a New York bistro, where he peeled and chopped
vegetables 12 hours a day, six days a week. For this, he received
the munificent sum of $65 a shift. The food service industry is
booming nationally, and students who complete a culinary school
education will almost certainly have a career ahead of them. But
they may not have a life. By Eric Asimov.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CIPRIANI (New York) _ To most New Yorkers, the name Cipriani
means just the boutique restaurant in the Sherry-Netherland that
his father, Arrigo, opened in 1985 and where they serve the Bellini
cocktails invented at Harry's Bar in Venice (started by Giuseppi
Cipriani's grandfather in 1931). But that profile is about to get a
lot higher. By Florence Fabricanbt.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-OPERA (Undated) _ Using wine labels, the sommelier at
Harry's Bar in London makes collages that depict opera scenes
involving wine. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   HANMADE-MOZZARELLA (New York) _ Mezzogiorno, Tribeca Grill and
Bice are among the restaurants that want handmade, tender
mozzarella that tastes and smells as pure as it looks. They all
rely on the early morning visits of Giuseppe Cuomo, a traveling
mozzarella maker. His family has done the same for three
generations in southern Italy, and Cuomo, 52, continued the
tradition after he moved here 20 years ago. By Suzanne Hamlin.
</P>
<P>
   GARLIC-BROTH (Undated) _ In this season of good vegetables and
good garlic, soups based on a meatless garlic broth are a pleasure.
By Barbara Kafka.
</P>
