<SLUG> BC-WHISTLEBLOWER-FIRED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTRICT FIRES OFFICIAL WHO SAID SCHOOL WAS BUILT ON TOXIC SITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERRI HARDY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The head of the city schools' environmental
department says he was asked to resign just two days after he told
lawmakers that the district made a mistake when it built a middle
school on a toxic site.
</P>
<P>
   Hamid Arabzadeh, director of environmental health and safety,
said in interviews Monday and Tuesday that he knew his job was in
jeopardy before testifying before the Joint Legislative Audit
Committee about the placement of Jefferson Middle School in South
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told that if I said anything against the district, I
would be fired -- but it was important that I tell the truth,''
Arabzadeh said.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Scott Wildman, D-Glendale, who serves as chairman of
the Joint Legislative Audit Committee, is investigating whether the
resignation was sought as punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely concerned that a person testified before the
committee and then shortly thereafter was terminated,'' Wildman
said. ``If in fact there is a nexus between his testimony and his
removal from the district, I would take that to be an extremely
serious matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of meeting with a top official Monday afternoon, when
Arabzadeh expected to be fired, the health director said he went
out on medical leave for stress suffered from the push to have him
leave the district.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Unified School District spokesman Brad Sales said he
could not comment because it is a personnel matter.
</P>
<P>
   Wildman said district officials had told him that Arabzadeh's
departure was the result of other difficulties. But he declined to
provide details and said he and members of his committee staff
would look into the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues in the environmental health field said Arabzadeh is
well-respected and that his departure will be a loss to the
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very well-respected in his field. He is a straight
shooter who does not bow to pressure,'' said James Unmack, vice
president of technical operations for Weststates EHS Services, an
environmental consulting firm that meets regularly with Arabzadeh
as part of a working group of Los Angeles city and county
industrial health officials.
</P>
<P>
   At last week's legislative hearing, state officials said the
LAUSD's shoddy review had failed to detect contaminants in the land
under the school. Arabzadeh responded: ``I fully agree. It should
have been done differently.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his remarks so infuriated his superiors that the next
day he was called in and presented a letter of resignation, but he
refused to sign.
</P>
<P>
   In the less than six months that he has been on the job,
Arabzadeh said most of his efforts to increase efficiency or safety
have been stymied.
</P>
<P>
   Arabzadeh recommended against the purchase of a $350,000
electron microscope, which he said was unneeded. He also felt that
10 staff members whose work focused on analyzing asbestos samples
could have been better utilized examining health concerns in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said the asbestos analysis could be done for far
less money by an outside lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many things they did made no sense,'' Arabzadeh said. ``Our
real work should have been in safety, but it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
