</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-755&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T IS NEAR DEALL FOR NO. 2 COMPANY IN CABLE TV
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for inserts, refinements throughout)  (sw) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The AT&AMP;T Corp. is close to an agreement to acquire
the nation's second-largest cable television operator in a deal
that could sharply expand AT&AMP;T's ability to provide Internet access
and local telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between AT&AMP;T and Tele-Communications Inc. is expected
to be worth at least $25 billion in stock. A final agreement had
not been reached late Tuesday night, but a deal could be announced
as soon as Wednesday, an executive close to Tele-Communications and
an official who had been briefed on the talks said on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is seeking to acquire only Tele-Communications' cable
properties, which connect to homes, not its programming unit, which
creates television programs, said a person close to
Tele-Communications, known as TCI. Tele-Communications' programming
unit, Liberty Media, already trades as a separate stock. Its
ultimate fate is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T is prepared to pay about $50 for each share of
Tele-Communications' stock, the person said. That would represent a
premium of more than 28 percent to Tele-Communications' closing
stock price of $38.6875 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Any deal between the two companies is likely to face a rigorous
review by regulators including the Federal Communications
Commission. If the deal wins approval, it will firmly put the stamp
of C. Michael Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's new chairman, upon one of America's
most venerable corporations.
</P>
<P>
   A merger between AT&AMP;T and Tele-Communications would be the
biggest sign yet that trying to deliver high-speed access to the
Internet and other advanced services is one of the strongest
imperatives in today's business world.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Internet has emerged as a new sort of media
that could rival radio and television in its impact on the nation's
economy and culture. The technological bottleneck that has kept
cyberspace from becoming a true mass media has been the difficulty
in transmitting large amounts of digital data to everyday homes.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers gain access to the Internet at speeds a mere fraction
of those available to people in modern offices. That has kept the
process of linking to cyberspace a relatively awkward procedure in
some ways akin to using a ham radio.
</P>
<P>
   But by acquiring Tele-Communications, which serves 14.4 million
customers, AT&AMP;T would gain direct access to homes and apartments
for the first time since the leading long-distance company spun off
its local telephone operations in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The importance of the Internet to AT&AMP;T became clear last week
when news emerged that the company had engaged in preliminary
discussions to merge with America Online Inc., the nation's biggest
provider of access to cyberspace. AOL rebuffed AT&AMP;T, though the two
could still strike a marketing alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Although new telecommunications carriers boast more advanced
networks, AT&AMP;T retains a vast capacity to transmit information of
all sorts from coast to coast at lightning speeds. By merging with
Tele-Communications and gaining its many wires into homes, AT&AMP;T
would acquire an ability to bypass its own ornery progeny, the Baby
Bell local phone companies. That could allow AT&AMP;T to create an
end-to-end network that would allow the company to deliver not only
Internet data but also everyday phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   With their control of the copper telephone wires that stretch
into most every home and apartment, the Bells have appeared to have
an advantage in some ways over long-distance companies like AT&AMP;T
and MCI Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecommunications Act of 1996 cleared the way for the Bells
to enter the long-distance market once they convinced regulators
that they had opened their local networks to potential competitors.
Likewise, long-distance telephone companies won the right to
compete in local markets. The Bells have not yet won approval to
offer long-distance service, but were they to gain the go-ahead,
they could be expected to win large chunks of the long-distance
market away from traditional long-distance carriers by buying
long-distance capacity in bulk and reselling it at a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Long-distance companies like AT&AMP;T, however, would face the huge
cost of building elements of local networks on their own. Indeed,
AT&AMP;T agreed in January to acquire Teleport Communications Group
Inc., a competitive local phone company, for $11.3 billion in a bid
to jump-start that effort.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about a possible alliance between AT&AMP;T and a major
cable company has been rife in the industry for months and caused
cable stocks to rise sharply on Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The cable industry has been spending billions of dollars to
upgrade its lines to offer more data options at faster speeds. TCI
in particular has been busy upgrading the capacity and speed of its
cable systems. TCI is one of the leading companies behind At Home,
the cable industry's broadest venture to offer high-speed Internet
access to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone and cable television industries have been locked
in a battle over which sector would be first to provide high-speed
Internet access to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways an AT&AMP;T-Tele-Communications deal would represent a
return to a strategy tried by Tele-Communications' chief executive,
John Malone, in 1993, with a proposed merger with the Bell Atlantic
Corp. That deal later collapsed as visions of cable companies'
delivering phone service and telephone companies' delivering movies
into living rooms failed to take shape.
</P>
<P>
   In many respects TCI is responsible for the evolution of the
nation's cable system into what it is today. The company traces its
roots to 1956, when Bob Magness, a Texas Panhandle rancher, sold
some cattle to build his first cable TV system. Nine years later
Magness, who died in 1996, moved the company to Denver to serve
small towns in the Rocky Mountains and hired John Malone, a
32-year-old executive at General Instrument, to help him expand.
</P>
<P>
   The effort grew into a company with more than $7.5 billion in
annual sales and cable television operations in more than 40
states, Argentina, Brazil, Britain, France, Germany, Japan, Mexico
and Spain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
