<HEADER>
A3678 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-24 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS' TINKERED LINEUP COMES THROUGH FOR MOYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The lineup the Mariners put on the field Tuesday
looked a lot more like the '59 White Sox than the '27 Yankees. Five
of the starters carried batting averages of .251 or less.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a season of flailing and frustration for a club
favored to win its division. So however quirky it might have
looked, manager Lou Piniella wrote the names on a lineup card.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a different lineup out there,'' Piniella said after the
team's error-free, 5-3 victory over San Diego. Then he took a long
pause before adding, ``For what we have, this is our athletic
version.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich Amaral led off, replacing left fielder Glenallen Hill, who
has four errors and who made a perplexing baserunning gaffe in the
Monday night loss to San Diego. Amaral had two stolen bases and
scored three runs.
</P>
<P>
   Utilityman Jeff Huson, despite hitting .178, was inserted at
second for Joey Cora, whose latest defensive lapse was a popup he
let fall in right field for two critical Padre runs Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see what we do tomorrow (at second base),'' Piniella
said. ``I don't want to be pinned down to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But Piniella was happy to be pinned down about his third baseman
tonight for the first of two games in San Diego. He said it would
be Russ Davis, back from the ashes after 19 errors and a four-game
benching, during which time he got some work in left field and at
second base.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had an RBI single Tuesday but more importantly, handled
six chances at third flawlessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I'm proud of the kid,'' Piniella said. ``I was
well-pleased. He looked like a different player out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, you can do that once, you can duplicate it many times
over. He's in there tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Ducey also filled in for Jay Buhner in right field, as
Buhner continues to recover from the effects of having arthroscopic
knee surgery in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needed a day off,'' Piniella said. ``It's going to take him
awhile to get back into condition to play with any regularity.''
</P>
<P>
   The most important contributor, however, was pitcher Jamie
Moyer, who seems to go longer the older he gets. Moyer came within
three outs of a fourth complete game and a third shutout this year,
in a career that has seen only 15 complete games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been pretty consistent all year,'' said Moyer, who is now
5-6 but with a 3.58 ERA. ``But the wins haven't been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer was devilish to the Padres through eight innings, never
facing more than four in any inning. After he allowed a leadoff
single to Tony Gwynn in the ninth and a double by Greg Vaughn,
Piniella provided the 30,961 matinee fans some comic relief.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella emerged from the dugout to talk to Moyer to ask him how
he felt. With Heathcliff Slocumb warming up, the crowd, only too
wary of the frequent bullpen atrocities, booed Piniella roundly.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting lasted maybe a second, and when Piniella began the
retreat to the dugout, he doffed his cap, bringing down the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I step out of the dugout ... '' Piniella said,
trailing off. ``I was just having some fun, nothing more, nothing
less.''
</P>
<P>
   It got serious momentarily, when Ken Caminiti rifled a double to
score both runners. Piniella then went to get Slocumb, who promptly
allowed Wally Joyner's double and, after two outs, a single by
Carlos Hernandez that brought the go-ahead run to the plate.
Slocumb struck out pinch-hitter Walt Sweeney to end it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best development for Seattle was Davis, who admitted
that the left field-second base work is mostly window dressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody knows it around here, my heart's at third
base,'' Davis said. ``That's where I belong. I really don't think
too much is going to come from that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest imposed upon him, Davis said, ``They brought in
some new faces (journeyman Rico Rossi), and I have to accept it. I
have no one to blame but myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Said shortstop Alex Rodriguez, ``Russ is a good ol' Southern
boy. He works hard and has a heart of gold. Everyone is a family
member here, and you don't like to see anybody go through hard
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr.'s 29th homer in the first got the M's pointed
toward their third win in five games on the homestand. Rodriguez
had two more hits, giving him nine in his last 15 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   With five games left until the midpoint of the season, Rodriguez
has 26 homers and 18 stolen bases, which gives him a chance at the
select 40-40 club populated by only two players, Jose Canseco and
Barry Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to talk about that at all,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's Mariner starter won't be talking, either. Randy
Johnson meets one of the National League's best, Andy Ashby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
