<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MES-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DEFEAT ORIOLES, 6-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ For Bernard Gilkey, it was about time.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets' left fielder has endured a testing month. One
at-bat after snapping an 0-for-25 slide on June 12, Gilkey was hit
in the face with a fastball by Ryan Dempster of the Florida
Marlins. After singling in his first at-bat back nine days later,
Gilkey went 0 for 9. That made him 2 for 36 when he stepped to the
plate with two out and two Mets on in the seventh inning on Tuesday
night against the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey, who had not collected an extra-base hit since June 5,
nevertheless batted cleanup on Tuesday night, with the slumping
John Olerud taking a rare night off. And when Gilkey rapped a
two-run, opposite-field double to right off Arthur Rhodes, it
scored both runners, thrust the Mets ahead by 4-3 and sparked them
to a much-needed 6-3 victory over the Orioles at Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey said he knew his luck was going to change. ``Last night,
after my last at-bat, I felt pretty close,'' he said. In that
at-bat, against Mike Mussina, Gilkey worked an 0-2 count full
before grounding out hard.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey's double on Tuesday night, which highlighted a three-run
inning, erased the 3-2 lead the Orioles had taken into the bottom
of the sixth after a 1-hour-26-minute rain delay. Not only did it
spare the Mets (40-32) from losing for the sixth time in seven
games, it kept Masato Yoshii from absorbing his third straight
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost certainly a coincidence, but since the Mets
acquired Yoshii's good friend, Hideo Nomo, from the Los Angeles
Dodgers on June 4, neither Yoshii nor Nomo has won a game for the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii lasted just three and a third innings on Tuesday night.
Not counting a two-inning stint on June 2 that was cut short in
Pittsburgh because of a severe thunderstorm, Tuesday night's outing
was Yoshii's shortest as a major leaguer. Before that start, Yoshii
was 4-1 with a 2.33 earned run average. Since the Mets traded for
Nomo, Yoshii, who is 4-3 and whose era has now risen to 3.65, has
allowed 26 hits and 17 runs in 19 innings, an 8.05 era.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Nomo, who is scheduled to start Thursday night at
Shea Stadium against the Orioles, is 0-1 with a 4.50 era in three
starts with the Mets. Over all, Nomo is 2-8 with a 4.95 era, with
50 walks in 80 and two-thirds innings. And on Tuesday, a member of
another organization, one that was initially interested in
obtaining Nomo, revealed that the team had been swayed by medical
reports that Nomo had a condition similar to that of the former
Yankee prospect Eric Milton, who was found to have a
multidirectional instability in his pitching shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   In layman's terms, that is basically a laxity in the shoulder,
which creates too much flexibility _ and which might be one reason
why Nomo has struggled with his control throughout this season.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, said of Nomo's
condition: ``His shoulder's fine. There are absolutely no concerns
about his health. He was clocked at 92 his last game out. His
velocity's fine. Our doctors read the medical reports to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said laxity in the shoulder and pitching mechanics
``tend not to be related. And he has no more laxity than he had
last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no question that Nomo has struggled with his
location. What is currently wrong with Yoshii, who allowed six
hits, while walking two and striking out one, is another matter
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   But Manager Bobby Valentine said he relieved Yoshii so early
only because heavy rain was expected soon. ``Three runs wasn't
going to yank him from that game,'' Valentine said. ``The rain did.
I played it like it was the eighth inning.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets' bullpen, which has had problems of its own,
finished the job just fine. Turk Wendell, Brian Bohanon, John Hudek
(1-4), and Dennis Cook all held the Orioles scoreless from the
fourth through the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   And then John Franco nailed down his 17th save in 19 attempts by
closing out the final inning, after Rey Ordonez _ who had three
hits and made another spectacular diving play at short _ had driven
in an insurance run in the top of the eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
