<HEADLINE>
SONICS LOOK TO MAKE MOST FROM LATE DRAFT PICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Sonic war room during the past several NBA drafts
has been more like a pot on a cold stove _ not much stirring.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Sonics garnered relatively nothing from the
draft mostly because they usually owned a late first-round
selection. The Sonics won't find the next Gary Payton or Vin Baker
drafting that low again, but they believe they must make
Wednesday's draft count for something.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the biggest decisions don't have to be something like
``Want more coffee?'' Or ``Will it be Chinese food or pizza?'' Or
``Oh, by the way, trade out of the first round and send the pick to
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Several elite teams have proven that choosing late doesn't
necessarily sheild it from potentially good talent. Chicago
acquired the rights to Toni Kukoc early in the second round of the
1990 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Players such as Indiana's Antonio Davis, Charlotte's Bobby Phils
and the Los Angeles Lakers' Nick Van Exel are other examples of
belated draft picks who have turned into solid NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   The Utah Jazz have mastered the art of finding gems long after
the first-round hoopla has fizzled. The Jazz found Bryon Russell
with the 45th pick in 1993 and selected Shandon Anderson at No. 54
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Backup point guard Howard Eisley originally went 30th to
Minnesota in 1994. Eisley, Anderson and Russell were integral parts
of Utah's back-to-back NBA Finals run.
</P>
<P>
   The point is clear: Late does not always mean out of luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about this year,'' said Billy McKinney, the
Sonics' vice president of basketball operations. ``After the top
six or seven picks, (the draft) is going to be buck wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since the Sonics corralled Payton in 1990 have they
experienced a memorable draft day. Payton was an easy pick at No. 2
overall. Granted, teams that average 55-plus wins _ such as the
Sonics since selecting Payton _ do not have the luxury of selecting
that high.
</P>
<P>
   However, the general consensus from last month's pre-draft camp
in Chicago is that teams selecting in the lottery slots (1-11)
probably won't hit the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   There is a large middle ground in this draft, and the list
starts before the 10th pick is consummated. That is good for the
Sonics, who pick 27th in the first round and 32nd and 33rd in the
second. It is bad news for teams seeking a quick fix; this year's
crop is considered bland even at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona point guard Mike Bibby is expected to be taken first.
But even though he is the most skilled player in the draft, the Los
Angeles Clippers have not guaranteed they will make Bibby the No. 1
pick.
</P>
<P>
   If Bibby isn't the first pick, almost certainly it will be
Michael Olowokandi. The 7-foot-1 center from the University of the
Pacific is a project who took up the game only three years ago.
Olowokandi played only one productive season.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Olowokandi nor Bibby are considered ``impact players,''
which have been virtually assured in the top 10 of most drafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were in the (Clippers') shoes, it's a very tough
question,'' said McKinney, who as general manager of the Detroit
Pistons took Grant Hill with the third pick in 1994. ``As of the
other day, no one is a lock. No one can get a handle on where these
players will go.''
</P>
<P>
   With just six players under contract, the Sonics need virtually
everything to shore their bench. They would like to find a young
backup point guard, small forward or power forward/center in the
draft or via free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Filling one gap could happen several ways, such as:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Packaging all three picks in a trade for a two- or
three-year player;
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Packaging the picks to trade up in the draft;
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Trading down; or
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Making one of the picks a keeper (i.e. James Cotton last
year).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of interest in our pick. We're keeping all
of our options open,'' McKinney said. ``There are a couple of
players we have interest in that will go before we pick. If we
decided to keep all three picks, we'll take a player we'd like to
develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important about this draft is that we have a coach who
has a tremendous reputation for developing young players. He's not
afraid to develop these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Westphal, who replaced George Karl as Sonics coach last
week, takes great interest in the draft. While in Phoenix, Westphal
was responsible for advancing the careers of Cedric Ceballos and
Richard Dumas _ both late second-round picks.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the Sonics have traded down and selected
second-rounders to avoid having to pay a first-round prospect a
guaranteed three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   This year's draft talent is so evenly spread that several trades
could take place. The thought process is that teams can get the
same player with the 27th pick that can be had with the 12th. This
is why the Sonics might try to trade up or down as the first round
develops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not particularly star-heavy,'' said Sonics president
Wally Walker, ``but there are a lot of decent prospects, guys who
will make NBA rosters. ... It's the best overall group I've seen in
five years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
