<SLUG> BC-GLF-TECHNOLOGY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLF TECHNOLOGY COMES BLASTING OUT OF BUNKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Posing as the poster boy for Callaway golf clubs in a
visor and designer black vest displaying the company logo, John
Daly broke out laughing when asked if he had ever been on a
trampoline before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've been on a trampoline, but I haven't found many that
can hold my fat (rear end),'' Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the world's best golfers, Daly was having trouble
understanding a new test the United States Golf Association has
come up with to determine if all the new metal drivers on the
market conform to a standard that measures their ``trampoline
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   After imposing a moratorium on approving new drivers with
titanium heads earlier this year, the USGA last week used the U.S.
Open to announce that it would test any new clubs to determine if
they caused balls to spring into flight much like a trampoline.
</P>
<P>
   Daly was not alone in his confusion. Players, manufacturers and
golf writers had anticipated that the USGA might declare some new
clubs illegal for play, thus putting a huge dent in the
billion-dollar golf club business.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade alone, metal alloys, graphite and even
ceramic materials have made their way into golf clubs, which were
once made of either wood or steel with only rare exceptions.
Similar materials are being woven into balls, which are being
designed to do everything from travel farther to spin with better
control.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, club heads have been steadily getting bigger.
While distances have not gone up appreciably, the new clubs have
made it possible to avoid many mis-hits, keeping balls flying in
straighter lines. They also have skyrocketed in price, running
anywhere from $350 to $500 for the Greatest Big Bertha, Callaway's
latest model.
</P>
<P>
   All of this would be fine with most golfers, except that the
USGA, which governs the rules and standards of the game, wants to
ensure that players can't gain an unfair advantage simply by buying
a high-tech club or ball.
</P>
<P>
   The issue came to a head last month after the USGA temporarily
withheld approval of the new Ping ISI Titanium driver from Karsten
Manufacturing. It had been submitted to the USGA for approval in
January, but the association announced it was looking into all
thin-faced metal drivers to determine if they had the trampoline
effect that Daly couldn't understand.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Callaway's Big Bertha drivers weren't under direct
scrutiny, the company had hired an antitrust attorney and announced
it was ready to battle the USGA in court. It also took out
full-page ads in the New York Times that declared: ``There is
absolutely no good reason why millions of golfers should ever be
required to give up their Big Bertha or comparable brands of metal
woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with such a mounting backlash, the USGA suddenly backed
off last week and said that all clubs now on the market or already
used in competitive play conformed to its new test standards and
would be legal. But it left the door open to deny approval in the
future if new clubs have too much of a spring-like (as in
trampoline) effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the literal sense, all clubs have some spring-like effect
because all clubs deform at impact,'' said David Fay, USGA
executive director. ``Bob Jones' driver deformed at impact, the
wooden-headed drivers used in the 1987 U.S. Open deformed at
impact, and so do the thin-faced, large-headed drivers that the
majority of players in this U.S. Open will use.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue centers on the fact that metal woods in particular
have gotten bigger, wider and more expensive, and use space-age
materials designed to make the ball go farther and straighter with
more consistency.
</P>
<P>
   For Daly, who seems like he could drive a ball 250 yards with a
broom, the issue isn't with the clubs the pros use. As someone who
endorses Callaway's Big Bertha titanium drivers, Daly was concerned
that the USGA was preparing to take clubs out of the hands of the
average golfer, who relies on new technology to improve scores and
enjoyment of the game. He equated it with building a better, safer
airplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't it be nicer to fly in an airplane that you know will
never go down?'' he said. ``I don't think the technology should be
stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly isn't alone in his concern that the USGA was becoming all
too fussy about the new technology in golf. One of golf's all-time
greats, Jack Nicklaus, also shared Daly's concerns, even though
Nicklaus would like to see the pros all use a standard ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I worry about is maintaining the integrity of
the game at its highest level,'' Nicklaus said. ``... (But) I don't
think that we need to reduce the advances of technology that have
made the game so much more pleasurable for a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the technology wars in golf appear to be at a
standstill until the USGA's new testing procedures for clubs are
officially put into place in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Many clubs, like the Callaway driver, have been granted
conditional approval by the USGA in the past, but those could be
endangered if the association discovers a trampoline effect in
testing, which will involve taking a plate from the driver and then
blasting a golf ball at it to measure how far it springs.
</P>
<P>
   Daly, who has seen slow-motion video of the test, doubts it can
even prove anything like a trampoline effect exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you're seeing is a golf ball compressing on a club head,''
he said. ``The head isn't going in, so that's not a trampoline
effect. That's the impact of a golf ball on a club head.''
</P>
<P>
   There are companies that have tried to get around the USGA
entirely by going straight to the market with their clubs without
formal approval, such as when Bullet Golf unveiled its Hollow Point
driver. Its metal head had a cut-out section that was declared
illegal for play by the USGA, but when the company filled the
hollow area with metal, the club became erratic off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers, understandably, are worried that the USGA is
paying far too much attention to the new technology. But they also
took heart in the USGA's findings that clubs now approved and on
the market have not ``lessened the skill required to play the game
at championships such as the U.S. Open or at the recreational
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Scores last week at the U.S. Open at The Olympic Club in San
Francisco were just as high as they were three decades earlier,
despite all the technological advances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of titanium drivers has not contributed to a dilution
of the role and contribution of (golfing) skills,'' said Wally
Uihlein, chief executive officer and chairman of the
Titleist-Footjoy Co. ``That's very important as far as the timeless
issue of the balance between tradition and technology.''
</P>
<P>
   But the war of words is hardly over, especially as manufacturers
begin to search for the next big advances in equipment. All they
can do is hope their new clubs of the future will meet the USGA's
tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last six months, we haven't been able to know what
(the USGA) is going to do and what kind of lines are going to be
drawn,'' said John Solheim, chief executive officer of Karsten
Manufacturing Co. ``It makes it very difficult for us to continue
testing. ... It means as you try to develop things, you're just in
a state of hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
