<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THROUGH THE LOOKING GLASS OF MODERN MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Recently I walked across town to the Pierpont Morgan
Library to view an exhibition of manuscripts and books by Charles
Dodgson, a.k.a. Lewis Carroll, the author of ``Alice in
Wonderland'' and ``Through the Looking Glass.'' What I really went
to see was the colored proof sheets of Sir John Tenniel's glorious
engravings, which are more closely entwined with the tales they
illustrate than those by any other artist except William Blake, who
illustrated his own poems. Alice, the Duchess, the Mock Turtle and
the Gryphon looked much as they always have, feet firmly planted on
the cross-hatchings of Wonderland, faces perplexed by the odd
sobriety of the world those characters will forever inhabit.
</P>
<P>
   Though I had come to revisit Alice et al., I was struck by a
different exhibition, called ``Settling New Scores,'' a display of
modern music manuscripts on loan from the Paul Sacher Foundation in
Basel, Switzerland. These were the cross-hatchings of a different
wonderland. The autograph scores, by Stravinsky, Schonberg, Webern
and many others, evoked purely visual metaphors _ a painting by
Jasper Johns, for instance, or perhaps, in the more furious
passages, the motion of the driving wheel and main rod of a steam
locomotive racing on slender rails across a featureless prairie.
Only visual metaphors came to mind for the simple reason that an
orchestral score is, to me, a little like the topo map of a place
I've never been. I can tell by the crowding of the lines that the
going gets very hard, but I can't actually see the cliffs and the
steep scree slopes the map represents.
</P>
<P>
   I do read music. That is, I decipher it, as laboriously as
someone trying to get through ``The Golden Bowl'' by spelling the
words aloud. I was warned long ago, by an elderly piano teacher in
a small Iowa town, that I would regret my habit of playing by ear.
Now I know what she means. Between the polyphonic complexity of the
manuscript scores displayed at the Morgan Library and the musical
intuition of my facile but decidedly simple-minded ear, there is an
overwhelming gap. I realize now _ chalk this up in the book of
intellectual lamentations _ that there was everything to be said
for learning to play the piano by eye, for letting seeing music
become a means of hearing music.
</P>
<P>
   That's almost paradoxical enough for Lewis Carroll. And it only
begins to hint at the puzzles latent in the manuscripts in
``Settling New Scores.'' There is, as the composer Henri Dutilleux
puts it, the problem of time. ``Did you know,'' he said, ``that the
duration of a page of orchestral music is rarely more than six to
ten seconds, but it sometimes takes a whole day to write it?'' For
Conlon Nancarrow, who composed for the player piano using a
piano-roll-punching machine, the problem of time was even worse. It
would take him, writes Kyle Gann, ``eight months of punching to
complete what was for him a major work of three to six minutes.''
This is, indeed, doing all the running you can do to keep in the
same place.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps someday I will have learned, really learned, to read
music properly. And perhaps someday I will learn calculus too, as
I've always meant to do. But for now I can only play a little by
ear _ songs no more complicated than the Mock Turtle's ``Beautiful
Soup'' _ and I'm still trying to master the basic branches of
arithmetic the Mock Turtle was taught when he got ``the best of
educations'' at the bottom of the sea: Ambition, Distraction,
Uglification and Derision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 0152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3687 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANGELS-LADN     06-24 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BULLPEN CAN'T HOLD LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ There was a smattering of fans who began
heading toward the exits in the bottom of the seventh inning of
Tuesday night's game between the Los Angeles Dodgers and Anaheim
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to assume they were Dodgers fans getting a jump on
traffic, just as they do at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the game was all but over, the Dodgers bullpen
wasting another lead. The Angels rallied late in the game for the
second night in a row, this time scoring three runs in the seventh
inning and one in the eighth on their way to a 6-4 win before a
sellout crowd of 43,719 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The victory enabled the Angels, winners of 20 of their last 23
games, to maintain their 3{-game lead in the AL West over Texas.
The Dodgers remained 13{ games behind first-place San Diego in the
NL West.
</P>
<P>
   Only one night earlier, the Angels took advantage of the
beleaguered Dodgers bullpen, scoring all six runs in the final
three innings to win 6-5. Tuesday, Dodgers starter Dave Mlicki
allowed only two unearned runs through six innings before he had to
leave the game.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki was knocked dizzy, but it wasn't the Angels hitters doing
the damage.
</P>
<P>
   On Darin Erstad's infield single in the fifth inning, second
baseman Wilton Guerrero fielded the ball before colliding with
Mlicki, Guerrero's head smacking Mlicki in the left side of his
jaw. Mlicki had to leave one inning later, and the Angels took
advantage of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 3-2 in the seventh, the Angels loaded the bases with
one out against Will Brunson. Jim Bruske replaced Brunson and got
Cecil Fielder to hit a chopper to the hole at short. Third baseman
Juan Castro could only deflect the ball into shallow left field as
two runners scored to give the Angels a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Walbeck singled in another run later in the inning off
Bruske to put Anaheim up 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers got close with a run in the eighth inning off Pep
Harris, but Shigetoshi Hasegawa got Gary Sheffield to fly to right
field with the potential tying run on third, ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad gave the Angels an insurance run in the bottom of the
inning with an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Angels' 21st come-from-behind win this season.
Whatever their deficit, they seem to feel they can rally. Their hot
streak started May 31 when they came back from a 5-0 deficit at
Minnesota to win 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to explain how important it is to come back and
win games, Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``As a game goes
along, the confidence is there. They know what it takes, they know
how to approach it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of times during games in the season where
you're down in the seventh inning, and you hear a voice down the
bench say `It's our time, time to step up.'''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Jarrod Washburn was adequate in six innings,
giving up three runs and eight hits. But he left the game trailing
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Harris (1-0), making his first appearance in almost two weeks,
got the win over Brunson (0-1). Rich DeLucia got the final out to
record his second save of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In his three starts as a Dodger going into Tuesday's game,
Mlicki _ acquired June 4 in the trade for Hideo Nomo _ already had
as many wins this season (two) as Nomo had in 12 starts.
</P>
<P>
   And after blanking the Angels for the first three innings
Tuesday, Mlicki's consecutive scoreless-inning streak reached 19,
the longest of any Dodger pitcher this season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels snapped the streak with two runs in the fourth,
courtesy of the Dodgers defense. Castro at shortstop and Guerrero
at second made errors on hard-hit ground balls to start the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Both baserunners scored, one on a double-play ball and the
second on a two-out bloop single by Orlando Palmeiro, tying the
game at 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had taken a 2-0 lead with single runs in the second
and fourth innings, both runs driven in by Paul Konerko. Konerko
led off the second inning with his third homer of the year. He
singled home Raul Mondesi (double) from second in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   After the Angels tied it in the bottom of the fourth, the
Dodgers regained the lead in the top of the fifth. Eric Young
singled, stole second and third and scored on Eric Karros' double
for a 3-2 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
