<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3932 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MELFISHER25-COX     06-24 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MELFISHER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Treasure trove of jewels dates back to 18th century
 &HT;    By Susannah A. Nesmith
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ With the kind of optimism unique to a
career treasure hunter, Mel Fisher is predicting a golden summer.
</P>
<P>
   There's the treasure one of his subcontractors just found, a
collection of jewels unveiled this week that Fisher says date to
1715 when a fleet of Spanish ships went down in a hurricane south
of Sebastian Inlet. His daughter says they're worth about $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   And there's the report his office just released that he says
refutes government claims that he sold counterfeit Spanish coins
this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's billions and billions of bucks worth of treasure down
there,'' he said Tuesday from a hotel room in Fort Pierce: He's in
town searching for treasure, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to counterfeit coins. I've never had the time.
And I'm going to be too busy this summer too.''
</P>
<P>
   The 76-year-old treasure hunter gained the proverbial fame and
fortune in 1985 when he discovered the Nuestra Senora de Atocha.
The sunken ship made him rich and got him in trouble with the
government, which claimed he destroyed a bed of seagrass to get to
the treasure. Since then he's made a career out of finding treasure
and fighting the government.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has more than a dozen subcontractors working for him
scouring wrecks he found in the Florida Keys and all the way up the
coast. One of those subcontractors, Steve Hancock, found the five
rings and the pair of earrings unveiled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of rings has three emeralds similar to some he found last
year that were appraised out at $380,000,'' said Fisher's daughter,
Taffi Fisher-Abt. ``The pair of pearl earrings each has 11 pearls.
They're very unique looking. It's amazing that he found a pair.
Ususally we find one and we don't find the other one for a year
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher-Abt said Hancock had been out hunting only for a week
when he discovered the jewels last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to find a ton more this summer,'' Fisher-Abt said.
``We're just getting started.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the report, Fisher-Abt and her father see it as a sign
that good things are going to happen. For one, they hope
prosecutors will drop their investigation of Fisher's shop in Key
West.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began this spring after a man complained that
he bought a coin from Fisher's shop for $5,900 but then an
insurance appraisal said it was a fake. Undercover investigators
bought another coin from Fisher's shop and a state expert said it
too was a fake.
</P>
<P>
   Both coins came with the certificates of authenticity saying
they came from the 1733 treasure fleet that sank off Duck Key. But
state archaeologists told the investigators they don't know of any
coins recovered from site C-2044, the one listed on the
certificates.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's ludicrous,'' Fisher says. ``C-2044 is entire Monroe
County. Certainly they've recieved gold coins and all kinds of
treasure from Monroe County. Do you know how many wrecks there are
in the Keys?''
</P>
<P>
   No one from the Monroe County State Attorneys Office was
available Tuesday to talk about the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In April investigators from the State Attorneys Office and the
Florida Department of Law Enforcement raided Fisher's treasure shop
in Key West and seized 25 to 30 coins.
</P>
<P>
   They were looking for more coins like the two they had analyzed,
coins that Fisher bought from an old friend, Bob Kruse, a Deerfield
Beach investor. Kruse invested in some of Fisher's subcontractors,
Fisher said. Investors in the subcontractors get a share of the
loot found on any expedition. Unfortunately, two of the
subcontractors who supposedly gave Kruse the coins are dead. The
third doesn't remember.
</P>
<P>
   And Kruse does have a conviction on his record for selling
counterfeit coins _ he was sentenced to prison in 1977 in
Pennsylvania for it. But Fisher stands by his friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were replicas, that's all they were, and he was giving
them away,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   And he stands by the coins he bought from Kruse.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher sent a coin from the same batch to a Tampa testing
company. The company's report shows deposits on the coins that
match deposits on other coins that have sat at the bottom of the
ocean for years. The coins even had tiny versions of barnacles on
them, Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ever tried to get barnacles off a boat?'' he said Tuesday.
``It's about impossible. Barnacles make a glue that can't be
duplicated by man. People have tried. How would I get those on
there?''
</P>
<P>
   So why would the government go to such trouble to get him?
Fisher says it's all a conspiracy. Government officials, in league
with environmentalists, have always been after his treasure. The
fact that his shop was raided on April 22 makes him especially
suspicious. Not only was it Earth Day, it's the day federal
officials sued him for the damage done to the seagrass around the
Atocha wreck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems all so ludicrous,'' he said. ``They did it on
Earth Day. What does that tell you?''
</P>
<P>
   Susannah A. Nesmith writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
