<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3933 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURTLE-DEATHS25-COX     06-24 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURTLE-DEATHS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turtle deaths blamed on busy boat traffic
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Experts are blaming busier boat traffic
spurred by two months of good weather for an increase in turtle
deaths in Palm Beach County and the Treasure Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Officials report finding 22 dead turtles so far in June between
Boca Raton and Fort Pierce, including one Monday in Delray Beach
and two Tuesday, in Gulf Stream and Manalapan. Boat collisions or
propeller cuts are blamed for at least 14 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   While direct comparisons with previous years aren't available,
``it appears we've been having a higher-than-normal level of
strandings,'' said Paul Davis, program supervisor for Palm Beach
County's Department of Environmental Resources Management. ``As
soon as Memorial Day hit, the numbers started jumping.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers don't blame careless boaters; they say turtles are
hard to see and just happen to be struck when they surface for air.
They urged boaters to avoid or go slower near reefs, where turtles
congregate.
</P>
<P>
   Some injuries could have been old or occurred after the animal
was dead, officials said. Some animals initially may have drowned
in nets and some killed by sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the beached turtles had been dead for several days and
were heavily decomposed or partially eaten, often making it hard to
determine sex, weight, age and cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   While boats were blamed in only 15 percent of turtle strandings
_ dead and alive _ statewide in the last 10 years, they are cited
in 15 of the 29 strandings in Palm Beach, Martin and Broward
counties from January to April and 22 of the 32 in May, the Florida
Department of Environmental Protection said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that there are just more turtles around,'' said
Kristin Fick, a DEP researcher in Tequesta. She said green turtle
nestings and populations fluctuate from year to year.
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Kleinberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 0958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
