<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3935 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBA-JASONWILLIAMS-COX     06-24 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-JASONWILLIAMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA draft: Past could haunt ex-Gator Williams
 &HT;    (EDS: Written before Wednesday evening's NBA draft.)
 &HT;    By Jorge Milian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jason Williams is no angel.
</P>
<P>
   In less than one season at the University of Florida, Williams
was suspended three times by Gators coach Billy Donovan for
breaking team rules.
</P>
<P>
   Finally midway through last season, Williams was banished for
good by Donovan after reportedly failing a drug test.
</P>
<P>
   None of that appeared to have much effect on NBA teams who were
to conduct their annual draft in Vancouver Wednesday night.
Williams was ranked by most analysts as the second-best point guard
in the draft behind Arizona's Mike Bibby, who is expected to be the
top pick.
</P>
<P>
   The general consensus was that Williams, who played less than
two seasons of college basketball, would be gone by the 15th
selection of the first round and others thought he could go much
higher than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have compared him to Pete Maravich,'' Heat General
Manager Randy Pfund said.
</P>
<P>
   People have also compared Williams to less savory characters
like Lawrence Phillips, Randy Moss and Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Like Rodman, Williams sports enough tattoos to satisfy the crew
of a battleship. Williams also has a fondness for earrings and is
saddled with enough baggage to make even Rodman wince.
</P>
<P>
   In his short stay in Gainesville, Williams quit school once,
complained repeatedly about having to attend classes, pouted
incessantly when he didn't play well and, according to several
newspaper reports, failed drug tests twice.
</P>
<P>
   But when Williams managed to keep himself eligible and out of
trouble, he was a magician on the court. Before being booted from
the team, Williams led the Gators in scoring with 17.1 points per
game and was first in the Southeastern Conference in assists (6.7),
steals (2.8) and free-throw percentage (.840).
</P>
<P>
   The high point for Williams came in a victory against eventual
national champion Kentucky at Rupp Arena in early February during
which the West Virginia native scored 24 points and dominated the
action.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately two weeks later, Williams was an ex-Gator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can look myself in the mirror and our coaching staff can
look themselves in the mirror and know that we did everything
possible to help this kid,'' said Donovan, who first coached
Williams at Marshall University in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' antics earned him the moniker ``Wild Child.'' To some
in the NBA, he's the draft's wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Boston General Manager Chris Wallace says teams have to consider
the ``Randy Moss factor'' in evaluating Williams. Moss, the
talented but troubled wide receiver, dropped like a rock in April's
NFL draft because of prior legal and behavioral problems. Moss,
ironically, was a teammate of Williams at DuPont (W.Va.) High
School.
</P>
<P>
   But those comparisons are unfair, according to Dan Tobin of
Professional Management Associates, which represents Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a bad guy,'' Tobin said. ``To compare him to Randy
Moss or Lawrence Phillips is apples and oranges.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, for his part, has had little to say since leaving UF.
Williams' representatives have advised the 6-foot-1, 190-pounder to
keep a low profile until the draft.
</P>
<P>
   But while in Toronto interviewing with the Raptors late last
month, Williams told a reporter he's a changed man.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're worried about the trouble off the court, but I'm
proving them wrong,'' Williams said of NBA teams. ``I'm on the
right path. I've never given up and I don't plan on making more
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 0959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STODA-COLUMN25-COX     06-24 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Vanbiesbrouck's new leash on life needs scrutiny
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Let's say there are two brothers named
Bryan and Terry.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say they have a pet dog named Beezer.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say Beezer has been, mostly, good and faithful. Let's say
he has, mostly, guarded the house well and let's also say just
about everybody in the neighborhood loves him.
</P>
<P>
   But let's say Beezer is getting old and let's say it's going to
be very expensive to keep him around much longer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, let's say Bryan, in a position of sibling authority, thinks
it's time to get rid of Beezer. No, not get rid of him that way.
Bryan simply figures he'd be OK without Beezer and Beezer may be
better off living somewhere else, anyway. And let's say Beezer
hasn't seemed at all upset about the prospect of leaving.
</P>
<P>
   But let's say Terry isn't so sure about Bryan's plan. Terry
thinks Beezer is still valuable. Terry certainly thinks it's at
least worth the effort of exploring the possibility of keeping
Beezer.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan and Terry have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   OK, apologies for the analogy to Beezer, who, of course, is
Panthers goalie John Vanbiesbrouck, who is a kind and decent man
and in no manner of thinking a dog as a hockey player or a human
being.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remains that the Brothers Murray _ Bryan as general
manager; Terry as head coach recently hired by Bryan _ have a
monumental decision to make in the earliest stage of their new
relationship. And the strangest aspect of the situation is that
Bryan and Beezer appeared to have settled this issue a long time
ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was in March, with the Panthers in the concluding stages of a
miserable season, when Vanbiesbrouck said, ``Sometimes, you've got
to cut your losses and move on.'' Later, given the opportunity to
retract or soften a statement made in the immediate aftermath of a
game in which he was pulled, Vanbiesbrouck instead bristled, ``I
meant what I said. Absolutely ... things have been going on for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   If that wasn't Beezer biting Bryan, who was serving as general
manager and head coach at the time, then what was it?
</P>
<P>
   Bryan is going along with Terry so far, but doesn't sound
inclined to go too far. And there's a huge gap between so far and
too far. Bryan said on Monday that ``Terry thinks John is a good
goaltender'' and that ``(Terry) likes him.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry thinks.
</P>
<P>
   Terry likes.
</P>
<P>
   No reading between the lines required. Bryan doesn't consider
Vanbiesbrouck a smart investment when the price figures to come in
at something around $4 million per season in a multi-year
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan ponders more efficient use of that kind of money. Think
puppies. Think a litter of young players.
</P>
<P>
   Beezer has played 14 full seasons in the NHL _ that's 98 years
in a dog's life, by the way _ and has spent the last five of those
seasons with the Panthers. But he was mediocre last year (18-29-11
with a 2.87 goals-against average), and animosities were on clear
display all around as Florida dissolved into one of hockey's worst
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Beezer is out there lounging on the porch. Officially, he
sheds the leash next Wednesday when his day of eligibility for
unrestricted free agency arrives.
</P>
<P>
   What should the Brothers Murray do at the outset of their new
alliance?
</P>
<P>
   They should scratch Beezer's ears and tummy and back in
appreciation of all he has done.
</P>
<P>
   And then they should just scratch him from all future plans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
