<HEADER>
A3937 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN25-COX     06-24 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Intrusion as their goal
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ It's always fun, sort of like one of those
back-seat games for the road, to hear a Republican Party gathering
invoke a call for less government intervention and then to count
the ways party faithful want more.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Gov. George Bush was doing the invoking at the state
party convention and sounding Reaganesque. Depending on your
ideological pocket dictionary, Reaganesque means either
``visionary'' or ``contradictory and hypocritical.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan never wanted to get government off people's backs.
That was a damnable lie. On a host of very personal matters, he
wanted government hip-deep. Abortion. Drug testing. School prayer.
Wiretapping. Pornography. On each issue it wasn't ``Government is
the enemy.'' It was ``Bring on government.''
</P>
<P>
   At the state convention Bush heralded a ``responsibility era''
where people don't turn to government for deliverance but one in
which ``each of us is responsible _ for our actions, our decisions,
our families and our communities.'' The Gipper would give this his
mark of approval.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take Bush long, however, to find one of those issues
in which government is next to godliness. That would be the
abortion issue. Since states can't ban it, opponents try to
undercut abortion rights where they can. One that's popular would
be to require parental consent when minors seek abortion. Bush said
such a requirement would be high among his priorities if
re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   Given a moment's analysis this is a peculiar cause for real
conservatives. Its premise is the doctrine of ``parental rights,''
which means, ``government stay out of family matters'' _ that
parents' rights are inviolable.
</P>
<P>
   But who's the parent here? If we are to take ``parental rights''
literally, proponents should be crusading for the right of the
pregnant teen _ the real parent here _ to decide for herself.
</P>
<P>
   What you learn is not to put rhetoric to the test when you hear
``government is the enemy.'' A lot of these people want government
intrusion more than anything in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans, like the late Barry Goldwater, clearly are
uncomfortable with these discrepancies, particularly on abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   True anti-government sorts would crusade for privacy and freedom
of choice, but remember the rallying cries of Republicans who
pleaded the case for rejected Reagan Supreme Court choice Robert
Bork. They, as did he, decried Supreme Court rulings that made
privacy a constitutional right. They evoked images of rights run
amok, government handcuffed from deciding which private behavior
was OK and which was verboten.
</P>
<P>
   Well, you bet _ this privacy stuff is a dilemma. Anyone who
believes privacy is inviolable has been too long at the compound.
</P>
<P>
   But if privacy is the most fundamental principle of liberty,
that thing guaranteed in the 14th Amendment (to be denied only with
due process of law), its biggest enemy is the Reagan legacy and the
authoritarian impulses it nurtured, particularly within the
religious right.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush hasn't been one to kowtow to that segment of his
party. Indeed, he clashed with former state party chairman Tom
Pauken, who was identified with the more strident social
conservatives. Bush doesn't need their help to lead the GOP in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be fascinating, should Bush run for president, to
see how he contorts himself to please the religious right, whose
blessing he'll need to win key caucuses and primaries.
</P>
<P>
   And here's what he'll have to say to win the love of the
righteous extreme: Government isn't the problem. Government is the
solution.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
