<HEADER>
A3979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BALLET-JUBILEE-NYT     06-24 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BALLET-JUBILEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
100 WORKS FOR CITY BALLET'S 50TH 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City Ballet will mark its 50th
anniversary with a yearlong celebration during which 100 ballets
will be performed, Peter Martins, the company's ballet master in
chief, announced at a news conference Tuesday at the New York State
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company is known for its large repertory, Martins
said that ``One hundred ballets is unprecedented, even for us.''
(The troupe's current spring season at the State Theater includes
47 works.) The anniversary offerings range from several premieres
to revivals of such pieces as George Balanchine's ``Bugaku'' and
``Liebeslieder Walzer'' and a new full-evening ``Swan Lake,''
staged by Martins.
</P>
<P>
   Opening night, Nov. 24, will duplicate the New York City
Ballet's inaugural program, on Oct. 11, 1948, of Balanchine's
``Concerto Barocco,'' ``Orpheus'' and ``Symphony in C.'' All former
dancers with the company will be invited to participate in the
curtain calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nutcracker'' will be on view from Nov. 27 through Jan. 3.
Martins said that performances might feature special guests,
although he could not yet list specific names.
</P>
<P>
   The week beginning Jan. 5 has been named a ``Balanchine Black
and White Celebration.'' It will be devoted to many of the
choreographically complex but austerely costumed works (among them
``Agon,'' ``Concerto Barocco'' and ``The Four Temperaments'') that
established Balanchine as a major balletic abstractionist.
</P>
<P>
   The repertory weeks that follow include a premiere to be
announced and special evenings of ballets to Russian, British,
French, Austrian, German, Italian and Polish music, as well as
programs devoted to Stravinsky, Brahms, Ravel, Bach and Chopin.
</P>
<P>
   The winter engagement closes with performances Feb. 23-28
honoring the American choreographer Jerome Robbins and emphasizing
his ballets to European scores.
</P>
<P>
   The company reopens on April 27, when Martins' new ``Swan Lake''
begins a two-week run. Martins said that although much of the
production derives from the traditional version by Marius Petipa
and Lev Ivanov, ``The thinking of Balanchine is a major influence
upon my `Swan Lake.'''
</P>
<P>
   The spring season continues with a two-week Stravinsky Festival
(May 11-23), with a new ballet by Christopher Wheeldon; a weeklong
Tchaikovsky Festival (May 25-30) and a three-week American Music
Festival (June 1-20), with new ballets, to be announced, to music
by Duke Ellington and Wynton Marsalis. The American festival also
includes programs of early and recent choreography by Robbins to
American scores. The season concludes with ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream,'' June 22-27.
</P>
<P>
   Martins announced that he was planning Monday night seminars
featuring former stars of the company, and that Edward Villella,
Melissa Hayden, Suzanne Farrell, Merrill Ashley and Arthur Mitchell
had already agreed to participate. City Ballet's anniversary will
also be marked by an autumn tour with 26 performances in
California, Texas and New York State (in conjunction with the State
University of New York) and by a major exhibition at the New-York
Historical Society on April 7 through Oct. 17, 1999.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1032EDT &QL; 
