<HEADER>
A4002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUNY-EDUC-NYT &LR;      06-24 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUNY-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW WAY OF FINANCING NEW YORK STATE COLLEGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The trustees of the State University of New York
adopted a budget on Tuesday that allows campuses to keep the
tuition and fees they bring in, a step aimed at making the colleges
more responsive to market forces.
</P>
<P>
   The move is widely viewed as a harbinger of the broader
transformation of the university that its board has sought for
several years, but that some legislators and campus representatives
have fought.
</P>
<P>
   The colleges have been turning over their tuition revenue to a
central university pot. The money has then been reallocated under a
complex formula that has allowed the university to keep open
smaller campuses that some see as less economically viable.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, the budget for next year gives more money to
all campuses. The actual increases for the fiscal year that begins
July 1 range from less than 1 percent for the five Colleges of
Technology to more than 7 percent for the Binghamton, Geneseo and
New Paltz campuses. No increase in tuition is envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   But critics fear that in the long term, the new formula
establishes a Darwinian system that will leave smaller campuses
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that this model will lead to many campus closings,''
said Kenneth P. LaValle, chairman of the State Senate's Committee
on Higher Education, ``and that it will factionalize the state
university system, pitting campuses against each other.''
</P>
<P>
   State legislators have long been wary of changes that could
threaten campuses in their home districts. When SUNY tried to pare
campuses several years ago, for example, it was stymied by
legislators who fought the loss of institutions that were important
to their communities economically and culturally.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates of the new system said it would strengthen the
colleges by encouraging them to improve their programs and attract
more students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The colleges will have to go out and hustle,'' said Thomas W.
Carroll, president of the Empire Foundation for Policy Research, a
conservative interest group that has been pressing for a more
market-oriented approach. ``This is a fantastic change from the
socialist cross-subsidy method that has kept people afloat by
administrative fiat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before,'' he said, ``it didn't matter whether you were run
well or poorly. The only thing that mattered was that you didn't
close your doors, or the state legislators would get upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Within SUNY, the new budget is seen as a first step toward a
broader system of performance-based financing. Under such a system,
SUNY would allocate tax money to the campuses based on factors like
the types of courses they offered and how their students scored on
standardized tests. SUNY's provost, Peter Salins, has developed a
preliminary list of such performance indicators that he will
discuss with the colleges in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Senator LaValle and other state legislators tried unsuccessfully
last week to pass legislation that would prevent SUNY from adopting
a new financial system. ``My fear was that if we left Albany
without passing anything, the trustees would take action,'' LaValle
said. ``By adopting the budget, they have done it.''
</P>
<P>
   But rather than voting on a new system, the trustees, meeting at
the SUNY College at Plattsburgh, adopted a budget that reflected
some of the basic principles of that system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never have voted on an approach,'' said Scott W. Steffey,
SUNY's vice chancellor for university relations. ``But we have
changed the way we have constructed it so there are incentives, and
so that it is easier to see how the money is being apportioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuition represents only about 40 percent, or $600 million, of
the SUNY budget, which will total $1.6 billion next year, up 4.4
percent from this year. Most of the rest comes from state
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Although all of the state-operated campuses will see budget
increases, some will be bigger than others. The university centers
at Albany and Binghamton are among the winners, with increases of
about 7 percent. In contrast, SUNY Buffalo and the state units at
Cornell University will see increases of only about 3 percent. SUNY
Stony Brook will see a 5.5 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   The changes do not apply to SUNY's 30 community colleges, which
draw some of their financing from their communities.
</P>
<P>
   Small colleges, which are seen as most vulnerable unless they
can raise their enrollments, are being at least partly protected
under the new formula. SUNY officials said that they will provide a
certain level of financial support for basic operations at colleges
with enrollments of 5,000 students or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   The new budget also raises the amount given to colleges to match
the money they bring in for sponsored research to 20 percent, from
9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
