<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4005 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-COMETS- &UR; SWOOPES-A     06-24 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERSTAR, SUPERMOM  
 SWOOPES FINDS TIME TO DO IT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
 SWOOPES-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most famous mother in the WNBA has a birthday party to plan.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan Jackson is 1 Thursday so Sheryl Swoopes is thinking not
only about a game against the Mercury tonight, but the party at
Chuck E Cheese's Pizza on Friday and Jordan's first haircut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandma said you're not touching his hair until he turns 1,''
Swoopes said. ``I've been looking forward to the haircut more than
the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 11 mothers in the 110-player WNBA, four are with the
defending champion Houston Comets, including league Most Valuable
Player Cynthia Cooper, who is raising six of her nieces and nephews
and adopting the youngest.
</P>
<P>
   Because of marketing _ Swoopes was one of three players
trumpeted by the league in its ``We Got Next'' campaign _ and
timing _ she gave birth four days after the league's first game _
Swoopes is Supermom of the 1990s. Husband Eric Jackson, along on
the trip here with Jordan, is sharing as a primary caregiver and,
counting endorsements, mom is bringing home a seven-figure salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing right now is finding enough time to do
everything,'' Swoopes said. ``To do my job, to take care of what
I've got to do off the court, to go home and be a mom, to go home
and be a wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Her schedule became too much June 9, when she missed a pair of
Comets practices, one of them a public workout. Coming a day after
an 81-79 exhibition loss to Cleveland, the absences were
interpreted as the first public sign of Houston hoops not being big
enough for Swoopes and Coop.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes' mundane explanation of dad out of town, grandma ill and
no baby-sitter played less glamorously and certainly was no excuse
for her not informing Comets Coach Van Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was blown way out of proportion because people
turned it into what they wanted it to be, which was a feud between
me and Cynthia,'' Swoopes said. ``Cynthia had nothing to do with
the reason I was not at practice. Van and I talked and discussed
everything. He knows why I wasn't there, and the team knows why I
wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of team issues, which had nothing to do with any
individual, that needed to be talked out. We talked them out, and
that's that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever was worked out in those critical days before the season
opener left the air clear enough for the Comets to start 5-0, three
short of the league record for consecutive victories. And the
deeper Houston moves into the 30-game season, the more its stars,
including Tina Thompson, are able to see how they can peacefully
co-exist.
</P>
<P>
   All play different positions: the 5-foot-10 Cooper at shooting
guard, 6-foot Swoopes at small forward and 6-2 Thompson at power
forward. When they are aligned just right, as they were last week
against Cleveland in combining for 69 points (Swoopes 25, Thompson
23, Cooper 21), the opponent should be entitled to an early
surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Even when one of them is way off, like Swoopes' 0-for-10
shooting against Los Angeles on Sunday, the others respond (50
points combined from Cooper and Thompson) and someone else steps up
(Monica Lamb's 14 points and 11 rebounds).
</P>
<P>
   ``That's saying a lot about our team,'' Swoopes said. ``I can't
ask for a better situation than I'm in right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, it takes more than five players to win. I know that,
Cynthia knows that. We know we're in a great situation. You've got
Cynthia on one wing, myself on the other wing. You've got Tina
inside or outside. You've got Kim (Perrot) at the point. When Wanda
(Guyton) is healthy, she's a monster on the boards.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes, 27, made her name in Texas, first at Brownfield High
School, then as national Player of the Year at Texas South Plains
Junior College and Texas Tech, which won the 1993 NCAA title by a
bucket over Ohio State. She was the third-leading scorer for the
U.S. National Team that went 60-0 in 1995-96 and won the Atlanta
Olympic gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Eight players off that Olympic team became the nucleus of the
American Basketball League while Swoopes, Lisa Leslie, Rebecca Lobo
and Ruthie Bolton-Holifield cast their professional future with the
WNBA. Nikki McCray is the only one so far to have switched sides,
trading her 1996-97 ABL MVP title for a job with WNBA expansion
Washington Mystics.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes' unplanned pregnancy rocked the boat a bit, and there
were critics of her rush back to the court six weeks after giving
birth. She made it into 11 games, including the playoffs, with only
flashes of the player who averaged 24.9 points and nine rebounds at
Texas Tech and was too perfect for The Swoosh (Nike) not to enlist
for Air Swoopes, a shoe now in its fourth model.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes was to have played on the American team that completed a
9-0, gold-medal run at the World Championships on June 7, but she
withdrew in favor of a full training camp with the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel like the timing was right,'' she said. ``It was
very important for me to be in camp, not just so I could get in
shape and work in Coach Chancellor's system. The biggest thing was
to show my teammates I had an opportunity to go and do something
else, but this is my job and this is more important to me right now
than the World Championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the LA game _ ``I've never, ever a day in my life
played that bad,'' she said. ``I just felt I was out there taking
up space'' _ the results have been promising. Although her average
plunged four points to 15.8, she still is ninth in WNBA scoring and
also contributing four rebounds, two assists and two steals per
game while playing 30.6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's not enough for the Lake Avenue Badgers, who
harass Swoopes about her shooting in a new Nike commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes is shown harmlessly playing in the park with Jordan when
three Badgers, chiefly actress Kyla Pratt, soon to be seen with
Eddie Murphy in the movie ``Dr. Doolittle,'' suggest her jump shot
needs some work. ``Girl, where is your mama?'' Swoopes asks. ``Mama
can't help your jump shot,'' responds Pratt.
</P>
<P>
   A line that must have flashed through Swoopes' mind a time or
two during her fiasco at the Forum and the Mercury faithful hope to
be chanting tonight. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
