<HEADLINE>
NO. 14 MAY BE LUCKY FOR COYOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Unlike last year, when they sat in frustration until
drafting Finnish defenseman Juha Gustafsson with the 43rd pick, the
Coyotes depart for Saturday's NHL entry draft in Buffalo, N.Y.
armed with a first-round selection.
</P>
<P>
   What type of player will they be drafting at No. 14?
</P>
<P>
   If the history of the No. 14 pick runs to form, probably a solid
if not spectacular player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the prominent names taken at No. 14, and you know
exactly why our scouts have put in thousands of hours and have
traveled hundreds of thousands of miles to uncover possible
talent,'' Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot of projection, skill and plain luck that
goes into picking a player who in five or 10 years someone will
say, `Can you imagine Phoenix got that guy with the 14th pick?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It can and has been done.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, the Boston Bruins drafted Terry O'Reilly with the 14th
pick. He played 14 years and 891 games for the Bruins, scoring 606
career points before retiring to become the coach.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Rangers tabbed center Rick Middleton at No. 14
before wrongheadedly trading him to Boston for an aging Ken Hodge.
Middleton retired after a 14-year career in which he played 1,005
games and 988 career points _ nearly a point a game.
</P>
<P>
   And wing Brian Propp played 15 years and scored 1,004 points in
a 1,016-game career.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, such up-and-coming stars as Chicago wing Ethan
Moreau, Colorado wing Adam Deadmarsh and Washington defenseman
Sergei Gonchar have been No. 14 picks. So were defensemen Calle
Johansson, Stephane Quintal, Terry Carkner and Bobby Dollos.
</P>
<P>
   The book is still out on the past three No. 14 picks:
</P>
<P>
   Left wing Michel Riessen, who is still developing in Switzerland
and has Edmonton drooling to sign him.
</P>
<P>
   Center Marty Reasonor, who led Boston College to this year's
NCAA title game and is contemplating whether to sign with St. Louis
or return to college.
</P>
<P>
   And defenseman Jay McKee, who has fluttered between Buffalo and
the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident we'll be able to pick a player who will have a
long and productive career in this league,'' Smith said, reminding
that Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk was a 19th pick.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are Smith is right.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1969 _ 30 entry drafts _ only injury-prone center Pat
Peake (1991), left wings Claude Bovin (1988), Normand Leveille
(1981) and Alex McKendry (1976), center Jim Malone (1980) and right
wing Danny Lucas (1978) can be described as wasted picks at No. 14.
</P>
<P>
   As opposed to when O'Reilly, Middleton and Propp were taken,
Smith said the draft is a much bigger crapshoot now.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1967-68 season, the NHL changed the minimum draft age
from 18 to 20, then changed it to 19 after the '78-79 season and
back to 18 after the '79-80 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know a lot more about a player and it's easier to project
him when he's 20 than it is when he's 18,'' Smith said. ``In two
years we may or may not know if our 14th pick was worth it or not.
You're taking young kids, sometimes frail, and trying to project
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 17, I weighed 185 pounds. When I played in the NHL,
I weighed 210 pounds. There was absolutely no way I would have been
the first pick of the draft (1978) in an underage draft like today.
Those two years have really increased the margin of error in
selecting any of these guys.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
