<HEADLINE>
RAW GARCIA NEEDS MORE POLISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas - Just when there was growing talk among the
Diamondbacks' power group that Karim Garcia hadn't made the
necessary adjustments to warrant sticking around, the still
baby-faced outfielder flashed some of his raw talent.
</P>
<P>
   The ballclub's decision-makers are suddenly in a holding pattern
with Garcia, waiting to see if the last two games have been an
aberration or if some of what they've been drilling into his head
is finally filtering through.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia remains on the chopping block, but his last two games
have helped restore the faith of the higher-ups within the
Diamondbacks organization, which selected Garcia fifth in the first
round of the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   One day after going 2 for 4, Garcia flicked a single to
right-center field on a curveball from Texas' Aaron Sele Tuesday
night, an at-bat that drew raves from within the Diamondbacks'
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, he slapped a single the opposite way, going with an
outside pitch instead of trying to yank it through the right side
of the infield, a bad habit which resurfaced during Garcia's final
at-bat when he tried to pull an outside breaking ball and wound up
meekly grounding to second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I need to be more consistent,'' the 22-year-old
acknowledged. ``I'm not frustrated but it bugs me when I don't do
better. I want to do better. At least I'm seeing progress now, I'm
not going backward.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while Garcia, who spent a month at Triple-A Tucson but was
recalled on May 31, was simply treading water. After going 2 for 4
in each of the last two games, he's pushed his post-Tucson average
up to .272.
</P>
<P>
   Overall he's batting .209, but he was at .143 when he was sent
down on April 27. He's also got seven extra base hits and 12 RBIs
in 66 at-bats since returning, better than the five extra-base hits
and four RBIs he had in 63 at-bats when he was sent down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they know it takes time,'' Garcia said. ``I definitely
feel more relaxed at the plate now because I have more of an idea.
I look for certain pitches and think of the count and the situation
in the game. I'm watching how they pitch to left-handers before I
come to bat. Before I was watching but not really digesting.''
</P>
<P>
   But just because the last two games have offered a better view
of Garcia does not mean he's on solid ground. After Sunday's loss
in St. Louis, a series in which Garcia went 2 for 11, there was
growing support from within to ship him back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major leagues is an accountable place,'' Manager Buck
Showalter said. ``Production is expected at some point. He's done
some things well and some things he needs to become more consistent
at.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia may be looking at the All-Star break as a cutoff to show
his progress. It's not inconceivable that if he slips back into
those bad habits, Garcia could find himself back in a Sidewinders
uniform by mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid can play,'' hitting coach Jim Presley said. ``He can
hit, run and has some big-time pop. Those are things you can't find
every day. He's got to put his tools to use. It's starting to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia is smart enough to know his big-league fate is currently
up in the air. He has the chance to have some big games the next
three nights if, indeed, Garcia has learned anything.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks will draw a mostly hard-throwing Rick Helling
and Todd Van Poppel, another predominantly fastball pitcher, before
Seattle's Bill Swift takes the mound Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Since Showalter has sat Garcia against left-handed starters,
Garcia should then take Saturday and Sunday off. The Mariners plan
to start Jeff Fassero and Jaime Moyer, both lefties.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks did not lie when they said Garcia is a work in
progress. It's just that at times this particular work seems to be
coming along slower than the Red Mountain Freeway. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
