<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK TRADE RUMOR REBUT TED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith and the agent for
star left wing Keith Tkachuk each scoffed at reports on a Phoenix
radio station that Tkachuk will be traded within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   KGME-AM (1360), citing two unidentified sources purported to be
friends of Tkachuk, reported throughout its morning show Tuesday
that Tkachuk will be dealt to one of four teams _ the Chicago
Blackhawks, the San Jose Sharks, or the New York Rangers or
Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's absolutely nothing to it,'' Smith said. ``It's simply
rumor time. I read somewhere today where (Jeremy) Roenick will be
traded before training camp. Now I'm hearing Tkachuk will be
traded. It's just another rumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still operating under the premise of having both of these
guys here next year. That hasn't changed.''
</P>
<P>
   KGME morning host Bruce Jacobs, however, went so far as to say,
``Tkachuk is flat-out telling people that he's going to be gone. .
. . He's big-time unhappy, and he says he's going to be traded
within the next two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk's agent, Bob Murray of Boston, said he was shocked by
those comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Keith does not want to be traded. He's made that very
clear from the beginning,'' Murray said. ``He likes it in Phoenix.
He wants to stay there. I don't think Keith has ever said anything
else. It makes no sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I don't know how friends might interpret a conversation _
if they ``are'' friends. But no, he doesn't want to be traded.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk, the Coyotes' captain, is in Winnipeg, where his annual
charity golf tournament is scheduled to begin Thursday, and could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   A trade could happen, however, if the Coyotes can't reach an
agreement with Murray on a multiyear contract extension for
Tkachuk, 25, the team's leading scorer the past three seasons and a
two-time All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have been negotiating for the past month or so,
and although they remain distant in discussions over money, the
talks have been productive and professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob and I talked a bit last Wednesday when we met (in
Washington), and we talked again this morning,'' Murray said
Tuesday. ``I wouldn't say things are great, but I wouldn't say
they're bad, either. We're talking. We're getting to the heart of
it and the nitty-gritty pretty quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk, who has two years remaining on his contract worth $2.8
million next season and $3 million the next, reportedly is seeking
a new pact worth at least $7 million a season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
