 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 391 - JUNE 24, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. BEN AFFLECK : RISING STAR MEETS AN ASTEROID IN 'ARMAGEDDON'
1997 was a big year for Ben Affleck. He charmed independent-film
fans in the surprise hit 'Chasing Amy,' charmed mainstream-film
fans in the surprise hit 'Good Will Hunting,' and finally charmed
worldwide audiences for the 1997 Oscars in winning the Best
Screenplay statue. Now he's co-starring with Bruce Willis and Liv
Tyler in 'Armageddon.' Affleck talks about the new movie, his
romance with Gwyneth Paltrow, how he has handled the sudden rush of
hype and what truth there is to rumours of a rivalry with his
longtime best friend and ``Good Will Hunting'' co-star/co-writer,
Matt Damon. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo.
_____________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   2. STEVEN SODERBERGH : INDIE SUPERSTAR VISITS THE MAINSTREAM
Steven Soderbergh revolutionized the independent-film world with
the erotic drama ``Sex, Lies and Videotape'' in 1989, and since
then has produced an impressive body of eclectic, highly personal
films. Now he is going mainstream with ``Out of Sight,'' a $49
million adaptation of Elmore Leonard's novel. Soderbergh talks
about the new movie, stars George Clooney and Jennifer Lopez, the
challenge of shaping truly individual films in an assembly-line
industry and why he has chosen to make an overtly commercial film
after a decade of independent work. By Ian Spelling. 1,200 words +
photo.
_____________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   3. AFTER 'HUSH,' JESSICA LANGE GOES FROM PROZAC
</P>
<P>
   TO BALZAC WITH 'COUSIN BETTE' Even two-time Oscar winners can
bomb now and then. Jessica Lange was last onscreen in the truly
awful thriller 'Hush.' She says she can laugh about that film now -
but she'd much rather talk about her latest, 'Cousin Bette.' In
this film, based on the provocative 19th century French novel by
Balzac, Lange tones down her natural vibrancy to play a dowdy
spinster with a black heart who weaves a web of intrigue. By Joshua
Mooney. BPI. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   _____________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   4. CHILDHOOD TALE COMES TO LIFE FOR 'MULAN' STAR MING-NA WEN
Actress Ming-Na Wen was born in China but grew up in Pittsburgh.
That East-West dichotomy, she says, has infused everything she's
done. Now, at long last, Wen fulfills a childhood dream by being a
part of a Disney animated film. She is the voice of the title
character in 'Mulan,' which is set in ancient China. The film has
cross-generational appeal. By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   5. SONNY SIDE UP Jazz saxophone great Sonny Rollins has been
speaking out on social issues for decades. His 1958 'Freedom Suite'
was a harbinger of the civil rights era. Now, 40 years later, he
has turned his attention to the environment on his new CD, 'Global
Warming.' ``If you are a black American, you can't help but be
political,'' he admits. Rollins sees his shift from civil rights to
the environment as a natural progression. ``We all know the
progress of racial justice,' he says. ``That's a hard thing to
dent, because the urge to feel superior is part of human nature.
But the environment is the common denominator; it's the equalizer
that will force everybody to act together.'' By Bob Blumenthal.
BPI. 2,000 words.
_____________________________________________________________
</P>
<P>
   6. VALENTINA'S DAY Forget bombshells. Italian actress Valentina
Cervi is one smart ragazza. She has made her mark in cinema by
playing brainy, complex and often repressed characters, not sex
goddesses. By Merle Ginsberg. From W magazine. 600 words. 
____________________________________________________________________
__
</P>
<P>
   7. TELLING LIFE STORIES : THE BOOM IN 'BIOGRAPHY' Everyone has a
story, the old saying goes - and if it runs long enough,
``Biography'' may tell them all. The surprise-hit TV programme
proves that, most of all, people want to hear about people. Andrew
Ryan looks at the secrets behind this popular series, including how
profiles are arranged, and, of course, how they decide who deserves
to be on ``Biography.'' From Canadian TV Guide. 1,100 words +
photo.
</P>
</TEXT>
