<P>
   Editors, attention Managing Editors, Wire Editors:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The New York Times News Service &LR;  is planning comprehensive
coverage of President Clinton's trip to China. Here is a
preliminary outline of stories to be filed today for release on
Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SUMMIT (Xian, China) _ A curtain-raiser from the ancient
capital of Xian, Clinton's first stop, a look at the risks and
benefits for President Clinton. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-GOALS (Beijing) _ A curtain-raiser from Beijing, on what
China wants out of the visit. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ZHAO (Beijing) _ A story on the ousted party chief Zhao
Ziyang, who has made an impassioned plea to China's Communist party
to admit the 1989 Tiananmen Square crackdown was a mistake. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   We will update this advisory as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, we call your attention to these stories which have
already moved:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FREEDOM (Shanghai) _ There is a growing realm of personal
freedom in China, where ordinary people now make choices about
travel, work, study and love with less government interference than
at any time in the nearly 50 years since the People's Republic was
established. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MIDDLECLASS (Beijing) _ Like a phoenix rising from the
ashes of communism, the last few years have seen the a stunning
growth of a flourishing Chinese middle class. Ten years ago, this
group did not exist, but now its core of independent businessmen
has been joined by a growing number of private-sector lawyers,
artists and employees of joint-venture companies. It is first
defined by what its members have: computers, microwaves, interior
decorators and, increasingly, cars and homes. But the rapid
accumulation of material things has left its psychological mark as
well, infusing this group with a kind of independence, and carefree
optimism, that has not existed in China for decades. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   (With art)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (Beijing) _ In his global vision, it seems, Bill
Clinton ranks right up there with Richard Nixon. Nixon will ever be
revered here for reviving ties between the United States and the
formerly isolated China. Now, in the days before Clinton arrives
for his first state visit to China, he is being lionized in the
official press and among elements of the intelligentsia as a
far-sighted statesman who had the wisdom to change course with
China, shifting from his initial attack stance to his current
policy of close engagement. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PIRACY (Shanghai) _ Accustomed to putting its best face
forward for an important guest, China is cleaning itself up for
President Clinton's arrival on Thursday. Not only are roads being
repaved, buildings whitewashed and entrance-ways decorated on
countless routes where the president is expected to travel during
his nine days in China, but the authorities are also cracking down
on many of the illegal activities that are ordinarily tolerated
these days, like the sale of pirated video and music compact disks.
By Seth Faison.
</P>
</TEXT>
