<HEADLINE>
GROWTH OF TELECOM EVIDENT AT SUPERCOMM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By Michael E. Kannell   
 c. 1998 Cox News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Supercomm drew attendance from all points on the
telecommunications compass.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day industry trade show here earlier this month, was
attended by an estimated 40,000 people and drew top executives from
companies that make equipment as well as those that provide all
manner of telecom services _ both wired and wireless. A sampling of
conversations with some of these executives shows how quickly the
lucrative field is growing.
</P>
<P>
   Carleton (Carly) Fiorina, president of the global service
provider business at Lucent Technologies, a unit that accounts for
60 percent of Lucent's $26.4 billion in annual revenue, was one of
the many top executives attending Supercomm.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorina, who helped shape Lucent's spinoff from AT&AMP;T, said the
surge of people to Supercomm reflects the industry's stunning
growth. ``We are only beginning to tap the demand. That market is
being driven by an insatiable global demand for data-intensive
applications and mobility.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent came away from AT&AMP;T with one of the greatest research
engines in the world: the 26,000 people at Bell Labs. The company
now sells a wide array of products to so many markets that AT&AMP;T _
once virtually its only customer _ represents only 10 percent of
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent has made several acquisitions and invested in some
start-up companies with interesting technology. But despite the
industry's spate of mergers, Lucent will not again meld itself into
some larger identity, Fiorina said. ``We intend to be a great name
in the 21st century _ with our name intact.''
</P>
<P>
   Teleport Communications Group is headed into the AT&AMP;T fold.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Annunziata, chairman, president and chief executive of
New York-based Teleport, said the spectacular growth of Atlanta has
made the area itself a draw for telecommunications companies.
Teleport, which provides local communications service to
businesses, recently opened an office here.
</P>
<P>
   The company's new role is to provide the shock troops for AT&AMP;T's
assault on the local phone markets, going after the most lucrative
parts of the market served by the regional phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting to the point where people will have a choice,''
Annunziata said.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T does $12 billion a year in business with the regional phone
companies _ money that Teleport can save for the company,
Annunziata said. ``I build the link, and I don't spend that with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The target is huge and growing: ``There is a $105 billion local
market. There is plenty there for us to cut up, so that we can grow
and for the (Bells) to grow as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Vienna, Va.-based Teligent Inc. is building wireless local
networks around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another great opportunity to change the landscape of
local phone service,'' said Richard Hanna, Teligent senior vice
president. ``You don't have to get a huge share of the market to do
well. Teligent is an integrated communications company that offers
small and medium-sized businesses local, long-distance, high-speed
data and Internet services over its own, digital wireless networks
in 74 major metropolitan areas throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The local business market _ which will include local,
long-distance, wireless phones, data and Internet _ will reach $250
billion in 10 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If all politics are local, perhaps all telecommunications will
someday be global.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Walz, president of Iridium North America, came to Supercomm
to promote company plans to start providing a global wireless
service in September using 72 satellites. ``We will flick the
switch, and the world is wired for wireless. If you want one phone,
one number and one invoice, you can do it with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has spent billions of dollars, yet expects no rush
of subscribers. ``Our business plan is predicated on having just
under 5 million customers by 2002. That's out of a market that will
be about 10 or 12 million people.''
</P>
<P>
   However, that small group of customers will likely be the cream
_ traveling professionals who need to stay in touch no matter where
they are and are willing to pay for the privilege. This group
includes executives from huge corporations, ``all the way down to a
small business owner whose livelihood depends on going to Japan,''
Walz said.
</P>
<P>
   At least two other global services are planned.
</P>
<P>
   Iridium's phones, which will cost several thousand dollars will
be capable of bouncing signals off a satellite overhead or
switching to the local cellular phone service _ if there is one.
About 90 percent of the world has no wireless coverage. In fact,
one-third of the United States has none, Walz said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two-thirds of the world's population has no phones at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
