<HEADLINE>
TRACKING COMMERCE ON WEB IS A FULL-TIME JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By Frances Katz   
 c. 1998 Cox News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before the Web was inhabited by the likes of ESPN,
MSNBC, Coca-Cola and Sony, nobody really cared who was surfing the
Web or what exactly they were surfing to. But once the medium
progressed from being a cool pastime for computer hipsters into a
serious business, the corporate world demanded the Web be
quantified and measured. Advertisers wanted to target their
advertising dollars on the Web just as they do on TV and in print.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Relevant Knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based Web measurement firm is one of a handful of
Web tallying wannabes vying for acceptance from corporate bean
counters. Founded in the summer of 1996 by two former Turner
Broadcasting executives, Jeff Levy and Tim Cobb, the company has
taken Nielsen's TV research methods and adapted them to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we looked at the Web, we saw there was nobody applying this
kind of approach,'' Levy says. ``Back in 1995-96, counting how many
`hits' you got didn't provide the kind of information advertisers
needed. Advertisers care about the Nielsen type of stuff,'' he
continues, ``How much time a user spent at a Web site.'' Other
companies such as Media Metrix and Net Ratings use a similar
research model as will Nielsen in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Most advertisers, ad agencies and the research community say
Relevant Knowledge's methodology and third party data assessment is
a Web measurement service they can live with. However, some still
find fault with the company's data, as they do with all current Web
measurement firms. The search engine Alta Vista claimed Relevant
Knowledge has under-reported its actual number of unique visits by
more than 5 million users.
</P>
<P>
   But even with this type of dispute, Levy and Cobb still have the
power to influence major Web media buys from clients such as
Microsoft and Intel. Companies such as the Gen-X Webzine Tripod
frequently cite their high ratings from Relevant Knowledge in their
press releases and company statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The firm also has enough influence in shaping the advertising
standards and naming conventions on mainstream Web sites such as
Yahoo and Warner Brothers to ensure Relevant Knowledge can capture
their data.
</P>
<P>
   Levy and Cobb founded Relevant Knowledge after they decided the
Web wasn't being accurately measured in a way meaningful to
advertisers or the Web sites themselves. ``We said `Wouldn't it be
great if we could get a random group of users and develop a
tracking software and process the data to give to customers?'''
</P>
<P>
   Relevant Knowledge randomly selects a panel of users who agree
to have their Web usage monitored for two years. Participants are
directed to a special Web site to download the software that will
track and record the data of every Web site they visit.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Relevant Knowledge had 6,100 users and are hoping to
ramp up to 10,000 users by the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Levy says the sample Relevant Knowledge uses is larger than the
Nielsen TV sample because there is so much fragmentation on the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not concerned with tracking millions of sites,'' he
says. ``Our focus is on people who are using the Web for commercial
advantage, for buying and selling products.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is constantly surprised by the information it turns
up. ``Observation changes behavior,'' he says. ``My first thought
is that nobody's going to go to a porno site if they knew they were
being watched and we would get this sort of G-rated view of the
Web.''
</P>
<P>
   But what they found out was the software was so unobtrusive that
users were wandering all over the Web to everything from CNN to
more X-rated fare. He also notes 35 users must visit a site before
it is officially recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Levy acknowledges Relevant Knowledge may not be the perfect way
to measure Web usage, but he still believes his company is closer
than most. ``Nobody measures it right,'' he says. ``But we are the
arbiter of who is number one.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
