<HEADLINE>
SECURE IN MY OWN IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Laziness is a vice, but a mighty useful one. Time and again,
it's led people to invent truly clever ways of doing things, simply
to avoid physical or mental labor. In fact, some of the most
interesting recent developments in computer security were created
to cope with the temptation to let things slide.
</P>
<P>
   Most computer security systems depend at least in part on
passwords, a notoriously risky method because of the weaknesses of
human memory. Most of us pick obvious words that are easy for some
vandal to guess. Or we end up using the same password over and over
for different purposes _ logging onto the office network, for
instance, and getting our electronic mail, and signing on to
America Online. It's all because we're too busy or too lazy to
memorize a couple dozen different passwords, or to pick words like,
say, syzygy, that you don't see every day.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the Holy Grail of data security is the creation of
systems that can let authorized individuals get control of a
computer without having to memorize anything.
</P>
<P>
   Now the solution is at hand, thanks to a technology you'll be
hearing a lot about in the next few years. It's called biometrics,
and it's about letting people use their own physical
characteristics as a password. In essence, we're teaching computers
to recognize an individual by his glance, his touch or the sound of
his voice.
</P>
<P>
   It works, too. Several Boston-area firms, including Miros Inc.
of Wellesley, Viisage Technology Inc. of Littleton and Polaroid
Corp. of Cambridge, sell security systems that let companies
identify people's faces.
</P>
<P>
   This stuff is presently beyond the reach of small businesses or
individuals, but other biometric products aim for the paranoiac on
a budget. Voiceprint software, for instance, doesn't require any
special hardware _ just a computer with a sound card and a
microphone, which is standard issue these days.
</P>
<P>
   A Chicago company called Veritel offers a voiceprint product for
locking up your most sensitive computer files. Its $59.95
VoiceCrypt system is available for Windows 95, 98 and NT systems.
It lets you do drag-and-drop encryption of any files on your
computer, making them unreadable by nosy colleagues. Nothing new
there _ products like Norton Your Eyes Only have offered this
capability for quite a while. What makes VoiceCrypt especially cool
is that you get access to the files by reciting a password into a
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Most speech-recognition programs, like Dragon Systems Inc.'s
Naturally Speaking and IBM's ViaVoice, are designed for dictating
memos into a word processor. You must spend a couple of hours
training these programs to recognize your voice. But VoiceCrypt
only needs a minute or so to analyze the characteristics of your
voice. You also type in answers to test questions that serve as a
backup password _ for instance, what color was your first car? If
you ever lose your voice, you can still type your way into the
system, without having to memorize yet another password.
</P>
<P>
   During a test of VoiceCrypt, I sometimes had to repeat myself
several times before the software could identify me. I also found
that it isn't too choosy about passwords. I could say any word that
came to mind, and VoiceCrypt would let me in if it recognized my
voice. But VoiceCrypt passed the most important test: Several of my
colleagues have tried to talk their way past it, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   There are other biometric possibilities for those willing to buy
extra hardware. The Canadian firm American Biometric Co. sells
BioMouse, a $299 device that plugs into a parallel port and reads
your fingerprints. Just press a digit against the BioMouse and
you're in.
</P>
<P>
   Some caution is in order. Biometric systems raise an important
privacy concern. You don't want firms sharing your faceprint,
fingerprint or voiceprint data with other firms, or the government,
without your permission. And they ought to store the data in an
encrypted format so nobody can steal it. I foresee the need for a
federal biometric privacy law before we'll feel entirely safe
around these gadgets. But imagine being able to read your e-mail by
saying ``open sesame,'' or getting money out of an ATM simply by
staring at it. It's a lazy man's dream.
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-18-98 1303EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
