<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-MAC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT IN THE CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DOUG BAILEY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite signs that Apple Computer Inc. is making a comeback _
analysts suggest the company will grow faster in the next nine
months than it has in the past two years _ software developers are
still wary about supporting the Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the evidence is anecdo-tal: A sales rep at an Oregon
company called Mentor Plus, which makes the only flight planning
software available for the Mac, advised me last week to buy the
Windows version because his company may soon abandon the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Other instances prove to be temporary: Intuit Inc., maker of the
best-selling Quicken financial management package, said earlier
this year it would no longer support the Mac, but reversed itself
within days after Apple revealed its new retail strategy, which
included bundling Quicken on its new computers.
</P>
<P>
   As Apple fans, we've learned to live with the uncertainty about
the future of our software. But it's infuriating when the company
folding the tent on Apple products is Apple itself.
</P>
<P>
   I've written before about the strange saga of the Apple PC
Compatibility Card, a plug-in device that puts a Pentium processor
under the Apple hood, allowing you to switch between operating
systems. Apple unveiled the card not too long ago, saying it was
100 percent compatible with Windows 95. But the card, which cost
about $900, could barely run Windows 95 and then could only run
about half of the programs written for it. The problem was it came
with 16-bit drivers that did not support many of the new features
in Windows 95, including long file names. Compared with
compatibility software solutions made by Connectix Corp. (Virtual
PC) and Insignia Co. (SoftWindows), Apple's expensive hardware
device was only marginally better in some areas and much worse in
others.
</P>
<P>
   When card owners complained, Apple hinted it would update the
card with 32-bit drivers. But suddenly, late last year, Apple
abandoned support for the card altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Mark Fonnemann, a Boston College student who, like me, was
stuck with a barely usable PC card for his Mac. Fonnemann started
an Internet campaign to reverse Apple's decision. Failing that, he
tried for months to persuade another company, Orange Micro Inc.,
which also makes PC compatibility cards for the Mac, to produce
32-bit drivers for the Apple card.
</P>
<P>
   Fonnemann, with the help of thousands of Mac users stuck in a
similar situation, almost succeeded. Orange agreed to help rescue
buyers of Apple's card but needed cooperation from Apple to get at
its proprietary software code. Apple refused.
</P>
<P>
   The story doesn't end there, though. Orange last week released a
new 32-bit version of its PC compatibility card and offered it to
owners of the Apple cards for just $399 (the product lists for
$549). By offering the new card, Orange believes Apple card owners
will be able to salvage some of their original investment _ the
Windows 95 operating system ($129) and possibly the extra RAM
bought for the card. However, Orange's card comes with just 16
megabytes of the new SDRAM, just barely enough to run Windows 95
plus some other programs. Adding more SDRAM will bring the price of
the card into the $500 to $800 range.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the response to Orange's program, which lasts
until August, has been so overwhelming the company was unable to
send me a card for evaluation in time for this column. But
Fonnemann has one and his review, along with his lengthy
correspondence with Apple and Orange, can be viewed on his Web site
at www2.bc.edu/(tilde)fonneman/apple.html.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, anyone want to buy an Apple PC Compatibility
card? Cheap.
</P>
<P>
   (Doug Bailey can be contacted at dbaile(at)mediaone.net)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-18-98 1318EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
