<SLUG> BC-CPT-HOLT-INTERNET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL TOY COMPANY SEEKS NET ADVANTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. _ Many small retailers are trying to figure out
how to make the Internet work for them. Holt Co. thinks it's found
a way.
</P>
<P>
   When Roz and Ed Holt started Holt Co. in 1979, the small Waltham
firm sold school furniture and equipment, such as overhead
projectors, to private schools. Today, the couple's son, Paul,
presides over a toy retailer and school supplier that aims to sell
most of its merchandise over the Internet, rather than from its
cramped Holt Educational Outlet store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to grow this company,'' says Holt, president
of the $10 million private firm. ``The research I have done says
the fastest, most economical way to grow was the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Holt Educational's technological refocusing, which
Holt estimates cost the company $300,000, is a tale of a successful
foray onto the World Wide Web, a medium that has brought mixed
sales results for both the toy industry and businesses in general.
This month, Holt plans to launch version 2.0 of its Web site, along
with separate sites for its subsidiaries. In a few years, Holt
says, he intends to take the privately financed company public.
</P>
<P>
   And Holt, which sells its products over the Internet, through a
mail-order catalog, and in its retail outlet, is anticipating
on-line growth. Currently, 10 percent of Holt's sales are from the
Web site; Paul Holt predicts those sales will rise to 50 percent of
the total next year.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials say Holt Educational, unlike other educational
and general toy stores, found profits on the Web because of its
integrated financial and ordering systems and its attention to
customer preferences in designing the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Holt's specialization in educational toys, particularly those
for children with learning disabilities, has also helped the
company create its own niche: developmental toys for busy,
well-educated, high-income parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parents who are on the Internet have no time,'' says David
N. Lord, promoted from chief financial officer to chief executive
just this week. ``It's a lot harder to buy an educational toy than
to buy a Barbie.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1979, Holt Educational has branched out from educational
supplies, creating a school furniture division, Holt Furniture
Environments, and a communications hardware subsidiary, GroupCom,
which markets videoconferencing equipment and related items.
</P>
<P>
   But the core business remains Holt Educational, run out of a
basement miniwarehouse below Holt's corporate offices, packed with
toys, teachers' supplies, and brightly colored stickers. Unlike
Toys ``R'' Us and other mass retailers, Holt concentrates on toys
that develop skills, such as reading or coordination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't sell the metal trains with a generator,'' Lord says.
``We sell the wooden ones which the child puts together. My
three-year-old daughter plays with her wooden train every night.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the modernization of this division that Paul Holt decided
to tackle first. That was almost three years ago. Holt Educational
already had a mail-order catalog business, but adapting to Internet
commerce required a technological overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   First, Holt hired Lord, a former department store executive with
a degree in accounting, as finance chief and chief information
officer. Lord, like all members of Holt's senior management team,
has young children.
</P>
<P>
   The plan Holt and Lord devised called for scrapping the
company's old computer system and buying new hardware. Of paramount
importance was integrating the new accounting and Web commerce
software so orders coming in over the Internet would not have to be
typed into a separate inventory system.
</P>
<P>
   With the Great Plains accounting program and Microsoft's Site
Server 3.0, which Holt Educational was the first to test in April,
the outlet's Web site reduced transaction costs from $2.25 to 50
cents, Lord says.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you order on our Web site, it automatically prints out a
packing list and we ship it,'' Holt says.
</P>
<P>
   Holt Education has 20,000 products available on its Web site; by
year's end, Lord says, 50,000 toys will be available. Holt's
12-member Web development team also included what Lord calls
``value-added'' features, like a regular advice column written by a
Lesley College education professor. The site's gift registry has
10,000 child subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Holt's site also allows customers to search for toys by several
criteria, including price, manufacturer, and category. Buyers can
track the status of their orders on a special FedEx package
tracking page. The company is continuously tailoring the site to
consumers' interests: when management discovered that longtime
store customers were printing their order forms off the Web site
and bringing them into the store to avoid paying shipping costs,
Holt decided to plan an in-store fulfillment center for this
year'sholiday season.
</P>
<P>
   And the efforts are paying off, Holt and Lord say: the average
site visitor looks at 21 pages, and 50 percent of Web hits are
return visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a year from now, we feel the Internet will overtake the
catalog,'' he says. The company is growing about 20 percent a year,
with sales for next year projected to be about $12 million. Of
that, about $2 million are expected to come from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Building on what they see as a successful formula, Holt and Lord
say the site's updated version will include customer profiling,
allowing the company's computers to automatically show specific
products that individuals have ordered or looked at previously.
``It makes it easier to shop on our site,'' Holt says.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Holt is not the largest toy company around, nor has
its Web site established itself as the most popular place to buy
toys on the Internet. Indeed, the market leader, Paramus,
N.J.-based Toys ``R'' Us Inc., this week launched its own Web site,
which will sell mainly mass-market toys such as Barbie. And other
competing Web sites abound, particularly those that sell Beanie
Babies and other hot toys.
</P>
<P>
   eToys, a Santa Monica, Calif.-based Web toy seller financed by
venture capital, launched a site in March 1997 that features both
educational and mass-market toys. While the company won't release
sales or Web hits figures, eToys says it sells 3,000 products over
the 'Net. It recently bought rival Toys.com.
</P>
<P>
   Jane E. Saltzman, vice president for merchandising at eToys,
says sites like hers combine the interactivity of a retail store
with the 'Net's search capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that's really great about being on the Internet,''
she says, is that the addition of eToys' keyword searches lets
customers ``recreate the absolute best experience of being in a
land-based store.''
</P>
<P>
   Fierce competition on the Internet also forces retailers to
constantly monitor prices, making toys cheaper, says Jerry
Bloomberger, who owns La Toys Etc., a Cedarhurst, N.Y.-based retail
store and Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the airline system, where you can get a Delta flight
for $100 and then you see a USAirways flight for less,'' says
Bloomberger, who specializes in Beanie Babies and other hot toys.
</P>
<P>
   But some retailers say the future of toy stores may not depend
on Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The folks I now that have gone on the Internet haven't had a
tremendous amount of success with it,'' says Sally Lesser, owner of
two Henry Bear's Park toy stores in Cambridge and Newton, and
president of the American Specialty Toy Retailing Association, a
trade group with 700 members. ``I'm not sure that the people on the
'Net, once they visit your site, are going to become your
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   And industry specialists disagree over whether the Web is an
effective medium for marketing toys at all. Some argue that even if
the Web does hold promise for toy sellers, Holt may not be the
best-positioned company to do business on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe value is inherent in the product, my sense is
that people are looking for more than a discount,'' says David L.
Hesel, a toy store owner and industry consultant in Concord, and
past president of ASTRA, who calls Holt ``a nonplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   At Holt Educational Outlet, nonetheless, Holt and Lord see the
Internet as their future. Indeed, they say, only differentiation
from other companies' Web sites will ensure their success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years from now, every company will be on the Internet,''
Lord predicts. ``It goes back to adding value.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-19-98 1358EDT &QL;
</P>
