<HEADLINE>
PARTITIONING COULD ADD CAPACITY, BUT NOT A WHOLE NEW HARD DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN   
 c.1998 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have a 1.2-gigabyte hard disk with 1 GB used up. I was told
I could effectively have a 2- or 3-GB hard disk by partitioning it.
True? If so, how do I go about it? And if I want to add a 5- or
6-GB hard drive, how can I tell if my system would support it?
</P>
<P>
   A. Someone gave you some bad information. It would be wonderful
if partitioning a hard disk could double its capacity, but no,
that's not true.
</P>
<P>
   Partitioning breaks a large hard drive into what appears to your
system to be multiple, smaller drives. It's like building a wall on
your drive, and saying everything on one side of the wall is drive
C, and everything on the other is drive D. You don't get two 1-GB
drives; instead, your 1.2-GB drive becomes two 600-MB drives _ or
however you configure them if they are not identical sizes.
</P>
<P>
   You can gain some hard drive space by partitioning, though. As
I've written in this space before, in the original File Allocation
Table system used with MS-DOS and early Windows 95, smaller drives
require less overhead per file, known as clusters. Bigger drives
require bigger clusters, so more space is wasted per file. The
wasted space, known as ``slack,'' can be as much as 40 percent of a
big drive.
</P>
<P>
   You don't necessarily need to partition, however, if you have
the right operating system. FAT32, a kind of file system found in
the most recent versions of Windows 95 and in the upcoming Windows
98, reduces cluster size on larger disks. When I converted a 1.2-GB
drive that was about 66 percent full to FAT32 recently, I gained
about 120 MB from the smaller cluster size! The amount of reclaimed
space varies, depending on the size and number of files on your
hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Whether your system will support an extra-large drive depends on
the operating system and the system's BIOS, which manages a PC's
most basic systems. Check with the manufacturer of your computer to
see what it will support. You probably can use special software
that would come with such a disk that would let an older PC see all
of the large drive's capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I bought a computer about a year ago that came with USB
ports. I haven't had a need to use them until now. I bought a
digital camera that uses USB and I can't get it to work. My system
doesn't see the USB ports, even though I have the add-in for
Windows 95 that enables USB support. What am I doing wrong?
</P>
<P>
   A. Many early systems with USB ports were shipped with the
feature turned off in the BIOS. Check the manual for your PC to see
how to get into the BIOS' setup feature. From there, look for a
setting to toggle your USB ports on or off.
</P>
<P>
   However, be aware that doing this will take up one of the
interrupt settings in your system, also known as IRQs. These are
the doorways through which your system's various devices talk to
the main processor. The USB ports, fortunately, take only one IRQ _
each device you add to the USB ports (they will hold more than
120!) will not require a separate IRQ.
</P>
<P>
   If you are out of available IRQs, you may have to do some
juggling, and even disable other devices, to turn your USB ports
on.
</P>
<P>
   Although most PCs have only two USB ports, you can now buy USB
hubs _ boxes with multiple ports that attach to the main port on
your PC. Like the hub used in an Ethernet network, it requires a
power supply. It has the benefit of bringing your USB ports up to
your desktop, instead of being stuck on the back of your CPU. Then,
you can plug several devices at once _ say, your digital camera, a
scanner, maybe even a mouse and keyboard _ into the hub.
</P>
<P>
   Got a question about your computer? Maybe Computing columnist
Dwight Silverman can help. Send e-mail to
dwight.silvermanchron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
