<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST IN THEIR CLASS STILL AREN'T PERFECT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN   
 c.1998 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intel Corp.'s Pentium II chip finally has made it into notebook
computers, which is something of an engineering feat. Anyone who's
seen what the Pentium II desktop chip looks like _ it's remarkably
similar in size and shape to a video game cartridge _ can
appreciate what it takes to cram it into a portable machine.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of Pentium II-based notebook computers have two other
challenges with this chip. First, it runs hot _ very, very hot. The
heat sink, a metal device that draws heat away from the chip, is
massive on the desktop version, further complicating the portable
design issues.
</P>
<P>
   And the Pentium II is a hungry chip. In order to provide lots of
computing power, it gobbles battery power.
</P>
<P>
   I discovered these problems the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   I use a portable computer to take notes when I conduct
interviews, and I often don't have a table to work on when I'm
talking to subjects. By the end of my first lap-based interview
using a Pentium II system, I was holding the notebook by the edges
with my knees to keep from scalding my thighs. Yeow!
</P>
<P>
   And flying from Houston to New York and trying to write this
column, I realized I'd better type fast. Trying to write on a plane
became a race against the clock. While traditional Pentium-based
notebook computers routinely get 3 to 4 hours of battery life, I
was hard-pressed to eke 2{ hours out of either of the Pentium II
notebooks I tried.
</P>
<P>
   Other than those two downsides _ and they are substantial _ both
systems I looked at were impressive.
</P>
<P>
   IBM ThinkPad 600 _ $4,350, IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for the aforementioned heat and power problems and a
couple of glitches, the ThinkPad 600 comes pretty close to
fulfilling my elusive dream of finding the perfect notebook
computer. This is one fine portable.
</P>
<P>
   The model I tried had a 266-megahertz Pentium II chip, 32
megabytes of memory, a four-gigabyte hard drive, a built-in 56K
modem, stereo sound and speakers, a 13.3-inch active matrix
display, a removable CD-ROM drive that could be replaced by a
floppy disk, all the ports you'd expect and headphone and
microphone jacks.
</P>
<P>
   As with all ThinkPads, it uses the TrackPoint pointing device,
and it remains the best implementation of this style of pointer.
The TrackPoint, which looks like an eraser jammed between the G, H
and B keys, is responsive, yet precise.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard has a near-perfect feel _ not too mushy, but not so
stiff that your fingers tire quickly. The layout is nice, too _ I
didn't find myself accidentally bumping the wrong keys, or hitting
the backspace key when I meant to hit delete.
</P>
<P>
   The 600 is relatively small for a Pentium II notebook _ most of
the others I've seen and tried are full-sized machines. This is
thin, about an inch, with a relatively small footprint. It weighs
about five pounds when stripped down to its barest essentials.
</P>
<P>
   However, it can be frustrating to use. It would not run my word
processor of choice, WordPerfect 8, no matter how many times I
reinstalled or applied service patches to the software. And the
modem was a bit flaky, occasionally refusing to connect to a
variety of other systems.
</P>
<P>
   The ThinkPad comes with all kinds of goodies. The modem can be
used as a speakerphone, and there's software support on board for a
video phone.
</P>
<P>
   But, there are the heat and power issues. The ThinkPad couldn't
make the Houston-to-New York run without petering out. And you can
keep your coach-class meal quite warm by resting it on the
ThinkPad's bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Latitude CPi _ $3,300, Dell Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The Latitude is Dell's bread-and-butter business portable, the
one it aims at big companies. Dell plans to keep its design the
same for some time, so computer departments don't go nuts trying to
keep up with the changes.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean this isn't a state-of-the-art machine. The
Latitude is fast _ it really approaches desktop power. It also has
a sleek, classy design, being only 1{ inches thick. Although it's
the same size as most other full-sized notebooks, its curved
corners and sculpted cover make it look more compact than it is.
Like the ThinkPad, it weighs about five pounds when stripped for
travel.
</P>
<P>
   The Latitude I tried was similar in configuration to the
ThinkPad, though it came with 64 megabytes of memory, which is
standard. It lacked the ThinkPad's built-in modem _ in fact, one is
not even available from Dell, which I think is a mistake. Dell will
sell you a PC card, but PC-card modems get lost and damaged. I'd
rather have one built inside the unit. However, it does have a
built-in Ethernet connection.
</P>
<P>
   The Latitude also has a relatively dark screen. Even at full
strength, it wasn't as bright as the ThinkPad. And if you turn it
down to save battery life, you'll find yourself squinting a lot.
</P>
<P>
   The Latitude uses a flat touch panel as its pointer. It's a
rather poor implementation of that technology. Fiddling with the
settings, I could never get it right _ it was either sluggish or it
zipped across the screen at the slightest touch.
</P>
<P>
   The keyboard, though, is as nice as the ThinkPad's. It's got a
softer touch, but still has a solid feel.
</P>
<P>
   The Dell got quite toasty on the bottom _ it was the model that
had me gripping its sides with my knees _ and its battery life was
dismal. I averaged about two hours with it, mainly because I didn't
want to turn the screen down to save power.
</P>
<P>
   While the power of these systems is undeniable _ with the
exception of the G3-based Apple PowerBooks, these are the fastest
portables you can buy _ heat and poor battery life make them
underachievers when it comes to the needs of road warriors. They'd
probably be fine as desktop replacements if the furthest you take
them from the office is your own living room.
</P>
<P>
   Got a comment or question about computing? Send e-mail to
dwight.silvermanchron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-19-98 1411EDT &QL;
</P>
