 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Just for Fun: Philips' hand-held unit performs many functions
worthy of PC  
 By Yusuf Davis   
 c. 1998 Cox News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTANTA _ The Velo 500 from Philips is a hand-held PC whose
price and functions land it midway between a personal digital
assistant and a laptop PC.
</P>
<P>
   Using Windows CE (the pared-down version of Windows) as the
operating system and 24 megabytes of memory, the Velo can perform
many of the tasks of a portable PC, including light word
processing, connecting to the Internet and sending and receiving
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Equipped with a large, bright screen, the Velo is easy to see
and use. It has a built-in 28.8k bps modem, which is accessed
through a pop-up phone jack.
</P>
<P>
   With miniature card slots for memory expansion and system
software upgrades, the unit is totally upgradable and will be
useful for years to come. Like other PDAs, the Velo has a tiny
keyboard, which reduces typing to hunt-and-peck.
</P>
<P>
   A docking station, AC adapter, phone cable and rechargable
battery pack are included.
</P>
<P>
   The Velo 500 has a suggested retail price of $650. For more
information, visit the Web site http://www.velo.philips.com.
</P>
<P>
   Saving your memories
</P>
<P>
   The Snapshot Photo Scanner can help you turn that shoebox full
of snapshots into a digital photo album in your computer. When
digitized, the images can be stored for posterity, edited for fun
and profit, or incorporated into other documents.
</P>
<P>
   Just plug the scanner into any Windows-compatible PC (sorry Mac
users) and the unit is ready to go. It will accept photos up to 4
inches by 6 inches and deliver images with an 800-by-1,200 pixel
resolution, in a rainbow of colors.
</P>
<P>
   Bundled with a variety of image-editing software, the package
contains everything you need to organize and store images or create
dazzling documents, snazzy images and other special effects. You
can also use the software to drop your pictures into pre-designed
greeting cards, invitations, certificates or awards. Or you can
create your own cards and calendars and send them all as e-mail
messages.
</P>
<P>
   For information, visit the Web site http://www.kodak.com.
</P>
<P>
   Quick, grab that image
</P>
<P>
   Another good way to get images into your computer is with the
QuickClip from Connectix. The difference between this unit and a
scanner is that QuickClip is an image-capture device, able to grab
video images as well as still images from a source and transfer
them to a computer file.
</P>
<P>
   QuickClip will grab images from a camcorder, VCR or laser disc
and place them into Web pages, newsletters and e-mail messages. It
comes with all the necessary software to capture images and store
them in a number of sizes and formats.
</P>
<P>
   Though it works well with Windows 95, QuickClip is designed
primarily for use with Windows 98 and is one of the first USB
devices available for video capture. It can grab up to 15 frames
per second and digitize them to a PC image in less than a minute.
</P>
<P>
   QuickClip retails for $99 and can be seen at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .connectix.com.
</P>
<P>
   A mechanical helper
</P>
<P>
   Emiglio is a multitalented, remote-controlled robot that can
serve as waiter or the life of the party. His eyes light up and his
helmet flashes as he roams about the room doing his master's
bidding.
</P>
<P>
   With movements directed with a wireless remote control, this
2-foot-tall robot can carry refreshments on a removable tray and
transport small objects in his spring-loaded digits or larger
objects in his included backpack.
</P>
<P>
   A microphone in the remote lets users supply Emiglio's voice. He
can speak in your voice or transform your words into a futuristic
digitized voice or a mechanical-sounding robot voice.
</P>
<P>
   When the party's over, Emiglio becomes a sentry night light.
Just plug in the included AC adapter and his helmet glows to
illuminate a hallway, entry or child's room.
</P>
<P>
   Available from the Sharper Image, Emiglio retails for $99.95.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-19-98 1934E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
