 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Cyberscene: Ocean of information available for boating
enthusiasts  
 By Bill Husted   
 c. 1998 Cox News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Long before there were brave surfers navigating
cyberspace, there were men -- and women -- who went to sea in
boats.
</P>
<P>
   While you might not be ready to go to sea today, this is the
right time of the year to spend some time on a lake, river or pond
in a boat. Whether you are an old hand or just now considering
taking up boating, you can use the sea of information on the World
Wide Web to set a fun and safe course.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go boating. In fact, let's go to Lets Go Boating, a Web
site at http://www.letsgoboating.com/. This is a good starting
point because most of the information is aimed at the beginner.
You'll find topic areas such as ``How much does it cost?'' ``Where
can I go?'' and ``How do I learn?'' There's also a link that will
take you to an area that will let you search for local marinas (a
great resource, since many both rent and sell boats).
</P>
<P>
   Our next port of call is called Boating America, and you can
find it at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .boatingamerica.com/. This is really a fine place to spend some
time. One of the few things associated with boating that doesn't
cost money are the stories boaters tell each other, some of 'em
true. You'll find a selection of these stories on this page.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just the start. You'll also be able to get
information about boating conditions in each of the states, browse
classified ads for boats that are for sale, and view sections
featuring gadgets that can soon deplete even the most generous
budget and tips on boating safety.
</P>
<P>
   One of the handiest features here is the bulletin board section
at http://www.boatingamerica
</P>
<P>
   .com/bbs/. You'll be able to leave notes for other users, asking
for advice or giving it. Things get really specific here. Where
else could you find a heated discussion about the valve adjustments
for a Mercury 3.0-liter Mercruiser engine? The value of this area
is the ability to get the sort of exact information and help you
wouldn't be able to find in the articles and features.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the best boating water around can be found in Army Corps
of Engineers lakes. That's why you may want to bookmark a site at
http://www.gorp.com
</P>
<P>
   /gorp/resource/us(underscore)nra/ace
</P>
<P>
   /ga.htm that lets you search these lakes and recreation areas by
state. You'll find 10 entries for Georgia, starting with Lake
Allatoona and finishing up with West Point Lake. Once on that page,
you can click on any of the 10 entries for screens full of really
specific information -- everything from fees, to a breakdown of the
recreational facilities and launching areas, to information about
hiking and camping.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Mall at http://
</P>
<P>
   www.themarinemall.com/ is mostly about buying stuff, but then so
is boating. There's a discussion forum that has areas for topics
such as fishing, boat handling and mechanical and maintenance tips.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find also links here to various retailers and
manufacturers as well as a classified ad listing. But there is
more, including links to various other boating pages as well as
links to weather information and a boating events calendar.
</P>
<P>
   One link that should come in especially handy is to the U.S.
Coast Guard. You'll find tips for boating safety here as well as
help understanding the rules and regulations for boating.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
