<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Is Earthlink Linked to Scientology?  
 By David Einstein   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I recently read in an online publica tion that Earthlink _
one of the largest Internet service providers _ is run by the
Church of Scientology. Is this true, or is it one of those
unfounded Internet rumors?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  The latter seems to be the case. It's true that Earthlink
founder Sky Dylan Dayton is a Scientologist, as were several other
top officials of the company when it started out. The company early
on also got some business from the church and its affiliates. But
the church appears to wield no influence over the company, nor is
there evidence that Dayton pressured workers to join up.
</P>
<P>
   FYI, Scientology came under heavy fire on the Internet after it
sued another ISP, Netcom, because a disgruntled former Scientology
minister posted copyrighted church documents on a bulletin board
that had a contract with Netcom. The postings included a 17-page
transcript of confidential lectures by Scientology founder L. Ron
Hubbard. Netcom settled the suit in the summer of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I'm getting ready to take the plunge and buy a notebook
computer. Is it worth spending more for an active matrix display,
or is dual scan good enough. I plan to use the computer for word
processing, some spreadsheet work and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; An active matrix display (also known as TFT) contains more
than 1 million transistors _ three behind every pixel on the
screen. By comparison, a dual scan display uses just a couple of
thousand transistors that send signals through wires behind the
screen. Not surprisingly, active matrix provides a sharper picture,
which can be seen well even when viewing at an angle. By
comparison, dual scan displays are not as bright, and tend to
deteriorate when viewed at an angle. If you think you'll be using
your new notebook on a desk with proper lighting, a dual scan
display should be fine. But if you'll be working on a bus, a train
or a plane, active matrix is the way to go. It's also a must if you
plan to use the notebook for presentations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to providing a clearer picture, active matrix can
handle more colors and higher resolution than dual scan. But all
these advantages come with a price. You can expect to pay at least
$600 more for active matrix in a new notebook.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  Long URLs don't fit in the space allowed for it on my
Internet Explorer browser. How can I look at the whole thing to
make sure I typed it correctly?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  Try this: Place your mouse pointer just to the left of
where it says Links on the address bar (just to the right of the
address space). The pointer should turn into a short line with
arrows at either end. Hold down the left mouse button and drag to
the right to increase the size of the address space.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I'm about to buy a new computer, and I'd like to be able to
transfer my Favorite Places and Address Book entries to the new
computer from AOL on my old computer. Is there and easy way to do
this?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  Relatively easy. The Favorite Places are saved in a file
named after your screen name. Typically you'll find it in
c:aol30organize. Your address book info is in two files, AddrBk.ind
and AddrBk.lst, both of which are in c:aol30idb.
</P>
<P>
   Using Windows Explorer (which you'll find in the Programs menu),
save those three files to a floppy disk. Then place them in the
same folders in AOL on your new computer. (You may be asked if you
want to overwrite files already installed. Go ahead and do it.)
Then you should have access to your Address Book and Favs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I've been having a problem printing out pages from Web
sites. The last line of the page is sliced in half, with the top
half of the line at the bottom of the first page and the bottom
half of the line at the top of the next page. While it's usually
legible, it's still annoying. Any solutions?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  Try adjusting your margin settings. Click the file menu in
your browser and choose Page Setup. Then decrease the bottom margin
a little.
</P>
<P>
   Tip of the Week &QC; AOL users who are involved in fantasy baseball
leagues can set up a portfolio that includes statistics for all the
players on their fantasy team. Go to the keyword Stats BB, then
click Player Portfolio and follow the instructions. After creating
your portfolio you can check how your players did today, yesterday,
for the past week, two weeks, three weeks or for the entire season.
You can also get information on injuries and player transactions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com.
</P>
