<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 12:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4230 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON     06-24 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT DISMISSES WINDOWS 95 INJUNCTION  
 BY JULIA ANGWIN  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft won a short-lived legal triumph _ and sparked hopes of
a long-term victory _ against federal antitrust enforcers yesterday
when a federal appeals court overturned an injunction against
Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling will become moot tomorrow when Microsoft launches the
successor to Windows 95 _ the Windows 98 operating system _ at a
party in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But legal experts say the U.S. Court of Appeals decision bodes
poorly for the government's separate lawsuit against Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates an uphill battle for the government,'' said Sam
Miller, a San Francisco attorney who led the anti-Microsoft case at
the Justice Department four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The news caused Microsoft stock to soar $4.94 to an all-time
high of $100.75 and boosted the value of Microsoft chief executive
Bill Gates' holdings by $2.7 billion to $54.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   However, experts cautioned investors against irrational
exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over yet,'' said David Readerman, analyst at
NationsBanc Montgomery Securities. ``But it gives Microsoft some
support for its September 8 trial (on Windows 98).''
</P>
<P>
   Government antitrust enforcers are currently battling Microsoft
on two related fronts: Windows 95 and Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   On Windows 95, federal prosecutors accused Microsoft in October
of violating a 1995 antitrust agreement by requiring
computer-makers that want Windows 95 to install Microsoft's Web
browser. In December, a federal judge temporarily barred Microsoft
from forcing computer-makers to accept both products.
</P>
<P>
   On Windows 98, the Justice Department and 20 states accused
Microsoft last month of violating a broader set of federal
antitrust laws by using its monopoly power in operating system
software to muscle its way into the Internet market. A trial is set
for September 8.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's decision by a three-judge panel overturned on
procedural grounds the December preliminary injunction issued by
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson against Windows 95. The panel
unanimously found that Microsoft was not given adequate notice
before the injunction was issued.
</P>
<P>
   That means that in 90 days Microsoft will be free to require
computer-makers to install Internet Explorer with Windows 95.
However, while Microsoft will continue to offer Windows 95,
customers are likely to pick Windows 98 instead.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also unanimously overturned on procedural grounds the
lower court's decision to appoint Harvard law professor Lawrence
Lessig as a ``special master'' to help on the case.
</P>
<P>
   However, the panel stopped short of calling Lessig biased _ a
claim Microsoft made after discovering that the professor had once
written an e-mail that contained anti-Microsoft sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   And the panel split 2 to 1 on the most important part of the
ruling _ the question of whether Microsoft has the right to include
separate products such as its Web browser in the Windows operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has long argued that it has the right to put anything
it wants in its software _ even a ham sandwich _ if that is what
customers want.
</P>
<P>
   Judges Stephen Williams and Raymond Randolph appeared to
substantiate Microsoft's argument in the majority opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to imagine how the ruling could have been better for
Microsoft,'' said Joe Sims, antitrust attorney at Jones Day, Revis
&AMP; Pogue in Washington DC.
</P>
<P>
   In their 38-page decision, the two judges wrote that Microsoft
should be allowed to integrate any two products that work better
together than separately ``regardless of whether ... (they) ... are
marketed separately.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Patricia Wald wrote in a dissenting opinion that the
benefits of integration should be balanced against evidence that
the two products serve separate markets.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft attorney William Neukom said he believes the 2-to-1
victory will give ``substantive guidance'' to Judge Jackson, who
must decide later this year whether Windows 98 illegally includes
Microsoft's Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty fatal to the government's case,'' added Charles F.
Rule, a Washington antitrust attorney who consults for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said it was ``disappointed'' with the
appeals court decision and was ``reviewing its options.'' It could
ask the entireDistrict of Columbia Circuit Court of Appeals to
review the panel's decision or it could appeal directly to the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   And Microsoft competitors said it's too soon to count them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real battle will occur ... in September,'' said Mike
Pettit, executive director of ProComp, an anti-Microsoft coalition
based in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's just another twist in the protracted legal
battle between the government and the software giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, this is a very good day for Microsoft,'' said Rich Gray,
a San Jose antitrust attorney. ``But the Justice Department's
lawsuit is still very much alive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-23-98 2313EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
