<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4238 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COURT-MICROSOFT-B     06-24 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COURT-MICROSOFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING ALLOWS MICROSOFT TO REQUIRE BROWSER WITH WINDOWS 95 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US government's landmark antitrust campaign against
Microsoft Corp. was dealt a potentially serious blow Tuesday, after
a federal Appeals Court threw out an injunction that restricted the
way Microsoft can sell its Windows 95 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   In a broadly worded ruling, the federal Appeals Court for the
District of Columbia overturned a temporary injunction issued in
December that had barred Microsoft from requiring computer makers
to include Microsoft's Internet Explorer browsing software on
machines that run the Windows 95 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ruling could weaken the government's position in a
much broader case brought by the Justice Department and 20 states
on May 18. That case alleged Microsoft abuses its market power to
thwart competition. The issue of whether Internet Explorer and
Windows can be bundled together also is at the heart of the case,
which will be tried in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is bad news for Justice,'' Robert Litan, a former senior
antitrust enforcer at the department told Bloomberg News.``On the
surface it looks like it cuts the legs out from under Justice on
the browser operating system part of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives hailed the ruling as vindication of the
firm's long-standing practice of adding new features to its
operating systems. The decision ``affirms our central principle of
every company being able to improve its products and integrate new
features for the benefit of consumers,'' said Microsoft chief
operating officer Bob Herbold.
</P>
<P>
   The company's chief legal counsel, William Neukom, said the
ruling should also apply to the government's broadercase against
Microsoft. ``Many of the government's arguments in the lawsuit
filed last month are identical to their arguments in the case just
decided in favor of Microsoft,'' Neukom said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft stock soared on Tuesday's news, closing at 100 3/4, up
4 15/16 on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department issued a statement expressing
disappointment,and saying that antitrust regulators were
considering their next moves. ``We remain confident that the
evidence and our legal arguments in our antitrust case filed on May
18, 1998 will demonstrate that Microsoft's conduct has violated
federal antitrust law,'' the statement added.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has argued that by forcing companies that
use Windows 95 to also use Microsoft's browser, the company is
shutting out competition from rival browser makers, like Netscape
Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's 2-1 ruling, the court threw out an injunction
issued by US District JudgeThomas Penfield Jackson in Washington
and held that Microsoft did not violate a 1995 consent decree with
antitrust regulators. The Appeals Court said that because a
combined operating system and browser would benefit customers, the
1995 consent decree ``does not bar Microsoft from offering it as
one product.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the ruling, Microsoft is once again free to compel
computer makers to install Windows 95 with the Internet Explorer
icon visible when the computer is started up. The company says that
it hasn't yet decided whether it will do so, but that so few
computer makers actually removed the icon that the issue is
unimportant. In addition, nearly all computer makers are switching
over to Windows 98, which goes on sale in stores Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The same federal Appeals Court ruled last month that Jackson's
injunction did not apply to Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   In a hearing last month in the Windows 98 antitrust case, which
also is being heard by Jackson, the judge suggested he was eager to
hear the Appeals Court ruling: ``It may be that we will have a
decision in that case and we will have some expression of appellate
opinion on some of the issues that will cover this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Appeals Court Tuesday also overturned the appointment of
Harvard law professor Lawrence Lessig as a ``special master'' who
was to study the evidence in the Windows 95 case and provide
recommendations to Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The court called Jackson's appointment of Lessig an ``imposition
on the parties of a surrogate judge, and either a clear abuse of
discretion or an exercise of wholly nonexistent discretion.'' The
court did not address Microsoft's claim that Lessig was unsuited to
the task, because he purportedly had shown evidence of bias against
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued by Harvard Law School, Lessig declined to
express an opinion on the ruling. But he defended the right of
Microsoft attorneys to question his impartiality. ``Any litigant
has the right to a fair and impartial adjudicator, and it was
wholly proper for Microsoft's attorneys to raise any question that
they had about my background and my writings.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts questioned how much impact Tuesday's ruling will
have on the government's broader case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think it means that the government will lose their
case in September against Microsoft,'' said Lisa Wood, an attorney
at the Boston firm of Nutter McClennen &AMP; Fish. ``I think that the
decision is a narrow one,'' said Wood, who is vice chairman of an
antitrust committee of the American Bar Association &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Wood said that the essence of the ruling focuses only on details
of the 1995 consent decree between the government and Microsoft.
While the Appeals Court was highly critical of the Justice
Department's analysis of Microsoft's actions in the Windows 95
case, Wood said that those portions of the court's opinion don't
set a legal precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Some Microsoft critics agree. At ProComp, a lobbying group that
recruited former Senator Bob Dole and former federal judge Robert
Bork to campaign against Microsoft, the ruling was dismissed as a
sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that the real battle will occur in the compelling
and historically significant Sherman Act antitrust case that will
be tried in September,`` said ProComp executive director Mike
Pettit. ``That case is based on antitrust law, which is broader
than the consent decree language in today's ruling, and goes to the
heart of Microsoft's anti-competitive and predatory practices that
span the computer industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mountain View, Calif., Netscape officials were cautious. The
appellate ruling applied to Windows 95 and was decided ``largely on
procedural grounds,'' the company noted in a statement. ``It most
certainly did not decide the broad antitrust case,'' Netscape said.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape shares dropped 9/16 to $26 3/16 on the Nasdaq Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-23-98 2117EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
