<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-TECHNOREPORT23-CO     06-24 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNOREPORT23-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Tech Report: A phone that relays messages, or the call  
 By Michael Kanell   
 c. 1998 Cox News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Technology breeds technology.
</P>
<P>
   The more big advances in high tech become a part of our lives
--offering new methods to communicate, work and play -- the more
little devices come piggy-backing into view, offering themselves as
ways to do all those things a tad more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Television gave us the remote control. Computers have spawned
all manner of software, not to mention the Internet and e-mail. And
then there are phones. For decades, families were happy to have a
working phone line that led to the black square phone sitting on a
desk.
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed. Now there are cordless phones for home
and wireless phones for the road. Along with those advances come
some potential problems. For instance, you can't be in two places
at once -- at least, not yet -- and if you are on the road, you're
missing calls at home. Oh, sure, you have an answering machine or
voice mail, but to get the messages you'll either have to go home
or remember to dial in.
</P>
<P>
   But for some people -- especially those running home offices or
small businesses -- it would be nice to hear the phone ring right
away. Even better would be a way to screen calls. For mobile
professionals, a combination of those services could be very
useful. Especially for those people who are paged each time they
get a message, yet don't want to talk to everyone who calls.
</P>
<P>
   Phone analysts have talked for years about a future in which
everyone will have one number, a system that will follow you around
from one phone to another. And some phone companies -- including
MCI and BellSouth -- have offered services in which calls can be
forwarded to wherever you are.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also the hardware option. You will need at least
two phone lines, but SoloPoint, a California-based company, offers
a device that is meant to give users both screening and ``real
time'' access to home calls from the road.
</P>
<P>
   The SoloPoint M-200 hooks to your home phone. When a call comes
in, the M-200 immediately dials your wireless phone -- or a remote
wired phone, if you like -- which should ring within a few moments.
After picking up whichever line you are near, you are given a
chance to listen to the caller leave a message. Then it's up to you
whether you want to connect to the caller by pushing a button. If
you just hang up, the caller never knows you were listening in,
says Don Nanneman, a vice president at SoloPoint.
</P>
<P>
   The M-200 costs $250 and can be ordered directly from the
company (1-888-765-6225). For more information, call Solopoint
(408-364-8850) or visit its Web site (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .SoloPoint.com).
</P>
<P>
   Newsprint, the Net and truth
</P>
<P>
   The Net is bad for the truth. We have all heard the concerns
--self-righteous and otherwise -- about truth as a victim in the
development of technology. The Internet has been targeted as the
scourge of responsible journalism, blamed for the death of
credibility, the demise of good reporting and the end of facts as
we know them.
</P>
<P>
   There was Pierre Salinger and his reliance on Net sources for
saying the U.S. military shot down TWA Flight 800. There was The
Dallas Morning News posting false reports about Secret Service
agent voyeurs. There was Matt Drudge and his false reports about
Sidney Blumenthal. There was Matt Drudge and his true reports about
the investigation of President Clinton. There was ...
</P>
<P>
   Well, you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   You also may have noticed the recent embarrassment The New
Republic suffered as the result of stories written by Stephen
Glass. The reporter apparently spent a lot of time making things
up, while creating evidence such as notes, Web sites, voice mail
messages and faxes to support his stories. According to New York
Times reporter Robin Pogrebin, Glass spent as much time creating
fiction to lend his stories believability as he would have taken to
do them correctly.
</P>
<P>
   The work of young Glass -- by all accounts, a talented writer
--raises questions about journalism and technology and shows the
dangers of making assumptions -- which is, by the way, the first
principle of journalism. Neither the Net nor print seems to have a
monopoly on truth-telling. Glass' concoctions ran, not on the Net,
but in the mainstream and respectable printed press. His pieces
were in Rolling Stone, George and Harper's, and he had a story
scheduled for The New York Times Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   His deception came to light as the result of work by Forbes
Digital Tool, an online news operation.
</P>
<P>
   AOL settles sailor's complaint
</P>
<P>
   There's been a settlement with Tim McVeigh -- not the Oklahoma
bomber, the sailor who had the beef with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   That McVeigh, who listed his marital status as ``gay'' in an
online profile, was identified to Navy officials by AOL after the
online service had promised its users anonymity. The Navy lost a
court case over its investigation of McVeigh and gave him full
retirement benefits. Now AOL has admitted settling McVeigh's
complaint against it, saying the breach of privacy was caused by a
human error and that customer service reps will undergo ``scenario
training'' so they don't give out any more personal data, according
to The Industry Standard's Media Grok.
</P>
<P>
   AOL will pay an undisclosed amount in damages to McVeigh,
according to Media Grok, which covers and comments on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, see the Industry Standard site on the Net
(http://www
</P>
<P>
   .thestandard.net).
</P>
<P>
   Birds sing, fingers tap
</P>
<P>
   There are those who expect us eventually to have complete
mobility, pounding on our keyboards deep in the Amazon rainforest
while taking calls on our cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   A California company, InnoMedia Inc., offers the InfoWave, a
device that lets notebook and personal computers wirelessly connect
from distances up to 800 feet to ``a remote computer, modem,
printer or other peripheral.'' The link is made using a 900 MHz
signal, which can transmit data at a rate of 85k bps, according to
InnoMedia.
</P>
<P>
   InfoWave costs about $250. For more InnoMedia product
information, call (408-562-3535) or visit the company's Web site
(http://www.innomedia.com).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
