 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Mac News: Nisus Writer a bargain as substitute for Word  
 By Charles Haddad   
 c. 1998 Cox News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- If you're looking for a powerful yet inexpensive
alternative to Microsoft's Word 98, check out Nisus Writer.
</P>
<P>
   The price of this word processor has been lowered to $85.95,
making it a heck of a good deal. Nisus (pronounced ``nicest'') not
only offers most of Word's features, it can do many things the
market leader cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Nisus, for example, has 10 editable clipboards, unlimited undos,
synchronized scrolling between windows and the ability to rename a
document without closing it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Nisus has a more-powerful find feature, letting you
search and change things across several documents at the same time.
And it has an interactive page preview feature that immediately
updates a document as you change margins, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Upgrading to Word 98 would cost $149. A new stand-alone version
of Word costs $399.
</P>
<P>
   Some features missing
</P>
<P>
   While strong, Nisus does have some glaring weaknesses that make
it a poor choice for some tasks. It lacks, for example, the
powerful outlining feature in Word. Nor does it support
multiple-column formats in a single document view.
</P>
<P>
   Its table feature is also weak compared with Word's, which now
lets you draw tables of any size in a document.
</P>
<P>
   But for writing -- whether a one-page letter or a 1,000-page
book -- Nisus is hard to beat.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the program is lean. Nisus needs 5.5 megabytes of
internal memory to run, while Word takes nearly twice that amount.
It's also faster and more responsive than either Word or
WordPerfect.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that, unlike its competitors, Nisus runs out of a
computer's internal memory. Sometimes that can cause problems, but
most of them can be fixed by giving Nisus more internal memory.
</P>
<P>
   Uncluttered look
</P>
<P>
   Unlike any other word processor, Nisus sports a simple, clean
look. Your screen is not cluttered with bars of buttons as with
Word and ClarisWorks.
</P>
<P>
   Nisus has plenty of buttons and toolbars, but they are hidden
until you call them up. Most of them reside as tiny buttons drawn
into the right margin and bottom left corner of a document.
</P>
<P>
   One of Nisus' greatest strengths is the ease of adjusting it to
your personal working style. You can assign keyboard commands to
any function. Automating repetitive chores is also a breeze. You
can also assign a keyboard command to any automated task.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike Word 98, Nisus works with any Mac. That includes
older models such as the IIsi, the Classic and the LC.
</P>
<P>
   You can try out Nisus Writer by downloading a free demo from the
company's Web site at
http://www.nisus.com/nisus(underscore)writer.html. Give it try
before automatically opting for Word 98.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-22-98 1836EDT &QL;
</P>
