<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTH IS NEVER MORE IMPORTANT THAN THE FACTS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Her name is Patricia Smith. Occasionally, I would
read her stuff on the news wire.
</P>
<P>
   Every columnist whose work is distributed nationally reads the
work of other columnists whose work is distributed nationally.
We're curious about what our peers are doing. Maybe somebody has an
idea worth stealing.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Allen said once that imitation is the sincerest form of
radio. Same thing with columnizing.
</P>
<P>
   I'm still waiting to do my own version of a column Jimmy Breslin
wrote when I was a high school kid. He turned out a gem on the guy
who dug John F. Kennedy's grave _ on that ordinary working man's
feelings about that extraordinary working day. One of these days,
maybe I'll get a chance to do something like that.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Smith wrote for the Boston Globe. She's a gifted,
lyrical, almost magical writer. On the side, she does poetry and
other literary stuff. When I worked as an editor, I wrote novels,
but I have trouble doing that now. Four columns a week drains that
part of my brain.
</P>
<P>
   So, I would sometimes read her stuff on the wire, as she might
sometimes have read mine. I was a fan. That's why my jaw simply hit
my desk the other day when I read a story about her firing by the
Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Smith had been piping quotes. That's an ancient
newspaper term for making it up _ for sticking imaginary words into
imaginary mouths and printing them. In her farewell piece to Globe
readers, she admitted that she'd done that a few times, just to
lend drama to the point she wanted to make.
</P>
<P>
   She was ashamed of it, she wrote. She'd become a columnist by
entering journalism through the back door, as a writer first rather
than as a reporter. She suggested that perhaps the craft's prime
directive _ that facts are sacred above all else _ hadn't anchored
deeply enough in her consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Patricia Smith had done the wrong thing, and the
Globe had done the right thing by sending her on her way. It was a
big topic in newspaper city rooms. Unless you live in Boston,
though, it wasn't a hot subject for discussion elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But, you know, the world seems increasingly filled with rabid,
foaming press-haters. I hear from a good half dozen of them every
week. They tend to be hard right-wingers. Their favorite delusion
seems to be that we news people are lying to them _ and to you,
too, by the way _ out of a deep-seated desire to sway the general
population to liberal political causes.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a fairly middle-of-the-road guy. I tend to filter politics
through a half-century of life experience. You see enough
stupidity, and it's difficult to be doctrinaire on public issues.
</P>
<P>
   I lean toward what's likely to work, not to what conforms to
some rock-hard ideology.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I'm always surprised to hear from these people.
That's why I was surprised to hear from a few of them concerning
Patricia Smith. Ah-ha, they gloated. So, you guys do make it all
up, don't you?
</P>
<P>
   Well, no, we don't. Sure, I'm a writer. But I'm a reporter
first. No fiction here. I'll save that for the next novel _ if I
ever get around to doing another one.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect? Hardly. I average about five corrections a year. But I
don't invent people. I don't pipe quotes. And do you know why not?
</P>
<P>
   Because, to write a column honestly, you need to grasp in your
gut that the truth as you see it is never, ever more important than
the facts.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how elegantly you phrase it.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
