<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CHIAPAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE VIOLENCE FEARED IN RESTIVE MEXICAN STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico _ The peace process with the
Zapatista rebels is dead and mounting tension in the Chiapas
highlands makes widening bloodshed nearly inevitable, some
observers here say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peace process is completely stymied,'' said Carlos David
Alfonzo Utrilla, a member of the conservative National Action Party
and a congressional candidate in the southeastern Mexican state of
Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doors are closing, time is passing, and the pressure is
building,'' Alfonzo said. ``With the conditions we have here now, I
see the possibilities of large outbreaks of violence within the
next three months.''
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring such warnings were two shootouts June 10 involving
government forces and Zapatista rebels. At least nine people,
including a state policeman, died in some of the worst fighting
since a 1994 uprising for democracy and Indian rights.
</P>
<P>
   The shootouts near El Bosque came shortly after the resignation
of San Cristobal's Roman Catholic bishop, Samuel Ruiz, from the
civilian commission that was overseeing the peace accords signed
two years ago by the rebels and the government. The agreement has
foundered.
</P>
<P>
   With Ruiz's resignation, the civilian commission disbanded and
only a commission of Mexican legislators was left to broker talks
between the Zapatista leader, Subcommander Marcos, and the
government of President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   The government's peace commission faces uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Amado Avendano, a San Cristobal newspaper publisher and 1994
candidate for governor in Chiapas, said Ruiz ``acted as a cushion,
a shock absorber'' in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could tell the Zapatistas to hold on a little longer, to
keep cool,'' Avendano said. ``But now the (rebel force) is alone
against the government. I don't know if it is a coincidence, but
three days after Samuel's resignation, we saw the confrontations
with the Zapatistas.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said Zedillo _ who has traveled
to Chiapas four times in just over a month _ wants to jump-start
the dialogue, but the Zapatistas refuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president clearly called for direct, unconditional
dialogue last week,'' the official said on condition of anonymity.
``We are sitting at the table waiting for them to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   But few outside of Zedillo's long-ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party take that at face value.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government has hardened its position and
heightened military action,'' Alfonzo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zedillo is double-talking. He says he wants peace talks, but
puts every obstacle in the way to realizing them,'' Alfonzo said.
The president has denied such charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas launched a 10-day uprising in January 1994,
seeking rights for the mostly impoverished Indians in the region
and more self-rule. At least 150 people died before a unilateral
cease-fire spawned a series of peace talks over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the peace talks dragged on, violence simmered throughout
Chiapas.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by Mexican army troops, most of the Zapatista forces
holed up in mountain camps near the Guatemala border. Marcos
maintained contact with the outside world through a series of
communiques issued via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But clashes between civilian Zapatista supporters and a growing
number of pro-government paramilitary groups _ particularly in the
northern part of the state _ boiled over with the massacre of 45
unarmed civilians at a church in the hamlet of Acteal in late
December.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the shooting, Zedillo ousted the governor in
Chiapas and fired Interior Minister Emilio Chuayffet Chemor,
replacing him with tough-talking Francisco Labastida Ochoa, a
veteran politician with rumored presidential ambitions. Labastida
took on the task of getting the peace process in Chiapas back on
track.
</P>
<P>
   Government negotiators played up constitutional problems with
indigenous autonomy aspects of the peace accords and called the
Zapatistas back to iron out the differences, but Subcommander
Marcos wanted the accords respected as signed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, frustrated Zapatistas began setting up their own
autonomous municipalities. Zedillo and the state government
declared the Zapatista municipalities unconstitutional, and the
state police have disbanded at least four in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes in El Bosque this month followed its proclamation as
an autonomous Zapatista municipality.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz's resignation may mark the end of the peace accords. But
the move was necessary, argued Gonzala Ituarte Verduzco, vicar of
justice and peace in the diocese of San Cristobal de las Casas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (commission) had become a part of the state's plan to
delay the peace process, serving as a whipping boy and diverting
attention from the real issues,'' he said. ``Now we (the church)
can propose new initiatives, new ideas for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Zedillo condemned ``the theologians of violence,''
an apparent reference to Ruiz, who is known as the ``Red Bishop''
for his 40-year work with Chiapas' poor Indians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1305EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
