<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4286 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARING-TROUBLE-HNS &LR;      06-24 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARING-TROUBLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK, ROLL AND RINGING IN THE EARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Nick Ferrandino can still hear his sister's
advice, but he isn't listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister is an audiologist and has always told me to wear ear
plugs,'' said Ferrandino, a rock guitarist from Albany. ``Part of
me knows she's right and part of me just doesn't enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferrandino, 34, has been playing guitar for more than 15 years,
most recently with Lughead, an alternative rock band that prides
itself on sheer volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``The louder the better as far as I'm concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's aware of the danger. Musicians are among those most likely
to develop hearing problems, including a condition known as
tinnitus.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as head noise. An annoying ring, buzz or
high-pitched hum that affects one in seven Americans or about 36
million people. Of those, seven million have a severe case. Many
also suffer from hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone suffers from ringing in their ears at some time,
usually after a loud concert or a fireworks display. For people
with severe tinnitus, the ringing is constant. It can strike at any
age and is a lifelong problem.
</P>
<P>
   Tinnitus isn't a disease. It's a symptom that can be caused by a
lot of medical conditions, including high blood pressure, allergies
to cheese and chocolate and chronic use of certain medications,
like antibiotics and aspirin. With musicians or people who operate
heavy machinery, noise trauma is often to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people describe it like an engine running or like the
buzz of a horsefly'' said Donna Wayner, a audiologist at the
Hearing Center of Albany Medical Center and author of a new book,
``Hear What You've Been Missing: Coping with Hearing Loss.'' ``It
drives some people really nuts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Kelley of Colonie, N.Y., has spent the past 15 years
trying to cope with the changing landscape in her head. She was
diagnosed with hearing loss and tinnitus when she was 35.
</P>
<P>
   Her problem wasn't loud music but nerve damage from an unknown
cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually its like sleeping in the woods,'' she said of her
tinnitus. ``It can be very noisy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the noise is like a radio or an alarm clock, and on
one afternoon, Kelley said it resembled somebody dialing a
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to listen to it,'' she said. ``It's annoying
because you can't shut it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Tinnitus is a source of frustration for those who suffer from it
and audiologists who try to help.
</P>
<P>
   There's no cure. Wayner helps people learn how to live with the
problem and counsels them on ways to focus their minds away from
the noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people will tell you. `I've had it for 40 years and I
don't pay attention to it,''' she said. ``It depends on the
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley's tinnitus gets worse when she's under stress. To help
her cope, she attends a monthly support group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep it out of focus so it's not the biggest thing in
my life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Because tinnitus is such a complex condition with no single
cause, there's no recipe for prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Musicians, however, take a risk every time they play without ear
protection. Consider Pete Townsend of The Who. He's suffers from
tinnitus and hearing loss.
</P>
<P>
   H.E.A.R., a national group known as Hearing Education and
Awareness among Rockers, is trying to promote ear protection for
musicians and audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrandino has no problem hearing the warnings. He just isn't
ready to turn down the volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope it doesn't come back to haunt me later on,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
