<P>
   ECONOMY-COLUMN-RAMSEY (Undated) Americans are constantly told
they are not saving enough for retirement. In aggregate, that may
be so. But we are not aggregates.
</P>
<P>
   By Bruce Ramsey. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4318 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMY-COLUMN-RAMSEY     06-24 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-COLUMN-RAMSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIREMENT SAVING EXCUSES FRAUGHT WITH SELF-DECEPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans are constantly told they are not saving enough for
retirement. In aggregate, that may be so. But we are not
aggregates.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a recent survey of working Americans by the Employee
Benefit Research Institute. This survey looks at four groups: those
born after 1964, 1954-1964, 1946-1953 and before 1946. The
following are percentages of each group, younger to older:
</P>
<P>
   Expect to retire by 60: 46, 42, 35 and 21.
</P>
<P>
   Are ``very confident'' of having enough money: 32, 22, 18 and
25.
</P>
<P>
   Have some retirement savings: 65, 70, 76 and 78.
</P>
<P>
   Have at least $100,000: 5, 10, 21 and 34.
</P>
<P>
   Have nothing: 35, 30, 24 and 22.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also divides Americans into five types by the way we
think, plan and spend:
</P>
<P>
   Deniers: ``It's pointless to save for retirement. I might not
live that long.'' This group, generally older, is the most
deliberate in its refusal to save.
</P>
<P>
   Strugglers: ``Save? I can't afford it.'' These tend to be
middle-aged high-school graduates. They tend to prefer
forced-savings plans.
</P>
<P>
   Impulsives: ``Save? I want to buy.'' This group is mainly young,
married and raising families. Their appetites leave no room for
leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Cautious savers: ``I save a little. I hope it's enough.'' This
group tends to be middle- or higher-income, many of them divorced
or separated.
</P>
<P>
   Planners: ``I learned to save as a kid.'' These are the
disciplined savers. Most know how much they need for retirement.
They typically are educated, take more risks and earn more.
</P>
<P>
   Half the non-savers in the institute's survey said the No. 1
reason they didn't save was lack of money. But it's notable that
half offered another reason. When savers and non-savers were asked
if they could afford to put away $20 more per week, the institute
got a ``yes'' from 57 percent of the savers _ and 55 percent of the
non-savers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like a lot of money, a thousand bucks a
year,'' says Paul Yakoboski of Employee Benefit Research Institute.
``If they start early, $20 a week could make a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans are saving. What the survey shows, Yakoboski
says, is that many are doing it with ``blind hope, faith and
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Most are also relying on retirement plans. Virtually all big
companies offer such plans, but many small ones don't. When asked
why not, employers with no plans most often told the researchers
that their employees would rather have the cash.
</P>
<P>
   This seems to fly in the face of another fact. Attorney William
Song, head of the employee benefits group at Davies Roberts &AMP; Reid
in Seattle and a consultant to the U.S. Department of Labor, says:
``Seventy-five percent of union members have pension benefits. It
is less than half for non-union employees.''
</P>
<P>
   When employees get together in unions, they want pensions. So
are those small employers deluded? Dishonest? Some may be, but it's
not necessarily so. Yakoboski noted that the work force in small,
non-union companies is less permanent than the average union shop,
lower paid, and most especially, younger. ``These are people
typically not focused on retirement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The second most frequent reason for not having a retirement plan
was ``uncertain revenue.'' When asked what might induce them to
offer a retirement plan, two-thirds of these no-retirement
employers said ``increased profits.''
</P>
<P>
   But half also said ``demand from employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Among small employers with a retirement plan, only 35 percent
said it was a big help in attracting and keeping good employees _
and 19 percent said it was of no help at all.
</P>
<P>
   The retirement issue, in a way, is like medical insurance.
Government would like to have us all covered. On June 4 and 5,
President Clinton hosted a national conference on retirement
savings at which he and his labor secretary urged people to save
and companies to offer retirement plans. Song, who attended that
conference, notes particularly the value of defined-benefit plans,
in which the dollars-per-month are guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something to be said for a system of imposed
discipline,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security is also a plan of imposed discipline. Without
imposed discipline, more of us would end up wheeling around grocery
carts. But Americans resist too many impositions. We remain diverse
and cantankerous, some of us planners, some of us impulsives, some
of us deniers. The deniers are undoubtedly fools and should be
subject to all the propaganda that
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton, T. Rowe Price and guys like me can throw at
</P>
<P>
   them.
</P>
<P>
   But if they persist, it's their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ramsey is a writer and columnist for the P-I. His e-mail
address is bruceramsey(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
