<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4341 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-ELECTIONS-BOS     06-24 1461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-ELECTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN TRAIL IS BRAND-NEW TERRITORY FOR MANY IN ULSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALLYCASTLE, Northern Ireland _ As the sun dipped along the
Causeway Coast the other night, someone pointed out to 78-year-old
Joe Cahill that he had been on the run for 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on the run longer than that,'' he quipped, flashing
a mischievous grin as he walked this seaside town in County Antrim
looking for votes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Joe Cahill, a convicted killer and former chief of staff
of the Irish Republican Army, has spent most of his life on the run
or in prison. Now, he is campaigning for a seat in the new Northern
Ireland assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill is one of 296 candidates for the 108-seat body that will
be elected Thursday. Many of them are political neophytes. Some,
like Cahill, are convicted killers and products of a peace process
that led to the Good Friday agreement approved overwhelmingly by
voters last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new day,'' Cahill said, explaining how an old
``military'' man like him could ``go political.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The time for fighting is over,'' he concluded. ``The time for
dialogue is here.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, each of Northern Ireland's 18
districts will receive six seats in the new assembly. Unlike last
month's referendum, in which voters gave a simple yes or no to the
agreement, Thursday's election will call for them to rank
candidates in order of preference.
</P>
<P>
   In some districts, as many as 23 candidates will appear on the
ballot. Under the proportional representation system created here,
all who garner about 14 percent of the vote will get seats. Any
votes they receive above that level will be distributed to other
candidates according to preference.
</P>
<P>
   This means that both the voting and the tabulation process will
be complicated and time-consuming. Final results are not expected
until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the historic importance of the election, Northern
Ireland approaches it with a post-referendum apathy, exacerbated by
the drama of the World Cup soccer finals under way in France.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, 71 percent of voters in Northern Ireland supported
the Good Friday agreement, which formed the political institutions
aimed at resolving one of the world's most intractable conflicts.
More than 80 percent of eligible voters cast ballots, the highest
turnout in Northern Ireland's 77-year history. But the turnout is
expected to be more in line with a general election _ about 67
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some suggest that a small vote will help hard-core
anti-agreement forces win enough seats to wreck the assembly. Such
a daunting prospect could lead paramilitary groups, whose
cease-fires have been essential to the peace process, to conclude
that democratic politics cannot work here.
</P>
<P>
   But others like Sydney Elliott, a senior lecturer in politics at
Queen's University in Belfast, dispute the theory that a lower
turnout favors anti-agreement forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the referendum brought out a sizeable number of
(Protestant) evangelicals who took a moral position in voting no.
But politics to them is a dirty business, and I don't think you'll
see them voting this time around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are almost three times the number of candidates running
than the average in general elections and nearly twice as many as
those who ran in 1982, the last time Northern Ireland held an
assembly election. The plethora of candidates is explained in part
by the $47,000 salary assembly members will receive.
</P>
<P>
   But Elliott believes that it is the historic nature of the
assembly that has attracted such a large field. Thursday's vote
marks the first time since 1972, when local government was
suspended and direct rule was imposed by British Parliament, that
most people here have agreed to share power.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-agreement parties have called on their supporters to give
second preference votes to others who want the assembly to work.
Still, Elliott and others believe Thursday's vote will be cast as
usual, mostly along sectarian lines: Catholic nationalists who
aspire to unity with the Irish Republic will vote mostly for the
moderate Social Democratic and Labor Party (SDLP) and Sinn Fein,
the party linked to the IRA. Protestant unionists who want to
remain part of the United Kingdom will vote mostly for the Ulster
Unionists and the Democratic Unionists.
</P>
<P>
   The moderate Alliance Party, the only large bloc that attracts
both Catholics and Protestants, could benefit most from the
tactical voting.
</P>
<P>
   Which unionists win seats will determine the ability of the
assembly to withstand the efforts of obstructionists. Next week,
the two biggest vote getters, expected to be the Ulster Unionists
and the SDLP, will put forward a first minister and deputy who will
lead a 12-member shadow cabinet until the assembly is functioning
in the fall. Ten other ministers will be appointed according to the
size of their party's vote. Sinn Fein will probably get two cabinet
posts.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Unionists are led by the Rev. Ian Paisley, the
fundamentalist preacher who is adamantly opposed to Sinn Fein's
inclusion in the government. The Ulster Unionists, meanwhile,
remain divided over the issue of IRA weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble accepts British Prime
Minister Tony Blair's word that the IRA must gradually give up its
arsenal if Sinn Fein is to remain in the assembly and IRA prisoners
are to be released over the next two years. But dissidents don't
trust Blair and insist on ironclad assurances.
</P>
<P>
   Those who opposed the agreement are waging a campaign based
onthe same issues they used against the referendum - the fate of
weapons and prisoners. But this bloc received only 29 percent of
the referendum vote, and unless it does much better, it will be
hard pressed to obstruct the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly has mechanisms to encourage power-sharing and
consensus politics. On any contentious issue - and nearly every
issue is contentious in Northern Ireland - 30 or more members can
request a measure be passed by 60 percent of the assembly. This
calculus would prevent a repeat of the simple majority-rule system
in Stormont, the local parliament suspended in 1972, where
unionists used their majority to discriminate systematically
against nationalists and exclude them from power.
</P>
<P>
   On the stump in his hometown of Ballymena, the buckle of
Northern Ireland's Bible belt, Rev. Paisley insisted that his
forces need only 30 seats to render the assembly unworkable. As he
strolled around Ballymena, Paisley received almost universal
adoration. A lone heckler, an elderly Protestant named James Mark,
followed Paisley, urging the 72-year-old preacher to ``love your
neighbor. Love the Roman Catholics.''
</P>
<P>
   Paisley, a shoo-in for the assembly he has sworn to destroy, was
unmoved.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein's strategy of running Cahill in Paisley's North Antrim
constituency appears designed to irritate Paisley as much as elect
Cahill. Paisley has called Cahill's candidacy ``an outrage.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen McAllister disagrees. A mother of two young children in
Waterfoot, a small town on Antrim's rocky, majestic coast, she
thinks Cahill's candidacy proves that the IRA is serious about
using politics to fight for a united Ireland. She believes that
former loyalist gunmen are setting the same example as they work to
stay part of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young people look up to someone like Joe Cahill. If he
says its time for politics, then it's time for politics,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill has been surprised by how friendly people have been on
the campaign trail, including Protestants who abhor his IRA past.
``The only person who hasn't been respectful is Paisley,'' he said.
``He said I should have been strung up a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, just before he was to be hanged for his role in the
murder of a Belfast policeman, Cahill received a last-minute
reprieve. His cellmate, Tom Williams, went to the gallows. Asked if
Williams, an IRA icon, would support him or those who favor more
IRA violence, Cahill didn't hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom would be right beside me,'' Cahill said. ``We spent the
last 4 1/2 weeks of his life together. You get to know a person in
a situation like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cahill's gentle, grandfatherly demeanor and thick eyeglasses
belie his past, which was dedicated to the use of violence to force
the British to leave Northern Ireland. But as he trudged around
Ballycastle's neat streets shaking hands, Cahill talked about the
future, not the past, as he acknowledged he hadn't set foot in the
town in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1969, I haven't been around a hell of a lot,'' he
chuckled, recalling his three decades on the lam or behind bars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
