<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD NORTH CHURCH BALANCES PIETY, PATRIOTISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, the Rev. Stephen Ayres, vicar of the Old North
Church in Boston's North End, closed the church to tours because of
a funeral service.
</P>
<P>
   A guide leading a tour group was shocked when Ayres told him he
couldn't come inside. ```What do you mean you're closed?''' Ayres
recalls the guide saying. ```The church is always open between 9
and 5.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ayres said his response was, ``Hello _ this is a church;
funerals happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   While most tour guides are understanding, Ayres offers the
anecdote to underscore the challenge of running Old North _ making
sure people realize that one of America's most famous churches is
not a museum but home to a living, worshiping congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tourists are always amazed that this is not a dead church,''
said Ayres, who has been vicar since May of last year. ``This is a
living community of faith. That's also a message that we're trying
to get out to people moving into the North End.''
</P>
<P>
   The message is hitting home, judging by the growing number of
people showing up for Sunday services. Ayres says that about 120 to
140 regularly attend the liturgy. The number of members has jumped
in recent years from 20 to 60.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is definitely a sense that the congregation is becoming
more vibrant and that is certainly a positive development,'' said
Ayers, seated inside his office while yet another tour group filed
through the sanctuary a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   The church's robust growth is a byproduct of the changing
demographics of the North End, long identified as a tightly-knit
Italian enclave. In recent years, the neighborhood has attracted
many single professionals and young couples, some of whom have
found their spiritual niche at Old North.
</P>
<P>
   Immortalized in Henry Wadsworth Longfellow's 1861 poem, ``Paul
Revere's Ride'' it was the church from which Robert Newman agreed
to shine one lantern if the British approached by land and two if
by sea. It was built in 1723 as an Anglican congregation to provide
for the spiritual needs of the surrounding townsfolk. Old North is
officially called Christ Church in the City of Boston and is part
of the Episcopal Diocese of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The church flourished for decades. In the early 1800s, the Rev.
Asa Eaton, leading a thriving and affluent congregation, opened the
country's first Sunday School. More than 200 children were
enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   The church's decline began in the mid-19th century when an
influx of Irish immigrants and Russian Jews transformed the
neighborhood. This was followed later in the century by a wave of
Italian newcomers, who gave the community the distinctive flavor it
still has today.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of this century, only a handful of people
worshiped at Old North. Eventually, the parish was reduced to a
mission and taken over by the Episcopal bishop. Even today, the
Rev. M. Thomas Shaw, the bishop of the diocese, officially is the
rector of Old North, though Ayers is in charge of daily operations.
</P>
<P>
   The church boomed as a tourist spot when the Freedom Trail was
developed in the 1950s. Today, it is the second-most-popular site
on the trail, after the USS Constitution. More than 750,000 people
will trek through its storied walls this year. The church even has
its own Web site (www.oldnorth.com).
</P>
<P>
   Ayers, who came to Old North after six years at Emmanuel Church
in Wakefield, said he realizes that he must balance the patriotic
with the pious.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few years, the church plans to renovate some of
the buildings on the Old North campus and to add new space.
</P>
<P>
   He worries that visitors do not fully appreciate the role that
religion played in the country's founding. ``Was God blessing
America by starting the revolution from the steeple of a church?''
Ayer said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before Before beginning a three-day visit to Austria June 19,
Pope John Paul II said he hoped to try to salve the wounds of a
church reeling from news that the country's most senior prelate,
archconservative Cardinal Hans Hermann Groer, had been accused of
sexually molesting a schoolboy 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Groer was forced to resign as archbishop of Vienna. Several
priests and monks also accused Groer of sexual abuse. ``The pope
and his bishops want to help overcome these problems,'' John Paul
said during his weekly audience at the Vatican Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   _James C. Dobson, the powerful conservative political activist
and founder of the faith-based Focus on the Family, was said to be
recovering in a Colorado from what doctors said was a mild stroke.
Dobson entered a hospital in Colorado Springs late Tuesday after
becoming sick, according to a statement from his ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am doing as well as could be expected,'' Dobson said in the
statement. ``I will need to continue to take some time to get back
on my feet. Please pray for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said Dobson did not suffer any paralysis or loss of
consciousness. Dobson said his cardiologist told him, ``You must
have had an angel looking out for you.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, he has emerged as a major political player who
is pressuring the Repbulican Party to heed the concerns of social
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   _The Massachusetts Conference of the United Church of Christ,
the state's oldest and largest Protestant denomination, voted
overwhelmingly at its recent convention to oppose the death
penalty. The church joins the Roman Catholic Church as well as
liberal Protestant denominations and Jewish congregations in
opposing the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   _Metropolitan Methodios, bishop of the Greek Orthodox Diocese of
Boston, received a welcome surprise recently when George Behrakis,
a well-known church benefactor, announced that he was donating
$500,000 towards the purchase of a diocesan camp and retreat
center. Behrakis, who runs a pharmaceutical company, revealed his
donation at a diocesan dinner. The camp and retreat center will be
located in Contoocook, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
