<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLIM PICKINGS FOR BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins know all about highly touted center Vincent
Lecavalier, a sure bet to be one of the top picks _ if not the very
highest _ in Saturday's National Hockey League entry draft in
Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   They know of his Joe Thorntonlike size. They know of his 115
points in 58 games in the Quebec Major Junior Hockey League with
Plymouth last year. They know he is very skilled and has a nice
change of speed in his skating. They know he needs to get stronger.
</P>
<P>
   And most of all they know, in all likelihood, it doesn't matter
how much they know about Vincent Lecavalier. Or, for that matter,
David Legwand. Or Bryan Allen. Or Dmitri Kalinin. Or Vitaly
Vishnevsky.
</P>
<P>
   All are among the best of the best in this year's crop of
prospective NHLers. And, barring a major trade to vault up in the
draft order, all will be long gone before the Bruins get near
making their first pick.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a draft year makes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Bruins got a big-time boost _ and a healthy shot
of hope for years to come _ when they took Thornton with the first
pick overall and Sergei Samsonov with the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   This year, they don't pick until No. 48, and to make matters
even more sticky, at least in the short term, they could lose more
than they gain this weekend because they stand to surrender a
player _ perhaps veteran forward Mike Sullivan or defenseman Dave
Ellett _ to the aptly named Nashville Predators in Friday's
expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion draft is part of the business, said assistant
general manager Mike O'Connell. And the fact that the Bruins have a
solid group of younger players should take the sting out of losing
a body and not having high picks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, Joe Thornton comes in and has more of a role in the
team's success,'' O'Connell said. ``And hopefully Sergei will be
more prominent, start to the end, as will (P.J.) Axelsson and (Hal)
Gill. Hopefully those young players will step it up a notch,
(Jason) Allison as well as (Anson) Carter. (Kyle) McLaren still. We
have quite a few young players and hopefully they will improve.
They should improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Bruins had the first overall pick in the draft
for the first time since 1982, when they took Gord Kluzak. And they
had two picks in the top eight for the first time since 1970, when
they took Reggie Leach at No. 3 and Rick MacLeish at No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' first selection has never been as low as this year's
No. 48. They also have the 52d pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, we have to wait and see,'' said O'Connell. ``Last
year I'd say we definitely had the control of the draft. This year
is more wait and see. See what's available.''
</P>
<P>
   And hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope 20 people make mistakes,'' O'Connell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're hoping somebody slips, which happens,'' said director
of scouting Scott Bradley. ``What if a kid rated in our top 27
slips into our 45 range? That would be nice, and it's what we're
hoping for, but we're not counting on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor are they counting on a trade and certainly not counting on
coming up with two players who will make the team out of training
camp next fall as Thornton and Samsonov did last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have only six picks overall in the draft's nine
rounds. They would have picked 19th but traded their first-rounder
to Colorado for Landon Wilson and Anders Myrvold in November 1996.
The No. 48 pick is their own and the No. 52 is a compensatory pick
they got from Toronto for the Leafs' signing of free agent Kevyn
Adams. They also have picks in the third round (No. 78 overall),
fifth round (135), sixth (165), and ninth (250). They traded their
fourth selection to Los Angeles with Jozef Stumpel and Sandy Moger
for Byron Dafoe and Dmitri Khristich, their seventh-rounder to
Calgary for Sullivan and their eighth-rounder to Vancouver for
Grant Ledyard.
</P>
<P>
   Six picks overall, starting with No. 48?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a good deal of pressure to get a player,''
Bradley said. ``You don't want to get shut out in a draft. Ever. If
three or four picks out of this batch of six picks played with the
Bruins, we'd be happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think going in you think every guy has a chance, but you
have to look at the numbers. I don't have them in front of me, but
if you get two or three players out of one year, you're doing
terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensemen Joe DiPenta of Nova Scotia and Boston University and
Bobby Allen of Hull and Boston College are ranked Nos. 33 and 34
among North Americans by the Central Scouting Service, and when
goaltenders and European players are added in, they could well be
around by the time the Bruins pick.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, like all teams, have been checking out prospective
picks for months and will convene as a staff today in Buffalo. They
will conduct interviews with 20-30 players in the next couple of
days.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on Saturday, well after the Vincent Lecavaliers and
David Legwands have stepped to the podium and modeled their new
team jerseys, the Bruins will get their turn to pick a player.
</P>
<P>
   There is a bright side to where the Bruins stand, said
O'Connell. He thinks the talent available in the draft last year
was a little stronger than what's up this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we took a good time to have a bad year,'' said
O'Connell of the last-place finish that got the Bruins a
first-place pick last year. ``But who knows?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
