A4373 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRADS-CONSULT-ART-BOS     06-24 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRADS-CONSULT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRADUATES SEEK CONSULTANT JOBS BEFORE SETTLING DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Eric Moffett graduated from Princeton University last year
with a degree in economics, the Houston native knew he wanted to be
a businessman. Rather than choose an industry, however, Moffett
took what is becoming a more familiar road for recent college
graduates: He became a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Moffett joined the Boston office of Bain &AMP; Co., a strategy
consulting firm, as an associate consultant, a two-year position.
In his eleven months at Bain, Moffett has worked on cases involving
the software and financial services industries; he recently joined
the company's private equity group. And although he eventually
wants to start his own company, Moffett says Bain is teaching him
essential business skills. Better yet, his colleagues and bosses
understand that he might not want to be a consultant forever _ and
they support him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture really tends to foster entrepreneurial ventures,''
Moffett says, citing the case of Intuit Inc., the Mountain View,
Calif., software firm started by former Bain consultant Scott D.
Cook.
</P>
<P>
   As college students _ especially those who, like Moffett, have
liberal arts degrees _ put off making binding decisions about their
careers until later in life, management consulting is growing
increasingly popular as a step along the way toward a business
career.
</P>
<P>
   At Bain, about 7,000 resumes stream into the Boston office each
year from college seniors eager to snag one of about 70 job offers,
says Chris Bierley, vice president in charge of associate
consultant recruiting for Boston. In the past five years, Bierley
says, Bain's application rate for associate consultant positions
has jumped 20 percent each year.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Monitor Co.'s applications have grown each year; the
firm now gets 15,000 resumes nationwide from undergrads who want to
work in the North America division, says W. Sean Ford, head of
global recruiting for the Cambridge management consultancy.
</P>
<P>
   New York-based Mercer Management Co. saw its college graduate
applications jump 10 percent this year; only about 2 percent of
applicants are offered a job. McKinsey and Co., also a major New
York management consulting firm, hired 487 undergrads last year, up
from 396 in 1996 and 356 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   As the major consulting firms increase their overall personnel
about 15 percent a year, Ford says, Monitor and its competitors
have seen competition for associate consultant-level jobs heat up.
And today students graduating with less technical majors, such as
English and philosophy, are also lining up for interviews at
Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a broader range of majors applying year to year,''
Ford says. ``It's not just economics majors.''
</P>
<P>
   College seniors and consulting firms seem to be a perfect match.
A recent graduate may be looking for an interesting, well-paying,
short-term job with maximum exposure to different industries;
consulting concerns need energetic 22-year-olds with proven
problem-solving skills who are willing to travel frequently and
work long hours as part of a case team. Associate consultants at
major firms make about $40,000 per year; other expenses, such as
briefcases and PalmPilots, are often company-subsidized.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of 21-year-olds today are interested in being able to
solve a variety of problems and get a breadth of experience,'' says
Cathy Baker, head of nationwide recruiting at Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   And it's fun, young consultants say.
</P>
<P>
   ``In strategy consulting, the recent undergrad has the
opportunity to gain a bird's-eye view of the entire firm and how it
operates,'' says Tami J. Goven, an associate consultant who joined
Bain's Boston office last summer. ``You're typically working with
the most competitive, pressing issues a company faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Goven's story echoes the trend sweeping undergraduates into
consulting jobs. The Minneapolis native graduated from Duke
University in 1997 with a double major in economics and public
policy. After interning in the legislative affairs department of
Sun Microsystems, Goven realized she preferred a corporate
get-it-done attitude to the relative inefficiency of government.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``consultant'' used to apply most often to retired or
maverick executives who sold their expertise. But the new breed of
consultants knows little to nothing about its clients' businesses.
</P>
<P>
   With no experience in industry, Goven doesn't make solo
boardroom presentations to multimillion-dollar companies. But the
young consultant, who works about 60 hours a week, says an
undergrad's abilities _ ``people skills, communication skills,
analytical skills'' _ are still valued in a case team.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, brain power may be the most important thing a consulting
firm gets out of most young hires. ``A lot of business is difficult
to teach in books,'' says Moffett, the economics major. ``The only
real thing that came out of college that helped was the ability to
solve problems.''
</P>
<P>
   And this lack of experience in any one industry may be an asset.
A successful applicant usually has ``very strong academic
performance and the ability to work in teams,'' rather than
extensive exposure to the business world, Ford says.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things young consultants pick up on the job is
the lingo: ``Strong time-management skills,'' ``ramp-up period,''
and ``stream of analysis'' are all buzzwords that pepper Goven's
speech. But more than a supply of stock phrases, consultants say,
taking a two- to four-year job at a management consulting firm can
help the ambitious young businessperson land a job in industry.
</P>
<P>
   Take former Bain consultant Daniel J. Krifcher, now vice
president of America Online's AOL Studios, which develops new
concepts for the Virginia-based Internet provider. In 1983, after
graduating from the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School
with an undergraduate degree in systems and finance, Krifcher went
to Bain's Boston office, where he spent almost five years. The
consulting firm financed a start-up mortgage company he co-founded
after moving on.
</P>
<P>
   But leaving consulting didn't mean Krifcher left behind the
consultant's way of thinking, what he calls ``an analytical rigor,
a discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not exaggerating when I say that having been a consultant
right after college really set the tone for my career,'' says
Krifcher, who joined AOL after earning his MBA from Harvard
Business School. ``I learned that there's always an answer, always
a solution, no matter how complicated the problem and how short the
time frame.''
</P>
</TEXT>
