<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S MCCAIN VS. THE BAD GUYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can a man be too big for his political party?
</P>
<P>
   That question becomes pivotal to the challenge that a
presidential bid by Arizona Senator John McCain poses for the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   As a war hero and prisoner of war whose dogged committee work
has made him one of the most important members of the Senate
majority, McCain has attained a stature and level of popularity
that probably eclipse that of any other Republican. There are other
war heroes in the Senate _ Kerry and Kerrey, for two _ but McCain's
life story is the most dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   A screw-off at Annapolis (``I stood fifth from the bottom of my
class at the Naval Academy,'') a brash brat whose father and
grandfather were Navy men with ships named after them, McCain was
flying a Navy fighter over Vietnam when he was shot down, injured,
captured, tortured, and put on ice in the Hanoi Hilton for six
years, refusing offers to be repatriated ahead of his turn, denying
the enemy their propaganda payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years in Congress has seen him rise to chairman of the
Senate Commerce Committee. But his stout efforts to reform the
corrupt campaign finance status quo, and his bloody but
unsuccessful bid to curb teenage smoking, have placed him against
the leadership and consensus of his shame-faced Republican
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   It was the unrestricted soft money from the big tobacco barons,
as well as limitless contributions to individual senators
(including Democrats) and more than $40 million in targeted
broadcast advertising in the backyards of wavering GOP senators
that enabled Big Tobacco to bring the Senate Republicans to heel.
By working closely with White House advisers, and carving a
sensible middle-ground position on the complex issues around the
how-do-we-get-teenagers-to-stop-smoking? question, his Commerce
Committee voted 19-1 for a bipartisan compromise that had the
support of 57 of the Senate 100. Not enough, alas. The tobacco
lobby went to work on Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of
Mississippi, and some of McCain's Republican pals who had voted
with him in committee turned around and stabbed him in the back in
the cloture vote.
</P>
<P>
   Lott came up with 42 others beside himself, and they stood fast
for cancer, emphysema, and teen smoking. As a result, McCain glumly
recounted for a journalist lunch crowd Monday, ``3,000 more kids
will start smoking today, and one thousand of them will die
prematurely'' from tobacco-related illness.
</P>
<P>
   In his home state and elsewhere, tobacco company ads savage
McCain as a big-government liberal, a big-tax man, who has it in
for smokers, and people who like small government and low taxes.
It's the crudest kind of advertising, unanswerable at anything like
that volume, and it has turned voters against him, even back home,
where he's up for reelection.
</P>
<P>
   After November, McCain decides if he'll hazard a presidential
primary run. He knows now that he'll have the tobacco lobby after
him, as well as the Soft Money Industry, a shadowy collection of
special interests, whose nefarious influence is magnified by the
surreptitous supply of soft money to sycophantic senators.
</P>
<P>
   There are others riled at McCain _ the telecommunications giants
who have been ripping off consumers with higher phone and cable
rates (cable's up 17 percent in two years, fellow chumps), and the
ethanol lobby, which has ferocious clout with the corn-selling
farmers of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   McCain spit in the eyes of his North Vietnamese captors for six
years, and for his trouble they broke his arms and booted his butt.
Now the tobacco lobby is trying to do what the North Vietnamese
prison guards could not do _ break his will. The rifle butt has
been replaced by the TV spot, broadcast all over the back country,
riling the ranchers and rodeo hands of Arizona, telling them to
despise a senator who merely wants their kids to have a better
chance of not dying from lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the late Paul Tsongas, his cancer in remission and his
conscience running full-bore, took on his party's sacred cows in
the 1992 election cycle has a (OK, former) senator of some national
stature so gone to war against his party's orthodoxy. With Tsongas,
it was the Democrats refusal to buck any union dictate, do any kind
of favor for big business, or acknowledge the inefficiencies of
certain economic nostrums that made his pro-business policies
heresy for some in his party.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a latter-day Tsongas to many, is a true-blue
conservative who scoffs at suggestions he defect to the opposition
party. This is not a guy who defects, period. But even this
brass-bottomed conservative cannot stomach the soft money crack
habit of his colleagues, and their allegiance to the campaign funds
dangled by Big Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a rather complicated personal history, and to a
penetrating query about his readiness to have his personal life
dredged up for public inspection, he replies evenly: Take your best
shot. His life is wide open, he's had his peccadiloes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue to maintain that it's nobody's business. And
if that is something that hurts me, then that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not a guy who can be intimidated. And in today's tawdry
politics, that alone makes him worthy of considering no matter what
your philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
