<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4385 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-24 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUGENE MCCARTHY ON HOW TO KEEP POLITICS (REASONABLY) CLEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- The topics that lather area code 202 seem to
Beltway inmates random and unconnected. Not far away, in the
serenity of the Rappahannock Valley and in the shadow of Stony Man
Mountain, the mess seems coherent, of a piece.
</P>
<P>
   The flights and frights of campaign finance and special
prosecutors arise from a gullibly innocent lust for ``reform,'' an
effort ``to take the politics out of politics,'' according to
Eugene J. McCarthy. He's been writing books for 40 years, and his
latest, ``No-Fault Politics,'' laced with quotations from
Chesterton, Shakespeare, and ``Mr. Dooley,'' is as sharp as a
Minnesota winter.
</P>
<P>
   Calling special prosecutors ``a cure that spreads the disease,''
he writes: ``Congress has avoided its ultimate responsibility. It
has encouraged the courts to become deeply involved in prosecution
at a high level of politics. The function of the courts is to
judge, not to prosecute or appoint prosecutors.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy's solution? He has more faith in the Constitution than
do the ``reformers,'' whose legislation produced special
prosecutors. ``It is better to place the area of doubt within the
range of popular judgment than to pretend that partisanship does
not exist,'' he writes. ``We should abolish the special prosecutor
laws and practices and let Congress, the press, and the people make
the judgments. Better to overdo the impeachment process than
continue to abuse the silly and destructive special-prosecutor
process we now have.''
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment? The prospect rattles stemware in Georgetown, but
McCarthy thinks it can be a natural feature of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you remember when I said in the campaign that at the end
of my term impeachment would set a good precedent?'' he asked from
his Virginia farm. Having covered his 1968 campaign for president,
I do remember vividly what he said he would do first if elected:
``Tear down the fence around the White House.'' McCarthy disdains
cant and orthodoxy. Elected to the House in 1948 and to the Senate
in 1958, he made history in 1968 when he challenged the reelection
of President Lyndon B. Johnson. At 82, he is as trenchant as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, there's a premium on informers and bounty hunters,'' he
says. ``Stool pigeons are part of the judicial system. It seems
like everyone's a repo man now.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy's dissent extends to the ``puritan virtue'' of
``process liberalism'' infecting proposed changes in campaign
finance. ``The myth is twofold: that process equals policy and that
a good process is a clean or uncorrupted process. This is a
mechanistic and a simplistic view of public life and action, one
that bets everything on procedural reform,'' he writes. ``For the
innocents of our time, politics can never be clean enough. So in
the name of doing good, the innocents do much harm.''
</P>
<P>
   He names ``notable innocents.'' John Gardner is Public Innocent
No. 1 because the founder of Common Cause, ``with some help from
other people and organizations, reorganized Congress and
presidential politics ... into ineptitude.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, McCarthy wrote ``Frontiers in American Democracy,''
which warned how innocence could menace the coming decades: ``The
innocent is disposed to favor massive effort and all-out war rather
than containment or limited war, to demand action leading to final
decision when postponement of trouble or limited or even temporary
good may be the best that can be expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene McCarthy is not a prophet without honor, but he is a
private citizen without a Senate platform. He did not choose to run
again in 1970, in part because Public Innocent No. 2, Margaret
Chase Smith, ``generally a sound legislator,'' answered 1,000
consecutive roll-call votes, even though meeting roll calls ``is in
many ways the least important thing that senators do. Shortly after
I left the Senate, a roll-call vote was taken on what to do with
the remains of Smokey the Bear.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
