<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-WARD-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        MORE WASTE WOULD BE STORED AT WARD NUCLEAR SITE, REPORT
SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Elliot Zaret  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 23 -- The company that hopes to run the
proposed nuclear waste dump in Ward Valley has a history of not
containing radioactive materials at its sites and may be in
financial peril, according to a new report.
</P>
<P>
   And the company may be planning to put far more nuclear waste in
the site -- in a more dangerous form -- than it had originally
proposed, according to the report released Tuesday by the General
Accounting Office (GAO), the investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The report could put additional pressure on a plan which, since
it was first proposed 15 years ago, has been the subject of legal
battles, protests by Native American and environmental groups, and
has been the source of a heated battle between Gov. Pete Wilson and
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``These findings, together with questions raised in (a report
last year by economist F. Gregory Hayden) about the necessity for a
low-level disposal site in California and the ongoing environmental
concerns must raise very serious questions about the wisdom of
going forward with the Ward Valley project at all,'' said Rep.
George Miller, D-Martinez, who along with Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif., requested the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that, in light of all this evidence, Gov. Wilson
would terminate this project and end this very contentious and
litigious controversy once and for all,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for American Ecology -- the parent company for
U.S. Ecology, the company that would run the site -- did not return
calls for comment on the report.
</P>
<P>
   But in a letter included in the GAO report, American Ecology's
Joe Nagel attacked the report. ``Specious arguments offered by
project opponents are presented without providing readily available
scientific information which discredits those arguments,'' Nagel
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a proposal to build a waste disposal site in the
Mojave desert near Needles for low-level radioactive materials from
hospitals and nuclear plants. The plan to sell the land for the
site from the federal government to the state of California was
approved by the Bush administration on the day before Clinton took
office. The Clinton administration reversed the decision soon after
taking office.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the original land transfer was legal is the subject of a
pending court battle. But many groups have also questioned the
safety of the site because of the nature of the nuclear waste that
would be dumped and because of the proximity of the site to the
Colorado River.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO found that American Ecology had disposed of
significantly more high-level plutonium at its other sites in
Washington, Kentucky and Nevada than had been previously disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   At one site, in Beatty, Nev., which was used as a model for the
Ward Valley plan because of its similar desert location, employees
illegally dumped liquid nuclear waste -- which is barred from the
proposed Ward Valley facility -- throughout the 1970s. American
Ecology, then called the Nuclear Engineering Company, pleaded ``no
contest'' to two criminal counts and was fined $5,000 for each.
</P>
<P>
   Another facility at Maxey Flats, Ky., was run by the company for
25 years until it was closed in 1977 because the plutonium dumped
there had ``migrated'' hundreds of feet from its original burial
site. It is now a Superfund site.
</P>
<P>
   And, the report found, the company dumped 47,800 55-gallon drums
of radioactive wastes in the Pacific Ocean near the San Francisco
Bay between 1946 and 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``Visual observations using remotely operated vehicles and
submersibles show that many of the drums have ruptured and spilled
their contents onto the sea floor,'' according to the report. ``The
conclusions of the studies that have been conducted to determine
the levels of radioactivity vary on the significance of the
contamination.''
</P>
<P>
   In its application for the Ward Valley facility, U.S. Ecology
estimated that less than 1 pound of plutonium would be buried at
the site. However, according to the report, the company actually
estimates that it will dump about 124 pounds of plutonium-239 -- a
highly radioactive form that environmentalists say is 200 times
more toxic than weapons-grade plutonium -- at Ward Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The company denies that assertion. ``U.S. Ecology never
projected that 120 pounds of plutonium would go to Ward Valley,''
Nagel wrote in his response to the report, adding that they only
used the figure in a safety analysis because they wanted to use a
``conservative overestimate.''
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that an environmental impact study done
jointly by the state of California and the federal Bureau of Land
Management did not adequately address questions of whether
radioactivity could be released into the atmosphere, the water
table, or the surrounding land.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for Gov. Wilson, who has been fighting to purchase the
land for the dump since 1991, were unavailable for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
