<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-TOXIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIVIST BLAMES FRIEND'S DEATH ON SITE POLLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRATFORD, Conn. _ The Little League diamond is surrounded by a
chainlink fence, topped with rusty barbed wire and entangled with
weeds. The old light poles lean precariously toward the infield.
And the scuffed and faded red scoreboard looks down upon rotting
wooden bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   Raybestos field is built on landfill used by the now defunct
asbestos producer. It's where John O'Connor, the Cambridge
environmental activist running for the 8th Congressional District
seat, played baseball as a kid along with a friend, John (Kit)
Peters, who died of testicular cancer at 18.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in his campaign, O'Connor is blaming the toxic waste just
below the grass and otherwise strewn about this town, for Peters'
death. That event led to O'Connor's interest in environmental
protection and his work to win Congressional approval of the
Superfund environmental cleanup laws in the 1980s, he says.
</P>
<P>
   But town officials and health experts say there is no proof that
Kit Peters died as a result of exposure to toxic waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``That type of assertion is unfounded. It's understandable that
people who played on the field or people who had exposure to areas
where the waste was buried, particularly if individuals developed
cancer, will be suspicious about the cause of their cancer and may
link it to that exposure. But there is absolutely no evidence in
all of the studying we've done that can show us definitively the
cause and effect,'' said town health director Elaine O'Keefe.
</P>
<P>
   A decades-long study released several months ago by the
Connecticut Department of Public Health analyzed cancer data from
the department's Tumor Registry, one of the oldest in the country,
and environmental contamination data from the Environmental
Protection Agency. Computer-generated models were developed to
estimate exposure based on how close those with cancer lived to the
sites in Stratford, where the former Raybestos Corp. (now called
Raymark Industries) dumped its waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``No association between low birthweight and exposures to
Raymark waste was found,'' the study reported. ``In addition, no
consistent association was found between mesothelioma, testicular
cancer and all cancer cases occurring to persons under the age of
25 in Stratford and Raymark's waste exposures.''
</P>
<P>
   Bladder cancer rates and so-called early onset cancer, or cancer
in young people, were slightly higher, the report found, around
some Raymark sites, although the latter was found not to be
statistically significant.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said Tuesday it doesn't matter that the scientific
evidence doesn't support his claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Connecticut official who claims the study doesn't show a
health threat is an idiot masquerading as an expert,'' he said.
``Epidemiology is the crudest science of the sciences. It might
find a public health disaster, but nine times out of ten it misses
clusters of cancer. The larger point is that community exposed all
sorts of kids to proven poisons.''
</P>
<P>
   Raybestos made brake and clutch linings for cars at its Main
Street plant from 1919 until 1989, generating waste such as lead,
asbestos, PCBs and solvents that were dumped on public, residential
and commercial sites throughout the town _ a fact the study
supports.
</P>
<P>
   The plant itself is gone _ flattened, cleaned up, and
meticulously capped with asphalt pavement. There has been talk in
the town about soliciting a grocery store to move to the site. But
the Little League field remains off limits.
</P>
<P>
   The company left behind a $100 million national priority
Superfund site, a neighborhood filled with stories like those of
Kit Peters' parents _ who never sued the company _ and John
O'Connor, who is still suspicious enough to incorporate the story
into his Congressional campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``John O'Connor grew up near a ballfield built on an asbestos
dump,'' begins O'Connor's television ads which began airing
Tuesday. ``The dump caused one of his friends to die. Of cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy's parents, Aldana and Peter J. Peters, still live around
the corner from Raybestos Field. Aldana Peters says there was never
much of a controversy about the dumping in the neighborhood. And
she thought better in 1974 of writing a letter to the local paper
to suggest a link between her son's death and environmental
factors. She said she was worried that property values would
diminish.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Aldana Peters says she doesn't really remember John
O'Connor but recalls his family. She had not heard he was running
for Congress until his campaign called before the TV ads began
airing in the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often wondered what happened to them,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
