<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-GAMBLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE TARGETS GERMAN SITE USING `AOL' TRADEMARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM SOMACH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An Internet casino that called itself AOL Casino
but had no connection to America Online Inc. has pulled the plug on
itself after being slapped with a cease-and-desist order.
</P>
<P>
   The casino, at www.aol-casino.com and run from a computer in
Germany, went on line about a month ago in hopes of nabbing a share
of the lucrative Internet gambling market. Gamblers around the
world were able to open betting accounts at AOL Casino with a
credit card and then play blackjack, craps, roulette and other
casino games on line.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, the nation's No. 1 Internet service provider,
did not operate, sponsor, endorse or approve the AOL Casino,
America Online spokeswoman Tricia Primrose said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   America Online's legal department sent the AOL Casino a
cease-and-desist order June 16, telling the cyber-casino to stop
using the AOL name, Primrose said.
</P>
<P>
   ``America Online has spent lots of time, energy and money to
build the AOL brand name and we will not allow the name AOL to be
linked to something that we are not affiliated with,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the gambling site stopped operating, visitors to the World
Wide Web site now see another Internet casino _ the Circus Casino,
at which gambling is ``for fun without real money.''
</P>
<P>
   Circus Casino, also located at www.circus-casino.com, also is
based in Germany and is run by the same people who ran the AOL
Casino, according to Internet domain registration records.
</P>
<P>
   The real Circus Circus casino chain, which runs several real
casinos in Nevada, recently filed suit for trademark violation
against Circus Casino, but Circus Casino continues to operate on
line.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach anyone connected with AOL Casino for comment
were unsuccessful. A reporter's questions e-mailed to the AOL
Casino a week ago went unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, America Online is not satisfied with the demise of
AOL Casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``The domain aol-casino.com is still in use, as a link to
another casino, and that's no good,'' Primrose said. ``The whole
intention there is still to use the AOL trademark to drive traffic
to their site, so they have not fully complied with the terms of
the cease-and-desist order.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a cyber-gambling industry watchdog said America
Online's actions against the cyber-casino are just the beginning of
a new trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of casinos on the Internet that are illegally
using the names of established companies like AOL or Circus Circus
or Caesars Palace,'' said Lewis Gruppo, operator of Gamblersworld
(www.gamblersworld.com), a Web site that monitors the on-line
gambling industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``With almost 200 casinos on line nowadays, it's the quickest
way for a new on-line casino to get name recognition,'' Gruppo
said. ``And if you name yourself after something as well-known on
the Internet as AOL _ that's instant name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the established companies whose names have been stolen by
on-line casinos are now starting to fight back,'' he said.
``America Online is the first company to get rid of a cyber-casino
that stole its name, and Circus Circus is trying. Other companies
will follow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
