A4407 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-24 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP WORSHIP A LONELY SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How does a red-blooded American man get some time alone in Bill
Clinton's America? Here are the magic words: ``I'm going to watch
the World Cup. Anyone care to join me?''
</P>
<P>
   In a real country, like Great Britain, 95 percent of adult males
surveyed said they'd rather watch a World Cup game than have sex
with the woman of their dreams. In Germany, on the day the Fourth
Reich launched its 2-0 blitzkrieg of Team USA, employers expected _
and got _ zero attendance during the match time.
</P>
<P>
   But here? Don't get me started. The day of Germany-USA, I
waltzed around the Great Metropolitan Newspaper hunting for cronies
to savor the action with me. In the Living Arts section where I
work, the ``men'' were all waxing their ballet slippers, or
``appreciating'' Masterpiece Theatre preview tapes. I wandered over
to the GMN's legendary Sports section, and (itals)the television
sets weren't even turned on!(unitals) What kind of country is
this!?
</P>
<P>
   Men, women, children _ I'm telling you ... don't miss out.
Forget Michael, forget Pedro, forget the stupid U.S. Open, and
stupider Wimbledon. Those events are like streetcars; they'll come
back. The World Cup is unquestionably the greatest sports show on
earth, featuring the greatest athletes in the world. Even if they
do smoke in the locker room at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   How do I love World Cup? Let me count the ways. The ABC/ESPN
television broadcasts are sensational. You get to see two 45-minute
periods of commercial-free sports action, unadulterated by silly
``up close and personal'' profiles of athletes. In this galaxy, Bob
(Bootlicker) Costas is far, far away. The Cup commentators
helpfully explain the niceties of the game, and, more refreshingly,
they often shut up.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't believe in ethnic identities, World Cup soccer
reveals what a fool you are. The stolid Bulgarians; the quicksilver
Brazilians; the _ yes _ ruthlessly efficient Germans; the striving,
earnest, Americans whose star playmaker got kidney-kicked 30
seconds into the US-Germany game. The pain didn't last long; for
all intents and purposes, a perfectly executed German head goal
ended the match eight minutes later. Wilkommen to the National
League.
</P>
<P>
   This much said, national identity has proven to be a very
fungible commodity in World Cup '98. The American captain was a
German citizen until 1992. But that's nothing; defender David Regis
was a Frenchman until 25 days ago. Iran's coach lives in San
Francisco. Nigeria's coach, Bora Milutinovic (funny, doesn't sound
Nigerian) is in his fourth consecutive Cup, for his fourth
consecutive team. His previous employers were the United States,
Costa Rica, and Mexico. To paraphrase the great Tom Lehrer, Cup
allegiances are ruled by expediencies.
</P>
<P>
   Most blessedly, for all the kicking and shoving, head-bashing
and referee-baiting, the World Cup is not about the world, but
about sports. Only a moron, or Bill Clinton, cared about the
political implications of the US-Iran game. There were none. But
the soccer implications were huge, and it made for great viewing.
Both Nigeria and Colombia have changed governments since the World
Cup began. Who cares? If the teams come home winners, the
politicians can fool around to their hearts' content.
</P>
<P>
   And the game? I think the game is terrific. Sure, there's not as
much scoring as, say, when Tim Wakefield is on the mound for the
Sox. (Unforgettable Sunday Globe Page One headline: ``The
Netherlands ties Belgium, 0-0, in an intense, defensive soccer
struggle'') But the first 45 minutes of Colombia-Tunisia was one of
the most gripping athletic tilts I've ever watched. That same day,
Monday, the lead of the England-Romania match changed twice in the
last 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Can World Cup soccer usher in a new age of peace and universal
understanding? Possibly not. But if Norway can repeat last year's
sensational upset victory over Brazil, that will be conclusive
proof of the existence of God. At least for the Norwegians.
</P>
<P>
   (Post deadline addendum: Norway 2, Brazil 1. Yes!)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
