<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS SHARE RUN-UP BECOMING A MATTER OF FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Lycos Inc. really worth it?
</P>
<P>
   The ``it'' is the astounding value the stock market has placed
on the small internet company. Lycos shares were worth nearly $1.3
billion after they advanced another 4 1/4 to 68 3/4 Tuesday. The
stock has been on a tear to get there: up 66 percent this year and
a staggering 504 percent over the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos is among the small group of companies whose sites were
once classified as search engines but have since been acknowledged
as potential ``portals,'' the handful of places where millions of
people will routinely start when they want to get onto the Web.
Flashing ads and hooking customers along those Internet bottlenecks
are presumed to be huge business in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos stock got a big bump last year when it became one of the
few Internet firms in its class to actually turn a profit, tiny as
it was. The latest fuel added to the fire: Walt Disney Co.'s
purchase of a 43 percent stake in Infoseek Co., a Lycos competitor,
last week. A week earlier, General Electric Co.'s NBC television
network had purchased a majority stake in CNET's smaller Snap
Internet-search directory site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investments by both NBC and Disney have forced traditional
media players to really sit up and take notice of just what their
Internet strategy is going forward,'' said analyst Paul Noglows of
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos has commented publicly in recent months that it would be
interested in finding a partner in the traditional media world. The
rumor of the moment matches Lycos up with Time Warner Inc., which
has offered content on the Internet with only modest success
through its Pathfinder site and several others sites operated by
its Cable News Network subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   The details of such partnerships, which companies suit each
other, and on what kind of ownership terms, may be unclear. But the
deals are sure to be made, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every media company has talked to every portal,'' said
Chris Charron, an analyst at Forrester Research Inc. in Cambridge,
Mass. ``The combinations make an awful lot of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But they don't automatically justify today's stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos, based in Waltham, Mass., isn't alone as an Internet
company with a gigantic stock market valuation. Yahoo stock is
worth $6.8 billion, and the most valuable of them all, America
Online Inc., is worth $23 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, which earned 10 cents per share in its last quarter,
gained 8 1/2 to 1481/16 Tuesday. AOL, which spurned recent
overtures from AT&AMP;T Corp., trades at more than 200 times projected
earnings for the year ahead. It closed Tuesday at 106 1/4, up 5
1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos, which raised $100 million in a stock offering earlier
this month, is expected by analysts to lose money in the current
quarter and resume earning a modest profit in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The two deals struck this month between Internet firms and media
conglomerates may make business sense, but they shouldn't lead
investors to expect any windfalls.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement between NBC and Snap is small potatoes by the
television network's standard: It purchased a controlling interest
in the unit for $38 million.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's deal with Infoseek is much harder to value. Disney put
up only $70 million in cash, but threw in its Starwave unit.
Depending on who is guessing at the value of Starwave, which builds
and manages Internet sites, the Disney-Infoseek transaction is
worth $500 million to $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were disappointed. Infoseek stock has actually drooped
since the news last week, falling from 35 to 307/16 Tuesday. But
most of the Internet companies without partners have been hot
stocks this week.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts see the Disney and NBC deals as low-cost hedges on
the Internet by companies that want their share of the Web but
don't know how the business will unfold and are unwilling to
overpay anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Internet investors may indeed look back and see these as the
good old days when companies were young and their stocks cheap. But
paying up today for the stock remains an exercise in faith.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; There's more action in the ranks of United Asset Management Corp.,
the money management conglomerate that has been under pressure to
turn around lackluster results.
</P>
<P>
   UAM said Tuesday that Charles Salisbury, the company's top
marketing executive, would resign next month to spend more time
with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Provident Investment Counsel, UAM's second-largest affiliate,
said founder Robert Kommerstad would give up his title of chief
executive and let two younger managers run the 47-year-old Boston
firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
