<SLUG> BC-PUBLISHING-HOUGHTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUGHTON MIFFLIN STAYS INDEPENDENT WITH A DEPENDABLE MIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One by one, the icons of American book publishing have been
scooped up, often by foreign media conglomerates. Just in the last
few months, Random House and major parts of Simon &AMP; Schuster were
bought &UR;  &LR; by European owners.
</P>
<P>
   But Houghton Mifflin Co., the venerable 166-year-old publisher,
remains aloof from the pack. Bolstered by a strong textbook
business and a small but revitalized trade book division, North
America's last major independent publisher has posted &UR;  &LR; a solid,
though hardly &UR;  &LR; dazzling, track record.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with a fresh wave of mergers sweeping US publishing, can
Houghton Mifflin stay independent?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not for sale,'' declares Nader F. Darehshori, &UR;  &LR; 60,
Houghton Mifflin's chairman and chief executive, who got his start
peddling textbooks to colleges in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   The best defense against a takeover, of course, is
rising &UR;  &LR; earnings and a high stock price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shareholders do not object to independence as long as profits
are strong,'' says Robert L. Friedman, a senior vice president at
Franklin Mutual Advisors Inc., Houghton Mifflin's largest
shareholder with a 13 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin and its president, Michael Price, support management in
its bid to remain independent _ as long as earnings increase. ``We
are certainly comfortable that there's a lot of value in the
company right now,'' says Friedman.
</P>
<P>
   Price is known for making trouble when executives of companies
whose shares he owns don't produce results. He recently helped oust
Sunbeam Corp.'s chairman, ``Chain Saw Al'' Albert J. Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sure bet Dunlap's demise didn't go un-noticed in
the &UR;  &LR; Back Bay headquarters &UR;  &LR; of Houghton Mifflin, whose stock has
given investors reason to worry in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   In January it fell 24 percent on news that the company's 1998
earnings would be lower than expected because it would have to
spend more to develop new textbooks &UR;  &LR; and inoculate its computers
againt the &UR;  &LR; year 2000 bug. &UR;  &LR; From an October high of 40 1/4, the
stock dipped to 26 3/4 in January. On Friday, it closed at &UR;  &LR; 32
15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, earnings have fluctuated in recent years while sales
have grown only modestly. The company earned $49.8 million last
year on sales of $797.3 million. CIBC Oppenheimer analyst Rudolf A.
Hokanson expects earnings of $37 million in 1998, reflecting the
increased development and computer expenses.
</P>
<P>
   With a market capitalization of $1 billion, some analysts &UR;  &LR; think
the stock is cheap.
</P>
<P>
   That could make Houghton Mifflin tempting takeover bait in a
world of increasing consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   In the $21 billion US book publishing market, media giants like
Britain's Pearson PLC &UR;  &LR; and Germany's Bertelsmann AG have bought
American publishers, including top-ranked Random House, formerly
part of the Newhouse empire. Domestic companies like Time Warner
Inc. and Harlequin remain major players, but many of the smaller
companies have been bought by larger competitors.
</P>
<P>
   So far the company that counts Curious George, the children's
book heroine Martha, and novels by Philip Roth in its stable has
managed to stay independent by doing things its own way. Unlike the
big nameplate publishers that have been taken over in recent years,
Houghton Mifflin relies heavily on the dependable but unglamorous
field of textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   In its trade division _ which publishes fiction and nonfiction
titles _ it hunts for underappreciated and less expensive authors
and avoids paying huge advances for celebrities' books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management has always sought to do things their own way,''
says J. Kendrick Noble, a Texas consultant for the publishing
industry. ``Houghton is run well.''
</P>
<P>
   Darehshori's vision for Houghton's continued independence
includes the ambitious goal of $1 billion in sales in 2000. Analyst
Hokanson rates Houghton's stock a ``hold,'' noting that
Darehshori's sales target ``could be overly optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Houghton Mifflin itself has participated actively in the
consolidation craze, gobbling up several smaller houses. Founded in
1832, the Boston publisher grew through acquisitions, including
most recently McDougal, Littell &AMP; Co., a textbook company, which it
bought in 1994, and D.C. Heath, Raytheon Co.'s textbook unit, which
it acquired the following year for $455 million.
</P>
<P>
   While textbooks and educational materials are the company's core
business, Houghton also revived its flagging trade and reference
division under the leadership of Wendy Strothman, who joined
Houghton Mifflin in 1996 &UR;  &LR; from local independent Beacon Press.
After a period of rapid turnover in management, Strothman succeeded
in stabilizing the division, which publishes literature,
nonfiction, children's books such as the popular Martha series, and
reference books. &UR;  &LR; Her mantra is ``quality,'' a dictum she follows
in searching for underappreciated authors and refusing to pay huge
book advances for trendy books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are publishing books we think people will be reading for
decades to come,'' Strothman says. ``We are being very selective in
what we publish and the public is responding.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers say Strothman's approach is paying off. The
trade division's authors have won several major awards recently,
most notably the 1997 Pulitzer Prize for fiction, which went to
author Philip Roth for ``American Pastoral.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I think they've selected carefully and pushed hard,'' says
Andrew Wylie, Philip Roth's agent. ``We've submitted books to them
that they have not offered on.''
</P>
<P>
   And if anything, the company has stepped up its focus on
educational books, which accounted for 89 percent of sales last
year, up from 77 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houghton has been very careful over the last few years to
identify the school market as the market for them,'' says Charles
E. Hayward, former chief executive of Little, Brown publishing
house in Boston and now a &UR;  &LR; consultant. ``They've deemphasized their
trade division to some degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the trade division's revenues have remained around $90
million for the last five years, and some observers, such as
Franklin's Friedman, suggest Houghton should shed its trade
division to concentrate on textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Houghton Mifflin remains a major player in educational books,
number seven, according to the most recent ranking by &UR;  &LR; the industry
newsletter Subtext. It &UR;  &LR; is especially strong in sales to
kindergarten through sixth grade _ unusual among the major
educational publishers, most of whom concentrate on more profitable
college sales.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Houghton Miff-lin's formula can
help continue its legacy of independence. ``There's no predicting''
whether Houghton will eventually be bought out by a media
conglomerate, says Helene Atwan, director of Beacon Press, Wendy
Strothman's former publishing house. ``Nobody thought that Random
House would be sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say Houghton Mifflin's fate may hinge on whether the
company can expand past its core strength in school reading. ``I
believe that the way the educational publishing market is evolving,
it's becoming more difficult for companies to remain niche-oriented
and that scale is demanded if one wants to achieve consistent
success,'' Hokanson says. ``Houghton is on that edge between having
enough scale and being a niche player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
