<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COACH SELECTION CRUCIAL FOR US TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Before France '98, the last coach to bring the US
national team to The City of Light for a major international soccer
tournament was George M. Collins in 1924. Collins guided the US to
a 1-0 victory over Estonia, then a 3-0 loss to Uruguay in the Paris
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Collins was a competent businessman and coach; he had a .500
record with the national team. Collins was also an accomplished
writer _ he moonlighted as the Globe's soccer editor, sometimes
using the byline ``George Matthews'' (his middle name) to avoid
detection by his family.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sampson brought the US to Paris last week, with results
that were less satisfactory. His team is 0-2 in the World Cup,
losing to Germany, 2-0, and to Iran, 2-1. The Americans have one
game left, against Yugoslavia Thursday, but have already been
eliminated in the first round. Sampson will soon be gone, and this
is not to suggest his replacement come from the ranks of the media.
</P>
<P>
   But whoever takes over for Sampson must move the team in a
different direction. Sampson began this process when he became the
first US-born coach to openly acknowledge the Hispanic community,
as his predecessor, Bora Milutinovic, had. Sampson was greatly
influenced by Milutinovic and attempted to meld Milutinovic's
pragmatism with a sort of American concept of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson was fortunate to get this chance. He was to be a
caretaker when he guided the team for the first time against
Nigeria at Foxboro Stadium three years ago. The US, sparked by a
long-range John Harkes goal, rallied to defeat Nigeria, 3-2, on
June 11, 1995, and continued to achieve surprising results under
Sampson, including an upset of Argentina in the Copa America in
Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   But Sampson should have been replaced many months ago, mostly to
save him from the World Cup failure. He wasn't, though, because a
qualified, available alternative couldn't be found.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is a chance to do so. There are few proven coaches in
the US. The closest the country has come to producing a successful
professional coach is Bruce Arena, who guided D.C. United to two
Major League Soccer titles. Though Arena is a product of the
system, he has proven to be the exception.
</P>
<P>
   Arena is probably the best candidate, but he might be wise to
remain with D.C. United until 2002 World Cup qualifying begins.
</P>
<P>
   If the US Soccer Federation goes international, it would be wise
to take a lesson from Jamaica, which had excellent luck with Rene
Simoes, a Brazilian. Simoes found eight English players of Jamaican
descent to bolster a team that he described as being as skilled as
``trained seals'' when he arrived. The Jamaicans were athletic,
purposeful, strong, but they lacked discipline and tactical
awareness. Simoes grasped the Jamaicans' strengths and augmented
them with organization and enlightened training methods.
</P>
<P>
   The stereotypical US player has different characteristics than
the Jamaican. Perseverance, physical strength, yes. Ball skills,
no. The next US coach must advocate technique above everything
else.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, what US players should be doing is juggling the ball
like seals every chance they get. At least they should be allowed
and encouraged to have fun with the game. This cannot be
accomplished in coaching courses or through structured programs. It
should occur spontaneously, if youngsters are allowed the freedom
to make up their own games and routines.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one US coach can make a policy change. He must
balance the responsibility of attaining results with improving the
standard of play. Sampson constantly confronted this issue in the
proper spirit, but it is going to be a conundrum for whoever is
hired.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign coaches have been hired in the past by the USSF, which
went after the best of the best in the '70s. Dettmar Cramer of
Germany took over the national team, and Rinus Michels of Holland
was hired as an adviser. Cramer was simply overqualified for the
position, as might have been Carlos Alberto Parreira after he won
the 1994 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   There are coaches for situations. Milutinovic is a rare
chameleon, one who could teach US players defensive tactics, then
allow Nigerians to gamble with an all-out attacking style. Such a
coach is rare. But they exist, and they could be interested in the
potential of the US.
</P>
<P>
   The US attracts the best healers and scientists, the most
ambitious financiers, the most talented directors and actors, often
seeking opportunities that are unavailable elsewhere. Certainly,
the US has qualified soccer coaches who are in the country for
similar reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian coach, Jalal Talebi, is an example. Talebi has
resided in Palo Alto, Calif., for 14 years, but he was unnoticed in
his adopted country until he guided the Iranians to victory over
the US. Alkis Panagoulias had a similar international background
when he came to the US from Greece in the '60s. Panagoulias brought
Tab Ramos and others to the national team in the '80s. The next US
coach must find another Tab Ramos or two.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first acts of Alan Rothenberg's USSF presidency was to
hire longtime Fort Lauderdale, Fla., resident Nene Cubillas as a
regional coach. Cubillas, among the all-time leading World Cup
scorers, worked for a week and was never called back. Rothenberg's
good intention was apparently sabotaged by institutionalized
inertia and incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   The mishandling of Cubillas sent a message. An influential
faction of the USSF would exclude even the most credible of
``outsiders,'' whether they be Cubillas or Talebi. This must
change.
</P>
<P>
   There are too many USSF officials who appear to be amateurs or
glorified volunteers. National team players are coddled, not placed
in a position to succeed. Because of the inexperienced nature of
the support system, they are not afforded the advantages available
from the hundreds of millions of dollars of Nike sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   The insular nature of the USSF activities, the exclusionary
policies of the coaching programs, is reflected in low standards
for the national team and for MLS.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson driven home in this World Cup is that soccer is not a
nice sport in the international arena. There are big-money deals,
great amounts of pride on the line. Cutthroat deals are made off
the field and hard lessons are administered on it. There can be
great joy and pleasure, but there are also real hardships and pain.
There is no place for amateurs and volunteers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
