<SLUG> BC-SOC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIANS KNOW THE CUP'S INS AND OUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-GALMIER, France _ Miljan Miljanic, the president of
Yugoslavia's soccer federation, is chuckling (``We can laugh about
it now'') as he talks about how it was during the sanctions, when
the rest of the world kicked his country out of their game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am watching a match and the ball goes over the fence and all
22 players are chasing it,'' he says. ``Because they have only one
ball. If they lose it, they have no game.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball must not stop. That was the Yugoslavs' byword after the
United Nations made them stay home for 2 1/2 years as part of the
punishment for Serbia's ``ethnic cleansing'' policies. Between June
1992 and December 1994, neither the country's national team nor its
clubs were allowed to compete internationally.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs were expelled from the European championships days
before the event. They were kept out of the 1994 World Cup and
readmitted too late to qualify for the 1996 Olympics and European
championships. Their top players had to go abroad to make a living.
And the UN's harsh economic sanctions left the country's domestic
program on starvation rations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football for us became a fight for survival,'' says the
68-year-old Miljanic, who is considered the ``Grandpa'' of Yugoslav
soccer. ``If anything, the sanctions brought us together and made
us stronger. We would not be defeated. And now, we are here. This
alone is a victory for us.''
</P>
<P>
   After eight years on the sidelines, the Yugoslavs are back in
the game, with literally half the world watching. And if they can
beat or tie the Americans tomorrow night in Nantes, they'll advance
to the second round of the World Cup. The ball must not stop.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs want to stick around this quadrennial festival of
feet as long as they can because they know that their admission
ticket could be revoked again. They know that their government is
under fire from the international community for its armed crackdown
in Kosovo. They know the UN is rattling the saber, threatening
intervention. They know sanctions could be imposed anew.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to go back to a bad marriage,'' says Miljanic,
wincing.
</P>
<P>
   So the Yugoslavs are determined to make the most of their time
upon the stage, because they have learned how abruptly they can be
given the hook. They were already in Sweden for the 1992 European
tournament when the sanctions were imposed; they were sent home and
had to watch Denmark, their replacement, win the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shock of having to go back was unbearable,'' says
Miljanic. ``I never dreamed that could happen. I was so much of a
romantic that I couldn't believe there would be sanctions for
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   The shock turned to bitterness, and then resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sanctions were imposed on Monday,'' Miljanic says. ``On
Tuesday, we decide how we are going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the game had to continue. So the domestic league,
based around old Belgrade rivals Red Star and Partizan, kept going
even though many top stars joined foreign clubs to keep their
skills at a world-class level. The federation created intramural
``national'' teams and dreamed up competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people laughed,'' says Miljanic, ``but we had to keep
the interest.''
</P>
<P>
   And emphasis was increased on development at the youth level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even children as young as 10,'' Miljanic says. ``Because we
didn't know how long the sanctions would be. We thought they might
be even longer than they were. We needed to make sure we would have
players.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball must not stop, even if there was little more than the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The planes were grounded, the trains weren't working, the
buses had no petrol,'' says Miljanic. ``We had no equipment, no
soccer balls. But every match was played. How did we survive? I
don't know. We did it with creative simplicity and learning how to
be poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the federation remained in daily contact with its
stars who were playing in Italy, in Spain, in England, even in
Japan. Eventually, the sanctions would be lifted and the Mijatovics
and Stojkovics and Savicevics would have to pull on the
red-white-and-blue jersey again and put Yugoslavia back on the
global map.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the ban ended, the Yugoslavs felt the aftershock.
Because they hadn't played any international matches, their world
ranking tumbled to 196th and doomed them to a brutal Cup qualifying
group with Spain, the Czech Republic, and Slovakia. When the
Yugoslavs needed to beat Hungary in a special playoff to get their
ticket here, their years of bottled-up anger and frustration and
impatience found vent in astounding 7-1 and 5-0 victories.
</P>
<P>
   Then they went to Marseille for last December's draw and found
the football gods had played a perverse prank on them. Besides the
Germans, the three-time world champions whom they hadn't beaten in
25 years, the Yugoslavs drew a pair of political enemies in the US
and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The politics they have learned to take with a shrug. If you live
in the Balkans, politics comes with mother's milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many nations we have political differences with,''
says defender Zeljko Petrovic. ``This is just sport. The World Cup
is about football.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Yugoslavs, football was always their way of transcending
politics at home. Though the Serbs and Bosnians and Croats and
Slovenes and Macedonians and Montenegrins made for a volatile
country, they combined for a terrific soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   Seven times since World War II, Yugoslavia qualified for the
World Cup, reaching at least the quarterfinals four times. In 1990,
the last time the six republics competed as one, the Yugoslavs came
within a penalty kick of knocking off defending champion Argentina
and making the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Yugoslavia, football is the amazing social phenomenon,''
says Miljanic. ``Only in football was there no war between
republics.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavia of 1990 is no more. This Yugoslavia has been
reduced to Serbia and Montenegro and branded an outlaw state. Its
team here has been asked as many questions about politics as
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have questions about politics,'' coach Slobodan Santrac
said this week, in exasperation, ``you can contact our embassy in
Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics is what kept one of the world's most entertaining
soccer teams, ``the Brazilians of Europe,'' isolated and peering
through the stadium gate for eight years. Now the Yugoslavs are
back, as the French sporting daily L'Equipe says, ``like a phantom
coming out of the night''.
</P>
<P>
   Miljan Miljanic jokes about it now, but he still has the
1,000-page memorandum he wrote during the sanctions about how to
keep the ball rolling when nobody else will play with you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is what I write at the top,'' he says. ``I HOPE NO OTHER
COUNTRY EVER HAS TO USE THIS.''(Eds.: CQ caps)
</P>
</TEXT>
