<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4437 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOM-GRAVES-ART-BOS &LR;      06-24 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOM-GRAVES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE GRAVES SISTERS, ROWING IS A FAMILY ACT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Leslie Graves is learning what it's like to
hear her muscles cry, to look down at her hands and see raw patches
of pulp, to make a boat go a little farther and a little faster
when a cruise to Pluto seems more likely and markedly easier.
</P>
<P>
   Her three sisters? They already know. Alison Graves, 38, and Tia
Fischer, 39, rowed on their college teams, and Carie _ well, Carie
Graves, who turns 45 this week, is among the finest sweep oarswomen
in US history, making three Olympic rowing teams and winning a gold
medal in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   But Leslie, 43, had long been living in a world of books that
stretched her mind, not her hamstrings; that made her smarter, not
stronger; that touched her soul but did not make it whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there was some important part of life I had never
done,'' said Leslie. ``I didn't know what it was, because I had
never done it, but now I'm starting to figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Daybreak's mist still hugged the Charles River as she and her
sisters ended a recent training session that will take them to the
Pacific Northwest later this summer: On Aug. 14, they will face at
least 18 other boats in the Women's B 4(plus) category of the Nike
World Masters Games rowing competition.
</P>
<P>
   It's an exciting adventure for all of them, a rare chance as
adults to indulge and revel in their sisterhood, but as they talk
their eyes keep returning to Leslie. In this endeavor, it seems,
she has become the Sister of Sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how it feels: that surging at the end, the nervousness
at the starting line,'' said Alison. ``I keep thinking, if we were
to win this race, how it would be for Leslie.''
</P>
<P>
   For Carie, the women's crew coach at Northeastern University,
racing is a natural decision. For Alison, in public relations with
Hewlett-Packard, and Tia, a court commissioner in Los Angeles
County, it's a return to precious memories of hard-earned,
deeply-shared exhaustion. But for Leslie, studying at the
University of Wisconsin for her doctorate in the philosophy of
biology, it's uncharted territory that every day brings a new
revelation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never, ever in my life ever pushed myself to my limit on
anything,'' she said, another workout looming just seven hours
away. ``Relatively speaking, everything else I've ever done has
been a complete cakewalk.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of them, the logistics of rowing together seemed as
daunting as the romance of it was enticing. But Alison remembers
her reaction when the long-distance phone lines started humming
last March as the sisters _ she and Tia in southern California,
Carie in Cambridge, Leslie in Spring Green, Wis. _ began toying
with the notion. ``My first question was, is Leslie going to do
this? If Leslie is going to do this, I have no excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   And so they commenced: Carie plotting workouts and lining up
boats, Alison trying to drum up sponsors, husbands entreatied for
their help and patience, everyone flipping their calendars to
figure out when and where they could get together on the water. Hal
Menendez, a Madison attorney who had coxed for the sisters'
brother, Ross, when he was a Badger rower, was quickly lined up as
coxswain. The chance to share a boat, he said, with the legendary
Carie was an intoxicating mix of intimidating and irresistible; any
worries about Leslie's ability to get up to speed were assuaged by
her bloodline.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Carie and Ross, father Robert was captain of the 1956
Wisconsin rowing team. ``Based on the rest of the family,'' said
Menendez, ``I knew if she said she would do it, she would be
serious about it.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting in shape on their own over the summer, it was
October before the sisters came together in Boston for five days of
a major learning experience. ``We have an Olympic gold medalist in
our boat, so you think, we're going to be really good,'' Alison
said. ``After we had our first workout together it became clear
that wouldn't make any difference. Rowing is the quintessential
team sport. We all have to try to be as good as she is instead of
letting her pull us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty bad,'' Carie said.
</P>
<P>
   They reunited in Newport Beach, Calif., over the holidays, where
almost everyone _ including the nine children, ages 19 months to 19
years they have among them _ got sick with stomach flu. But,
between bouts of retching and cleaning up after their kids, the
sisters kept rowing.
</P>
<P>
   In May they regrouped in Newport Beach for just 24 hours,
courtesy of Nike, to film a promotional video for the Games (``This
is like the road trip of all road trips,'' Tia said) before their
training blitz here earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   It was after those eight days of grinding, blistering two-a-day
sessions on the Charles that it all began to come together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a lot further ahead of where I thought we'd ever be,''
said Carie earlier this week. ``We actually did three race pieces,
and they were pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Menendez agreed. ``I came off the water very confident this boat
has a chance to medal, if not win, and that's something people
would not have thought if they saw us eight months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time she signed on to this undertaking, just over a year
ago, Leslie was 35 pounds heavier and, by her own report, proud of
having drifted into fat middle age. Now, muscle has taken over from
fat and middle age suddenly doesn't seem so old _ ``Every time I
see her, she's a different woman,'' said Tia _ but the athletic
psyche is still proving a most worthy opponent. Coming late to the
cultural experience of being coached isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're accomplished in your field,'' said Menendez, ``and
suddenly somebody's telling you what to do and you can't talk
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is altering your self-image. ``You have talent,
Leslie,'' said Tia suddenly, speaking directly to her sister. ``You
underestimate yourself. You need to stop doing that. Now you need
to accept yourself as an athlete, not (as) a housewife with three
kids who's going out in a boat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She had to come into this feeling like she was the weak
link,'' said Menendez, ``and I hope she's starting to see herself
as just another link, because that's what she's become.''
</P>
<P>
   With race day just over six weeks away, the sisters look ahead.
On the morning of Aug. 14, at 11 a.m., after leaving their ``mom
worries'' on the shore from which their families will be cheering
and their proud father crying; after coast-to-coast visits in which
they shared Neosporin and ice packs as eagerly as sisterly gossip
and care packages of cookies from mom; after reenacting their
childhood of hard work together on the family farm in Wisconsin,
they will get in their boat.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie knows what she wants to happen next. ``I want to be able
to embrace and welcome what you have to do when you're body is in
extreme pain. That's been a real issue for me. I just want to be
able to not shut down in the face of the pressure. I want every
stroke in the race to be rowed with dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to have the words `I can't do this' not be in my
head.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
