A4492 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-ECONOMY-HNS &LR;      06-24 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA BOOM TO CONTINUE INTO NEW CENTURY, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A closely watched economic report said
California's robust economy will continue beyond 2000 despite the
downtown in trade with Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The strong economy has its downsides, according to the study,
including traffic congestion, increased pollution and soaring home
prices.
</P>
<P>
   But economists from the University of California at Los Angeles
said in the report that they prefer today's $4.4 billion state
budget surplus to the economic decline experienced only a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to believe there will be discontinuity
beyond 2000,'' said Tom Lieser, executive director of the UCLA
Anderson Forecast, a quarterly report from the Anderson Graduate
School of Management.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected California to continue to grow somewhat
faster than the nation ``over an extended period of time,'' in part
because of an infusion of well-educated workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, beyond 2000, Asia will again be an asset rather than
a liability,'' Lieser said of the only troubling statistics in his
findings _ the decline in exports to South Korea, Thailand, the
Philippines and several other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA study, released Wednesday, is even more optimistic than
that produced by the California Department of Finance, whose chief
economist, Ted Gibson, had been accused by some legislators of
being an optimist.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA projects that the growth in California's non-farm
employment, following last year's 3.3 percent increase, will be 3.4
percent in 1998 (compared to Gibson's 3.2 percent) and 2.5 percent
in both 1999 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA predicts associated gains in income _ 7.5 percent in 1998
(compared to Gibson's projected 7.2 percent), 6.5 percent in 1999
and 6.4 percent in 2000. Last year, personal income grew 7.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Job growth rates for the San Francisco Bay area remain
superlative, and have shown a tendency to be revised upwards in
annual benchmark reviews,'' Lieser said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieser said that in May, the Bureau of Economic Analysis of the
Commerce Department, using 1996 figures, found that the San
Francisco metropolitan area had the highest per-capita income in
the nation: $39,746, a 28.4 percent increase over 1990. New Haven,
Conn., was second at $38,962; West Palm Beach, Fla., third at
$38,962; and San Jose fourth at $35,395.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA quarterly report contained the best news in years for
Los Angeles County, the state's most populous with a payroll of 3.8
million people. The county has spent the '90s in recession or
lagging behind its neighbors to the north.
</P>
<P>
   In the first five months of the year, Los Angeles County had job
growth of 2.8 percent, still below the state average, ``but a lot
more supportive of what is going on elsewhere and it means the
county will not be a net charity case to the extent it has been,''
Lieser said.
</P>
<P>
   Orange County led the economic parade in Southern California,
with 4.5 percent job growth from January through May, and the
five-county Greater Los Angeles region had a 3.4 percent job gain
and an unemployment rate of 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Job growth rose by 2.4 percent in San Francisco in the first
five months, and 3.1 percent in Oakland. Statewide, job growth had
been 3.6 percent, a full percentage point higher than the national
rate, and unemployment in California is 5.5 percent, compared with
6.3 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   California accounted for about 15 percent of the national
increase in employment during the 12 months which ended in May.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions in much of Asia have affected trade. California
exports to South Korean declined 42.4 percent in the first five
months, and were off 38.6 percent to Thailand, down 18.9 percent to
the Philippines and 12.3 percent to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But exports to Mexico rose 30.5 percent, representing a $750
million increase. There were other major gains in Western Europe
and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is enough good news for now to offset the weakness in
major Asian nations,'' Lieser said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
