</P>
<P>
   SIDDONS _ Anne Rivers Siddons is not moving from Atlanta to
Charleston until November, but her thoughts obviously were already
there. Her new novel, ``Low Country,'' is set on the South Carolina
coast. To launch the book, HarperCollins hosted a lavish plantation
party for her near Charleston on Wednesday night. We talked with
Siddons on Tuesday about the move and visit her new Charleston
home. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-TEST _ Her knees were swollen, so Faye Ferrell slowly
climbed the steps into the mobile clinic, holding on to Iris
Amaker. ``Here is a technician who has never had a mammogram,''
Amaker said of the woman she had just recruited to have a breast
exam to screen for cancer. Ferrell, 72, had worked as a nurse in
the radiology and X-ray departments. But like many women over 50 in
Georgia, she had never had a breast X-ray herself. BreasTest aims
to change that. (Lee, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-SIDE _ Who qualifies, how the program is funded. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-BRIEFS _ An analysis of a 1996 outbreak of multi-drug
resistant pneumonia in an Okla. nursing home (11 sickened, 3 dead)
says that it's vital that the institutionalized elderly be
vaccinated; some patients with epilepsy can have clusters of
repeated seizures that are different from their regular pattern of
seizures and that last hours and a drug-containing gel that's
administered rectally seems to be effective, safe and inexpensive.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
