<HEADER>
A4515 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERB-THAIBASIL-TEX     06-24 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERB-THAIBASIL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AROMA OF SUCCESSFUL THAI DISHES BEGINS WITH A SPECIAL BASIL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABCs: Thai basil (''bai krapow'') is a shrubby annual that
reaches 2 feet, with sweetly aromatic leaves. The more sun it gets,
the redder the leaves turn.
</P>
<P>
   Growing conditions: Grow like other basils, planting from
transplants in late spring.
</P>
<P>
   Companion plants: Tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Food pairings: Fish, chicken, beef curry
</P>
<P>
   Caveats: Treat for worm damage with ``Bacillus thuringiensis''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CITY GRILL'S GULF REDFISH WITH SPICY SZECHUAN SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   6 redfish fillets, 1/3 to 1/2 pound each, OR fillets of
swordfish, tuna, mahi-mahi or shark
</P>
<P>
   Garnish: 6 Thai basil sprigs (see Note), lime wedges and
slivered scallion
</P>
<P>
   SZECHUAN MARINADE
</P>
<P>
   1 8-ounce can Szechuan chile paste, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dark honey
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Oriental sesame oil, see Note
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 or 2 fresh limes
</P>
<P>
   SPICY SZECHUAN SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Oriental sesame oil, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Szechuan marinade
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 tablespoons Thai basil, chopped, see Note
</P>
<P>
   Prepare marinade by mixing all ingredients, blending well.
</P>
<P>
   Mix ingredients for spicy Szechuan sauce; chill.
</P>
<P>
   Dip fish fillets in marinade and place presentation-side down on
grill over red-hot coals. Grill until well-marked by the grill,
turning once (approximately 8 minutes per inch of thickness of
fish).
</P>
<P>
   Serve with a generous dollop of spicy Szechuan sauce, either on
the side or melted on the fish, and garnished with a sprig of Thai
basil, several lime wedges and slivered scallion.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Available at Asian groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 521 calories, 40 grams fat, 6
grams carbohydrates, 34 grams protein, 88 milligrams cholesterol,
364 milligrams sodium, 69 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Herb Garden Cookbook'' by Lucinda Hutson (Texas Monthly
Press, $21.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN STIR-FRIED WITH TOMATOES AND BASIL
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 dried, hot red chiles
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon shrimp paste (''kapi),'' see Note, OR anchovy paste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound boned, skinned chicken (preferably from the leg), cut
into 1-inch squares
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon bright red paprika
</P>
<P>
   2 medium-sized tomatoes (about 6 ounces), dropped into boiling
water for 10 seconds, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (3 1/2 ounces) drained, canned straw mushrooms, see Note
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fish sauce (''nam pla),'' see Note, OR salt to
taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (packed) fresh Thai basil leaves (''bai kaprow),'' see
Note
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a wok or large frying pan over rather high heat.
When hot, add red chiles and garlic. Stir once or twice, and add
shrimp paste. Stir for about 10 seconds, breaking up paste, and add
chicken. Stir until chicken is lightly browned. Add paprika and
stir.
</P>
<P>
   Add tomatoes, mushrooms, fish sauce and basil. Stir for 1
minute. Turn heat to low and simmer gently for 10 minutes, stirring
occasionally. Dish may be made ahead and reheated.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with rice.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Available at Asian groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 320 calories, 18 grams fat, 7
grams carbohydrates, 32 grams protein, 96 milligrams cholesterol,
720 milligrams sodium, 51 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Madhur Jaffrey's A Taste of the Far East'' by Madhur Jaffrey
(Carol _
</P>
