</P>
<P>
   BREAST-TEST _ Her knees were swollen, so Faye Ferrell slowly
climbed the steps into the mobile clinic, holding on to Iris
Amaker. ``Here is a technician who has never had a mammogram,''
Amaker said of the woman she had just recruited to have a breast
exam to screen for cancer. Ferrell, 72, had worked as a nurse in
the radiology and X-ray departments. But like many women over 50 in
Georgia, she had never had a breast X-ray herself. BreasTest aims
to change that. (Lee, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
