<HEADER>
A4545 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SENECA-FALLS-3     06-24 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SENECA-FALLS-3RDTAKE-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SENECA FALLS: revolution's origins.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This summer is the 150th anniversary of the signing of the
Declaration of Sentiments at the first Women's Rights Convention in
the United States in Seneca Falls, N.Y., on July 19 and 20, 1848,
and a series of events will be held there in celebration. Most
events are scheduled for July 16 through 19.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton; the singer Judy Collins; the poet Maya
Angelou; Secretary of State Madeline Albright; the author Betty
Friedan, and the actress Sandra Bernhard are among the expected
participants. Here is a sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Events and Activities
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; National Women's Hall of Fame  &LR; holds its annual induction
ceremony at 10:30 a.m. on July 11, at the New York Chiropractic
College Athletic Center, 2360 Route 89, Seneca Falls. Those to be
honored include Ms. Albright, Ms. Angelou and Beverly Sills, the
soprano and arts executive. Tickets cost $30, $25 for Hall of Fame
Members, and $20 for those 18 and under or 65 and over. Tickets and
information: (315) 568-8060, extension 22. The hall's Web site is
www.greatwomen.org.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after its national convention ends in Rochester, about
60 miles away, the  &UR; National Organization for Women  &LR;  holds a rally
at noon on July 14 at Declaration Park, 136 Fall St., Seneca Falls.
Patricia Ireland, president, and Eleanor Smeal, past president,
will speak about the legacy of the Declaration of Sentiments and
NOW's goals. Free. Information: (716) 242-0516.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Religious Women and Women's Rights,''  &LR; a worship service and
presentation by the Rev. Betty Bone Schiess, an Episcopal priest,
and the Rev. Dr. Elaine Cleeton, a United Church of Christ
minister, will be at 7 p.m. on July 15 at the First United
Methodist Church, State and Chapel Streets, Seneca Falls. A
candlelight procession to the Wesleyan Chapel will follow; (315)
568-6306.
</P>
<P>
   Opening ceremonies of the celebration of the  &UR; 150th Anniversary
of the First Women's Rights Convention,  &LR;  will start between 10
a.m. and noon on July 16, depending on the schedule of Mrs.
Clinton. She and Gov. George E. Pataki of New York are scheduled to
speak at the outdoor ceremony, at Mynderse Academy High School, 105
Troy St. Free. Information: (315) 568-2991 or
www.nps.gov/wori/celeb98.htm.
</P>
<P>
   A two-day  &UR; Heritage Run  &LR; begins at 8 a.m. July 17, by the
Elizabeth Cady Stanton House, 32 Washington Street, Seneca Falls,
and goes to the Susan B. Anthony House in Rochester; the first leg
is to Canandaigua. Up to 240 individuals or teams (of any size) may
enter, but they must have sponsors and register in advance.
Proceeds benefit the Anthony house. Information and sponsorship
forms: the Monroe County Sports Development Corporation, 333 North
Plymouth Avenue, Rochester, N.Y. 14608; (716) 262-3832.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Common Ground,''  &LR; part of the Women's Hall of Fame
distinguished speakers series, focuses on women's and civil rights.
Ms. Bernhard and Ms. Friedan are among the scheduled panelists, at
2 p.m. on July 18 at the Stanton House, 32 Washington Street.
Information: (315) 568-8060, extension 22.
</P>
<P>
   A  &UR; ``suffrage march,''  &LR; including NOW officials, will be held
downtown on July 18 at 11 a.m., ending at Academy Square, Park
Street. Information: Seneca Falls Historical Society, (315)
568-8412.
</P>
<P>
   Performances
</P>
<P>
   A re-enactment of the July 4, 1876,  &UR; Declaration of Women's
Rights,  &LR; an update on the 1848 Declaration of Sentiments, will be
performed by Suzanne Pullen and Sally Roesch Wagner at 2 p.m. July
5 at Declaration Park; (315) 568-2991.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Equality of Rights: The First Women's Rights Convention,''  &LR; a
dramatization, will be performed July 15 at 2 p.m., and July 16,
17, 18 and 19 at 2 and 6 p.m. at Wesleyan Chapel, in the park.
Tickets, $10, are available at the visitors center, beginning at 9
a.m. the day of a performance. Information: (315) 568-2991.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Sun Flower,''  &LR;  a one-person play based on the life of
Elizabeth Cady Stanton, written and performed by Elizabeth Perry,
is scheduled for July 16 at 3 p.m. at the Academy Square
Auditorium, 12 Park Street, Seneca Falls. Free; (315) 568-8412.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Babes in Arms, &LR;  a drama group, will give portrayals of
Frederick Douglass, Lucretia Mott, Susan B. Anthony and Sojourner
Truth on July 16 at 3 p.m. and July 17 at 4 p.m., at Declaration
Park. Free; (315) 568-2991.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Judy Collins  &LR; in concert, July 16, 7 p.m., Mynderse Academy
High School football field, 105 Troy Street. Free; (315) 568-8412
or (315) 568-4117.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Why I Became a Women's Rights Man,''  &LR;  with Fred Morsell as
Frederick Douglass, will be performed on July 18 at 9 a.m. at First
Presbyterian Church, 23 Cayuga Street. It will be followed at 10
a.m. by  &UR; ``The Equal Rights Amendment: Our Legacy, Our Goal,'' &LR;  a
program commemorating the 75th anniversary of the equal rights
amendment campaign. Tickets are $10 for both from the Alice Paul
Centennial Foundation, Post Office Box 1376, Mount Laurel, N.J.
03054, (609) 231-1885, and at the foundation's exhibit at the
Women's Expo in Academy Square on Park Street, Seneca Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Daily Activities
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Past, Present and Future Tents  &LR; will be open July 16 to 19 at
the historical society, 55 Cayuga Street, with speakers and
discussion groups. Visitors are encouraged to write their memories
and hopes.
</P>
<P>
   The society will also sponsor a  &UR; Children's Tent  &LR;  July 16
through 19. Various performers, including the Indian storyteller
Charlene Winger-Bearskin, Gary the Happy Pirate, an Irish band and
dance groups, will appear. Both tents are open 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.
Free. Information: the historical society, (315) 568-8412.
</P>
</TEXT>
