<HEADER>
A4585 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-INITIATIVES-HNS     06-24 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-INITIATIVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA'S NOVEMBER BALLOT REPLETE WITH INITIATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Californians will be asked to vote on at least
five statewide ballot initiatives in the November general election,
continuing a trend of letting those who go to the polls act as
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   California's tribes are sponsoring a measure that seeks to
change state laws on Indian gambling, a proposition that is shaping
up as the most heated and expensive fight, pitting the tribes
against powerful gambling interests.
</P>
<P>
   Five propositions have been certified for the Nov. 3 ballot. At
least two more are likely to make the ballot before Thursday's
deadline for checking petition signatures.
</P>
<P>
   California is known nationally for its often contentious ballot
measures. In the June 2 primary, voters approved Proposition 227,
which essentially eliminates bilingual education. Past California
ballot initiatives have legalized the use of marijuana for medical
purposes and scrapped affirmative action in state hiring and
contracting.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent measure to qualify for the November ballot is an
education reform package sponsored by Gov. Pete Wilson. The
initiative would, among other things, lock into law Wilson's
efforts to reduce kindergarten through third-grade classes to 20 or
fewer pupils.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think kids are far too important to rely on the budget
drafters in Sacramento,'' said Mitch Zak, director of the Wilson
initiative campaign. ``We'd like to see it as a fundamental policy,
not a political contingency.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiative also calls for mandatory testing of teachers in
their subject areas, and would give parents new powers to determine
spending priorities in schools by allowing them seats on school
``governing councils.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature still has its chance to add measures to the
November ballot, including a much-debated $9 billion school bond
issue to build new classrooms and repair older schools. The
deadline for such measures is July 13.
</P>
<P>
   Other measures with enough signatures to make the ballot are:
</P>
<P>
   _ A proposition by environmentalists to give $218 million in
state tax credits each year until January 2011 to businesses that
switch from high-polluting vehicles and equipment to
cleaner-burning alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   _ An initiative by animal-rights groups to ban the use of
steel-jawed traps to kill nongame animals such as bobcats and
beavers for the sale of their fur. It also would outlaw two types
of poison used to kill coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   _ A measure to make it a felony to sell, trade or keep a horse,
burro or mule for the purpose of killing the animal for human
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of an unaddressed issue,'' said Cathleen Doyle, who
co-wrote the Save the Horses initiative. She said 150,000 horses
were slaughtered last year in the United States for their meat,
including an estimated 10,000 in California. ``People don't even
know this is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The consensus in Sacramento is that one issue will dominate the
ballot: Indian gambling. Analysts are predicting spending in the
race easily could exceed $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would change state law by allowing Indians to
operate slot machines and Las Vegas-style card games, rather than
the bingo and card games they operate now.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal representatives insist it is not an expansion of their
gambling operations. They say it simply would legalize what many of
the 40 California tribes that have gambling operations are doing
now.
</P>
<P>
   Tribes supporting the measure are running ads statewide,
thanking those who signed the initiative petition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of money to be made from the initiative, and
that constitutes a threat to current gaming interests in the state,
and that includes the state itself,'' which runs the lottery, said
Mark Petracca, chairman of the political science department at the
University of California at Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   The tribes are calling their campaign ``Californians for Indian
Self-Reliance'' and arguing the measure is the only way to keep
some tribes afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tribes in the last 10 years of tribal gaming have been able to
put together an industry that has created $4 billion worth of
economic activity in their local communities,'' said Dan
Pellissier, spokesman for the campaign. ``If the initiative doesn't
pass ... that $4 billion of economic activity will diminish. For
some tribes, it could be critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Two measures still are waiting for certification, though
supporters say they have more than enough signatures to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   One is an initiative to levy a 50-cent-per-pack tax on
cigarettes and other tobacco products to pay for early education
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The other proposition, sponsored by critics of the electric
power industry, would give consumers a 20 percent rate reduction,
double the cut ratepayers got under California's landmark
deregulation law that took effect in January.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also would prevent the power industry from
recovering losses from nuclear power plants and other money-losing
investments, which ratepayer advocates say add up to $28 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1458EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
