<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4591 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPERAS-80s-2TAKES-$AD     06-24 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERAS-80s-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 BELATED FRUITS OF THE OPERATIC '80s   (af)  
 By PAUL GIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The scarcity of good new operas in the present decade _ unless
something remarkable happens more than once during the next year
and a half _ makes all the more striking how much was achieved in
the 80s.
</P>
<P>
   Messiaen's only stage work, ``St. Francois d'Assise,'' was
presented by the Paris Opera. La Scala in Milan produced the first
three installments in Karlheinz Stockhausen's series of operas for
the days of the week: ``Thursday,'' ``Saturday'' and ``Monday.''
Luciano Berio had two operas staged in quick succession: ``La Vera
Storia'' and ``Un Re in Ascolto.'' So did Harrison Birtwistle, with
``The Mask of Orpheus'' and ``Yan Tan Tethera.'' John Adams's
``Nixon in China'' also made its bow.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of those works have entirely disappeared from the
theater. ``St. Francis'' had a spectacular second production, at
Salzburg in 1992, and will be revived there this summer. ``Nixon''
crops up from time to time, and so do the Berio operas: ``Un Re in
Ascolto'' most recently at the Lyric Opera of Chicago in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But all these pieces are more likely to go on playing in the
theater of the mind, their scores heard from recordings, and the
recent release on CD of ``Un Re in Ascolto'' and ``The Mask of
Orpheus'' fills two important gaps.
</P>
<P>
   Both works suggest answers to the question of why this great
flowering of opera occurred in the 80s. For one thing, there was
still, within large institutions, some trust in the avant-garde.
For another, composers and writers were starting to discover new
kinds of drama that would fit with new kinds of music.
</P>
<P>
   Action might be many-layered and repetitive, suggesting the
movements of memory or imagination. Characters would often be
mythic figures, whether ancient or modern: people who, again,
already have a place in our minds. Operatic drama was becoming,
like music at the time, fluid and associative.
</P>
<P>
   (The other question, concerning the sharp decline in the 90s,
can be answered with brute simplicity by citing lack of
investment.)
</P>
<P>
   The central character in ``Un Re in Ascolto'' (``A King
Listening'') is an impresario, and his mind is therefore doubly a
theater. What passes through that double theater, seemingly during
his dying moments, are thoughts of a staging of Shakespeare's
``Tempest,'' in which he is both producer and Prospero.
</P>
<P>
   These thoughts flit from casting to rehearsal, from rehearsal to
performance, under the shadow of greater tragedies in the greater
theater of real life. The singers Prospero auditions for the
principal female role all challenge him on a personal level and,
finally, also on a political level. Outside Prospero's theater
there is a revolution going on. How can his little kingdom survive?
</P>
<P>
   It can survive, Berio implies, by welcoming into itself its own
obsolescence and decay. If the musical theater can be used to
represent its own workings, then it can get around the
awkwardnesses of its historical and social superfluity. But only
for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Un Re in Ascolto'' not only Prospero but also opera itself
is portrayed in its death throes. The art is simply falling apart,
and Berio's score evokes that dissolution in masterly fashion while
providing broken lines of continuity, notably in Prospero's arias.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Un Re in Ascolto'' is opera dying, ``The Mask of Orpheus''
is opera in birth. Like Berio, Birtwistle recognizes that an
essentially discontinuous, undirected musical style _ a style that
has gone beyond the steady forward movement of tonal harmony _
should equally reach beyond linear narrative. But his alternative
is quite different. Instead of mingling various phases in the
development of one story, he mingles various stories.
</P>
<P>
   The main features of the Orpheus myth are all present in
chronological order in the opera _ the marriage of Orpheus and
Eurydice, her death, his descent into the underworld to retrieve
her, his failure to do so, his death _ but often they are told more
than once in differing ways. They can also be interrupted by
similar stories from Greek mythology, mimed to electronic music.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   And their importance can be other than expected. For instance,
Orpheus's journey through the underworld occupies the whole second
act, but the score barely registers the events we know from other
Orpheus operas: the hero's musical seduction of Charon, his
pleading with Pluto and Persephone, his backward glance.
</P>
<P>
   The story of ``The Mask of Orpheus'' is as deliberately
defective as that of ``Un Re in Ascolto,'' but the effect
Birtwistle creates is of a story being remembered with difficulty,
drawn out from chaos, not of one crumbling away. His theater is
more womb than hospital ward, and his music strongly suggests
pregnancy in its long stillnesses, or birth in its shattering
outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   It also strikes back to harsher times in its scoring for wind
and percussion, with no strings in the orchestra. Even the
marvelous electronic music, prepared in collaboration with Barry
Anderson, sounds ancient: much of it seems to be coming from an
enormous plucked or struck string instrument (Orpheus's lyre),
which embraces the whole aural perspective; other sequences provide
the great echoing voice of a god.
</P>
<P>
   The new recordings of both works come, inevitably, from public
performances. ``Un Re in Ascolto'' (Col Legno WWE 20005/6; two CDs)
is heard in its premiere production, at the 1984 Salzburg Festival,
which does not appear to have been too wonderful. Lorin Maazel and
the Vienna Philharmonic are not at home in Berio's music, nor are
some of the singers, with the notable exception of Sylvia
Greenberg, who is thrilling in the third auditionee's virtuoso
aria.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is also a fair amount of stage noise and
prompting, which makes the whole thing sound like a rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   It is disappointing, too, that the package includes no libretto.
Given only a poorly translated synopsis, which is not cued to the
musical numbers, a newcomer to the work will be lucky to know what
is happening when.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the recording of ``The Mask of Orpheus'' (NMC D050;
three CDs), made at a BBC performance in London in 1996, comes with
almost too much information. The entire libretto, by Peter
Zinovieff, is supplied, and it includes abundant stage directions
and design motifs as well as dialogue that seems to have been cut
from the finished work.
</P>
<P>
   This may give the impression of extreme complexity, whereas for
the ear the piece unfolds naturally and homogeneously. There are,
to be sure, longueurs. But there are also extraordinary passages,
including nearly all the electronic music, Orpheus's aria with
fierce, congealed piccolos in the first act, the serene flow of
wind chords at the first mention of the arches of the underworld,
and the new vivacity when the orchestra starts to play in the third
act, which was written several years after the other two.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Davis leads the BBC Symphony in a superb orchestral
performance, and the cast includes two important survivors from the
premiere, given 10 years before: Jean Rigby, dark and strong as one
of the Eurydices (the main roles are each sung at different times
or simultaneously by two singers), and Marie Angel, suitably
disturbing in the shrieks of the Oracle of the Dead.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Garrison is a bit talky as the principal Orpheus, but it is
perhaps a fault of the work that it does not sufficiently use
opera's chief resource: song.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, neither work quite measures up to its composer's
other achievements: Berio's ``Formazioni'' or Birtwistle's ``Earth
Dances,'' just to choose from orchestral works of the same period.
(``Earth Dances'' is available on Argo in a tremendous performance
by the Cleveland Orchestra, conducted by Christoph von Dohnanyi,
along with an equally tremendous account of the later ``Panic,''
featuring Ms. Davis and the BBC Symphony again.)
</P>
<P>
   Or it may be that both ``Un Re in Ascolto'' and ``The Mask of
Orpheus'' are real theater music, demanding to be seen as well as
heard. Birtwistle's opera won the most prestigious composition
prize in the United States, the Grawemeyer Award, more than a
decade ago. When will we see it staged?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4593 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-X-FILES-FILM-$ADV28-N     06-24 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-X-FILES-FILM-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUT IN THE SUNLIGHT, THE PARANOIA PALES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are two things the ``X-Files'' film has brought us that the
television show had not: the Barbie-as-Scully and Ken-as-Mulder
collectible dolls, each with its own little FBI badge.
</P>
<P>
   Merchandising has nothing to do with the film's many convoluted
plots, but money has everything to do with what happened to ``The
X-Files'' in its leap from television to the movies. One of
television's most inventive and creatively successful shows has
become just another enjoyable summer action movie.
</P>
<P>
   A victim of its inflated Hollywood budget and the big-bang
theory of filmmaking, the ``X-Files'' movie goes to the heart of
how television and film try to set themselves apart from each other
today.
</P>
<P>
   During its five seasons on television, ``The X-Files'' has
become a pop-cultural touchstone because it instills a vague,
insidious paranoia into every bit of daily life. At 40, the series'
creator, Chris Carter, is part of a generation that came of age
with Watergate and Vietnam, a generation that takes as a tenet that
anyone can be lying at any minute, especially the government.
Intentionally or not, that sense pervades ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Dana Scully (Gillian Anderson) is the rational scientist,
skeptical of the paranormal, and Fox Mulder (David Duchovny) the
intuitive believer in all things weird and wondrous, the viewers'
essential connection to them lies elswhere: in the heroes'
positions as FBI agents trying to get the goods on government
deception from the inside. Working for the government, they are at
the epicenter of cover-ups. This season Mulder even thought that
his evidence of alien life was itself a wily government conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, the show's tight focus, shadowy look and small scale
perfectly convey the insinuating tone and paranoia of the subject.
Creeping directly into our homes via television, ``The X-Files''
has found its ideal genre.
</P>
<P>
   On the big screen, that symmetry between subject and form is
exploded to bits with the first noisy blast, a terrorist bomb that
goes off in Dallas. Scully and Mulder have been temporarily
reassigned to the FBI's anti-terrorist squad, but they might as
well have been sent into a ``Die Hard'' sequel. When the film loses
its invasive tone and intimacy, it loses what makes ``The X-Files''
work.
</P>
<P>
   The film's extravagant landscapes, aerial shots and special
effects are definitely big-screen big (though in a summer when a
tidal wave has already wiped out New York City in ``Deep Impact,''
these effects are not exceptional).
</P>
<P>
   After a prelude set in 35,000 B.C., which establishes that a
sinister alien virus lived among us even then, the film moves on to
the Dallas bombing, meant to cover up the virus' existence. As the
heroes search for the truth, there is a large-scale homage to
``North by Northwest,'' in which helicopters chase Scully and
Mulder across a cornfield.
</P>
<P>
   There is the vast empty snowscape of Antarctica, where Mulder
goes to rescue a kidnapped Scully. There are stops at an English
country estate and eventually a sweeping Tunisian desert, where
evil humans are in cahoots with the aliens.
</P>
<P>
   The diffusion that destroys the creepy ``X-Files'' feeling
didn't have to happen. Film can obviously be as intimate as any
genre in the world. (Think of Bergman's ``Persona'' or classic
moments of Hollywood romance, like Sam singing ``As Time Goes By''
in ``Casablanca.'')
</P>
<P>
   But in the era of video and of actors crossing over more freely
from television to movies, a big-budget Hollywood film is intimate
at its peril. Explosive special effects offer audiences one of the
few things television cannot, and commercial filmmakers rarely
overlook that advantage.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a matter of whether television is better than film
or vice versa, a question that leads nowhere. Rather, the blithe
assumption that ``The X-Files'' needed to turn itself into a
high-action film reveals the rigidity and wrongheadedness of so
much Hollywood movie making.
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly possible for a television series to leap to the
movie screen successfully. From the start of its television days,
``Star Trek'' was broadly conceived, almost begging for a bigger,
more colorful cartoon canvas. ``The X-Files'' wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Though film viewers who haven't watched the television show may
wonder what the fuss is about, the movie is stocked with glimpses
of the creativity that makes the series work. When Mulder finds
Scully in Antarctica, she is in a state of suspended animation
inside a glass case, bringing to mind Snow White in her glass
coffin. It is an eerily effective image.
</P>
<P>
   So is the sight of the deadly black ooze (familiar to television
fans) that invades the body, crawling under the skin and into the
eyeballs like a horde of oily black worms. As for the
much-publicized question of whether Scully and Mulder kiss, the
film sets up a frisson that can run through the next television
season: are these two repressed enough to ignore a near-kiss
interrupted by a killer bee?
</P>
<P>
   And there is a priceless episode in which Mulder walks into a
bar, has too much to drink and spills his secrets to the bartender
(Glenne Headly). ``I'm the key figure in an ongoing government
charade, a plot to conceal the truth about the existence of
extraterrestrials. It's a global conspiracy, actually. ... So of
course no one believes me. I'm an annoyance to my superiors and a
joke to my peers; they call me Spooky, Spooky Mulder, whose sister
was abducted by aliens when he was just a kid and who now chases
after little green men with a badge and a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I would say that about does it, Spooky,'' the bartender
tells him as she takes away his glass. This small-scale early scene
deftly brings the audience up to speed. More important, it is a
witty piece of writing. It is a reminder that at its best, ``The
X-Files'' is a chamber piece, peering intimately into its heroes'
claustrophobic, misunderstood souls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1507EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
