<HEADER>
A4622 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV     06-24 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINA'S HISTORY DOWN THROUGH THE AGES
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON; CHINA-ODDITIES-$ADV25.
 &HT;    For Use Thursday, June 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China's history at a glance:
</P>
<P>
   400,000 B.C. _ Precursors. Present-day northern China is
inhabited by some of the world's earliest humans. Peking Man and
Peking woman are cave-dwelling hunters standing about half a head
shorter than today's Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   About 2200 B.C. _ Seeds. The first Chinese king _ Yu the Great,
tamer of floods _ founds China's first dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   221 B.C. _ Birth. The Qin Dynasty conquers warring neighbors to
unite the first single, centralized state that would become known
as China. Qin rulers built an early version of the Great Wall and a
multi-tentacled bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   960 AD-1278 A.D. _ Renaissance. Under China's ``golden age'' in
the Song Dynasty, China invents gunpowder, prints books with
movable type, introduces the magnetic compass and the civil service
examination.
</P>
<P>
   1278-1368 A.D. _ Occupation. Genghis Khan's grandson Kublai Khan
completes brutal Mongolian invasion of China, and Mongols choose
Beijing as Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
   1368-1911 A.D. _ Empire. The Chinese empire flourishes in
isolation from the rest of the world, but ultimately weakens and
collapses.
</P>
<P>
   1911-1949 _ Interregnum. The Qing Dynasty is succeeded by weak
parliamentary republic led by reformer Sun Yat-sen. Northern China
breaks off into warlord territories, which are finally conquered by
Sun's successor and brother-in-law Gen. Chiang Kai-shek. His
Nationalist Chinese regime proves too weak to deal with civil war,
endemic poverty and Japanese invasion.
</P>
<P>
   1934 - Communism. Communist guerrilla Mao Tse-tung leads a
5,500-mile ``Long March'' of 100,000 followers across 18 mountain
ranges to escape from Nationalist troops. The mythic retreat is the
prelude to Mao's takeover of China.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 13, 1937 - Massacre. Japanese troops storm into Nanjing and
begin a reign of terror in which at least 20,000 Chinese women are
raped and 30,000 fleeing Chinese soldiers are massacred.
</P>
<P>
   June 1949 - Redoubt. Chiang Kai-shek, having given up the
presidency of China, retreats to the island province of Taiwan.
Chiang asserts control over the island's population and digs in for
a communist cross-channel invasion that never comes.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 1, 1949 - Takeover. Communist leader Mao Tse-tung stands
atop the gate to the former Imperial City in Beijing and announces
the founding of the People's Republic of China. Mao promises
dictatorial treatment for ``running dogs of imperialism.''
</P>
<P>
   1950-53 - War. Americans and Chinese troops fight on opposite
sides in a bloody stalemate in Korea.
</P>
<P>
   May-July 1957 - Flowers. Mao Tse-tung tells communist
bureaucrats to ``let 100 flowers bloom,'' signaling a reform
period. Chinese intellectuals respond with a burst of grievances.
In July, Mao shifts direction. Tens of thousands are sent to labor
camps.
</P>
<P>
   1958 - Leap. Mao Tse-tung launches a ``Great Leap Forward''
scheme to multiply China's industrial and moral strength by
spreading small-scale mines, mills and factories throughout the
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   1959-60 - Famine. Peasants, caught up in ``Great Leap''
hysteria, fail to harvest crops. Food production falls
disastrously, leading to a famine in which 20 million Chinese die.
</P>
<P>
   1960 - Split. Soviet Premier Nikita Khrushchev orders thousands
of Soviet technicians out of China, as China and the U.S.S.R. break
apart over Khrushchev's criticisms of the ``Great Leap.''
</P>
<P>
   1966-1976 - Radicalism. Mao unleashes a more radical stage
called the ``Cultural Revolution,'' spearheaded by some 10 million
teenage ``Red Guards.'' Millions of intellectuals are ``sent down''
to the countryside for ``re-education.'' Mao's death in 1976 causes
a letup in repression.
</P>
<P>
   1978 - Modernization. New Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping launches
China's two-decade spurt of economic growth by loosening
communist-style controls and encouraging Western investment.
</P>
<P>
   1980 - Population. China adopts ``one-child policy,'' under
which women need permission from their work units to have children.
Some with unsanctioned pregnancies are pressured to abort, others
fined if they deliver an unapproved child.
</P>
<P>
   June 4, 1989 - Crackdown. About 500 to 1,000 pro-democracy
supporters are killed in Beijing when student protests in Tiananmen
Square are crushed by Chinese tanks.
</P>
<P>
   July 1, 1997 - Sovereignty. After a century and a half of
British colonial rule, China regains sovereignty of Hong Kong,
under assurances of semi-autonomous status for the port city.
</P>
<P>
   For clients of the New York Times News Service.(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
