<HEADER>
A4638 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERLINAIRLIFT-TEX     06-24 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERLINAIRLIFT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
50 YEARS AGO, OPERATION VITTLES SAVED A CITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS VAUGHN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before Operation Restore Hope or Operation Deny Flight, there
was Operation Vittles.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tongue-in-cheek name for a deadly serious mission that
came together 50 years ago this week: to supply 2.5 million
war-weary Berlin residents with enough food, supplies and heat to
outlast a Soviet blockade imposed June 24, 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-month Operation Vittles, better known as the Berlin
Airlift, also provided the infant Air Force with its first real
test. More significant, it helped establish the tradition of U.S.
involvement in humanitarian missions, a tradition that continues in
operations such as Restore Hope in Somalia and Deny Flight in
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who took part in the ]airlift, such as Fort Worth
residents Richard A. Campbell and John Kenderdine, it became a
defining moment in their lives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We were doing something for people that they couldn't do
themselves,'' said Campbell, who remembers being handed flowers by
Berlin schoolchildren after one mission. ``We were helping
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban Missile Crisis remains the most sobering example of
Cold War brinkmanship, and rightly so, given its nuclear threat,
said Air Force Col. John Brower, a professor at the Air War College
at Maxwell Air Force Base in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Soviets closed land access to West Berlin in a
dispute with their former allies over control of the city, the
risks for more bloodshed in Europe seemed very real as the
airlift's first planes took off June 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first skirmish of the Cold War,'' Brower said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenderdine is 85, a widower and retired brigadier general living
in a condominium in southwest Fort Worth. But he remembers the
tension of those days well, including seeing his wife qualify with
a rifle in preparation for war.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1948, Kenderdine was a lieutenant colonel in the Army
and the director of supply at a depot in Giessen, Germany, just
north of Frankfurt. He remembers a phone call summoning him to
Rhein Main Air Base for a meeting with Air Force brass.
</P>
<P>
   It was there that legendary Gen. Curtis LeMay asked Kenderdine
to come up with 500 tons of supplies for the first shipments into
Berlin in only a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   Kenderdine chose the ingredients to make bread. Neither coal nor
gasoline nor ammunition, but flour, milk and raisins were the first
cargoes delivered in an operation that would eventually fly about
2.3 million tons of supplies into Berlin on about 278,000 flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think anybody would criticize that,'' he said. ``It
was also the easiest thing to pull out of stock and load on short
notice, so that's what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first pilots was Campbell, a young lieutenant who
piloted a C-54 cargo plane. He was yanked from his assignment in
Japan and sent to Germany, where he was briefed on the still-new
radar approaches and told, ``Good luck.'' He flew five missions
into Berlin's Tempelhof airfield his first day there and hundreds
more during his six months of duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tempelhof was the hairiest of them all,'' recalled Campbell,
75, who retired as an Air Force colonel. ``The final approach
called for a letdown between the rubble of these huge apartment
houses, and it always looked like you were going to hit them with a
wing tip.''
</P>
<P>
   The airlift soon became an impressively fine-tuned operation,
given Germany's rain and fog and the complexities of air traffic
control. The planes followed concise schedules and flight paths,
touching down every three minutes during the height of the airlift.
</P>
<P>
   On average, about 5,000 tons a day were delivered to Berlin on
American and British aircraft. Unlike today's Air Force, however,
which can deliver as much as 100 tons at a time on cargo planes,
the Air Force of that time had planes that mostly could only carry
10 tons or less.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, about 180,000 tons of humanitarian supplies were
flown into war-ravaged Sarajevo from July 1992 to January 1996,
less than the Berlin Airlift transported in March 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Losing an engine on takeoff or landing was not uncommon, nor was
getting buzzed by Soviet fighters, who usually declined more
confrontational approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I once had three MiGs fly right across my nose as I made one
approach,'' Campbell said. ``They were close enough for me to
clearly see the pilots' heads.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year after it began, on May 12, 1949, the Soviets
lifted their land blockade around Berlin, though the airlift
continued until Sept. 30 to create a stockpile in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Five decades later, the Berlin Airlift is still studied by
officers and enlisted personnel as one of the Air Force's finest
hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``To keep a city alive for that period of time purely by air was
really a Herculean effort,'' Brower said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenderdine's involvement with the airlift ended after only a few
days, though he has never forgotten how Germans would pull over and
watch the endless convoys of supplies or how grateful they seemed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the proudest moments of my Army career,'' he
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
