<SLUG> BC-NAACP-CONGRESS-COX </SLUG>
     NAACP GIVE CONGRESS FAILING GRADE ON
CIVIL RIGHTS LEGISLATION
 &HT;     By KIMBERLY MARSELAS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Members of Congress have voted against civil rights
legislation 49 percent of the time during the 1997-98 session,
NAACP President Kweisi Mfume said Wednesday as he released the
group's 1998 legislative report card.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have followed the voting records of members of this
Congress and find that both the House and Senate have failed the
American people as it relates to civil rights issues,'' Mfume said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
plans to distribute the report card to all its 1,700 local
branches, hoping to increase voter awareness and turnout in
November and to defeat members who didn't vote for civil rights
legislation often enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to use this information as a sword to defeat
delinquent legislators of both parties and to bolster those of both
parties who care about and vote for equal protection under the law
for Americans,'' Mfume said.
</P>
<P>
   The group listed 50 ``zeros,'' or senators and representatives
who voted against the NAACP's stance on every key vote. This list
includes Sens. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, Lauch Faircloth, R-N.C. and
Jesse Helms, R-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP gave ``hero'' status to 137 legislators, meaning they
voted with the NAACP at least 90 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings were based on 10 key votes in the Senate and 12 key
votes in the House. Issues included affirmative action, juvenile
justice, voter empowerment, the budget, the census and the Senate
confirmations of Surgeon General David Satcher and Labor Secretary
Alexis Herman.
</P>
<P>
   The report card found that Republicans were far less likely to
support civil rights legislation. Eighty-seven percent of all
Democrats had a passing grade on the 1998 report card, while only
18 percent of Republicans passed. But Mfume insisted that the NAACP
would target members of both parties for defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that Southern delegations were the worst when
it came to supporting NAACP stances this year. Every Southern
delegation received an F for their lack of pro-civil rights votes.
</P>
<P>
   Only three states _ Massachusetts, North Dakota and West
Virginia _ received an A for their delegations' voting records this
session.
</P>
<P>
   In order to elect legislators who better represent the ideas of
the NAACP and its 1 million members, the group will spend ``every
dime that we can afford'' on grassroots activities and media
campaigns, Mfume said.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume said many of the low grades could be attributed to the
lawmakers' unwillingness to work together on effective legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The members ``would prefer not to compromise,'' he said. ``But
that does not help our government or our people. ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
