<HEADLINE>
CHINESE AMERICANS TAKE PRIDE IN PRESIDENT'S TRIP TO BEIJING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While politicians and pundits debate President
Clinton's historic trip to China, some Chinese Americans view the
visit as a matter of pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're proud because China is growing stronger and stronger,
so the United States has to pay attention to China,'' said Joseph
Leung, host of a daily Cantonese-language radio talk show that has
received numerous calls about Clinton's trip.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activists and Tibetans, however, hope Clinton can
make progress on a variety of substantive issues. But for Chinese
immigrants interviewed for this story, the president has achieved
something just by going.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco's Chinatown, many of the Chinese residents left
their homeland decades ago. They've married, worked, retired and
had children and grandchildren in the United States, but the
emotional bonds to the country of their birth are still strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the bottom of their hearts, anything that's good for
China, they agree with,'' said Frank Lee, a World War II veteran
who has lived in San Francisco for more than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Chang-Lin Tien, the former chancellor of the University of
California at Berkeley, saw the trip as an opportunity to boost the
image of Chinese Americans, tarnished by reports of Chinese
contributions to U.S. political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more the American public understands China, the more it
will help to defuse some of the negative publicity generated on
Asian Americans,'' Tien said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Chinese President Jiang Zemin have a full plate of
topics to discuss in their summit meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Tsai, a senior partner with Oakland, Calif.-based Wang &AMP;
Li Asia Resources, said the trip was getting lost in the media
chatter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's not very significant because it's being
detracted from by all the other garbage going on, from Donorgate to
Lewinsky,'' she said. ``I find that tragic because we really need a
really good and solid China policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsai was born and raised in the San Francisco area but recently
lived in Taiwan for six years. While there, she said, she was able
to observe U.S. foreign policy as a foreigner might view it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching from an outsider's perspective, you realize American
policy is not really coherent,'' she said. ``It seems to be very
reactive; it's not very proactive.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese journalist Zhang Weiguo said Clinton should take
advantage of Jiang's low domestic popularity to push for democratic
reforms. He said a popular saying in China goes, ``Mao Zedong was
like a tiger, Deng Xiaoping like a cat, and Jiang like a mouse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jiang Zemin may be willing to listen a little more,'' said
Zhang, who was imprisoned for 20 months after the 1989 student
movement in China. ``For Clinton, this is an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   One sensitive area for some Chinese Americans is the official
welcoming ceremony adjacent to Tiananmen Square, site of the bloody
crackdown on student protesters in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``If President Clinton joins with communist leaders at Tiananmen
Square, he will go into the wrong side of history,'' said human
rights activist Harry Wu, echoing the phrase used recently by
Clinton to chide China on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to participate in the formal welcoming
ceremony Friday at a building overlooking Beijing's central square.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wu acknowledges the need for dialogue with China, he
has long been critical of Clinton's policy of engaging China, which
he sees as appeasing China for mutually beneficial financial
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to sacrifice some short-term interests for our
long-term future,'' he said. ``Otherwise, the economic development
and prosperity we have today can be lost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
