<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4738 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-24 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY MAY BE MORE CALCULATING THAN WE THINK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look at Monica. See Monica smile. See Monica pose for the
camera.
</P>
<P>
   See Monica mock the independent counsel and the horse he rode in
on.
</P>
<P>
   Just perusing the pictures of Monica Lewinsky in the July issue
of Vanity Fair magazine, you might never guess that she's in a
truckload of trouble. You might never guess that she could end up
going to jail for her role in a White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky looks happy and carefree as she poses in the grass,
wearing a red-and-white checked blouse and blue jeans. She looks
happy and carefree on the beach, wearing a black dress and using a
mock flag as a backdrop. She even looks happy and carefree wearing
a cloak of pink feathers.
</P>
<P>
   Notice that Monica is wearing something in every photograph,
which sets her apart from alleged Bill Clinton paramours Elizabeth
Gracen and Gennifer Flowers, who posed nude in men's magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Vanity Fair is no Playboy or Penthouse, although the same issue
that features Lewinsky with clothing features a rear view of a
model without clothing in an ad for ``firm lift'' body lotion.
</P>
<P>
   Monica and the folks who helped her dress up for the photo shoot
did their best to make her look glamorous, but she hardly looks
like the sort of femme fatale whose charms could wreck a White
House. She definitely doesn't look like a criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's crime? The former White House intern stands suspected
of perjury, suborning perjury and conspiring to destroy America's
trust in its president.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that last one isn't a violation of the law, but it is
clearly the transgression that has placed Lewinsky in the path of
the legal bulldozer known as independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky told a friend that she had an affair with President
Clinton, and the friend told Starr. If sex was perpetrated in the
White House, Starr knew, those involved would eventually lie about
it. He also knew that a prosecutor who could document a sworn lie
about White House sex would be well on his way toward turning a
moral deficiency into a federal crime.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's photo shoot, needless to say, was analyzed, dissected
and second-guessed even before the pictures hit the newsstands. The
consensus criticism: She should have amused herself by reading a
magazine rather than posing for one.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking seems to be that the photographs damaged Lewinsky's
credibility, that they made her seem frivolous, impulsive and
perhaps overly enthralled with the notoriety she has achieved in
recent months. The problem with this criticism is that the critics
are presuming that Lewinksy wants to be credible, that she wants to
be a star witness in the Starr investigation of the president.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lewinsky might be on a carefully contrived mission to
damage her credibility. She might be deliberately going about the
business of making herself absolutely irrelevant in Starr's pursuit
of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   There have been reports that Lewinsky continues to be madly in
love with Clinton and that she wants no part of implicating him in
a crime. If it is well-established that nobody can believe a word
she says, Monica might figure, perhaps Starr won't be able to use
her testimony against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   If Lewinsky is useless as a witness, of course, Starr might
decide to turn her into a defendant. Starr is apparently convinced
that Lewinsky lied under oath about her relationship with Clinton;
the independent counsel might be inclined to prosecute her on
grounds of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   But would the public tolerate the prosecution of a youthful
ex-intern who was supposedly seduced by her boss, the president of
the United States? Starr might be seen as prosecuting a victim
while failing to hold the perpetrator accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's former lawyer, William Ginsburg, has always seemed to
believe that Starr would never do such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ginsburg, by the way, who encouraged Monica to pose for
Vanity Fair. If the pictures destroyed Lewinsky's credibility, they
may have accomplished exactly what she and Ginsburg hoped they
would.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
