<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA (Xian, China) _ Beginning the longest visit to
China by an American president, Bill Clinton will visit ancient
terra cotta warriors buried to protect a Chinese emperor who
unified the nation in 221 B.C. Clinton's itinerary underscores his
desire to avoid making politically charged negotiations the focus
of his summit with Chinese President Jiang Zemin. By STEWART M.
POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TIANANMEN (Beijing) _ Detachments of the People's
Liberation Army _ whose troops fired on pro-democracy demonstrators
in and around Tiananmen Square nine years ago _ will be part of the
official greeting for President Clinton. By almost any reckoning,
it will be one of the most controversial moments of Clinton's
presidency. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-MANAGED-CARE (Washington) _ A House Republican task force
appointed by Speaker Newt Gingrich unveils its plan to rein in the
managed care industry ``without big government.'' The plan is the
GOP's response to escalating popular discontent with managed care
and to the Democrats' attempt portray Republicans as beholden to
health care and insurance industry interests. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-ATTACKS (Washington) _ CIA Director George Tenet says
the United States is vulnerable to computer attacks that have the
potential to cripple national security. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-PILL (Washington) _ The House votes to bar the Food and
Drug Administration from spending money to test, develop or approve
any drug _ such as the French abortion pill RU486 _ that would
chemically induce abortion. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-EDUCATION (Washington) _ The Senate gives final approval
to a spending bill that includes the creation of education savings
accounts to help pay for tuition at private schools. The White
House says the bill amounts to an abandonment of public schools. By
GREG MCDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-STARTING-TIME (Washington) _ Sleep-deprived teen-agers
are the focus of a new bill introduced by Rep. Zoe Lofgren,
D-Calif. The measure would provide federal funds to school
districts that move their class starting times to at least 9 a.m.
Sleep experts say a later starting time would promote teen health,
academic achievement and safety. By NICOLE TSONG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RACIAL-ATTACK (Jasper, Texas) _ Ku Klux Klan leaders say they
will not cancel a weekend march in the Texas town where a black man
was recently beaten and dragged to his death. City leaders appealed
to the Klan to stay away. By RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-COSTS (Houston) _ NASA administrator Daniel Goldin
acknowledges that the international space station faces cost
overruns and delays, but he declines to say how much or how long.
While embracing an independent auditor's report about the station's
problems, Goldin says it is too early to ask Congress for more
money. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
