<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4747 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOGS-AND-PEOPLE-ART-8     06-24 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOGS-AND-PEOPLE-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LUCILLE, HONEY, IS THAT YOU?' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Don't eat the eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a sentence to consider. You could either be having
dinner in Chinatown _ or talking to a dog.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Caroline Knapp, the author of the best-selling
memoir, ``Drinking: A Love Story'' (Dial Press, 1996), is
addressing Lucille, her 3-year-old German shepherd mix, who has
been systematically gutting a stuffed animal _ a lemming, to be
exact. Surrounded by piles of white fluff from its insides, she has
started on the outside, and the eyes are the first to go, followed
quickly by the tail.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Knapp remains calm in the face of annihilation. She has
written a new book, ``Pack of Two: The Intricate Bond Between
People and Dogs'' (Dial Press), a thoughtful, sensitive analysis of
the all-out love affair she unexpectedly found in her relationship
with Lucille and that other people, especially women, find with
their own dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Knapp is certainly not unique. In ``Pack of Two,'' she cites
various studies on the subject, including one from the American
Animal Hospital Association in which 48 percent of female
respondents reported they relied more heavily on their pets than on
their partners or family members for affection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kinds of roles dogs fill can be hard to come by in human
relationships,'' Ms. Knapp said. ``We touch the dog or the pet at
whim. There is a lack of self-consciousness and a fluidity to it
that is absent from most human relationships. If someone acted that
way to you, you'd feel claustrophobic pretty quickly. It's a
boundary violation.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for ``Pack of Two'' came to Ms. Knapp, 38, shortly
after she found Lucille at a shelter, during a period she calls
``the aftermath of enormous upheaval.'' After 20 years of drinking,
during which time she graduated from Brown University and worked as
the life-style editor for The Boston Phoenix (where she still
writes a column) she entered a rehabilitation program and
celebrated 18 months of sobriety on the day she brought the dog
home. Toward the end of her drinking, both her parents died; her
father of a brain tumor in 1992, her mother, one year and 11 days
later, of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Ms. Knapp was also ending a long-term relationship
with her boyfriend, and left her editing job at The Phoenix to
write her first book. ``I was really adrift, and on top of that I
had a sense of decimated family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Which meant she was ripe for the unwavering loyalty and
affection of a dog. Though her family had dogs while she was
growing up, she had never had one of her own. She began pondering
life with man's best friend, but what she quickly discovered after
Lucille joined her was that the rest of the world perceived her
best friend to be a substitute for either a baby or a husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see a guy with his German shepherd and say he really
wants a baby,'' Ms. Knapp said, sipping her coffee and smoking one
of many cigarettes. ``People suspect there's some sort of twisted
sublimation going on. You somehow just don't measure up if you are
deeply attached to an animal instead of a husband or child. I think
there must be some sense of an animal as just a lesser being and
therefore the feelings should be less. `It's  &UR; just &LR;  a dog,' people
say.''
</P>
<P>
   She looked down at Lucille, who returned her gaze adoringly.
Lucille is a sweet dog, good natured and obedient, who has been
trained to stay in the living room of Ms. Knapp's half of a
two-family house whenever her owner goes into the kitchen. No
matter what the dog is doing _ ripping apart the lemming,
stretching or sighing _ the minute Ms. Knapp disappears from view,
Lucille stops, her ears go up, she looks toward the kitchen and
waits, vigilant, to find out what happens next. Only when Ms. Knapp
returns does she pick up where she left off.
</P>
<P>
   Once the decimated lemming was removed, Lucille heaved a sigh
and lay down on her L.L. Bean bed. All she had left was a chew toy
that was not nearly as exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a big sigh,'' Ms. Knapp said fondly, leaning over to
stroke Lucille's head as she fell asleep. ``She has to be the
center of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Once Lucille was out of the conversational loop, Ms. Knapp no
longer seemed as sure of what to say. She is a soft-spoken woman
with a pronounced sense of stillness about her. Her home is
comfortable yet spare, with its bare pine floors, big chairs and
exposed brick columns. The only dashes of humor come from dogs: a
Buddha dog sculpture and German shepherd angel Christmas ornaments
on the kitchen table, a towel that says ``Lucille,'' decorated with
paw prints.
</P>
<P>
   When she does speak, Ms. Knapp chooses her words deliberately
and tends to ask ``Does that make sense?'' at the end of her
sentences. That unnecessary question seems to underscore the
tentativeness she feels about the world around her.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like her owner, Lucille is rather reserved. She echoes Ms.
Knapp's stillness almost eerily, holding back her more doglike
moments for the three walks the duo take each day. Yes, three.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a lucky girl, she has a compulsive owner,'' Ms. Knapp
said, smiling. ``But we have a nice working routine. It provides
the structured breaks for me in my work. Without her, the only
thing I might ever say is `Large coffee with milk, please,' and
that might be it for the day.''
</P>
<P>
   In her relationship with Lucille, Ms. Knapp says, she has
discovered that two unexpected needs of her own have been filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, I gave her the childhood I never got, the
attention,'' she said. ``I came from an undemonstrative family. We
were loving in our ways, but we were not a very tactile group and I
find it deeply satisfying to be so. Dogs have such short life
spans, it's like a concentrated version of a human life. When they
get older they become much more like our mothers. They wait for us,
watch out for us, are completely fascinated by everything we do.
So, with her, she's the kid I never got to be and the mother I
never quite had. It's really quite remarkable how much they can
provide without any prompting. It's just built into the species.''
</P>
<P>
   Emily Dickinson, Ms. Knapp notes in ``Pack of Two,'' wrote a
letter to a friend in 1862 in which she said of dogs, hers in
particular, ``They are better than human beings because they know
but do not tell.''
</P>
<P>
   What does Ms. Knapp think Lucille knows about her?
</P>
<P>
   ``That she's the one with the biscuits,'' she said without
hesitation. ``Dogs are so immediate. I think she has a good grasp
of my moods, moment to moment. She's good at reading anger,
happiness, sadness and anxiety. I don't know how much further than
that it goes. It's the immediacy of the connection that's paramount
for her.''
</P>
<P>
   And what is paramount for Ms. Knapp? She lit another cigarette.
``I would like a degree of serenity and emotional freedom that
still eludes me somewhat. I am a fairly intense, which is a
euphemism for compulsive and rigid, person. It would be nice to
feel a little easier in the world. It's been six years since my
father died, five since my mother died, and there's a way in which
I'm still sort of reeling from it. I have been sober for almost
four and a half years, and it still feels like I'm reinventing my
life. Living alone, you're the architect of your life in a solitary
way.''
</P>
<P>
   And staying solitary remains her choice. Since ending her
relationship with her boyfriend, she has not started another. She
writes and lives here in this small house on a narrow road. Besides
walking Lucille, she sculls on the Charles River and attends
Alcoholics Anonymous meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up assuming I would get married and have children,''
she said. ``But years pass and you find yourself not doing it and
not doing it, and sometimes you begin to think you may be not doing
it for a reason. I have never felt that deep longing to be pregnant
that I hear other women describe. I melt at puppies, never at
babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucille started to wake from her nap. Ms. Knapp leaned over to
touch her. ``I guess I resent the idea that nurturing and loving
has to be in human form or childlike form,'' she said. ``It's just
dismissive to suggest it is an inferior set of feelings because
it's directed toward the dog.''
</P>
<P>
   She smiled. ``I feel the defensiveness in my voice that this is
`okay' because the `not okay' message is so strong. We live in a
culture that doesn't deal with difficult feelings very well. And
when you're talking about what a solace the dog is in the midst of
painful feelings, people get uneasy. Does that make sense?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course. Once Lucille stretched, she joined Ms. Knapp in
giving her high-10s, touching her paws to Ms. Knapp's palms.
``Excellent,'' Ms. Knapp crooned. ``You're a good girl.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident called to mind something Ms. Knapp writes about in
her book: the moment at the end of the day when she and Lucille
come home and shut the door behind them. ``It's solitude without
the loneliness,'' Ms. Knapp said. ``I'm shy. I'm still a fearful
person. I've always walked around with the sense that the world is
not a safe place. I didn't get the spontaneous gene or the
adventure one, really. After going through the day with its
stresses, when I shut that door at night, I don't have to deal with
anything but dinner, `E.R.' and my bathrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   She looked lovingly at Lucille, who presented herself to be
petted. ``I get the biggest charge out of ending the day with our
ritual of going up the stairs, and getting into bed,'' Ms. Knapp
said. ``I read, she has her head on my leg or my lap. And I'm in
dog heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Her smile was blissful. Lucille returned her gaze, panting
happily. She seemed to smile, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
