<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILLING-COOKBOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THERE'S SMOKE, THERE ARE FIREFIGHTERS GRILLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ya gotta love a cookbook that has a big beefy firefighter on the
cover.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph T. Bonanno Jr.'s first recipe fest, ``The Healthy
Firehouse Cookbook,'' is a collection of low-fat recipes from
firehouses around the country. His new effort, ``The Firehouse
Grilling Cookbook'' (Broadway, $23), takes the cooking outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   A nice touch in this no-nonsense book is the safety chapter,
something too rarely seen in barbecue books. But Bonanno is not a
preacher, either with the safety business, or with his other
sideline, fitness. (Check out the biceps on the guy.)
</P>
<P>
   RED DEVIL CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   4-pound chicken, rinsed and patted dry
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, crushed through a press
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Using a cleaver or heavy knife, cut down one side of the
backbone to cut the chicken in half. Cut down the other side and
discard the backbone. Place chicken on a work surface, skin side
up. Press hard on breastbone with the heel of your hand to flatten
the chicken.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, whisk together the wine, oil, lemon juice,
garlic, oregano, red pepper flakes and salt. Place chicken and
marinade in a zippered plastic bag. Close bag and refrigerate for
at least 1 hour and up to 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Build a charcoal fire in one side of an outdoor grill and let
burn until covered with white ash. Place a large disposable
aluminum foil pan on the empty side of the grill and fill halfway
with water. In a gas grill: Preheat on high. Turn one burner off,
and keep the other burner(s) on high. Place the foil pan on the off
burner and fill halfway with water.
</P>
<P>
   Remove chicken from marinade. Lightly oil cooking grate. Place,
skin side down, over the pan. Weight the chicken with an aluminum
foil-wrapped brick. Cover and cook for 25 minutes. Remove brick and
turn chicken. Cover and continue cooking (without the brick) until
chicken shows no sign of pink when pierced at the thigh bone, about
25 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   Using a cleaver or heavy knife, chop chicken into quarters and
serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 500 calories, 31 grams fat, 1
gram carbohydrates, 51 grams protein, 164 milligrams cholesterol,
449 milligrams sodium, 56 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-SMOKED SALMON FILLETS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   2 cups oak, alder or hickory wood chips
</P>
<P>
   3 cups inexpensive, but tasty, dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup grainy ``country-style'' French mustard
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh dill
</P>
<P>
   Four 7-ounce salmon fillets, with skin
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   In medium bowl, soak hickory chips in the wine for at least 30
minutes. Drain chips, reserving wine. Set chips and wine aside.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, using 2 1/2 pounds of briquettes, build a charcoal
fire on one side of an outdoor grill. Let the fire burn until
medium-hot _ you should be able to hold your hand at grate level to
a count of three _ and the coals are covered with white ash. Place
an empty aluminum foil pan on the empty side of the grill. Pour
wine into the pan. Sprinkle a handful of chips over the coals and
cover.
</P>
<P>
   In a gas grill: Preheat on high. Turn one burner off and the
other burners to medium. Place an empty aluminum foil pan over the
off burner. Pour wine into the pan. Place drained chips in a metal
chip box. Or, wrap the drained chips in aluminum foil, pierce a few
holes in foil and place foil packet on the heat source. Cover and
allow a few minutes for the chips to build up a head of smoke.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, mix the mustard, brown sugar and dill,
dissolving the sugar. Brush the salmon skin with the oil. Spread
mustard mixture on the flesh side of the salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly oil the cooking grate. Place the fish fillets, skin side
down, over the pan. Cover and smoke until salmon looks opaque when
prodded in the center with the tip of a knife, 20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Using a wide spatula, transfer the fillets to dinner plates. If
the salmon skin sticks to the grate, slide the spatula between the
skin and flesh and lift off the salmon, leaving the skin on the
grill. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 337 calories, 16 grams fat, 4
grams carbohydrates, 40 grams protein, 109 milligrams cholesterol,
255 milligrams sodium, 42 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
