<HEADER>
A4757 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-BIRD-WATCHING-ART     06-24 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BIRD-WATCHING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRDS IN THE BUSH AND THE DATABASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Utah, Conn., Iowa, N.Y., Wash.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By LES LINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hey, I just entered my sightings from my last trip, and Avisys
says I hit 100 birds for the year from the train,'' Mike Savage
recently announced to members of his online bird-watching
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were stopped at a red signal along the Great Salt Lake,''
continued Savage, a train engineer in the West for Union Pacific
who spots birds from the cabs of the 400,000-pound, yellow-and-gray
locomotives he drives. ``I raised my binos to scan the shore, where
I had willet, lesser yellowlegs and greater yellowlegs (No. 99)
together in one view. The greater was a new train bird for me and
was quickly followed by No. 100, a black-bellied plover, also a new
train bird.''
</P>
<P>
   Train birds? For the uninitiated, bird-watchers (or ``birders''
as the serious ones call themselves) tend to be compulsive
list-keepers. They keep lists of bird species seen in places like
their yards, counties, states. They keep trip lists, seasonal
lists, annual lists and life lists, which are all the birds seen in
one's lifetime. And Savage keeps what has to be the most unusual
list of all.
</P>
<P>
   As a bird-watcher in the 1990s, he also keeps his birding lists
on a Hewlett-Packard palmtop computer loaded with Avisys software,
which was written for birders by a birder. Other bird-watchers
frequently use other aids, like a global positioning system device
to help them know where they are _ not to mention such
sophisticated devices as a high-end Sony cassette tape deck with a
parabolic microphone for recording and playing back songs to lure
recalcitrant birds out of vegetation and into the open.
</P>
<P>
   Time was when a life list was kept with penciled check marks
next to columns of bird names arranged in taxonomic order _ loons
first, sparrows last _ in the front of a field guide by Roger Tory
Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   There were pocket checklists on folded cardboard, not pocket
computers, for recording the species seen on special trips to
national parks or wildlife refuges. And notes about observations in
the field were kept in a notebook of the paper-carrying variety,
not one with an Intel chip aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Time was when binoculars were the only hardware a birder
carried. They were bulky, heavy and costly field glasses, often
military surplus. If you were in a group birding from the edge of a
marsh, someone probably had a spotting scope that provided a fuzzy
view of ducks in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Times certainly have changed in the world of bird-watching, a
pursuit that red-blooded outdoorsmen once derided as a hobby for
little old ladies in tennis shoes. One company alone, Bushnell,
markets more than 80 models of binoculars in a wide price range,
while Carl Zeiss offers a technological breakthrough: a 20-power
spotting scope that weighs only 42 ounces and can be held and
focused with one hand.
</P>
<P>
   The scope's optical components are mounted on a mechanical
suspension system that eliminates a shaky image from hand movement
(although the suggested price tag, $2,995, might cause a quiver or
two). There is also a large choice of night vision binoculars and
scopes for watching the nocturnal activities of whippoorwills and
owls.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just a start. ``There's a real need for birding
Sherpas,'' Dr. Arie Gilbert said as he hefted an enormous duffle
bag into the back of a friend's mini-van one day not long ago for a
morning of birding along the Housatonic River near Kent, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert, a New York chiropractor and hard-core birder since his
high school days, totes a load of equipment: Leica 10x42
rubber-armored binoculars, among the ne plus ultra of birding
optics; a Minolta 35-millimeter autofocus camera with a 500-mm
telephoto lens for documenting unusual sightings; a Kowa zoom
spotting scope and a heavy Bogen tripod to support it; a Sony tape
deck with parabolic microphone, and often a laptop computer with a
Global Positioning System receiver and DeLorme's Street Atlas
program for navigating to and around unfamiliar areas. Oh, and yes,
somewhere in the bag there's a Peterson field guide.
</P>
<P>
   Another high-tech birder is Savage, 42, a Union Pacific engineer
from West Jordan, Utah, who hauls a hundred or more freight cars on
a 264-mile run between Salt Lake City and Elko, Nev. The tracks
cross the Great Salt Lake Desert, climb the Pequop Mountains and
descend into the Humboldt River Valley _ a spectacular range of
wildlife habitats where the train passes through just two towns and
there are very few cars for the driver to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   So Savage never leaves for work without binoculars and his
computer. ``It's a good thing I don't have to steer,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Other birders carry handheld GPS receivers like Garmin's GPS
III, which is marketed for hikers. They track unmarked trails and
update printouts from Toposcout CD-ROMs that contain all of the
United States Geological Survey topographic maps for their
particular state.
</P>
<P>
   The laptop computers plugged into their car-lighter sockets are
likely to be loaded with an audio CD with the vocalizations of
nearly every North American bird species, along with a program
called Avisys Song that enables a fast comparison of similar songs
by very different birds, like the worm-eating warbler and the
chipping sparrow.
</P>
<P>
   What Gilbert didn't bring along was a cellular phone, which Ann
Johnson, vice president of the Iowa Ornithologists' Union and Web
master of the Iowa Birding site on the Internet, considers
essential for live updates to and from friends as she runs around
the countryside near Des Moines on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johnson, a management analyst for the Iowa Department of
Human Services, picked up the bird-watching bug from a genuine
little old lady in tennis shoes, her grandmother. ``I attribute my
real start to the day when I was 7 and told Granny there was a
parrot on the corncrib,'' she said. ``That bird, a pileated
woodpecker, holds the place of honor on my life list.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cellular phones also let birders quickly report sightings to any
of the dozens of Rare Bird Alert telephone hot lines around the
country, including several in the New York metropolitan area. These
bird-alert reports are also available on the Internet, but they are
usually updated on a weekly basis.
</P>
<P>
   For the truly fanatical, the Houston Audubon Society offers a
subscription reporting service on rare birds in the United States
and Canada. In addition to Internet access to sightings and
directions, it offers a ``We Call You'' service; birders who need
certain species for their North American lists get a call if one of
them _ or a bird completely new to the continent _ is reported.
</P>
<P>
   There are quite a few takers. A study on the economic impact of
wildlife watching, released this month by the Federal Fish and
Wildlife Service, said 17.7 million Americans took bird-watching
trips in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A subset of those binocular-wielding millions are the men and
women who aspire to the exclusive 700 Club and 800 Club, limited to
birders who have seen more than 700 or 800 of the 914 bird species
north of the Mexican border. They keep bags packed for sudden trips
to places like Cape May, N.J., where a brown-chested martin, a
South American swallow, turned up last December.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, birders in dire need of ``twitches,'' sightings of
rare species, may rely on pagers for breaking news. ``A typical
twitcher will be searching around when a message like `great auk on
Outer Hebrides' comes on,'' said John Farrar, a British trade union
official in South Yorkshire. ``The twitcher will drop everything,
apart from his or her scope and credit card, and charge off
north.'' Of course, the great auk, a giant penguinlike ocean bird,
was last seen in 1844. But that's the general idea.
</P>
<P>
   Like his American counterparts, Farrar carries a handheld
computer to record sightings on Avisys, a Windows database system
devised by Jerry Blinn, who was a programmer turned manager before
he retired from International Business Machines and wrote Avisys.
</P>
<P>
   Blinn, definitely a serious birder, markets the software and its
companion, Avisys Song, through his company, Perceptive Systems in
Silverdale, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Birders have an insatiable appetite for data on what they've
seen, where they saw it and why,'' Blinn said. ``They want a
program where they record the habitat, the weather, the bird's
behavior, even unbelievable stuff like cloacal swelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Many birders' databases can be viewed on personal pages on the
Web. That's a new way to brag about one's life list _ but the sites
are also a useful place to find information if you need to know the
arrival dates of spring migrants, for instance, in a particular
area.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Internet, there is enough information about birds to
keep a watcher indoors for a month, including the huge Breeding
Bird Survey database at the Patuxent Wildlife Research Center in
Maryland. Other pages offer mnemonics to help birders remember
songs and calls, like ``look-up, over-here, see-me, up-here'' for
the red-eyed vireo; sound files for 51 Brazilian birds, and the
insane song of the laughing kookaburra, an Australian kingfisher.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the Web, through satellite tracking, it is possible
to follow a Laysan albatross' 90-day, 25,000-mile round trip over
the North Pacific to find food for its chick. Web cameras focus on
nesting peregrine falcons in Seattle, white storks in Germany and
tree swallows at the Cornell Laboratory of Ornithology in Ithaca,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   In partnership with the National Audubon Society, the Lab (as
birders know it) offers nonscientists the opportunity to ``bird
with a purpose'' by participating in online projects like Warbler
Watch. The Web page of the Gay Birders Club in England ``enables
contact between gay and lesbian bird-watchers worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   And if your e-mail box isn't full, you can subscribe to any of
some 60 specialized mailing lists on subjects like seabirds,
cavity-nesting birds, hummingbirds or Turkey's birds. The Web
supersite that has Internet links galore is (what else?) called
Birding (birding.miningco.com).
</P>
<P>
   Or you can grab a beat-up Peterson guide and binoculars worn to
the bare metal by years of heavy use, leave all the high-tech
gizmos at home and go on what Gilbert calls ``a treasure hunt,''
watching the activities of the most common birds, like the American
robin, for half an hour without worrying about peer pressure to run
up the day's score. Gilbert said, ``That's the fun part of
birding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
