<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE HEAT IS ON, IT'S TIME FOR FROZEN PASSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All I want is a beach boy to fan me. Oh, OK, he could spoon-feed
me, as well. This year's heat has been so debilitating that it saps
any energy you might want to expend in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   But, wait. Here are two very cooling recipes that require no
heat.
</P>
<P>
   The first was sent in by Tweazer Shewmake. ``My wonderful
mother-in-law, Vivian Elder, gave me a recipe for frozen passion
that sounds like the pineapple sherbet Karen Davis requested.''
</P>
<P>
   FROZEN PASSION
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1/2 gallon
</P>
<P>
   15-ounce can Eagle Brand Sweetened Condensed Milk
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can crushed pineapple (with juice)
</P>
<P>
   2-liter bottle cream soda (all of which won't be used)
</P>
<P>
   Mix milk and fruit together, pour into freezing container, then
stir in the cream soda to fill container to proper level for
freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Other fruits and flavors of soda can be substituted, such
as raspberries (frozen are fine) and raspberry soda.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per cup: 321 calories, 5 grams fat, 68
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 18 milligrams cholesterol,
100 milligrams sodium, 13 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   And something else cool: Christie Goodman, Arlington, sends the
following recipe _ perfect for a summer entree.
</P>
<P>
   CAESAR SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 heads romaine lettuce, washed, dried and torn
</P>
<P>
   Red chile dressing, recipe follows
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup croutons
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Parmesan cheese, freshly grated
</P>
<P>
   Place lettuce in a large bowl. Toss well with red chile
dressing. On each of 4 serving plates, place dressed lettuce. Add
croutons and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Red chile dressing:
</P>
<P>
   4 anchovies
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon red chile powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   In food processor, place all of the ingredients (except the
olive oil) and blend them. With food processor still running,
slowly dribble in the oil.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 462 calories, 45 grams fat, 8
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 11 milligrams cholesterol,
541 milligrams sodium, 88 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Request:
</P>
<P>
   Now here's one that's a reach. Lou Ann Morey, Burleson, has lost
a recipe devoured by a new family member _ a puppy named Sugar.
It's Dinah Shore's recipe for cioppino, that wonderful San
Francisco fish stew. Lou Ann says it's great for entertaining
because it can be made ahead and needs only mounds of sliced,
buttered sourdough bread to make a meal.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
