<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LITERARY-SITES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITERARY SITES OFFER MORE THAN WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (jt)  
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no frigate like a book to take us lands away,'' Emily
Dickinson wrote. Of course, she died in 1886, decades before anyone
conceived of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who sympathizes with Dickinson and has access to the Web
should set aside a hefty block of time and hie to a site called
Literary Locales. It is listed on a page maintained by the English
department at San Jose State University
 &UR; (www.sjsu.edu/depts/english) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   With a click, you can visit 122 places that figure in the lives
or the works of nearly as many writers (some have more than one
site). There are, of course, links to Shakespeare and the Globe
Theater, Proust's Combray, the West Yorkshire hills that the
Brontes called home, Dickens' Kent and many more places that
undeniably figure in the literary canon. There are also links to
such lesser-known authors as Flannery O'Connor, Anais Nin, Raymond
Chandler and Langston Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   With so many options, it was hard to choose where to go first.
That decision grew harder, not easier, because each site turned out
to be totally different from the others, which only heightened the
sense of exploration.
</P>
<P>
   Chaucer's Canterbury seemed intriguing _ and it was. Up popped a
map of the town today, with several roads highlighted in yellow.
You decide where you want to go, what you want to look at, from a
fish-and-chips shop to the Norman castle. After this introduction,
look above the map and click on the box marked ``Canterbury Web.''
Find and click on ``Canterbury Tales,'' then on ``The Chaucer
Pages.'' The scene-setting music you hear is ``Bring a Torch,
Jeannette Isabella,'' and you can now choose among quotes from
Chaucer, a list of his works, a biography, essays on him and
additional sources and books.
</P>
<P>
   But tarry on this page a little longer: at the bottom is a link
to the ``Anthology of Middle English Literature,'' which takes you
to similar offerings on Sir Gawain, Everyman and other medieval
plays and lyrics, each with an early music accompaniment (``Sumer
Is Icumen In'' for Gawain).
</P>
<P>
   The ``Canterbury Web'' page has many more options, including a
list of local hotels, restaurants and other tourist information for
those who want to make a real visit (which turned out to be not
untypical for these sites).
</P>
<P>
   For a total change of mood and sound, go back to the main list
and try ``Edgar Allen Poe's Favorite Haunts,'' which lists links to
Poe's cottage in the Bronx, his house in Baltimore and his national
historic site in Philadelphia. The best is the Poe museum in
Richmond, where your arrival is met with crashing thunder. You can
tour the museum's rooms, and you can access (under ``A Poe
Pourri'') samples of his works, a biography and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Poe enthusiasts will then want to move to ``Poe's Virtual
Library'' back on the main page, which lists links to
bibliographies, biographies, clothing, courses, movies, comics,
plays, family ties and you-name-it about Poe.
</P>
<P>
   A.A. Milne has two sites. ``Cotchford Farm'' in East Sussex,
where Milne vacationed and which he used as a setting for
``Winnie-the-Pooh'' and ``The House at Pooh Corner,'' offers
background and a nice picture of Poohsticks Bridge, but its real
value is as a link to other Pooh sites. Back on the Literary
Locales menu, the site called ``A.A. Milne's Ashdown Forest''
covers that ground and more, with more pictures of the bridge, the
surrounding area and scenes from the books, like Roo's sandpit.
</P>
<P>
   It was time for something more exotic: Palermo, Argentina, known
here as ``Jorge Luis Borges' Childhood Home.'' Almost a homage,
this site begins with a gallery of photographs of Borges. Then it
moves on to a serious examination of him, with a biography, a
compendium of critics' views of his works, an outline of his
influence on other authors and a collection of quotations,
including ``I have always imagined that Paradise will be a kind of
library.'' This site, by the way, also has a section in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   And so to the Middle East. For many people, Naguib Mahfouz _ his
Nobel Prize notwithstanding _ does require an introduction.
``Naguib Mahfouz's Cairo'' provides one, Cliff Notes-style: a
biography, an analysis of his development as a novelist, the
beginning and ending passages of ``Palace of Desire'' and ``Adrift
on the Nile,'' a few one-liners lifted from reviews and an
anthology of his works, with brief synopses of 8 of his more than
30 novels.
</P>
<P>
   Half a world away, there is ``Yukio Mishima's Home,'' a
Victorian house in Tokyo that requires only a brief stop. Click on
his name to call up an illustrated page giving a little summary of
his life and listing the works of Mishima, thought by some to be
one of Japan's postwar literary stars. Mishima committed suicide in
1970 and will soon be honored with a museum near Mount Fuji;
construction is to begin in the fall. For a preview, click on
``Mishima Cyber Museum.'' One listing, the history of his life, is
available only in Japanese, but others are in English.
</P>
<P>
   If you click on Proust's Combray, you will land in the village
in central France once called Illiers, but renamed Illiers-Combray
after Proust used it as the setting for the vacation home in
``Remembrance of Things Past.'' The page offers a description and a
few pictures, but scroll to the bottom for the best part: icons
depicting Proust himself. Click and you are in the realm of a
newsletter called ``Proust Said That,'' in which you will find that
Proust ``ate little, surviving on a diet of cafe au lait toward the
end of his life, and that, when he was 13, in response to a party
question `Who would you have liked to be?' he answered, `Since the
question does not arise, I prefer not to answer it. All the same, I
should very much have liked to be Pliny the Younger.''' There's
more, of course, including a recipe for bouillabaisse.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the sites offer more in the way of scene setting than
they do about an author. ``Langston Hughes' Lawrence,'' for
example, provides the basics of his life, illustrated by
photographs of his home and schools in Lawrence, Kan. But the site,
including links, tells more about local history and about Kansas
than about Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Others are simple and simply literary. ``Dylan Thomas' Fern
Hill'' provides just the text of that poem, pictures of the Welsh
farmhouse in question and a nearby creek, and a brief recounting of
a local tale about the farm.
</P>
<P>
   Tours are popular. ``D.H. Lawrence's Eastwood,'' which follows
the blue-line trail through Nottinghamshire, past homes he lived
in, is typical.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites proved disappointing. ``Bronte Country'' seemed all
too commercial, designed to lure tourists and sell merchandise more
than to slake the thirst of devoted readers. And ``Samuel Beckett's
Fermanagh'' is a link to the official site of the Northern Ireland
Tourist Board, which doesn't even mention Beckett. Likewise for
``James Herriot's Yorkshire,'' which gets you to the Yorkshire
Tourist Board.
</P>
<P>
   Only trial and error will tell you which Literary Locale is
evocative and which is perfunctory, which site to bookmark and
which to dismiss.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
