<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4773 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HARING-SITE-NYT &LR;      06-24 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HARING-SITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARING SITE BLENDS THE SERIOUS AND THE QUIRKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: In 2ND GRAF: THE WORD (EQUAL) SHOULD BE REPLACED WITH THE
SYMBOL)  
 (af)  
 By MICKEY MEECE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even those who are not familiar with the late artist Keith
Haring may get a kick out mf a Web site dedigated to his work.
</P>
<P>
   Landing upon www.haring.com can leave a visitor as gleeful as a
child racing down a slide or as thoughtful as an adult
contemplating$the AIDS slogan ``Silence (equal) Death.''
</P>
<P>
   Click on the Haring-drawn pyramid Art icon to find Exhibits and
Activities and relish Haring's range as an artist, from the somber
AIDS posters in Activism to the innocent Flipbooks.
</P>
<P>
   There, two Men With Holes, one red and one aquamarine, begin an
</P>
<P>
   animated routine. They move up and down. Aquamarine sticks a hand
through the large hole in red's chest; then red pokes a leg through
aquamarine; next, both cartwheel through each other, and finally
there's a twirl.
</P>
<P>
   Internet novices may be attracted to the splashy, colorful
presentation of Haring's widely recognized art icons, like crawling
babies, barking dogs and break dancers. And Web aficionados may
find the use of three-dimensional spaces and characters that
``morph'' into different figures compelling.
</P>
<P>
   In Haring World, visitors are taken to Haring Garden, a
three-dimensional landscape of shadowy green grass and blue skies
that never end. In this world, you control the movements of a
Haring figure, who, at the mouse's urging, flies through the
garden. Ahead are Haring sculptures and if you move the man just
right he will climb up on some of the appendages and fly off the
other side.
</P>
<P>
   Haring, who died of AIDS in 1990, was an internationally
acclaimed artist who was influenced by urban street culture and
children. Inspired by graffiti artists, Haring turned New York City
subway stations into his studio in the 1980s. He used white chalk
on the black paper in unused advertising spaces to draw hundreds of
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Haring was asked to do artwork on computers, said Julia Gruen,
executive director of the Keith Haring Foundation in Manhattan,
which owns the rights to his artwork and paid for the Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so thrilling for him to think that his images could be
sent out over the airways,'' she said. ``He thought that would be
the most amazing thing. Were Keith alive today, we can assume he
would be very involved in current Internet developments.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kaiser, director of the Riverbed Group in Manhattan, which
created the Web site, said, ``The great blessing about Haring's
work is it adapts itself to almost any medium.''
</P>
<P>
   Joshua M. Briggs, who works at the Tony Shafrazi Gallery in
Manhattan, which has had Haring shows, agreed. ``It's pretty well
suited to be reproduced in any form, on T-shirts, on the
sidewalk,'' he said. ``It works well on screen, with clear, simple
images.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
