<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENBLATT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSENBLATT PROFITS FROM TRAVAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lessons, like opportunities, can come from unexpected places in
life. But boxing is a difficult life, and the lessons most often
come at difficult times.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, though, nothing about boxing seemed difficult
for Dana Rosenblatt, the Malden middleweight who returns to the
ring Thursday night at Foxwoods against a tall, wily veteran named
Arthur Allen on the undercard of the Buster Douglas-Lou Savarese
pay-per-view show.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt had had 28 straight victories and a promotional deal
with Bob Arum that earned him escalating paydays of $25,000, then
$85,000, and finally $350,000 for a pay-per-view show against a
shopworn local hero named Vinny Pazienza whom Rosenblatt didn't
think much of.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the night he fought Pazienza went just as his career
had. It was a straight line toward the top as he pounded Pazienza
half-blind with his jab, doing terrible damage to an old warrior.
But the old warrior had learned lessons long ago that he was about
to teach young Rosenblatt.
</P>
<P>
   Pazienza had learned how dangeorus boxing is not from seeing
others in such danger but by being there himself and surviving.
Whether that is what led to what followed is hard to know, but
suddenly, Rosenblatt was down minutes before his moment of sure
victory, down from an unseen but crushing right hand to the cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt lost bitterly just seconds later, with Pazienza
having to be pried off him while he lay trapped and in a fog along
the ropes. It was the kind of deep shock that has ended many young
fighters' careers, but Rosenblatt was stronger than that.
</P>
<P>
   He's had to be, because it has taken him nearly two years to get
up from that punch and what followed it.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt won a comeback fight for chump change against veteran
Glenwood Brown in which he broke his right hand with the third
punch he landed. After six months off, he came back to the gym
renewed and ready and stayed that way for all of five minutes
before he broke the hand again. When that bone snapped, Rosenblatt
didn't, but it was a struggle not to.
</P>
<P>
   ``That totally let the wind out of my sails,'' Rosenblatt said.
``Forget about boxing? What about my life? It was dead stopped for
14 months. I didn't know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got pretty depressed sitting around, getting fat. I didn't
know if I should go back to college or look for a job. I didn't
want to do any of that stuff. I wanted to fight, but after the
second injury, I started to wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was all in my favor, and then it seemed like
everything was all against me and piling up. I was dumbfounded. How
could this possibly happen? That was the low, low point for me. It
was as low as I've ever been. I started to wonder, `Will I ever be
healthy?' Thoughts come into your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   It was then that Rosenblatt remembered something he'd heard his
old rival say during one of their overheated press conferences
before Pazienza taught him about defeat. He remembered how the guy
had struggled to make weight so often but always seemed to and
struggled to come back from terrible losses and always seemed to
and struggled to come back from something worse after he broke his
neck in a car accident and was told he'd never fight again but
seemed to do even that.
</P>
<P>
   He remembered not what he found distasteful about Pazienza, who
is loud and brash. What he remembered was the day he heard him say,
``You're only a loser when you quit. And I don't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quoting a guy I wouldn't quote too often, but what he said
was so suitable for this sport,'' said Rosenblatt. ``He showed me a
philosophy that applies to this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting where you learn things sometimes. I have more
respect now for a guy like Vinny, who hit rock bottom and came
back, because now I know what it's like to come back in this game.
I know how humbling it is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt has fought twice since his second hand injury,
winning in March and again in April against nonentities for short
money in bouts designed merely to get him comfortable. Allen is a
bit more difficult, although his lack of punching power gives
Rosenblatt the advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rosenblatt (30-1, 22 KOs) agrees he has an advantage,
he does not see it as one based on his power. His edge is simply
that he has learned things that only pain and disappointment can
teach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a much better fighter,'' Rosenblatt said. ``I'm 20 percent
better because all the time I was hurt, I kept going to the gym and
just working with my left hand. I'd been a one-handed fighter
before but I didn't realize it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't need a 14-month layoff, though. It was miserable. It
killed me to see a guy like Keith Holmes win and lose the
middleweight title while I was out. To see guys like Holmes and
(World Boxing Association champion William) Joppy, guys who were
well behind me, go by me hurt, because that should have been my
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``But setbacks make you a more hardened, experienced person. I
know if I'd beaten Vinny and got the fight with Ray Leonard that
Bob was talking about and stopped him like (Hector) Camacho did,
I'd be a millionaire today, but I'm not in this game to make a
quick hit. It's my career. That's why I'm still here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 26 and coming into my best fights and my physical prime
and I feel ready. I know now that some hardships should come to you
along the way. There was a time when everything was moving fast and
I started getting ahead of myself and my plan. The road to the top
seemed shorter than I thought. Then after what happened the last 14
months, the road seems like it's gotten longer just when I thought
it would get shorter. So I guess everything's probably about where
it should be, huh?''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night it will be for Rosenblatt because he'll be where
he should be. He'll be in a fight.
</P>
<P>
   A smarter guy in a fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
