<HEADER>
A4781 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-PALM-SOFTWARE-2TA     06-24 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PALM-SOFTWARE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PILOT FANS, LOTS OF BELLS AND WHISTLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Real life is starting to look a lot like science fiction. With
its flip top and handy size, the new Palm III personal organizer by
3Com/Palm Computing has been frequently likened to the flip-top
``communicator'' used on the original ``Star Trek'' television
show.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm III may look like a television prop on the outside, but
the adaptable little electronic organizer has lots of computing
muscle on the inside.
</P>
<P>
   Known as Pilots, the Palm Pilot and now the Palm III have won
the hearts of consumers, corporate folks and programmers since the
first one was introduced in 1996. More than a million of the
devices have been sold, and Palm Computing says more than 7,000
developers are working on applications for its palmtops.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to these developers, the Palm Pilot can now function as a
loan calculator, a computerized chess game, a scrollable copy of
Shakespeare's ``Twelfth Night'' and a miniature movie viewer, all
rolled into one convenient shirt-pocket package.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these programs can be downloaded from Palm Pilot Web
sites (America Online even maintains a healthy amount of Pilot
programs in its software libraries (AOL keyword: PalmPilot), and
many are now sold on CD-ROMs.
</P>
<P>
   If you have recently purchased a Palm III, chances are it came
with the Bonus Pack CD from Macmillan Digital Publishing USA that
Palm Computing is shipping with the new model
(www.macmillansoftware. com). Although the CD does not contain an
extensive amount of material _ much of it consists of ``lite''
versions of commercial programs _ it serves as a basic software
sampler.
</P>
<P>
   The disk might also help newcomers see how easy it is to load
third-party programs onto their Pilots. A financial calculator, a
traveler's almanac and an organizer that downloads favorite Web
pages from a personal computer to the Pilot are some of the
programs included on the Bonus CD.
</P>
<P>
   Several games are also included, perhaps as an incentive to
entice new owners to explore the CD. The rudimentary graphics are
far from 64-bit but the Bonus Pack's handheld arcade offers Sub
Hunt and Mine Hunt, proving that no video-game suite is complete
without a couple of contests featuring bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Macmillan Digital Publishing also offers the Business Plus Pack
for Palm Pilot. As the name implies, the applications included on
the CD, like money management and productivity programs, are aimed
specifically at business and financial professionals. It can be
found on the company's Web site or in software retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Web sites go, the one from Palm Computing (www.palm.
com) contains a wealth of information and links to other resources.
Featuring news about Pilot products, the site is also home to an
online catalog of accessories and software. You can also find
information on hardware, like an attachable modem or the add-in
card that turns the Pilot into a pager. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are more than a thousand programs written just for the
Palm Pilot, and a good sampling of them can be found on two
programs on CDs: Everything for Palm Pilot (www.pilotmall.com) and
Pilot Island's Goodies (www.pilotisland. com). The Web is a
bountiful provider as well, as one finds when entering The Pilot
Zone (www.pilotzone.com).
</P>
<P>
   Testing was done on a first-generation Pilot 5000 synced to a
Power Macintosh 7500 and a Palm III hooked up to a Compaq Deskpro
PC running Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Pilot's functions is its ability to Hot Sync _ when
the Pilot is put into a special ``cradle,'' a one-button operation
and a special cable and connector that hooks into the back of the
desktop machine makes it exchange information with a desktop
computer, so things like appointment schedules are up to date in
both places. Once the Pilot is hooked up to the desktop computer,
software can be uploaded from the desktop to the Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the Pilot's popularity is that it is one of the
only palmtops that is compatible with Macintosh computers as well
as PCs, although the software for the Macintosh has not had as many
functions as that available for the PC.
</P>
<P>
   A long-awaited upgrade to the Macintosh desktop software is due
in August, and Palm Computing reports that third-party developers
are already working on software that will allow Mac users to
realize the Pilot's potential for fax, e-mail and expense
reporting, plus Internet and office-network connectivity.
</P>
<P>
   A caveat: before going hog-wild at the software buffet, you
might want to make sure that vital data is backed up on a desktop.
With the copious amount of code out there, there is always the
chance of loading a program that has more bugs in it than the
rainforest, inadvertently crashing your Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Upon seeing what is out there for the Palm Pilot, the ``Star
Trek'' link doesn't seem to be solely one of physical resemblance.
Three of the four collections offered a program called Tricorder
written by Jeff Jetton. This nifty little application lets your
Pilot mimic a 1980s ``Star Trek'' tricorder, complete with graphics
and computerized burps, chirps and beeps.
</P>
<P>
   It is also available (along with several other pleasant Pilot
diversions) at Jetton's Web site at
www.mindspring.com/jetton/pilot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   EVERYTHING FOR PALMPILOT, VOLUME I &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ISO Productions; $14.95; Windows 95 and NT, and Macintosh.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything'' is a serious boast in any context, but this
collection seems to come close. There are 763 applications listed
on the CD-ROM, with directions to a Web site for Pilot software
released after the disk was pressed (www.pilotmall.com).
</P>
<P>
   The Pilot programs in this collection are far-ranging and span
the usual array of graphics, financial and communications options.
There are a number of automotive-maintenance reminder programs,
several specialized clocks, calendars and calculators and an
application called Multimedia Player, by Daniel Springwald, that
lets you watch movies on the Pilot's tiny screen (although the
index notes that ``you probably won't be watching `The Godfather'
anytime soon'').
</P>
<P>
   For musicians, there are 13 applications in the Music/Sound
category. Fretboard, a free program written by Dave MacLeod,
displays the finger positions for chords on a range of stringed
instruments, like guitar, banjo, violin and mandolin.
</P>
<P>
   Fretboard will also beep the notes for you, but only people with
perfect pitch will probably be able to glean much from the tones
coming from the Pilot's speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The disk also contains digitized subway maps for New York,
Boston, Washington and London and tiny Pilot-ized versions of the
video-game relics Pong and Missile Command. The supporting software
needed for some of the more elaborate programs is usually included
on the disk.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of these applications can be found on the Web, the
creators have designed an excellent interactive index for efficient
browsing of the contents. The index file lets the user search for a
particular program or category of programs.
</P>
<P>
   It displays an information card for each application, with a
description, price, memory requirements and the name and e-mail
address of the programmer. The index is a good search tool, but it
could use a copy editor, as typos were found in several entries.
</P>
<P>
   The index also shows a screen shot (if available) of what a
particular program looks like on a simulated Pilot screen. There is
an Install button at the top of the Index window so you can mark a
program for loading onto your Pilot during the next Hot Sync
session.
</P>
<P>
   The on-screen experience with the Everything for Palm Pilot's
graphical database gives new meaning to the term ``window
shopping'' and brings to mind online catalog surfing (without tying
up the telephone line for hours).
</P>
<P>
   Many programs here are free, but many are shareware. So in
addition to the cost of the CD, you may have to shell out an
additional fee ($10 to $20 on average) if you like a program enough
to buy it from its creator. The disk also includes commercial demo
versions of some applications, plus other Pilot information and
resources.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much software readily available here that the
biggest problem is deciding what to load, and how much, onto your
trusty Pilot. Space, as they say, (italics)is(end italics) the
final frontier. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PILOT GOODIES, VOLUME 1 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Pilot Island Publishing; $34.95; Windows 95, 98 and NT.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The crown jewel of the Pilot Goodies CD-ROM is the Pilot Island
company's Breeze interface for the desktop computer. The interface
is far more intuitive than the native Palm Pilot installer program
and is a visually elegant way to select third-party applications to
install on your Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Colorful graphics and sound make the Breeze interface playful.
The program categories on the main screen are represented by icons
floating on a tropical island. As you pass the cursor over an icon,
the sound of steel drums echoes, and clicking the icon calls up all
the programs in the category.
</P>
<P>
   A button bar, called the Breeze Command Center, leads you from
step to step in a few quick clicks, from choosing the programs to
doing a Hot Sync. You can see a list of the programs (and the total
file size) for everything you have chosen to upload.
</P>
<P>
   The Breeze also allows a user to put several programs into a
specific group that can be regularly loaded all at once _ like a
selection of different games and time-killer programs you can load
for whichever fidgety kid you're taking to the orthodontist this
week. Best of all, you can use the Breeze to install Pilot software
you find on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   With such an easy way to choose and upload files, you will want
to look immediately for some programs to install. The Goodies disk
contains more than 300 pieces of shareware and freeware.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the most popular programs in the Pilot universe show up
on the disk, including Launchpad, a small utility that lets you
separate the icons for your Pilot applications into tabbed layers
for easy access and organization.
</P>
<P>
   The applications run the gamut, from serious techie staples like
Web browsers and a tracker program to work with a GPS receiver to
more down-to-earth offerings, like something similar to an
Etch-A-Sketch game. There is a Hot Stuff area that holds some of
the most useful programs, including a Pilot defragmentation utility
(for standard maintenance) and a document file containing a list of
United States telephone area codes.
</P>
<P>
   The educational offerings on Goodies are particularly strong.
Budding scientists can load up the Periodic Table of the Elements,
a metric converter and a guide to patent law. Linguists can fare
well, too, as several shareware foreign-language dictionaries,
including French, Spanish, German and Japanese, are available.
</P>
<P>
   With the Caribbean-inspired theme of the Breeze interface, you
might get a craving for a few drinks with paper umbrellas. The
Pilot Island folks seem to have anticipated that _ they included a
file with plenty of shrimp recipes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1626EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
