<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4799 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORGAN-CATERER-1700(2     06-24 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGAN-CATERER-1700(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BET MARTHA STEWART DOESN'T KNOW HER CATERER HAILS FROM WICHITA
FALLS, TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Note to employers: Resumes can be deceiving. Take a look at this
one.
</P>
<P>
   Name: Pamela Morgan
</P>
<P>
   Place of birth: Wichita Falls, Texas
</P>
<P>
   Education: University of Texas
</P>
<P>
   First job: Dancer with modern dance troupe, Austin
</P>
<P>
   Probable outcome: Ceramic artist with an organic garden in Round
Rock
</P>
<P>
   And the employer would be dead wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Morgan is one of New York City's hottest caterers,
creating events for President Bill Clinton, Martha Stewart and
Garth Brooks. Her takeout/dine-in shop, Flavors, gets rave reviews
from the likes of John Mariani, Daniel Boulud and Gael Greene. The
petite North Texas native is definitely swimming with the big fish.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan fell in love with New York City while visiting there with
her friend Dean Ornish (another Texan who's definitely in the big
pond). Nothing would do but that she would try her legs at hoofing
in the Big City. But on the way to stardom, she got sidetracked by
the food bazaar that is New York.
</P>
<P>
   That led to a job at the Silver Palate, the definitive takeout
store (and cookbook) that put chicken marbella into the culinary
vernacular. It was a time of American palates experimenting with
all sorts of things: balsamic vinegar, tapenade and aioli platters.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan learned her lessons well and went on to develop her own
style, a ``Texas meets Tuscany'' marriage of what she calls
``really flavorful food with bold tastes. Tuscan food is simple,
and our food is, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Now her flavors have been published in ``Flavors,'' (Viking,
$29.95), a collection of dishes such as smoky chicken with herbed
goat cheese stuffing and crab and corn cakes with chipotle
remoulade. In Fort Worth last week to promote her book, she
marveled at how food has grown across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Eatzi's and was very impressed. There was so much
freshness and creativity, I felt like I was in New York. And I'm
glad they're going to open one in New York,'' Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   But after dinner at cutting-edge AquaKnox, she was eager to move
on to Wichita Falls to eat barbecue and fried chicken prepared by
her family's longtime cook. It's a far cry from ``The Market
Table'' at Flavors, where about 20 dishes are presented daily,
along with an all-organic potato bar, an oatmeal bar and a lemonade
bar.
</P>
<P>
   But not so different, really, than Luby's. ``I just love their
banana cream pie,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to imagine Morgan catering to the rich and famous. The
dinner she prepared for President Clinton, a $25,000-a-person
fund-raiser in a private home, included butternut squash soup,
seared red snapper with white beans, and angel food cake _ because
the president doesn't eat chocolate. After dinner, she presented
Clinton with a bag of extra-spicy gingersnaps to take aboard Air
Force One.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, Morgan met Hillary Clinton, who hadn't been
at the dinner. ``She said `Oh, I heard about those cookies,' '' and
Morgan gave her a copy of the cookbook, which includes the recipe.
Hillary asked: ``If I cook from the book, will I look like you?''
</P>
<P>
   Not a chance, darling. There are some Texanisms that just don't
translate.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKED BAKED BEAN SALAD WITH MOLASSES-MUSTARD VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   2 cups (about 3/4 pound) small dried white beans, such as Great
Northern
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon yellow mustard seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup drained, finely chopped, oil-packed, sun-dried tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsulphured molasses
</P>
<P>
   2 canned chipotle chiles (canned smoked jalapenos in sauce),
with clinging sauce, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cold-pressed extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely diced red onion
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup finely chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, cover beans with cold water and let soak for
at least 4 hours, or overnight for convenience.
</P>
<P>
   Drain beans. In large pan, cover them with fresh cold water. Set
over medium heat and bring to a simmer. Cover tightly, lower the
heat and cook gently, stirring once or twice, until just tender,
35-45 minutes. Drain and cool.
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, combine vinegar and mustard seeds and let soak
for at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, whisk together the soaked seeds and vinegar,
the sun-dried tomatoes, molasses, chipotles and salt. Gradually
whisk in the oil.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, toss together the beans, dressing, onion and
parsley. Adjust seasoning. Serve at room temperature, more or less
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 349 calories, 12 grams fat, 48
grams carbohydrates, 14 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 290
milligrams sodium, 32 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK FOREST HAM SANDWICHES WITH DIJON-BRIE SPREAD
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 sandwiches
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ripe brie, chilled
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon Tabasco
</P>
<P>
   1 large green onion, thinly sliced (tender top included)
</P>
<P>
   1 21-inch-long crusty baguette, split horizontally
</P>
<P>
   1 pound thinly sliced Black Forest ham, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Trim rind off chilled brie. Let the cheese come to room
temperature. In food processor, combine brie, mustard and Tabasco.
Process, stopping once or twice to scrape down sides of the work
bowl, until smooth. Transfer to a container and stir in green
onion. The spread can be used immediately or prepared several days
in advance. Cover tightly and refrigerate. Return to room
temperature if chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the cut sides of the baguette with the brie mixture,
dividing it evenly and using it all. Ruffle the ham onto the
baguette bottom. Set the top section in place. Cut the baguette
crosswise diagonally into 4 equal sections. Serve within an hour or
two.
</P>
<P>
   Note: This classic Flavors sandwich is a subtle twist on ham and
cheese. For so few ingredients, the sandwiches have great flavor if
you get the best ham and brie and a good gutsy bread.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 751 calories, 44 grams fat, 31
grams carbohydrates, 55 grams protein, 180 milligrams cholesterol,
2,270 milligrams sodium, 53 percent of calories from fat. MORE &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
