<HEADLINE>
HUGE MICROSOFT PHOTO FILE IS PART OF A BIGGER PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(ja) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Need an aerial picture of your house or your business or even
the Great Wall of China? There's no need to ask the government for
a satellite photo; just get on the Web and ask Microsoft Corp.,
which unveiled an online database this week granting access to
satellite and aerial pictures of nearly half of the United States
and some foreign sites.
</P>
<P>
   While Microsoft says that its database, called Terra Server
(www.terraserver.microsoft.com), is the largest database available
on line, there appears to be some dispute about that. In any case,
the project not only marks the creation of one whopper of a digital
scrapbook, it also says something very big about Microsoft's effort
to enter the database business, using as an opener a venture that
can capture the public imagination. Microsoft's strategy is to use
Terra Server to prove that its software and operating system are
suited to massive databases.
</P>
<P>
   Business strategy aside, the mechanics of the database are
impressive. A 45-foot-by-25-foot Compaq computer in Canyon Park,
Wash., holds satellite images of the United States and Europe and
aerial photographs of the United States. The aerial photographs
come from the U.S. Geological Survey; the satellite pictures are
distributed by Aerial Images, which in turn obtained them through a
branch of the Russian Space Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Two years in the making, the project offers access to images
previously unavailable to the public _ at least not without much
more time, effort and bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   The images are useful, according to Microsoft, for farmers,
academics and businesses needing survey information, as well as for
ordinary Netizens who want to peruse their surroundings. There are
also pictures from on high of such landmarks as the Great Wall of
China and Central Park. The test site got 4 million hits on
Tuesday, the day after it was first publicized nationally.
</P>
<P>
   The USGS pictures can be downloaded for free. The photos from
Aerial Images cost $7.95 to $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the database contains 178 million photos covering 45
percent of the United States and portions of Europe. Within two
years, the creators hope to have images of the entire contiguous 48
states. ``We hope that you'll be able to start at Barstow, Calif.,
and move the cursor east until you get to the Atlantic Ocean,''
said John Hoffman, president of Aerial Images.
</P>
<P>
   There is a handful of publicly available databases offering even
more than Microsoft's one terabyte of data, which is enough
information to fill 2 million books taking up 15 miles of shelf
space. A site from Dialog Corp. offers about 2.5 terabytes listing
U.S. patents and images; an IBM site that also includes patents is
1.5 terabytes.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, IBM _ a clear competitor for Microsoft in its
effort to collect database business _ has some opinions about the
Terra Server's size. ``It's not the world's largest database on
line,'' said Jeff Cross, an IBM spokesman. Cross added, ``We've
been at this for a while. It's good to see other companies learning
to put large databases on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Microsoft's original goal was to create the database
not for consumers but as a showcase for technology. It considered
creating a database of major league baseball statistics, or of
every trade in the history of the New York Stock Exchange, but
neither project provided enough data to suit its goals.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that Microsoft wants to play in this
industry, known as enterprise computing. The database software
business is a $10 billion market, according to Richard Winter,
president of Winter Corp., a Boston consulting firm that
specializes in large databases. The industry is dominated by names
like IBM, Oracle, Sybase and Informix. Microsoft is not a player at
the very high end.
</P>
<P>
   Many of today's multiterabyte databases are used inside
companies. By making Terra Server accessible over the Internet,
Microsoft is trying to show that its software can also be used
inside companies, where storage and retrieval demands are less
severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting statement from Microsoft,'' Winter said.
``It says, `Sit up and take notice. We're going after the big
database market.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
