A4806 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-BIRD-WATCHING-OPT     06-24 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BIRD-WATCHING-OPTICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HANDFUL OF VIEWING POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By LES LINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For bird-watchers, power means power. Higher-powered optics make
birds appear closer so they can be identified through the field
marks that, for example, distinguish a lesser yellowlegs from a
greater yellowlegs.
</P>
<P>
   Those differences are often subtle: The greater yellowlegs has a
long, slightly upturned bill and thicker leg joints, while the
lesser yellowlegs has a straight bill. If you see the two
shorebirds side by side, the lesser is noticeably smaller, but
otherwise it's a tough call.
</P>
<P>
   Ten-power binoculars deliver the highest magnification that is
practical for handheld viewing _ if you have steady hands _ but
many bird-watchers, especially women, prefer 7X or 8X models. If
you want to view an oriole in the top of a shade tree in your yard,
binoculars are all you will need for a good look and a confident
check mark on your list.
</P>
<P>
   But wetlands birds, like loons, ducks, gulls, sandpipers and
herons, as well as birds of prey, are typically seen at a distance.
That is when a spotting scope is useful. Models that zoom from 15X
to 45X or from 20X to 60X are popular among birders, but a sturdy
tripod is needed to keep the image from jiggling.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, if there is a stiff wind, you can get queasy from a
tremor in the image that increases along with the magnification.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to hold a spotting scope in your hand, even at the lowest
magnification, is futile. Or at least it was until Carl Zeiss, the
famous German optical company, adapted 16th-century technology and
introduced a 20-power stabilized monocular/scope that can be
comfortably held and focused in one hand. With the press of a
button, the image becomes sharp and rock-steady.
</P>
<P>
   The military has used high-power gyro-stabilized binoculars for
decades, notably on ships at sea, but they are heavy and require a
power source. Further, the gyro takes time to spool up to speed,
and a power source, like a battery pack, is required. And the
gyro's whine, while inaudible to humans, spooks wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The stability of the Zeiss 20x60S depends on mechanical
ingenuity, not electronics. There isn't one circuit inside the
light, ergonomically contoured and water-resistant housing of the
scope, which weighs just 42 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the scope's prism, which is required for image reversal,
is mounted in a suspension system that moves left, right or down
with the user's hand so the incoming light rays always fall on the
same image plane. Any vibrations caused by hand tremors are
mechanically suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   For some bird-watchers, a drawback of the Zeiss stabilized
monocular is its suggested retail price: $2,999.95. If your pockets
are deep and you prefer a 20-power stabilized binocular, which is
heavier and not so slick to use in the field, Zeiss has that, too _
for $4,999.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
