<HEADER>
A4810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOGRAMS-ART-NYT &LR;      06-24 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOGRAMS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVE NEW WORLD STUCK ON THE ROAD TO KITSCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Crossing the swimming pool with the relentlessness of a Steven
Spielberg tracking shot, the boy's goggles splash bits of green and
orange and purple: they are the holographic images of hungry shark
mouths on the eyepieces of Speedo's new hologram goggles. The
wearer can look through the goggles, but the viewer sees the shark
faces or, alternately, shark eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Holograms are shimmering across the land on summer toys and
movie tie-ins. Last year, they starred in a pop watch for ``The
Lost World'' with a dinosaur's eye holographed on the face. This
year, they glimmer on baseball cards, T-shirts and tennis shoes.
The Air Jordan Jumpman logo on basketball shoes has been turned
into a hologram.
</P>
<P>
   Once holography was the photography of the future. Once, when
the very word ``laser'' was full of magic and promise, National
Geographic put a hologram on its cover to astonish its readers. Now
the hologram is disposable glitter. Coming home to the world of
placemats and mugs, it has entered the realm of the mundane.
</P>
<P>
   Subliminally, holograms still say high tech, but they are found
more and more in low-tech applications. Inexpensive holograms and
holographic foils have their serious moments, to be sure: they are
used as seals to authenticate boxes of videotapes or software, or
they appear on credit cards or even currency to insure,
theoretically, against counterfeiting.
</P>
<P>
   But holograms are now routinely faked by clever counterfeiters,
and one for the new euro banknotes was stolen a few weeks ago. Like
mere humans, they are no longer invulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, holograms will seem as corny as 3-D. I have a 1950s
Xograph 3-D postcard of the Empire State Building; the card is
thick, and the clouds seem layered an inch behind the building.
There also used to be flicker disks given as prizes in boxes of
Cracker Jack: the batter hit the ball as you turned the disk in the
light. Another classic was the 1964 campaign button that turned
from ``L.B.J.'' to ``For the U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Until 1992, the Museum of Holography in the Soho section of New
York City had as much artistic ambition as the Minimalist works on
show at the Leo Castelli or John Weber galleries. The holograms
seemed as fragile as the first daguerreotypes, which also looked
different from different angles. One star item at the museum showed
a woman blowing a kiss as the viewer walked around the image; it
was as titillating in its own small way as Edison's scandalous
early film, ``The Kiss.'' Holograms were so space-agey that they
turned up in ``Star Wars,'' with the fuzzy, low-resolution figure
of the pleading Princess Leia.
</P>
<P>
   But some people take holograms much more seriously. In ``The
Holographic Universe'' (HarperCollins, 1991), Michale Talbot argues
nothing less than that the universe is itself one giant hologram.
In this combination of pop science and parapsychology, Talbot thus
explains out-of-body experiences, quantum theory problems, the
paranormal and other ``unsolved riddles of brain and body.''
One-upping Descartes, he writes that ``our world and everything in
it . . . are only ghostly images, projections from a level of
reality so beyond our own that it is literally beyond both space
and time.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a belief seems holographic in itself _ hyped up with trompe
l'oeil; false like the melodramatic hues of the holographic image,
somewhere between opal and oil slick. Those colors shimmer
nervously, as if the stationary image was no longer enough and, in
the multimedia world, must be in motion.
</P>
<P>
   In this regard, holograms seem right for the time; the sometimes
dizzying depth of their space represents easy truths and cheap
profundities. Hollow and show-offy, holograms are the tie-dye of
the '90s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
