<HEADER>
A4833 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVIC-RENEWAL-COX &UR;  &UR; `N     06-24 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIC-RENEWAL-COX </SLUG>
     `NATION OF SPECTATORS' A THREAT TO
DEMOCRACY, PANEL REPORTS
 &HT;     By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Warning that democracy is threatened as America
becomes ``a nation of spectators,'' a national commission urged
Americans on Wednesday to take active roles in their communities
and the political arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people in America feel powerless'' and have grown
``passive and disengaged'' when it comes to fulfilling their civic
duties, former Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., said at a news conference to
release a report by the National Commission on Civic Renewal.
</P>
<P>
   But most citizens have only themselves to blame, said William
Bennett, a Republican who served as education secretary under
President Reagan and was commission co-chairman along with Nunn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fret about the weakness of our families, but will not make
the personal commitments needed to preserve them. We worry about
the consequences of out-of-wedlock births, but refuse to condemn
them. We deplore the performance of our public schools, but somehow
we can't find the time to join parents' associations, attend school
board meetings or even help our children with their homework.''
Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn also called on Americans to stop waiting for others to do
the work for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we place adult gratification over the well-being of our
children?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's 18-month study was summarized in a 67-page
report that Bennett called ``tough on Americans.'' It found
troubling signs of the breakdown of civil society. Neighborhood and
community ties have frayed, public schools are often unsafe and
popular culture is vulgar, and political participation is at
depressed levels, Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   Among dozens of recommendations, the commission urged Americans
to join a school, church or community association, pitch in to
improve his or her neighborhood, and try to raise each child in
two-parent family whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett also said Americans need to take personal responsibility
by cultivating partnerships with faith-based institutions, raising
standards in civic education and encouraging journalists to promote
public awareness of civic issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``A free society depends on the standards and behavior not just
of our leaders but average citizens as well,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   The key, Nunn said, was not inventing civic activity from
scratch but finding ways to build on the work quietly being carried
out by thousands of community groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many organizations have been ignored,'' Nunn said. ``They need
volunteers and publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to spark a national discussion on the issue, the
commission will form four task forces that will address family,
neighborhood, school and entertainment industry issues.
</P>
<P>
   One task force will update an index unveiled Wednesday that
gauges the country's civic health.
</P>
<P>
   The index, which measures trends over the past quarter-century
in such indicators as voter turnout and membership in
organizations, ``indicates a significant overall decline in the
quality of civic life in America over the last 25 years,'' Bennett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Rimel, president of The Pew Charitable Trusts, which
funded the commission's project, attributed the decline in part to
Americans taking their voting privileges for granted. They would be
``outraged,'' she said, if ``their voice didn't count in
determining their future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why its so ironic to me that cynicism is spreading
across the land,'' she said. ``It will cost America and it will
cost big.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
