<HEADER>
A4836 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CHINA-HNS &LR;      06-24 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO PAY HOMAGE TO CHINA'S PAST IN HIS NINE-DAY VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIAN, China _ President Clinton's carefully scripted itinerary
in China underscores his emphasis on visiting benign tourist stops
designed to generate favorable media coverage across the country
rather than making tough negotiations the centerpiece of his trip.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he will view legions of 2,200-year-old, life-size terra
cotta warriors buried to protect an ancient Chinese emperor before
he begins his summit with Chinese President Jiang Zemin in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, arriving here Thursday for the first visit to China by
an American president since the Tiananmen Square massacre in 1989,
will spend more time in the country _ nine days _ than any of the
four previous American presidents who have visited this vast nation
since Richard Nixon cracked open the door in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clinton's schedule sets aside fewer than 11 hours for
private meetings and social occasions with the Chinese president or
Vice Premier Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton, accompanied by First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton and their daughter Chelsea, will honor China's 5,000-year
history by visiting popular sites and reaching out to the nation's
people with roundtable discussions and stops at out-of-the-way
villages.
</P>
<P>
   American and Chinese officials hope that the first family's
travels will also broaden Americans' understanding of this country
of 1.2 billion people, which hopes to become the largest economy in
the world early in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Col. P.J. Crowley, a spokesman for the White House
National Security Council who is accompanying the president, said
Clinton's history-laden itinerary is deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Summits are not just about how much time presidents spend
together,'' Crowley said. ``The Chinese people understandably want
respect for their country as a great power. We expect they will
welcome the president's visit as that kind of recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   The cities that Clinton will visit span the breadth of Chinese
history. He opens his journey in Xian, a former imperial capital
that was thriving 1,100 years before the birth of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton then visits Beijing to hold official meetings, Shanghai
to rendezvous with successful entrepreneurs; Guilin to stress
environmental concerns; and Hong Kong, Asia's cosmopolitan
financial hub that reverted to Chinese control last June after 156
years as a British colony.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after arriving here in Xian Thursday morning (EDT)
following an 18-hour flight, the president will visit the restored
ancient stone wall that girds this one-time mercantile capital,
which served as the eastern terminus of the fabled Silk Road.
</P>
<P>
   Xian, the capital of China for 1,100 years, once echoed with the
sounds of Chinese traders and the camel caravans that they used to
transport perfumes, jewels and horses from the eastern frontiers of
the Roman Empire along the Mediterranean in exchange for Chinese
silks, porcelain and paper.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his family will also visit the famed terra cotta
warriors that lie buried within sight of the tomb of Qin
Shihuangdi, the ruthless emperor who forged a united nation in 221
B.C.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday in Beijing, Clinton will stand in the West Plaza in
front of the Great Hall of the People gazing across Tiananmen
Square during an official arrival ceremony. The 98-acre square in
the heart of Beijing has served as the setting for political tumult
throughout Chinese history, including the bloody 1989 crackdown on
pro-democracy demonstrators that left hundreds dead.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Clinton will visit the medieval Forbidden City that
housed 24 isolated Chinese emperors from the 14th century until the
demise of the last emperor in 1911. Clinton also will visit the
Great Wall, remnants of which wind at least 2,000 miles from the
west to the outskirts of Beijing in the east.
</P>
<P>
   Next Thursday, en route from Shanghai to Hong Kong, Clinton will
see the round-topped limestone Guilin Peaks in southern China that
have inspired generations of poets and painters. The setting along
the Li River draws more than 6 million Chinese tourists and 500,000
foreigners each year, who gaze at the fairytale landscape of
limestone mountains soaring up to 600 feet above tangerine orchards
and fields of rice, taro and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a master of hand-to-hand politics at home, also plans
to visit three Chinese villages, including one that is more than
400 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The president referred to his goals as First Salesman for the
American way of life in an address at the National Geographic
Society on June 11. ``The more we share our ideas with the world,
the more the world will come to share the ideals that animate
America,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials welcomed Clinton's mission as evidence that
U.S.-Chinese relations have recovered from the chill that followed
the 1989 violence in and near Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very fact that Clinton will travel all the way across the
ocean to China to pay respect to this great nation will be
appreciated as a sign of friendship and goodwill,'' said a senior
Chinese official, speaking on condition of anonymity before
Clinton's arrival.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
