<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 3-FOOT EXCUSE FOR BEING LATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you ever run out of excuses for why you were late for work,
I've got a brand new one. Tell them, ``There was a snake in the
garage and I couldn't get to my car!'' It happened to me, and I'm
still shaking in my pumps.
</P>
<P>
   One morning last week I was getting dressed for work and I told
my son to go ahead and put his golf clubs in the trunk so I could
drop him off for lessons on my way to the office. Two minutes
later, he came running in, screaming and dancing like James Brown:
``Snake in the garage! There's a snake in the garage! Mom, there's
a huge snake in the garage! I think it's a python!''
</P>
<P>
   As he is prone to exaggeration (can't imagine where he got that
from), I went ahead and finished applying my lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, son,'' I said. ``I do believe there's a snake in the
garage but I doubt it's a python. Pythons don't live in this part
of the country, and they're really huge. It's probably just a
garden snake. He's as frightened as you. If he's still there, we'll
just toss him into the grass.''
</P>
<P>
   I grabbed a broom on my way to the garage and boldly stepped
onto the oily concrete. Out of the corner of my eye, I saw
something move by the trash can. I turned and saw the longest,
fattest, scariest snake that I have ever seen outside of a zoo. I
screamed, ran back into the house, and slammed the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geez! Did you see that thing? I think it's a boa constrictor.
I'm glad I didn't leave the keys in there. He's big enough to
drive!''
</P>
<P>
   ``See, I told you. What are we gonna do? He's right by the
car.''
</P>
<P>
   I took deep breaths and tried to think. I spent much of my youth
in the woods of East Texas and am no stranger to snakes. I pride
myself on my courage and resourcefulness. So I did what any 90s
kind of girl would do. I called my husband at work and yelled:
``There's a snake in the garage! There's a snake in the garage!''
</P>
<P>
   My knight rushed home to save me; admittedly, a little smug at
first. He reached for a hoe and started poking around for the
``little earthworm.'' All of a sudden, this huge, hissing head
emerged from behind the lawn mower. That sucker was a good 3 feet
long! Husband did a jump Carl Lewis would envy while my son and I
wasted no time chiming, ``Told you so!''
</P>
<P>
   Thus the battle between man and nature began. My husband chased
the snake all over the garage. I begged him to let the police
handle it but he wouldn't. ``He came into my garage and scared my
family,'' he said. ``Call whoever you want, but he's mine!'' But I
was so afraid that the snake would bite him, or vice versa, that I
called 911 anyway.
</P>
<P>
   When I went back outside, my husband had cornered the snake in
the branches of a red-tip photinia and was trying to spear it with
the hoe. My son was yelling, ``Get him, Dad!'' from 100 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, the animal control people arrived and snared what
they said was some kind of ``bull'' snake. I imagine they took it
to safety and freedom far, far away.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one believed me when I told them why I arrived at
work an hour late. And I haven't parked in the garage since. Did I
mention that I usually stayed inside the house in the woods of East
Texas?
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is an Arlington wife, mother and
dentist. Write her in care of the Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram
St., Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
