<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE COMPLETES UNDEFEATED FIRST-ROUND; DENMARK ADVANCES DESPITE
LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ The Tour de France continues for the host nation,
and so far it has won every stage in style.
</P>
<P>
   In an anxious fortnight for France, which has seen its bright
and shiny World Cup tarnished by strikes in the air and ticket
scandals and rioting and neo-Nazi salutes on the ground. But the
French team has yet to be troubled on the field.
</P>
<P>
   It won its three first-round games by a combined score of nine
goals to one, and its 2-1 victory over Denmark on Wednesday made it
the first team in this World Cup to head into the second round with
a perfect record.
</P>
<P>
   Only two other host nations have started as well: Uruguay in
1930 and Italy in 1990. The coming weeks will tell if the French
will follow on the heels of Uruguay, which won, or Italy, which
lost before even reaching the final. What is clear after
Wednesday's match is that France has no shortage of players capable
of contributing.
</P>
<P>
   The French national team has long had a nickname for its
reserves. They are called ``les coiffeurs'', or the hairstylists: a
reference to the fact that reserves in the World Cup are able to
keep their locks dry and in place as they observe the real players
from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   But after three games in these finals, the only French players
who have yet to perspire for their nation are backup goalkeepers
Bernard Lama and Lionel Charbonnier. Against the Danes, who also
qualified for the second round despite their loss, Jacquet started
seven different players than he did in the opener against South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The French coach with the first-communion haircut did it for
some good reasons. Star playmaker Zinedine Zidane is out for two
games, including the much more important second-round match on
Sunday, after thoughtlessly raking his cleats on the leg of a Saudi
player.
</P>
<P>
   Three other regulars _ captain Didier Deschamps, Bixente
Lizarazu and Laurent Blanc _ were rested to avoid the risk of
picking up second yellow cards that would have knocked them out of
the second-round match along with Zidane.
</P>
<P>
   It was a calculated risk: France still needed a draw to clinch
first place in Group C. But France has the players to gamble and
win, although France doesn't get the chance to see them on its own
soil very often.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, France's defensive midfield composed of Patrick
Vieira and Emmanuel Petit certainly looked more familiar to Arsenal
fans, who watch Vieira and Petit play together every week in
England, than to the Lyonnais.
</P>
<P>
   France's central defense composed of Marcel Desailly, who is
having a magnificent tournament, and Frank Leboeuf will play
side-by-side for the trendy English club, Chelsea, next season.
France's outside fullbacks on Wednesday, Vincent Candela and
Christian Karembeu, play for clubs in Italy and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   But dispersion does not seem to equate with confusion in this
era. Brazil won the last World Cup with a largely expatriate
lineup; the Danes won the 1992 European Championship with an even
higher percentage of players making fine livings abroad. The Danes
have yet to come close to duplicating that performance.
</P>
<P>
   Their midfield has looked shaky here; they also appear to lack
speed defensively, which is one thing it is increasingly hazardous
to lack in this era where the only breathing room seems to come
down the wings. But in one of the weaker groups in this World Cup,
the Laudrup brothers, Michael and Brian, and their Swedish coach,
Bo Johansson, still had enough savvy to earn a date with Nigeria in
the second round.
</P>
<P>
   The Danes came into Wednesday's match with four points to South
Africa's one. They also came in a with a four-goal edge in goal
differential, which meant that even if Denmark lost by a goal to
the French, South Africa would have to outscore Saudi Arabia by
three goals.
</P>
<P>
   For a short while, it appeared Denmark might have reason to feel
apprehensive. That was after Youri Djorkaeff converted a penalty
kick in the 12th minute, and South Africa took a 1-0 lead against
the Saudis. But in the 42nd minute in Lyon, after Vieira fouled
Michael Laudrup slightly outside the penalty box, Italian referee
Pierluigi Collina signaled for a direct free kick.
</P>
<P>
   Before the French team had time to set up its wall, Laudrup
placed the ball on the ground and quick-kicked it to teammate
Martin Jorgensen, who was already streaking toward the French goal.
Jorgensen was quickly yanked down from behind by Candela, and
Laudrup was soon equalizing with a penalty kick in the same stadium
where he played in 1984 in the European Championships.
</P>
<P>
   It was a delightfully opportunistic play and the first
embarrassing moment for the French team in this tournament. After
the Saudis erased the South African lead by converting a penalty
kick of their own late in the first half, it was time for the Danes
to start preparing for Jay-Jay Okocha and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   But first they would have to surrender the game-winner in the
56th minute to Petit, who slammed home a 22-yard shot after Robert
Pires' and Desailly's shots were blocked.
</P>
<P>
   It was another joyful moment for the 27-year-old Petit, who
played his first Division I match at age 18 in France but seriously
considered quitting soccer three years ago because of personal
problems and creeping ennui.
</P>
<P>
   He has found harmony in England, winning the title last spring
with Arsenal and its French coach Arsene Wenger. This summer, he
wants another title with another French coach, and though Group C
was hardly the Group of Death, it is clear that Petit and his
president Jacques Chirac, who was in attendance in Lyon, have no
reason to think small.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be at the final on July 12 in St. Denis,'' Chirac said.
``Hopefully, I will be able to watch France again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
