<HEADER>
A4862 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-EMAIL-VACATION-AR     06-24 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-EMAIL-VACATION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO TAKE TIME OFF FROM E-MAIL AND SURVIVE
</HEADLINE>
  (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV.: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(See also CIR-EMAIL-IGNORE-ART) 
 (ja) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each summer, Batya Friedman and her husband, Peter Kahn Jr.,
both professors at Colby College in Waterville, Me., take their
daughter Zoe and move to a 670-acre outpost without electricity
five hours northeast of San Francisco. They use solar power to use
their computers to write, but they can get no e-mail. They can use
a phone only twice a month, on trips to town.
</P>
<P>
   If people who are used to reaching her regularly become
frustrated with her absence from the Net, Friedman advises them to
write her an e-mail, print it out, put it in an envelope and put a
stamp on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the summer, each communication I get I do really read,
while the rest of the year I'm overwhelmed by the amount of e-mail
messages I get,'' said Friedman, who teaches computer science, as
she sat in an Oakland, Calif., coffee shop before the family headed
for the woods. ``It's an opportunity for focus, and that's harder
to achieve when you are so accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, America, it is possible to be too plugged in. Studies show
that e-mail is slowing down the workplace, and cellular phones
outnumber across the country. Weren't most people secretly pleased
last month when the malfunctioning Galaxy 4 satellite stifled 50
million pagers, with all the serendipity of a snow day? Just look
for ``information overload'' on your basic Web search engine: one
search turned up 16,590 matches. Even though some technology
advances, like slicker upgrades and faster modems, are welcome, the
acceleration in the rate of information flow has become troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm wondering what the saturation point is of this constant
connectivity,'' said Robert McArthur, vice president for academic
affairs at Colby College. ``There's a great line from John le
Carre, `They're fed up and asking for more.' People are
complaining, but they are putting themselves in the way of more
connection.''
</P>
<P>
   While some chronicle the ill effects of high technology, others
turn their backs on electronic communication _ for a week, a month,
a season _ and reap the benefits. Even Bill Gates, chairman of
Microsoft Corp., regularly takes a ``think week'' off line, coming
back with fresh ideas garnered from reading and discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to synthesize and focus on priorities _ go up to
the 15,000-foot level and really think about directions,'' said a
Microsoft spokeswoman, Mariann Allison. He lets people know he will
not be spending much time on e-mail that week, then reads, talks
and plays with programs and Web site ideas, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Others set aside periods to ignore e-mail and turn off their
cellular phones in the hope of becoming more creative and
productive.
</P>
<P>
   Call it soaring without a Net.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Life Unplugged.
</P>
<P>
   During summers off line, Friedman has edited a book, and Kahn,
who teaches human development, has written one. Also, Friedman
completed a good bit of a successful proposal for a National
Science Foundation grant. The collaborative projects she worked on
while in California were a bit more streamlined, she said, because
they did not go through a huge number of drafts via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are harder to reach, people solve their problems on
their own,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that some of her acquaintances had picked up on her
idea by turning off the ringers on their phones, finding offices
without phone lines or simply slowing the pace at which they reply
to e-mail. The couple have started the Mina Institute in their
summer destination, Covelo, Calif., for the study of technology and
the human relationship with nature.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``People on cell phones are now reachable in their cars on their
commute, and time that used to be down time or transition time is
time used by employers,'' said Gerry Sussman, a professor at the
School of Urban Studies and Planning at Portland State University.
``Electronic communications makes possible a much deeper
penetration for the commercial use of anything,'' he added, citing
unwanted e-mail, phone solicitations made from computer-generated
lists and television advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Crabb, a psychology professor at Penn State University,
has studied the effects of technology on personality, particularly
through a phenomenon he calls ``de-skilling,'' the loss of
competencies like using an abacus, slide rule or paper, long ago
replaced by a calculator, or a dictionary, replaced by a spell
checker. He said the problem can seep over to some children who
lose their social skills when they watch video screens for too
long.
</P>
<P>
   He also has pondered how new technology causes people to do odd
things like using Web cameras that allow exhibitionists to
broadcast performances of their bodily functions on the Internet,
to the delight of voyeurs. The potential for electronically induced
soul sickness alarms him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know from lots of research that when human beings _ and it
doesn't matter from what culture _ don't get enough time to
themselves, they become stressed, sick and they can't function as
well,'' he said. ``There are clear benefits to having private times
and spaces.''
</P>
<P>
   A southern California philosopher, Michael Heim, worries that
the recent mania for information erodes the human capacity for
significance. ``With a mind-set fixed on information, our attention
span shortens,'' he wrote in ``The Metaphysics of Virtual Reality''
(Oxford University Press, 1993). ``We collect fragments. We become
mentally poorer in overall meaning.'' Communication technology has
benefited from that old American maxim: If it's new and hot, it
must be worth having (which goes a long way toward explaining the
success of network television and the sport utility vehicle).
</P>
<P>
   ``The assumption is you need to be connected the way technology
allows you to be connected, 24 hours a day, wherever you are,''
said Friedman. ``But it's not clear that that enhances the quality
of our lives or the productivity of our work lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Microsoft, no enemy of connectivity, encourages some of its
managers to unplug _ temporarily. Andrea Tevlin, an internal
leadership consultant at the huge software company, based in
Redmond, Wash., said she and some of her senior co-workers are
better managers for logging off e-mail occasionally, for four or
five days at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm telling people I am going to be off-line for a week,
I'm saying, `I delegate the responsibility to you to do this,' and
they are empowered,'' she said. ``In a work context when you pull
yourself off-line, you have more time to converse with people,
think conceptually and think about how to make the human system I'm
operating in operate differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning off the technology is also an issue in the realm of
recreation. Nothing beats a toy with lots of buttons to push.
McArthur from Colby College is amused by the gizmos he sees boaters
and sailors buying, such as phones and high-frequency radios that
e-mail transmissions to the middle of the ocean. ``This stuff
coming in seems to be defeating the whole point of going out on
your boat and getting away,'' he said. ``People don't want to get
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Ira Spring, a Seattle-area author of more than 50 guidebooks on
hiking in the Northwest, sees the disadvantages of carrying
cellular phones or global positioning systems into the wilderness _
they too often lose their signals, and hikers may not have the
skills to read a map or compass and find their way out of the
woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you spend your time on a phone when you're out in wild
areas, you're not enjoying the wild areas,'' said Spring, who
doesn't miss his e-mail when he's out of town, and whose co-author,
Harvey Manning, graduated to an electric typewriter from a manual
one just two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Heim, who has written about information fixation, said
humans must do more than unplug, and what they do while unplugged
is more important than the length of time they spend away from
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without rebooting our awareness, it doesn't matter whether we
unplug or not. Technology re-trains our nervous system. It gives us
a pace and tempo,'' he said via e-mail, his preferred medium. ``We
need to actively plug ourselves into the operating system of earth
and sky, mountain and river, inhale and exhale.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
