<HEADLINE>
ULTIMATE PRODUCT PLACEMENT: YOUR FACE BEHIND THE RAY-BANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Mass.)   (af)  
 By BRUCE HEADLAM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Risky Business.'' ``The Blues Brothers.'' ``Top Gun.'' ``Men in
Black.'' What these movies have in common _ other than making
enormous amounts of money _ is that they all featured characters
who wore Ray-Bans, sunglasses made by the eyewear division of the
optical products giant Bausch &AMP; Lomb.
</P>
<P>
   From the Wayfarers made famous by Tom Cruise to the Predators
donned by Tommy Lee Jones and Will Smith, Ray-Ban has been one of
the shrewdest practitioners of product placement, the insertion of
consumer goods into Hollywood movies.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Ray-Ban have taken product placement to its next
level: your face. In April, Ray-Ban introduced a feature on its Web
site (www.rayban.com) called the Virtual Preview, which allows you
to superimpose images of more than 60 Ray-Ban models _ from the
Outdoorsman to the Daddy-O _ over your image.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought, `Wouldn't it be great if consumers could see how
they looked in Ray-Bans while they sit at home in their pajamas?'
'' said Kristi Hughes, Ray-Ban's manager of online marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual Preview isn't quite that easy. You must first send a
front-facing photograph of yourself, which the company will scan
and put on the site for a $3 fee. (If you own a scanner, you can
upload your own image and save the $3.) Once your face is loaded
onto the site, Ray-Ban will send you a password, which you can use
to call up your image after you have downloaded both Shockwave and
Alpha Mania plug-ins. Only then (by this point, you could have
visited every Sunglass Hut in the state) can you use Virtual
Preview.
</P>
<P>
   The interface is routine: Click on the style of sunglasses and
it appears on the bridge of your virtual nose or, if you prefer, on
the nose of one of the models Ray-Ban has provided. You can use the
controls to move the sunglasses up and down _ or from side to side,
if you want to know how your Ray-Bans might look if you fell asleep
wearing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife was always trying to get me in those wraparound
shades,'' said Pat D'Antonio, a corporate events producer in New
York who tried the site. ``I wanted to say to her, `There, I'd look
like an idiot.' '' While he enjoyed seeing his face on line, he
said, the experience hasn't changed his preference for Wayfarers.
</P>
<P>
   What does Virtual Preview mean for shopping on line? Ray-Ban
says it's the first service of its kind in eyewear. In its first
full month, Virtual Preview attracted almost 17,000 visitors; 8,000
of those downloaded the plug-ins but only a few dozen sent photos.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, even if you send in your image, you can't order
sunglasses through the site: Ray-Ban is interested only in driving
traffic to retail outlets. ``Anything that can identify a site or
improve traffic adds some value,'' said Shanta Puchtler, an analyst
with the commerce technology strategies group at Forrester
Research. ``Whether it's really a selling tool, that's another
question.''
</P>
<P>
   What Virtual Preview could be is the first wave of
personalization _ a popular Internet buzzword _ of the online
shopping experience. ``You might see it in soft goods like
clothing,'' Puchtler said. ``There is talk of people entering their
color-me-beautiful palette and having an entire outfit dynamically
displayed.'' If that happens, get the wide-angle camera ready.
After all, can Virtual Khakis be far behind?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
