<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      06-24 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING Q &AMP; A 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DORA GALITZKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dying Dill
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am embarrassed to write this letter, but my frustration has
overcome my embarrassment. Running an active kitchen, I always look
forward to the summer with my window boxes full of herbs _ basil,
parsleys, chives and dill. All of the herbs thrive with the notable
exception of dill. I cannot keep it alive and my salmon suffers. If
you can solve this problem, the level of my cooking will improve
considerably.
</P>
<P>
   A. Make your salmon before the hot weather hits, then switch to
lobster. The true destiny of dill is to produce seed, not sauce.
Were we more classically educated, we would take a clue from its
botanical name, Anethum, derived from the Greek words ano (upward)
and theo (I run). As the cool weather and lengthening days of
spring give way to the heat of summer, dill, along with cilantro
and chervil, suddenly hear their biological clocks ticking loud and
clear. Time to grow tall and reproduce, then die.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arthur O. Tucker, a research professor specializing in herbs
at Delaware State University in Dover, said you can lengthen your
season by planting early, as soon as the night temperatures stay
above 25 degrees Fahrenheit. Seed directly in the ground or
transplant young potted plants, keeping as much growing medium
around the roots as possible because dill resents being
transplanted bare root. Seed again in the early fall for a few more
weeks of fresh dill; it will even withstand light frost. The
compact selections Fernleaf and Bouquet are ideal for pot or window
box culture.
</P>
<P>
   Besieged Hemlock
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have four 10-foot hemlocks in my backyard, and they
developed small clumps of white dots along their branches. I was
told by a local nursery that this is a type of insect egg, and they
recommended I spray with an oil-base solution. I was told the oil
would suffocate the eggs and kill them.
</P>
<P>
   It worked for a couple of weeks, and then the dots reappeared.
Another nursery told me that it was a fungus, and that an Ivory
soap solution would cure the problem. Again, it worked for only a
couple of weeks. Any idea what this could be and how I can get rid
of it permanently? I don't want to lose the hemlocks, and I notice
their growth stops when these white dots are present.
</P>
<P>
   A. Hemlock wooly adelgid is a voracious pest that can kill
hemlocks in a few years if not treated. Those white dots are a
protective waxy substance the insect uses to protect itself and its
eggs. If you were thorough in your spraying, the eggs and insects
are most likely dead, but the waxy mass can persist for months.
</P>
<P>
   There are two generations each year, so even though you should
spray all parts of the tree with horticultural oil or insecticidal
soap as soon as you see them, get into a regular schedule of
spraying once sometime between April and late June and again in
September to catch both generations when they are most vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Dwindling Peaches
</P>
<P>
   Q. Last year my 5-year-old peach tree produced scads of peaches
only to lose them all. I blamed the squirrels at the time. This
spring the tree again produced scads of baby peaches, and when I
saw some of them on the ground I placed netting around the tree. I
am now left with about four or five peaches that still seem to be
growing. What is going on here? Am I lacking something, like
fertilizers? Or is this the nature of the beast? I would like a few
suggestions on how I can raise my peach production.
</P>
<P>
   A. I hope you have apologized to the squirrels. This is the
nature of the beast, although your harvest can be improved.
</P>
<P>
   A mature tree will produce about 500 peaches from its 30,000
blossoms, a ratio of about 1 to 60. That sounds as if there is a
natural conspiracy, and there is, sort of. Fruit may fail to mature
for several reasons. If pollination isn't complete, the seed inside
may not be viable, and the fruit is aborted early.
</P>
<P>
   Win Cowgill, an agricultural agent with Rutgers Cooperative
Extension in Hunterdon County in New Jersey, said cloudy weather
like this spring's forces fruit trees to make a choice: use the
limited sunlight to produce more leaves for photosynthesis, or
produce fruit. Leaves win. And finally, there's the phenomenon
called June drop. From late May into early July, fruit trees
self-thin, dropping enough fruit that the tree can support the
rest, both nutritionally and literally _ overloaded branches can
break.
</P>
<P>
   To get the most from your tree, don't overfeed it (nitrogen
promotes foliage growth, not fruit), keep the ground below the tree
free of weeds, thin the small peaches so there is six to eight
inches between fruit, and prune every March or early April, while
the tree is still dormant, to promote vigorous new growth. Prune
older branches, since peaches fruit on wood that is a year old. Of
course, the easiest way to increase your production is to buy more
trees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to:
</P>
<P>
   Garden Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd Street
</P>
<P>
   New York, N.Y. 10036
</P>
<P>
   or by e-mail to:
</P>
<P>
   gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished
questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILLY-GARDEN-NYT &LR;      06-24 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-GARDEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ENGLISH GARDEN LEARNS TO RELAX 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MAC GRISWOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAYNE, Pa. _ Chris Woods, 45, strode through the entrance court
at Chanticleer, the public garden here, where he has worked since
1983, the last nine years as executive director and chief
horticulturist. ``It's a dream job,'' he said. ``Thirty-one acres,
10 gardens, 10 expert gardeners and an annual maintenance budget of
a million dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Chanticleer, on the Main Line outside Philadelphia, and open to
the public since 1990, was endowed by its own private foundation to
preserve suburban green space. Since 1912, the compound has been
the property of the Rosengartens, philanthropists and
pharmaceutical manufacturers, whose company was eventually acquired
by Merck.
</P>
<P>
   A sensory overload of tender and hardy plants surrounded Woods:
blue agaves and fescues, bananas, striped cannas, rare euphorbias
and the four-foot-wide white-splashed green leaves of variegated
petasites. More down-to-earth than they looked were beautiful
overflowing pots of fleshy tropicals _ Woods' selections from Home
Depot.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the No. 1 retailer of plants in America, I believe,''
he said. ``They call everything `foliage plants' and the price is
$2.99.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods was wearing khaki bush shorts, a Hawaiian shirt and a full
head of brilliant yellow hair _ made blonder, he said, by the
strong American sun. Born in England, Woods is now a U.S. citizen.
Like Auden or Isherwood or Hockney, he is an expatriate who has
flourished flamboyantly in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a degree of optimism here that only people from
large countries can feel, no matter how illusory their sense of
infinite space is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has awesome gardening credentials. He started at Britain's
Royal Botanic Gardens at Kew and later worked at the fantasy
village of Portmeirion, in Wales; Bateman's (Rudyard Kipling's
garden), and Cliveden, the three-centuries-old British estate near
London.
</P>
<P>
   But if Chanticleer is English, ``it's an English garden on
hormones,'' Woods said. His aggressive form of gardening is, he
says, more American than anything else, but he makes good use of
his English training.
</P>
<P>
   This month, a rectangle of flower beds at Chanticleer looks the
way Americans think an English garden SHOULD look: delicate,
evanescent _ a mass of silvery soft pastels. An Arts-and-Craftsy
wooden pergola foams with blush-colored Dr. W. Van Fleet roses. But
delicacy is deceiving here: the cloudlike look will continue
through Philadelphia's muggy summer and bounce back floriferously
in September, since Woods has selected heat- and humidity-resistant
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Totally different is the formal garden surrounding Chanticleer's
main house, whose broad terrace design displays the influence of
Thomas Sears, an early 20th-century Philadelphia landscape
architect. Near the blue swimming pool, twin changing pavilions _
in an arch 1930s style with trelliswork and peaked copper roofs _
look as if Katharine Hepburn might walk out of them straight into
``The Philadelphia Story.''
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was an opportunity for understated conventional
planting, it is here, given all the architectural hoo-ha going on.
Sears' eyebrows would go through his hairline at the sight of
Woods' magnificent all-chartreuse planting along one retaining
wall, which includes yellow dwarf bamboo and mother-in-law's
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Serious horticulture underpins every one of Woods' 10 gardens _
the fabulous ponds rimmed with plantings; the witty Italian Garden,
which Woods calls ``postcard Tuscany'' (a scroll of wheat
punctuated with red cedars posing as cypresses, stretched across a
lawn); the native meadow. His craft is best seen in the Asian Wood.
The magically shadowed understory of a grove of 80-foot-tall native
tulip poplars, sycamores and maples, it may look like an American
woodland to a nongardener, and that is fine with Woods.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a large number of the 618 species and hybrids here were
grown from seed collected by today's consummate plant hunters in
Korea, China and Japan. Many of them are Woods' friends, who send
their rarest discoveries to Chanticleer knowing they will be well
cared for.
</P>
<P>
   Plant lists are stuck unobtrusively, English-style, into a small
stand at the entrance to this garden. There are no plant labels, no
directional signs, no design-oriented or scientific descriptions
mounted on plaques.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberately, there is no effort at Chanticleer to educate
visitors about history, culture or cultivation requirements.
``Chanticleer is a pleasure garden,'' Woods said, ``and my sole
esthetic responsibility is to make people feel good. My experience
with visitors is that they don't come to a garden to learn stuff,
they come to enjoy. You are supposed to feel it is OK just to
admire the plants here, which is somewhat of a radical thing.
Walking is what you do. And sitting.''
</P>
<P>
   He proudly pointed out that Chanticleer offers no regularly
scheduled educational activities, and added, ``We don't have a gift
shop, weddings, concerts, theater, dogs, smoking, sports, a
restaurant, picnic tables or picnics.''
</P>
<P>
   As Woods walked around the gardens , he said: ``I think American
and English public horticulture is meant to be intimidating. I'm
trying to create an intimate institution, one small enough for
visitors to be able to ask questions of our gardeners, who are
always available on open days. I don't want a visitor to feel
processed. It shouldn't be like peristalsis.''
</P>
<P>
   His determination to make visitors at Chanticleer relax and use
their eyes underscores how most public horticulture emphasizes
education over experience. Like art museums that must mount
blockbuster shows, public gardens are in a jam: attendance figures
and programs meant to appeal to every demographic sector help bring
in the money that keeps them afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Since Chanticleer doesn't rely on admissions for maintenance,
Woods is free to be a maverick. ``Why must we call something `The
Romantic Garden?''' he asked. ``Why `The Garden of Tranquillity?'
Why not a `Divorce Garden,' or a `Garden for the Grumpy?'''
</P>
<P>
   All around him there was romance and tranquillity that needed no
label: sheets of yellow foxgloves cascading down an embankment; the
half-closed eyelids and sleeping smile of a stone face, the work of
Marcia Donahue, a sculptor in Berkeley, Calif., dreaming at the
foot of a pyramid carved from a living false cypress. It was enough
to make the thirstiest horticultural self-improver just give up and
enjoy it all.
</P>
<P>
   Chanticleer is open Wednesday to Saturday, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.,
from April 1 to Oct. 31. There is a $5 admission for adults; free
for those 16 and under.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne, Pa., is about two hours from New York City. Information
is available at (610) 687-4163.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
