<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     06-24 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Thursday, June 24. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SUMMIT (Xian, China) _ President Clinton's aerial caravan
arrives Thursday for a visit eagerly sought by his Chinese hosts as
long-overdue recognition of China's status as a major global power.
The success of the visit will be measured not in the number of
agreements reached or documents signed but in whether Clinton and
President Jiang Zemin can subtly redefine the relationship between
the two nations and show a dynamic and diverse China to an America
deeply uneasy about the conduct and intentions of that rising
nation. By John M. Broder. (With map/graphic, showing Clinton's
itinerary.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-GOALS (Beijing) _ China would love President Clinton to
announce this week that Taiwan, which China considers a renegade
province, will get no more American weapons or that the economic
and military sanctions the United States imposed after the bloody
1989 crackdown on student-led demonstration in Tiananmen Square
will be lifted. In truth, as the leaders here already know, China
will get few if any of the policy changes it wants during the state
visit that begins on Thursday. But China's leaders and people are
ecstatic about the visit, which is already being hailed here as a
great step forward in diplomatic relations. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ZHAO (Shanghai) _ In a striking act of political defiance,
Zhao Ziyang, China's former Communist Party chief, challenged the
nation's leaders to use President Clinton's visit as an opportunity
to admit that the Tiananmen crackdown in 1989 was an immense
political blunder. Zhao, the silvery-haired ex-leader who has been
under house arrest since May, 1989, made his case in a letter to
the Party's Central Committee by arguing that only in a reversal of
the official verdict on the crushing of 1989's student movement
will the government be able to retain any legitimacy with its
people. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Junik, Yugoslvia) _ Richard Holbrooke met with
members of the Kosovo Liberation Army on Wednesday, calling the
Kosovo crisis ``explosive,'' and comparing it to the early stages
of the Bosnian and Vietnam conflicts, after the rebel commander
dismissed his calls for a cease-fire and a return to the province's
former autonomous status. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   SALVADOR-NUNS (Miami) _ Newly released State Department
documents dealing with the killing of four American churchwomen in
El Salvador in 1980 indicate that members of the Salvadoran
military high command suspected that one of their number ordered
the killings and informed American diplomats of that belief,
casting doubt on years of official assertions by both governments
that no senior officers were involved in the slayings. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH (Washington) _ House Republicans unveiled a
long-awaited proposal to define patients' rights and set uniform
nationwide standards for health insurance, especially health
maintenance organizations. The health insurance industry
immediately denounced the proposal, saying it would increase costs
for consumers. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AFFIRM (Washington) _ The White House announced a new
affirmative action policy under which minority-owned businesses
will be given an advantage when they compete for government
contracts in industries where surveys show they are
underrepresented but not in industries where they seem to have a
fair share of the market. The policy was devised to meet the terms
of a Supreme Court decision in 1995 that strictly limited the
justification and scope of government programs that grant
preferences based on race or sex. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ In an amendment offered to the
spending bill for the Agriculture Department, the House of
Representatives on Wednesday voted 223-202 to effectively bar the
Food and Drug Administration from approving an abortion pill. The
amendment, offered by Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., would ban the FDA
from using federal money to regulate or approve a drug that
chemically induces abortion. It would apply to the drug known as RU
486, the French abortion pill also known as mifepristone. By
Katharine Q. Seelye. (Early summary from wires.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-DROPOUTS _ The high-tech field, the fastest growing of
the nation's economy, has become so voracious in its hiring that
computer science departments across the country are losing graduate
students and, in growing numbers, undergraduates to an industry
fueled by vast sums of money. Many experts fear that fundamental
research will decline and that the next generation of American
computer scientists will be stunted. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-TCI _ AT&AMP;T Corp., the nation's largest telephone company,
said it had agreed to acquire Tele-Communications Inc., the No. 2
cable television provider, for $31.8 billion in stock in a deal
that is the most far-reaching product yet of the 1996 congressional
deregulation of the telecommunications industry. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUIT _ To Microsoft Corp., a federal appeals court
ruling in the company's favor on Tuesday was a gratifying triumph
of sweeping import for its long-running antitrust battle with the
government. To the Justice Department and 20 states pitted against
Microsoft, it was merely a bump in the road as they head to court
again in September with a broader antitrust case against the
company. Yet antitrust experts said Wednesday that the
split-decision by the three-judge panel _ a majority opinion
written by a conservative and partial dissent opinion from a
liberal _ was both a big win for Microsoft and a reflection of
wider debate over how antitrust doctrine should apply to
high-technology industries. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
