<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4910 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-INFANT-SOFTWARE-N     06-24 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-INFANT-SOFTWARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER AND ME, AND BABY MAKES 3 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ga.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monday, 11:41 p.m.: At this moment, the baby officially turns 9
months old, ready to take advantage of a new trend: software for
the exceedingly young.
</P>
<P>
   My husband examines the packaging on the Jump Start Baby CD-ROM
(ages 9 to 24 months), which I dismiss as a marketing gimmick to
entrap overzealous, achievement-driven parents.
</P>
<P>
   How, after all, can a baby use a computer? By Tuesday morning,
my husband agrees that no ``average'' baby can use a computer. But
what if Clementine isn't just average? What if she is one of those
prodigies? There must be plenty of genius infants and toddlers out
there. Otherwise, why introduce products like this into the
marketplace? We can't afford not to know.
</P>
<P>
   I phone Amy Bruckman, an assistant professor of computing at the
Georgia Institute of Technology who studies how children interact
with computers. While she is unwilling to comment on Clementine's
IQ, Ms. Bruckman confirms that products aimed at encouraging young
children to use computers are a new and growing segment of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trend is not just about software,'' Ms. Bruckman says.
``I am starting to see specialized hardware for very young
children. I saw something a few weeks ago that looks like a plastic
toolbox and fits over a keyboard. A child uses it to interact with
the computer.'' She is referring to Hasbro Interactive's Tonka
Workshop CD-ROM Playset, still in development.
</P>
<P>
   I realize that if I do not introduce infant-enhancing software
now to Clementine, she could be totally unprepared in a few months
to graduate to toddler-facilitating hardware. My husband and I
agree that the only sensible thing to do is to conduct a controlled
experiment to see how well the baby tolerates exposure to software.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, 8 a.m.: Seated on my lap facing the computer, the
subject appears relaxed and interested as my husband installs Jump
Start Baby. He coos, ``Look, Clembo, Daddy has a CD-ROM. Can you
say C-D-ROM?''
</P>
<P>
   The subject grins toothily. On screen, an animated, cuddly brown
teddy bear appears, crooning: ``Say hello to the sun! It's time to
have some fun.'' The subject laughs aloud (good), lunges for the
keyboard and strikes it with her left fist (good!), an action that
somehow transports the bear to a farm scene, where it stands in
front of a red barn (slightly confusing). The bear is now wearing a
floppy hat similar to those that have proved so flattering to an
aging Walter Matthau.
</P>
<P>
   The subject laughs. ``She likes it,'' my husband says, relieved.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, 8:01 a.m.: The subject appears to be losing interest in
Jump Start Baby. She arches her back, bucks wildly while rolling
her eyes and accidentally strikes the keyboard with a tiny (but
meaty) foot, an action that prompts the bear to say, ruefully,
``Good night.'' Eventually, the screen goes black. Infant attempts
to suck on mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, 8:04 a.m.: My husband looks up from the instructional
pamphlet that accompanied the software (``Very young children can
create and control the fun themselves!'') to announce worriedly,
``It says here that even an infant as young as 9 months old may
remain engaged for as long as 10 minutes before losing interest.''
</P>
<P>
   In horror, we stare at the subject, who lasted a mere 60
seconds. Does she have an unusually short attention span? The
subject inserts her left foot into her mouth and blows spit bubbles
onto her big toe. She appears unconcerned.
</P>
<P>
   The program we glimpsed so briefly has eight different games,
each aimed at promoting a specific kind of development. For
instance, Down on the Farm is supposed to develop listening skills
and music appreciation through its songs and rhymes about farm
animals.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the games we never actually got to see. Puzzle
Time, for instance, ``helps children make sense of their perceptual
world.'' And Dress Teddy ``builds vocabulary of body parts, clothes
and environmental conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want her to build her vocabulary of body parts,'' I say. I
want it badly.
</P>
<P>
   I phone Knowledge Adventure, the company that manufactures Jump
Start Baby, and am given the phone number of a psychologist,
Corinne Rupert, who has reviewed and critiqued the new product.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, noon: Dr. Rupert, a specialist in child development,
tries to reassure me by pointing out that children as young as
Clementine can vary widely in their rates of development. The
important thing, Dr. Rupert says, is not to measure your baby's
technological prowess against some mythical ideal. The important
thing is to relax.
</P>
<P>
   I'm losing patience. ``Just tell me how to lengthen her
attention span,'' I snap.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rupert considers that. ``Does she grab for the keyboard?''
she asks.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, yes! She grabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does she watch the monitor?'' Dr. Rupert says. ``Yes? Then I
would start with something more simple. Maybe a screen saver
activity, like dancing balls or squiggly lines, to start helping
her be able to watch and follow shapes.''
</P>
<P>
   I say thank you, but I feel torn almost as soon as I hang up. My
current determination to subject the baby to a software encounter
is contradictory to a belief I held just as firmly in the days when
my oldest daughter was an infant.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, I tried to shield my first baby from the influences of
most technology _ TVs, computers, her father's Water Pik _ on the
theory that__ Well, I cannot remember the reason. I believe _
firmly _ that it had something to do with the dehumanizing effects
of technology. Or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   Now I know this to be false. Technology has given us wireless
baby monitors and microwave ovens to warm bottles and the odorless
diaper pail. ``No studies have been done, but I certainly don't see
any harm in having very young children play at the computer,''
agrees Ms. Bruckman, at the Georgia Institute of Technology. ``On
the other side of the coin, I don't see any harm in not doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The more important question is this: Is it fun? The answer, for
Clementine right now, is yes, absolutely. For about 60 seconds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4914 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-UNREAL-NYT &LR;      06-24 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-UNREAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER GAMES: HOLDING THE REINS OF REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(ja) 
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Myst was a reason to buy a multimedia PC, Unreal is the
killer application for 3-D accelerator cards. The game (published
by GT Interactive, $49.95) will run on a Pentium 166, and with no
hardware frills, it is an engaging first-person shooter comparable
to Quake. But on a 200-megahertz machine with a 3Dfx Voodoo 2
board? Cue the choir. The tornado has plucked you out of Kansas and
you have crash-landed in Oz.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, according to Unreal's back story, you are a prisoner
whose spaceship has crashed on a mysterious planet en route to a
penal colony. After exiting the wreckage, you emerge into a world
filled with rippling waters, breathtaking architecture, cavernous
mines and a menagerie of gothic beasts. Ninety percent of the fauna
are trying to kill you. But that seems a small price to pay for
such breathtaking beauty. Overhead, cirrus clouds race across the
sky, casting shadows on the ground. A bird of prey circles in the
distance. An alien rabbit (one of the few nonhomicidal creatures on
this planet) scampers on the grass.
</P>
<P>
   It's a huge world. If you fire your gun across a chasm, the
bullet takes a long time to hit the other side. If you drop
something off a cliff, it takes a long time to smash on the ground.
And you hear it a split second after you see it _ light travels
faster than sound. Sound acts the way it should in this world. It
bounces differently indoors and outdoors, in tunnels, over water
and off stone walls, taking into account the number of obstructions
in a room.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what it says on the box, this world isn't unreal. It's
hyperreal. Everything you see and hear has been sharpened.
Crystallized. Heightened. Torch flickers seem more flamelike than
real fire. Water is more watery. Footsteps are crisper. Large
exhaust fans are backlighted with just the right amount of dust in
the room so the blades cast perfect cinematic shadows.
</P>
<P>
   And every so often, even though this is supposed to be virtual
reality, you'll see an artifact of film. A lens flare. Coronas
around the lamps. The ghosts of another medium. When the action
changes, the lighting changes the way it would in a film, and the
soundtrack changes. If you're walking down a corridor and the music
suddenly stops, you know something really bad is about to happen.
That's the difference between real and Unreal: great
postproduction. If you could hire Industrial Light and Magic to
render your perceptions, that is how you would see the world.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to play with reality in film, you have to be a
director. If you want to tinker with it in Unreal, all you have to
do is hit the Options menu. You control the horizontal. You control
the vertical. You control most aspects of the space-time continuum,
as well as the number and relative intelligence of your enemies.
The most interesting thing to toggle is game speed, which you can
set anywhere from turbo (for the die-hard twitch fiends) to slow
motion (for people whose reflexes are less than razor sharp). If
you slow the action, the software automatically adds frames to
smooth the animation. If you play in extremely slow motion with
tons of monsters, the whole game plays out like a John Woo movie.
</P>
<P>
   When you are through playing in this world, you can build your
own. The people who programmed this game left all their
construction tools on the disk in a kit called Unreal Ed, the
Unreal level editor. It used to be that if you wanted to build your
own levels of a PC game, you had to be a programmer. Now all you
have to do is point and click.
</P>
<P>
   It's the holodeck, more or less. You start with a
three-dimensional grid. You import geometric shapes and give them
properties _ height, radius, translucency and reflectiveness _ then
make them solid or not, visible or not. You have more than 3,000
textures to choose from as you cast texture onto the surfaces, or
you can use your own. Stone. Water. Lava. Sky. Add light, in any
permutation of color, saturation and brightness. All of it is
rendered on the fly. If you move a torch around in a room, you will
see the light on the walls change in real time.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of heart-pounding action in Unreal. But making
the sky is what really leaves you breathless. You turn on the
stars, put the planets in place, set the clouds in motion. You hang
the moon (A little to the right. . . . No, that's too far. . . .
Just a bit higher. . . . There. . . . Perfect).
</P>
<P>
   Cue the sun.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, you have two options. You can populate your
planet with artificially intelligent monsters. Or you can invite
your friends and associates over for a multiplayer online death
match. Judging from the proliferating number of Unreal Web sites,
the latter appears to be a more popular option. Because the only
thing more fun than wreaking havoc on a gorgeous alien planet is
wreaking havoc on your friends on a planet that you have personally
built.
</P>
<P>
   At unreal.org, unrealnation.com or any of the big online game
servers, new pieces of this world are being uploaded, downloaded
and swapped daily. Players are pulling together Unreal instant
messaging lists. New monsters are being born (in one home-brewed
version of the game, the alien bunnies have become deadly
attackers, a la Monty Python).
</P>
<P>
   People are giving one another construction tips, renovation
advice and suggestions about the feng shui of virtual buildings.
It's like a cyberpunk version of ``This Old House.'' You can pick
up new objects for your game space or see how other people are
using texture and lighting effects. In 10 years, Martha Stewart
will be selling wallpaper this way. We will all be able to fly
through her well-pruned gardens. With automatic weapons. Death
match at the Stewart manse.
</P>
<P>
   We have the technology. Dare to dream.
</P>
<P>
   (E-mail address: Herz(AT)nytimes.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
