<HEADLINE>
MILD CLEANERS ARE BEST FOR A COMPUTER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (jt)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I've been reluctant to wipe off my computer screen when it
gets dusty, fearing that I might damage sensitive equipment. What
can I use to clean it? A. Many computer monitors have an antiglare
coating on the glass surface of the screen. Strong cleaning fluids,
mildly abrasive cloths or excessive rubbing _ while great for
removing sticky fingerprints _ can scratch or dissolve the
protective coating.
</P>
<P>
   Most computer stores sell pads, sprays and fluids designed for
use on video-display screens. Some products, while a little
pricier, include both a prepackaged wet pad (soaked in a
combination cleaning and antistatic solution) and a lint-free dry
pad (to remove stubborn spots and leave the screen free of
streaks).
</P>
<P>
   In a pinch (financial or otherwise), you can clean your
monitor's screen with a soft, lint-free cloth moistened with water
or a mild glass cleaner. Paper towels may leave lint all over the
glass, so avoid using them. If you use a spray bottle, spray the
liquid onto the cloth, not directly onto the screen. Gently wipe
the screen until it is dry and then enjoy the view.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com or postal mail to Questions, Circuits,
The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959.
This column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
