<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FORFALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME OF THE ANTICIPATED BIG BOOKS OF FALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Stephanopoulos dishes dirt, Nicholas Evans follows up
``The Horse Whisperer,'' and Danielle Steel takes a risk by writing
about the death of her 19-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   What else is in store for book lovers this fall? For starters,
new works from established authors Philip Roth, Ellen Gilchrist,
Paul Theroux and John Edgar Wideman.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh yeah. Dame Agatha Christie returns from the dead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE QUALITY BOOKS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Philip Roth's ``American Pastoral'' won the lion's share of last
year's fiction awards. He returns in October with ``I Married a
Communist,'' (Houghton Mifflin, $26), the wrenching tale of a
decent man whose past political life returns to haunt him during
the McCarthy witch hunts.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Gilchrist's ``Flight of Angels'' (Little, Brown, $24,
September) is a collection of finely crafted short stories that
ought to put her in the hunt for Pulitzer consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Theroux's apparent equal love of travel and himself has
rendered some of his recent work unpalatable, though never
unreadable. ``Sir Vidia's Shadow'' (Houghton Mifflin, $24, October)
recounts the author's long friendship with fellow scribe V.S.
Naipaul. If Theroux is on his game, this could be the winter's best
nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   Because his writing is so dense, multifaceted and apparently
convoluted, John Edgar Wideman is not destined for the upper
reaches of any bestseller lists. But the man is a literary master.
``Two Cities'' (Houghton Mifflin, $24, September) tracks a woman's
life through tragedy and subsequent emotional rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE BEST SELLERS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Three years after ``The Horse Whisperer,'' Nicholas Evans is
``ba-a-ack'' with ``The Loop'' (Delacorte, $25.95, September),
another modern-day Western yarn about a seemingly unsuited man and
woman finding each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winter in Arcadia'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15.95, October) is
more heartwarming (or stomach-turning, depending on your
disposition) short fiction from Richard Paul Evans, the fella who
wrote ``The Christmas Box'' trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   The most curious publishing event is a doubleheader from
Danielle Steel. In November, fans can savor ``Mirror Image''
(Delacorte, $26.95), a typical Steel potboiler about two sisters
who are ... guess-whats of each other. But first, Steel offers
``His Bright Light'' (Delacorte, $25, September), a painfully
personal account of the life and death of Nick Traina, her
19-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG NAMES &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Cornwell has sold gazillions of her noirish Kay
Scarpetta mysteries. For Christmas she offers ``Scarpetta's Winter
Table'' (Putnam, $18.95), an 80-page novella about one Dec. 25th in
the lives of Scarpetta, niece Lucy and pal/sparring partner Pete
Marino. No case to solve as such, just a brief look at the three
chugging eggnog.
</P>
<P>
   Robert B. Parker's back, but not with old reliable Spenser.
``Trouble in Paradise'' (Putnam, $22.95, September) is the second
time around for new lead character Jesse Stone. Spenser could whip
this guy with both hands tied behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   The newest by James Patterson is ``When the Wind Blows''
(Little, Brown, $25, November), action-packed enough to please his
most ardent fans.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Francis takes us back to the racetrack with ``Field of
Thirteen'' (Putnam, $24.95, September), a short-story collection.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a quarter-century, gonzo journalist Hunter S.
Thompson has been working ``The Rum Diaries'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
$25, October), purportedly based on his early experiences as a
free-lance writer based in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SLEEPERS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Cathleen Schine's ``The Evolution of Jane'' (Houghton Mifflin,
$24, October) describes the estrangement between cousins. ``The
Love Letters'' gained Schine some attention; perhaps ``Evolution''
will be her breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Life for a Life'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23, August) may
introduce lots more readers to Ernest Hill. It's the story of an
inner-city father who ends up befriending the teen-aged murderer of
his son.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FICTION &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Dame Agatha Christie departed this mortal coil in 1976, but she
has a ``new'' book coming out in September anyway. ``Black Coffee''
(St. Martin's Press, $22.95) was originally presented 58 years ago
as a three-act play featuring Hercule Poirot. London-based theater
critic Charles Osborne has adapted the stage drama for book format.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Mosley made his mark with the Easy Rawlins mystery
series. Now he offers ``Blue Light'' (Little, Brown, $23, October),
drama-cum-sci fi about a mysterious cosmic beam that ``quickens''
DNA for some California residents in the mid-'60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hill Country'' (Longstreet, $25, October) is the sequel to
Janice Woods Windle's unexpected bestseller ``True Women.'' Meet
Laura Hoge Woods, who, in her 90s, advises LBJ on how to end the
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' own Kinky Friedman weighs in with ``Blast From the Past''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $23, September), with the semifictional lead
character Kinky hitting his head and reliving previous escapades.
</P>
<P>
   James D. Hall introduces us to forensic photographer Alexandra
Rafferty in ``Body Language'' (St. Martin's, $24, September). Hall
has never quite reached the upper sales echelon. Maybe his new lead
character will get him there.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Monkee Michael Nesmith's ``The Long, Sandy Hair of Neftoon
Zamora'' (St. Martin's, $24.95, November) is not expected to rival
last year's ``Cold Mountain'' as a critically acclaimed first
novel. Plus, Davy and Mickey and Peter aren't in it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NONFICTION &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Some of us thought we already knew more about Cher than we
really wanted or needed to, but the venerable chanteuse wants to
bare all in print, not just in skimpy dresses. ``The First Time''
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) hits bookstores in November, one month
after Little, Brown publishes ``Family Outing'' ($24), the memoir
of Chastity Bono, a lesbian who works for gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Berg's ``Max Perkins: Editor of Genius'' was wonderful.
In ``Lindbergh'' (Putnam, $30, September), he turns his attention
to one of America's most troubled, yet revered, heroes.
</P>
<P>
   James Chase profiles ``Acheson: The Secretary of State Who
Created the American World'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $30, August). Dean
Acheson's world stage machinations still affect us, and Chase
reminds us why and how.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Guralnick's ``Last Train to Memphis'' is considered the
definitive portrait of Elvis Presley's early years. Now he's back
with ``Careless Love'' (Little, Brown, $27.95, December),
delineating The King's sad middle age.
</P>
<P>
   Who better to dish dirt than former Clinton adviser George
Stephanopoulos? His ``All Too Human'' (Little, Brown, $27.95,
November) promises ``sharp portraits'' of Bill and Hill, VP Al Gore
and Gen. Colin Powell, among soon-to-be-offended others.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
