<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS25-TAKE     06-24 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS25-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (Eds: In two takes.)
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I never miss a Rita Hayworth or Betty Grable movie on TV, but
I seem to have missed the announcement of a new postmaster general.
Do you have any information about this person?
</P>
<P>
   A: William J. Henderson, 50, was named the 71st postmaster
general of the United States effective May 12. Henderson is the
first postal employee to have the top U.S. Postal Service position
in 12 years. A graduate of the University of North Carolina, he
began his postal career as a management trainee in 1972. Over the
years, he has been a postmaster in Memphis and Stockton, Calif.;
field division manager/postmaster of the USPS's Greensboro, N.C.,
division; Southern Region director of employee and labor relations;
and chief marketing officer and senior vice president. Henderson
replaced Marvin Runyon, who resigned after six years to return to
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the saying ``Here's mud in your eye!''
when toasting someone?
</P>
<P>
   A: The toast originally was made in the muddy trenches of World
War I, or in the cafes where English and American soldiers spent
their furloughs trying to forget them, according to the Facts on
File Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My 5-year-old grandson and I were wondering: When was the
first cartoon series shown on TV, and what was it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Telecomics originated as a syndicated series in 1949.
Picked up by NBC and renamed The NBC Comics, it made its network
debut Sept. 18, 1950. Featured characters included Brother Goose,
Joey and Jug, Johnny and Mr. Do-Right, Kid Champion and Space
Barton. The series was canceled March 30, 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please settle a minor skirmish in my family. Are the people
who broadcast the weather onThe Weather Channel all meteorologists,
or are they simply paid announcers?
</P>
<P>
   A: Perhaps you could say they're hybrids. When The Weather
Channel first started, it used ``degreed meteorologists'' almost
exclusively, said spokeswoman Kathy Lane. Now, however, other
people also are hired. ``They have to have a passion for weather,
and be good communicators,'' she said. A lot of the people you see
have degrees in science, journalism or broadcasting, and some come
from the armed forces ``where meteorology plays a big role,'' Lane
added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why were the ``doughboys'' of World War I called that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although the nickname doughboy for U.S. infantrymen was
popularized in World War I, it was part of Army slang for many
years before that, according to the Morris Dictionary of Word and
Phrase Origins. Elizabeth Custer, widow of Gen. George (``Custer's
Last Stand'') Custer, explained it this way in her memoirs of the
general: ``A doughboy was a small, round doughnut. Early in the
Civil War, the term was applied to the large, globular brass
buttons on the infantry uniform, from which it passed by natural
transition to the soldiers themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How big is Ted Turner's ranch in New Mexico? How does it
compare in size to the entire state? And how does it compare to
something most of us would be familiar with, such as the Great
Smoky Mountains National Park?
</P>
<P>
   A: Turner has several ranches in New Mexico: Vermejo, 578,000
acres; Ladder, 155,000; and Armendaris, 350,000. Total, 1,083,000
acres. The state covers 77,672,960 acres (121,364 square miles).
The Great Smoky Mountains National Park covers 520,269 acres.
Turner also owns ranches in Montana and Nebraska. The total acreage
of all eight ranches in the West, according to the New York Times,
is 1.29 million. That would be about 2,015 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The shroud of Turin is back in the news because of its last
public showing until 2000. Have any miracles ever been attributed
to it?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you mean ``miracles'' in the sense of sick or injured
people being cured by viewing or touching the shroud, which many
believe is Christ's burial cloth, Q&AMP;A found no documented evidence.
But the very fact that the shroud was saved in April 1997 from
flames that heavily damaged the 15th century San Giovanni Cathedral
in Turin, Italy, was considered miraculous by no less than Pope
John Paul II. After the fire, in which a Turin firefighter salvaged
a silver box containing the shroud, the pope was quoted as saying:
``A miracle. A holy icon venerated by so many over the centuries
has again been saved from the flames.'' The firefighter who smashed
through four layers of bulletproof glass protecting the shroud also
claimed something miraculous had happened by saying God gave him
the strength to wield his sledgehammer. The shroud _ which some
experts, using carbon dating, have declared isn't old enough to
have been woven at the time of Jesus' death _ also survived at
least two other attempts to set fire to the Turin cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some utility companies ask for customers' Social Security
numbers when they apply for service. When I first got my Social
Security number in 1959, the card had this statement printed on it:
Not to be used for identification purposes. What's the position
now?
</P>
<P>
   A: While the Social Security Administration is aware of concerns
about the increasing uses of Social Security numbers for client
identification and recordkeeping purposes, it still warns people
not to use their Social Security card as an identification card.
And while several other government agencies are permitted by law to
use Social Security numbers _ such as banks and other financial
institutions using the numbers to report interest earned to the
Internal Revenue Service _ there's no law either authorizing or
prohibiting their use, the agency says.
</P>
<P>
   If it makes you feel better, Social Security insists that
providing numbers to private companies, government agencies or
anyone else who asks for them doesnot give them access to your
Social Security records. The privacy of an individual's records is
guaranteed, the agency says, unless disclosure to another
government agency is required by law, or the information is needed
to conduct Social Security or other government health or welfare
programs. And you always have the option of refusing to provide the
number to a business or other enterprise. However, that may mean
doing without the purchase or service for which your number was
requested.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard that Vice President Al Gore referred to Michael
Jordan as Michael Jackson, but I didn't see anything about it in
the papers. Is that true?
</P>
<P>
   A: The verbal air ball indeed did happen. And no, we won't
mention any similar Dan Quayle-isms. Here's how Gore's remarks went
when he was speaking at a Washington function, as reported by CNN's
``Inside Politics'':
</P>
<P>
   ``That was quite a win. I tell you, that Michael Jackson is
unbelievable. Isn't he _ just unbelievable. Three plays in 20
seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Commentator Judy Woodruff followed a video clip of the incident
by saying, ``Well, that probably was just a slip of the tongue, but
it is doubtful that Al Gore impressed anybody, at an event
promoting the importance of fathers, with his knowledge of
basketball's greatest star. The vice president apparently confused
Michael Jordan with another M.J. known for songs, not slam dunks.''
And no word about whether Gore ever apologized to anybody about the
miscue.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read an explanation about how coffee is decaffeinated. What
is the process for taking caffeine out of cola?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no such thing as ``decaffeinated cola,'' said Chris
Rosenbloom, spokeswoman for the American Dietetic Association and a
nutritionist and professor at Georgia State University. When colas
(soft drinks) are first produced, they are virtually
``caffeine-free.'' Caffeine is added later ``as part of the flavor
profile,'' in the words of the National Soft Drink Association. Of
course there is such a thing as ``caffine-free'' cola for people
who wish to restrict their caffeine intake. But it isn't cola that
has had caffeine added to it, and then has been processsed again to
take the caffine back out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
