<HEADER>
A4994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAND-PAINTED-WALLPAPE     06-24 1590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAND-PAINTED-WALLPAPER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART SCHOOL GRADUATE RE-INVENTS THE LOOK OF WALLPAPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It took 12 years for Elizabeth Dow to perfect a
method of hand-painting wallpapers so subtly that they appear to
glow from within, like a letter held up to a lamp.
</P>
<P>
   But don't ask her how she did it. Everything about the process _
from the recipe cards for the pigments of her imagination to her
glues and the shape of the drying fans _ is a secret guarded as
zealously as the formula for Chanel No. 5. Employees, even summer
interns, are required to sign nondisclosure agreements; patents are
pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you find something that works using materials that anyone
can buy, you have an edge that's proprietary,'' said Ms. Dow, 40,
(Hint: she uses a squeegee.) Ms. Dow trained as an artist but fell
in love with the business of making wallpaper when she was in her
20s. Ms. Dow has a knack for perfecting the way things get done;
she says she inherited it from her grandfather, an inventor of
conveyor belts for eggs, among other creations.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder she's protective: Ms. Dow is re-inventing the look of
wallpaper. Hers are a far cry from the lilac bouquets running up
and down grandma's walls. Whether it's a sage parchment, a
pewter-colored paint that's hand-rubbed into rice paper or a
collage of translucent squares each dyed individually and arrayed
on a field of muted green, Ms. Dow's papers have a modern integrity
that's anything but mechanistic. Irregularities, the slight
slippages of paper on paper and the uneven edges showing a human
hand at work bestow a sensual minimalism perfectly in tune with
today's more-of-less interiors.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dow is riding the crest of wallpaper's bouyant new appeal.
While the industry overall has remained steady at $2 billion in
sales a year, the boutique end of the wallpaper business _ where
most of the papers are screened, printed, blocked or painted by
hand _ is expanding rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the increased interest in fashion for the home,''
said Marita Thomas, the editor of The Wallpaper, the trade
newsletter. The Imperial Home Decor Group, the Ohio company that
says it's the largest wallcovering business in the world, reported
a 200 percent increase in the sale of some papers in its top-end
Van Luit line ($55 to $90 a roll), with overall sales jumping from
$200 million to $400 million between 1996 and 1998. Stark Carpets,
a premier rug manufacturer, just introduced its first line of
wallpapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an `old lady' thing anymore,'' said Ms. Dow, whose
hand-painted wallpapers hang in the homes of such un-grandmotherly
types as Michael Ovitz, Steve Winn, Calvin Klein and Paul Simon, as
well as in the boardroom of the Andy Warhol Foundation and a
high-roller suite at Caesar's Palace in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The translucency of color she achieves has a hand-washed
effect that's especially beautiful,'' said Jamie Drake, the
interior designer who is now working on Madonna's Manhattan
apartment. ``There aren't many choices when it comes to the luxury
end of modern wallpapers. The texture and geometric patterning
really set hers apart.''
</P>
<P>
   High-end often means high-priced, comparable to buying art for
the walls. Ms. Dow's labor-intensive papers, made at her workshop
in SoHo and sold in showrooms across the country, are priced from
$29 to $80 a yard. To paper the walls of an 18-by-20-foot room with
a $48-a-yard paper would cost about $4,500, even before the
installers arrive. ``This is the couture end of wallpapers, said
Robert Bitter, the co-president of Scalamandre, who added that
handmade wallpapers provide a measure of instant gratification for
those who are enthusiastic about custom painting but have a hard
time envisioning what a mural will look like. ``Most people want to
see exactly what they're going to get ahead of time,'' Bitter said.
``It's easier to choose a wallpaper pattern from a sample book and
get it installed without all the mess and the fumes of a major
paint job.''
</P>
<P>
   There's high-end wallpaper, and then there's extreme wallpaper.
Sanderson sells William Morris' ``Acanthus'' pattern, at $2,300 per
roll, using the original handblocks used by Morris, the founding
father of the Arts and Crafts Movement in England. Each panel
requires 20 blocks and 20 days to print.
</P>
<P>
   Wallpaper has a long history of ups and downs in popularity. In
the 1880s, wallpapers were all the rage. Morris created
hand-blocked prints with dense foliage patterns that are still
favorites for stairways and powder rooms. Edith Wharton loathed
wallpaper. ``It was well for the future of house decoration when
medical science declared itself against the use of wallpaper,''
Miss Wharton wrote in ``The Decoration of Houses.'' Ever the
aristocrat, she favored frescoes or tapestries interspersed between
bois de Versailles paneling.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1950s, wallpapers had been relegated to kitchens and
bathrooms, where anti-ornamental modernists allowed themselves to
indulge in a few loopy atomic-style patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional interiors have always laid on the chintz patterns,
especially when papering second and third bedrooms. Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis coveted exquisitely expensive scenic papers by
Zuber from France and caused an uproar when she had a rare example
removed from an historic house in Maryland and installed in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   On a tour of Ms. Dow's SoHo factory-atelier, some 30 employees _
many of them recent art-school graduates _ can be seen bent over
long tables, elbows high as they rub in the paint on hundreds of
rolls of wallpaper a week. Ms. Dow herself has traded in her
painter's overalls for a black-and-white working artist look.
</P>
<P>
   From an office cluttered with sample rolls, cartons of ferns
from Nepal (used in a collage paper) and cold cups of coffee, she
contemplated luxury wallpaper's recent comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you paint directly onto the wall, it looks hard,'' she
said. ``Something is lacking in terms of depth and warmth of color,
and people feel that.'' In keeping with the ``last gasp of the
millennium'' penchant for authenticity (or its appearance), she
said, ``no one wants an effect that's heavy-handed anymore or that
looks like it was trowled on,'' adding, ``It's too theatrical.'' At
the same time, thanks to the influence of globally focused
interior-design magazines and style books, people are ready and
eager to explore beyond the all-white wall.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dow's own distinctive sense of color is as strong and clear
as a signature on a will. She developed it over five neck-breaking
years as a restoration painter, working on Victorian museum houses.
``It was extremely challenging,'' Ms. Dow said, recalling her
immersion course in complementary shades. ``I was constantly mixing
colors, sometimes 50 a day.''
</P>
<P>
   At her own weekend house, built last year in East Hampton, N.Y.,
Ms. Dow has used her favorite palette of muted colors _ saturated
dusky shades of blue, green and clay gray that one might imagine
existing at the edge of a desert in spring bloom. Surprisingly, the
single-story house is not plastered room after room with wallpaper.
First, there aren't really any rooms, apart from two bedrooms at
each end of a long rectangular central block that houses the living
room, dining space, kitchen and library alcove. It has 12-foot
ceilings and French doors instead of windows making it feel more
like an Austrian villa than a weekend house.
</P>
<P>
   The mottled blue, green and concrete-colored hues of the Italian
floor tiles used throughout the house (and flowing outside to the
courtyard) bring to mind handfuls of dried pigment scattered on the
ground. ``There's a dusty quality to them that's very soft and
natural-looking,'' Ms. Dow said, comparing their random colorations
to her own collage papers.
</P>
<P>
   For the living room walls, she chose art works, like Ellen
Carey's Polaroid print negative that's over six feet tall and
colorless. ``I deal with wallpaper 48 hours a day,'' Ms. Dow said.
``I wanted to give myself a break, a creative respite. Art is my
first love.''
</P>
<P>
   The bedrooms are different. Her own is papered in Champagne
Truffle ($48 per yard), a paper with a slight glimmer, a
sophisticated update on gold-leaf. How it's made is typical of a
Dow wallpaper: a copper-colored base coat is hand-rubbed into rice
paper, followed with a second layer of tinted pearlized paint
applied with a squeegee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is spontaneity to get the effect of a colorfield
painting,'' said Ms. Dow, who advises her staff ``to go rough with
the squeegee.''
</P>
<P>
   The guest bedroom features one of Ms. Dow's signature collage
papers, called Stone's Throw ($52 a yard). The base paint is the
same sail-cloth white, an exterior paint from Benjamin Moore, used
on the walls of the main space. Ms. Dow then layered on a grid of
squares, each one hand-torn and tinted, then glued to the wall and
spaced an eighth of an inch apart. ``People try to make
associations: `It's like stone, it's like tile,''' she said. ``But
it's really just all about paper and the unique way that paper
absorbs light and color. It creates feelings. It's enveloping. It
has an almost structural strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallpaper has been good to Ms. Dow, who has seen her business
double every year for the past five. For her 40th birthday last
year she bought herself a 1970 Mercedes 280SL convertible. She
chose it for its color, naturally, a shimmering agate green.
Perhaps you'll see it next year _ on Madonna's walls.
</P>
</TEXT>
