<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CHINA-ODDITIES-$AD     06-24 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CHINA-ODDITIES-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MAINSTREAM CHINA IS NO MAIN STREET USA
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON-0625; CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV25.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A typical Chinese urbanite bicycles down a frenetic
rush hour street -- small daughter tucked into a backseat and
packages filling the basket in front. Ignoring the chaos, he chats
into the cell phone clamped to his ear.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is among the legion of arresting oddities that will
punctuate the trip through China of President Bill Clinton and his
entourage.
</P>
<P>
   Such culture clashes are no more unusual than those presented to
Chinese visiting America -- for example, when they hunt vainly
through hotel rooms for the terry cloth slippers and thermos of hot
water that are ever -present in Chinese hotels.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, visitors have been coming to China to absorb the
brilliant colors, pungent scents and tinkling sounds of a land that
many in the West expected to find ``backward.'' But even in the
13th Century Marco Polo found China filled with marvels, much as
travelers do today.
</P>
<P>
   Cell phones, for example, seem to be more pervasive in Chinese
cities than in most any sophisticated American metropolis. People
in taxis, on bicycles, walking down the street, riding a bus,
sitting in restaurants or shopping in book stores, food stores or
shoe stores can be found engaged in intense conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Mobile phones are so popular because they are both cheaper and
more accessible than permanent telephone connections in the home.
Regular phone service reaches a mere 8 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Another peculiarity to visiting Americans may be the white
cotton gloves worn by many taxi drivers, elevator attendants,
cyclists and street sweepers worried about soiling their hands.
Some women wear gloves when simply walking down the street. In the
extremely health-conscious Chinese society such attention to dust
and bacteria makes perfectly good sense. (The elbow-length gloves
some women cyclists wear, however, are a defense against the sun,
not dirt.)
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Clinton group well may sight any number
of bare baby bottoms in wandering town and country. Little ones at
the wobbly-toddling stage often are dressed for outings sans
diaper, in pants that are slit up the back. Parents carry a cloth
to catch the leakage if necessary, but often don't bother if a
semi-discreet corner or open space presents itself.
</P>
<P>
   The practice may get complicated, for example on a train. A
mother occasionally can be seen sprinting down the aisle, baby at
arms' length, heading toward the restroom (commonly known as the
water closet, or ``WC'') at the end of the car.
</P>
<P>
   Queries about this habit have produced the explanation that,
yes, Chinese do use diapers, both disposable and cloth. But some
parents sometimes prefer to let their babies experience the natural
freedom of diaperless days, and no one seems to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that helps explain the gloves.
</P>
<P>
   A pervasive and vibrant aspect of Chinese culture is the color
red. It is thought to be lucky, so spices up the scenery
everywhere. Red lanterns big and small hang outside restaurants and
shops. Brides who wear the same billowy white dresses seen
everywhere from Macon to Moscow traditionally have a bit of red
tucked away somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton goes ahead with his planned visit to the Shanghai
Stock Exchange, he even will find the big board listing stocks on
the rise in red, while those declining are lit in green -- exactly
the opposite of Western exchanges. An official explained that the
first Shanghai exchange followed the Western color pattern, but it
made no sense to the clientele. When the new exchange opened last
year the board was made right, Chinese-style.
</P>
<P>
   Americans dining in China also will encounter some opposites. In
a typical Chinese restaurant in China, the soup will come at the
end of the meal and the rice will be the penultimate arrival --
served after the last hot dish has been placed on the table (but
before the soup).
</P>
<P>
   Here the rice and soup are considered filler food, traditionally
served toward the end so as not to detract from the more important
meat or fish dishes. Back when meat was scarce and expensive, the
rice and soup were backups to fill the stomach after the good stuff
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Rice also is seen as counteracting the buzz that a diner
drinking beer or wine is expecting from the alcohol, thus
compounding the reasons for serving it toward the end of the meal.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Optional trim. Story can end here.)
</P>
<P>
   So much for phenomena of sight and taste. There is also an
unusual sound sensation that can be found at least in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Walking down the street around dusk, the stroller may hear a
rippling, calliope melody quite distinct from the pop music blaring
from open-front stores to attract young customers. It may take a
while to find the source of the flute-like music, but perhaps
following the nose will help.
</P>
<P>
   The pleasant tune can be traced to a big white truck temporarily
double-parked in the street while workers fan out to commercial
establishments to pick up the results of the day's work. Much
preferable to the horn-honking that Beijing's drivers lavishly
utilize to announce their presence, it is the municipality's most
civilized effort to alert pedestrians and drivers that the garbage
truck is coming.
</P>
<P>
   For clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
