<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5016 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-REAL-ESTATE-775&AMP;AD     06-24 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REAL-ESTATE-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TIMEOUT FOR HOME SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's a kind of hush all over New York _ New York's
residential real-estate market, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Whether hush or hiccup or breathing spell _ all terms used by
brokers to describe the market since the beginning of June _ the
city's biggest companies agree on one thing: The frenzy has abated,
at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   While the market usually loses momentum in summer, many real
estate brokers and agents say that this June is different from last
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no lull last year,'' said Peter Marra, president of
William B. May Real Estate, a company with 135 agents in Manhattan
and Brooklyn. ``There is a lull right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark Halstead, managing partner at Halstead Property Co., said
accepted offers for this month are 10 percent below last June's,
following a steady rise in the last five months. He called the
current market ``a kind of correction, like the stock market
makes.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Rogers, managing director at Douglas Elliman, the city's
largest residential firm, said he felt the market was at a plateau,
calling that ``a healthier thing, when things sell in six months
rather than six days.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Wild West atmosphere of the first quarter of
this year _ when bidding wars were common, and so were broken deals
_ he said: ``The quantum leap has happened; the catching-up from
the recession has happened. My sense is we're going to enter a
pretty stable market.''
</P>
<P>
   The brokers say the slowdown _ whether permanent or temporary _
is caused by several things, including the overpricing of
apartments (and a dearth of good ones), a reluctance among banks to
affirm the high prices with their appraisals, and a nervousness
among buyers about the stock market and the economic troubles in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Some contend that the main reason is a lack of appealing
apartments in all price ranges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great spring market _ many more listings than last
year _ and everything got cleaned out,'' said Barbara Corcoran,
chairman of Corcoran Group. ``And there is definitely buyer
resistance. The high prices scare the hell out of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Bader, chief executive of Skyscraper Mortgage, the city's
largest mortgage brokerage company, said the residential
real-estate market was ``stagnating'' _ but not for lack of buyers,
the usual reason for a summertime lull.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got mortgage preapproval applications stacked up like
cordwood on our desks,'' he said. ``People are panting to buy
something, but they say they can't find anything. They may have
sold their own apartment, but they can't find something to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a common complaint. Brokers interviewed this week said
that many sellers, reacting to reports about the frenzy, have
overpriced their apartments.
</P>
<P>
   As Kay Brover, head of Douglas Elliman's West Side office,
explained it: ``An apartment sells in a building for $750,000. The
next apartment would normally come on for $775,000. But now the
seller wants to price it for $895,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Even realistically priced condos and co-ops can linger, agents
say. Apartments that a few months ago would have sold in a day or
two, with multiple bids, have not yet been sold, or are being sold
with normal bargaining. Ms. Brover said she also knew of several
buyers who were backing out of deals. One who had already signed a
contract forfeited his $175,000 down payment on a $1.75 million
condominium on the West Side last week. Brokers blamed cold feet.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Peters, president of Ashforth Warburg Real Estate,
said his sales staff met Monday to discuss the current market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agents seemed to be equally divided between those who
believe the market is just taking a breath and those who say
everywhere they go, the brokers are worrying that prices may have
peaked,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While some brokers said they would not have complete statistics
until the end of June _ and others said they compiled them only by
quarter _ Halstead said he keeps ``elaborate records from the time
there is an accepted offer on a property.'' And the number of
accepted offers for the first two weeks of June was ``about 10
percent off the same time last year.'' (He said bids were off more
on the West Side than the East Side.)
</P>
<P>
   Although Halstead described the slowdown as a hiccup, agents at
his company said they had been advised to counsel sellers to reduce
the prices of exclusive listings that don't sell within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the brokers interviewed also said that banks seem to
have decided that the market is overheated and are therefore more
reluctant to make loans. ``The banks are tightening their belts,''
Ms. Corcoran wrote last week in a memo to her 300 agents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although an apartment at 222 Riverside Drive went to contract
for $950,000, the bank's appraiser valued it at only $900,000, said
Pam Tomlin, a Corcoran agent. The deal might have fallen through,
she said, if the buyer hadn't agreed to cover half the purchase
price with his own money.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Fitting, another agent, said Chase Manhattan Bank had
refused to give a mortgage for a $575,000 apartment in Trump
Palace. Ms. Fitting said on Tuesday that her customers were
applying to another bank.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Satkiewicz, an executive vice president of Mitchell,
Maxwell &AMP; Jackson, the city's largest real-estate appraiser, said
that despite efforts to ``give the banks four, five and six
comparable sales _ rather than the standard three _ we're still
getting twice as many of our appraisals kicked back by the banks
for more justification than we did even a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Although neither the Douglas Elliman agency nor the Corcoran
Group keeps statistics on accepted offers _ the first commitment by
buyer and seller on a piece of real estate _ Corcoran produced
statistics on the number of responses to real-estate advertisements
that it placed in the Sunday classified section of The New York
Times. Although 35 percent more ads were placed during the first
two weeks of June, 33 percent fewer people called about them than
in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these bidding wars have frightened not only the
million-dollar investor but the studio and one-bedroom buyers,
too,'' Ms. Corcoran said.
</P>
<P>
   Like all the other brokers interviewed, she was quick to point
out that the events that have made would-be buyers nervous _ things
like bidding wars and the troubles in Asia _ have only slowed the
market, not crippled it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still signing lots of contracts,'' she said, ``so
certainly not all of them are scared off. But there's no longer the
fever pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Dexter Guerrieri, president of Vandenberg Real Estate, a small
Upper West Side company that specializes in town houses, said that
his company's real-estate advertisements ``don't pull in as many
customers'' as they did in the spring and that the company
``doesn't have as many buyers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're still making deals at full asking prices,'' he said,
reeling off a handful of accepted offers. ``I'm not a bit
worried.''
</P>
</TEXT>
