<HEADER>
A5032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      06-24 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, June 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hazy, hot and humid weather will dominate the southern
two-thirds of the country from the western Plains to the Atlantic
Seaboard. High pressure over the Southeast will promote sunshine
and record heat in Georgia and the Carolinas while a wedge of very
hot air pushes northward into the Plains.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary between a more comfortable air mass over central
and eastern Canada and the steamy air over much of the nation will
stretch from Maine to South Dakota. Showers and clusters of
thunderstorms will dampen many sections from Minnesota to western
New England.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest rain is likely around the northern Great Lakes
where a jet-stream disturbance passes overhead. A few
thundershowers are expected to form in the Appalachians because of
the uneven heating of the terrain. A narrow line of thunderstorms
should also develop between Chicago and Kansas City during the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A disorganized disturbance over the Gulf of Mexico will
contribute more clouds to the western Gulf Coast along with bands
of thundershowers that will move slowly toward the northwest. The
hot, dry weather will persist in northern Florida, though isolated
afternoon thunderstorms will occur.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably cool air will cover the Northwest as brisk onshore
winds push chilly, moist air inland from the North Pacific. Showers
will be common from Washington and Oregon to Montana and Wyoming.
Snow levels in the northern Cascades will drop to near 5,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest will be sunny and seasonable. Morning low clouds
will continue to obscure much of the California coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Heat Index
</P>
<P>
   Warnings for heat-index values between 100 and 110 degrees were
issued in parts of the Southeast on Tuesday. Also called the
apparent temperature, the heat index is the warm-season analog to
the wind-chill index. When the air has a high moisture content,
cooling by evaporation from the skin is reduced and the stress on
the human body is increased. Therefore, when the humidity is above
normal for a given temperature, the heat index is higher than the
actual air temperature. However, the heat index does not take into
account variables such as wind or sunshine, which also can
contribute to heat stress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
