<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5041 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-LEGAL-0624-     06-24 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-LEGAL-0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT RULING COULD AFFECT LARGER CASE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno said Wednesday that an
appeals court setback would not derail the Justice Department's
landmark antitrust suit against Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still think we can proceed, and we'll do so,'' Reno told
reporters the day after an appeals court panel's ruling in a
related case undermined a key government position in its broad
lawsuit charging the software giant with illegal monopolistic
practices.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a three-judge panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals for
the District of Columbia struck down a temporary injunction that
had stopped Microsoft from requiring manufacturers to include its
Internet Explorer browsing software on computers that operate on
Microsoft's Windows 95 system.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal analysts called that ruling a major blow to the
Justice Department's broader charges that Microsoft abuses its
market dominance to stifle competition. The major antitrust case,
set for trial in September, focuses on Microsoft's ``bundling'' of
the upgraded Windows 98 operating system and Internet Explorer
browser.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court ruling could ``cut the legs out from under the
Justice Department'' on a key part of the major case, said Robert
Litan, director of economic studies for the Brookings Institution
and a former deputy attorney general in the antitrust division of
the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be very discouraging from their point of view,'' he
said, adding that it appeared that the government was ``slam-dunked
by the court.''
</P>
<P>
   While the ruling was on a narrow issue, the language of the
three-judge panel was ``very broad,'' Litan said. ``They
essentially said that judges shouldn't be in the business of
designing software.''
</P>
<P>
   Litan said the message is unlikely to be missed by U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who issued the injunction that was
overturned and who is scheduled to preside over the antitrust
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The ``government has to put a brave face on this,'' but the
decision does ``cast a large shadow on the upcoming case,'' said
William Kovacic, a former Federal Trade Commission official who
teaches antitrust law at George Mason University in Fairfax, Va.
</P>
<P>
   There are ``three legs'' to the Justice Department lawsuit, he
said. One contention is that Microsoft has entered restrictive
contracts with computer makers. That is not affected by the appeals
decision. The second allegation is that Microsoft tried to entice
its browser rival, Netscape, into a market division. That leg is
also not crippled by the decision, said Kovacic.
</P>
<P>
   However, the third leg is that Microsoft tried to use
``bundling'' of technology to extend its monopoly to other segments
of the market. ``This third leg is the most important part of the
case,'' said Kovacic. And this is the part that the appeals panel
dealt with specifically and sweepingly.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Justice Department vowed Wednesday to press ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence in the case we have filed,'' Assistant
Attorney General Joel Klein, head of the antitrust division, told
reporters after testifying in a congressional hearing on telephone
company mergers.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said the Justice Department is considering its legal
options, which include an appeal of the panel's ruling, and is not
negotiating a settlement with Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday's decision involves the consent decree,'' Klein
said. ``The case we have filed in federal court is under the
Sherman Act. We think that the case is strong.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Microsoft general counsel William Neukom said the
appeals court ruling has ``important consequences'' and is ``very
much a vindication of our business practices and our legal
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft could use the ruling as the basis to file a motion
seeking a dismissal or summary judgment in the broader antitrust
lawsuit _ especially of the portions dealing with the browser
bundling, said Litan. If that happened, the Justice Department
would almost certainly appeal the panel's ruling to protect against
the possiblity of the case being thrown out, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
