<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRILLIN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FAMILY MAN': GRACEFUL, FUNNY ESSAYS ON THE USUAL TOPICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here, in the 16 funny essays composing ``Family Man,'' is Calvin
Trillin, the humorist, on the subjects of raising children and
staying married. His advice is succinct. On children: ``Try to get
one that doesn't spit up. Otherwise you're on your own.'' On
finding a long-term wife: ``Wander into the right party.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, ``Handing out advice on family matters is not my
game,'' he writes. ``For most people, the process of rearing
children is so all-encompassing that there isn't any way to adhere
to any policy that doesn't coincide with their natural way of doing
things. Getting advice on the best way to bring up children is like
getting advice on the best way to breathe; sooner or later, you're
probably going to forget it and go back to your regular old
in-and-out.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of giving advice, Trillin uses these essays to knit
together his many anecdotes and routines on the subject of family,
some of which have appeared in different form in The New Yorker and
other magazines. These subjects touch on, for instance, using your
family as material for your writing. His rules here are: not during
the sensitive teen-age years and no embarrassing stuff unless
you're sure you're Dostoyevsky. Otherwise, as he puts it to his
wife: ``I hope you're not under the impression that what you just
said was off the record, Alice. Nobody mentioned anything about
deep background or not for attribution or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Or his subject might be the genetic differences between men and
women, which occasions him to write about roller coasters,
asparagus, movies, eating alone, ``what's au courant in clothes,''
lobsters, James Carville and Mary Matalin, cooking, scenery, day
people and night people and his belief ``that in the spring female
human beings get a deep biological urge to replace the living-room
slipcovers.''
</P>
<P>
   Or he will write about pets. It's not that he hates cats. That
would be prejudice. ``What might be fair to say is that I have
never met a cat I liked.'' It seems to him ``that many of the
attributes cat fanciers apply to cats _ independence, the ability
to care for themselves, an admirable absence of obsequiousness
toward human beings _ can be claimed for periwinkles as well, and
in a much more manageable package.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what his topic, the boundaries between them are
seamless. Some of his most graceful writing is in his transitions.
His timing and delivery are perfect. He doesn't ring an off-key
note. In ``Nuptials du Jour,'' he will be pondering the subject of
gay marriages, his only problem with them being, ``At the end of a
gay Jewish wedding ceremony, how would you decide who stomps on the
glass?''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly you find yourself attending the birth of the Trillins'
first child, Abigail, prepared for by the Lamaze method. The author
has accepted the obstetrician's invitation to change into scrubs
and join him for delivery. ``Having heeded his warning not to leave
my wallet in the locker with the rest of my clothing, I was holding
it in my hand as we entered the delivery room; scrubs have no
pockets. Then I realized that the elastic in the pants I'd been
provided had about given out _ I suppose it makes sense to use the
older outfits for new fathers for a while, before throwing them
away _ so I had to hold up my pants with the other hand. As I
neared the delivery table, Alice reached out to take my hand, as we
had seen so many women do in the movies shown in natural childbirth
classes. I had no hand available.''
</P>
<P>
   Trillin's secret, besides his command of prose, is that he knows
exactly who he is. The family joke may be, as Abigail puts it, that
he's ``a simple lad from the Midwest'' married to ``a fancy Eastern
girl.'' But he comes from Kansas City in the ``show me'' state.
He's a thoroughly urban person with insatiable curiosity and
contempt for pretense, especially in himself. He writes for The
Nation only because it's ``the closest magazine to my house.'' He
summers in Nova Scotia, where neighbors speak a distinctive, not
particularly grammatical form of English. He plans to hold his
daughters' wedding receptions in the Triple Eight Palace, ``a huge
dim sum parlor on the second floor of a Chinese shopping mall under
the Manhattan Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course the mask of humor Trillin wears also serves as his
armor, which bars us from seeing any sadness in his life.
Occasional bad news does get out: Alice's bout with lung cancer,
his own heart bypass surgery. But the visor quickly slams shut. He
writes that after his operation, the surgeon advised him and his
family how often he was to nap and how he was to avoid long periods
at his desk. ``We all nodded soberly. When he had finished, I tried
to look both brave and prudent. Then Abigail said, `I hate to say
it, Daddy, but it's hard to see just how that differs from your
regular routine.'''
</P>
<P>
   One is left to wonder if the mask ever slips, if he's ever
caught off guard, if he ever blunders clumsily. But it's no use. On
a first-grade outing when a boy who is holding his hand suddenly
asks him, ``Are you divorced yet?'' he shoots right back, ``Not
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there a less than entertaining moment reading these essays? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Man''
</P>
<P>
   By Calvin Trillin
</P>
<P>
   184 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $20.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
