<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ON COMPUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ill.)   (af)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Web Surf With Disney  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disney Online, a three-year-old unit intent on bringing all the
fluff and pink that is Disney to cyberspace, Wednesday opened
Disney's Internet Guide, a Web search and directory site for
children and families.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed Dig (www.dig.com), the new site is designed to compete
with Yahooligans, Yahoo's popular kids' directory. And in a sign
that the company is wasting no time capitalizing on its new
partnership with Infoseek, the site will also soon serve as the
kids' directory on Infoseek.
</P>
<P>
   Like Yahooligans, Dig contains eight wholesome categories, like
Animals and the Outdoors, Stories and Comics, Games and Toys, and
Arts and Entertainment. Each of the Dig categories, which,
according to the company, ``collectively represent what Disney
Online considers to be the best of the Web for kids and families,''
have been picked by Dig team members and will be reviewed every few
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really comes back to our overall Disney Online mission, to
provide a gateway to the Internet,'' said the president of Disney
Online, Richard Wolpert. Wolpert said Disney Online had been
working on development of the new site for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Disney Online has lagged behind its competition. According to a
rankings list maintained by Media Metrix, Disney Online barely
registers among the top 20 Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The new partnership with Infoseek, in which Disney acquired a 43
percent stake in Infoseek, is expected to help, but analysts are
skeptical of Disney's overall prospects of displacing others as a
so-called portal site _ the Web site Internet users see when they
first log on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're using Yahoo now, particularly if you're an adult,
there's no way you're going to switch to Infoseek and Disney, not
in this life,'' said Keith Benjamin, an Internet analyst with
BancAmerica Robertson Stephens. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A link to the new site will also be available on the Disney home
page (www.disney.com). Dig is Disney's fourth Web site. In addition
to Disney.com, the company maintains Family.com and Disney's Blast
Online, a paid subscription service for children. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On-Line Medical Aid for China &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Timed to coincide with President Clinton's visit to China this
week, American and Chinese doctors plan to perform a live
consultation over the Internet Thursday night to discuss two
severely ill children in China. It will be the first real-time
medical consultation between China and the United States over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The event is less a practical medical move than a show of
diplomacy. Members of the Clinton Cabinet are expected to be on
hand with doctors at the Medical University in Xian, a city in
central China, as they consult pediatricians at the Lucile Packard
Children's Hospital at Stanford University about a 12-year-old girl
with inflammation of the heart and a newborn with brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   The consultation will take place using standard Internet tools
for audio and video, as well as a ``white board'' feature that
enables participants to share text, images and sketches.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there's direct interplay, you get more from it,'' said
Dr. David Teitel, chief of pediatric cardiology at the University
of California at San Francisco, who will be participating. ``They
can respond, and you can respond more quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been other experiments with telemedicine in China,
relying mainly on e-mail among doctors. Several hospitals in China,
including Peking Union Medical College Hospital, have acquired
sophisticated video-based teleconferencing systems, but such
systems are not available for the rest of China's population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the world has satellite links to Beijing, which is
not a very real test of medicine to China,'' said John Reuling,
director of information technologies at Stanford University's
School of Medicine. Reuling said the group had chosen to use widely
available Internet tools rather than state-of-the-art
video-conferencing systems because they wanted to focus on what was
actually available to doctors in Chinese cities outside the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   High-performance computers provided by Sun Microsystems will be
left in Xian so further exchanges between doctors from both
countries can take place. The consultation was organized by Bridge
to Asia, a nonprofit group. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Popular Target: Family Trees
</P>
<P>
   The Web is an obvious destination for the genealogically
inclined, and its popularity among family tree makers was
underscored earlier this week when AT&AMP;T released the results of a
survey: nearly one-third of those responding said they had used the
Internet to seek family roots.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of more than 5,400 AT&AMP;T Worldnet Service
subscribers, one out of every 12 respondents said they had a
family-tree Web page. Of those who did not, nearly 70 percent said
they would like to create one.
</P>
<P>
   April Helm of Savoy, Ill., a professional genealogist who, with
her husband, Matthew, maintains several Web sites on genealogy,
pointed to the convenience of the Web as the principal reason for
the explosion in interest in genealogy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are finding the Internet is a good tool for researching
their family because it saves them from having to leave their house
to find records,'' Ms. Helm said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that AT&AMP;T released its survey, it announced a
genealogy page on the AT&AMP;T Worldnet Service Web site
(www.att.net/find/ genealogy). The AT&AMP;T Genealogy Page features
links to genealogy resources and family-tree software. The company
has hired the Helmses as its resident genealogy experts. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Crackdown on Piracy &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To fight software piracy, long the bane of the industry, the
Software Publishers Association plans to get tough by pressing
charges more often and publicizing a rogues' gallery.
</P>
<P>
   A report released last week by the association and the Business
Software Alliance showed that in 1997, the industry lost $11.4
billion worldwide to producers of illegal copies of business
software applications.
</P>
<P>
   Four in every 10 copies of business applications are bootlegged
versions, according to the report. The number does not include
software for general consumer use.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the association has settled about 90 percent of cases
with fines and confidentiality agreements. But leniency apparently
hasn't worked. ``There has to be zero tolerance when it comes to
software piracy,'' said David Phelps, an association spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Some countries have improved, the report says. Five years ago in
Europe, 9 out of 10 software programs were pirated, but that number
has dropped to 5 out of 10. Piracy is worst in Bulgaria, China,
Indonesia and Vietnam. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SELECTIVE SCREEN Just what the Web needs _ another filtering
program. But this two-in-one product looks like a good one. SOS
Kidproof, from Sterling Strategic Solutions, filters inappropriate
Web sites and protects PCs from accidental or intentional
tampering. And the company says it can distinguish between a Web
site containing ``breast of duck'' and one with questionable
pictures. The $29.95 package is expected to be in retail stores
next month. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAKING ROOM ON LINE According to a report issued jointly earlier
this week by two research outfits, International Data Corp. and
Relevant Knowledge, the number of home Web users in the United
States will increase to nearly 102 million by 2002 from roughly 30
million.
</P>
<P>
   IDC reports that the percentage of those users who purchase
items on line will grow to almost 50 percent from 36 percent, with
overall spending increasing to more than $54 billion in 2002 from
$4.3 billion in 1997. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SHOP TALK Speaking of shopping, Compare.net (www.compare.net),
the online shopping guide, announced deals with Classifieds 2000
and Deja News, the Internet discussion group search and archive
service, to allow its shoppers to search classified ads and get
access to discussion groups for peer opinions on products like
washing machines and used Corvettes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
