<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM STRIKE A QUESTION OF PRIORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do the autoworkers on strike against General Motors Corp.
understand that Americans aren't compelled to buy GM's cars and
trucks? Do they care? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the grievances that sparked the strike, the United Auto
Workers leadership must be aware that it is risking significant
long-term damage to GM's much-needed customer loyalty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Union members and UAW executives say the strike is about saving
jobs, but such logic is difficult to follow. While it's true that
UAW membership has shrunk substantially over the past quarter of a
century, it's also true that this is a result of rising production
efficiency throughout the industry forced by mounting competitive
pressures globally. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the industry today is much different than it was a
generation ago, the GM arm of the UAW insists on pretending the
world is as it was in 1950s and 1960s. That was before the advent
of global competition, an era when Detroit's Big 3 could give labor
whatever it wanted and pass the increased labor costs along to the
buyer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In today's car-buying world there are no doubt still some
die-hard GM loyalists who will purchase nothing but GM products.
There aren't enough of them, however, to carry the day. GM's
viability depends on offering better vehicles at competitive
prices, which won't be possible without labor and management
working in harmony to achieve that goal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Given GM's labor relations record in recent years, it would be
easy to blame management's apparent inability to reach a happy
middle-ground with the UAW. Neither side should get hung up on who
is right and wrong, though. They should focus instead on what's
realistically possible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most average car buyers, it's safe to say, don't have an
emotional stake in a labor dispute involving some of the highest
paid blue-collar workers in American society. They just want to be
able to purchase the best quality vehicle at the lowest possible
price. If they can't get it from GM, there are a dozen or so other
producers willing to fill their needs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So why aren't the many GM workers idled unwillingly putting more
pressure on the striking few to do whatever it takes to get
everyone back to work? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One theory emerging among labor economists following the auto
industry is that labor's intransigence is a demographic thing. This
line of thinking holds that since the average age of GM workers is
close to 50, UAW members aren't all that worried about the
company's long-term prospects. If things go sour, the old-timers
can grab their ``30-and-out'' retirement package and live off the
fat of their pension plan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the younger union members are left holding the bag, well,
that's just tough luck, according to those leaning toward the
cynical view. It's never a good idea to generalize, but it's an
easy theory to buy into. Ford and Chrysler are getting stronger,
while GM's generation-long erosion of its market share is
undoubtedly a continuing sign of weakness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, union members and their negotiators seem
determined in this instance to pursue tactics designed to further
weaken their company. The only winners will be the older GM
production workers. The losers will be the younger union members,
the white-collar workforce, the shareholders and management. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's as though UAW generals are fighting the last war and the
troops are more than willing to sacrifice themselves in battles
that can't be won. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
