<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WILKINSON-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MONTY' ROLE GIVES `RIDE' ACTOR A TASTE OF STARDOM AFTER THREE
DECADES OF WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Wilkinson can divide his life into P.M. and A.M.
</P>
<P>
   That's short for ``pre `Monty' '' and ``after `Monty.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Playing the role of Gerald, the unemployed foundry manager who
teaches his former employees how to disrobe for fun, profit and
self-respect, Wilkinson was a major factor in the success of ``The
Full Monty,'' the little British film that has earned almost $250
million worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, ``Monty'' also has wrought some changes in the
life of this journeyman English actor, who has been in town filming
Ang Lee's Civil War film, ``Ride With the Devil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly made a difference,'' Wilkinson, 50, said of
``Monty'' during a recent interview at a local hotel. ``Oddly
enough, it was brought home to me right here in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Westport the other night having dinner, and a glass
of wine appeared on my table. I told the waiter I hadn't ordered
it, and he pointed to a group of people at another table and said
they had ordered it for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it's one thing to be recognized in London, where I've
been doing television and theater for years. But here in the
American Midwest?''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson, who in person looks 10 years younger and 20 pounds
lighter than the characters he portrays on film, has wasted little
time in capitalizing on his ``Monty'' fame by taking roles in
American movies. He recently completed a film with martial-arts
star Jackie Chan shot in Los Angeles, and after ``Ride'' he'll be
doing a movie in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me says I could have used this 15 years ago,'' he
said. ``But you go with what you have. That's just the way it
panned out.''
</P>
<P>
   Though born in England, Wilkinson spent much of his childhood in
Canada, where his parents hoped to buy a farm but ended up working
in an aluminum foundry in British Columbia. The family returned to
England when Tom was 11.
</P>
<P>
   Though he describes his mother as ``a gifted amateur actress,''
Wilkinson wasn't exposed to his future profession until his last
year of secondary school. ``I was inveigled into directing a play _
Ionesco's `The Bald Soprano' _ and immediately I knew what to do,
how it all worked. I suddenly realized this was my metier.''
</P>
<P>
   He attended the Royal Academy of Dramatic Arts and then launched
a stage career that saw him working all over Britain. Gradually he
began getting roles in British television shows, many of which have
been broadcast in the United States by PBS. In one of the popular
``Prime Suspect'' entries, for example, Wilkinson played a police
bureaucrat who made life difficult for the show's heroine, played
by Helen Mirren.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '60s were a really wonderful time,'' Wilkinson said of his
early years as an actor. ``It marked the emergence of the Beatles
and Bob Dylan, who were poets as well as musicians, and I realized
that a life in the performing arts was not just something done by
other people. We were all radicals in those days, earning 6 pounds
a week and squatting in vacant buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to drift. I could always get work. I only needed enough
for a bottle of wine and a pack of cigarettes.''
</P>
<P>
   Marriage and two children, now ages 6 and 10, put a crimp in
that lifestyle. Four years ago Wilkinson decided to concentrate on
feature films.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant turning down lots of theater and TV work in
Britain. It was almost like starting over again.''
</P>
<P>
   But it paid off. He appeared in ``Priest,'' ``Smilla's Sense of
Snow,'' ``The Ghost and the Darkness,'' ``Oscar &AMP; Lucinda'' and Ang
Lee's ``Sense and Sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon he will be seen in ``Wilde,'' portraying the real-life
Marquess of Queensberry, the certifiable sadist (and boxing
enthusiast) largely responsible for the imprisonment of gay
playwright Oscar Wilde on morals charges. That film is to open July
3 at the Fine Arts Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   ``His grasp on sanity was not as firm as it could have been,''
Wilkinson said of the marquess, ``which is a characteristic of
inbred nobility. And the purest-bred people in the world are the
British aristocracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to find the point of view of your character, no
matter how repellent he may seem. You can't act a bad guy. You
can't portray him as simply horrible. What he does may be horrible,
but as an actor you've got to see things through his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Iago in `Othello,' whom I've never played but always
wanted to. His motives are never really explained, and as an actor
you have to decide just what those motives are. You must justify
his actions.''
</P>
<P>
   In a few weeks Wilkinson can be seen in ``The Governess,''
playing an early 18th-century gentleman inventor who falls in love
with his children's governess (played by ``Good Will Hunting'' star
Minnie Driver).
</P>
<P>
   He also has a featured role in the upcoming ``Shakespeare in
Love,'' starring Gwyneth Paltrow as the young woman who inspires
Shakespeare's sonnets.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Ride With the Devil'' Wilkinson plays Orton Brown, a
Missouri farmer who allows wounded Confederate guerrillas to
recuperate in his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's actually a very simple man,'' Wilkinson said. ``His Bible
dominates the front room. He's a straight arrow in the same way
that many farmers still are.''
</P>
<P>
   After nearly 30 years, one might expect a bit of weariness to
creep into Wilkinson's work. But just the opposite seems true. He
says he's more in love with acting than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's childish really. It's all about that childlike quality
you have to keep hold of. It's a big game of pretend. I watch my
kids play, and that's what I do. I play. I pretend. And after all
this time, I'm still addicted to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
