<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5066 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-COUSIN-REVIEW-K     06-24 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-COUSIN-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFUSED CAST PRODUCES A MISGUIDED `COUSIN BETTE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Cousin Bette,'' a drama, is rated R for sexuality. Running
time is 1 hour 52 minutes. Two out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   With her last gasp, the dying woman (Geraldine Chaplin) begs a
spinster cousin to look after her surviving husband and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promise,'' says drab, colorless Cousin Bette (Jessica
Lange). ``I'll take care of all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   That may sound like a selfless pledge; actually it's a deadly
threat.
</P>
<P>
   The plain, impoverished Bette is sick of being a
maid-without-pay for her hoity-toity Paris relations. Years of
cruel indifference, if not outright abuse, have steeled her against
the family's womanizing, spendthrift patriarch, Hector (Hugh
Laurie); his icky daughter Hortense (Kelly Macdonald); and his
selfish son (Toby Stephens).
</P>
<P>
   Now it's payback time.
</P>
<P>
   Adopted by Lynn Siefert and Susan Tarr from a 1845 novel by
Balzac and helmed by famed stage director Des McAnuff in his film
debut, ``Cousin Bette'' has the makings of a fiercely black comedy.
Only nobody seems to have told the actors.
</P>
<P>
   One of the film's running jokes is Bette's miserable luck. Even
when she plans a terrible revenge on Hector or a member of his
brood, blind luck steps in to deflect the blow. As often as not,
the scheme backfires on Bette _ like she's some sort of Wile E.
Coyote in a hoop skirt.
</P>
<P>
   This could be amusing. But the film is painfully
straightforward, played like a ``Masterpiece Theatre'' melodrama
rather than a sly wink at familial dysfunction. Every time there's
a choice between clever and dull, this movie opts for dull.
</P>
<P>
   Bette adopts a starving artist, Wenceslas (Aden Young), and
orchestrates for him a career-making commission. How is the
lovesick old maid rewarded? By seeing Hortense snatch the young man
right out from under her nose.
</P>
<P>
   Bette then takes another tack, attempting to ruin Hortense and
Wenceslas' marriage by urging a coquettish burlesque star
(Elisabeth Shue) to seduce Wenceslas. Of course, the trollop falls
for the young man in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   In the end Bette finally does get even, but by then few in the
audience will care.
</P>
<P>
   Lange, usually a terrific actress, plays Bette absolutely
straight. But at least she seems at home in the 1840s Paris
setting. Almost everyone else in this movie hasn't a clue.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie seems to think he's doing a brief comedy sketch on one of
his old British TV shows. Quinn is an utterly bland,
one-dimensional young hunk. And Shue is a 20th-century girl, no
matter how frilly her costumes. Playing a period character
apparently is beyond her.
</P>
<P>
   McAnuff, whose stage triumphs include the musicals ``Big River''
and ``The Who's Tommy,'' delivers a first film that looks good but
plays like bad community theater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
