<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE WINS TOP PRIZE IN BIRDING COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Seattle aced out Chicago, San Francisco and
Washington, D.C., for the title of America's Birding Capital.
</P>
<P>
   In a fiercely competitive 24-hour bird-watching spring marathon,
Seattle's crack team found the greatest number of species out of
the number expected in its region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phooey. It's very annoying,'' said Arthur Feinstein, director
of the National Audubon Society's Golden Gate chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm elated,'' said birder Debbie Fisher, Ranier Audubon head,
who sent her teams to the Pacific Coast, Puget Sound, Cascade
Mountain foothills, Kings County and eastern Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so close. Take a breath. I was really surprised. I just
found out this morning,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   The competition, the first of its kind for the National Audubon
Society, that raised more than $1 million for state and local
conservation programs.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Gate's Feinstein congratulated Seattle, but he's still
assessing the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw 191 bird species. That's a heck of a lot of species,''
Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it sounds like kvetching and sour grapes, but it's that
damn handicapping system. We're going to have to look at it more
closely next year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Audubon Society asked each metropolitan area to
submit a list of birds that it might possibly see. The prize went
to the chapter that found the highest percentage of birds on its
list.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Murray, Audubon's National Birdathon manager, explained:
``Golden Gate Audubon had 259 species that they could have seen.
That includes all the species that are likely to be seen at this
time of year, migrating through or indigenous to the San Francisco
area. They saw 191 species, or 74 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle had a possible number of 225 species, essentially less
than the San Francisco Bay area because they don't have as many
diverse habitats. They saw 192, which is 85 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington D.C. found 84 percent; Chicago found 82 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
