<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-HIGH-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW SUBSTANCE MAKES `HIGH ART' A MEDIUM PLEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``High Art,'' a drama, is rated R for strong sexuality,
pervasive drug use and language. Running time is 1 hour 36 minutes.
Two out of four stars.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the characters in ``High Art'' work for a
cutting-edge photography magazine and pepper their conversation
with critical cant. It's the kind of language that's indecipherable
on the printed page (try reading just about any art publication)
and sounds laughably pretentious actually coming out of someone's
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   This is, after all, a way of speaking that imparts upon the user
a certain patina of high style while making little sense.
</P>
<P>
   Writer//director Lisa Cholodenko's debut film operates in much
the same manner. It's got style out the wazoo: drug-drenched
languid pacing, a heady undercurrent of eroticism, even some
knowing satire about the art scene.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end all that chic tends to keep us distanced from the
characters. It's like watching fish in a bowl; they look pretty
swimming in circles, but it's darn difficult to care what happens
to them.
</P>
<P>
   Syd (Radha Mitchell) is a young woman who has just been promoted
at Frame magazine. But basically she's just a glorified go-fer, and
she's desperate to climb into a position of real authority.
</P>
<P>
   When Syd discovers a once-trendy photographer _ Lucy Berliner
(Ally Sheedy) _ living in an apartment above hers, she envisions a
comeback by Lucy as her own ticket to the big time.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy, though, hasn't picked up a camera in years. Dropping out
of the art scene, she says, was ``a mental health decision.'' And
while she's gratified by Syd's interest (``I haven't been
deconstructed in a long time''), she's not sure she wants to break
out of the cozy cocoon of sex, drugs and rock 'n' roll she has
built with her lesbian girlfriend, a perpetually zonked-out German
actress named Greta (Patricia Clarkson).
</P>
<P>
   So begins a slow seduction of feints and jabs. Syd (who has an
ineffectual live-in boyfriend) tries to maneuver Lucy onto the
pages of her magazine. Lucy tries to maneuver Syd into bed.
</P>
<P>
   Who's the seducer and who's the seduced? Hard to say, for both
women keep their motives to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about ``High Art'' is Sheedy's performance. One
of the queens of the '80s Brat Pack, Sheedy has undergone a
startling transformation. Her Lucy is an emaciated heroin user,
beset by lethargy and reluctant even to leave her apartment.
Despite her inability to function any longer in the cutthroat art
world, she's intrigued by this young woman who's come a-courting.
Could Syd represent a new start, both personally and
professionally?
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's Syd is an ambitious, mercenary soul hiding behind a
baby face. The strength of her performance, though, is that Syd
never seems ruthless. It's easy to see why Lucy succumbs.
</P>
<P>
   For pure, unadulterated scene-stealing, look to Clarkson (of
TV's ``Murder One''), who is both funny and harrowing as the
drug-soaked Greta. Speaking in a husky growl like Dietrich on
downers, moving in slow motion, wobbling about the room and boring
everyone with memories of her one movie with Fassbinder, Clarkson's
Greta provides ``High Art'' with desperately needed comic relief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
