A5069 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-NOLOOK-REVIEW-K     06-24 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-NOLOOK-REVIEW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT W. BUTLER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 ACTOR BURNS FAILS DIRECTOR BURNS in `NO LOOKING BACK'  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``No Looking Back,'' a romantic drama, is rated R for language.
Running time is 1 hour 36 minutes. Two and a half out of four
stars.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Burns the filmmaker is turning out to be a pretty interesting
fellow. A lot more interesting, actually, than Ed Burns the actor.
</P>
<P>
   In ``No Looking Back'' the maker of the male-oriented ``The
Brothers McMullen'' and ``She's the One'' pulls an unexpected
switch by giving us a story from a woman's point of view. And a
serious story at that.
</P>
<P>
   Claudia (Lauren Holly) has her future all laid out for her _
whether she likes it or not. A lifelong resident of blue-collar Far
Rockaway, N.Y., she's a waitress in a diner and is living with an
old high school classmate, Michael (Jon Bon Jovi), who wants to
marry her though she hasn't agreed to a date. Her mom (Blythe
Danner) and sister (Connie Britton) live just around the corner;
her dad skipped out on the family years before, leaving Mom an
emotional wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Then into Claudia's too-predictable life steps the
unpredictable: her high-school flame Charlie (Burns), who abandoned
her several years before to indulge his wanderlust. Now he cruises
back into town, vaguely sheepish about his long absence but cockily
assuming that he and Claudia will pick up where they left off. He's
an unstoppable romantic force.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, his smugness infuriates Claudia. On the other,
Charlie was once the love of her life, and now he's offering escape
from a stifling existence.
</P>
<P>
   This is Holly's meatiest part to date, and despite the
character's slightly generic aspects she does a fine job of
inhabiting the role and capturing Claudia's yearning and
frustration. Bon Jovi is good as a loyal stiff who can't help it if
he doesn't exactly light her fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   But Burns' Charlie is a problem, an obvious loser whose
self-confidence is largely unjustified and whose allegedly
irresistible charm we must take on faith. Indeed, the character is
virtually the same one Burns has played twice before. He's starting
to look like a one-note wonder who's just a bit too taken with
himself.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, ``No Looking Back'' absolutely nails its
working-class milieu, from the wind-battered streets of this
seashore town and the Budweiser//Rolling Rock ambience of its bars
and restaurants to the Bruce Springsteen ``Tunnel of Love'' era
songs on the soundtrack. Burns has captured the angst of lives
spent waiting for something _ anything _ to happen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
