A5071 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-EXTREME-KANSAS     06-24 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-EXTREME-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVY RAINS GOOD FOR KC GARDENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Knee-high, the Swiss chard seems to be
exploding out of the ground like a green-bubbly monster. Red veins
as bright as blood run down the center of each dinner-plate sized
leaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at these,'' says Kathy Marchant, as she stoops down to
touch one leaf. Her garden, a quarter-acre plot at 17th and Summit
streets, sits across from her natural foods store, The City Garden,
and her restaurant, The Bluebird Cafe. Visitors are encouraged to
walk the garden's mulch-lined paths and take in the sights and
fragrances of hundreds of spicy-sweet smelling herbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a pretty good year for our plants...because there's
been enough water,'' she says. ``In spite of everything, it's
really been a very good year, so far.''
</P>
<P>
   This week's strong storms, recent blasts of heat, and those 17-
and 13-year cicadas swarming over everything that doesn't move make
for just another typical growing season in Missouri. Taking on
challenges almost equal to a Biblical plague, gardening around
these parts requires not only a green thumb but also guts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I couldn't be a farmer and deal with all this,'' says
Fred Pereira, horticulturist and Master Garden volunteer at the
Missouri University Extension Service. ``They have to be stoic
about these things. But living in this growing zone, a lot of
Missourians have learned how to cope with the changes here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plants may look poorly after a strong storm, but it's amazing
how quickly they snap back by themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many gardeners are enjoying the fruits of not only this
season, but last season's as well.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the borders of a picket fence at Marchant's garden,
sunflowers form a 20-foot canopy, and tower almost 7 feet high.
``These are just volunteers, a weed bed really,'' Marchant says.
``We never planted them. They just grew up this year, survivors of
the mild winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is doing well. The plants love the rain. But it's
the heat that kills off the lettuces.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Natural Weather Service predicting cooler than average
summer temperatures, gardeners who grow lettuce may be in luck. But
meteorologist Dan Virgillito stresses the key word in this
prediction is ``average.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Flat-out averages can be deceptive,'' he warns. ``In June,
we've been all over the map temperature-wise. But the average so
far says that we're below temperatures for this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Averages ignore the fact that you can have long stretches of
heat waves. All it takes is a few cooler days to bring down the
average temp for that month. But it will still feel like a heat
wave.''
</P>
<P>
   The rain that has already drenched gardens has pushed 2 inches
above the rainfall average for June. Normally, precipitation hovers
around 3 inches; as of Monday, the total rain for the month dripped
in at 5.43 inches. And more rain is predicted.
</P>
<P>
   But rain doesn't hurt a garden unless the garden was placed in a
poor drainage site, says Bruce Chladny, a horticulturist and
extension agent at the K-State Research and Extension in Wyandotte
County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides the rain, people are also finding branches and twigs
littering their yards,'' he says. ``They think it's from the wind,
but it's really the cicadas.''
</P>
<P>
   Female cicadas lay their eggs by drilling a hole inside of a
tree branch. ``It looks like a pin-prick,'' Chladny explains. ``She
drills a hole, then puts a series of lines all along a branch.
What's happening is these strong winds are then making the branches
break.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can do to stop it. I tell people, clean up
the branches and smooth out any rough breaks to help the tree heal
faster. That's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of these challenges, there is one thing gardeners can
do to help their gardens grow:
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulch,'' Chladny says. ``But stay away from mulches with weed
seeds or those that have not yet gone through heat. If the mulch
hasn't heated up yet, it will, right on your garden, and kill
everything you've got out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absolute best mulch is...well, take The Kansas City Star,
open it flat, and put two sheets on top of each other. Place it
around your plants then pile any organic mulch on top of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty is at the end of the season all you need to do is
rototill everything under and you're ready for the next growing
season.''  &LR; brk:Great growing advice
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tips to help your garden grow:
</P>
<P>
   - Look at your garden everyday. ``Monitoring is the key,'' says
Fred Pereira, Missouri Master Gardener and horticulturist. ``If you
see something has wilted, give it a good soaking. Don't spray water
into the air but get it down near the plants roots. Water is a
precious resource and you're wasting it if you spray it into the
air.''
</P>
<P>
   - Mulch. ``Mulching keeps the moisture in the ground,'' Pereira
says. ``Mulch not only keeps plants from drying out, but it keeps
weeds down and prevents fungus from growing on the plant.''
</P>
<P>
   - Fertilize. ``I encourage people to use the everyday, common
fertilizer,'' he says. ``Anything that reads 5-10-5, or 10-10-10,
even 13-13-13, are good additions to the garden. But don't add too
much. I put half the specified amount on my garden. And I put
compost around the plants too.''
</P>
<P>
   - Call an expert if you can't identify what's wrong with your
plants. The Master Garden Volunteer Hotline is at 833-8733; the
K-State Research and Extension in Wyandotte County is at 299-9300.
</P>
<P>
   - Do all of the above and your plants will avoid stress _ and
bugs. ``Stressed plants attract bugs like a magnet,'' Pereira says.
``A healthy plant repels bugs. It's simple to have a green garden;
just keep your plants happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1752EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5072 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCES-WOMEN-KANSAS     06-24 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCES-WOMEN-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR HELPS OTHER WOMEN GET PAST THRILL OF SPENDING TO JOY OF
SAVING  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Author Colette Dowling no longer charges $3,000 a month on her
credit cards _ she doesn't have credit anymore. She is no longer a
homeowner _ her homes were sold and all profits went to the United
States government. At 60, she no longer has a retirement account _
she spent it renovating one of those houses she had to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Although she earned more than $1 million in the '80s on her
best-selling book The Cinderella Complex, within five years she had
spent it all. She sabotaged herself financially, amassing a $70,000
tax debt that is still not paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Today Dowling watches how she spends her cash as closely as a
dieter writing down every morsel. In trying to understand her
behavior she discovered something that surprised her: She wasn't
alone in her struggles with money.
</P>
<P>
   Dowling began documenting a trend about women and money, which
launched work on her seventh book, Maxing Out: Why Women Sabotage
Their Financial Security (LittleBrown, $23.95). Dowling shares not
only her story but those of other women who have floated
obliviously into a sea of debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to me could happen to anyone,'' she said, in a
telephone interview from Minneapolis during her book tour. ``Mine
is just more dramatic because of the sum involved. But I found that
women are especially vulnerable. We have been trained early on that
the entire sense of ourselves as female has been tied to not having
money, not managing it and not being financially independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Dowling, a divorced mother of three, had no problem handling
money as long as her children lived at home or as long as there was
a significant other in her life looking over her shoulder, keeping
her in check.
</P>
<P>
   But the kids grew up and left. Then she left her relationship.
When the money from her book began rolling in, Dowling lost control
of her finances. Her life became a fog of spending. In renovating a
home that she called her ``little fairy tale house,'' Dowling
dipped into her retirement account, promising herself to replace
the funds she borrowed. Each dip brought more penalties in taxes
against her. As the house became more beautiful, her retirement
account disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   She never knew exactly how much money was in either her checking
or saving accounts. She didn't want to know. Spending gave her a
sense of power _ until the day her money ran out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget the date,'' she said. ``April 15, 1994. I
opened the bill from my accountant for my taxes and it said I owed
$50,000.'' (Eventually, that sum grew to $70,000 when the next
year's taxes came due.)
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, Dowling learned she was broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most women have good abilities to deal with financial
situations,'' she said. ``But the equation changes when they're on
their own. When the restraints were gone in my life, spending money
gave me a thrill. It was at times, almost intoxicating....
</P>
<P>
   ``My biggest fear afterward was that I wouldn't understand why
it happened, therefore dooming myself for it to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Dowling began hearing of other women who fell into financial
problems. Heiress Gloria Vanderbilt had to sell off two luxury
homes to pay her tax debt. A newly divorced Duchess of York spent
her way into thousands of dollars of debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never paid attention to those stories before, but now I was
riveted by them,'' Dowling said. ``When I looked deeper into our
society, I saw this happening over and over again, mostly to
women.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sheets, of Consumer Credit Counseling Service of Kansas
City, said it is common for both men and women to spend money when
they've gone through a life change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are transitional points where a kind of
unleashing happens,'' he said. ``I've seen many go off the deep-end
spending. When they're free of a burden, or something that caused
them a lot of pain and suffering, they want to experience joy
again. So they spend. So many also forget to watch the repayment
side. Sixty percent of the people we help are women.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because women learn early that creating a home is their
job, Dowling said. Dealing with money isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although a lot of women aren't going to want to hear this,
there are still those of us who are waiting for someone to rescue
them from working full time their entire life, or from having to
worry about finances,'' she said. ``Many women equate
self-sufficiency with ending up isolated, alone and uncared for....
Money is the final frontier of feminism.''
</P>
<P>
   Dowling found her way out of her financial abyss by joining
Debtor's Anonymous. Leery of its 12-step program at first, she
found that the 12 steps taught her valuable tools in managing
money. One step was to write down every cent she spent. She also
joined several women's groups to develop new friendships, and she
began a women's investment group to learn the stock market from
square one.
</P>
<P>
   She rents a small house from a friend in upstate New York and
has almost paid off her tax debt to the government, but an illness
last year set her back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no retirement and no disability insurance,'' she said.
``I am rebuilding it all. But I know I can do it. I'm in such a
different place than I was four years ago. Now watching my finances
grow feels pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women sabotage their finances because they're afraid of
money's power. But I'm not afraid of it anymore.''  &LR; brk:SIDEBAR
</P>
<P>
   Dowling has these suggestions to help women avoid maxing out
financially:
</P>
<P>
   - Have only one credit card.
</P>
<P>
   - Pay off that credit card debt every month.
</P>
<P>
   - If you have debt you're overwhelmed with, join a support group
to help you through it. ``I recommend Debtor's Anonymous highly,''
she said. ``Their 12-step program really works.'' Debtor's
Anonymous' Web site includes its 12 steps. That address is
www.debtorsanonymous.org.
</P>
<P>
   - If you don't have any debt, seek out information on investing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Association of Investors Corporation (NAIC) puts
out a monthly magazine filled with great tips,'' Dowling said.
``Women will spend hours shopping for the best deal. Just think if
they spent that time investing in the stock market?'' NAIC can be
reached at (248) 583-6242.
</P>
<P>
   - Join an investment club or begin your own. ``Learning about
the stock market with a group of women is really inspiring,'' she
said. ``By pooling your resources you learn without a lot of risk.
You'd be surprised how little time it takes to make an investment
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   - Begin saving 10 percent of every check that comes your way and
put it aside for your retirement before you pay any other bill.
``Pay yourself first,'' Dowling said.
</P>
<P>
   - Keep a journal of every cent you spend.
</P>
<P>
   ``By keeping a journal I learned I was spending $30 a month on a
lousy cup of coffee every morning when I bought my paper,'' she
said. ``It was just a habit. Now I wait and make a delicious cup at
home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
