<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5074 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUMANICS-50TH-KANSAS-     06-24 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMANICS-50TH-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN HUMANICS REAPS A DIFFERENT KIND OF PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 LAURA R. HOCKADAY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A national but virtually unknown
organization, based in Kansas City for half a century, observed its
50th anniversary with a dinner Thursday (June 18) at the
Marriott-Muehlebach Tower.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders and staff members of nonprofit agencies from Kansas City
and throughout the United States attended the event for American
Humanics. Many guests, representing Boy Scouts of America, the
American Red Cross, Habitat for Humanity International and other
national human service organizations, had studied American Humanics
as college undergraduates.
</P>
<P>
   They had learned how to earn a living in the nonprofit world:
How to budget, raise funds, work with volunteers. Armed with an
American Humanics certificate, they had moved immediately into
management positions with nonprofit agencies.
</P>
<P>
   For David J. Ross II, scout executive of the Heart of America
Council of Boy Scouts, his American Humanics classes led to a
lifetime career and marriage. He and his wife, Jane Fey Ross, met
in classes at Missouri Valley College in Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Today Ross is responsible for a $6 million annual budget for the
Heart of America Council that serves 51,000 youths from 7 to 21
years old in 19 counties in Missouri and Kansas, has 38 full-time
staff members and 16,000 adult volunteer mentors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven of our staff members have American Humanics
certificates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Living in a virtual cocoon for most of its life, American
Humanics, with headquarters at 4601 Madison Ave., is now coming
into its own. It is called on for young talent by human service
organizations across the country, offering assistance in everything
from housing to recreation. Backed by corporate foundations instead
of federal dollars, nonprofit agencies are mushrooming and the
demand for qualified staff to run them is exploding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our program is currently taught on 54 campuses, but by 2001 we
hope to be on 100 campuses,'' said American Humanics President Kirk
Alliman. ``The unique thing about the program is that it is the
only one of its kind offered to undergraduates. Nearly 70
universities offer nonprofit management education for graduate
students.''
</P>
<P>
   Father of American Humanics
</P>
<P>
   The late H. Roe Bartle, best remembered as Kansas City's mayor
from 1955 to 1963, is the father of American Humanics. In Kansas
City to represent him at the anniversary was his daughter,
``Jimmy'' Bartle Taylor of Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For 27 years Bartle led the Greater Kansas City Area (now the
Heart of America) Council of Boy Scouts. As executive director, he
was responsible for hiring qualified staff members. He had no
trouble finding people with good hearts and intentions, but many
knew nothing about running an organization.
</P>
<P>
   What they had was ``consecrated ignorance,'' said Bartle, known
for his way with words. A big man with a big voice to back his
ideas, he came up with a solution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of longtime civic leader Jerry Cohen and others,
Bartle founded American Humanics Inc. in Kansas City in 1948. His
idea was to teach college undergraduates the business side of
running nonprofit agencies. Courses would be conducted on campus,
and experienced agency executives would present classroom lectures
and workshops. Students would volunteer in community agencies,
learning from on-the-job experience. At graduation, they would have
the management skills to run nonprofit agencies from the top.
</P>
<P>
   Bartle's idea _ in force since its inception _ was ahead of its
time. Fifty years ago, most college campuses were not interested in
adding American Humanics courses to their curriculums. Veterans
returning from World War II were completing their education on the
GI Bill and considering careers in the for-profit, not the
nonprofit, field. So American Humanics began and grew within a
small network of colleges. That picture has changed dramatically in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program may be the least known of the legacy of H. Roe
Bartle but the most far-reaching, with 2,700 alumni today,'' said
Norman E. Swails of Lee's Summit, retired presiding bishop of the
Reorganized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, with
headquarters in Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Swails took advantage of the American Humanics courses taught at
Missouri Valley College. After his graduation in 1952, he went to
work for the Boy Scouts. When he retired 31 years later, he was
assistant chief scout executive//national director of finance. One
of his last duties was to successfully complete a $56 million
fund-raising campaign. In 1985 he came to Independence to direct a
$60 million building campaign for the new RLDS temple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe my careers in scouting and in the church to American
Humanics,'' he said. ``The program taught me the principles of
working with volunteers and raising money.''
</P>
<P>
   Spreading the word
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Alliman was president of Hesston College, north of Wichita,
Kan., when he was tapped to be president of American Humanics in
1992. His mission: To spread American Humanics to college campuses
across the country. The program had managed to infiltrate only 12
colleges since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Alliman hired a dynamic director of campus expansion. Phyllis A.
Wallace had been national associate director for the YMCA in
Chicago for 10 years. Since joining American Humanics in 1995,
Wallace has expanded the program from 12 to 54 campuses. About 900
students are enrolled today, but Alliman and Wallace want to have
5,000 enrolled on 100 campuses by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Funding for the expansion has come from a $2.4 million grant
from the W.K. Kellogg Foundation, based in Battle Creek, Mich., and
a $250,000 gift from the Ewing Marion Kauffman Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have focused on minority college campuses,'' Wallace said,
``because nonprofits are crying out for minority staff _ for
African-Americans, Hispanics, Asian-Americans and Native Americans.
And they are desperately wanting men. Traditionally more women have
gone into the nonprofit field. It is possible now to enter the
nonprofit sector with the idea of not only doing good for others,
but earning a starting salary of $25,000 to $30,000. In Kansas
City, there are more than 200 job opportunities available
annually.''
</P>
<P>
   American Humanics courses are offered only on four-year college
campuses, Wallace said, because a bachelor's degree is required for
anyone receiving a humanics certificate. The latter represents 180
hours of course work and 300 hours of internship _ on-site
volunteer work with a community agency.
</P>
<P>
   Rockhurst College is the only area metropolitan campus offering
American Humanics courses. Jenny Rinella, a 1993 graduate with a
humanics certificate, is executive director of the program there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I majored in sociology, but I am particularly talking to
business students about American Humanics because the combination
is a good one for starting a career,'' Rinella said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Lozares, a Rockhurst senior majoring in economics, is
taking humanics courses with the hope of someday making life better
on the reservation he knew as a child in Meridian, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a member of the Mississippi Band of Choctaw Indians and
spent my early childhood on the reservation,'' he said. ``People
there are poverty-stricken and in poor health. I hope to work with
the children.''
</P>
<P>
   The dozens of American Humanics graduates working in management
roles in the Kansas City area include:
</P>
<P>
   - Liz Russell Willman: The first person to serve as executive
director of the 9-year-old Shawnee Mission Education Foundation,
which provides grant money for teachers and principals to fund
innovative projects.
</P>
<P>
   - Marshall Hollingsworth: Director of finance, National Center
on Fathering, based in Merriam.
</P>
<P>
   - Phil Hanson: Executive vice president, financial resource
development, Heart of America United Way.
</P>
<P>
   - Cyndi Roth Campbell: Director of volunteer recruitment for the
Greater Kansas City chapter, American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to night school to get my American Humanics
certificate,'' said Campbell, who handles the records for nearly
800 volunteers. ``During my internship I volunteered at the Red
Cross. I think one of the great assets of the humanics program is
that your instructors are brought into the classroom from the
not-for-profit field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional educational experience tries to simulate the
real world. But American Humanics brings the real world into the
classroom. When you are turned out into the world, you are ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
