<HEADLINE>
LOOK OUT! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kate's weight a plus
</P>
<P>
   For plus-sized women who have been made to feel lesser for it,
the times have definitely started to change. Among their ranks,
Emme, the model, is hosting cable channel E!'s ``Fashion
Emergency.'' Rosie O'Donnell is the toast of Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   And now the most recent role model for young large women is
``Titanic'' romantic lead, Kate Winslet. After an apparent bout
with yo-yo weight swings, the actress recently told a British
magazine she has decided to accept herself (and weight) as she is.
</P>
<P>
   Lane Bryant, the national plus-size retail chain, cheerfully
delivers the news along with the announcement that the 17- to
25-year-old category is the fastest growing segment of the
plus-size market.
</P>
<P>
   The accept-yourself battle may not be totally won. Some
psychologists maintain emotional angst over body size is still a
major complaint among their young patients.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, a Lane Bryant survey of 500 women between ages 17
and 25 indicated 91 percent believe a woman doesn't have to be
skinny to be sexy, and 99 percent wanted the same fashion choices
as thin women ... meaning body-conscious silhouettes, shapely
T-shirts and bare summer dresses.
</P>
<P>
   The company will shift some gears to reach out especially to the
young customer this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer rising
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lopez, who appears with George Clooney in the film
``Out of Sight,'' has a new contract as exclusive model for the
L'Oreal company. You'll see her in advertising for VIVE hair care
products.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez also portrayed the title character in the film ``Selena.''
 &LR; hed:And the bride wore, uh,...
</P>
<P>
   The latest sign of the new world is a press release advising
brides on how to deal with a tattoo for the wedding.
</P>
<P>
   From David's Bridal, a chain of retail stores, comes some
valuable tips such as: Long gloves cover a tattoo design on the
upper arm. A scoop neck enhances a butterfly on the chest. And
opaque body makeup patted on from the outer edges, dried and
repeated will camouflage the artwork.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone for how-to's on camouflaging pierced parts?
</P>
<P>
   Dress for the picnic?
</P>
<P>
   Flags apparently still have fashion appeal, at least among some
of the 2- to 10-year-old set. Heart's Designs, the Lenexa-based
children's wear company, says its patriotic flag motif clothes _
featured in Children's Wear Digest and area stores _ are runaway
best sellers for the third straight year.
</P>
</TEXT>
