A5080 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FONDA-0624-COX     06-24 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FONDA-0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TED TURNER THE FEMINIST IN THEIR MARRIAGE, JANE FONDA SAYS
 &HT;    Not for Atlanta
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pssst. Media mogul and Southern dawg Ted Turner is
a ... feminist!
</P>
<P>
   So says Jane Fonda, Turner's outspoken wife, who enlivened a
National Press Club luncheon Wednesday with tales of her
six-year-old marriage to Turner, personal anecdotes about her
struggles with self-esteem and serious talk about her favorite
subject, teen pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though he's a Southern boy, and I've been married a few
other times, he is the feminist,'' Fonda said of Turner, CNN's
founder. ``And he allows me to be roughly equivalent. ... There are
some women who think that doesn't sound right, that's not
politically correct. But you know what? It's true. I am way
stronger than him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fonda, looking about half her age (she is 60), left virtually no
subject untouched in an hour-long speech to a packed house of the
capital's media brokers.
</P>
<P>
   She blasted the leadership of the Christian Coalition. ``They
don't care about children that are not white, middle-class
Christians,'' she said. ``As far as they're concerned, others can
be eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   She defended the Tomahawk chop, which fans use to cheer on the
Atlanta Braves. ``It's what the crowd likes to do,'' she said.
``There are more important issues for Native Americans to work on
than the tomahawk chop.''
</P>
<P>
   She declined to slam the Chinese for their policy of forced
abortions. ``It's a very complicated issue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She urged movie-goers to boycott movies containing sex and
violence _ especially the ones that ``put sex and violence
together.''
</P>
<P>
   And she pronounced feminism as decidedly Not Dead. ``Feminism
means that you ask of your partner to be given your space, to be
seen and to be heard and to be recognized, and to be put on a
pedestal when your turn comes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About the only question Fonda dodged was one about Monica
Lewinsky, the White House intern who is under investigation by
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr for reportedly lying about a
sexual relationship with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda reserved her most passionate remarks for the subject of
teen pregnancy, a cause to which she has devoted herself to through
the Georgia Campaign for Adolescent Pregnancy Prevention. She
applauded recent figures showing teen pregnancy was down 12
percent, but said America's rates were still too high.
</P>
<P>
   She called on Congress to reverse current mandates that require
schools that accept federal sex education money to encourage
abstinence only in sex education curriculums. Sex education must
promote abstinence, but also teach children about contraception,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some children for whom the ``Just Say No'' message,
if started early enough, can be effective,'' she said. ``But I do
know that it doesn't work for all kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
