u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABIES-CDS25-COX     06-24 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABIES-CDS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's baby CD program to last a year
 &HT;    By Alma Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Zell Miller's program to send newborns home with
an album of classical music will last 12 months, the governor said
Wednesday at a news conference in which he presented the first
babies with a copy of ``Build Your Baby's Brain Through the Power
of Music.''
</P>
<P>
   The classical music album, a pet project of Miller's, will be
handed out to all new Georgia parents, starting in July. It's being
provided free to the state by Sony.
</P>
<P>
   In proposing albums for babies, Miller cited studies showing
classical music can stimulate babies' brain development and, as
children grow, help them excel in math. Classical music is also
considered soothing to fussy infants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought the children of Georgia were the smartest
anywhere. With this program, we can now give them an even greater
head start,'' Miller said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Liner notes on the album include a short note from the governor
urging parents to play the music for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including conservative radio host Rush Limbaugh,
laughed when Miller announced his proposal in January. But Sony
Music Entertainment took him seriously and will produce 100,000
cassettes and compact discs to distribute to the 110,000 babies
born in Georgia each year. The company is providing the albums for
free.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals throughout the state are already receiving shipments.
</P>
<P>
   Miller will have left office when the yearlong effort expires.
It remains to be seen whether his successor, or someone else, will
try to keep the program going.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who already have children don't have to wait until they
have another baby to get a copy of the album. But it will cost
them.
</P>
<P>
   Sony will sell the cassettes and compact discs to the public. To
order call 1-800-356-1052. CDs cost $11.98, cassettes $6.98, plus
$3.95 for shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
