<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5085 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSOURI-SCHOOLS-KAN &LR;      06-24 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-SCHOOLS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI GOVERNOR SIGNS MEASURE THAT WILL HELP KANSAS CITY SCHOOL
DISTRICT AVOID BANKRUPTCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY _ Calling it a ``monumental piece of
legislation,'' Gov. Mel Carnahan signed into law Tuesday a bill
that will help the Kansas City School District avoid bankruptcy
once state desegregation payments end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case where very conflicting interests on this issue
all came together in a very splendid way,'' Carnahan told
reporters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly's approval of the bill in May ended years
of disputes over how to end court-ordered desegregation payments
without damaging the Kansas City and St. Louis school districts.
The state has paid about $3 billion since 1981 to help remedy
education inequities in the two districts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This really was a miracle of the session,'' said House Speaker
Steve Gaw, a Moberly Democrat. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, even as the governor signed the measure, some school
district officials still said they think their students are being
treated unfairly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Springfield, for example, stands to get an extra $1.6 million a
year under the bill, but school leaders say they think Kansas City
and St. Louis still will get more than their fair share of state
money. The Springfield board has asked its attorney to determine
whether there are grounds for a lawsuit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City now gets $100 million a year to help desegregate
schools, but the funding is scheduled to end June 30, 1999. Under
the new bill, Kansas City will get $40 million, which school
officials said will help the district survive financially. To make
up the rest of the money, Kansas City will cut spending
dramatically. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City school board member Lance Loewenstein, who went to
Jefferson City several times to urge support for the legislation,
said it helps ensure the district's return to local control, to
neighborhood schools and to fiscal responsibility. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we don't have as much money floating around
makes us much more disciplined in everything we do,'' Loewenstein
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to providing money for Kansas City schools, the bill
earmarks money for basic state aid and for shoring up the St. Louis
School District. Other school districts around the state also will
benefit, with money being divided up among school districts based
on their tax levies and the proportion of students in poverty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bill also legalizes charter schools in the Kansas City and
St. Louis school districts. Charter schools get taxpayer dollars
but are independently run, with the aim of giving families
alternatives to traditional public schools. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The measure requires settlement of the 26-year-old St. Louis
desegregation case before schools in the Kansas City district can
get the $40 million. Critics said that was unfair to Kansas City,
which has settled its desegregation lawsuit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Carnahan said he feels good about chances for just such a
settlement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there are no guarantees; but my assessment is very
optimistic,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bill provides remedies that plaintiffs in the St. Louis
lawsuit said were needed for a settlement, said Mary Still,
spokeswoman for Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon. Still said
Tuesday that settlement talks continue among parties in the
lawsuit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jewel Scott, executive director of the Civic Council of Greater
Kansas City, said after the ceremony she thinks the Kansas City
School District will get the $40 million provided by the bill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Loewenstein also said that he has received assurances that the
General Assembly will provide some financial relief for Kansas City
if St. Louis doesn't settle its case. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During days of legislative debate, critics of the bill,
including many rural lawmakers, alleged that Kansas City and St.
Louis district schools still get too much compared with other
school districts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ted Tabor, assistant superintendent for administration in
Springfield, noted Tuesday that Kansas City and St. Louis will get
more state aid for students in poverty than Springfield will. But
under the bill that aid depends on both the number of students in
poverty and the district's levy, which is a strong gauge of local
support. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Springfield the levy is $3.17 per $100 of assessed valuation
compared to $4.96 in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan said he was mystified by criticism of the bill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they want to continue court-ordered desegregation payments
forever?'' he asked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Loewenstein shared the governor's attitude, noting that the
legislation actually helps free up more money for rural districts,
because it replaces the $100 million annual desegregation subsidy
to Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The rural districts need to understand that if we hadn't
settled with the state and pursued this legislation, they would be
paying into perpetuity,'' Loewenstein said. ``The state's
obligation would continue well beyond the year 2000 and well beyond
the amount of money we will now get on an annual basis...The rural
districts need to realize we did them a favor.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
