<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-ATTACKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIA CHIEF WARNS THAT AMERICA IS VULNERABLE TO COMPUTER ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States, the only superpower in the
world, is vulnerable to computer attacks that have the potential to
cripple the nation, CIA Director George J. Tenet said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet said several nations are developing plans and training
personnel to sabotage military and civilian computer systems in the
United States in the event of a war.
</P>
<P>
   ``These countries realize there's no way they could beat the
United States in a conventional war, so they're looking to level
the playing field by going after our dependence on computers,'' he
told the Senate Committee on Government Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., asked him to
identify the countries, but Tenet declined. However, later in the
hearing, he hinted that Iran, Iraq and Libya were among those
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq, Iran and Libya have all put in programs to increase
their information technology in relation to their military
capabilities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Defense Department study showed that the Pentagon's
computer systems were attacked 250,000 times in 1995. Last year,
Defense Department computer engineers secretly tested their
computer defense system by launching 38,000 attacks of their own.
The engineers, using computers and software available to the
public, succeeded in breaking into the systems 65 percent of the
time. More troubling, according to Tenet, was that 63 percent of
the attacks went undetected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have staked our way of life on the use of information ...
but we are building this on an insecure foundation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Lt. Gen. Kenneth A. Minihan, director of the National
Security Agency, the government's electronic spying division, said
the growing interdependence of computer systems around the world
not only boosts America's vulnerability but also helps shield the
identity of computer attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than attacking a system directly from their own
computers, hackers often go first through other computers.
Investigators then must attempt to backtrack until they discover
the origin of the attack, although in most cases they fail, Minihan
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike a normal battle, in cyberspace we rarely know who is
hitting us and where they're hitting us from,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Minihan added that potential attacks may not always be aimed at
the military. Computer systems that are relied on by banks, public
utilities and transportation networks, such as trains, also are
considered primary targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like in World War II when we tried to disrupt the enemy's
war machine by bombing factories and wreaking havoc on their
economies, our enemies will try to take out our main industries by
cutting off their computers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all computer attacks committed in the United States
currently are done by hackers who have no political goals, he said.
But he added, ``We know of one (politically motivated hacker
attack) and we suspect others.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenet said the foreign governments that are developing their
computer attack capabilities are known to be studying the hackers'
methods and how the U.S. military is responding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they are working on programs to use this type of
attack, so we have a window of opportunity to get some defenses put
in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Minihan said the military is working on computer defense shields
that can detect and repel an attack but he said that a fail-proof
system has not yet been developed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Americans also face a serious security threat from the potential
problems stemming from the so-called Year 2000 computer bug, Tenet
and Minihan said. Because of a programing error in many older
computer chips, experts predict that many computers will shut down
or display incorrect information on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Since Russia's defense systems run on computers that are
infected with the bug, some U.S. analysts fear that country's
missile defense systems could begin to malfunction or even break
down completely.
</P>
<P>
   The American analysts worry that the Russians could mistake a
shutdown of their missile defense systems as an attack, prompting
them to order a counter-assault, Tenet said.
</P>
<P>
   In one scenario in which Russia's missile systems continue to
work but show incorrect information, U.S. analysts fear the
Russians might order a counter-attack to an assault that, in
reality, is taking place only on their computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   Tenet said U.S. military and civilian computer experts are
working with the Russians to ensure that no misunderstandings occur
on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
