<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: LAWYER ATTACKS TABLOID'S TAPES; HISTORIC EXHIBIT FOR
CHILDREN; TANGLEWOOD SEASON OPENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Representing Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman, the heavyweight
Hollywood lawyer Bert Fields says he is planning to sic federal and
state prosecutors on The Globe, a supermarket tabloid, for printing
what is said to be the contents of a private telephone conversation
between the couple.
</P>
<P>
   In an article with the headline ``Is Tom Cruise's Marriage
Hanging by a Thread?,'' published in The Globe's June 30 issue, the
newspaper says that in the taped conversation Ms. Kidman complains
to Cruise about their marriage, accuses him of shouting abuse at
her and calls him a bore who always tells her at night that he is
exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   He, in turn, reminds her of a recent gift of jewelry and says
she didn't show up for a romantic evening he planned.
</P>
<P>
   Fields said it was a violation of federal and California law to
divulge the contents of a conversation that had been illegally
intercepted if it was known that it was illegally intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   He characterized the tape as ``phony,'' said it was apparently
spliced together from several conversations and added that he had
put The Globe and similar newspapers on notice that the
conversations had been illegally intercepted. He said he intended
to file civil lawsuits as well.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Frost, editor of The Globe, said, ``The Globe does not
break the law, and we do not invade people's privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and Again
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Old New York and a newer York will cross paths
Thursday at the New-York Historical Society, where Sarah Ferguson,
the duchess of York, will officiate at the opening of a new,
permanent interactive exhibition for young visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``Kid City,'' it is intended to illuminate urban life and
its infrastructure. The centerpiece of ``Kid City'' is an
environment simulating the corner of Broadway and West 82nd Street
on the Upper West Side of Manhattan in 1901.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors may open doors to learn about the residents, peer into
mailboxes to educate themselves about old-fashioned mail service
and handle items from store displays to learn about shopping long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Season's Start
</P>
<P>
   Despite the calendar, summer arrives in different ways and at
different times. One is the opening of the Tanglewood season, on
Friday in Lenox, Mass., with the annual Chamber Music Weekend,
featuring the Boston Symphony Chamber Players and the Juilliard
String Quartet in three concerts in Seiji Ozawa Hall. Ozawa is to
lead the Tanglewood Music Center Orchestra on five occasions this
summer, beginning on Tuesday with a performance of Brahms' Symphony
No. 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
