<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5113 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-24 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TOYING WITH THE CHARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The whole issue of dueling referendums sparked by a
feud over Yankee Stadium seemed silly at first, but relatively
harmless.
</P>
<P>
   A shootout with cap pistols.
</P>
<P>
   Council Speaker Peter Vallone wanted a referendum on this
November's ballot asking voters if the City Charter should be
amended to prevent the use of municipal funds to help finance a
stadium for the Yankees on Manhattan's West Side.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, angered by that proposal, decided to
trump it with his own charter revision initiative. It would have
nothing to do with a stadium. But by law Giuliani's proposal would
take precedence, knocking Vallone's off the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Boys being boys. That's the way it looked at first glance.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that neither initiative was a good idea. Changing
the City Charter is the municipal equivalent of amending the
Constitution. It shouldn't be done lightly. But at least Vallone's
proposal was limited to the stadium question. Giuliani's is
something else again. He is not playing with a cap pistol. The
mayor has taken serious and bitter aim at his critics and political
enemies, is threatening to transform the way city elections are
held, and has gone out of his way to limit public participation in
the potentially historic changes.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the hit list are the Independent Budget Office,
which, among other things, had the temerity to do an honest review
of the West Side stadium proposal; and the office of the public
advocate, currently held by Mark Green, who has tried, so far
unsuccessfully, to get information on how the city handles certain
police brutality cases.
</P>
<P>
   Both offices were established during the last overhaul of city
government to protect the public's interests. In an astonishing
power grab that has gotten nothing like the attention it deserves,
the mayor, through his Charter Revision Commission, a collection of
his political cronies, is seeking to abolish them.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to do away with political labels _ Democrats,
Republicans, etc. _ in city elections. As this is a heavily
Democratic city, the change would heavily benefit Republican
candidates, under the guise of nonpartisanship.
</P>
<P>
   Is all of this being clearly explained to the public? And will
everyone who is interested get a fair opportunity to comment and
make suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   Are you kidding? The motto of the Giuliani administration is
``conceal we must.'' The required public hearings for the charter
review process have been scheduled around the July 4 holiday, when
many New Yorkers are not even in town. The first hearing is in
Staten Island on the night of July 1. That's a great way to insure
a huge turnout. Those who want to speak will have to register at
the site at 6 p.m. When the hearing gets under way they will be
allowed a grand total of three minutes to address these and other
major changes in the government.
</P>
<P>
   Conn Nugent, the director of Citizens Union, a civic group that
supported Giuliani in the last election, joked about the process:
``Three minutes, Mr. Madison. Three minutes, Mr. Franklin.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``It's kind of funny, but it's also bordering on the
farcical, and that's the part we don't like.'' He criticized both
the mayor and Vallone and used the term ``wrong-headed'' to
describe ``this whole treatment of the Charter as a short-term
tactical instrument.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Russianoff of the New York Public Interest Research Group
sent a letter earlier this month to Peter Powers, a former deputy
mayor who is chairman of the Charter Commission. The letter, which
was endorsed by Nugent and representatives of Common Cause, the
League of Women Voters and the City Club, said in part:
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, ballot proposals for this year's general election
must be delivered to the City Clerk before Labor Day. This is not
enough time to conduct a responsible review of any serious changes
in New York City's governance.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a simple statement of fact. But if what you really want
to do is punish your political enemies and bolster your power at
the expense of truly representative government, then there is
plenty of time between now and Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you almost have to act fast. You have to get it done
before too many people catch on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
