<SLUG> BC-BRANDY-MUSIC-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RHYTHM `N' BLUES, BUT NOT TOO BLUE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Dimitri Ehrlich, the music editor at MTV, is collaborating on a
book about hip-hop culture.  
 By DIMITRI EHRLICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine cruising along a coastal road at sunset in a cherry-red
sports car with the top down. Sure, the image is a cliche. But does
every experience have to be original to be fun?
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of ``Never Say Never,'' the second album by the
teen-age rhythm `n' blues singer Brandy, lies not in her inventing
anything new but in her delivering familiar pleasures with all the
accessories. And she can really sing.
</P>
<P>
   For a performer who just turned 19, Brandy seems to have a
grown-up control freak's attention to detail, and it has served her
career well. When she was 14, she recorded her debut album, an
innocuous but polished set of pop and rhythm `n' blues songs that
sold four million copies.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Brandy has starred in the popular television series
``Moesha'' and landed her first major film role, acting opposite
Jennifer Love Hewitt in ``I Still Know,'' to be released this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The album's first single, ``This Boy Is Mine,'' a duet with
another teen-age singing star, Monica, continues Brandy's string of
successes. The song, which has topped both the pop and rhythm `n'
blues charts, concerns a typical adolescent drama: two girls lay
claim to the same boy.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing particularly surprising happens during the song;
instead, it gets its energy from Brandy's dynamic but controlled
vocal performance. Her voice is rawer than that of her mentor,
Whitney Houston; it has an appealing throaty quality that allows it
to cut through the soppy backing vocals and gossamer synthesizer
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Brandy is far from being a risk taker, and every note on ``Never
Say Never'' (Atlantic), like every move in her career (including
being a prom date for Kobe Bryant of the Los Angeles Lakers) is
carefully planned.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her finesse, though, there is a vulnerability in her
voice that distinguishes her from her peers. Singers like Monica
and Aaliyah can infuse a song with gospel-inflected fervor equal to
Brandy's, but Brandy has an edge of authentic emotion that sets her
apart.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Top of the World,'' a head-bobbing duet with the rapper
Mase, Brandy answers critics who think her life is a fairy tale,
summoning a moaning, cigarette-burnt vocal that is as defiant as it
is slinky. Brandy plays the hip-hop ingenue, a sexy image far
removed from the squeaky-clean one she presents on her television
sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   The song's propulsive, syncopated cadence stands out on an album
otherwise mired in mid-tempo numbers, and the harder-hitting beat
highlights Brandy's sensuality and energy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the album's finest moments is ``One Voice,'' a gospel
ballad. With a choir behind her, it's easy to imagine Brandy back
in the Mississippi church where she got her start. Here she sounds
as if she were un-self-consciously exploring the gift of her voice
before millions had heard it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
