<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-745&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING BOOKS: WRITING'S DONE _ WHAT'S NEXT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a book fails, the author sometimes says it wasn't published
well. Often enough that's correct, although there is a lode of bad
books in the stores that no one could turn out successfully.
</P>
<P>
   So in this summer of consolidation in book publishing, there
remains little chivalric romance between authors and their
publishers. Whatever affair of the heart and mind is left in this
new conglomerate world is still between the writer and the editor
(or perhaps the author and the agent), not the publisher. The root
of the squalling is the question: What does it mean to be published
well?
</P>
<P>
   There is a simple, if pared-down, definition of what good
publishing means, said Phyllis Grann, president of Penguin Putnam
Inc. ``It means that the publisher has gotten the book to the
attention of all the potential buyers the book has.'' Not every
book publisher achieves this seemingly elementary goal.
</P>
<P>
   Irwyn Applebaum, president and publisher of Bantam Books, has
this corresponding thought. ``I want everyone'' at Bantam ``to
think of the full life of the book, from hardcover through
paperback,'' he said. ``Some publishers are content to have
different people responsible for different parts of the publishing,
but for me the advantage of being the publisher is getting everyone
thinking about the book; then you can set your priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   All this sounds emulative, and there are indeed other publishing
houses that consistently publish well. Alfred E. Knopf, for
instance, is one, although it's hard to tell whether it is the
publisher or the house's long-standing mystique that seemingly
carries it as smoothly as a stone rolling down a hill. Farrar,
Straus &AMP; Giroux is another.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the author the speeded-up world of book publishing
can appear to be full of transgressions that include slothful
publishing, slapdash editing and playing hide-and-seek with the
agent.
</P>
<P>
   What precisely do authors complain about, often with
justification? Poor distribution. There is nothing more
disheartening for a writer than to get good reviews and wangle some
radio and television interviews only to find that few, if any,
copies of the book have actually been shipped to booksellers to be
sold. Such horror stories are legion.
</P>
<P>
   Writers groan about publishers who don't send their work to
reviewers, at times just forgetting to do so, or don't even put
them in galley proofs for magazines to see early for possible
excerpting.
</P>
<P>
   ``In these cases you need a miracle for anyone to know about a
book,'' one author said. ``If you don't have a sizable advance, you
are not only not getting a country house, you're not getting your
book out there.''
</P>
<P>
   In a world in which book selling is frequently about buzz _ and,
as Applebaum said, ``the best-seller lists are treated like other
entertainment guidelines such as Nielsen ratings or the weekly
box-office tallies of movies'' _ authors have had to become
students of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the minimum I expect organized professional marketing, not
unprofessionalism and disorder,'' said the writer of a favorably
reviewed book on a subject that one would suppose would have wide
appeal. The book didn't do well commercially.
</P>
<P>
   Another writer, speaking as the others did on the condition of
anonymity, said that her novel had received ``wonderful
prepublication blurbs, but the publisher said it was too late to
put them on the jacket even though they came back to the house very
quickly after the manuscript was sent out.''
</P>
<P>
   A well-published book is one for which the publisher has made
all the correct pre- and post-editorial decisions. Which means, for
example, that the product, the book, has the best possible jacket;
that its publication date is the moment it will sell best against
competition; that the right amount of marketing and advertising and
public relations has been done; that the publishing house's sales
force has been both led and listened to about the book's potential.
In short, that everything about the book's actual publication
crescendos together at the moment of highest impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all this is done, the book has been given every
opportunity to break out,'' said Ann Godoff, who is president and
editor in chief at Random House and is also a book editor. ``Every
project to a certain extent is different; its publicity and
marketing climate different,'' she said. Each book is in essence a
different product requiring disparate editors and publishing
campaigns.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An editor, unlike a publisher _ unless one is both _ has the
hands-on relationship with the author, with line-by-line
responsibility for producing the most powerful manuscript. The
editor is rightly the cheerleader, sometimes with an almost
siblinglike relationship to the writer.
</P>
<P>
   That is why it's the publisher who decides, for instance, how
many copies of a book will be printed and distributed, and even
whether the publishing house's option for the writer's next book
should be exercised. Which is sometimes the riskiest decision a
publisher can make, with the potential for the most punishing
results to the publishing house, since the stakes can be so high.
</P>
<P>
   When an author writes a best-selling first novel, the agent
demands tons of money for the second. Recently, Random House, which
published Joe Klein's hugely successful ``Primary Colors,'' decided
that the asking price for his second novel was too steep, and
passed. Dial Press took the gamble that Klein, writing under his
own name, not as Anonymous, could do it a second time, and agreed
to the seven-figure advance demanded.
</P>
<P>
   Random House now faces a similar decision with the next book by
John Berendt, whose ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' has
been such a colossal success that when it appears on The New York
Times' nonfiction best-seller list as No. 12 on July 5, it will
have been on the list 207 weeks, one week short of four years.
</P>
<P>
   Starr Lawrence, editor in chief at W.W. Norton, who faces the
same ``should we or shouldn't we'' challenge over buying Sebastian
Junger's next book (``The Perfect Storm'' has been on the hardcover
best-seller list for a year), said that the very question of
whether a book is published well is ``a trigger phrase that usually
occurs in the negative, and means the publisher didn't spend as
much money advertising as the agent would have wished.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence doesn't deny that publishers fumble, but, he said,
``there are things that don't work, no matter what you do or
spend.'' He added: ``There are good books that don't work. That's
the fortunes of war.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Applebaum said on behalf of his publishing kin, a bit
caustically, ``There are no bad books, only bad publishers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
