<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ODDITIES _ BEIJING _ A typical Chinese urbanite bicycles
down a frenetic rush hour street -- small daughter tucked into a
backseat and packages filling the basket in front. Ignoring the
chaos, he chats into the cell phone clamped to his ear. The scene
is among the legion of arresting oddities that will punctuate the
trip through China of President Bill Clinton and his entourage.
Such culture clashes are no more unusual than those presented to
Chinese visiting America -- for example, when they hunt vainly
through hotel rooms for the terry cloth slippers and thermos of hot
water that are ever -present in Chinese hotels. For centuries,
visitors have been coming to China to absorb the brilliant colors,
pungent scents and tinkling sounds of a land that many in the West
expected to find ``backward.'' But even in the 13th Century Marco
Polo found China filled with marvels, much as travelers do today.
Cell phones, for example, seem to be more pervasive in Chinese
cities than in most any sophisticated American metropolis. People
in taxis, on bicycles, walking down the street, riding a bus,
sitting in restaurants or shopping in book stores, food stores or
shoe stores can be found engaged in intense conversations.
(Kunstel/Albright , Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-HISTBOX _ Main dates in Chinese history. (Albright, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The Main story expected to move by 2 p.m. EDT; An update
will move 9:30 p.m. EDT for AMs.
