<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-MAIN _ Tracking developments: any new cases, whether test
results are back from the water samples at White Water, any DNA
testing results on the E.coli samples, how is the word getting out
to doctors, hospitals, health officials in other counties and
states, checking to see if CDC is involved yet, still trying access
to DHR command center. (McKenna, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-POOLS _ Is it safe to go in the water? Not just White
Water but any neighborhood or private pool? That's the question
parents want answered. The answer is yes, but we'll tell them why
with a review of pool regulations in Georgia, and reassurance that
chlorine kills most bacteria and other germs. Also asking CDC
whether the second known case of transmission of the deadly strain
of E. coli will lead to tighter regulations. And checking to see if
concerned parents are calling the E. coli hotline or their
pediatricians. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-FAMILIES _ When a young Alabama boy came down with E. coli
0157:H7, before the Jack in the Box incident raised public
awareness, his mother sprang into action. She formed S.T.O.P., a
network of thousands of parents whose kids also survived the bug.
S.T.O.P's founder will be at the hospital today to meet with
Atlanta Braves shortstop Walt Weiss's child. (Guthrie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-KIDS _ A rundown of the condition of the kids, any changes
in conditions how many kids (if the number changes), their names if
we can get them; any comments from family members about how the
kids are doing. If no comments from family members, might could do
this as a bulleted update, with age, where hospitalized, status.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-DISEASE _ When a child gets HUS, how does the disease
typically progress? We'll talk to doctors about what treatment
involves, what can happen, from full recovery to mild damage to
kidneys or lungs and brain, to major damage, to death. (Lee,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-BOX _ A little box that explains what E. coli 0157:H7
means; how it got its name. (Guthrie, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-RESEARCH _ Checking with Georgia Tech and UGA, which both
have ongoing research into ways to fight E. coli, and with other
researchers about what's in the works to detect or prevent this
deadly pathogen. Georgia Tech is working on a sensor for early
detection and UGA is working on a neutralizing agent. (Aldag,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   RESTUDY _ West Palm Beach, Fla. _ A half-century ago, weary from
an unending cycle of flood, drought and fire, South Florida
residents asked Washington to build them a barrier against the
extremes of nature. It worked. All too well. Federal engineers
constructed a 1,600-mile-long bulwark of canals, levees, pumps and
floodgates to ensure that people would always have enough water _
but never too much. Now the engineers say it's time to start over.
They want to redesign the entire drainage system. Environmentalists
call it the Everglades' last chance. It will mean transforming the
landscape once again, creating a network of reservoirs occupying
enough territory for a good-size city. Imagine water covering eight
Miamis or two Philadelphias. Water managers will use
so-far-untested methods to store hundreds of billions of gallons
more than 1,000 feet underground, hoping to retrieve the water
years later. (King, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   w/URBAN _ West Palm Beach, Fla. _ A plan to assure a future
water supply for residents of northern Palm Beach County is shaping
into a turf battle, with wary governments positioning themselves to
keep the spigot on and the flow of new taxes off. (Englehardt, Palm
Beach Post) 20
</P>
<P>
   w/DEEP _ The federal plan to save the Everglades depends on the
untested practice of storing up to 1.7 billion gallons of water
underground every day during wet years and pulling it back up
during dry times. Never mind that it's never been done before on
such a massive scale. (Englehardt, Palm Beach Post) 16
</P>
<P>
   CRITTER _ West Palm Beach, Fla. _ While the rest of us swelter,
watch our gardens wilt and ask when the rain will return,
scientists are calling the dry spell a blessing for the Everglades.
After all, it was just a few months ago that El Nino-driven rain
was drowning marsh-dwelling trees and making life miserable for
wading birds. For them, the dry skies offer a chance to breathe _
and breed. ``We know with the lower water, the healing will
begin,'' said Herb Zebuth, a coordinator for the state Department
of Environmental Protection's West Palm Beach office. ``And for
that, we're grateful.'' (King, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WORKS _ West Palm Beach, Fla. _ The county has banned home
fireworks displays, but how on earth are all the cities going to
enforce this. We check and see whether local government will be
tracking the citations. Also, we'll go to fireworks stands to find
out what vendors, residents say. ( O'Meilia, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HEAT _ Three helicopters are parked at the airport ready
to be used to fight Texas wildfires should they break out. One of
the helicopters is like the one sent to Mexico to fight the fires
there. We take a look at these helicopters and whose manning them.
Also any additional heat-related news. (Thomas, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   OZONE _ The ``ozone action'' alert declared for Thursday, the
third one this week, highlights metro Atlanta's continuing air
pollution problem. And the problem could be even worse than we
think, because the state Environmental Protection Division issues
pollution forecasts based on an ozone standard now declared
out-of-date by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency. The
difference is stark: Under the new standard, based on levels
averaged over eight hours rather than one hour, metro Atlanta
actually had twice as many ``bad air'' days in May than the five
EPD reported. And if the new standard were applied here, EPD
officials say the region would register three times the average 11
violation days during the ozone season. (CAtlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BABIES-CDS _ Georgia Gov. Zell Miller rolls out his classical
CDs and tapes at a wednesday 10 a.m. p ress conference in his
office. (AHill,Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TURTLE-DEATHS _ Experts are blaming busier boat traffic spurred
by two months of good weather for an increase in turtle deaths in
Palm Beach County and the Treasure Coast. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MELFISHER _ With the kind of optimism unique to a career
treasure hunter, Mel Fisher is predicting a golden summer. There's
the treasure one of his subcontractors just found, and the report
his office just released that he says refutes government claims
that he sold counterfeit Spanish coins this spring. (Nesmith, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
