<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PEONY-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLOW `PEONY' TO TOUR, FRENCH URGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Sidebar with CHINA-PEONY) 
(bl) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A French government-backed arts festival, which is
co-producing ``The Peony Pavilion'' with the Lincoln Center
Festival, expressed ``astonishment'' Wednesday that the Kunqu Opera
Company had been prevented by Shanghai officials from traveling to
New York, and it urged the Chinese authorities to intervene to
settle the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Josephine Markovits, artistic director of the Festival d'Automne
a Paris, which is scheduled to present Chen Shi-Zheng's production
of the classic Chinese opera in Paris in November, said she had
been working to reverse the Shanghai Bureau of Culture's decision
through diplomatic channels and in coordination with Nigel Redden,
director of the Lincoln Center Festival, who has been in Shanghai
seeking a solution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to keep a low profile in the hope that this would
help,'' she said, commenting on the absence of reports of the
incident in French newspapers. ``The French ambassador to Beijing
sent letters last weekend to the Chinese Ministry of Culture and to
the mayor of Shanghai expressing concern. Now we have decided to
issue a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement, signed by Alain Crombecque, the Paris festival's
director general, and Ms. Markovits, recalled that the sets and
costumes for the opera belonged to its co-producers, who have
contributed $500,000 toward the production.
</P>
<P>
   After presentations in New York next month, and Paris in
November, the opera was due to be staged in the French city of Caen
in December and in Sydney, Australia, and Hong Kong in January
1999. Theaters and festivals in these cities are also co-producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Festival d'Automne a Paris will not resign itself to the
annulment, for obscure reasons, of so much Chinese and Western
effort and so much talent,'' the statement said. ``It hopes that,
in the interest of all, Chinese authorities will find a positive
outcome to what would simply become an unfortunate episode.''
</P>
</TEXT>
