<SLUG> BC-CIR-PALM-PILOT-ZONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB ARCHIVE STRETCHES FROM AIR TRAVEL TO `WAR AND PEACE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE PILOT ZONE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   www.pilotzone.com &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AS with cult television shows, the Palm Pilot's increasing
popularity has proved to be fertile ground for a number of
unofficial Web sites offering scores of files for downloading. The
Pilot Zone, one of the larger and more elaborate of these sites, is
a well-organized archive that is updated regularly.
</P>
<P>
   The software is grouped into nine categories including Games,
Utilities, Graphics, Development and Productivity, and each
category contains at least four subcategories. There are six
subcategories in the Calculators group alone, featuring medical,
scientific and financial programs.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to do a little Palm reading, the site
contains a bulging library of classic literature in the form of
``etext'' files in the Docs category. To use many of these text
files on the Pilot, you need to install text-reader software like
Aportis Doc, a $39.95 piece of shareware.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have that, you can go to the Pilot Zone and get ``Les
Miserables'' (1,714,175 bytes). Many of the etexts in the Pilot
Zone are provided by the Macduff Lending Library (www.macduff.net),
a linked site that offers 298 great works, like Shakespeare and
Zane Grey's ``Riders of the Purple Sage.''
</P>
<P>
   Serious bibliophiles may find perusing lengthy manuscripts on
the Pilot's small screen akin to reading ``War and Peace'' _ which
you can actually download here _ on a digital watch. The tiny texts
do help to pass the time if you are trapped in a less-than-engaging
staff meeting or stuck at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of airports, there are many travel applications on this
site, accommodating users who need programs that can provide
exchange-rate information, unit converters and a handy way to track
frequent-flyer miles.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball fans might find something of interest in the Sports
section of the Docs category. The official rules for scoring are
posted here in Pilot form, and there are applications that will
install the 1998 American League or National League schedule onto
the Pilot, adding the season's games into the organizer's datebook
for you.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the stockpiled software, the Pilot Zone has a
Frequently Asked Questions section and a What's New page listing
recent updates, plus a list of the most popular recent downloads
and an area especially for Palm application developers to
contribute their own creations to the site.
</P>
<P>
   The Pilot Zone is vast, and it takes some time to wade through
all the treats available, especially if you are not cruising with a
particularly zippy modem. If you just can't decide what you want
and need some divine guidance, try downloading one of the Pilot
applications here that recreates an all-knowing fortune-telling
ball and ask away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
