<HEADLINE>
SENATE PASSES EDUCATION SAVINGS BILL AMID THREAT OF PRESIDENTIAL
VETO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate gave final approval Wednesday to a bill
that would allow the creation of tax-free savings accounts to help
pay for elementary and secondary school costs. President Clinton,
who objects to tax writeoffs for private school tuition, promises a
veto.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president will veto it, and there are ample votes to
sustain. So that was an exercise in total futility,'' said Senate
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., after the
Republican-controlled chamber passed the bill 59-36.
</P>
<P>
   The House has already given its approval to the bill, known as
the ``A-Plus'' education savings account measure.
</P>
<P>
   Before departing for China on Wednesday morning, Clinton
predicted that his differences over education matters with the
Republican-controlled Congress will likely be ``a major conflict''
during this election year. Clinton favors more federal funding to
help build new schools and hire more qualified teachers, but his
requests have been denied for the most part.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still hope that I will not have to sign an education bill or
veto one that shortchanges the future of our children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During a brief, but spirited debate on the legislation,
Republicans touted it as having bipartisan support. But only eight
Democrats joined with GOP members in passing the measure and two
Republicans sided with the 34 Democrats to reject it.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bill was authored primarily by Sen. Paul Coverdell,
R-Ga., it picked up several co-sponsors on the Democratic side who
were attracted to a provision that would also allow the savings
accounts to be used to pay for public school expenses, such as
transportation, computers and other supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow parents, relatives, guardians, benefactors
and even businesses to put aside up to $2,000 per child each year
into tax-free, interest-bearing accounts to be used for education
expenses. It also increases from $500 a year to $2,000 a year the
amount that can be put into tax-free savings accounts used for
college tuition and other higher education expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., said ``the point is'' that the
legislation would ``encourage America's families to save for
education'' whether they send the children to private or public
schools. She threw her support behind the savings accounts
provision because it includes language she authored to make it
easier to discipline students who bring firearms into the
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans insisted that the bill is designed to help take care
of a student's most important needs no matter what the economic
status and give parents and local school officials more control
over how best to deal with education problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This money will be guided almost like a missile system right
to the problem the child has,'' Coverdell said.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic opponents called the Coverdell proposal
``misguided,'' contending that it would do nothing to solve the
existing problems of crumbling schools, overcrowded classrooms and
shortages of qualified teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said that the savings accounts
would benefit mostly higher-income Americans who already have their
children in private schools. ``I don't want to squander money on
things that don't make a difference in the lives of people,'' she
said. ``We need to fix up our schools. ... Kids are learning about
gravity because the ceiling is falling down on their desks.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also decried the efforts by House Republicans to make
deeper cuts in long-established education and other programs
designed to help the nation's poor school children. Specifically,
they objected to a move in the House this week to eliminate federal
youth summer jobs programs and funding to help poor families with
home heating bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is an absolute sham,'' Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.,
said of the savings account legislation. ``On the one hand, we hear
the Republicans saying we are going to save our public education
children. But on the other they are gutting the very programs
...that do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said the savings account bill, which
would cost about $1.5 billion over 10 years, would also perpetuate
``divisions in our country between those who have and those who
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill called the savings accounts the beginning
of a ``new approach'' that would ``enhance'' local efforts to
create better educational opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the president will see that the benefits are so great
that he couldn't possibly veto this opportunity for every child in
America to have more enhancements and more options so our public
school system will be the best that we can give,'' said Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison was successful in getting an amendment attached to the
savings account bill that would allow federal funding of voluntary
single-sex classrooms and schools.
</P>
<P>
   The provision would give public schools the option of offering
voluntary single-sex classrooms, as long as they do it for both
sexes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
