<HEADER>
A5143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UKRAINIAN-DANCE-REVIE     06-24 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UKRAINIAN-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN.: N.J.)  
 UKRAINIAN FOLK DANCES STAGED WITH TOUCH OF GENIUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV.: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(ja) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even in a crowded ballet season, one company remains
a must for any dance lover: the Virsky Ukrainian National Dance
Company.
</P>
<P>
   At root, most folk dances have something to do with making the
crops grow. But when theatricalized with a touch of genius and a
great deal of creativity, they become part of an international
dance repertory. To watch the fabulous virtuosity of this company's
young men and women in their vibrantly colored costumes on Tuesday
night at City Center was, as a cheering audience showed, to
appreciate great dancing by any definition.
</P>
<P>
   Like Igor Moiseyev, his contemporary in Moscow, Pavel Virsky
knew how to capture the essence of folk dances and recreate them
for spectators, not participants. The company he founded in Kiev in
1937 is made up of professional dancers with ballet training; hence
the larger-than-life plasticity of the men, whose deep plies, flips
and spins in the air and loose-hipped kicks are executed with a
lightness that makes their bravura all the more astonishing. Effort
is concealed; power is redefined.
</P>
<P>
   The women's lyricism does not preclude speed and precision while
moving with swivel-smooth grace into a mosaic of changing patterns.
There are enough ideas here to nourish any choreographer in search
of concepts and structure.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the troupe's season in the New York area is
brief. After a two-day hiatus, it will perform again Friday and
Saturday nights at City Center before appearing at 4 p.m. on Sunday
at the New Jersey Performing Arts Center in Newark, N.J..
</P>
<P>
   Virsky himself died in 1975, a few years after his company made
its New York debut. There were those in the West who saw the
Moiseyev and Virsky troupes as instruments of Soviet propaganda
because they always showed smiling peasants. But this was to
overlook the artistry that made these companies what they were.
</P>
<P>
   Communism has crumbled since the Virsky troupe's last visit in
1988; Ukraine is now independent, and the performers onstage are
still smiling, simply because any folk-inspired dancing deals more
often than not with celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Myroslav Vantukh, who became artistic director in 1980, has kept
this in mind while adding his own choreography to the pieces by
Virsky on the program.
</P>
<P>
   The latter include ``The Lads From Kiev,'' a superbly danced
contest between two male groups, one short, one tall. The tall unit
skips in with a mazurka step, while the other group counters with a
spring and kick in the air. One member of the short team seems
suspended in air in a spin, a human helicopter.
</P>
<P>
   Steps that are special to Ukrainian dances are always at the
forefront. ``Povszunets'' is a tour de force for the teen-agers in
the company, who have the flexibility to remain in squatting
position, no matter what they do.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Virsky fuses unison and variety, as he does in his martial
dance for Cossacks, galloping with their spears, and in the
familiar ``Hopak,'' executed with amazingly high split-leaps.
</P>
<P>
   Vantukh's welcoming dance, ``Ukraine, My Ukraine,'' is a
dazzling medley of regional dances that introduces the method at
work. The orchestra, conducted by Vitaliy Redko, shifts its rhythms
as the chain dances and coiling circles make room for the couples
who will later perform Vantukh's fine and quick shepherd's dances
from the Carpathian areas of Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   The program includes dramatic vignettes. Outstanding examples
are Virsky's wistful courtship in ``Podolyanochka,'' and ``Under
the Cherry Tree,' his love triangle for three puppetlike figures.
All are sketched with basic emotions and a national touch coming to
the fore.
</P>
</TEXT>
