<HEADER>
A5151 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY-COX     06-24 0213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waylon can do anything he wants
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Waylon Jennings were a rock star, this would be his
Beatles-like white album. From the ``Run Through the
Jungle''-inspired witchy bass of the opening title track through
odd tempos, experimental instrumentation and offbeat lyrics,
Jennings has obviously come to a personal epiphany: When it comes
to the studio, he can do anything he pleases. And that's OK.
</P>
<P>
   During his 30-plus years in the business, Jennings has produced
a catalog of work better than just about any in country music,
often due to his willingness to take risks and try bold new
approaches to the country formula. Sometimes the stretch makes this
album a bit quirky and inconsistent, as with player piano rolls
mixed in with reverb. But Jennings' midlife attitude shines through
here, like welcome sun burning off the fog. ``I appreciate it if
people like what I do,'' he says, calling from Nashville. ``If they
don't, I don't really care.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Closing In on the Fire''
</P>
<P>
   Waylon Jennings. Ark 21. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Lone wolf Waylon goes his own way with style.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1827EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5152 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-KHAKI-COX     06-24 0181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-KHAKI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black and tan
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 28: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Khaki's cool. Black's hot.
</P>
<P>
   The tan slacks are as ubiquitous as jeans. Black, which attracts
the sun, is a rare sight in the sweltering months. Khaki connotes
ease. Black implies an edginess.
</P>
<P>
   Together, black and tan create a look that's simultaneously
comfortable and cosmopolitan. They're the ideal combination for
those occasions that aren't too dressy or casual, either.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to wear black-and-tan together to fit in, or get
in. Most summer dress codes are so lax that khakis can be worn with
any old top to events ranging from christenings to funerals without
anyone casting critical stares.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're fashion-conscious, it's not enough to make it
merely through the threshold of propriety. To distinguish yourself
from the khaki-clad masses, you've got to complement those tan
pants with black, Jack.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
