<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES REFLECT UNEASE OVER JAPANESE PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury securities lost early gains and ended mixed
Wednesday, reflecting some disappointment over the results of a
government debt auction and uncertainty about Japanese financial
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said market participants were concerned about any
further rise in the dollar because that might provoke more central
bank intervention to support the yen, as when the United States and
Japan bought yen last week and sent the dollar down sharply. The
dollar has since retraced much of the loss.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond slipped 8/32, to a price of 106 22/32. Its
yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose to 5.66 percent,
from 5.64 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In early dealings, Treasuries followed the dollar fairly
closely, as the U.S. currency initially gained strength against the
yen, retreated on rumors of Japanese central bank intervention and
rebounded on skepticism about Japan's ability to solve its
financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds also derived some early strength from the government's
monthly report Wednesday on production of long-lasting goods, which
showed a sharp decline in May. The report suggested that the crisis
in Asia was slowing economic growth, which tends to help the bond
market, because it diminishes the possibility of higher inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But bonds began to weaken after the Treasury's $11 billion
five-year note auction was seen as a little below average, with the
notes awarded at a price to yield 5.454 percent, less than the 5.47
percent dealers had anticipated. The results suggested softer
demand than expected for new Treasury debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
