<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hardships of Irish give new meaning to word `poverty'
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 28: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Pulitzer Prize-winning book ``Angela's Ashes'' upset me so
much I would read awhile and put it aside and turn out the light.
But you can't go to sleep on a family in the crisis of Frank
McCourt's characters, starving and freezing, with a baby in the
family dying every few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   So I'd pick the book up and go on. Somebody said it's my
Presbyterian background that makes it hard, if not impossible, to
give up on a book once started. So I read on, and I regard it as a
very fine, if not enjoyable, book. Friends tell me it has humor in
it, but the only passages that caused me to laugh were those
attacking Protestants. The mother in the book, called ``Mam,''
defended her generous Jewish neighbor, but she had no good to say
about Protestants _ and I really valued Mam, who is the Angela of
the title.
</P>
<P>
   If there's anything heartening about this book, it is the
realization that most Americans haven't seen the poverty and
suffering that afflicted the people of Limerick, Ireland, while we
were having our own Depression. Those of us who were lucky enough
to have food and a place of warmth and comfort didn't know how bad
things were in Ireland, where children would fight for the peeling
off an apple.
</P>
<P>
   I am well-acquainted with poverty, but it's the American kind,
and that may not be close to what the poor Irish have suffered. A
friend who was also pained over the book said immigrants living in
New York may have gone through somewhat the same, and they may
have. Things, I hope, never got that bad in the South, even in the
dark days of the Depression.
</P>
<P>
   I had two social worker friends, Miss Florence Van Sickler, who
later headed the child welfare bureau here, and her assistant, Miss
Dorothy Bennett, who introduced me to far poorer people than I had
ever known, babies crying for milk, old folks suffering from
pellagra. But they got help, and so did the men we saw in bread
lines and in the flophouses along the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe in Mobile, Ala., the incidence of the needy wasn't as
great as in Ireland, but I saw my first dead person outside a
Hooverville house made of cardboard and tin signs on the city dump.
I didn't know it at the time, never having encountered death
before, but the man may have starved to death.
</P>
<P>
   It was shocking to a teenager, but no worse than the death of a
railroad engineer whose body I saw hauled out of Mobile River after
a train wreck. Death was death, and I didn't know people died from
starvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela's Ashes'' makes that very real, and unbelievably sad. I
think it is the death of little babies that is so hard to take.
Oddly enough, old aunts convinced me that grown-ups could take it.
They lived during Reconstruction days after the Civil War, and
hunger was very real to them, except that they lived on a farm and
almost always could get something to eat from the earth _ even
collard greens for breakfast, as my Great Aunt Dillie favored. One
thing she made clear to me when I was a finicky teenager was that
you're lucky to have any food at all, and the idea of holding out
for toast and orange juice was so funny she couldn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Frank McCourt is a fine writer, but he has almost banished my
old desire to vacation in Ireland. We were there once and it is
very beautiful, but memories of those bad old days of starving
dying babies would haunt me. There is a sad line toward the end
when he is sailing to America that he speaks to a Limerick man who
left Ireland ``and never got over it.'' ``You ask God,'' he adds,
``if there's any chance he could give you one soft, rainy Limerick
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
