A5157 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-OPPOSITESEX-CO     06-24 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-OPPOSITESEX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For `Sex' star, director is `so wise'
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 28: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christina Ricci could be carved out of soap. That's because her
skin is so pale and glowing. And also because, this afternoon,
she's about as animated as a bar of Ivory.
</P>
<P>
   Lumped in the corner of a sofa at the Swissotel Atlanta, she
plays a variant of good cop/bad cop with ``The Opposite of Sex''
writer-director Don Roos.
</P>
<P>
   He'll rattle off an articulate speech about his comedy, which
opened Friday. Then it's her turn to say something. Usually only a
few syllables. ``I agree'' or ``Yes, that's right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Her usual quote is `Don is so right,''' he quips.
</P>
<P>
   She pitches in: ``So wise; he's so wise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a high-energy act,'' says Roos, the screenwriter of
``Single White Female'' and ``Boys on the Side,'' with a cheeriness
that belies his own words. ``We basically like to sit around and
lounge, watch TV and talk about people.''
</P>
<P>
   A hit at this year's Sundance Film Festival, ``The Opposite of
Sex'' stars Ricci as 16-year-old Dedee, who wrecks her gay half
brother's life. After shooting it, the 18-year-old ``Addams
Family'' and ``The Ice Storm'' star stayed at the Los Angeles home
of Roos and his boyfriend for a couple of months. She lives in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day I came home from editing, and she was exactly
where I'd left her on the couch,'' Roos remembers. ``All she said
was, `Wow, you have a lot of channels on your cable.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ask her what she did during her two-month stay, and Ricci
doesn't try to amend his story: ``I watched TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Roos didn't write the role of chain-smoking Dedee with a
particular actress in mind, he says he can't think of anyone else
pulling it off. ``Christina was perfect in the role. She brought an
incredible amount of vulnerability and intelligence to it. She
instinctively knew who this character is . ... Which is very scary
if you think about it.'' He glances at the actress on the opposite
end of the couch. ``She's so much a part of you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So wise,'' Ricci murmurs again and laughs. Perking up long
enough to cobble together a few sentences, she explains what drew
her to the ``Sex'' script: ``It was some of the best dialogue I'd
ever read, and it was a strong character for a teenage girl. That's
unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And there were no cats and no ghost,'' Roos cuts in, alluding
to Ricci's kid flicks ``That Darn Cat'' and ``Casper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really obnoxious how everybody keeps throwing that stuff
in my face,'' she shoots back.
</P>
<P>
   He shrugs. ``I haven't actually seen `Casper.' But people love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ricci: ``Yeah, they do. It's actually not that bad ... for a
kids' movie.''
</P>
<P>
   She's definitely in her don't-cast-me-as-a-kid phase now. In
another Sundance film, ``Buffalo 66,'' she plays a young woman
posing as director-star Vincent Gallo's wife. In ``Fear and
Loathing in Las Vegas,'' she's a lost soul trudging around the
city, tripping on acid and lugging bad portraits of Barbra
Streisand. And in ``The Opposite of Sex,'' not only does she have
sex scenes and smoke nonstop, she goes into labor.
</P>
<P>
   That was her fave scene, she says: ``I liked giving birth. That
was fun.'' But she didn't research the mechanics of pregnancy. ``I
just imitated all the movies I'd ever seen where women gave
birth.''
</P>
<P>
   Roos didn't do much research either. ``I think we made a few
mistakes,'' he says of the scene. ``But you know, I've never seen a
child being born, because who wants to see that, basically?'' being
squeezed out,'' Ricci says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange way to continue the race, don't you think?''
Roos agrees.
</P>
<P>
   Roos initially planned to make his directing debut with ``Loose
Women,'' starring Meg Ryan. But Ryan got cold feet and backed out
of the project. Lawsuits ensued. But so did the idea for his new
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very angry, so I just went to bed for a long time. A
week. And I watched cable,'' Roos says. ``And because I was very
angry, this image of a 16-year-old girl hurling a chair into an
open grave came to me. And everything flowed from that.''
</P>
<P>
   As you might have guessed, Ricci plays that girl.
</P>
<P>
   Roos says inspiration comes from all sorts of places. But in
this case, ``I watched a lot of Sandra Bullock in the movie `The
Net' when I came up with the idea. It was playing a lot that week.
And I guess I was inspired by the sound of her clicking away at her
keyboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Quoth Ricci: ``So true. So wise.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
