<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5159 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-MINIVIEWS-COX     06-24 0371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIVIEWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini views: Reviews of movies now out on video
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``Fast, Cheap &AMP; Out of Control'' (unrated) _ Nonfiction
filmmaker Errol Morris has always gone after big issues, whether
it's the slippery nature of legal evidence (``The Thin Blue Line'')
or the workings of the universe (``A Brief History of Time''). His
latest is an oblique, haunting essay on mortality and the
obsolescence of mankind. He makes his points through mesmerizing,
intertwined interviews with four men devoted to unique occupations:
topiary gardening, lion taming, robot engineering and the study of
mole rats. The film is like a piece of music, a bittersweet sonata
that gets inside your mind and moves you in ways you can't quite
name. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Mr. Magoo'' (PG) _ Leslie Nielsen plays the live-action
myopic man. And your heart sinks. Nielsen is an engaging actor.
It's just that, well, he's not 3 feet tall with a huge head, a
potato-size nose and a perpetual squint. In short, he's not Magoo.
Still, Nielsen has amusing moments as he forges gamely through the
generic caper-comedy script by ``Naked Gun'' alum Pat Proft.
Advocacy groups for the blind have denounced this movie. But the
star and director Stanley Tong have taken great care not to turn
Mr. Magoo into an object of derision. It's a big heart, not bad
eyesight, that defines him. Grade: C +
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Postman'' (R) _ The setting is the post-apocalyptic
United States of 2013, a place of rusting cars and people dressed
in those sci-fi/medieval costumes familiar from flicks like
``Waterworld.'' Kevin Costner directs and stars as a fellow who
raises people's hopes by posing as a mailman, reviving the
long-dormant message service and sparking a war with a fascist
group of thugs led by Will Patton. The script can't decide whether
this postman is a pacifist or a fighter, a hero or the victim of
his own PR. Costner seems to feel no embarrassment about putting
himself (yet again) at the center of a trumped-up mythology. It's a
big, overlong, boring ego trip. Grade: C -
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
