<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS25-COX     06-24 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS25-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Audio reviews: Feedback on the latest sounds
</P>
<P>
   By Russ DeVault, Doug Hamilton, Shane Harrison, Sonia Murray,
Nick Tate, and A. Scott Walton
</P>
<P>
   -- POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagination''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Wilson. Giant. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   It's great to hear Brian Wilson's voice again. Make that voices
_ the genius behind the Beach Boys layers as many as 96 vocal
tracks on the tunes that make up his first album in 10 years. Too
bad those pipes are put to the service of such mundane songs. Mired
in blah adult contemporary instrumentation, ``Imagination'' serves
up one Muzak-ready track after another. And Wilson's ever-winsome
ruminations on love and loneliness are beginning to take on a
creepy edge. ``Keep an Eye on Summer,'' for instance, finds the
55-year-old singer pondering the post-graduation fate of a high
school romance. Only ``Lay Down Burden,'' a moving tribute to
Wilson's late brother Carl, truly resonates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rufus Wainwright''
</P>
<P>
   Rufus Wainwright.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   The progeny of celebrated musicians are suddenly as prevalent as
teenage girls at a Leonardo DiCaprio movie. Sean Lennon, Jakob
Dylan and Emma Townshend are all carrying on the family business.
Wainwright's surname may not be as familiar, but father Loudon
Wainwright III and mother Kate McGarrigle both have created some
fine music. ``Foolish Love'' and ``Beauty Mark'' recall some of his
mother's work with her sister, Anna. Like Randy Newman and
collaborator Van Dyke Parks, Wainwright's songs often recall the
music of the pre-rock era. They reveal new depth with each hearing,
until they begin to sound like the standards they bring to mind.
That's a substantial accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   -- JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Standing Together''
</P>
<P>
   George Benson. GRP Records.
</P>
<P>
   9 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   What an ironic title George Benson has chosen for his latest
release, ``Standing Together.'' This one's condemnably disjointed
enough to merit the ``Contractual Obligation'' stamp. The fifth
track, ``Poquito Spanish, Poquito Funk,'' will strike groove mavens
as worth the entire album's price, but the title of the fourth
track, ``Cruise Control,'' speaks indicatively of what's on this
record: Benson warbling through sappy love songs, watered-down
tunes for adult contemporary radio, and too few flashes of this
honey-throated guitarist's scat-along brilliance. Six tracks out of
nine feature Atlanta-based percussionist Lil' John Roberts; the
best track and the only one that Benson composed, '``Poquito ...
Poquito ...,'' doesn't. Hard-core Benson collectors should buy this
CD eventually, if only because it'll look right ``Standing
Together'' among his others.
</P>
<P>
   -- SOUNDTRACK
</P>
<P>
   ``Quest for Camelot''
</P>
<P>
   Various. Curb/Warner Bros./Atlantic. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Celine Dion continues her reign as queen of the soundtrack
sirens, lending her power-pop pipes to the central ballad from this
Disney wannabe. Wrapping her supple voice around ``The Prayer,''
Dion delivers the strongest performance on this patchwork of Carol
Bayer Sager/David Foster pop tunes. LeAnn Rimes, Steve Perry and
Andrea Bocelli also make cameo vocal appearances. But the big names
are generally outclassed by Dion and the fresh, folky tracks from
the Irish singing group the Corrs. Beyond these few bright spots,
there isn't much to elevate this collection of insipid,
relentlessly upbeat songs.
</P>
<P>
   -- RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Make It Reign''
</P>
<P>
   Lord Tariq &AMP; Peter Gunz. Codeine/Columbia. 19 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to introduce yourself as party-starters, then turn
around and try to play tough guys. And that's basically the only
struggle with the Lord Tariq &AMP; Peter Gunz debut. As tiring as a
19-song album can be, the producers keep it interesting with
varying musical backdrops. Some variety in delivery would really
help Tariq &AMP; Gunz, but they're still decent storytellers, leaving
story selection the issue. One minute it's ``Fiesta,'' which makes
saccharine-pop Lionel Richie's ``All Night Long'' seem streetwise.
The next, they're shooting in the street. As much fun as the two
seem to be having on the million-selling lead single ``Deja Vu
(Uptown Baby),'' why stop?
</P>
<P>
   -- COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Perpetual Emotion''
</P>
<P>
   Earl Thomas Conley.
</P>
<P>
   Intersound. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Holding Her and Lovin' You,'' ``Your Love's on the Line'' and
some other tunes from Earl Thomas Conley's catalog are recycled
here, but that doesn't detract from the pleasure of hearing his
rich, winning baritone after an absence blamed on professional,
personal and physical problems. Most of the repeats are too old for
newcomer fans to know them, and Conley's longtime fans will like
the new versions by one of country music's best interpreters. Other
standouts include the cut-loose ``I Ain't Crazy'' and ``Scared
Money Never Wins,'' an admonition to keep getting up and trying
again, no matter whether it's in love or life in general.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
