<HEADER>
A5162 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-ROCK-COX     06-24 0284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-ROCK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vintage Van Morrison: Miracles do happen
 &HT;    By Eileen M. Drennen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine, after 20-some years of wearing out your favorite Van
Morrison albums _ whether you'd name ``Astral Weeks,'' ``Tupelo
Honey,'' ``St. Dominic's Preview'' or ``Irish Heartbeat'' _ you
come across new songs, previously hidden from you, tacked onto the
end. They would not have been listed anywhere; you would discover
them by chance. The same great R&AMP;B-kissed Irish soul you know by
heart, only in variations that are completely new to you.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of miracle that die-hard fans usually only dream
of. But in this case, it's true. Skipping through ``The Philosopher
Stone'' is like coming upon Morrison's musical notebooks, where
ideas are worked out, arrangements tested, favorite themes hashed
and rehashed. Here's ``Laughing in the Wind,'' a horn-powered 1973
blues workout with Jackie De Shannon's vocals hugging Van's like a
coat. Morrison's harmonica sparks on the bluesy ``Don't Worry About
Tomorrow''; his falsetto begs a lover for release on the plaintive
jazz dream ``Try for Sleep.'' Take a pew in the First Church of
Passion Unbound for ``Lover's Prayer.'' ``There There Child'' feels
like it was born right after ``Jackie Wilson Said'' or ``These
Dreams of You.'' So many revelations that you realize that
Morrison, like Bob Dylan, isn't the best judge of his own work.
</P>
<P>
   And you wonder what else he has locked in the vaults.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Philosopher's Stone''
</P>
<P>
   Van Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   Polydor. 30 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
