<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guitars a welcome sound on heat-seeking 'Hav Plenty'
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Fire,'' ``Heat'' and Faith Evans on a ballad _ hey, ``Hav
Plenty'' has just about all the elements for a hot album.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's co-producer, singer and producer, Kenneth
``Babyface'' Edmonds, and Des'ree light the embers with a spare,
smoldering cover of Bruce Springsteen's ``Fire.'' New Atlanta R&AMP;B
duo Absoulute follows and keeps the mood going with ``Heat,'' a
slinky, simple come-on that, like most of this album, makes
prominent use of guitars.
</P>
<P>
   That's an unfortunate rarity on R&AMP;B records of late. But that's
their loss and SWV's gain, as the group incorporates muscular
wah-wah guitars into a spirited reworking of the Jackson 5's ``I
Wanna Be Where You Are.'' SWV's Coko appears earlier as well,
vocally bulldozing her way past an obviously outmatched Jon B on
the still enjoyable ``Keep It Real.''
</P>
<P>
   Swooning and soaring up there with Coko is Erykah Badu on ``Ye
Yo'' and Faith Evans, one of the closest voices contemporary R&AMP;B
has to gospel, on ``Tears Away.'' Floating over the hypnotic
keyboards, Evans' call to ``Come to me so that I can be in love''
is certain to elicit only one response: ``gladly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hav Plenty'' soundtrack
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Yab Yum/550 Music/Sony. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: ``Hav Plenty'' has a lot that pleases.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
