<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5164 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-SIDDONS-COX     06-24 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-SIDDONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Novelist counting on new surroundings to refresh her writing
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a white linen suit that is rapidly wilting, Anne
Rivers Siddons pauses under a live oak on cobblestoned Church
Street and wipes her face with a handkerchief.
</P>
<P>
   It is 99 degrees in the shade. There are no Englishmen or mad
dogs about, only sweat-soaked tourists and one best-selling
novelist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unbearable,'' Siddons says, leaning against an iron
gate near the historic 1758 house she bought a few weeks ago. ``I'm
beginning to have second thoughts about moving here in November.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, refreshed by a sudden breeze, the
61-year-old author is enthusiastic again about her newly adopted
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crape myrtle is gorgeous,'' she gushes, ``and I can walk
to three antique book stores right down the street. I think this
city will be good for me. My writing needs a little jump-start
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   In Charleston to launch her 14th book, ``Low Country,'' Siddons
retreats to the coolness of her hotel bar to talk about leaving
Atlanta and starting a new life in South Carolina's Lowcountry.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the furniture is out of the house in Atlanta and we've
bought a small condo near Lenox Square. I'm not going to give
Atlanta up totally. I plan to come back at least once a month.'
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she says, her next book will probably be set in
suburban Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to become a Charleston writer. I'm just going to
write in Charleston.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, she is eager to mine the city for
literary material.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that somebody hasn't written a book on
Charleston like `Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil.' Maybe it
would take a journalist from the outside to do it. I was talking to
people last night whose families had been here for hundreds of
years and the stories were the most bizarre things I had heard.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems that everyone had a grandmother or an aunt or knew some
other strong, slightly deranged woman who did outrageous things and
got away with them. Of course, she couldn't use any of those
stories she heard and hope to remain in Charleston, Siddons quickly
adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charleston is a masculine town to me, with the lawyers who
control family money and run things. But the legends and the
stories and the flavor come from the women.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of that flavor comes through in ``Low Country''
(HarperCollins, $25). The heroine, Caroline Venable _ Caro to her
friends _ is married to a wealthy South Carolina developer who has
his sights set on a beautiful, unspoiled island populated by Gullah
families and wild ponies. The island is Caro's heritage, left to
her by her grandfather, and she is determined to save it. There are
complications, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of Siddons' novels, ``Low Country'' is a story of one
woman's renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write about women who are in transition; they're
unfinished,'' Siddons explains over a glass of artificially
sweetened tea. ``Women my age are faced with many losses and
changes in their lives. They aren't necessarily finished by the end
of the book, but they do have one foot on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the books touch a chord in many readers. More than
250,000 copies of her 1997 novel ``Up Island'' were sold and she
gets a steady stream of fan letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so complimentary,'' says Siddons' husband, Heyward.
``They say, `You turned my life around.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what is so satisfying about writing,'' Siddons says.
``Touching people. I would like to be taken a little more seriously
in New York, but that's not going to happen. I will never be
considered anything but a regional writer by The New York Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of critical acclaim _ a Times reviewer once
cited her ``shamelessly energetic brand of overwriting'' _ Siddons
is a commercial success. She has one book left on a four-book
contract with HarperCollins worth an estimated $13 million. And
though she is not yet on a level with Danielle Steel or Mary
Higgins Clark, who get $12 million per book and whose sales are
near the million-copy mark, she is nonetheless one of
HarperCollins' best-selling authors.
</P>
<P>
   ``She definitely knows her mostly female audience better than
most of her contemporaries in the South,'' says Bob Summer of
Publishers Weekly, the industry's trade magazine.
</P>
<P>
   For more than three decades, Siddons wrote lovingly about
Atlanta. But traffic jams and unbridled development at the expense
of neighborhoods and historic structures finally got to her, she
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta had a very specific feel to it in the '60s. It doesn't
have that feel anymore. It seems too homogenized. In Charleston,
there's development, but more historic buildings have been saved
here than in any other big city. And here they celebrate the past.
They don't pretend it never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
