<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5165 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NOTES25-COX     06-24 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After reading ``Storm'' and ``Tide'', you might not want to go
near the water
 &HT;    Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're searching for beach books that are more substantial
than sea foam, the latest batch of paperbacks is worth a look.
</P>
<P>
   For outdoor adventure tales, it's hard to beat ``The Perfect
Storm'' (Harper, $6.99) by Sebastian Junger. This superbly written
true story of an October 1991 ``storm of the century'' that hit a
fishing vessel off the coast of Massachusetts is more terrifying
than the scariest fiction. The doomed six-man crew of the Andrea
Gail faced winds of 120 mph and waves 10 stories high. Drawing on
interviews with family members and other fishermen, Junger
skillfully captures the fury of the storm while weaving in details
of the men's lives.
</P>
<P>
   Another water-related book is John M. Barry's award-winning
``Rising Tide'' (Touchstone, $15). The winner of the Southern Book
Critics Circle and Lillian Smith awards, ``Rising Tide'' is an epic
tale of one of America's greatest natural disasters. The
Mississippi River flood of 1927 had more wide-reaching consequences
than the 1 million homes it invaded. It changed the politics and
social structure of the South by destroying empires of tenant
farms, eroding the power of New Orleans bankers, driving hundreds
of thousands of blacks to the North and paving the way for the rise
of Huey Long.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the night the flood hit Greenville, Miss., Barry
switches to three separate stories. One involves the engineers who
fought over ways to control the river, finally settling _
disastrously, it turns out _ on levees. Another story is the
history of the aristocratic Percy family, and a third is about the
New Orleans bankers whose decision to dynamite a levee and flood an
area south of the city resulted in their political demise.
Meticulously researched and well-written, Barry's narrative is as
sure and swift as the river itself.
</P>
<P>
   Now for something on dry land: a baseball diamond, to be exact.
The Polo Grounds in New York is the opening setting for
``Underworld'' (Scribner, $16), Don DeLillo's brilliant portrait of
America in the Cold War years. The date is Oct. 3, 1951, and the
Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Giants are facing each other in the
final playoff game for the pennant. Among those seated in the
stands are Frank Sinatra, Jackie Gleason, Toots Shor and J. Edgar
Hoover.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the game, an FBI agent pulls Hoover aside to
share the news that the Soviet Union has detonated its first atomic
bomb. Bobby Thomson's home run would be called ``the shot heard
'round the world,'' but echoes of that Russian shot would
reverberate for decades. The rest of the novel is a story of a
generation in the shadow of the bomb. ``Underworld'' is a
masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   While DeLillo attempts to capture the entire nation in his
sweeping novel, James Lee Burke is content to focus on a smaller
landscape. Deaf Smith, Texas, is the setting for ``Cimarron Rose''
(Hyperion, $7.99), Burke's compelling crime novel about Billy Bob
Holland, a former Texas Ranger who is now a defense lawyer. When
Vernon Smothers' boy Lucas is accused of raping and killing a girl,
Vernon asks Billy Bob for help. Because Lucas is really Billy Bob's
son, he has no choice, even if it means dredging up family secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cimarron Rose'' is a departure for Burke, whose well-known
Dave Robicheaux series is set in Louisiana, but the writing is just
as crisp and the misfit characters just as memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
