A5166 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER25-COX     06-24 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN hires lawyer to probe sarin report
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA--CNN has hired First Amendment attorney Floyd Abrams to
conduct an independent investigation into the accuracy of its
controversial report on U.S. use of nerve gas in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing is being looked at as heavily as we know how,'' CNN
anchor Jeff Greenfield said Wednesday. ``We're in the process of
finding out, did we make a mistake or were we right?''
</P>
<P>
   A news organization hiring an outsider to review its reporting
is unusual. Abrams, who represented The New York Times in the
Pentagon Papers case and argued for cameras in the courtroom in the
O.J. Simpson trial, will look at CNN's research and process and
report back to CNN executives. Greenfield says CNN will then report
to viewers on the accuracy of the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we're not going to do is rush in until we know what
we're saying,'' Greenfield said. ``This is a 28-year-old event. It
ain't like there's a piece of paper we can refer to.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were wrong, we'll tell you that,'' Greenfield continued.
``If we were right, we'll tell you that. If we were `right, but
...' we'll tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial report, which aired June 7 on the new magazine show
``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time,'' charged that U.S. military forces
dropped sarin nerve gas in Laos in 1970 and killed American
defectors and civilians. Retired Maj. Gen. Perry Smith, CNN's
former military adviser, resigned in protest over what he says is
an erroneous story and CNN's refusal, so far, to retract it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is not sloppy journalism, but irresponsible,
dishonest journalism,'' Smith said Wednesday in a telephone
interview from his home in Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has been conducting his own investigation into the story
since it aired and said it is ``completely wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN executives such as NewsGroup CEO Tom Johnson and CNN/US
president Richard Kaplan have declined to comment on the accuracy
of the report or on the investigation; Greenfield's comments are
the most candid yet from inside CNN confirming that the network is
investigating a story it promoted heavily. And Smith's comments
about CNN are his most pointed yet as the controversy over
Operation Tailwind, as the military called it, continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the raid and the alleged nerve gas use was also
published in Time in a piece written by international correspondent
Peter Arnett and CNN producer April Oliver. (Although Arnett was
the reporter on the on-air piece, Oliver did much of the research
and interviews.) But in the current Time, a ``To Our Readers'' note
from managing editor Walter Isaacson states: ``We feel the doubts
raised deserve full exploration. ... When we get more of these
facts, and, we hope, a clearer picture of what may have happened,
we will report them to you, correct any mistakes and try to clarify
any disputes that remain.''
</P>
<P>
   Although CNN does not know when it will make a full public
accounting of Abrams' report, the network does plan to address the
controversy at 6:30 p.m. Saturday on ``Reliable Sources,'' its
weekly show that deals with media issues. ``NewsStand'' senior
executive producer Pam Hill and senior producer Jack Smith are
scheduled to appear on the program.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN story about Operation Tailwind was also seriously
questioned by Newsweek, a Time competitor, which quoted Eugene
McCarley, the Army captain who led the raid, as saying, ``It's all
lies.'' McCarley was one of several men involved in Operation
Tailwind interviewed on camera by CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen Smith, who was CNN's military adviser on retainer but
was not consulted before the story ran, said he spoke with several
people involved in Tailwind, including the two pilots who dropped
the gas. Smith said both pilots maintained they were certain it was
tear gas they dropped, not nerve gas. They said there were no
special provisions taken for loading the gas, and no chemical suits
or instructions issued to the pliots, even though they were flying
50 feet above the trees and faced exposure, Smith said. The pilots
were interviewed by CNN, but not included in the final story.
</P>
<P>
   Although several aspects of CNN's report, which was titled
``Valley of Death,'' have been questioned, the largest single
dispute is over whether it was nerve gas or tear gas that was
dropped from the planes. Two men on the Tailwind mission told CNN
it was nerve gas, and a chemist said the symptoms of those
afflicted, including convulsions and rapid unconsciousness, were
not associated with tear gas.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Rose, a former Special Forces medic who treated the
Tailwind wounded, said Tuesday at Washington's National Press Club
that he is positive ``beyond a shadow of a doubt,'' that tear gas
was used, not nerve gas. Rose said he was also interviewed by CNN
but was not included in the ``Valley of Death'' story.
</P>
<P>
   CNN interviewed more than than 200 people associated with
Tailwind for more than eight months. Many of them spoke on
background to CNN and confirmed the nerve gas story, CNN spokesman
Steve Haworth said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was a weapons and tactics officer for an Air Force
squadron and flew 130 missions over Laos in 1968-'69. ``There were
a lot of spooky things going on in Laos, mostly initiated by the
CIA,'' he said. ``I don't think anybody can say with total
confidence that somebody might not have done something really bad
or illegal in the Laotian theater. But it is impossible that nerve
gas was used in Operation Tailwind.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
