<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-SARAJEVO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drama, trauma in war-ravaged Bosnia
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Welcome to Sarajevo'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   British director Michael Winterbottom found Thomas Hardy's
19th-century melancholy in ``Jude'' and the desolate romanticism of
British back roads in ``Butterfly Kiss.'' He continues to extend
his range with this documentary-textured drama, set in the flaming
ruins of war-torn Bosnia in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Dillane plays a British TV journalist whose vow of
objectivity gets tested by his stumbling upon an orphanage in the
line of fire _ and by a 9-year-old girl there, whom he impulsively
promises to take home with him to England.
</P>
<P>
   The strong supporting cast includes Kerry Fox and Woody
Harrelson as fellow journalists, who meet at the bar of a
shrapnel-scarred hotel, jockeying for the best footage and
placement on their newscasts back home.
</P>
<P>
   By turns darkly funny, scary and moving, ``Sarajevo'' gathers
emotional power without lapsing into cheap sentimentality. It's
helped by its basis in reality; it's a dramatized account of a real
story.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B +
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
