<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5168 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-750&AMP;ADD-N     06-24 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. NEGOTIATOR MAKES NO PROGRESS WITH KOSOVO REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-FRANCE) 
(ps) 
 By CHRIS HEDGES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUNIK, Serbia _ Richard Holbrooke met with members of the Kosovo
Liberation Army on Wednesday, calling the Kosovo crisis
``explosive,'' and comparing it to the early stages of the Bosnian
and Vietnam conflicts after they rejected his call for negotiations
with the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was going back into the rice paddies of the
Mekong Delta and seeing the same tragic scenario playing itself
out,'' the special envoy told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The loosely organized rebel bands are saying they will fight for
an independent state or die in the process, reiterated that
uncompromising stance, to Holbrooke's open frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who was nominated last week as the new United States
representative to the United Nations, stressed to the rebels that
Washington and NATO did not support their demand for an independent
state in Kosovo, but instead hoped to prod Belgrade to return the
autonomous status that was revoked eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting on Wednesday was the first between a senior U.S.
official and the rebel group, which was branded a ``terrorist''
organization earlier this year by senior State Department
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke's decision to meet with the rebels, a move that is
likely to anger Belgrade, underscored Washington's fear that
Ibrahim Rugova, the pacifist ethnic Albanian leader, has seen his
authority and prestige evaporate as more and more ethnic Albanians
take up arms. Ethnic Albanians constitute 90 percent of the
population of the province.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel commander in Junik dismissed Holbrooke's calls for a
cease-fire and an autonomy agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope this visit will lead NATO and the United States to
stop this Serbian aggression,'' said Lum Haxhiu, 40, who met with
Holbrooke wearing a uniform and equipped with an AK-47 assault
rifle. ``We didn't like what Holbrooke said about trying to bring
peace to Kosovo. We need freedom, not just peace. It is freedom
that we are fighting for.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO has threatened to take measures against Serbia, including
carrying out air strikes, if Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
does not halt the sweep against the armed separatists that has
driven some 80,000 ethnic Albanians from their homes and left more
than 300 dead since March.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a deep reluctance on the part of NATO officials to
carry out such strikes, fearing they could lead to NATO forces'
becoming embroiled in a large-scale confrontation with the Yugoslav
military. Air strikes, these officials say, would also assist the
rebels, who now control about 40 percent of the province, in the
battles with the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who negotiated the Dayton accord that brought peace
to Bosnia, has secured an agreement from Milosevic to permit the
western alliance to deploy 100 military observers in Kosovo, and he
is pressing the Milosevic to withdraw most of the 50,000 soldiers
and special police officers, lift roadblocks and establish a
cease-fire. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade, however, has dismissed any withdrawal until attacks by
the ``Albanian terrorists'' are terminated and order is restored in
the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the real possibility of NATO intervention the chances
of ethnic cleansing by the Serbs is significantly increased,''
Holbrooke warned.
</P>
<P>
   The refusal by the armed Kosovo rebels to accept a cease-fire or
talks with Belgrade can only exacerbate the conflict, western
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is both sides are being provocative,'' said a senior
diplomat traveling with the Holbrooke mission. ``It is not just one
side.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. envoy appeared dismayed at the scale of the destruction
he saw in towns like Decani, which was heavily damaged by the
fighting. The town is now deserted and most of its 20,000
inhabitants have fled to nearby villages or across the border to
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decani is awful,'' Holbrooke said, standing outside homes that
had been gutted by shells and fire. ``It looks like western Bosnia
when I went there in 1992.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not fighting, this was the Yugoslav security forces
driving people out,'' he said. ``I think the Serbs should get out
of here, and the residents should come back and be given government
help to reconstruct their homes.''
</P>
<P>
   The mushrooming rebel movement lacks a central command structure
and the numerous armed groups are rapidly plunging the province
into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke has called on Rugova, who has suspended talks with
Belgrade until the crackdown on Kosovo ends, to return to the table
with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova told the local Albanian language-press that the rebel
fighters ``must take orders from me or it could be fatal to
Kosovo.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The rebels, in a move that brought the conflict closer to the
provincial capital of Pristina, took control of an open pit coal
mine in Delacvac, five miles outside Pristina, on Tuesday night.
The mine supplies the huge Obilic power station for the province,
as well as parts of Serbia and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Events on the ground have been moving faster than the
diplomatic process,'' Holbrooke said. ``We are not waiting for
intricately coordinated positions in order to try to stop this.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing near a gaping hole from a mortar shell in a cement
wall, he said, ``We are standing in the middle of what amounts to
an Albanian enclave surrounded by Serbian forces, three kilometers
from the Albanian border and both sides are primed for a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The fighting along the road between Pec and Pristina forced
Holbrooke's convoy of white armored vehicles to make several
detours. At one point the cars turned back because of heavy sniper
fire. As Holbrooke spoke with rebel fighters the sound of distant
artillery explosions reverberated in the hills.
</P>
<P>
   A group of reporters who did not accompany Holbrooke to Junik
came under fire briefly at a checkpoint a half-mile away when Serb
police and rebels exchanged shots. There were no injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
