<HEADER>
A5188 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-STARTING-TIMES     06-24 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-STARTING-TIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATION WOULD ENCOURAGE LATER START TIMES AT HIGH SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Starting school later could improve the health and
academic success of high school students, sleep specialists said
Wednesday as they endorsed legislation that would encourage school
districts around the nation to start classes after 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., sponsor of the bill, said it would
offer school districts up to $25,000 in federal money if they would
push back their start times.
</P>
<P>
   She said later start times are necessary ``so that students are
in school during their most alert hours and can achieve their full
academic potential.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no national standard for high school start times.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep expert Dr. William C. Dement of Stanford University told a
Capitol Hill news conference that teenagers undergo a change in
their biological clocks at puberty, making them more alert at night
but sleepier in the morning. As a result, early start hours at many
schools is detrimental to academic success, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep expert Dr. Mary Carskadon, of the Brown University School
of Medicine, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are waking up and going to school at a time when their
brains are still in the night-time mode,'' she said. ``The average
16-year-old would perhaps have to go to bed at 8 p.m. to get enough
sleep to be at school at 7:30 in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Some high school students endorsed Lofgren's bill.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Hottot, 17, a student at Herndon High School in suburban
Herndon, Va., said he had to get up at 5:55 a.m. to get to school
on time. He said he was sleepy in his morning classes and that his
academic performance suffered as a result.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so interested in mathematics, so I would kinda let
loose in that class and let it take over and fall asleep. Needless
to say, my lowest course grade this year came in trigonometry,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dement said a later school start time could also help prevent
such problems as student-linked crime in the early afternoon when
parents are still at work or dangerous driving by sleepy students
on the way to school.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James P. Moran, D-Va. also blamed early school start times
for the rise in crime in the early afternoon when students get out
of school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have arrested the crime rate in virtually every category,
except between 2 and 5 in the afternoon _ and that's when crime
keeps going up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lofgren's bill faces a tough future in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Bill McCarthy, the spokesman for the House Education Committee,
said Congress wants to provide more federal funding for schools
without red tape, and this bill ``smacks of red tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Lofgren said she introduced the legislation in order to educate
school districts about the problems of early start times.
</P>
<P>
   If the legislation helps make the school districts more aware of
the issue, they will change their start times regardless of the
federal money incentive, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
