<HEADER>
A5192 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TIANANMEN-HNS     06-24 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TIANANMEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIANANMEN CEREMONY MAY BE MOST CONTROVERSIAL MOMENT OF CLINTON'S
PRESIDENCY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Gunfire will break out again in Tiananmen Square on
Saturday _ to welcome a U.S. president to China.
</P>
<P>
   Detachments of the People's Liberation Army _ whose troops fired
on pro-democracy demonstrators in and around the giant plaza nine
years ago _ will be part of the official greeting for President
Clinton, the first U.S. head of state to visit since the massacre,
which killed hundreds. Clinton, who left Washington on Wednesday,
will get a 21-gun salute.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials say a Tiananmen Square ceremony is how a state
visit must begin, and the White House has gone along, despite
complaints from human rights activists and the Republican
leadership of the House.
</P>
<P>
   By almost any reckoning, it will be one of the most
controversial moments of Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In its current configuration, the square is an odd focus of
controversy _ 100 or so acres of dull concrete.
</P>
<P>
   But it is ``the most emotionally and historically charged urban
space in China,'' wrote Yale historian Jonathan D. Spence, and the
scene of internal and international power struggles for at least
300 years.
</P>
<P>
   Peasants, in the midst of a brief rebellion as the Ming dynasty
collapsed, occupied the square in 1644. Foreign troops camped in
the plaza in 1900 as they attempted to put down the Boxer
Rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   The square stands immediately in front of the south entrance of
the old imperial compound, just outside the Gate of Heavenly Peace
(Tiananmen in Chinese), a structure so central to the nation that
it is on the official seal.
</P>
<P>
   From atop the gate, Mao Zedong, whose portraits still hang from
the deep red portal, declared the birth of the People's Republic of
China on Oct. 1, 1949, at the end of the civil war. At the
beginning of the Cultural Revolution, up to 1 million young Red
Guard zealots crowd into the square waving the ``little red book''
of selected Mao precepts. The leader's mausoleum was constructed on
the south side of the square, and thousands of visitors a day line
up in regimented ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the cosmological center of China,'' said David Lampton of
the Johns Hopkins School of Advanced International Studies. ``For
somebody to say he's not going to go to Tiananmen Square is, in
effect, to say he's not going to China at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But other old China hands see Clinton's acquiescence to the
ceremony in starker geopolitical terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to make him eat crow,'' said James Lilley, U.S.
ambassador to China during the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   It was probably not happenstance that the Chinese government
announced the welcoming ceremony June 4 _ the ninth anniversary of
the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, the U.S. House voted 305-116 that Clinton
should not participate until the Chinese government apologizes for
the deadly crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton contends that after agreeing to make the trip, he has
little say in the logistical aspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is going to be a state visit to China, and I am going
to be the guest of the Chinese, then they should be designing the
terms of the arrival ceremony, not me,'' the president told a White
House news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics have accepted that Clinton's participation is
inevitable and have attempted to move the debate along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue is what does he say when he gets there,'' said
Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., a leading opponent of Clinton's China
policy.
</P>
<P>
   The last time that many Americans truly tuned in to China was
nine years ago at the time of the democracy demonstrations and
crackdown, and the dominant memory is the tanks of the People's
Liberation Army rolling into the square as soldiers began carrying
out the orders of the Chinese Communist leadership to disperse the
demonstrators by any means necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Lampton, who was formerly chief of the National Committee on
U.S.-China Relations, said U.S. television networks devoted about
800 hours of coverage to the uprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of Americans, Tiananmen Square became the defining
experience about how to perceive China,'' said Richard Haass,
director of foreign policy studies at the Brookings Institution and
a National Security Council staff member in the Bush
administration. ``And it took on a significance greater, in a
sense, than it deserved. ... The United States and China ... lost a
decade.''
</P>
<P>
   That is far too temperate an analysis of Clinton's visit for
Chinese directly affected by the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The red carpet he will walk on is soaked with the blood of our
relatives,'' Professor Ding Zilin, whose son was killed in the
massacre, told the South China Morning Post. ``Of course, the state
leaders of other countries get the same reception there, but the
United States is different as it is a superpower of the free world
and is supposed to uphold justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The cry has been taken up by Clinton critics in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer of the conservative Washington-based Family Research
Council said Clinton's plans to be received in Tinananmen Square
``insult democracy advocates around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty religious and human rights groups protested Clinton's
plan in a statement that told the president: ``You are bestowing
legitimacy to the ground where innocent blood was needlessly
shed.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House hopes that Clinton's visit, even with the
intense criticism, will serve to get the United States past the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of Clinton's China policy are having none of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This post-Tiananmen issue is a myth,'' Pelosi said. ``Unless
prisoners of conscience are allowed to speak freely in China, we
are not in the post-Tiananmen era. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of dissidents from the crackdown remain in jail, and
some have recently been returned to prison, according to democracy
activists.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based Chinese Democratic Justice Party said last
month that more than two dozen activists in one province were told
not to leave home during Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Some China analysts contend it would have been difficult _ and
politically pointless _ to escape a ceremony in the square.
</P>
<P>
   If the object of the trip is to improve relations, asked
Lampton, ``why bother going if the first thing you're going to do
is insult the Chinese leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``To refuse to go,'' he added, ``not only would be insulting the
Chinese leadership but also insulting the Chinese people. They
wouldn't understand why he was doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5195 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRICK-HERON-ART-2TA     06-24 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRICK-HERON-ART-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRAVELER IN THE SUMPTUOUS REALM OF COLOR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Martin Filler writes on art and architecture for House Beautiful
and The New York Review of Books.  
 By MARTIN FILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Patrick Heron, 78, the British painter and art critic
whose retrospective exhibition opened at the Tate Gallery on
Thursday, is accomplished in many things, but following orders is
not among them.
</P>
<P>
   A pacifist and conscientious objector during World War II and a
crusader for environmental causes in Cornwall, where he has lived
and worked for most of his life, Heron has rarely taken pointers
about his art from anyone, no matter how influential. Yet that is
precisely what he said the critic Clement Greenberg once proposed
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clem Greenberg was an amazingly manipulative so-and-so,'' said
the soft-spoken, white-haired Heron as he sat in the London
architectural office of his daughter Katharine Heron and her
husband, Julian Feary, during a recent visit. ``I was virtually the
first British painter or critic to praise the Abstract
Expressionists full blast, and when Clem came to England in 1954,
he grabbed my hand and said, `The only English critic.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But Clem had a fiendish agenda,'' continued Heron, who wrote
for The New Statesman in London and Arts in New York. ``I have
letters from him beseeching me to wipe out everything two or three
feet from the edge of the canvas, bunch everything in the middle,
let it stand for a while, and then tell him how I felt about it. If
I had accepted his invitation and started painting according to his
precise formula, what would I have been producing _ a Gottlieb, a
Frankenthaler? I told him to go to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   The 80 canvases were selected by the critic David Sylvester and
are on view at the Tate through Sept. 6. They demonstrate in their
stylistic variety and surprising turns of direction that Heron _ a
self-styled explorer of ``the continent of color'' _ has
consistently run counter to prevailing tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was particularly intrigued by Rothko in the early 50s,''
Heron recalled. ``But I'm afraid he went into production, as a
great many Abstract Expressionists did. It's rather reprehensible.
Art should not be the making of a product. It's really
investigation, absolutely parallel to a scientific discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Heron is often cited as a member of the St. Ives School, a group
of modern artists who worked at midcentury in the Cornish resort
town of St. Ives, where he still maintains a beachfront studio. Yet
his sumptuous, color-saturated abstractions of organic shapes bear
little resemblance to the cool, monochromatic compositions of other
St. Ives figures like Ben Nicholson, Dame Barbara Hepworth and Naum
Gabo.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has Heron much empathy for the work of his other countrymen.
``No British painter was ever my model,'' he asserted, ``although I
believe Constable was a very great artist indeed, with an immense
international influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Given his distaste for parochialism and the gritty, urban
subject matter of the School of London painters, Heron early on set
his sights across the English Channel. Typically, it was not the
colossus, Picasso, to whom he looked for inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heroes were Matisse, Bonnard, Cezanne and Braque,'' he
said. ``During the war, I used to go to the Redfern Gallery in
London, the first place I ever showed, week after week to look at
this wonderful thing, `The Red Studio' by Matisse, which to my
amazement I had found in the downstairs room.'' It is now in the
Museum of Modern Art in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonnard is gigantic, too,'' Heron went on to say. ``The week
he died, in 1947, I was so moved that I wrote a long essay, one of
the themes of which was that Bonnard was not the fag-end of
Impressionism, but right in the center of totally major
20th-century painting.''
</P>
<P>
   According to John Elderfield, chief curator at large of the
Modern and a co-curator of its current Bonnard retrospective:
``Patrick was one of the first critics to see this, and it often is
a painter who has that perception. I do think that painters are
professional lookers, and Patrick is a builder of pictures in much
the same way Bonnard was.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Heron's visual acuity and independent streak can be traced to
his childhood as the son of artistically minded Fabian Socialist
parents. He now recalls that he knew he would be an artist at the
age of 3. A few years later his family moved to Welwyn Garden City,
the Hertfordshire new town based on utopian planning principles.
</P>
<P>
   Summers were spent at St. Ives and nearby at Zennor, where the
artist now lives in Eagle's Nest, a seaside house where he stayed
as a boy. His father, a silk manufacturer, hired modern artists and
architects to establish an avant-garde image for his firm, Cresta
Silks, and at 14 Patrick designed his first silk scarf for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Heron's lifelong leftist sympathies, he has never used
his art to express his political beliefs. ``I think the greatest
mistake ever made is to mix painting and politics,'' he said.
``Politics should be conducted in terms of action, and painting is
an entirely different matter. I love all images and hate all
symbols.''
</P>
<P>
   That feeling extended to some of Heron's most successful
paintings, including a luminous series of horizontally striped
canvases _ on view in the Tate show _ from 1956-57. These and
others were clearly prompted by the intense light, majestic scale
and wild natural forms of Cornwall's coastal landscape and the sea
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   But it was long forbidden to mention that affinity in the
artist's household. As Susanna Heron, herself an artist and the
younger daughter of the painter and his wife, Delia, who died in
1979, recalled: ``There was certainly a time when it was not
allowed to say there was a resemblance. I can remember coloring in
black-and-white postcards of the landscape around Zennor and
sending them to him anonymously. He looked at them and nothing was
ever said.''
</P>
<P>
   And though as a youth Heron won acclaim for his 1947 portrait of
T.S. Eliot, now in London's National Portrait Gallery, he has since
done personal likenesses only rarely. One recent return to the
genre came at the behest of his friend A.S. Byatt, the novelist and
critic.
</P>
<P>
   Heron painted her against a white background in the loose,
brightly colored calligraphic style that he has been pursuing for
the last decade (The work was added to the National Portrait
Gallery collection in April.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more compelling is the first charcoal sketch he made of
Ms. Byatt in 1995, also acquired by the gallery. Though the
subject's face is left blank in the drawing, the overall
resemblance is uncanny. One can understand when Ms. Byatt writes,
``It looked, I said, like a portrait of what it feels to look out
of my head from inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Another debut during this busy year for Heron is the permanent
installation of ``Big Painting Sculpture,'' a 68-by-40-foot metal
screen he designed in collaboration with his architect daughter and
son-in-law for a pedestrian walkway between two high-rise buildings
in the Pimlico section of London. It will be featured in the show
``Color in Space: Patrick Heron, Public Projects'' at the St. Ives
branch of the Tate from July 18 through Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Intended to act as a wind baffle, the six-layer structure uses
yachting technology to rig and stabilize a collection of biomorphic
metal cutouts painted in the same vivid reds, blues, greens and
oranges Heron likes to wear together.
</P>
<P>
   Dramatically lighted at night, ``Big Painting Sculpture'' will
become an exotic ornament to its drab setting, much as the artist's
early works brightened the postwar British art scene.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the London Tate exhibition catalogue by Sylvester and
Martin Gayford, a selection of the artist's essays, ``Painter as
Critic: Patrick Heron Writings, 1945-1997,'' edited by Mel Gooding,
is also being published this season. But the author is not eager to
be remembered primarily for his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never thought of myself as a critic,'' he said, ``I wrote
simply because I was so enraged at the low level of comprehension
of what I felt was excellent. I really hate to say this, but I love
art.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
