<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5197 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-PORTAL-ART-865&AMP;AD     06-24 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PORTAL-ART-865&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTALS: GATEWAYS TO THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By PETER WAYNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the past, Internet insiders liked to use the phrase ``prime
real estate'' to describe the places online where people liked to
congregate. The new catch term is ``portal,'' which is often
invoked in talk about the online plans of companies like Netscape,
Infoseek, Lycos, Yahoo and Microsoft. Each of them wants to be the
entryway to the Net, the place where users pause and look around
before deciding where else to go once they have logged on.
</P>
<P>
   The word emerged as Internet developers realized that cyberspace
could have places equivalent to town squares, business districts or
malls by providing places where people could turn first by force of
habit.
</P>
<P>
   A portal is a place where people look for information. People
might turn to particular portals first because they are fairly
certain that they will find the information they want there. Yahoo,
for example, has become a popular portal because it provides
reliable and comprehensive listings of things on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape has built a big portal business simply by programming
its browser to open at its home page by default. Users could set a
different first page or start with a blank one, but many stay with
Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   At first thought, being the first Web page that pops up on a
viewer's screen each day doesn't seem to be particularly valuable
for the company providing the page. People use the verbs ``browse''
and ``surf'' to describe the way they move around the Internet, so
most users will probably not hang around that first page for long.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a mall, the Internet allows browsers to jump from a
portal to any other place on the Web, including another portal. So
stores and sites without ``prime real estate'' are not as hard to
reach as they might be in a large mall or town center.
</P>
<P>
   But even persuading Internet users to pause at a portal can be
quite valuable. The portals carry advertising, and revenue from
that already reaches into the millions of dollars. Companies like
Netscape and Microsoft quickly realized that these revenue streams
might be more valuable than sales of the browser programs
themselves. Netscape gives away its browser, but it says Excite
paid $70 million for a premium spot on Netscape's page.
</P>
<P>
   The banner advertisements that float across the top of pages can
be an ideal way to place brand names and announcements in front of
computer users. Advertisements for products are also common.
Microsoft is a major advertiser, for instance, of its serious
products like Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Microsoft also plays the portal game. The company
caught the eye of the Justice Department with its plan to grant
spots on its opening Windows screen, on the so-called channel bar.
This bar, one of the major new features of Internet Explorer 4.0,
appears on the desktop in an easy-to-reach position. It contains a
number of icons for Web sites, including a Walt Disney page and The
New York Times on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Parceling out this real estate raised questions about whether
Microsoft was using monopoly power to gain control of popular
content on the Internet. The channel bar, however, has not gathered
as much steam as other portals, and Microsoft announced plans in
March to drop the bar from the 5.0 version of Internet Explorer
around the same time that the Senate began inquiries into contracts
between Microsoft and the companies with space on the channel bar.
</P>
<P>
   Other portal owners are succeeding by looking for ways to make
money by steering people to preferred merchants. The Alta Vista
search engine, another popular site, offers people a chance to jump
immediately to Amazon's Web site and search for books related to
their Alta Vista search.
</P>
<P>
   That integration is valuable enough for Amazon to pay fees to
Alta Vista. Don Bradley, a spokesman for Compaq, the company that
bought Alta Vista when it bought Digital Equipment, said that Alta
Vista would get a commission for steering a customer to Amazon even
when the customer did not buy anything until a return visit later.
</P>
<P>
   Portals like Infoseek, Excite and Lycos began mainly as search
engines, and the search software can also be designed to make money
for a company. A search may return thousands, if not millions, of
hits _ lists of sites related to a given topic _ and each search
engine has some way to sort its findings.
</P>
<P>
   Alta Vista offers a service that, for $40, allows a person or
company to register a word, like Titanic, and arrange for a special
Web site to come to the top in a separate section of search results
when someone searches for that word. In this case, a search for
Titanic takes a browser to www.titanicmovie.com, a site that
promotes the movie. Advertising does not affect the order of the
rest of the search results.
</P>
<P>
   The latest rounds in the portal wars include adding new
information _ news, sports scores and other items _ intended to
draw people into the page and keep them coming back. Games are also
frequently offered as a lure. Internet-based games are burgeoning,
and some portals are giving them away. Yahoo, for instance, offers
poker game software that allows people to play against others in
the country.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Netscape's new version of its Netcenter portal, still being
tested, will present multiple pages with content tailored to
different markets. One, for instance, will offer a mixture of
business news and features for small businesses. The Netcenter
developers are redesigning the site in much the same way that
newspapers or magazines work to identify and attract potential
readers. If the readers show up, the advertisers will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many people wonder what it will take to create large
portals that many people will want to visit on the Web. Many users
continue to enjoy the fragmented, eclectic and very homespun nature
of the Web. Several Web pages run by a single writer, like Matt
Drudge, are very popular and thus fairly powerful. But none have
the concentration of viewers that the major networks and newspapers
still have.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the cleverest new portal may be the four buttons on
the new Compaq keyboards. If you push the Search button, the
computer will take you to the Alta Vista site, which brings in
advertising dollars to Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of mutual back-scratching means that the world of
``real estate'' on the Web is starting to gain the flavor of land
deals in the real world. It may be only a matter of months before
someone remakes ``Chinatown,'' the movie about real estate
double-dealing in Los Angeles, and substitutes characters from
Silicon Valley.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
