<P>
   JOURNAL-LITHUANIA _ VILNIUS, Lithuania _ It is a grim,
frightfully intimate job performed by Juozas Aleksiejunas. He gives
guided tours of his former hell. The 76-year-old Aleksiejunas
escorts visitors around Lithuania's appallingly well-preserved KGB
prison, a lingering monument to the bleak, brutal days of the
Soviet Union. ``I felt ill when I came back here,'' he said of his
first glimpse of the prison in 1992, almost 50 years after his
incarceration. ``People who left this building after interrogation
here just wanted to see it torn down. But if you tore it down the
evidence would be gone.'' (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Tuesday, June 23 in both the (i) International and
(k) Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CHICANOS _ MEXICO CITY _ The National Association for
Chicano and Chicana Studies holds a conference in Mexico City for
the first time, bringing together people on both sides of the
border who are linked by heritage yet often mutually misunderstood.
The June 24-27 meeting reflects Chicanos' fascination with Mexico's
Zapatista rebels, as well as scholars' ample research on
immigration, machismo, political power and gay identities. Also of
interest: the cultural similarities and differences between
Chicanos and Mexicans. At a press conference for Mexican
journalists to promote the conference, one cultural clash emerged
right from the start: Why, a puzzled journalist asked, was the
conference going to be held mostly in English? Don't Chicanos speak
Spanish? (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
</P>
