<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-PILL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO BAR FDA FROM APPROVING ABORTION PILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted Wednesday to bar the Food and Drug
Administration from spending federal money to test, develop or
approve any drug _ including the French abortion pill RU-486 _ that
would chemically induce abortion.
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 223 to 202, lawmakers amended the fiscal 1999
agriculture spending bill to include the ban, then overwhelming
approved the $56 billion agriculture bill. Thirty-five Democrats
joined 188 Republicans in voting for the anti-abortion measure.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of abortion rights swiftly attacked the move, although
even the sponsor of the amendment, Rep. Tom A. Coburn, R-Okla.,
conceded it was unlikely to be approved by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategy is to raise the level of level of debate on what
we're doing,'' Coburn, a physician, said in an interview. ``We're
spending federal dollars to figure out how to kill children ... We
ought to be spending the FDA's resources on things that improve
life, not take it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Linda Smith, R-Wash., told the House ``the job of the FDA
is to promote the health of all Americans. That includes unborn
children.''
</P>
<P>
   A leading opponent, Rep. Nita M. Lowey, said the amendment was
``broad and vague'' and could prohibit the development of new
contraceptive methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts ideology ahead of science and compromises women's
health ... This amendment would tie the FDA's hands, rendering it
absolutely helpless in its primary task _ to evaluate scientific
data,'' Lowey, D-N.Y., told the House.
</P>
<P>
   An Rep. Lynn Woolsey, D-Calif., called the amendment ``one more
time when members of Congress act like they know more than the
scientists and experts.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after taking office in January 1993, President Clinton
lifted the import ban on RU-486. His order came on the 20th
anniversary of the Roe vs. Wade Supreme Court ruling that
established a woman's right to an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   RU-486 has been available for nearly a decade in France and also
is used in Britain and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the Population Council, a nonprofit
research organization that focuses on reproductive health issues,
filed an application with the FDA in March 1996 to make the pill
available for women.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, the FDA declared the drug safe and effective,
but said the agency needed details on how it would manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   The Population Council initially had a Hungarian company ready
to manufacture the pill, but the company pulled out a year ago,
said Christina Horzepa, a spokeswoman for the group. Since then,
investors interested in producing the abortion pill have been
negotiating with companies to find a manufacturer, saying they are
optimistic they will bring the drug to market in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The French method involves taking two pills. The first, RU-486,
also known as mifepristone, loosens the uterine lining. That is
followed two days later with another pill called misoprostol, which
causes contractions. The pill causes an abortion for most women
within 24 hours after taking the second pill, but for others it may
take as long as two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Feldt, president of Planned Parenthood of America, said
Coburn's amendment was ``unethical and irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more evidence of the anti-choice congressional
leadership's relentless agenda to make abortion less available,
less safe and less effective,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
