<SLUG> BC-HAYESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hayes tries to conclude deal to restructure investors' stake
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Norcross-based Hayes Corp. said Wednesday it had
renegotiated more favorable terms in a stock deal with several
investors. The modem maker also said it has a new chief financial
officer, Charles Marantz, 52, who succeeds Jim Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The financial restructuring is an attempt to change terms of a
deal made with holders of about $42 million of the modem company's
convertible preferred stock. Those investors represent about 11
different funds. The cash was used for working capital when Hayes
went public in 1997 by merging with Access Beyond, a computer
networking company that was already public.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Howard, the company's chief executive, said Wednesday terms
had been reached with seven of those 11 funds, representing about
half the $42 million investment. The company has lawsuits pending
against the other investors, who have so far declined to accept the
company's offer to convert the preferred shares to common shares at
$9 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Howard said the original deal needed to be renegotiated because
``the company feels that it was misled by the preferred
(investors).''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes magazine, in its July 6 issue, calls the original
arrangement ``an ill-conceived deal last fall to raise desperately
needed working capital'' and said Hayes was ``in bad shape once
again.'' Howard said he disagreed with the article and many of its
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes stock hit an all-time low Wednesday at $2.62 1/2 but
closed at $3.31 1/4, up 12 1/2 cents. Howard said the initial
negative reaction came because the ``market wants it (the
renegotiation with preferred shareholders) fully resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes successfully emerged from bankruptcy in 1996 and at first
reported strong quarters of growth, but begin to falter as the
market for computer modems stagnated. Howard said the company's
hopes have been pinned to the promise of new Internet technology
such as cable TV modems and digital subscriber line technology used
by telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
