 &HT;    On deck: New York Yankees
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: 7:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV, Radio: TBS, 750-AM.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: LHP Denny Neagle (8-5, 3.25; 1-0,
1.17 lifetime vs. Yankees) vs. LHP David Wells (9-2, 4.28; first
appearance vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Notes: A hard time for Neagle, who requested that his start be
moved up a day so that he can serve as a pallbearer Friday in the
funeral of a close family friend in Maryland. On top of that, he is
trying to recover the form that just a few weeks ago had delivered
him to a 7-1 record and 2.82 ERA. In the five starts since, Neagle
has given up 19 runs on 36 hits, including seven home runs in his
last 36 innings. He has been hurt by the big inning during that
stretch, giving up three or more runs in four single innings. His
last outing, at Montreal on Friday, was a disaster, as he yielded
eight runs before being pulled in the second inning. He is working
on three days rest for the first time this season and just the 12th
time in the last five years. He went 4-4 with a 3.04 ERA in those
starts and averaged 6 1/3 innings. Wells faced the Braves only once
in his half-season in the National League but it was a big night--
Game 3 of the 1995 NLCS when he started for Cincinnati. He lost 5-2
that night but shut out the Braves into the sixth, when Charlie
O'Brien hit a three-run homer.
</P>
