<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAPORTA25-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Design won't strip neighborhood vision
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- When Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta announced plans
to move its new headquarters to the corner of 10th and Peachtree,
several urban enthusiasts in Midtown rolled their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   For years, grand schemes had been planned for that block. An
urban retail-entertainment center. A mixed-use office, residential
and retail development. A new home for the Atlanta Symphony. A
central plaza for festivals and events.
</P>
<P>
   But a federal building?
</P>
<P>
   How in the world could one design a high-security federal
building that would not deaden potentially the most important
undeveloped block in Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   The answer resonated on Wednesday. Leaders of the Midtown
Alliance agreed that the end result was the best they could hope
for given the Atlanta Fed's building requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Guynn, president of Atlanta's Federal Reserve, acknowledged
Wednesday that the design likely would not have been as sensitive
to the community had it not been for an active and agressive
planning process known as Blueprint Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   When the Federal Reserve first announced plans to move its
headquarters from downtown to 10th Street, Midtown Alliance leaders
already had signed on to an elaborate, grassroots process to plan
the commercial corridor along Peachtree Street. It hired urban
designer Anton Nelessen to help coordinate the community's vision
for Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   In a tour of the neighborhood in February 1997, Nelessen voiced
what others were saying privately, saying, ``it is really a
miserable place to put that building.''
</P>
<P>
   Guynn's first reaction was anger. But he decided to translate
that criticism into a challenge to show that the Atlanta Fed could
be a good neighbor in Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were clearly influenced to go the extra mile or the extra
10 miles,'' Guynn said. ``It was important to me that (Nelessen),
among others, see we were able to do something that he didn't
believe we could do, that we could try to do something that he
could be proud of as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelessen, who is based in Princeton, N.J., Wednesday had not yet
seen the Atlanta Fed design, but he was delighted to hear Guynn's
comments. ``Excellent,'' he said. ``It proves that the whole notion
of the community planning process can have an impact on the
corporate community.''
</P>
<P>
   Midtown leaders who had seen the plan were especially
encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fabulous,'' said Harald Hansen, chairman of Blueprint
Midtown and retired chairman of First Union-Georgia. ``It was
absolutely magnificent, recognizing what they do, and be able to
blend that into what Blueprint was all about.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the big and little touches that impressed Susan Mendheim,
president of the Midtown Alliance. The trees on top of the parking
deck. The public space along Peachtree Street. A money museum off
the main entrance where the public is welcome. The commitment by
the Fed to the streetscape around the block _ closely spaced tree
plantings, light fixtures, wide sidewalks. All that conformed the
vision described in Blueprint Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   Mendheim also credited Guynn for participating in an all-day
workshop to plan the neighborhood, for serving on the Midtown
Alliance board and for wanting to please the community with a
sensitive building design.
</P>
<P>
   ``It enables us to point to the very center of Midtown and say,
`This is the standard,''' said Mendheim, adding that she has
developers coming to her office every day wanting to see the plans
and develop projects that fit the vision for Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely a living plan,'' Hansen said. ``We are
putting size and substance to it every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
