<HEADER>
A5242 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CHINA-CLINTON-0625     06-24 1737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CHINA-CLINTON-0625-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON BEGINS MAKE-OR-BREAK CHINA TRIP
 &HT;    With CHINA-ODDITIES-$ADV25; CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV25
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT, MARCIA KUNSTEL and BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Heaping contention upon controversy, President
Clinton kicked off a nine-day China tour Wednesday by delaying his
departure to assail the country's harsh press controls, saying
Beijing is waging ''a losing battle'' in its historic attempt to
manage an open economy with a repressive government.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic gesture sharply at odds with the tone White House
aides had hoped to set for his first-ever trip to China, Clinton
criticized Beijing during a hastily-called White House interview
with three journalists China has barred from covering the
president's visit.
</P>
<P>
   He told the reporters _ two Americans and one Indian, all of
whom work for Radio Free Asia _ that China had ''made a mistake''
in revoking their visas over the weekend, and he said the move
illustrated a far broader chasm between the United States and
China.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a losing battle to try to keep ideas that are contrary to
official dogma out of the public debate,'' Clinton told the
reporters. ''Oppressive government, in the end, will be resisted by
people and, in the end, is inconsistent with developing a free
economy. You can't say, 'We're going to have a free economy but
we're going to try to keep controls on what people know, what they
hear, what they can say.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the remarks during a 45-minute Oval Office
interview, while the presidential helicopter, Marine One, waited on
the South Lawn to take Clinton, First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
and their daughter, Chelsea, to Andrews Air Force Base for their
Air Force One flight to China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is to arrive Thursday in the ancient city of Xian,
becoming the first American president to visit China since troops
crushed a democracy movement near Tiananmen Square on June 4, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Xian, with the whole world watching, nine of the
most pivotal days in Clinton's presidency are starting to unfold on
Thursday to the sound of Chinese gongs.
</P>
<P>
   Future historians will measure Clinton's every step in China to
gauge whether this is a journey into greatness or a lame duck's
descent into mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders have agreed to make a joint effort to establish
a constructive relationship between the countries for the next
century,'' said the official Chinese Xinhua news agency as Clinton
was aboard Air Force One to China.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what is startling so far is that so little about the final
outcome of the summit is pre-determined, even as the Chinese
unfurled a carpet as long as two football fields to greet the first
American president to visit the People's Republic of China in nine
years.
</P>
<P>
   The question marks are big ones:
</P>
<P>
   -- Will Clinton be able to make a case for human rights and
religious freedoms without irrevocably angering his Chinese hosts,
whose bottom-line objective is to avoid being humiliated'' on what
they view as internal'' matters?
</P>
<P>
   -- Will the two sides hammer out an agreement to pinch off the
threat of nuclear catastrophe under the exigencies of late-night
summit negotiations, as often happens in these high-level meetings,
or will they fail to bridge the final gaps??
</P>
<P>
   -- Will the volatile issue of Taiwan, which the Chinese side has
put at the top of the agenda in recent days, disrupt what both the
Americans and Chinese had hoped would be a smooth summit pushing
bilateral relations up to a new level of cooperation?
</P>
<P>
   Once the breathtaking pageantry of Thursday's Emperor's
Welcome'' in this ancient walled city is finished, Clinton's
journey will get far tougher. Events immediately preceding
Clinton's expected arrival here on Thursday night China time (7:30
a.m. EDT), did not bode well for smoothness.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments _ a pointed last-minute rebuttal to Beijing's
decision to ban the journalists _ followed weeks in which he has
sought to parry the protests of human rights activists, many of
whom insist he should not go to China, others of whom have asked
that he meet with political dissidents there. Clinton has
repeatedly stressed the need for Washington and Beijing to build on
common ground across a broad spectrum of issues, ranging from
efforts to contain nuclear weapons and combat global crime to
stabilizing the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Radio Free Asia flap, however, underscored the continuing
differences between the two Pacific giants and the lingering
imperfections in their often troubled relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ''It shows you the downside of the government over in Beijing,''
said Radio Free Asia's executive editor, Dan Southerland, former
Beijing bureau chief for the Washington Post. '' Despite all the
talk of change, and they have opened up in many ways . . . there is
still a lot of information that is not available to the Chinese
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Radio Free Asia is funded by the U.S. government in an effort to
counter China's state-controlled media with alternative news
oriented toward China and often laced with critiques of Beijing's
repressive human rights practices.
</P>
<P>
   With strong backing from Clinton, the service began broadcasting
across China _ in the local languages of Mandarin, Cantonese and
Tibetan - in 1996, over the objections of the Chinese government,
which regards the service as American propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Chinese government has always taken particular offense
with my support of creating Radio Free Asia, because they believe
that we did it for the purpose of undermining the government of
China,'' said Clinton, adding ''we think everybody ought to have
free access to ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Radio Free Asia reporters _ Arin Basu, an Indian; Patricia
Hindman, an American citizen, and Feng Xiaoming, also an American
citizen _ were assigned to cover Clinton's trip to China, along
with nearly 400 other Washington-based journalists and media
technicians.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, however, China revoked the visas it had issued
to the Radio Free Asia reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they made a big mistake,'' Clinton told the banned
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   With freedom in Tibet an issue gaining more adherents in
America, a lobbying group did manage to get into China on tourist
visas Wednesday and was awaiting the presidential entourage in
Beijing to monitor'' the visit and assure the media doesn't forget
the charges that Tibetan religious and cultural freedoms are being
suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know the limits of Chinese government tolerance for
groups such as ours, but we think it is important to be here during
the summit,'' said John Ackerly, president of the International
Campaign for Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   The American side also continued receiving a spate of letters
from human rights groups and individual Chinese, some of whom have
asked Clinton's help in getting their relatives freed from prison
or labor camps.
</P>
<P>
   The wife of detained dissident Liu Nianchun told Beijing-based
journalists she had written a letter to Clinton asking him to pay
her a visit to discuss her husband's case.
</P>
<P>
   Chu Hailan, called on Clinton to push the Chinese government to
free my husband so he can receive medical treatment.'' However, the
Clinton administration was evidently still torn over whether
Clinton should meet dissidents during his China visits.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, two Taiwanese groups fearing Clinton somehow
will accede to China's pressures to help it regain control of the
break-away island province demonstrated on Wednesday at the
American Institute in Taiwan, where U.S. interests are represented.
One banner read ``Opposing selling-out Taiwan at the Clinton-Jiang
Summit.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Simply by making this such a long trip, and by heralding it as
the emergence of a new and important relationship for the 21st
Century, Clinton created his own high-stakes game.
</P>
<P>
   The visit may be just as crucial for the political fortunes of
China's President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   The role of the 51-year old Clinton in promoting better
Sino-U.S. relations has been touted throughout the media in the
run-up to Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
   A new photo book featuring flattering pictures and highlights of
Jiang's trip to America last October was announced sold out last
week the day after it went on sale.
</P>
<P>
   And Chinese television reported Wednesday that videos of a
documentary about the visit, which proclaimed its significance and
aired for the first time last Friday, already are on back-order.
The news item did not mention that Clinton, the guy standing next
to Jiang in various shots, is arriving on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But a gush of publicity has aired in recent days about the first
American presidential visit in nearly a decade, and the general
message beaming out to the Chinese public is that this relationship
with America is important. The rest of the message is that Jiang
has worked wonders to bring relations to this point.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the state-run newspaper Market Economic News
compared the significance of the Clinton visit to the two previous
milestones in Sino-U.S. relations -- President Richard Nixon's
visit that ended hostile relations between the two nations in 1972,
and President Jimmy Carter's move to finally end formal diplomatic
ties with Taiwan and recognize mainland China instead.
</P>
<P>
   Not all factions of political China are convinced that the bold
economic changes Jiang has permitted and the budding friendship
with America are the correct routes to follow.
</P>
<P>
   A conservative bloc in the high councils of China's communist
party will be ready to pounce if Clinton steps out of what they
consider to be in line, particularly on the human rights issues the
American leader is being pressured to address by domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang and other leading officials in the last few days have
focussed on two areas they want Clinton to address: a stronger
statement that America will not accept any independence initiatives
by Taiwan, and elimination of barriers to China's economic and
trade growth.
</P>
<P>
   In China's sometimes mercuric political atmosphere, it is hard
to predict what might befall Jiang if the American side proves
embarrassingly balky on those issues. What answer Clinton gives is
less important than how he gives it.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
