<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Thursday, June 25 and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-REACTION (Undated) Antitrust regulators said Wednesday
they are proceeding at full steam in their litigation against
Microsoft, despite an appeals court ruling Tuesday that many
observers said torpedoed their case. The regulators say they've
raised several issues that are unaffected by the ruling, involving
Microsoft's exclusive contracts with online content providers and
computer makers. Analysts acknowledge that those issues are
separate, but say the question the appeals court did address --
Microsoft's strategy of integrating its Internet browser into
Wondows -- was so important that the broader case might be
crippled. Still, they say, Microsoft must be careful not to act
rashly between now and the Sept. 8 trial, or it could squander some
of the gains it made with Tuesday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   By Warren Wilson. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-ODYSSEY (Undated) The Odyssey, a converted North Sea
drilling platform that is the centerpiece of a multinational
project led by The Boeing Co. to do what's never been done before _
launch satellites into space from the ocean _ left Russia Saturday
for its homeport of Long Beach, Calif. The voyage should take about
80 days.e on the weather.The first launch is set for later this
year and Boeing could not afford to gamble on the weather. The
public can follow the Odyssey's course on a Boeing web site that
will track the platform's progress each day until it arrives at its
Long Beach beth not far from the Queen Mary.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AUTISM-GORTON (Washington, D.C.) The parents of autistic
children haven't been too happy with Slade Gorton ever since he
proposed making it easier for schoolteachers to kick out unruly
disabled children from classrooms. But their response has had an
effect on the senator; yesterday he joined ER star Anthony Edwards,
former Mariner Bill Krueger, and various other luminaries in
proposing legislation to boost funding for autism research, much of
which is conducted at the UW. Gorton also for the first time
publicly revealed thatt he has an autistic grandson _ a fact that
was unknown to his own staff until two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (story will move in the ``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WHEAT-NORTHWEST (Washington, D.C.) The House Wednesday voted
373-48 to approve an agriculture spending bill that would change
the nation's nuclear nonproliferation policy to exempt Northwest
wheat from the sanctions imposed on India and Pakistan. The
exemption can not come soon enough for Washington state wheat
growers, whose largest market is Pakistan. Wheat farmers were
already reeling from record low prices when Pakistan detonated
nuclear weapons last month, triggering automatic sanctions that
included a ban on the agricultural credits Pakistan uses to buy up
about 37 percent of the wheat grown in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (story will move in the ``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (San Diego) Mariners at San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Street. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DRAFT-SONICS (Seattle) Sonics have three picks in the late
first and early second rounds of the NBA draft Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-COLUMN-THIEL (Undated) Bill Walton says Michael Jordan will
be back next year, and he likes the Sonics' hiring of Paul
Westphal. Walton also says it is ridiculous that a strike looms
over an NBA in which both sides are making tons of money.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
