<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-SPAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARAGUAY'S VICTORY OVER NIGERIA SENDS SHATTERED SPAIN SQUAD HOME  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENS, France _ Spain Wednesday became the first great
soccer-playing nation to bow out of the World Cup as even a 6-1
victory over Bulgaria proved inadequate to secure qualification for
the second round.
</P>
<P>
   The shattered expression of veteran goalkeeper Andoni
Zubizarreta, and the tears of midfielder Fernando Hierro, caught
the agony of a proud nation that has never managed to match the
countless victories of its mythical Real Madrid and Barcelona clubs
in the supreme test of the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Spain paid for a terrible start to the tournament. After its 3-2
defeat to Nigeria and and a 0-0 draw with Paraguay, the team was
was no longer master of its own fate Wednesday, knowing that even a
convincing win would be inadequate if Paraguay beat Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely what tiny Paraguay did, winning 3-1 against a
Nigerian side that had already qualified for the second round and
fielded several substitutes. The victory meant that Paraguay, and
not Spain, joined Nigeria in the last sixteen and will meet hosts
France in the elimination phase of the competition on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saved our pride tonight,'' the Spanish coach Javier
Clemente said. ``But the defeat to Nigeria had a strong
psychological impact, and after that we struggled. What can I say?
Life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite qualifying for the World Cup ten times, and often
starting among the favorites, Spain has never managed to do better
than a fourth place in the 1950 tournament in Brazil. Since
Clemente took over in 1992, Spain has lost only four times in 54
matches, but has not been able to shake its World Cup jinx.
</P>
<P>
   It was a match that increasingly took on a surreal quality as
the teams became aware that, whatever the result, they were both
going home. For Bulgaria, which reached the semifinal of the 1994
World Cup in the United States, the game clearly marked the end of
an era as veteran players, including star striker, Hristo
Stoichkov, were substituted by the team's visibly angry coach.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset in France, Bulgaria has looked slow,
disorganized and ill-tempered, a team in visible decline. Wednesday
was no exception, and Spain quickly took advantage of the Bulgarian
disarray. The Spanish side was lifted by a glittering display from
Barcelona striker Luis Enrique, a player of unusual mobility and
vision who will now be denied a chance to make a lasting impact on
the tournament. Moving into the left side of the penalty-box in the
sixth minute, he was brought down. Fernando Hierro converted the
resulting penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes later, Luis Enrique burst onto a pass from
Etxeberria, brushed off two challenges and cooly slipped the ball
past the Bulgarian goalkeeper. In his defiant howl of jubilation,
and the accompanying raised fist, all Spain's frustration at its
initial failings was evident.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage in the match, the Spanish players clearly believed
they were set for qualification as the Nigeria-Paraguay game, being
played at the same time, was tied. Their elation, and relief, were
evident _ but fragile. Bulgaria, having tied and lost its first two
games, tried to fight back and were denied what looked like a
legitimate penalty just before halftime, when substitute Luboslav
Penev was brought down as he rounded Zubizarreta. But, in one of
many controversial decisions during this World Cup, the referee
denied Bulgaria's heated claims. Spain dominated play in the second
half, adding a third goal from the young Real Madrid striker
Francisco Morientes in the 55th minute. But soon after, word that
Paraguay had taken the lead against Nigeria clearly began to filter
onto the field, and even three more goals for Spain could not lift
the team's spirits. Morientes scored again in the 81st minute, and
substitute Kiko added two more in the 88th minute and in injury
time. Bulgaria managed one response, when striker Emil Kostadinov
blasted the ball past Zubizarreta in the 58th minute.
</P>
<P>
   But long before the end, the game had become an empty shell, a
parody of a match being played out by two eliminated teams.
Although Spanish officials privately expressed anger at Nigeria's
decision to field a second-rate side against Paraguay, they knew
that in the end they had only themselves to blame.
</P>
<P>
   In this midst of the drama, Zubizarreta stood out as a deeply
touching figure. It was his terrible mistake against Nigeria in
Spain's first game that allowed Nigeria to equalize and go on to
win the game. The 36-year-old goalkeeper and captain was faultless
Wednesday night, but it was too late for him and for Spain. In all
likelihood _ and he knew it _ this was Zubizarreta's last World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1907EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
