<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5248 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-REDCARD-     06-24 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-REDCARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFEREES AT WORLD CUP ADHERING TO DEMAND THEY GET TOUGHER  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ Joseph Blatter, the new president of FIFA,
soccer's international governing body, had a message for the
referees several hours before Cameroon was beaten by Italy last
week: they needed to get tougher.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, after Cameroon's World Cup came to an end against
Chile in another flurry of red cards, yellow cards and questionable
referee's judgements, its coach Claude Le Roy had a message for
Blatter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he should stick to administrative duties,'' Le Roy said.
</P>
<P>
   Refereeing has been a contentious subject for as long as
organized soccer has existed, but the issue has taken on new
urgency in this World Cup, where referees have reached into their
shirt pockets and scribbled names in their notebooks at a historic
clip.
</P>
<P>
   After 36 first-round games in France, the men in black had shown
15 red cards, which signify automatic expulsions. In 1994, when the
last World Cup finals were held in the United States and dangerous
tackling was already being actively discouraged, referees handed
out a total of 15 red cards in the entire tournament, which
comprised 52 matches. The number of yellow cards, or cautions, is
also on the rise compared to the last World Cup, with an average of
3.61 per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think FIFA has insisted on this, and the referees are trying
to comply,'' said French captain Didier Deschamps. ``But it's not
easy for them. They don't want us finishing our matches with seven
playing against eight.''
</P>
<P>
   Red cards have not been the only topic generating heat in
conversations in the world's living and board rooms. Debates over
penalty kicks are to soccer what debates over pass interference are
to the NFL, but there has been more grist than usual for debate in
France.
</P>
<P>
   On the second day of this competition, referee Lucien
Bouchardeau of Niger awarded Italy a penalty kick against Chile in
the 85th minute after defender Ronaldo Fuentes' right fist got in
the way of a ball kicked by Roberto Baggio. Fuentes' hand-ball
appeared unintentional, but Bouchardeau opted for the hard line.
Italy salvaged a draw, and back in the Chilean village of Glorias
Navales de Vina del Mar, local police said that a 23-year-old named
Leopoldo Oses Lagunas got into an argument with his uncle about the
call and was stabbed to death.
</P>
<P>
   After Cameroon drew with Chile on Tuesday, when an apparent goal
by goalkeeper Francois Omam-Biyik was wiped out by a questionable
foul called on Patrick Mboma, some white-owned shops were attacked
in the Cameroon capital of Yaounde in protest. Two Cameroon players
also were given red cards in that match. Soccer can be serious
business, and the fact that another controversial late penalty kick
allowed Norway to defeat Brazil on Tuesday and knock Morocco out of
the second round did not improve the mood of Joseph Owona,
Cameroon's minister of sport, who attributed it all to
discrimination against Africa.
</P>
<P>
   FIFA spokesman Keith Cooper dismissed the idea of any conspiracy
among the referees and said that ``no one had officially complained
about the refereeing.'' Nonetheless, Denmark did write to FIFA to
complain after two of its players were given red cards against
South Africa on a day when five red cards were awarded in only two
matches.
</P>
<P>
   What quickly became known as ``Red Thursday'' came the day after
Blatter said referees were not sanctioning tackles from behind
consistently. Michel Platini, the co-president of the French
Organizing Committee who will soon join Blatter at FIFA, already
had said, ``those referees who don't apply the rules will be sent
home.''
</P>
<P>
   The movement to crack down on dangerous defensive play is hardly
new. The yellow card was introduced in 1970 to provide another
means of punishing those who consistently flouted the rules, and
the push for further change began after the 1990 World Cup finals
in Italy, where Diego Maradona and other creative players spent
much of their month being hacked at from all angles. FIFA formed a
task force, composed of players, coaches and journalists, which
proposed new rules to make the game more offensive and attractive.
The movement gathered speed with the retirement of Marco Van
Basten, a Dutchman who was once considered the world's finest
striker and whose career ended before age 30 because of a series of
leg injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Former FIFA president Joao Havelange and many other
administrators, including Blatter, were convinced that Van Basten
had been victimized by too many tackles from behind. Referees in
1994 received explicit instructions to ``protect the player who
wants to play from the players who enter the field to only
destroy.'' That meant awarding red cards for dangerous tackling,
and though the number of goals increased in the United States,
Blatter, then secretary general, felt the right balance had yet to
be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   In principle, the laws of soccer have not changed since the last
World Cup. Tackles from behind and tackles that physically
jeopardize an opponent were subject to a red card in 1994, just as
they are now. What has changed is FIFA's tone and desire to see its
laws more strictly enforced. The question is when referees can give
players the benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of mixed signals out there,'' said Cameroon
defender Rigobert Song. ``I can sense some confusion on the
referee's part.''
</P>
<P>
   Platini criticizes many referees for not being able ``to feel
the flow of the game'' and has called for the professionalization
of the refereeing corps, which is still made up, even at the elite
level, of part-time employees, most of whom have other jobs to
supplement their income. He also maintains that the current system,
whereby a referee from each competing nation is given a spot int
the World Cup, is equitable but not effective. A referee from
Italy, for example, which has one of the world's strongest leagues,
has had more experience judging soccer at the speed and level at
which it is played in the World Cup than someone from Saudi Arabia,
Iran or, for that matter, the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``In truth there are great differences in level between them,''
Platini said. ''The first two matches of this World Cup really
started well, and after that it got bad. We only should put the
best in the World Cup, even if it penalizes some countries.''
</P>
<P>
   There also have been calls for the use of video to judge vital
sequences, like whether a ball has crossed the goal-line or whether
a penalty kick should be awarded. That is a controversial concept
in a conservative sport, but not as controversial as the idea of
adding a second referee on the field to help cover more of the
action.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
