<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FRANCE-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 FRANCE URGES ALLIES TO DEFINE PLAN FOr AUTONOMY FOR KOSOVO  
(See also KOSOVO-U.S.) 
(bl) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France called Wednesday for an international plan to
restore autonomy to Kosovo province in Serbia, with the threat of
NATO military intervention if Serbian authorities did not quickly
agree to negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Contingency planning intensified at NATO headquarters in
Brussels on Wednesday, Allied diplomats said, as special U.S. envoy
Richard Holbrooke met with Albanian leaders in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   His meeting came a day after he pressed Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to stop Serbian attacks and resume political
talks with the rebels. Serbia and Montenegro are the last republics
remaining in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials are also meeting this week with Serbian
authorities to try to get talks restarted.
</P>
<P>
   A top Albanian political leader in Kosovo, Ibrahim Rugova, said
in Brussels on Wednesday, ``It's difficult to talk when ethnic
cleansing is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   But NATO Secretary General Javier Solana warned Rugova that the
Allies did not support independence, which is the rebels' goal.
Kosovo had autonomy within the Yugoslav federation until Milosevic,
then president of Serbia, revoked it in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Some 90 percent of Kosovo's population is ethnic Albanian, and
with more than a third of the province now controlled by rebels,
French officials said, they fear events could quickly spin out of
control and spread fighting to Albania and Macedonia. Both
countries have called for NATO intervention to prevent a widening
of the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This seems to me the right moment for the international
community to define a statute of genuine autonomy for Kosovo,''
said French President Jacques Chirac at a Cabinet meeting Wednesday
morning. ``That is necessary to restart negotiations between the
two parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Chirac also said only ``very firm action by the international
community,'' including the threat of military force, could break
the cycle of violence in Kosovo as it did in Bosnia three years
ago, after years of ineffective United Nations peacekeeping action
there.
</P>
<P>
   But he said France continued to believe that a mandate from the
U.N. Security Council would be needed before NATO could go into
action in Kosovo. Both Russia and China, permanent members of the
Security Council with the right of veto, oppose military
intervention.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Russia, the United States, France, Germany, Italy and Britain,
the ``contact group,'' issued a call in London on June 12 for
Serbia to stop its attacks, withdraw its military forces and resume
talks with ethnic Albanian leaders in Kosovo, or face the
possibility of NATO action. Some 200 to 300 civilians have been
killed by Serbian forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Russian President Boris Yeltsin the following
week, Milosevic said he would start the talks but he did not agree
to withdraw his forces. The 16 nations of NATO continued to draw up
military plans, and Allied ambassadors in Brussels ordered that the
plans be ready to be carried out within 24 hours of a political
decision to go ahead, some officials said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said the planning covered options from
large-scale air strikes against Serbian air defenses and other
strategic sites all over Yugoslavia, through moving peacekeeping
troops or monitors onto the border between Albania and Kosovo.
Another option, the officials said, was simply to stage another
demonstration of air power like the one held over Albania and
Macedonia last week to try to intimidate Serb commanders.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said that Serbian forces had apparently sealed
off much of the Albanian border and that only a dozen refugees from
Kosovo a day had been seen moving across, compared with hundreds a
day earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   France, which has backed the military planning, pressed for as
wide a range of options as possible and resisted NATO military
authorities who urged a quick, heavy series of air strikes as the
only action that would impress the Serbs, French officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
