<SLUG> BC-BOX-DOUGLAS-SAVARESE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUGLAS AND SAVARESE LOOKING PAST THEIR FIGHT TO SOME BIG MONEY
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET, Conn. _ James ``Buster'' Douglas and Lou Savarese
are both looking at their bout here at the Foxwoods Resort Casino
on Thursday night as crucial to the heavyweight division's future.
That would be laughable if the division wasn't such a shambles. The
fighter left standing here may well be in line to fight Evander
Holyfield or Lennox Lewis for a title or a big payday.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas (36-5-1) and Savarese (37-2) are headlining a card that
includes a welterweight bout between Julio Cesar Chavez (100-2-2)
and Ken Sigurani (22-1), a middleweight bout between Dana
Rosenblatt (30-1) and Arthur Allen (23-3) and a women's
superlightweight bout between Lucia Rijker (10-0) and Lisa Ested
(6-1). The fights will be broadcast on TVKO pay per view.
</P>
<P>
   Now that ``Seinfeld'' is in summer reruns, Bob Arum, of Top Rank
Boxing, is banking on Thursday night television viewers being
willing to spend money on another show about nothing. Chavez was
added to prop the card up, and for his effort was given a lucrative
rematch against Oscar De La Hoya in September. Arum has promised
Chavez a $250,000 bonus if he knocks Sigurani out.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas, who was in a diabetic coma and weighed more than 400
pounds two years ago, is trying to salvage self-respect in the
sport and make a few bucks. Savarese, who has lost two of his last
three bouts, is looking at this as his last stand. ``I want to be
on top of the game,'' Savarese said. ``I don't want to be a
journeyman. This is my fight. I have to win this fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Since emerging from his coma and trimming off what amounts to a
middleweight boxer _ 160 pounds _ Douglas has fought, and won, six
times. But his last bout was nearly a year ago, on July 13, 1997,
against Quinn Navarre. An October bout was scuttled because he
injured his hand. Douglas, 38, believes a good showing against
Savarese, 32, will put him in line for possible bouts against Lewis
and Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a point where they are running out of bodies,''
Douglas said. ``Being impressive against Savarese will put me in
line. There will be a public demand. This will put me in the middle
of the road. People will be saying, `Why are you ducking him?'''
</P>
<P>
   A quick inventory of the division gives credence to Douglas'
estimation. Holyfield, the World Boxing Association and
International Boxing Federation champion, is waiting for Henry
Akinwande's hepatitis B to clear up so that he can defend the WBA
title. After that, Vaughn Bean, the IBF No. 1 contender, is waiting
for the champion.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the World Boxing Council champion, has a date with Zeljko
Mavrovic on Sept. 26 in a mandatory bout. Mike Tyson, who can
appeal his current suspension on July 9, is on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   And if that isn't enough, George Foreman, 49, and Larry Holmes,
48, are expected to square off in January in a senior heavyweight
bout. Douglas, who knocked Tyson out in 1990 to win the undisputed
heavyweight championship and lost the title to Holyfield in his
next bout, has already been mentioned as a possible opponent for
Tyson if his suspension is lifted. Douglas said that people still
view his knockout victory over Tyson as a fluke and he views his
knockout loss to Holyfield as an embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese has been training with Holyfield's personal trainer,
Tim Hallmark. Savarese spent 13 weeks doing the same workout that
transformed Holyfield from a cruiserweight to a heavyweight. The
regimen includes sprints instead of traditional roadwork, plus
weight training, which is normally taboo for boxers. In addition,
Savarese has been doing yoga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
