<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-US-YUGO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS HAVE TO GET SERIOUS AGAINST YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ It would be nice to give old boys like Marcelo
Balboa one last turn around the pitch in a star-spangled jersey. To
let Preki Radosavljevic catch up on things with his old countrymen.
Or to give a nod to 2002 and put the rookies out there.
</P>
<P>
   The US men's soccer team has been eliminated from the World Cup
since last Sunday, after all. So why not treat Thursday night's
group finale with Yugoslavia at the Stade de La Beaujoire like a
consolation match?
</P>
<P>
   Because it's a consolation match only for the Yanks, who are
playing for pride and a feel-good point or 3 before scattering for
home tomorrow. The Yugoslavs are out for blood.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing personal, mind you, even though the US government treats
Yugoslavia (i.e., Serbia and Montenegro) as an outlaw state. ``We
will play against the US as any other match,'' insists captain
Dragan Stojkovic. ``The politics, it does not concern us.''
</P>
<P>
   All Stojkovic and his mates want from the Americans are the 3
points they thought they had against the Germans last time. The
Yugoslavs, who hadn't beaten Germany in 25 years, were leading,
2-0, with 14 minutes left _ and stopped playing. The Germans
promptly popped in two goals in six minutes and walked off with a
draw.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Yugoslavs held on, they already would be through to the
second round. Now, unless Germany defeats Iran in Montpellier
Thursday night, Yugoslavia needs at least a draw against the US to
advance. What the Yugoslavs really want, though, is to win the
group and play a runner-up in Montpellier instead of a victor in
Toulouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win big, we go to Montpellier,'' says Miljan Miljanic,
president of the Yugoslav football federation. ``If we win small,
we go to Toulouse. If we lose big, we go to Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Americans don't show up and play, they could be on the
short end of a long score, and they know it. So whom will coach
Steve Sampson have in his lineup? Except that he'll start Brad
Friedel in goal, Sampson isn't saying. ``Whether it's the old guard
or the new guard,'' he says, ``the best 11 players will be on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the old guard _ striker Eric Wynalda, defenders
Alexi Lalas and Marcelo Balboa, and midfielder Radosavljevic _ have
been on the field little or not at all during the tournament and
aren't particularly happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players come here to play, not to sit on the bench,'' says
Sampson. ``It's normal for players who aren't seeing playing time
to voice their frustrations.''
</P>
<P>
   After the opening 2-0 loss to Germany, Sampson started five new
faces against Iran because he wanted an attacking lineup. Odds are
he'll go with a more balanced look, with more defenders in the
midfield. ``Yugoslavia is an elite team,'' Sampson says. ``We have
to play intelligently, but at the same time, we have to take risks
to create scoring opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, who are only 2-5-3 in their last 10 matches with
but three goals in their last five, want dearly to take home a
stuffed bear from this global church bazaar after reaching the
second round in 1994. ``We'd like to finish on a good note,'' says
defender David Regis. ``We're going to play seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs, who were banned from the last Cup because of
their government's ``ethnic cleansing'' policies, are going to play
for survival and redemption. Though the country that qualified for
seven Cups after World War II has broken apart, the reputation of
its soccer team _ inventive but undisciplined, brilliant but
mercurial _ endures.
</P>
<P>
   Blowing a two-goal lead to the Germans was just another line on
the resume. Same old Yugos. ``That's why everyone calls us the
Brazilians of Europe,'' sighs Miljanic. ``We do not win many
tournaments but we play beautiful football. We are like a beautiful
woman with no brain.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the Yugoslavs are on, as when they vaporized Hungary,
7-1 and 5-0, to qualify for the Cup, they score goals in bunches.
They may have nothing personal against Uncle Sam, but he happens to
be in the way. So if the Yanks treat the contest like a church
bazaar, they may go home with the booby prize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
