<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-EUSTIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM EUSTIS; FOUNDED VT. MUSIC FESTIVAL; AT 36  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A memorial service will be held on Saturday for William J.
Eustis, chief executive officer of Eustis Cable Enterprises Ltd.,
dog lover and founder of the annual Funk and Blues Festival in
Brookfield, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Eustis was a self-taught businessman whose cable
installation operation stretched from the United States to
Indonesia. He died last Thursday when he fell from a cliff in
Jamaica. He was 36.
</P>
<P>
   Friends described him as an inveterate Dead Head _ a devotee of
the Grateful dead rock group _ whose personal style statement
tended toward jeans, open shirts and a perpetual smile. Each
August, he sponsored the Blues and Funk festival on his farm and
donated the proceeds to the local elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   He made news in St. Petersburg, Fla., on May 17, 1997, when he
hired an airplane to trail a banner over the city offering a reward
for the return of his dog, a pit bull terrier named Samson, who had
been abducted while Mr. Eustis was preoccupied with a cable
installation crew.
</P>
<P>
   According to an account published on the front page of the St.
Petersburg Times, Mr. Eustis paid $585 to the pilot and offered a
$5,000 reward.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot said he saw throngs of people on the streets looking
for the dog. Some would break off and search in pairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who has ever loved a dog knew I wasn't crazy,'' said
Mr. Eustis. ``If he lives another five years, that's pretty cheap
loving over five years.''
</P>
<P>
   The man who had absconded with the dog took it home. When his
wife saw the pooch, she kicked them both out. They slept overnight
in a car.
</P>
<P>
   Hounded by the thought that his high profile theft would soon be
discovered, he arranged to return Samson to Mr. Eustis in a
supermarket parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The dognapper declined the $5,000 reward, but Mr. Eustis
insisted that he take $500. He said his reunion with Samson was
sweeter for him than it was for the dog, which had grown fond of
his temporary master. ``I'd been missing him and he'd been out
having fun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Eustis was born in Japan. He graduated from Tabor Academy in
Marion and attended Ithaca College in New York.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mr. Eustis' uncle, Samson is now living in
``semi-retirement'' in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Eustis leaves his parents, Ralph and Merry Eustis of
Mattapoisett, Mass.; a brother, Ralph of Vernon, Conn.; and his
longtime companion Lisa Michel of Brookfield.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
