A5274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-TAXCUTS-EDUC     06-24 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TAXCUTS-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE BACKS BILL OFFERING TAX BREAKS FOR EDUCATIONAL EXPENSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Ga., Mass.)   (bl)  
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Wednesday voted to send President
Clinton a bill that would provide tax breaks for parents who save
for education costs, including private school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has said he would veto the legislation. In a
recent letter to House Speaker Newt Gingrich, Clinton called the
bill ``bad education policy and bad tax policy'' that embraces the
wealthy, shrugs off the poor and siphons federal tax dollars from
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   With the votes in the House and Senate falling slightly short of
the numbers needed to override a veto, Republicans and Democrats
will take competing education agendas to the public for the
November elections _ one that calls for funneling money into public
schools and another that advocates redirecting that money to
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, a compromise between the House and the Senate,
passed the Senate 59-36.
</P>
<P>
   While the bill is the centerpiece of a Republican education
agenda and is designed to make in-roads on an issue that Democrats
have successfully used to their advantage, it drew some Democratic
support. Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., co-sponsored the bill with
its chief architect, Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a simple idea,'' said Torricelli. ``How basic. American
families can save their own money, in their own savings accounts,
without taxation, to educate their own children in the school of
their own choice. What possible argument could anyone have with
that proposal? And yet people have found reason to object.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which would expands a program that promotes
saving for college, would allow family members and other sponsors
to contribute up to $2,000 a year to special savings accounts for
individual elementary and secondary school students. The money
would have to be used for education expenses, like tutoring,
computers and private and religious school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Interest on the money and withdrawals from the account would be
tax free and could be rolled over for college expenses. The
program, which would cost the federal government $1.6 billion over
10 years, would be phased out for individuals who make more than
$95,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the debate the two parties have used statistics to
their own advantage. While Coverdell maintains that the bill would
benefit 20 million children and lead to savings of $12 billion over
10 years, Democrats say that the average yearly benefit for a
student would be minuscule, between $7 and $37.
</P>
<P>
   To try to draw Democratic support and thwart a veto, House and
Senate negotiators removed several contentious provisions from the
bill and added a few sweeteners, including $210 million for reading
programs. The move appealed to some Democrats but not enough to
override a veto.
</P>
<P>
   With dogged persistence, Republicans have seized on Coverdell's
proposal, the only major education legislation in Congress this
year, to castigate Clinton for his stance on education, which they
view as unimaginative, short-sighted and beholden to the teachers'
unions.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have long favored a policy of ``school choice,''
which has grown in grass-roots popularity. It would permit tax
dollars to be used for private schools as a way of making public
schools more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   But the concept is reviled by Democrats who frame it as a
Republican attempt to abandon public schools in favor of religious
and other private schools, and they point to Coverdell's bill as
the first step leading down that path. Most Democrats advocate
earmarking funds to repairing schools, building new ones and hiring
more teachers, and tried several times to derail Coverdell's bill.
</P>
<P>
   On the Senate floor Wednesday, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.,
criticized Republicans for pushing the bill at the same time that
House Republicans had voted in a subcommittee to slash funds for
summer jobs programs and educational technology, among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cut back $1.8 billion yesterday, and they are over here
now in the United States Senate saying we are doing the most
revolutionary thing for public school students,'' Kennedy said.
``This is an absolute sham.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
