<HEADER>
A5275 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-HOOLIGANS-BOS &LR;      06-24 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-HOOLIGANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS SEEK SOLUTION TO HOOLIGANISM PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Many solutions have been proposed for ``the hooligan
problem.'' British newspapers have called for the banning of
English teams from international soccer competition. In the 1980s,
then Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher tried issuing Orwellian-style
identification cards to fans. Before the England-Romania World Cup
match in Toulouse Tuesday, a Romanian Mafioso offered ``to calm''
the hooligans along with some compatriots _ provided he be released
from a French prison.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem is not so simple. First of all, it is not
confined to English supporters. Germans best described as
``pseudo''-neo-Nazis have been involved in the most disturbing act
of violence at France '98. After Germany and Yugoslavia tied, 2-2,
Sunday, three policemen were attacked outside Stade Felix Bollaert
in Lens, leaving David Nivel, a 43-year-old squadron commander,
comatose.
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Helmut Kohl called the incident ``a national
disgrace,'' and the Germans offered to pull out of the World Cup.
The request was denied by tournament organizers, who were
especially disturbed because it occurred on FIFA Fair Play Day,
when Iran and the United States were meeting in relative peace.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 91 arrests at France '98, most occurring in
Marseille, where England met Tunisia in its opening game. Markus
Warnecke, 27, of Hamburg and Karl-Heinz Elschn, 27, of Brunswick
were arrested for assaulting Nivel. England's second game was
relatively calm, but authorities are preparing for a potential
hooligan battle when England meets Colombia in Lens tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   And things could get worse. If England qualifies for the second
round, it could confront Argentina, recalling memories of the
Falklands/Malvinas conflict. After that, there is a possible
quarterfinal date with Germany or Holland _ hooligan heaven for
some, a nightmare for most.
</P>
<P>
   But first, there is the matter of England advancing. England
needs at least a tie against Colombia to move on and appears
capable of accomplishing that. The English qualified for France '98
by playing for such a result in a 0-0 draw with Italy in Rome in a
pressure-filled atmosphere of clashes between fans and police. The
Italians were perceived as heavy-handed as 40 fans were arrested
and five injured.
</P>
<P>
   French World Cup organizers have attempted to be more tolerant.
</P>
<P>
   But as Nivel remains on the edge of death, tension is bound to
increase between law enforcement officers and exuberant fans. There
will be increased vigilance because of the presence of two of
England's most famous supporters _ Prince Charles and Prince Harry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed there were about 20,000 supporters in Marseille
and Toulouse,'' said Stephen Beauchampe, former international
officer of the Football Supporters Association and now a journalist
with the BBC. ``There will be double that in Lens, and most don't
have tickets. I'm worried about what could happen because there has
been so much talk for so long about trouble in Lens that it could
be a self-fulfilling prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is sold out and tickets are only available on the
black market. Lens is a small venue for an enormous amount of fans,
and it is only three hours from London on the train. A lot of
people are flying to Brussels because all the flights to France are
booked. It's a Friday night. There is the added significance
because England are facing defeat. This has the potential to be the
biggest problem of the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   The capacity of Stade Felix Bollaert is 41,275, larger than the
population of Lens, a coal mining town north of Paris. Lens was
awarded six World Cup matches because it is among the most
supportive cities of soccer _ RC Lens won the French championship
last season. Lens's economy has been declining, and the World Cup
was supposed to boost its image.
</P>
<P>
   To minimize trouble, Lens Mayor Andre Delelis is encouraging
businesses to close during the match. Even Zebulon, the bar which
serves as headquarters for fans of RC Lens, will likely comply.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol sales have been banned within a 50-kilometer radius of
Lens. An additional 1,200 police and gendarmes, plus 100
plainclothes officers, will be present, according to Daniel Cadoux,
prefect of Pas de Calais. English fans will be under surveillance
by ``spotters'' especially wary of Category C hooligans, those with
criminal records.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly not unique to Britain, and what is happening
here is an eerie recall to Italy '90, when the English had problems
in Sardinia and the Germans had problems in Milan,'' said John
Williams, director of the Sir Norman Chester Centre for Football
Research at Leicester University. ``Some Germans have said they
want to show the English we are up for it as well as they are. And
when a local group, such as the Tunisians in Marseille, are
involved, the problems can escalate.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said most of the hooligan problems have been solved in
England, where the Premier League is thriving and soccer has become
very fashionable and richer than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dutch and Italians have domestic problems related to the
nature of nationhood, history, traditions, and masculinity,'''
Williams said. ``There are strong supporters of club sides in
Italy, but their identity resides with the club and the city state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Germany and England are different. They each have a recent
historical tradition of a real and perceived role in the world
which is quite similar, and their reaction to other races is
similar. England is influenced by its recent colonial past, and
Germany is undergoing the strains of unification and the
integration of migrant Poles and Turks. Between the two countries,
you have a very strong, bellicose, almost innate sense of
superiority. They are almost competing for the world hooligan
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the blame for problems at the World Cup has been placed
on FIFA and the CFO, the French Organizing Committee, for the
ticket distribution plan. Since the black market is thriving, fans
are encouraged to try their luck, creating a glut of ticketless
fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scotland was allocated 3,000 tickets and there were 20,000
Scots at their games,'' Williams said. ``They paid large amounts of
money to buy tickets from another source.''
</P>
<P>
   The hooligan problem is not about to disappear. But as long as
rival groups remain separated, it can be controlled. This was the
lesson of the first two England games at France '98. In Marseille,
the North African immigrant population is high, providing a
perceived threat to hooligans. In Toulouse, the aeronautics
industry thrives, and the game was played on a weekday night. Both
Marseille and Toulouse are nearly 1,000 miles from London. Lens is
much closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of the 30,000 or so who will come to Lens, 200-400 will be
looking for trouble,'' Beauchampe said. ``But there is more
determination among supporters to try to calm things down, like the
Scots have done over the years. There will be occasional blips like
Marseille, but at the stadium in Marseille, there were no issues.
The trend is that things are improving quite a bit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
