<HEADLINE>
PIONEER GROUP EXPECTS SECOND-QUARTER LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Citing its troubled natural resource operations and
roiled markets in Russia and Asia, The Pioneer Group Inc. said
Wednesday that it would report a loss of around $10 million, or
$0.40 per share, for the second quarter ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The diversified asset management company blamed the shortfall _
which comes after earnings of $0.21 a share in the previous quarter
_ on its Siberian timber project, Moscow bank, and gold mine in
Ghana. Analysts had forecast Pioneer's second-quarter net income at
around $0.21 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setback, the Boston-based company, which earns most
of its revenues from its US mutual fund business, said it expected
its worldwide operations to be profitable for the last six months
of this year. Shares in Pioneer, which has over $23 billion in
assets under management, slipped 1 5/16 to close at 26 5/16
Wednesdayon the New York Stock Exchange. .
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer is now seeking a strategic partner for its timber
business, which has been felled by log prices that are at historic
lows and depressed demand from Asian consumers. The company will
adjust downward the value of its log inventory by $2 million for
the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Citing power supply glitches at the company's gold mine, Pioneer
chief financial officer William H. Keogh said he anticipated more
disruptions in gold output later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Other losses came from the Pioneer Bank in Moscow, in which
Pioneer has an 80 percent stake. Keogh said Pioneer still planned
to sell a 35 percent stake in the bank to an Estonian bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
