<SLUG> BC-MA-DEREG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILITY DEREG CAMPAIGN DEALT BLOW IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The effort to repeal utility deregulation in this state
was dealt a serious blow Wednesday when the Supreme Judicial Court
ruled against some of the campaign's signature collection
practices.
</P>
<P>
   But the State Ballot Law Commission will have the final say when
it decides _ as early as today _ whether the ruling should be
applied to all the signatures.
</P>
<P>
   While the Committee for Fair Electric Rates collected more than
enough signatures to win a spot on the ballot, the state's highest
court said volunteers made a big mistake when they altered petition
sheets with a highlighter pen and placed the group's name with a
return address on others.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the ruling, more than 10,000 signatures would be
rejected, leaving only 100 extra signatures keeping it on the
ballot. But depending on what the Ballot Law Commission decides,
that number could drop well below the amount needed to put the
issue before voters in November.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's decision is expected to hinge on a
technicality.
</P>
<P>
   The retail and industrial groups who took the matter to the SJC
claiming unfair signature collection practices may have made a
fatal mistake. When the objectors stated their case, they were
supposed to supply a list of all the signatures they were
challenging. But they accidentally left out signatures from
Barnstable and Berkshire counties.
</P>
<P>
   The commission will have to decide whether signatures from those
counties should be covered by the ruling. If they are, the ballot
question will die.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how I'd like them to come down,'' said Robert Ruddock,
executive vice president of the Association Industries of
Massachusetts, which challenged the signatures. ``We believe we
have a good case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruddock said the return address information printed on the
signatory sheets contained the name of the Committee for Fair
Electric Rates, which ``turned a document into propaganda.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't simply their return address, it was the name of
their organization, which was a slogan to persuade people,''
Ruddock added.
</P>
<P>
   John O'Connor, who is leading the repeal of deregulation, said
he was outraged by the SJC ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pathetic that the Supreme Court threw out 10,000
signatures simply because our volunteers stamped a return address
on the petition,'' said O'Connor, who is organizing the repeal
effort and running for the 8th Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when democracy is beleaguered, when big money is
corrupting or soiling the democratic process, that the Supreme
Court has sided with big money over grassroots efforts I think says
something about the relationship between the utility companies and
the those in power in this state,'' O'Connor added.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor is trying to repeal deregulation because he says the 10
percent initial discount customers are receiving on their power
bills is too small and that there is no real utility competition in
the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0380 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5281 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-A-PLUS-0624-COX     06-24 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-A-PLUS-0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE APPROVES EDUCATION ACCOUNTS AND SPARKS PARTISAN BATTLE
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders plan to gather in the Capitol's
august Statuary Hall on Thursday to hail final congressional
approval of education savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, approved by the Senate on Wednesday, will likely go to
President Clinton's desk after the July 4th recess, and Clinton has
said repeatedly he will veto it.
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, Republicans plan to extract as much
political mileage out of the legislation as they can. Sen. Paul
Coverdell, R-Ga., who is the chief sponsor of the measure and who
is up for re-election this year, plans to fly around Georgia next
Wednesday to promote the education bill, and he is urging his
Republican colleagues to do likewise during the upcoming
congressional break.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be well armed when they leave here,'' Coverdell said
Wednesday after the Senate vote. ``It is a great message and a
great victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell's legislation would allow parents, guardians and other
third parties such as unions and corporations to contribute up to
$2,000 annually to tax-free savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Money from the accounts could be used to fund private school
tuition, public school fees, tutoring costs, or books and supplies.
Unrelated language in the bill extends business tax deductions for
companies that send employees for further education, and authorizes
the Department of Education to spend $210 million on reading
programs.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a provision to allow federal funds to be spent on
same-sex public schools or classes, sponsored by Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison (R-Texas).
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want is for every parent in our country to have the
same option that a parent who can afford private school has,''
Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., a co-sponsor of the
legislation, and Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., said they would seek a
meeting with Clinton to prevail on him to sign the bill, but other
Democrats predicted that Clinton will hold fast on his veto pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not only say to the president, don't sign it _ I'd say
veto it,'' said Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass. ``What this bill does is
comfort the comfortable and do very little to assist the problems
of those who are in the most challenged areas of our school system
in this nation. And that's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, one of eight Democrats to vote for the bill, said 70
percent of the tax benefits would go to families earning less than
$75,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a bill that comforts the comforted,'' Lieberman
said. ``This is a bill that lightens the burden on the overburdened
middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats opposed to the legislation have also begun to stake
out political ground to attack the Republicans on in this election
year. In addition to accusing the Republicans of blocking Clinton's
proposals to reduce class sizes and repair school buildings,
Democrats will also hammer the GOP for proposing new cuts to
education spending.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the House Appropriations subcommittee handling
education eliminated $860 million in funding for summer jobs
programs and rebuffed Clinton's requests for money to place
violence prevention coordinators in 6,500 schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``You find me an educator ... that does not believe that funding
those summer jobs is light years more important than this program
about a potential savings that is going to go primarily to the
private school,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass. ``What
hypocrisy.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
