<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5285 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-JAIL-SUICIDES-BOS &LR;      06-24 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-JAIL-SUICIDES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAIL SUICIDE RATE SOARING IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ZACHARY R. DOWDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Angela Arduini, 33, was awaiting trial at
MCI-Framingham on charges of assault and shoplifting when she tied
prison bedding to her neck and hanged herself last July.
</P>
<P>
   She left a suicide note behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' said &UR;  &LR; Ruth Arduini of Worcester, Angela's
mother. ``She was supposed to be on suicide watch. If she was, we
can't understand why they gave her a sheet in her cell.''
</P>
<P>
   Arduini's death was one reason Massachusetts had a prison
suicide rate last year nearly four times the national rate,
according to a study by the National Center on Institutions and
Alternatives, which trains criminal justice agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The study, funded by the US Department of Justice, found that
the state's prison suicide rate was 74 per 100,000. The national
rate is 21 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates say the number of suicides over a longer period is
alarming, too. The state's five-year prison suicide rate is 38 per
100,000, nearly double the national rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extraordinarily high,'' said James Pingeon, an attorney
who handles prison-related cases at the Center for Public
Representation. ``If it was one bad year you could say it's a
fluke, but a five-year period gives you a trustworthy sample. It
seems clear that people are dying because they don't get adequate
mental health treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight prisoners turned their cells into scaffolds last year,
despite scrutiny by prisoner advocates since the November 1996
suicide of inmate John C. Salvi III, who had been convicted of
murdering two women at Brookline reproductive clinics.
</P>
<P>
   After Salvi's death, the University of Massachusetts Medical
Center found critical gaps in the Department of Correction's
psychiatric services. But &UR;  &LR; the most urgent suggestions, including
that the staff of full-time psychiatrists be boosted from four to
nine, have not been followed because of lack of funding, DOC
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Dennehy, DOC deputy commissioner, said the department
has retrained staffers and implemented UMass recommendations that
did not require money. She said the DOC has required Correctional
Medical Services, whose contract was just renewed for three years,
to meet all of the report's requirements.
</P>
<P>
   So far in 1998, no suicides have been reported by the DOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any single death is of concern to us,'' Dennehy said.
</P>
<P>
   John Noonan, director of health services for the DOC, said CMS
is forming a partnership with UMass to provide psychiatric services
once the new contract is finalized.
</P>
<P>
   State representative Kay Khan, a Newton Democrat who had tried
to raise the DOC's funding for mental health services by $2 million
last year, is again urging passage of legislation to get prisoners
help.
</P>
<P>
   The House is mulling a measure that increases the DOC's $44.3
million budget for health services by $3 million and earmarks
enough &UR;  &LR; money for the &UR;  &LR; nine full-time psychiatrists. The Senate is
considering similar legislation, but its version provides nearly
$800,000 less and does not include mental health services.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not addressing prisoners' mental health needs, because
all the suicides had psychiatric histories,'' Khan said.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Lee would agree. The Dorchester woman said her son, Andre
Brown, committed suicide after three years in prison and an hour
after he was put on suicide watch in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he was adequately cared for,'' said Lee, still
angry at DOC officials. ``Prison is not a place where they're
interested in treating people for mental illness. It's dangerous
that these people can have this kind of control and are not held
accountable for what happens to people in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   The UMass report estimated that between 12 and 15 percent of
prisoners have major mental illnesses such as schizophrenia or
manic depression. Pingeon has said that 25 percent of all prisoners
have milder disorders that would warrant professional treatment
outside prison.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other tragedies linked to prisoners' mental
illness: In 1996, an undiagnosed prisoner with schizophrenia gouged
out his own eyes; in 1994, a mentally ill prisoner bludgeoned his
cellmate to death and proudly summoned correction officers to
inspect the carnage on the cell floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised the suicide rate isn't higher because life in
prison is meaningless,'' said Jill Brotman, executive director of
the Massachusetts Prison Society, an advocacy group. ``The cuts in
rehabilitative programs over the last five or six years only serve
to further cripple and enrage people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay M. Hayes, who monitors such suicides for the National
Center on Institutions and Alternatives, said Massachusetts prisons
have long had higher-than-normal suicide rates, citing a 10-year
study (1984-1993) that showed a rate of 32 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Massachusetts has a prisoner population that is only
25th in size among the 50 states and facilities run by the Federal
Bureau of Prisons, its suicide rate over that 10-year period was
16th. The national suicide rate in the general population is 12 per
100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly what I was predicting,'' said James Gilligan,
who was the state's clinical director of prison mental health
services from 1981 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Gilligan said, a murder a month and a suicide
every six weeks was not uncommon. In 1977, prisoners successfully
sued the state, resulting in federal oversight of medical and
psychiatric care until 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1991, US District Judge W. Arthur Garrity dismissed the
case. Shortly thereafter, then-governor William F. Weld fired 23
psychiatrists and social workers from Gilligan's group. Gilligan
and psychiatrist Joan Eccleston quickly resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the courts walked out, the state went back to business as
usual,'' he said. ``I didn't want to keep up a charade that we
could meet mental health service needs of this population.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
