r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-24 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
INFORMING ON INFORMER ORWELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new 20-volume edition of  &UR; George Orwell &LR; 's works reveals that
the writer informed on  &UR; Charlie Chaplin &LR; ,  &UR; George Bernard &LR; 
 &UR; Shaw &LR; , poets  &UR; C. Day-Lewis &LR;  and  &UR; Stephen Spender &LR; , novelist  &UR; J.B. &LR; 
 &UR; Priestley &LR;  and theologian  &UR; Reinhold  &UR; Niebuhr &LR; , as
``crypto-communists.''
</P>
<P>
   Orwell gave an alphabetical list of 130 names to an arm of the
British Foreign Office, &LR;  shortly before he died of tuberculosis in
1950. The editor of the new publication, which for the first time
names names, has withheld 30  &LR; names of people still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``1984'' and ``Animal Farm'' defined himself as a
fervent socialist but equally fervent anti-totalitarian.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PROSE AND PLEATS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Excerpts from fashion designers' published notes about their
fall 1998 collections, as reported in GQ:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prada &LR;  cites ``Transmigration of winter chromosomes, between
form and use,'' which GQ translates to mean ``Ducks fly south, but
you cannot wear them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sandy Dalal &LR;  says, ``Ugly beauty came over me like a thrilling
rash,'' which GQ interprets as ``My plaid pants gave me German
measles. O happy life! O songs of joy!''
</P>
<P>
   Says  &UR; Issey Miyake &LR; , ``People, galaxies, carnage and sea
urchins/Eat cosmic debris.'' Says GQ: ``No translation available.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; Look what Monday's item about  &UR; Cybill Shepherd &LR;  dragged in:
the ol' People Who Know People game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Philip Tucker &LR; 's mother was Shepherd's Brownie troop leader.
 &UR; Margot Smith &LR; 's mother was a friend of  &UR; Lorna Luft &LR; 's grandmother,
who used to cook blintzes for her. And  &UR; Alex Behr &LR; 's husband's
co-worker's mother went to a beauty salon where  &UR; Monica Lewinsky &LR; 
once worked.
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; Country singer  &UR; Reba McEntire &LR;  told Country America magazine
that  &UR; James Cameron &LR;  wanted her to play the role of
unsinkable &UR; Molly Brown &LR;  in ``Titanic,'' but a conflicting concert
tour prevented preventing  &LR; her from signing.  &UR; Kathy Bates &LR;  got the
part instead.
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; Following last week's item about the Cockettes documentary,
 &UR; Kreemah Ritz &LR; , one of the original members of the troupe, sends
word that he is working on a book about the Cockettes, as well as
designing an exhibit  &LR; exhibition about another Cockette,
``Sylvester: Metamorphosis,'' to open this fall at the Gay &AMP;
Lesbian Historical Society and the Hormel Center at the Main
Library.
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; After officials in Maine tried to ban  &UR; Dorothy Allison &LR; 's
novel ``Bastard Out of Carolina, &LR; '' in that state's schools,
novelist  &UR; Tabitha King  &LR; (wife of  &UR; Stephen King &LR; ), &LR;  paid for copies
of the book to be sent privately to high school students there,
says Girlfriends magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; ``X-Files'' star  &UR; David Duchovny &LR;  told Movieline magazine
that he's learned lots about acting from his dog. ``And what
lessons has your dog taught you?'' asks the interviewer. ``Just
total focus,'' says Duchovny. ``Total concentration. Maybe one ear
goes back to figure something out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOUR WAYS TO ESCAPE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jeanne Martinet &LR; , who's written ``The Art of Mingling,''
suggests in Maxim magazine that there are four steps to the art of
non- &LR; mingling, that is, getting away from a boring conversation:
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; Use anything the bore says as a bridge to another subject
(``So you found a way to get discount airline tickets, eh? How much
do you make anyway?'')
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; Make a human sacrifice (``Oh, there's my friend, Joe. Joe,
have you met Don?'') and then slip away.
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; Say a simple ``It was nice meeting you,'' and walk away on
the spot.
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; Bring up a subject so boring that the person who has been
boring you walks away in disgust. (Maxim suggests ``an article you
read in Esquire.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Once, when we were away, Dumpling, our eight-foot-long,
30-pound boa constrictor, went through our library pulling out
books and throwing them on the floor like a petulant child. As I
picked up the books, I noticed that every one was by my wife's
favorite author, Danielle Steel.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &LR; From a Modern Maturity story about the sensibilities of pets,
as noted by  &UR; Betsy Nolan &LR; .
</P>
