<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5293 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      06-24 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (pr) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, June 25. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927; e-mail,
patryan(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ZHAO (Shanghai, China) _ In a striking act of political
defiance, Zhao Ziyang, China's former Communist Party chief,
challenges the nation's leaders to use President Clinton's visit as
an opportunity to admit that the Tiananmen crackdown in 1989 was an
immense political blunder. Zhao, the silvery-haired ex-leader who
has been under house arrest since May, 1989, made his case in a
letter to the Party's Central Committee by arguing that only in a
reversal of the official verdict on the crushing of 1989's student
movement will the government be able to retain any legitimacy with
its people. By Seth Faison. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET
in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Inside: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-PEONY, other sidebars, map of
Clinton's itinerary and graphic timeline.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH (Washington) _ House Republicans unveil a
long-awaited proposal to define patients' rights and set uniform
nationwide standards for health insurance, especially HMOs. The
health insurance industry immediately denounces the proposal,
saying it will increase costs for consumers. By Robert Pear.
(Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-TCI (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T Corp., the nation's largest telephone
company, says it has agreed to acquire TCI, the No. 2 cable
television provider, for $31.8 billion in stock in a deal that is
the most far-reaching product yet of the 1996 congressional
deregulation of the telecommunications industry. By Seth Schiesel.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) With graphics,
sidebars inside.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-ASSESS (Undated) _ News analysis: How the deal reshapes the
competitive landscape. By Saul Hansell. (Scheduled to move by 9
p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) Story runs under a 3-column
photo-graphic layout.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUIT (Undated) _ To Microsoft Corp., a federal appeals
court ruling in the company's favor Tuesday was a gratifying
triumph for its long-running antitrust battle with the government.
To the Justice Department and 20 states pitted against Microsoft,
it was merely a bump in the road as they head to court again in
September with a broader antitrust case against the company. Yet
antitrust experts say the split-decision by the three-judge panel
is both a big win for Microsoft and a reflection of wider debate
over how antitrust doctrine should apply to high-technology
industries. By Steve Lohr. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-DROPOUTS (Undated) _ The high-tech field, the fastest
growing of the nation's economy, has become so voracious in its
hiring that computer science departments across the country are
losing graduate students and, in growing numbers, undergraduates to
an industry fueled by vast sums of money. Many experts fear that
fundamental research will decline and that the next generation of
American computer scientists will be stunted. By Ethan Bronner.
(The story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AFFIRM (Washington) _ The White House announces a new
affirmative action policy under which minority-owned businesses
will be given an advantage when they compete for government
contracts in industries where surveys show they are
underrepresented but not in industries where they seem to have a
fair share of the market. The policy was devised to meet the terms
of a Supreme Court decision in 1995 that strictly limited the
justification and scope of government programs that grant
preferences based on race or sex. By David E. Rosenbaum. (The story
has moved in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ In an affirmation of its
anti-abortion stance, the House vots to block the FDA from
approving an abortion-inducing pill. (Story will include other
appropriations battles.) By Katharine Q. Seelye. (Scheduled to move
by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-LUVVIES (London) _ British arts groups protest Tony
Blair's Labor government culture policy as neglecting highbrow in
favor of pop. By Warren Hoge. (Moved in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
