<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-COX </SLUG>
   380&AMP;ADD  CONGRESSIONAL CONFEREES AGREE ON IRS REFORM
BILL
 &HT;     Eds: Material at end can be used as a separate text box.
 &HT;     By SHANNON JOYCE 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Senate and House leaders reached an agreement
Tuesday on a bill to restructure the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we are very happy to announce that we have reached a
bipartisan agreement on a plan that will change the way the IRS
does business,'' said Sen. William V. Roth, Jr., R-Del., who
chaired the House-Senate conference committee in charge of the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our reform bill will be the most comprehensive overhaul of the
Internal Revenue Service ever enacted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Swift approval of the compromise is expected in both houses of
Congress, and President Clinton is expected to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes two years after a group of tax experts,
members of Congress and former IRS employees and commissioners
began a thorough study of the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rob Portman, R-Ohio, who co-chaired the group along with
Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said the bill closely follows their
recommendations and should end many of the IRS's current problems.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would give taxpayers new protections, hold IRS
employees accountable for their actions, and create a nine-member
board to guide the agency and review its procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 50 taxpayer protections in the bill are provisions
that shift the burden of proof to the IRS in court proceedings,
insulate a divorced or separated individual from his or her
ex-spouse's tax burdens, and extend an attorney-client privilege to
accountants and other tax practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law will increase the likelihood that the IRS will work
for the people and not the other way around,'' Kerrey said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also require the IRS to fire employees who
vengefully violate IRS rules, falsify documents or fail to get the
proper approval for seizing property.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, said the bill ``has given David the
taxpayer an arsenal of slingshots to use against Goliath the IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Congress passed major changes to the IRS was in
1952.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the second biggest agency in government. We did it on
a bipartisan basis. We did it in a short period of time,'' Portman
said of the bill. ``So it truly is a great accomplishment of this
Congress, and the American people will benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The bill's major provisions would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Create a nine-member board whose members include the secretary
of the Treasury, the IRS commissioner, an employee representative
and six private sector members.
</P>
<P>
   _ Put an IRS contact name and phone number on all the agency's
correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   _ Require the IRS to fire an employee who commits perjury,
falsifies or destroys documents to hide mistakes, willingly fails
to obtain the required approval for property seizures, commits
assault or battery against a taxpayer or IRS employee, or violates
the civil rights of a taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
   New taxpayer rights include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Shifting the burden of proof to the IRS in court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Insulating divorced or separated individuals from their
ex-spouse's tax burdens.
</P>
<P>
   _ Suspending interest penalties if the IRS does not notify a
taxpayer within 18 months of the violation. In 2004, the time limit
would change to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cutting the ``failure to pay'' penalty in half if the taxpayer
is paying the debt by installment.
</P>
<P>
   _ A computation of penalties or interest in each notice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Giving accountants and tax practitioners an attorney-client
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   _ Giving taxpayers 30 days to request a hearing before seizing
any property.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prohibiting the IRS from seizing residences without a court
order or for debts less than $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
