<HEADER>
A5296 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-MANAGED-CARE-HNS &LR;      06-24 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MANAGED-CARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS PRESENT PLAN TO CONTROL MANAGED CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans on Wednesday announced their plan
to regulate managed health care programs, offering legislation that
gives patients an elaborate system for appealing plans' adverse
health care decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But the long-awaited Republican plan, billed as ``protecting
patients without big government,'' did not give patients the right
to sue managed care companies when they suffer because of health
care decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The right-to-sue rule is contained in the competing Democrats'
``Patient's Bill of Rights'' and a separate proposal of Rep.
Charles Norwood, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the various other plans, I will tell you this
Republican plan is as good as it gets,'' Rep. Bill Thomas,
R-Calif., chairman of the House Ways and Means health subcommittee,
told a packed Capitol press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was referring to the Academy Award-winning motion picture
``As Good As It Gets,'' in which actress Helen Hunt complains about
a managed care company's treatment of her son. Politicians in both
parties have pointed to the movie as a sign of popular resentment
toward managed care, a trend confirmed by several public opinion
polls.
</P>
<P>
   Managed care plans save money by limiting patients' choices of
doctors and access to specialty care. About 85 percent of people
who get health insurance through their employers are now in managed
care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., appointed by House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., to chair a Republican task force that produced the
legislation, said the GOP plan would ``provide patients with the
necessary protection to get them well, without new taxes, without
more bureaucracy or the heavy hand of government.''
</P>
<P>
   At the press conference, Norwood said he would endorse the
Republican bill and halt efforts to get his own legislation through
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked as hard as I know how over the last three years in
order to have liability in any final product,'' he said. ``I lost
that ... But I can tell you without a doubt it is time now to pass
this (Republican) legislation, because it is the right thing to do
for the patients of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood said the Republican bill contained ``75 percent'' of
what was in his bill, the Patient Access to Responsible Care Act,
known on Capitol Hill as PARCA. ``I don't think anybody has any
doubt that in this town where 435 (House members) get to have an
opinion, that ain't bad,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, the proposed legislation represented a major
effort by House Speaker Newt Gingrich to make up for political
setbacks on what has been a vexing issue for the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally responsive to health care and insurance lobbyists,
the Republican leadership has been ambivalent on what to do about
managed care at a time when Democrats and Norwood were responding
to public resentment with measures to bolster patients' leverage
against health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Many nervous Republicans endorsed the Norwood or Democratic
bills, while others urged Gingrich to make some response to the
managed care issue, especially in view of the prospect that managed
care would become an issue in the November elections. Republicans
have a narrow 12-vote majority in the House..
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Democrats have tried turning the managed care
issue into a political bonanza, running television ads in
individual districts that contrast their candidates' support of
managed care regulation with the Republicans' lack of ideas on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the Republican announcement mirrored the shifting
political ground.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Pollack, executive director of Families USA, a group
advocating tight controls on managed care, said the GOP proposal
was filled with ``poison pill'' elements that are so controversial,
they could never pass the House.
</P>
<P>
   Among these are a proposal to cap doctors' medical malpractice
liability at $250,000, something Republicans have failed to push
through Congress because of staunch Democratic opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is designed to insulate Republicans from criticism
that they do not advocate health care consumer protections, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Vice President Al Gore said, ``The
Republican proposal does not nearly provide the protections that
Americans need in a patients bill of rights.'' But he added, ``We
are hopeful this ... signals a renewed effort to get beyond raw,
partisan, election-year politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Federation of Independent Business and the Health
Insurance Association of America, usually allies against any
regulation of managed care, split on the Republican proposal.
</P>
<P>
   NFIB, which represents small businesses that frequently cannot
afford health insurance for employees, praised the bill for
permitting interstate small business alliances to purchase health
insurance at competitive prices.
</P>
<P>
   But the HIAA, which helped torpedo President Clinton's 1994
health care legislation drive with its famous ``Harry and Louise''
television ads, called the Republican bill ``a mishmash of
cobbled-together ideas that are guaranteed to raise consumers
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Republican measure, when a managed care plan decides
it will not cover a particular medical treatment or procedure, a
patient may take the complaint to a company internal review board,
supervised by a physician.
</P>
<P>
   Patients not satisfied with the review board decision could take
their complaints to an independent panel of medical specialists.
Emergency complaints would be expedited so that all appeals would
be completed in a matter of days.
</P>
<P>
   Patients still not satisfied then could take the managed care
company to court. The Norwood and Democratic bills permit court
action for any health plan decision that injures health, regardless
of the outcome of appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea here is to get the plan to go along with the internal
and external reviews,'' said Rep. Jim Talent, R-Mo. The appeal
route, he added, also is aimed at ``resolving these matters swiftly
up front, so (patients) get the care they need when they need it
(and) health care dollars are devoted to care, not to litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   At the press conference, Republicans readily acknowledged they
incorporated many of the ideas that first appeared in the Norwood
and Democratic proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a high degree of commonality in certain areas,'' said
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Among the common features of the Republican bill and the
Democratic and Norwood measures are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Require managed care plans to provide access to emergency room
treatment at hospitals not affiliated with a patient's plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prohibit the ``gag rule'' that keeps doctors from discussing
treatment options not covered by a plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Appeals of adverse managed care decisions to external
independent reviewers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
