<HEADER>
A5297 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-U.S./MEX     06-24 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-U.S./MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN P. LOPEZ 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAINT-ETIENNE, France _ Their places in this world have been turned
upside down.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has gone south. Mexico has risen.
</P>
<P>
   Geography and World Cup expectations have given way to the
reality that today's Mexico and U.S. matches end a remarkable World
Cup first round that could not have gone worse for the Americans or
better for El Tri.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans came to France among the dangerous dark horses in
the field, with impressive recent results and a previously absent
air of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   But two weeks later, they are French toast. And German toast.
And, worst of all, Iranian toast.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. players and coaches are making travel arrangements home and
wondering if the two tiny steps forward in the 1990 and 1994
tournaments have given way to a giant leap backward in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been unlucky but we also exhibited a terrible
inefficiency in front of the goal,'' U.S. coach Steve Sampson said.
``We're going to have to do a lot of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, on the other hand, seemed to limp into the World Cup
finals last month.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bickering, hurting team, still getting accustomed to a
new coach and unsettled at various positions. But two weeks later,
Mexico is undefeated and talking about outattacking one of the best
attacking teams in the world today, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the groups were selected last December, I'm sure our
opponents were happy to have been drawn against us,'' Mexico coach
Manuel Lapuente said. ``Now, they are not so confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the coach of the explosive Dutch team, which faces Mexico
today at Stade Geoffroy-Guichard in a crucial Group E game here,
has called the match vital to his team's hopes of making it deep
into the World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have a lot of trouble in this game,'' Dutch coach
Guus Hiddink said. ``Mexico is playing with a lot of confidence and
going at everybody. We want to win the group, but they have the
same hopes. If we can beat Mexico and win our group, it will be big
for our confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States, which faces Yugoslavia in a meaningless game
for the U.S. team after the disappointing losses to Germany and
Iran, merely hopes to salvage a few nuggets of pride from the
wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very tough group, and we didn't play well,'' veteran
U.S. defender Thomas Dooley said. ``In the first match we gave
Germany too much respect, and then in the match against Iran we
were right on the edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd scored a goal first, and we had our chances, it could
have been an easy win for us. But it wasn't. We have to try to pick
it up now and prove that we are a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's game in Nantes is one of those pride games. It was
supposed to mean something. Both nations were supposed to be
walking on pins and needles in anticipation of its kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Tuesday the Americans officially became the tourists
that some would say they were in the first two games. Sampson
canceled practice and invited wives and girlfriends to join the
players in taking in various Paris sights.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one sign of concession by Sampson and the U.S.
Soccer Federation. Wednesday, the team went through only a light
practice, and Sampson acknowledged that as much as he hoped for a
victory today, he would give various reserve players a chance to
start and taste the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, goalkeeper Brad Friedel, who backed up Tony Meola
at the 1994 World Cup but never saw action, will start in place of
Kasey Keller. And because this could be the final World Cup chance
for such U.S. veterans as Alexi Lalas, Marcelo Balboa and Jeff
Agoos, who was the final player cut from the 1994 team, it is
expected they also will play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever 11 players we put out there, it's going to be with
winning in mind,'' Sampson said. ``Our aim in the match is to prove
that we can compete with one of the very best teams in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a meager goal, considering the high hopes this team had a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important that we be very professional in this game
because any time you have an opportunity to play in a World Cup
match against a team like Yugoslavia, you should use it as a great
experience,'' Sampson said. ``We're hoping that's going to be the
attitude of the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps once the game begins, the U.S. team will be out to prove
something. But since the Iran game ended, it has been obvious the
U.S. players merely want this bad experience to end so they can go
home.
</P>
<P>
   Several players have made arrangements to fly out of France on
Friday morning, and there are obvious ill feelings about how
Sampson has handled the team during the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran scorer Preki Radosavljevic, who has played just 33
minutes in the tournament, said Sampson was ``just trying to find a
reason for not playing me'' when Sampson said he didn't think Preki
was in top condition.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the normally media-friendly Eric Wynalda, another top
scorer who did not play against Iran, has said little since the
Iran game.
</P>
<P>
   But then there are the Mexicans, whose turnaround and cool under
the pressure of trailing 1-0 in both first-round games has them
thinking a berth in the second round is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico can guarantee a trip to the 16-team second round with a
win today over the powerful Dutch. The Netherlands remains favored
to beat Mexico, especially after whipping the South Koreans 5-0 in
its last outing and because Mexico could be without scoring ace
Luis Hernandez, who injured his ankle against Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexico is conceding nothing. What a drastic change from a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to Europe under heavy criticism, and it's true we
weren't at our best,'' Mexican keeper Jorge Campos said. ``But
we've silenced our critics. Our team now is united, and it believes
in our chances to keep winning. This is the World Cup. We've raised
our level of play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
