<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RANKS OF HOMELESS INCLUDE MORE FAMILIES, STUDY FINDS
 &HT;    By REBECCA CARR
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Homelessness across America is increasingly turning
into a family affair, with more families in search of shelter than
ever before, according to a study released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by the Homes for the Homeless's Institute
for Children and Poverty in conjunction with Columbia University in
New York, evaluated the homeless populations in 10 urban areas,
finding that the typical homeless family is a single mother with at
least two children under the age of 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homelessness today is a family issue, and a children's
issue,'' the report states. ``The real picture that emerges from
behind these numbers is of thousands upon thousands of homeless
children nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, researchers interviewed 777 homeless families from
Atlanta; Chicago; Dallas/Fort Worth; Milwaukee; New York; Norman,
Okla.; Salem/Eugene, Ore.; San Antonio; San Francisco, and South
Bend, Ind. The study examined their overall quality of life,
including housing, job and educational backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The study does not include comparative data for all cities.
However, using New York as an example, the study found that the
number of homeless families living there increased by more than 500
percent from 1981 to 1995. Last year, the first year that
information was made available, there were 700,000 homeless
families living in America.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also sees homelessness as a pressing issue.
Seizing upon the study as evidence that more ought to be done,
Andrew Cuomo, secretary of the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban
Development, said the study should persuade Congress to approve
President Clinton's budget request of $1.15 billion in grants and
vouchers to help the homeless. That is a 40 percent increase in
grants for the homeless over this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton's economic policies have brought new
opportunity to millions of our people, but homeless Americans
remain only spectators to the wave of prosperity sweeping across
our nation,'' Cuomo said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Republican appropriators have allocated about $975 million for
homeless grants, up from $823 million spent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
