</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ZHAO (Shanghai, China) _ In a striking act of political
defiance, Zhao Ziyang, China's former Communist Party chief,
challenges the nation's leaders to use President Clinton's visit as
an opportunity to admit that the Tiananmen crackdown in 1989 was an
immense political blunder. Zhao, the silvery-haired ex-leader who
has been under house arrest since May, 1989, made his case in a
letter to the Party's Central Committee by arguing that only in a
reversal of the official verdict on the crushing of 1989's student
movement will the government be able to retain any legitimacy with
its people. By Seth Faison. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET
in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
