   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUIT (Undated) _ To Microsoft Corp., a federal appeals
court ruling in the company's favor Tuesday was a gratifying
triumph for its long-running antitrust battle with the government.
To the Justice Department and 20 states pitted against Microsoft,
it was merely a bump in the road as they head to court again in
September with a broader antitrust case against the company. Yet
antitrust experts say the split-decision by the three-judge panel
is both a big win for Microsoft and a reflection of wider debate
over how antitrust doctrine should apply to high-technology
industries. By Steve Lohr. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-DROPOUTS (Undated) _ The high-tech field, the fastest
growing of the nation's economy, has become so voracious in its
hiring that computer science departments across the country are
losing graduate students and, in growing numbers, undergraduates to
an industry fueled by vast sums of money. Many experts fear that
fundamental research will decline and that the next generation of
American computer scientists will be stunted. By Ethan Bronner.
(The story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-AFFIRM (Washington) _ The White House announces a new
affirmative action policy under which minority-owned businesses
will be given an advantage when they compete for government
contracts in industries where surveys show they are
underrepresented but not in industries where they seem to have a
fair share of the market. The policy was devised to meet the terms
of a Supreme Court decision in 1995 that strictly limited the
justification and scope of government programs that grant
preferences based on race or sex. By David E. Rosenbaum. (The story
has moved in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ In an affirmation of its
anti-abortion stance, the House vots to block the FDA from
approving an abortion-inducing pill. (Story will include other
appropriations battles.) By Katharine Q. Seelye. (Scheduled to move
by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ARTS-FUNDING (London) _ British arts groups protest Tony
Blair's Labor government culture policy as neglecting highbrow in
favor of pop. By Warren Hoge. (Moved in ``e'' news file.) Eds.:
Budgeted earlier as BRITAIN-LUVVIES.
</P>
