<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIOS MAKES EARLY EXIT; SAMPRAS, GRAF CRUISE TO VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Bewitched by a few blades of grass,
second-seeded Marcelo Rios self-destructed in his first-round match
at Wimbledon on Wednesday, losing an opportunity to find Grand Slam
respectability and another chance to snatch the No. 1 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Disgusted with himself, Rios elected to direct that disgust at
the venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take Wimbledon, like playing on grass, like a really
important thing,'' he said after being upset, 6-3, 3-6, 7-5, 3-6,
6-3 by Francisco Clavet of Spain, a 29-year-old journeyman whose
only resemblance to the talented but tempestuous Rios is his
virtually nonexistent Wimbledon resume.
</P>
<P>
   After Rios dropped his serve, along with the third set, he began
to lose interest in his shotmaking and Clavet merely had to guide
the ball within the boundaries and wait for the better player to
play like a beginner _ a beginner with a bad attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tennis, when you see it on grass, it's not tennis,'' said
Rios, who has now lost in the first round here twice in three
years. ``It's not a surface to watch or play tennis on; it's really
boring. You just serve, return, go in, that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rios' low opinion was not shared by Jennifer Capriati, who
verged on jubilance after powering her way into the second round
past the Australian Nicole Pratt, 6-4, 3-6, 6-4 in her first
Wimbledon appearance in five years.
</P>
<P>
   It was a landmark victory for the 22-year-old Capriati, who
reached the semifinals here in 1991 but had not passed the first
round of a Grand Slam tournament in her last five attempts, dating
back to the 1993 U.S. Open loss that preceded her two-year spiral
into substance abuse and despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to believe in myself, that I can go all the way, and
maybe that's not No. 1, maybe that's just No. 5, but that's fine,''
said Capriati, a wild-card entry here.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing comes automatically for Capriati anymore, but most of
the big names, including the defending men's champion Pete Sampras,
the seven-time women's champion Steffi Graf and sixth-seeded Monica
Seles were on automatic pilot Wednesday as springlike conditions
settled in after Tuesday's disruptive showers.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras cruised past Mikael Tillstrom, 6-4, 6-4, 7-6 (7-5); Graf
reached the third round with a 57-minute 6-0, 6-4 demolition of
Henrieta Nagyova, and Seles walloped Alexandra Fusai, 6-1, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   One contender who had problems was fourth-seeded Greg Rusedski,
the Canadian-born British star, whose match with the qualifier Mark
Draper was delayed by rain Tuesday with Draper leading, 4-6, 6-2,
5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Rusedski, capable of becoming the first British man to win here
since Fred Perry in 1936, had sprained an ankle two weeks ago at
Queens Club and displayed all the mobility of the bronze statue of
Perry that guards the grounds. He was glued to the baseline,
double-faulted 18 times and hoped it would rain all week so that he
would not have to resume Wednesday on his one good leg.
</P>
<P>
   When Rusedski woke up to a blue sky, he knew it was curtains. He
decided to withdraw after morning practice. The Court One crowd let
out a collective groan when it heard; then there was more music to
face.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that Rusedski, a 1997 U.S. Open finalist who has
the fastest serve on the circuit, had played Tuesday against the
wishes of his coach, Tony Pickard. Unhappy that Rusedski had
disregarded his advice in favor of that of his physiotherapist,
Reza Dandesman, Pickard waited until Rusedski withdrew and then
informed him that their relationship was over, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no ranting and raving,'' said Pickard, Stefan
Edberg's former coach, who came out of retirement to guide Rusedski
into the top five. ``Over the last two weeks, there was a total
breakdown in communication. There were outside influences telling
him he was fit to play; I didn't consider he was, but the thing
that broke the camel's back was the fact that for two days I
couldn't find him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusedski described the timing of the break-up as a case of
Pickard's ``showing his true colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickard had an angry retort: ``Maybe the young man would be a
lot better to say nothing, because if I was to elaborate for you, I
think you would all tear him to pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Eighth-seeded Cedric Pioline, who reached the final last year,
lost his first-round match to Marc Rosset, 6-4, 3-6, 4-6, 7-6
(7-5), 13-11.
</P>
<P>
   _ Karol Kucera, seeded 15th, was ousted by Vladimir Voltchkov, a
218th-ranked qualifier from Belarus, 7-6 (8-6), 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   _ The only seeded woman to lose was No. 9 Amanda Coetzer of
South Africa, who sank in the second round for the seventh time in
nine visits. This time she was dispatched by 33rd-ranked Naoko
Sawamatsu of Japan, 3-6, 6-3, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former No. 1 Jim Courier, a first-round loser in four of his
last six Grand Slam tournaments, was eliminated, 6-4, 7-6 (8-6),
6-4, by Thomas Johansson of Sweden. But a rising star, 21-year-old
Jan-Michael Gambill of Spokane, Wash., survived a momentous debut.
After three days of rain-interrupted play, and after squandering 10
match points, Gambill won, 7-6 (8-6), 6-4, 6-7 (5-7), 4-6, 8-6
against Sjeng Schalken of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first five-set match, and I've never had a match
last three days,'' said Gambill. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
