<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNAP-FAGAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAGAN EXPECTED TO USE `NECESSITY DEFENSE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When he is arraigned Thursday in Middlesex Superior
Court, Stephen Fagan will take the first step in the battle to
defend himself against charges he kidnapped his two daughters from
his ex-wife 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But since his arrest, Fagan has been laying the groundwork for
his legal strategy: the so-called necessity defense.
</P>
<P>
   In newspaper and TV interviews, Fagan never denied he took his
daughters. Rather, he insisted he swept them away from their
mother, Barbara Kurth, because their lives were in danger from her
neglect.
</P>
<P>
   If the case goes to trial, Fagan hopes to convince a jury he
saved his daughters from a greater harm.
</P>
<P>
   The necessity defense is rarely successful in courts here,
specialists say. But Fagan can employ it to win an acquittal if he
convinces a jury of three things: that the children were facing a
clear and immiment danger; that his action was necessary; and that
there was no legal alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third one is usually the stumbling block,'' said John
LaChance, president of the Massachusetts Association of Criminal
Defense Lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan says he took the girls, then ages 2 and 5, to Palm Beach
and changed their identities to save them from Kurth, whom he
describes as a neglectful, alcoholic mother.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, 56, will be arraigned before Judge Joseph A. Grasso
Jr. &UR;  &LR; on two counts of kidnapping and one count of contempt of a
probate court order, which had prohibited Fagan from taking the
children out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, who is free on $250,000 bail, was arrested in April in
Palm Beach. He had masqueraded as Dr. William S. Martin, an
Ivy-League-educated psychiatrist, wealthy socialite, and
philanthropist.
</P>
<P>
   The girls were living with Kurth in North Adams in 1979 when he
picked them up for a three-day visit and never returned. Later, he
told them their mother died in a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, Fagan remarried twice and raised the girls with his
affluent wives. His daughters, Rachael Martin, 23, and Lisa Martin,
21, have prospered by all accounts and have stood by their father.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth, meanwhile, hired private detectives but did not find the
children. A research scientist at the University of Viriginia,
Kurth has adamantly denied she had a problem with alcohol or was
neglectful.
</P>
<P>
   LaChance said Fagan's chances for success with the necessity
defense may depend on whether his attorney, Richard M. Egbert, can
convince a jury that his client ``had no alternative but to get
(the children) out of there before they were badly harmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Chapman, former head of the Massachusetts Bar
Association's criminal section, said that strategy will allow
Egbert ``to present evidence that will engender sympathy for your
client _ evidence, for instance, about Barbara Kurth's conduct that
would not otherwise be admissible.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are risks, Chapman said. ``The bad thing about it is
that, like the insanity defense, you have to essentially admit you
did the crime,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LaChance said the defense has worked in some cases, such as a
person driving with a suspended license because he or she was
taking someone to the hospital in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman said judges often refuse to give the jury the option of
acquitting a defendant on the basis of necessity. He cited a recent
needle-exchange case in Peabody District Court in which a defendant
accused of distributing hypodermic needles to drug users claimed he
was acting to prevent the greater harm _ the spread of AIDS. The
judged barred the necessity defense, and the defendant's conviction
was upheld on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But Amy Carter, the daughter of former President Jimmy Carter,
won acquittal with the necessity defense in 1987 after she was
charged with trespassing and disorderly conduct for joining in the
occupation of a building at the University of Massachusetts at
Amherst to protest CIA recruitment there.
</P>
<P>
   When the case came before a jury in Northampton, Carter's
attorneys argued that the courts and Congress could not control the
CIA, so the protest was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Hoopes, a Boston defense attorney, agreed that Fagan's
biggest hurdle could lay in persuading the judge to give
instruction on the necessity defense to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some sympathy for (Fagan) out there,'' Hoopes said.
``If he can get a judge to instruct on necessity, he has a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is fighting in the right direction,'' Hoopes added. ``Does
he have enough to get there? I don't think he is going to know
until he sees who he draws as a (trial) judge.''`
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
