<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5318 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CIVIL-RIGHTS-3     06-24 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CIVIL-RIGHTS-3TAKES-$ADV28-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUMS OF A MOVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., June 28)  
 (JT)  
 By KEVIN SACK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the notion was broached nearly a decade ago, it seemed
tastelessly morbid. A museum of the civil rights movement was to be
built at the Lorraine Motel, the motor lodge in Memphis where the
Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. was shot to death in 1968 while
standing on the balcony outside Room 307.
</P>
<P>
   But seven years and 650,000 visitors later, the decision seems
as visionary as the men and women whose courage and strategic
insight are now honored by the museum. Of all this country's
monuments and shrines, few hold the visceral power of the National
Civil Rights Museum in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   As visitors wend their way down a chronological path through the
movement, walking past the burned-out hull of a Freedom Riders' bus
and tasting the abuse served up to lunch counter demonstrators,
many are moved to tears as they come upon the culmination of their
tour and, in the minds of many, of the movement itself.
</P>
<P>
   Preserved behind glass is Room 307, just as King and his
lieutenants left it on April 4 after a staff meeting that ended
shortly before the assassination at 6 p.m. An unmade bed. A room
service tray cluttered with dirty dishes. That day's Memphis
Press-Scimitar. A butt-filled ashtray.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out a window, you can trace the path of the bullet from
the rooming house across the street to the spot where King fell,
now marked by a wreath of red and white carnations. The mournful
mood, reflecting the destruction of both a 39-year-old leader and a
movement's momentum, is set by a recording of Mahalia Jackson
singing ``Precious Lord,'' just as she did at King's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years after King's death, commemorations of the struggle
for civil rights are proliferating across the South, a region once
preoccupied with memorializing the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   There are now civil rights museums in Memphis and Birmingham,
Atlanta and Little Rock, Selma and Savannah, several among the
premier tourist attractions in their cities. A museum is scheduled
to open in the fall at the old Mount Zion Baptist Church in Albany,
Ga., a staging ground for that city's demonstrations. Ground was
broken in April at Troy State University in Montgomery, Ala., for a
40,000-square-foot Rosa Parks Library and Museum, scheduled to open
in 2000. Money is being raised to build a museum at the former F.W.
Woolworth in Greensboro, N.C., where four students began the sit-in
movement in 1960, a protest against segregation at lunch counters
and in other public places.
</P>
<P>
   The current building boom has been inspired by the graying of
the civil rights generation and a feeling that the heroes of the
1950s and 1960s, both the famous and the footsoldiers, should be
acknowledged in a formal way. In doing so, the museums celebrate
the remarkable distance that race relations have progressed in the
second half of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   In almost every instance, the most compelling displays at the
museums _ even more so than the newsreels of memorable marches and
speeches _ are the artifacts of segregation, numbing in their
matter-of-factness. What stayed with me after a visit to the
Birmingham Civil Rights Institute in April was a photograph of a
laundry truck, emblazoned with an advertisement reading ``We Wash
for White People Only.'' Even dirty laundry, the curators point
out, was not allowed to mix.
</P>
<P>
   Another impetus in the construction of the museums, civil rights
veterans say, has been the ignorance of the movement by today's
students, who are often only a generation or two removed from the
Montgomery bus boycott and the 1963 March on Washington. One of
those veterans, Julian Bond, the chairman of the NAACP and a
prominent civil rights historian, said in a recent interview that
not one of the 500 students he surveyed between 1989 and 1993 in
classes at five prominent universities could correctly identify
George Wallace, the defiantly segregationist former Governor of
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   In their educational mission, the museums strive to place the
civil rights movement within the mainstream of America's
revolutionary tradition. The Memphis exhibition pointedly concludes
with a plaque bearing words not of King, but of Thomas Jefferson:
``A little rebellion, now and then, is a good thing. . . . It is a
medicine necessary for the sound health of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, several of the museums include replicas of the
Birmingham jail cell where King wrote his famous 1963 letter to
white ministers, proclaiming that the non-violent protests of the
day had brought the country ``back to those great wells of
democracy which were dug deep by the founding fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in that same letter that King made one of his most
prescient predictions. ``One day,'' he wrote, ``the South will
recognize its real heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   National Civil Rights Museum, Memphis
</P>
<P>
   As was the case in so many Southern cities, the Lorraine Motel
was one of the few lodgings available to black travelers when King
arrived in Memphis to lend his support to a sanitation workers'
strike. While the facade, with its distinctive green doors and
yellow trim, has been maintained as it was in 1968, the interior of
the motel has been gutted and expanded into 10,000 square feet of
display space and galleries.
</P>
<P>
   The Memphis museum provides by far the most comprehensive
interpretation of any of the civil rights exhibitions, and it is
sometimes criticized for being too dense with words. The time line,
after all, begins in 1619 and touches on slavery, Nat Turner, Dred
Scott, Harriet Tubman and Frederick Douglass well before moving on
to Jim Crow segregation, a term derived, you learn, from a minstrel
show called ``Jump Jim Crow.'' A less demanding alternative to
reading the lengthy historical explanations is a one-hour
tape-recorded tour, narrated by Ruby Dee and Ossie Davis, that
moves you through the museum at a brisker pace.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The displays are full of first-person accounts and copies of
original headlines and documents, but the most memorable moments
are interactive. When you walk on to a green and yellow Montgomery
city bus, you find the first five rows reserved for whites, and a
mannequin of Rosa Parks seated defiantly in the second row. As you
take your seat, a driver's voice barks: ``I need that seat now.
Please move back. If you don't move from that seat now I'll have
you arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more powerful is a reconstruction of a lunch counter, where
gray statues of protesters sit in front of video screens showing
footage of an actual sit-in. In the videotape, taken during the
Greensboro sit-in, a black man sits stoically at a lunch counter as
a white tough dumps a milkshake on his head.
</P>
<P>
   The museum makes effective use of a tape recording of a tense
telephone call in which President John F. Kennedy confronts Gov.
Ross Barnett of Mississippi about the unrest accompanying the
enrollment of the first black student at the University of
Mississippi, James Meredith. And it humanizes King with the
transcript of a telephone conversation with his wife, Coretta Scott
King, while he was jailed in Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's the baby?'' he asks. ``How's Bernice?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine, growing, cute as a button,'' she responds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's wonderful,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But the museum is at its best in documenting the final hours of
King's life and the chaos that followed the assassination. The
words of the Rev. Ralph David Abernathy, who was at King's side at
his death, are used to convey the sense of emotional convulsion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy Young was the first to get up there by me,'' Abernathy
recalls. ``And Andy said, `Oh God.' He said, `Ralph, it's over.' I
became furious. I said, `Don't say that. Don't you say that, Andy.
It will not be over. It will never be over.'''
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham Civil Rights Institute
</P>
<P>
   Dedicated in 1992, this handsome museum and archive is the
centerpiece of a complex of civil rights sites in downtown
Birmingham. It is across the street from the 16th Street Baptist
Church, where a bomb set by Klansmen in 1963 took the lives of four
young girls. And just to the north of the museum, across 16th
Street, is Kelly Ingram Park, where the helmeted troops of Police
Commissioner Eugene T. (Bull) Connor confronted protesters earlier
that year. The park, now remade as ``a place of revolution and
reconciliation,'' is a regular stop for the city's schoolchildren,
who come to experience the past through James Drake's powerful 1992
metallic sculptures of water cannon and snarling dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The museum itself depicts the civil rights movement through the
prism of the Birmingham experience, with timelines that note
milestones in that city along with their national context. The tour
begins with a brief film about the history of the city. Then the
screen lifts to reveal the entrance to the rest of the exhibition,
beginning with a display of water fountains designated for either
whites or blacks.
</P>
<P>
   The museum cleverly demonstrates the racial inequities in
education and health care that had become so accepted in
Birmingham. In 1944, for instance, the average class in a black
school in Birmingham had 43 students, compared to 24 at white
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Here you also see the original door to the jail cell that
confined King in 1963, as well as copies of his police fingerprint
sheets. And you learn of the 50 unsolved bombings against black
citizens or institutions from the late 1940s to the mid 1960s that
gave the town its nickname, Bombingham.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the video of the waterhosing of students is
gripping and its melding with recent interviews with the same
people provides a nice touch. Another high point is the showing of
King's ``I Have a Dream'' speech at the March on Washington in a
circular room where video walls create the sensation of being on
the Mall that day.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King Jr. National Historic Site, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   This site, many civil rights buffs agree, is not what it should
be. Instead it reflects years of distrust between the King family
and the National Park Service, a distrust that culminated in the
early 1990s when the Park Service went ahead with plans to build a
visitors center on land the Kings had wanted for a museum. The
family continues to search for a site for the museum. While none of
the exhibits scattered down Auburn Avenue offer a comprehensive
account of the movement, it remains a valuable stop on any trip to
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to King's elegant tomb, its white marble mirrored in a
blue reflecting pool, is always a solemn experience. The
inscription is perfect in its simplicity:
</P>
<P>
   REV. MARTIN LUTHER KING, JR
</P>
<P>
   1929-1968
</P>
<P>
   `` FREE AT LAST. FREE AT LAST.
</P>
<P>
   THANK GOD ALMIGHTY
</P>
<P>
   I'M FREE AT LAST.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the adjacent Freedom Hall, which is part of the
family-managed King Center, visitors can see King's Nobel Peace
Prize and displays of personal effects of King and Mrs. King.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, the National Park Service has erected a
visitors center that features two films, one about King and one
about the Sweet Auburn business district where he was born and
where he worked. It also includes a modest exhibit of videotapes
and text about the movement, with King's biography used as a
framework. The park service is currently in negotiations with the
King Center about the possibility of taking control of the center.
</P>
<P>
   The park service offers tours of the upper middle-class home at
501 Auburn, where King was born and where three generations of his
family lived. Park service rangers reel off plenty of King family
lore, like the anecdotes about how young M.L. broke the piano stool
to shirk his music lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Another worthwhile stop is Ebenezer Baptist Church, the brick
sanctuary where King, his father, the Rev. Martin Luther King Sr.,
and his maternal grandfather, the Rev. A.D. Williams, all preached.
In a deal with the park service, Ebenezer is about to complete
construction of a glass and steel building next to the historic
site visitors center. The original Ebenezer will then be leased to
the park service, which should offer a wonderful opportunity to
interpret the vital role played by the black church in the civil
rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Planning a Visit
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; National Civil Rights Museum &LR;  in Memphis is on the edge of
downtown at 450 Mulberry St; (901) 521-9699. Museum hours from June
through August are 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. Monday through Saturday, 9 a.m.
to 8 p.m. on Thursday, and 1 to 6 p.m. on Sunday. Closed Tuesday
year round. From September through May, the hours are 9 a.m. to 5
p.m. Monday through Saturday, 9 a.m. to 8 p.m. on Thursday, and 1
to 5 p.m. on Sunday. Admission is $6, $5 for seniors and college
students, and $4 for children from 4 to 17. Children 3 and under
are free. Free admission Monday from 3 to 5 p.m. (to 6 in summer).
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Birmingham Civil Rights Institute &LR;  is at 520 16th St.
North, Birmingham; (205) 328-9696. Museum hours are 10 a.m. to 5
p.m. Tuesday through Saturday and 1 to 5 p.m. on Sunday. The museum
is closed on Monday. Admission is $3, $2 for seniors, $1 for
college students and free for children 17 and under. Admission is
free on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors center for the  &UR; Martin Luther King Jr. National
Historic Site &LR;  in Atlanta is at 450 Auburn Ave., N.E.; (404)
331-6922. The center, which features films, videos and exhibits, is
open from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily in winter, until 6 p.m. from
Memorial Day to Labor Day. Tours of King's birth home at 501 Auburn
Ave., limited to 15 people per tour on a first-come basis, depart
on the hour from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. in winter (on the half-hour from
10 to 5:30 in summer) from Fire Station No. 6 at 39 Boulevard,
N.E., at the corner of Auburn Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Self-guided tours of  &UR; Ebenezer Baptist Church &LR;  at 407 Auburn
Ave., N.E., in Atlanta are permitted from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday
through Saturday except during church services and other church
events. (No touring is permitted on Sunday, though visitors are
welcome at church services.) Exhibits at the Freedom Hall of the
 &UR; King Center  &LR;  at 449 Auburn Ave., including King's Nobel Peace
Prize and displays of personal artifacts of King and Coretta Scott
King, are open the same hours as the historic site. King's crypt,
part of the King Center complex, is accessible at all hours. All of
the King historic site locations are within a two-block span, and
all are free.
</P>
<P>
   Other Museums
</P>
<P>
   A number of other civil rights museums are worth visiting. The
 &UR; Central High Museum and Visitor Center &LR;  is at 2125 West 14th St.,
Little Rock, Ark., (501) 374-1957, commemorates the ugly
confrontation that accompanied the desegregation of the school in
1957. It opened last year in a restored Mobil service station
across the street from the school. With some of the starkest
photographic and video images of the entire civil rights movement,
the modest exhibit effectively recreates the horror felt by the
nine black students who entered the school under the escort of
Federal troops.
</P>
<P>
   It is open from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. Monday through Saturday and
from 1 to 4 p.m. on Sunday. Admission is free.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Ralph Mark Gilbert Civil Rights Museum, &LR;  460 Martin Luther
King Jr. Blvd., Savannah, (912) 231-8900, documents the history of
black residents in that coastal city from the Civil War through the
boycotts and demonstrations of the 1960s. Named in honor of a
minister and NAACP leader who is considered the father of the civil
rights movement in Savannah, the museum is situated in an historic
1914 building that was once home to a black bank.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is open from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday through
Saturday. Closed Sunday. Admission is $4, $3 for seniors and $2 for
students.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; National Voting Rights Museum and Institute,  &LR;  1012 Water
Ave., Selma, Ala., (334) 418-0800, sits near the foot of the Edmund
Pettus Bridge, site of the ``Bloody Sunday'' confrontation of 1965.
The small museum, which features photographs and memorabilia, is
open from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tuesday through Friday and from 10 a.m.
to 3 p.m. on Saturday. &UR;  &LR;  Open Sunday and Monday by appointment
only.  &UR;  &LR;  Admission is $4, $2 for students.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
