<HEADLINE>
FLEMMI EXPECTED TO TESTIFY WHEN MOB HEARINGS RESUME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The federal court hearings that have provided almost
daily revelations about the hidden world of FBI agents and their
prized informants have been suspended for now, without hearing from
the man whose affidavit started it all last summer:
gangster-turned-informant Stephen Flemmi.
</P>
<P>
   When testimony resumes in August, Flemmi, the acknowledged
co-leader of the Irish mob and sometime FBI informant for 30 years,
is expected to finally take the stand. But what he will say _ and
what prosecutors will be allowed to ask him _ is still a matter of
debate, as shown by a hearing Wednesday in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Kenneth J. Fishman, doesn't want the government to ask Flemmi
about his alleged involvement of three unsolved murders _ including
the May 1981 murder of millionaire World Jai Alai owner Roger
Wheeler in Oklahoma, the May 1982 killing of fringe
gangster-turned-informant Edward ``Brian'' Halloran in Boston or
the August 1982 killing of World Jai Alai president John ``Jack''
Callahan in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Flemmi and his criminal partner, James J. ``Whitey'' Bulger were
suspects in the Wheeler murder but were never charged.  &UR;  &LR; Halloran
was killed four months after he began talking to the FBI about
Bulger and Flemmi's alleged involvement in the Wheeler killing.
</P>
<P>
   Halloran had told the FBI that Callahan claimed Flemmi was the
getaway driver for the Wheeler shooting and Bulger the back-up
driver. When the FBi questioned them in November 1983, Flemmi and
Bulger each denied they were involved in the three murders.
</P>
<P>
   In April, former FBI supervisor John Morris testified that he
told Bulger and Flemmi's handler, agent John Connolly, that
Halloran had implicated them in Wheeler's murder. But Connolly has
denied talking to Bulger and Flemmi about Halloran before Halloran
was murdered.
</P>
<P>
   The issue outlined before Judge Mark L. Wolf Wednesday hinges on
the scope of Flemmi's testimony and whether he would have the right
to invoke his Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination if
asked about the three murders.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf is considering whether extortion and racketeering charges
brought against Flemmi in 1995 should be dismissed. In a court
affidavit filed last June, Flemmi claims that Morris told him and
Bulger they could do anything as long as they didn't ``clip
anyone'' _ slang for murder. Morris has denied it.
</P>
<P>
   In court Wednesday, Fishman argued that the government should
not be allowed to ask Flemmi about subjects that Fishman does not
raise during direct examination of his client.
</P>
<P>
   That means, for instance, that if Fishman does not ask Flemmi
about the three murders, the government can't, either. Fishman
argued that the murders are not covered by the 1995 indictment
being challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, does the government have the right to
cross-examine regarding any criminal conduct Mr. Flemmi is alleged
to have committed?'' Fishman said.
</P>
<P>
   Fishman indicated that his questions to Flemmi will focus on the
allegations his client made in three affidavits filed last year,
none of which mention the murders of Wheeler, Halloran or Callahan.
</P>
<P>
   But Assistant US Attorney Fred M. Wyshak Jr. said the wide scope
of the hearings _ which have featured a parade of witnesses called
by the defense and hundreds of pages of FBI documents detailing
Bulger and Flemmi's alleged criminal activity dating back to the
1960s _ have opened the door on those subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have placed in play every crime Mr. Flemmi has
committed,'' argued Wyshak.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf has asked both sides to submit written arguments during the
break in testimony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
