<SLUG> BC-N.M.-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS RETAIN SEAT IN SPECIAL ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a victory that Republicans trumpeted Wednesday
as a promising omen for the November elections, Heather Wilson, a
Republican, won a House seat on Tuesday in a special election in
Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   But strategists on both sides said Mrs. Wilson's triumph over
Phil Maloof, a Democratic state senator, in holding a seat that has
been Republican for nearly three decades might say more about local
political dynamics than signal any shift in the larger electorate.
</P>
<P>
   While education was the overriding issue, Republicans in New
Mexico said their victory turned largely on the double-digit
showing of a Green Party candidate, who appeared to have siphoned
votes from Maloof, and from what their polling found was a
perception that Maloof was not up to the job.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wilson, a 37-year-old former New Mexico Cabinet officer who
was an arms negotiator in the Bush White House, will be sworn in
here on Thursday to complete the term of Rep. Steven Schiff, a
Republican who died of skin cancer in March.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious problem for Maloof was the strong finish of the
Green candidate, Robert Anderson. A similar scenario was played out
in New Mexico's Third Congressional District in May 1997 when Rep.
Bill Redmond, a Republican, defeated Eric Serna, a Democrat who
lost much of his support to a Green candidate, Carol Miller, who
drew 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a warning shot across the bow of all Democratic
candidates where there are active Green candidates,'' said Daniel
Weiss, political director of the Sierra Club, which had dispatched
organizers to Albuquerque to help Maloof. ``This demonstrates that
the Green Party can be a powerful force for defeating
pro-environmental candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   While Anderson campaigned very little, he built name recognition
by appearing in televised debates with the other candidates. His
support may have come not simply from his position on the
environment; his appeal may have been that he offered voters a
respite from the negative attacks that marked the Maloof and Wilson
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   With all but the absentee ballots tallied, Mrs. Wilson drew 45
percent; Maloof, 39 percent and Anderson, 15 percent. All three
have been nominated to run again in November for a full two-year
term. For weeks, polls had shown that the race was neck and neck in
the First Congressional District, which is about evenly split
between Democrats and Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats acknowledge that Mrs. Wilson's victory in her first
race for public office gives her an edge in the fall. Maloof drew
on his family fortune to outspend Mrs. Wilson by far, and Democrats
had hoped that he would win so the party would only have to wrest
10 seats from the Republicans to regain control of the House. The
national Democratic Party was so invested in the contest that it
sent Hillary Rodham Clinton and Tipper Gore, among others, to the
district last weekend to campaign for Maloof.
</P>
<P>
   ``This provides an enormous psychic boost to Republicans around
the country,'' said Glen Bolger, Mrs. Wilson's pollster, ``and more
importantly to Republicans in the House who have been reading three
months of stories about how the Democrats were going to retake
Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolger said debates during the campaign were unusually helpful
to Mrs. Wilson because his surveys showed that Maloof turned off
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swing voters said he had the intellect of a grape,'' Bolger
said.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the impact of the Green candidate, Bolger said
Greens might not have voted at all had Anderson not been in the
race because Maloof registered an 82 percent unfavorable image
among them.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Frost of Texas, chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, conceded in an interview that
Maloof would have been far better positioned in November had he won
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly better if you have the incumbent; there's no
question about that,'' Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he intended to examine the strength of the Green
Party but that he was not prepared to say Anderson had cost the
Democrats the election.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader, the consumer advocate who ran for president as the
Green candidate in 1996, said the outcomes in New Mexico this year
and last should be a wake-up call for Democrats to field more
progressive candidates. And he noted that Green candidates were
running in November in two of New Mexico's three congressional
districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic Party is still in denial,'' he said. ``As
Greens begin fielding more candidates, we're going to see more of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Maloof, who is 31, pledged to spend what it takes to win in
November. ``Whatever the outcome,'' he said referring to Tuesday's
election, ``we still have November.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
