<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5330 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVIC-LIFE-BOS &LR;      06-24 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIC-LIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL DECRIES DECLINE OF CIVIC LIFE IN US 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Public trust in politicians and government is about
as low as it can go, and neither good economic times nor some
encouraging social trends are getting Americans off the sidelines
and into the action of creating a more civil society, a new report
says.
</P>
<P>
   The National Commission on Civic Renewal, a high-powered panel
of academics, business executives, and Washington insiders, issued
a failing report card Wednesday on the nation's moral health and
concluded the state of American civil life is as depressed as it
was during the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be a time of hope for Americans,'' the report
said. ``And when we consider our economic circumstances, it is. But
when we assess our country's civic and moral condition, we are
deeply troubled.''
</P>
<P>
   William Bennett, co-director of Empower America, a conservative
think tank, and author of the morally prescriptive ``Book of
Virtues,'' co-chaired the commission along with former senator Sam
Nunn, a Georgia Democrat. They said they overcame their political
differences to agree that lack of civic participation is weakening
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corrosive cynicism has crippled our civic spirit, and a sense
of helplessness has zapped our civic strength,'' said Rebecca
Rimel, president of the Pew Charitable Trusts, the philanthropy
that sponsored the 18-month study of declining citizen
participation in the US political process.
</P>
<P>
   The result of these ill feelings, the commission said, is that
Americans have become a ``nation of spectators'' who, instead of
taking individual reponsibility for their communities and families,
stand on the sidelines and whine or sit in front of the television,
mindlessly clicking the remote control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many of us have become passive and disengaged,'' the
report said. ``Too many of us lack confidence in our capacity to
make basic moral and civic judgments, to join with our neighbors
... to make a difference. Never have we had so many opportunities
for participation, yet rarely have we felt so powerless.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not all: According to the panel, which studied social
trends over 25 years as well as new survey data, Americans fret
about weak families but don't work to strengthen them, deplore
pubic schools but won't help their children with homework, worry
about out-of-wedlock births but won't condemn them, complain about
vulgar TV shows but don't turn off the set, and reelect leaders
they say they distrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans claim they are busier than they have ever been, that
they are stressed, stretched, and under extreme pressure for
time,'' said Bennett, who was President Reagan's education
secretary and President Bush's drug czar. ``Yet what we found is
that Americans have more leisure time than they ever have. They
watch more television than they ever have.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the question about time is how are Americans spending it,
and are they giving up civic things in order to keep the boat, or
the second house, or fourth motorcycle?'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission report says that compared to earlier generations,
Americans today place less value on what they owe society and
whether they need to play by the rules or fulfill obligations as
citizens. At the same time, they express individual liberty by
valuing self-gratification and personal choice more, Nunn said.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-member commission proposed a series of steps to civic
renewal, recommending that individuals join at least one civic
association, neighborhoods institute crime watches and clean-up
projects, and schools offer instruction in good citizenship and
historic documents, like the Federalist Papers.
</P>
<P>
   Analyzing and abhoring the end of a civil society has become one
of Washington's most popular academic pursuits. This commission's
report is the latest in a series of studies looking at why
Americans distrust government and politicians, why they don't vote,
and whether their disengagement from civic life is somehow warping
the nation's moral fiber.
</P>
<P>
   It also has some practical consequences. Low voter turnout and
declining political activity _ from making fewer campaign
contributions to not volunteering for a candidate _ can affect the
outcome of elections.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Solo, president of the nonprofit Institute for Civil Society
in Newton, says the commission's report ``misses the mark'' and is
typical of what happens when Washington's intellectual elite has a
conversation with itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``From where I sit, this doesn't look to me like a nation of
spectators,'' Solo said. ``There is a lot of innovation and
creative activity going on at the grass-roots level, where people
are redefining community and what being involved means.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report is most depressing because the elitists in
Washington treat local people like colonists and try to prescribe
their own 10-point training program for democracy,'' Solo said.
``What Americans have learned _ and the commission hasn't _ is that
national politics is not going to solve national problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the commission's report does note ``the stirrings of a
new movement of citizens acting together to solve community
problems.'' Because the movement operates on a shoestring and is
``nontraditional'' _ in other words, the impetus comes from
churches, foundations, and volunteers rather than government _ the
movement ``has gone largely unnoticed, unappreciated and
unsupported,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said another hopeful sign is some of the ``most
worrisome trends'' included in its index of national civic health
are turning around. Among them are crime rates, which have fallen
sharply in this decade; the lower divorce rate; improved school
performance; fewer teenage pregnancies; and even distrust in
government, which has leveled off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal shouldn't be a leveling off at the bottom,'' Nunn
said. ``We've got to see the trendline _ and trust in government _
going up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
