<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-265ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO BLOCK APPROVAL OF ABORTION PILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an affirmation of its anti-abortion stance, the
House voted Wednesday to block the Food and Drug Administration
from approving an abortion-inducing pill.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA in 1996 had deemed the pill, RU-486, safe and effective
and allowed its use in limited, tightly controlled studies. But it
has not given final approval for the pill's general use.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion opponents described the measure as a way to prevent the
use of taxpayer dollars to further the killing of unborn children;
abortion-rights advocates said the measure, which was attached to
an agriculture appropriations bill, was a circuitous way to try to
prevent women from having any kind of abortion, even one that they
say is the earliest, safest and least-invasive.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of Wednesday's House action _ on a relatively close
vote of 223-202 _ is unclear. The measure came to public attention
with so little advance notice that its sponsor, Rep. Tom Coburn,
R-Okla., an obstetrician who has delivered more than 3,200 babies,
said he was still looking for someone to introduce it in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, even under Republican control, has been more
supportive of abortion rights than the House. But if a similar
measure did pass the Senate, it would present President Clinton
with a dicey political dilemma, and neither side would predict
Wednesday what he might do.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who supports abortion rights, has supported the
advancement of RU-486 in the past. But opposing this measure would
also mean vetoing the broader, politically appealing $56 billion
agriculture bill.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The bill provides $23 billion in food stamps, $609 million for
food-safety inspection and $2 billion for rural economic projects.
It also helps wheat farmers by exempting them from sanctions on
India and Pakistan for exploding nuclear devices and protects
subsidies for sugar processors and peanut farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, a spokesman for President Clinton, said the
administration opposed the bill. He said it would mistakenly allow
Congress to intervene in the drug-safety standards of the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   But Lockhart stopped short of saying the president would veto
it. ``We're early in the process,'' he said, suggesting the Senate
would scrap the measure. ``We think we can solve this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, supporters of abortion rights were concerned that Clinton
could waver on this matter because he is under political pressure
on other fronts and has not held much sway lately on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This White House needs to issue a strong veto message
immediately,'' said Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., a leading defender in
the House of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton has stood firm in allowing a procedure that
abortion opponents call partial-birth abortion, the administration
has sent signals that Clinton could side with the Republicans on
the most recent anti-abortion measure to arise in the House. The
bill would make it a crime for anyone to transport a minor across
state lines for an abortion. Clinton's chief of staff, Erskine
Bowles, recently wrote a letter to Congress saying that the
president would support the measure if it were properly drafted.
</P>
<P>
   And the difficulty of opposing the entire agriculture bill
because it contains anti-abortion language was demonstrated by the
House. The agriculture bill passed overwhelmingly, 373-48. It was
opposed by 23 Republicans and only 25 Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
