A5340 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-ROBERTSO     06-24 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-ROBERTSONCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Getting foothold on soccer a pipe dream for U.S.
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NANTES, France _ By nature, Americans aren't quitters. We're the
world's leading can-do country by far. Bigger, better, richer _
that's what Old Glory stands for.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, in soccer. Or football, as most of the rest
of the globe knows it.
</P>
<P>
   When the soon-to-be-unemployed U.S. coach, Steve Sampson,
accused his floundering team of, yikes, playing ``like Americans''
against Iran, he spoke a cruel truth. In the planet's most popular
sport, we remain second-rate. We're closer to being the Clippers
than we are to being the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Lots of reasons, none of which you need for me to
reiterate. They beg the obvious. A more to-the-point question is, I
think, ``Why should it make any difference?''
</P>
<P>
   We aren't very good in field hockey, team handball, table tennis
or cricket, either.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, we don't play cricket, do we? Perhaps we shouldn't
play soccer, either.
</P>
<P>
   No, that's not right. It provides wonderful exercise for our
kids without presenting a grave threat to their collarbones.
Anything that can drag America's youth away from MTV and Nintendo
for a couple hours a day definitely has merit.
</P>
<P>
   As for continuing our clearly quixotic quest to become a soccer
Goliath, however, it appears time to contemplate aborting the
mission with the current Coupe du Monde drawing to another dreary
conclusion for the overmatched U.S. entry.
</P>
<P>
   A loss to Yugoslavia here in this Brittany seaport tonight _ a
likely scenario given the demoralized, divided state of the U.S.
team, never mind the Yugos' practical need to whip the Yanks by as
many goals as possible _ will leave Sampson's Delilahs exactly
where America's starry-eyed kiddie contingent of 1990 stood in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Oh-and-three. Zero points. Four-F in Group F. To date, the U.S.
has spent more than three hours scampering about the pitch and
scored one goal. In short, and in shorts, we are jogging in place.
This despite at least a generation-long effort to produce, in
sufficient quantities, men who can compete on reasonably equal
footing with the Ronaldos, Baggios and Zidanes.
</P>
<P>
   If it hasn't happened by now, people, it ain't going to happen.
Baseball is our, quote-unquote, national pastime, yet we can't
develop enough major-league pitchers to adequately fill out
rosters. How are we supposed to imagine strikers gifted enough to
play Premier League in England, much less star for Turin's
Juventus, AC Milan or Real Madrid? The notion is absurde!
</P>
<P>
   It's the same reason baseball goes begging for good arms. Our
best, and hungriest, athletes choose other pursuits. When the
children of the inner city start practicing headers and bicycle
kicks off graffiti-marked walls in Brooklyn, South Central LA or
Houston's Fifth Ward, then will we have a snowball's chance of
winning the World Cup. The American college system has no hope of
developing a team on par with the mighty Brazilians, Italians or,
for that matter, the war-weary Yugoslavians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer in the USA is still a very young sport,'' notes Vujadin
Boskov, Yugoslavia's wizened veteran of a half century in the game.
``(Americans) run a lot, work a lot, but they still do not have
outstanding individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody coached Michael Jordan into becoming Michael Jordan. He
had the right genes, and the requisite want-to, to evolve into the
world's greatest athlete. Had he picked soccer instead of hoops as
the sport he intended to dominate, he would be at least the equal
of any player anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't, because poor, black kids in rural, backwater
towns or teeming slums have no more exposure to soccer than a boy
in Marseille, Naples or So Paulo has to squash. They're more apt to
accidentally wind up with a 5-iron, or a hockey stick, in their
hands than wearing an Umbro shirt.
</P>
<P>
   So what's to lament? We can't be the best at everything. We must
pick our spots _ and sports _ and not fret about the rest. Soccer
doesn't need America's rabid interest to thrive, and we don't need
soccer to amuse us. Our society already misdirects too much energy
and resources toward jock pursuits at the expense of education and
public services.
</P>
<P>
   When the U.S. Soccer Federation says it needs $40 million to
meet the demand for grants by local associations to upgrade their
programs, the heart stops pumping for a moment. Talk about throwing
good money after bad, particularly if the underlying goal is to
raise our own Ronaldo.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Rothenberg, the Federation's president, may have had the
best idea when he joked before the Iran defeat about dispatching
more U.S. servicemen to mingle with the populace in soccer's A-list
countries. Because fathering a soccer star abroad seems a far
easier proposition than growing him in the back yard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
