<SLUG> BC-HN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS PLAY BY THE RULES IN EXPANSION DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In deciding whom to leave unprotected for Friday's NHL
expansion draft, the Bruins had to figure out how best to play by
the rules.
</P>
<P>
   According to the NHL guidelines that will be used for stocking
the Nashville Predators, Boston must expose at least one defenseman
and forward who played 40 games this year or 70 combined in the
last two years. President-general manager Harry Sinden said the
Bruins wanted to protect two goaltenders _ Byron Dafoe and Rob
Tallas _ which meant they could protect just three defensemen
initially.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're allowed to protect one additional player, forward or
defenseman, and we chose to protect an extra (fourth) defenseman,''
said Sinden. ``Had we protected only one goaltender, we could've
protected five, but we were not in a position to lose a goalie. We
weren't going to leave Robbie exposed, anyway, but had we had any
thoughts of that, we wouldn't have done it after Byron's (shoulder)
surgery. That forced us to leave both Dave Ellett and Grant Ledyard
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellett's age (34) and sizable contract and Ledyard's age (36)
made it worth the calculated risk for Boston to expose them. Sinden
said he preferred to take a chance on losing them than someone like
25-year-old Darren Van Impe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think he's better than Ellett and Ledyard, but would
we lose him? I think there's a good chance we would,'' said Sinden.
</P>
<P>
   The likely forward to be lost is two-way center Mike Sullivan,
30. Sinden believes the Bruins have enough depth at the slot
position that if Sullivan is selected, they can absorb it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a matter of deciding between him and Landon Wilson,''
said Sinden. ``I don't think they'll take Mike. Wilson is our
draft. We look at No. 19 (Boston's first-round pick, which Colorado
received in trade for Wilson and defenseman Anders Myrvold) and
say, `Would we sooner have what's there at 19 or have Wilson?' He's
only 23. To us, he's a way better prospect than anything that's
available at 19. He's got to play more, he's got to get better to
stick, but so would the No. 19 guy. It would've been different if
it were the top No. 6 or 8, but I think right now, by getting
Wilson, we got every bit as good a player as we would at No. 19.''
</P>
<P>
   Another possible loss could be 32-year-old enforcer Ken
Baumgartner, a favorite of coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very important to the chemistry and the makeup of the
team,'' Sinden said. ``The coach feels he needs him badly, and I
agree with him. He could be drafted by Nashville. I'm led to
believe they won't, but he could be. If he is, we've got to look
somewhere else for that kind of a role player. But for $80 million
(the expansion fee), you've got to give up something. There are a
number of players like him available who are younger, and we knew
there would be, so you calculate that they'd take a younger player.
Whether they do or not, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Another scenario is that Nashville, which must take a player
from each of the 26 established clubs, could select a Bruin who can
become a free agent as of next Wednesday, anyway. That way, the
Predators would adhere to the rules, wouldn't have to sign the
player and thus would have more money to spend elsewhere, and the
Bruins really wouldn't lose anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the impression _ and it was only an impression _ that
they would take a player from us that they really didn't want and
just dump him, not even sign him,'' said Sinden. ``I call it a
throwaway pick. Then instead of taking on a contract, they would
take a throwaway pick and use the money to go out and get a
different free agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden used defenseman Evgeny Shaldybin as an example. If the
Predators take him and don't make him a qualifying offer, Shaldybin
would be a total free agent. Nashville could use the money it
would've paid him to put toward an unrestricted free agent like
Brett Hull.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are allowed to take six people like that from across the
league,'' Sinden said. ``If they passed on six contracts, even at
$500,000 a player, that would give them $3 million to go out and
work with. There's a thinking (by other teams) that they're going
to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for making deals, Sinden will wait to see how the expansion
draft plays out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose if we lost a defenseman in the draft, we'd be
initiating something,'' he said. ``With Ellett and Ledyard, plus
the four we're protecting and Hal Gill, that gives us seven, which
is all we need here. We need another two or three in Providence who
could come up and play. Johnathan Aitken going down there makes
eight. On defense, we're not really deep in the organization right
now. Barry Richter and Jon Rohloff haven't really worked out, and
the Russians we tried haven't come around.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
