<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DOUGLAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUGLAS HOPING TO REPEAT HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET PEQUOT RESERVATION _ His face looked drawn and his
belly seemed to sag, fighting against the elastic of his purple
waistband as he stepped on the scales Wednesday. Buster Douglas was
ready to fight.
</P>
<P>
   That is the way it is for Douglas these days, eight years and
150 pounds having come and gone since the night he destroyed Mike
Tyson in Tokyo for the world heavyweight championship. That
evening, Douglas was a 231-pound, 29-year-old fanatic hell-bent on
only one thing: winning a fight. Thursday night he will be someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   When he enters the ring at Foxwoods to face a younger
heavyweight named Lou Savarese, Douglas will be a 242-pound,
38-year-old man who has lost a title and all those pounds just to
reach this point ... which is probably only one or two more
victories away from another shot at Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas will be seeking the first of those victories against
someone who appears to be his polar opposite. While Douglas looked
worn out and soft Wednesday, like a man who has lost too much
weight to rid himself of all the skin that once surrounded it,
Savarese looked like an action movie hero. At 234 1/2 rock-hard
pounds, the 32-year-old Savarese appeared to be everything Douglas
no longer was. But boxing is deceiving in that way. What you look
like and how you fight are often two different things, and that is
what Douglas will be counting on when he hitches up his shorts on
pay-per-view to risk future millions against a fighter who has lost
two of his last three but has the appearance of a guy who could
derail an old man in search of one last dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fighting him because he was the only one out there,
actually,'' said Douglas (36-5-1) when asked why he was risking
what's left of his future against Savarese (36-2), who is barely a
year removed from a split-decision loss to George Foreman. ``We
thought we had other opportunities but we didn't have a ton of
smart possibilities. I expect him to come to fight, but this kid is
going to get peppered. He's going to get totally outclassed.
Totally outgunned. Totally outmanned.''
</P>
<P>
   If he is, Douglas will have won his seventh straight fight since
a six-year layoff that came after he lost the titles he'd won from
Tyson to Evander Holyfield in his next outing. By the time Douglas
collapsed from a punch in the nose from Holyfield, he had learned
that Shakespeare's King Lear was right about the difficulties of
ruling the kingdom, regardless of what kingdom we're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uneasy lies the head that wears the crown,'' Lear once
lamented. And Douglas learned that firsthand after being peppered
by lawsuits before he found himself outclassed, outgunned, and
outmanned by Holyfield and a battery of lawyers for Steve Wynn, Don
King, and John Johnson (his former manager).
</P>
<P>
   After that fight, Douglas walked away from boxing and began to
eat. And eat. And eat. He ate until he weighed nearly 400 pounds
and lay in a diabetic coma. Then it was back to boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started this for my health, but it's changed,'' Douglas
said. ``Now it's an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity is to relive a moment that ran too short. It is
the opportunity to get another shot at Tyson or Holyfield or the
title World Boxing Council champion Lennox Lewis now owns. It is an
opportunity to save his health and his spirit, which was lost in
boxing's maze after he became the accidental champion that glorious
night in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this started again, really, all I wanted was a chance to
rewrite things with Holyfield,'' Douglas said. ``Now all three of
them are about the same to me, and it's exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more joyous now than it was in 1990. I guess it's a
little surprising it got to this, because by the latter part of
last year, it didn't look like things would work out (proposed
fights with John Ruiz, Roy Jones Jr., and Lewis collapsed). Now I
hear my name mentioned with the Big Three, so I'm ready to fight
Savarese for this little (International Boxing Association) title
and then go after a world title ... or that little punk.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow it always seems to come back to that little punk when
Buster Douglas's name is in the conversation. He was the first to
lick Godzilla, the first to show what was really behind the curtain
in the Land of Oz. He was the first to destroy Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are still many fight fans who will argue that it was
all just a fluke, that Douglas happened to be a 42-1 shot in the
right place at the right time to beat a guy who mentally had been
worn down by his own sad circumstances. Buster Douglas understands
those people, just as he understands the risk he is taking night
against Savarese.
</P>
<P>
   But he is unconcerned because he believes another chance is
coming and Lou Savarese will provide it for him, and when it
arrives, he will answer both the bell and those charges one last
time, just like he did that night in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll knock his ass out again,'' Douglas said of Tyson.
``Holyfield beat a shell of what I beat. That (expletive) punk.
It'll be easier this time. It'll be just like what's going to
happen to this kid Savarese. He's going to get peppered. He's going
to get totally outgunned.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings Buster Douglas back to the man he is really
chasing. Back to Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it is Holyfield he wants, not Mike Tyson. It is
Holyfield, not Lennox Lewis; Holyfield, not Lou Savarese;
Holyfield, not another world title. It is Holyfield and Holyfield
alone because it was he who took Douglas's self-esteem when he
knocked him on his back nine minutes into their meeting in Las
Vegas, leaving him lying on the floor with no desire to get up even
though many thought he could.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson may be in his future, but Evander Holyfield is why
Douglas will risk millions Thursday night against Tyson. He risks
them to one day get back in front of Evander Holyfield and stay
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to get the opportunity to show him my best,'' Douglas
said. ``His time is short, but I do think there's a chance,
especially with the Henry Akinwande fight falling out. He doesn't
really have many competitive opponents, either.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Douglas heard his name called. It was time to strip
down to his shorts, his lower abdomen hanging low like a
gunfighter's belt. He looked like an old man in front of the
bathroom mirror, gravity winning a fight with his waistline.
</P>
<P>
   But he stood there, anyway, half-naked, and weighed in before
posing next to Savarese, who looked so much younger and so much
stronger and so much more like a fighter than Buster Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he went back to his room, his trainer, John Russell,
by his side, knowing that what he looks like at a weigh-in won't
matter Thursday night. What will matter is what he does. And as he
shuffled away, one of his supporters looked at him and said,
``Buster's going to walk through this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   From the looks of the two of them, it hardly seemed possible,
but eight years ago, this same man stood in a similar situation
with another fighter no one thought he could beat, and the rest is
history. By late Thursday night, either Lou Savarese or Buster
Douglas will be, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
