<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO:BUFETE-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S BUFETE INDUSTRIAL: BUILDING CONFIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international and ``f'' financial files.) 
 By BRENDAN M. CASE 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    MEXICO CITY _ Being a shareholder in Bufete Industrial has been
rough going lately.
 &HT;    The Mexican construction and engineering company lost three big
public tenders last year after management all but promised it would
win at least one. Its backlog of projects grew, but didn't provide
much cash flow to pay the debts weighing down its balance sheet.
And the Federal Electricity Commission (CFE) continued to delay
payment of a three-year-old Bufete receivable worth at least US$65
million, a further drag on the bottom line.
 &HT;    This year could be different. New tenders will provide new
chances to win a brass ring, Mexico's construction recovery could
boost revenues 20 percent to 30 percent from Bufete's level of $495
million last year, and the CFE might finally pay up.
 &HT;    With some good news to trumpet, markets might even take stock of
the strength of Bufete's underlying strategy: Since 1994, the
company has diversified its business within Mexico and successfully
expanded abroad, laying the groundwork for a sturdy, well-tempered
balance sheet.
 &HT;    But only the groundwork. For now, Bufete needs to reduce its
$280 million debt load, interest payments on which essentially
cancel out operating profits. ``The balance sheet is definitely an
issue, as well as investors' frustration regarding the CFE
payment,'' says Gordon Lee, an analyst with Deutsche Morgan
Grenfell in Mexico City.
 &HT;    Bufete could also regain market confidence by proving it can
still win large public tenders. Much of last year's discontent
regarding Bufete came from its failure to win one of the contracts
tendered by state-owned oil monopoly Pemex, worth around $1 billion
each.
 &HT;    Worst of all, Bufete and several Japanese partners lost the
contract to refurbish Pemex's Cadereyta refinery near Monterrey to
an upstart alliance of Mexico's Tribasa, South Korea's Sunkyong
Engineering and Germany's Siemens _ even though the project's
premium engineering work is Bufete's specialty.
 &HT;    Jarringly, the Bufete group's bid was nearly double the
winner's, leading to speculation that one of them misunderstood the
requirements.
 &HT;    It's not clear who erred or how, but the debacle made Bufete
look amateurish.
 &HT;    Financial strength became crucial in Mexico's construction
industry in the wake of the economic crisis of 1995, as Pemex and
the CFE introduced projects that were financed by the contractors _
and their foreign partners with better access to foreign financing.
That shift did not play to Bufete's traditional strengths, but with
a return this year to direct financing by the state companies,
Bufete's strong engineering skills could help it win one or more of
three large refinery refurbishments in Ciudad Madero, Salina Cruz,
and Minatitlan. Each is reckoned to be worth as much as $800
million. Winning one could be an immediate shot in the arm for
Bufete's stock.
 &HT;    ``Operating profits are very sensitive to movement in [revenue]
growth, because operating costs are pretty steady,'' says Sebastian
Shatel, an analyst with Caspian Research in Mexico City. ``The
outlook for Bufete is more positive just because of that.'' Big
projects get headlines and boost stock prices, but counting on them
is risky. Indeed, Jose Mendoza, Bufete's president, moved to reduce
Bufete's traditional reliance on Pemex and the CFE in 1994, and
seems to have succeeded. While the big disappointments of last year
dominated the market's attention, Bufete also proved itself a
diversified company with important foreign interests and a good mix
of domestic projects.
 &HT;    In late 1994, Bufete took its first big step abroad by buying
the Chilean construction firm Ovalle Moore. Even as Mexico copied
Chile in everything from telecommunications liberalization to the
introduction of a private pension plan, Bufete learned that the
Southern Cone country's construction industry was fragmented and
actually less advanced than Mexico's. By introducing its own
technology and management ideas, it has turned Ovalle Moore into a
market leader _ and the source of nearly 25 percent of Bufete's
revenues last year. Bufete is also active in Argentina, built a
refinery in Ecuador, and has even ventured into the United States
with simple projects such as housing complexes and schools.
 &HT;    With so much foreign activity, more than 50 percent of Bufete's
1997 revenues were in dollars (some of which came from Mexican
projects denominated in dollars). That percentage should fall a bit
this year if the company's core Mexican operations make a comeback,
but it will also provide a nice cushion against any future peso
surprises. Within Mexico, the company won a project to build
low-income housing in Tabasco _ not glamorous work but something
that allows Bufete to keep its foot in the door of a fast-growing
market.
 &HT;    With continued diversification, serious debt reduction and a bit
of luck in scoring a big contract this year, shareholders could
smile again.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
