<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-1,000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T TO ACQUIRE TCI, NATION'S SECOND BIGGEST CABLE PROVIDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: AT&AMP;T-ASSESS, AT&AMP;T-FCC, AT&AMP;T-EXECS,
AT&AMP;T-MARKETPLACE) 
(ART ADV: 3 graphics _ merger logistics, map showing TCI's national
reach, recent deals in telecommunications _ are being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ps) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, the nation's largest telephone company, said Wednesday
that it had agreed to acquire Tele-Communications Inc., the second
biggest cable television provider, for $31.8 billion in stock in a
deal that is the most ambitious product yet of the 1996
deregulation of the telecommunications industry by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T will assume TCI's debt of about $11 billion and will pay
$5.5 billion in cash to repurchase shares it issued to TCI in a
previous transaction. AT&AMP;T will also acquire TCI's interest in a
venture that delivers Internet data over television cables. That
gives the deal a total value of about $48.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Combining AT&AMP;T's financial muscle and nation-spanning
communications network with TCI's wires into millions of homes
would create a communications behemoth with a reach unrivaled since
AT&AMP;T spun off its local phone operations in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, behemoths in general are not what they used to be in
the communications industry. Since the Telecommunications Act of
1996 was signed two years ago, huge mergers have become almost
common in the industry, with the seven Bell local phone companies
agreeing to become four and MCI Communications Corp. making a deal
to be acquired by Worldcom Inc. for $37 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But a deal between AT&AMP;T and TCI could be the first to make a
concrete difference in how everyday consumers purchase and use
communications services. By giving AT&AMP;T an electronic path into
millions of homes and apartments, the acquisition could create
vibrant competition in the market for local telephone service for
the first time since AT&AMP;T's predecessor was led by Alexander Graham
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies said they wanted to begin selling digital
phone and data service over the cable system by the end of next
year but would not commit to a firm timetable for deployment. The
companies said they would begin to bundle and jointly market one
another's existing services as soon as possible, even before the
deal closes.
</P>
<P>
   TCI and its affiliates have run wires past about a third of the
nation's households. So even after acquiring the cable giant, AT&AMP;T
would not have a clear path into the local market for most of the
nation's consumers. And it is not entirely clear how difficult and
expensive it will be to adapt TCI's cable networks, which are
generally designed to transmit information in only one direction,
for use in two-way data and voice communications.
</P>
<P>
   But that is what C. Michael Armstrong, who took over as AT&AMP;T's
chairman just last November, intends to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this doesn't deliver on the promise of the telecom act of
'96, I've just missed my bet,'' he said in an interview Wednesday.
Armstrong said he was sending a message to the Bell companies,
which dominate the local phone business: ``We intend to show up.
Also, many in Washington had some doubt that AT&AMP;T was serious about
pursuing the $110 billion local exchange business, and this mutes
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The hectic pace of communications mergers has raised hackles on
Capitol Hill and at the Federal Communications Commission. But the
commission's chairman, William Kennard, approached the AT&AMP;T
announcement with an encouraging attitude on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies bring some synergies that are quite
compelling,'' he said in an interview. ``They're not direct
head-to-head competitors but both of them have said in the past
that they want to offer a package of services to consumers. If
through the combination they are able to bundle services and be
more competitive with the incumbent providers, it's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard added that his review would hinge on the details of the
companies' plans, which he had not yet seen. But his positive
comments were very different from the reaction AT&AMP;T received the
last time it tried to break into local markets through acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   After news emerged last summer that AT&AMP;T was negotiating to
acquire SBC Communications, the Bell company that provides local
phone service in much of the West, Reed Hundt, then the
commission's chairman, called such a deal ``unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   TCI had a preliminary agreement to be acquired by Bell Atlantic
Corp. in 1993, but those talks fell apart amid antitrust concerns.
The two common communications pipelines into homes are the phone
wire and the cable television wire. By acquiring TCI, Bell Atlantic
would have eliminated a potential competitor.
</P>
<P>
   But AT&AMP;T has minimal presence in local markets, and by acquiring
TCI it could potentially become a more formidable competitor
against its former subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Kimmelman, co-director of the Washington office of
Consumers Union, a consumer advocacy group, said the deal held
promise but added a note of skepticism about AT&AMP;T's intentions of
competing for local phone business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the deal that is the make-it-or-break-it for the
telecom act,'' he said. ``This is the first proposal for
cross-industry competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Using industry shorthand for telephone calls, he added: ``Every
effort to use the cable wire for telephony has been less than
successful. I'm concerned that AT&AMP;T maybe is buying the cable cash
cow and milking it for profits and hoping _ hoping _ that it can be
used for telephony.''
</P>
<P>
   TCI is in the first phase of a $1.7 billion project to upgrade
its networks to offer advanced service. But Malone said that TCI
had little chance to buy the asset it needs most for the future: a
widely recognized brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a strong, well-established communications brand our
penetration with these sorts of services would be adversely
affected,'' Malone said. ``It would be virtually impossible for my
company to construct a brand on our own to enter that space.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why all TCI services will be sold under the AT&AMP;T name.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, holders of TCI Series A stock would
receive .7757 shares of AT&AMP;T. Holders of the cable companies'
Series B stock, including Malone, would receive .8533 shares of
AT&AMP;T stock.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T expects to finish the deal in the first half next year. The
company said the acquisition would dilute its earnings for the
first two years after the deal's completion and add to its earnings
after that.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Malone would join AT&AMP;T's board and remain chairman of Liberty
Media, TCI's programming wing, which would remain under his control
even as its stock became a so-called tracking stock of AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T would fold TCI's cable assets into its consumer business
and spin off that unit as another tracking stock. John Zeglis,
AT&AMP;T's president, would become chairman of the consumer unit while
Leo Hindery, TCI's president, would become the unit's chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong would remain at the helm of the AT&AMP;T parent company,
which would retain the company's network operation and the units
that sell services to business customers and other communications
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for a AT&AMP;T and TCI combination started last November
when Armstrong visited Malone to discuss ways the two companies
could work together, the two men said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies began final negotiations just last Tuesday,
they said. Several days ago, a small team of executives from both
companies holed up with their advisers to hammer out the details of
an agreement, said a person close to those talks. By Monday,
Armstrong and Malone were spending long hours at the offices of
AT&AMP;T's law firm, Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen &AMP; Katz, in face-to-face
meetings hashing out the final details.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month AT&AMP;T held preliminary discussions with
America Online Inc., the No. 1 provider of access to cyberspace,
about a merger between the two companies, but America Online was
not interested in such a deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
