<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XIAN SCRAMBLES TO READY ITSELF FOR CLINTON'S ARRIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-GOALS, CHINA-ZHAO,
CHINA-LAW, CHINA-PEONY, CHINA-PEONY-FRANCE, CHINA-RELICS-FEUD) 
(bl) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIAN, China _ With just 24 hours to go before President
Clinton's arrival here, this city was madly at work putting the
finishing touches on its latest make-over.
</P>
<P>
   Although most everyone knew that Clinton was coming here soon,
it was only Wednesday morning that the local news media announced
that the big day was Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As if anyone needed an announcement.
</P>
<P>
   On Weiyang Road leading into town from the airport, ads and
slogans had been removed from factory walls, covered with a fresh
coat of whitewash. The police were standing on freshly painted
traffic kiosks. And orange cones that stretched for miles guarded
freshly painted divider lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Xian is very dusty so they've even dusted off the greenery,''
said a taxi driver who gave his name as Ma. ``I hope President
Clinton doesn't nap on the way into town, otherwise this will all
be for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Police are part of the scenery in China. But even for China,
their presence around this city of 2.7 million people was huge,
with police cars and motorcycles outnumbering civilian cars on some
stretches of highway.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, police seemed far outnumbered by the small armies
of street cleaners in bright orange vests who crouched at the edge
of streets like the busy Second Ring Road, meticulously sweeping
every last speck of dust into sewers or dustpans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sub-district government had a meeting last week and told
us that Clinton was coming so we should keep the city especially
clean,'' said Li Putan, 62, a migrant worker from Gansu province
who was raking, then sweeping, a seemingly spotless patch of dirt
across from Xiaoyanta Park.
</P>
<P>
   Pedicabs, ordinarily a common form of transport in Xian, were
ordered off the street two weeks ago. Pedicab drivers have
organized demonstrations to protest, but none of that was apparent
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some factory workers, like those at the Xian Petrochemical
Plant, said long-overdue pension payments had been paid in full so
that all would be calm for the presidential visit.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, workers had hung dozens of red lanterns at the
elegant South Gate of Xian's old city wall, where the president
will be welcomed in an elaborate ceremony Thursday evening. For the
moment, each lantern remained carefully wrapped in its plastic bag.
Enormous rolls of red carpet lay piled on the pavement, waiting to
be laid out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome Americans,'' said Liu Yongchen, a balding retired
factory worker who now runs a toy stall in the cavernous, private
Changle Market.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how he had heard of the Clinton visit, he replied:
``The owner of the mall called us all to a meeting last week and
told us to welcome Americans. Everything is pre-arranged here!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
