<HEADER>
A5403 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-ANTITRUST-06     06-24 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-TCI-ANTITRUST-0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MERGER PRESENTS ANTITRUST REGULATORS WITH A DILEMMA
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The AT&AMP;T Corp.'s proposed $68 billion takeover of
cable giant Tele-Communications Inc. will be closely examined by
federal officials in a regulatory high-wire act destined to shape
the way American homes and businesses buy telephone services worth
more than $1 trillion a year.
</P>
<P>
   As details of the proposed mega-merger developed Wednesday, it
wasn't clear whether the Justice Department or the Federal
Communications Commission would ultimately be charged with deciding
whether to bless the deal or condemn it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will be reviewing that,'' Attorney General Janet Reno told
reporters, ''but there is no final decision that has been made with
respect to whether the FCC would handle it or we would handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the issues will revolve around a question that has
perplexed telecommunications regulators ever since the government
ordered AT&AMP;T to spin off its regional companies in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   That question, put simply, is: When must regulators intervene to
promote increased choices and improved prices for consumers of
telecommunications services, and when should they get out of the
way and let technology and market dynamics play that role?
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma has been complicated by technological advances that
have revolutionized telecommunications over the past 14 years,
turning an industry built on copper wire, creosote-soaked poles and
dial tones into a global web of satellite signals, cell phones and
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   When the government broke up Ma Bell, it essentially split the
industry into two parts: the regional ``Baby Bells'' such as
Atlanta-based BellSouth would offer local service, while AT&AMP;T and a
handful of competitors would provide long-distance service, relying
on the regional companies to relay the calls to homes and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side of the industry was ever fully satisfied with being
shut out of the other _ by regulations, in the case of the Baby
Bells, and by the high cost of installing local lines and switching
systems, in the case of the long-distance carriers _ of part of the
telephone business.
</P>
<P>
   Buying TCI would give AT&AMP;T something it currently doesn't have:
a wire into millions of homes. With some engineering changes, that
wire could carry high-quality telephone calls and extremely fast
connections to the Internet as easily as it carries cable
television signals.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, would enable AT&AMP;T to provide one-stop shopping
for millions of consumers, something the telecommunications
behemoth has wanted since the breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ''This goes back to 1984,'' said former AT&AMP;T executive Douglas
Dunn, dean of the graduate school of industrial administration at
Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh. ''It has been AT&AMP;T's
passion.''
</P>
<P>
   By enabling AT&AMP;T to provide a full bundle of telecommunications
services, said Dunn, the merger would increase competition and
promote increased options for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the Justice Department is concerned, Dunn said, that
should satisfy any potential anti-trust concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''My guess is it's a free ride through Justice,'' said Dunn.
''The FCC's going to have a much tougher time.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the FCC is charged with actually enhancing
competition, not merely protecting it.
</P>
<P>
   ''This merger is eminently thinkable,'' FCC Chairman William
Kennard said Wednesday in a speech to the Federal Communications
Bar Association, ''but only if there are tangible consumer
benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The FCC is already under challenge by the Baby Bells to allow
them to compete in the lucrative long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 Telecommunications Act was designed to facilitate their
entry into long-distance, but the Baby Bells aren't satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, for instance, hasn't been able to win federal
approval to offer long-distance rates, said the company's
Washington spokesman, Bill McCloskey.
</P>
<P>
   If the AT&AMP;T-TCI deal is approved, he said, it could crack open
the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have an increased urgency for the FCC to allow us into the
long distance market,'' McCloskey said, ''because you have a major
competitor now able to come in and offer the kind of services
people want _ everything on one bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry analyst John Mayo, a professor of economics, business
and public policy at Georgetown University, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ''This one seems to have, at least on its face, an essentially
pro-competitive engine driving it,'' Mayo said of the proposed
AT&AMP;T-TCI merger.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   Eyeing a raft of industry mega-mergers _ last year's $22.7
billion wedding between Bell Atlantic and NYNEX; a pending takeover
of MCI Communications Corp. by WorldCom for $37 billion; and SBC
Communications Inc.'s proposed $62 billion merger with Ameritech _
some analysts see consolidation resulting in fewer choices, not
more, for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is part of a larger story of how the telecommunications
law (of 1996) is one of the greatest has-beens that never was of
all time,'' said George Kleinfeld, an attorney with extensive
global telecommunications experience with the Washington firm of
Rogers &AMP; Wells. ''The giants have decided to consolidate or to
cooperate, to make the market less, rather than more, competitive.
This is just one more example of that rather sad trend.''
</P>
<P>
   FCC Commissioner Susan Ness, not surprisingly, doesn't see it
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the core of FCC merger policy is that merger review helps
to promote the pro-competitive, deregulatory framework established
by Congress in the Telecommunications Act of 1996,'' Ness testified
Wednesday before the House Judiciary Committee. ''Signs of budding
competition are emerging.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
