<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERU PREMIER OFFERS TO QUIT IN DISPUTE OVER AMERICAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ Peru's prime minister of three weeks said Wednesday
that he had offered to resign after President Alberto Fujimori
rejected his suggestion to pardon an American imprisoned on
terrorism charges. Fujimori declined the resignation offer.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Javier Valle Riestra sparked a storm of
congressional protests when he said Sunday that the 1996 military
trial of Lori Helene Berenson, a 28-year-old former New York
resident, was legally flawed and should be annulled.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Fujimori emphatically and swiftly rejected the
suggestion that Ms. Berenson be expelled to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Valle Riestra, in a radio interview Wednesday, said he was in
``a difficult emotional situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I live in a difficult situation because I can't be in
continual and constant disagreement with majority opinion,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since his surprise appointment as coordinator of Fujimori's
cabinet only three weeks ago, Valle Riestra has made a series of
statements opposing government policy that have puzzled foreign
diplomats and local journalists alike.
</P>
<P>
   On his first day as prime minister, he said he opposed
Fujimori's expected bid for a third term in 2000. Soon after, Valle
Riestra said he disagreed with the government's plan to use
military courts to try common criminals. And he has suggested that
several Cabinet members be dismissed and replaced by human rights
lawyers who have been critical of Fujimori.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Valle Riestra's televised statement on Sunday about
Ms. Berenson that left him isolated from the entire Fujimori
administration and much of the political establishment. Newspaper
editorials harshly criticized him, as did several prominent
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Valle Riestra said Ms. Berenson should be pardoned because of a
lack of due process and ``for reasons of state and for the sake of
Peru's prestige.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berenson has been held in a tiny cell high in the Andes
since her conviction in January 1996 by a tribunal that did not
allow her lawyers to question evidence or to cross-examine
witnesses. She was accused of aiding the Marxist guerrilla group
Tupac Amaru in a plan to take the Peruvian Congress hostage. Ms.
Berenson said she was innocent but expressed sympathy for the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's choice of Valle Riestra came as a complete surprise.
The 67-year-old constitutional lawyer and former congressman had
long been a member of the leftist APRA party and an advocate of
human rights. But with Fujimori's standing in the polls falling,
the economy jeopardized by the Asian economic crisis, and sensitive
negotiations with Ecuador over a border dispute entering a crucial
stage, several experts said the president was looking to broaden
his base and improve his image by naming a liberal to be prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, Valle Riestra sounded tired and frustrated,
as if acknowledging that his efforts to push reforms in the
Fujimori administration had failed. But by an afternoon news
conference, he sounded defiant again, as if Fujimori's refusal to
accept his resignation signified a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will continue in this struggle, even when I oppose the chief
of state,'' he told reporters, shaking his fist. ``All the
repressive acts of this government must be opposed, and that is
what I will continue to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
