<HEADLINE>
JUDGE QUESTIONS USE OF CONSUMER LAW IN HANDGUN SAFETY EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A Superior Court judge questioned Wednesday whether
state Attorney General Scott Harshbarger has the authority under
the state's consumer protection law to require handgun
manufacturers to meet new standards for quality and safety.
</P>
<P>
   During a hearing on a request by gunmakers to block a new set of
handgun safety regulations, Judge Diane Kottmyer said Harshbarger's
approach could have an effect on every product sold in
Massachusetts _ not just those handguns Harshbarger believes are
unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's simply no way to narrow a (legal) holding that the
attorney general has the authority to issue these regulations so
they do not apply across every line of product sold in
Massachusetts,'' Kottmyer told Assistant Attorney General Glenn S.
Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaplan argued the regulations &UR;  &LR; Harshbarger announced last
spring are narrowly drawn and affect only handguns that do not meet
the standards. Such failures, he said, makes the guns a danger to
consumers; therefore, Harshbarger was well within his authority to
set new standards.
</P>
<P>
   Kottmyer said she would hand down a decision on the request for
a temporary court order by Tuesday, when a new set of regulations
are to go into effect. Arguments over the regulations are expected
to continue through August.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking the state consumer protection law, Harshbarger has
issued regulations on handguns broken into three phases. The first
phase took effect Jan. 15 and requires warning labels on each
handgun sold in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In the second phase, set to begin next Tuesday, all handguns
sold in the state must meet minimum standards governing the quality
of materials used to make them. They must also pass a test to
ensure they will not accidentally fire when dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The third phase, scheduled for Sept. 30, requires all handguns
to have trigger locks, requires gunmakers to build guns with
triggers stiff enough to resist the pull of a child, and an
indicator that shows how many cartridges are in the gun.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Frank A. Libby, Jr., who represents several gun
manufacturers and gun store owners, told Kottmyer that Harshbarger
went too far when he issued the new regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's swimming well past the markers,'' Libby said.
</P>
<P>
   Libby also filed affidavits from store owners who said the new
regulations could put them out of business.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Wayne Marshall, the owner of the Gloucester Cobbler store,
said the cost of doing the proposed safety tests on used handguns
sold by his store are high enough to bankrupt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect that the total costs of these tests alone will force
me out of business,'' Marshall wrote in his affidavit. He said the
store is his sole source of income and that handgun sales account
for 48 percent of his annual revenue, which ranges from $60,000 to
$90,00 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Eldon McElhiney, the owner of a self-named store in Waltham,
said handguns account for 88 percent of his $220,000 in yearly
sales, but the regulations have caused one supplier to stop selling
new weapons to him.
</P>
<P>
   But John A. Wortmann, Jr., an attorney who represents the
Massachusetts Association of Police Chiefs, nine physician-related
groups and the Center for Handgun Violence, told Kottmyer that
regulators already set manufacturing standards for all kinds of
products, such as automobiles. Gunmakers alone are wrongly exempt
from goverment scrutiny on the quality and workmanship of their
product.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
