<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ MAKING CHEMICAL WEAPONS, U.N. OFFICIAL SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The chief United Nations weapons inspector for
Iraq told the Security Council on Wednesday that laboratory tests
left no doubt that the Iraqis had loaded deadly VX nerve agent into
missile warheads, but he said he was content to go along with a
Council decision to call for further tests.
</P>
<P>
   The new analysis will be carried out at laboratories in
Switzerland and France to address Iraq's contention that the U.S.
Army laboratory that originally found traces of VX was biased.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Butler, the executive chairman of the U.N. Special
Commission, which is charged with eliminating weapons of mass
destruction in Iraq, described the original findings as ``utterly
unambiguous.'' The tests, he said, detected traces of VX and
stabilizing chemicals on warhead fragments that United Nations
inspectors retrieved at Nibai, Iraq, in March.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters later, Butler said he made clear to the
Council ``that there is no doubt that VX was present in some of the
warhead remnants.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``In the spirit of cooperation, we've said, yes,
we'll re-run some further tests in other labs and see what they
come up with.'' Butler said he expected their findings to be
consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Butler said a delegate had asked whether there could have been a
mix-up in the tests. ``The answer is no,'' he said. ``These are
unique products. They were of VX. They were found in ammunition,
namely a missile warhead. That's weaponization.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the new tests, the U.S. representative, Bill
Richardson, said, ``We have no problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler told the Council that the laboratory's findings were
``very serious,'' because while Iraq admitted producing VX, it has
denied pouring it into weapons. VX is so lethal that a few drops
can kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now these findings show that they did weaponize it,'' Butler
said. ``They put it into missile warheads.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest analysis, which was completed two weeks ago, revives
a lingering uncertainty about whether the VX stocks were destroyed,
as Baghdad reported. VX has a long shelf life and could be stored
for years, experts say.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Security Council urged that Butler press ahead with the work
schedule for disarmament that he recently proposed to Iraqi
officials. He said he would ask them how much VX agent was produced
and what happened to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to work with Iraq on this with good will and get to
the bottom of the question of how much of this substance did they
make, where did they put it, where is it now,'' Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq initially denied making VX, then said that some was
produced experimentally but later destroyed. Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz said 1.7 tons of VX were produced, but not of
weapons grade.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's efforts to shake off the oil embargo imposed after it
invaded Kuwait in 1990 have been undercut by the latest report on
VX. Aziz, who is visiting Spain, charged in a Madrid interview
Wednesday that the disclosure of the analysis was a ``political
strategem'' to poison the atmosphere before the Security Council
reviews the sanctions issue.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Iraqi officials visited the Council to
describe their progress in qualifying for the lifting of sanctions.
Wednesday, Britain's chief representative, Sir John Weston, called
the VX analysis ``a rather potent symbol'' of the gap to be bridged
before Iraq could be declared free of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the United States also protested a letter that Iraqi
Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed Sahaf sent to the Security Council
last Friday in which he disparaged a senior State Department
official, Martin Indyk, as ``a known Jew and a Zionist.'' Sahaf
complained that Indyk, who is assistant secretary of state for Near
Eastern affairs, told some journalists that Washington was planning
a new effort to build up political opposition to Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statements of the United States assistant secretary of
state, Martin Indyk, who is a known Jew and Zionist, are simply an
official and documented reaffirmation of the enmity of the United
States administration toward Iraq,'' al-Sahaf wrote. He asked that
his letter be circulated as a Security Council document.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said five other delegations expressed support for the
U.S. view that ``racist slurs in a Security Council document are
totally unacceptable.'' He called upon Sahaf to apologize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
