<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5415 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNION-RALLIES-NYT &LR;      06-24 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNION-RALLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR CAMPAIGN HIGHLIGHTS WORKERS' RIGHT TO UNIONIZE
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN.: Calif., N.C., Conn.) 
 (ja) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO kicked off a campaign Wednesday to highlight labor's
argument that the right of workers to join unions is being unfairly
undercut by fierce employer hostility and by laws that labor
leaders say do little to protect workers seeking to unionize.
</P>
<P>
   The labor federation has begun the campaign in an effort to
embarrass fervently anti-union employers and to pressure Congress
to strengthen labor laws by, for example, increasing penalties for
employers who dismiss workers for supporting unions.
</P>
<P>
   For labor leaders, the campaign is important because they hope
that it will reduce some obstacles to organizing at a time when
labor's stepped-up efforts to recruit millions of workers have
failed to catch fire.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO, with 13 million members, sponsored rallies in more
than 70 cities Wednesday to focus the public's attention on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, hundreds of union supporters demonstrated to
protest a Marriott hotel's resistance to a unionization drive. In
North Carolina, farm workers rallied to pressure Mount Olive Pickle
Co. to stop fighting unionization.
</P>
<P>
   At rally after rally, speakers talked about how companies
frequently dismissed workers who headed unionization drives and how
the courts often did not order them reinstated until years later,
often after the organizing drives had fizzled.
</P>
<P>
   Some labor leaders likened the campaign to a new civil rights
movement, asserting that the only legally guaranteed right that
Americans are afraid to exercise is the right to form a union.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Trumka, secretary-treasurer of the American Federation
of Labor-Congress of Industrial Organizations, addressed a rally
Wednesday in Norwalk, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth,'' Trumka said, ``is that in this most advanced of
industrial democracies, you can lose all your rights when you try
to join or form a union. No freedom of assembly; if you assemble
you can get fired. No freedom of speech; if you speak up, you can
get fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Trumka was in Connecticut to support workers trying to organize
at the Doubletree hotel in Norwalk and the Honey Hill Nursing Home
in Stamford. Doubletree is a subsidiary of the Promus Hotel Corp.
</P>
<P>
   He also visited New York City, where limousine drivers rallied
in their effort to unionize the Last Radio Group and restaurant
workers rallied at Angelo &AMP; Maxie's Steakhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Yager, general counsel of the Labor Policy Association, a
business-backed policy group in Washington, said the labor's
campaign was misguided, insisting that unions' recruitment woes
stemmed not from external obstacles but from themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they can't sell their message to employees,'' Yager
said, ``so they have come up with all sorts of other scapegoats for
that failure.''
</P>
<P>
   To generate broader support for their campaign, AFL-CIO leaders
also urged unions around the nation to seek support from community
groups and the clergy to help counter employer campaigns to keep
out unions.
</P>
<P>
   The labor federation cited a study by a Cornell University
researcher who found that 75 percent of private-sector employers
aggressively oppose unions, that 80 percent hire anti-union
consultants, that 32 percent dismiss workers involved in organizing
drives and that 50 percent threaten to close plants if workers
choose a union.
</P>
<P>
   Labor officials at the rallies also detailed how unionized
workers received better wages and benefits than nonunion employees.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Denise Mitchell, the AFL-CIO's communications
director, said: ``This campaign has a dual message. If we say
workers in the country are denied the right to organize, it
wouldn't be very meaningful unless we also explain what unions do
to make workers' lives better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
