<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SURROGATE-MOTHERS-GAY     06-24 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURROGATE-MOTHERS-GAYS-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL BUT GROWING NUMBER OF WOMEN HELPING GAY MEN HAVE CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Iowa, Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROKEN ARROW, Okla. _ Diane Thornton said that often, when she
looked at her 5-year-old and 3-year-old sons, she felt there was a
debt unpaid in her life, a kindness unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thornton and her former romantic partner, who are lesbians,
each conceived one of the boys with sperm from the same gay friend,
and she told him that if he ever wanted to have and raise a child
himself, ``You just say `boo.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He never did. So Ms. Thornton, 36, a social worker who lives in
this suburb of Tulsa, went in search of a surrogacy agency with gay
men among its prospective parents. Two months ago, for $15,000 plus
expenses, she gave birth to a boy, who lives with his father and
his father's partner in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This child was conceived in their hearts long before it was
conceived in my womb,'' she said. ``I gave him 35 weeks,'' she
added, referring to a pregnancy that ended in a slightly premature
delivery, ``but I didn't invest my hopes in him. His parents were
doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   As uncommon as Ms. Thornton's actions may be, they are not
singular. In a society that is still grappling with its attitudes
toward gay people having equal rights or marrying, let alone
raising children, a small but growing group of women _ most, it
seems, heterosexual _ are willing to go to extraordinary lengths to
help gay men have children genetically related to them.
</P>
<P>
   The exact number is unknown, but a few experts on surrogate
parents said at least scores of women have acted, or agreed to act,
as surrogates for gay men. Their existence reflects the explosion
in the use of surrogate parents for infertile couples and the
emboldening of gay men and lesbians, many of whom no longer see
their sexual orientation as a barrier to being parents.
</P>
<P>
   The surrogates who help them are venturing onto largely
uncharted terrain and issuing a bold challenge to traditional
models of family life.
</P>
<P>
   It is a challenge that deeply unsettles many Americans. Some
legal and medical experts say that surrogate parent arrangements
exploit vulnerable women and treat babies as commodities. And many
conservative and religious groups say that children raised by gay
and lesbian parents get a distorted picture of right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're exposing kids to an unhealthy environment,'' said Steve
Schwalm, a senior policy analyst for the Family Research Council,
an advocacy group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But that sentiment is part of what motivates the surrogates who
work with gay men, even though heterosexual couples are willing to
pay surrogates as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they had the ultimate restrictions placed on them in
trying to become parents, and I wanted to say it was ridiculous,''
said Michele Cohen, 31, in an interview in her two-room apartment i
n Santa Rosa, Calif., about 50 miles north of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cohen, who is training to become a childbirth counselor, is
three-months pregnant through artificial insemination by one of two
gay men who live together in the Northeast. Two years ago, she
delivered a baby boy for a gay man in California who did not have a
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cohen, who is heterosexual, has a 4-year-old son, whom she
is raising alone. She said the financial burden is eased by her
surrogate mother fees.
</P>
<P>
   She said she revels in being open-minded and has known gay
people well. While that description fit most of the six surrogates
interviewed for this article, one of them, Jennifer Waterman, 27, a
nurse in Red Oak, Iowa, had never met an openly gay person when she
decided, a year ago, to become a surrogate parent for one.
</P>
<P>
   Her inspiration was twofold, she said. A cousin's painful
experience with infertility had persuaded her to do something to
help people frustrated in their desire to have children, and a
community college project that involved reading ``And the Band
Played On,'' a book about the AIDS epidemic, had filled her with
compassion and admiration for gay men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just clicked,'' Ms. Waterman, a married woman with two
children of her own, said in a telephone interview. She roamed the
Internet, found a surrogate agency that worked with gay men and is
now trying, through artificial insemination, to get pregnant for a
gay couple in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   She has the blessing of her husband, Robert, 27, who served for
several years in the Navy and is studying to become a high school
teacher. ``I know how I am with my kids,'' he said, ``and I'd hate
to be in the shoes of someone who couldn't have kids.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Waterman, Ms. Thornton and Ms. Cohen are working with
Growing Generations, an agency in Beverly Hills, Calif., that
sprang up two years ago and has matched more than 15 gay couples
with surrogates.
</P>
<P>
   Other signs also indicate that surrogacy for gay men _ arranged
in rare cases for at least a decade _ is taking firmer root. Last
month, Andrew W. Vorzimer, a Beverly Hills lawyer, got a California
judge to list two gay men on the birth certificate of a girl
conceived through the artificial insemination of a surrogate. It is
believed to be a precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Vorzimer said, the names of the biological father and
mother go on the birth certificate; the mother then relinquishes
her legal rights while the father's partner applies for a
second-parent adoption.
</P>
<P>
   Although several states, including New York and New Jersey, do
not allow surrogacy agencies to operate in their borders, dozens of
agencies operate elsewhere, especially in California.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Zager, director of the Organization of Parents Through
Surrogacy, estimated that 10,000 babies have been born through
surrogates in the last two decades. She said that a miniscule
percentage of them went to gay men, with whom most agencies,
fearing added controversy, will not work.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming majority of children being raised by gays and
lesbians were conceived in earlier heterosexual relationships,
adopted, or born to lesbians through artificial insemination. And
the price of surrogacy _ from $30,000 to $70,000 for the
surrogate's fee and legal and medical expenses _ is prohibitive for
most people.
</P>
<P>
   Still, experts said an increasing number of men are like Will
Halm and Marcellin Simard, a Beverly Hills couple who used a
surrogate to have a daughter, now 2 years old, and are expecting a
son from another surrogate, Elizabeth Nila, 33, of San Diego, who
is six-months pregnant. Halm, a lawyer, is the chief executive of
Growing Generations.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nila has no genetic relation to the fetus she is carrying:
she had an embryo, created through the in-vitro fertilization of
another woman's egg, implanted in her uterus. Halm declined to say
whether he or Dr. Simard, a cardiologist, provided the sperm,
because they think of the child they are expecting as both of
theirs.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nila, who is married and was raised in a Roman Catholic
family of eight children, said she has a lesbian sister and
believes that society should be more accepting of gay men and
lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   She also said that when she was a surrogate for a heterosexual
couple, she worried that the woman envied her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not jealous,'' Ms. Nila said over lunch with Halm in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Halm responded: ``I'm glad she's going to get the stretch
marks.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nila, a homemaker, has two children and two stepchildren of
her own. Reputable agencies insist that surrogates be experienced
at motherhood, so they can better imagine what it will mean to give
up a child.
</P>
<P>
   The surrogates with Growing Generations, who seem to be women of
relatively modest educations and means, said the money they
received, $15,000 to $20,000 plus expenses, came in handy but was
not their primary motivation. They said their willingness to do
something that most women would not do made them feel special, and
that they liked being pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Their contracts typically specify what sorts of medical
treatments they are willing to undergo and whether they would abort
in cases of birth defects or multiple pregnancies. The intended
parents are almost always present at childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   But the relationships often become more involved. When Halm saw
news reports of contaminated tap water, he brought Ms. Nila two
cases of bottled water. He also consulted her about names for the
baby.
</P>
<P>
   She said that she plans to pump breast milk after the delivery,
freeze it and express mail it to him, and she has informally agreed
to carry another child for him and Dr. Simard.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thornton, the Oklahoma woman, gets regular reports about the
son, conceived through artificial insemination, that she gave up
two months ago, but said she never really thought of him as hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my children, and I can tell you every nuance of my
children,'' she said. ``My children are the most incredible in the
world. Their baby's nice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
