u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-WATER-0624-COX     06-24 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-WATER-0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INDIAN LEADERS LEARN ADMINISTRATION OPPOSES WATER PROJECT
 &HT;    BY EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ute Indian tribal leaders had planned to testify
before Congress on Wednesday in support of a scaled-down version of
the Animas-La Plata water project.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they spoke to the U.S. Senate about their shock and
sadness upon finding out a few hours before the hearing that the
Clinton administration strongly opposes the slimmed-down project,
dubbed ``A-LP Lite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The government-to-government relationship that the
administration talks so much about is a big joke,'' said Clement
Frost, chairman of the Southern Ute Tribal Council. ``They do not
stand behind their word.''
</P>
<P>
   At stake is a measure, introduced by Sen. Ben Nighthorse
Campbell, R-Colo., that would largely provide municipal and
industrial water to Ute tribes and other communities in southern
Colorado and northern New Mexico. The project has been estimated to
cost about $290 million, about one-third of the size of the
original plan.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said the scaled-down project has major
problems, including environmental impact and language that could
make the federal government pay for delivering water from a water
project near Dolores and constructing facilities to deliver water
on the Ute Mountain Ute Reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appears to be a need to allow for exploration of a
variety of alternative means to deliver water to the tribes,'' said
Eluid Martinez, commissioner of the Bureau of Reclamation, who was
grilled by angry members of the Senate Indian Affairs Committee and
the Senate Water and Power Development subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, appearing flustered, admitted he had first seen the
administration's final statement just four hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The admission caused Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, to respond:
``And you expect us to take your statement seriously?''
</P>
<P>
   Inouye asked Martinez if he had a comparable bill that the
administration would agree to.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't,'' he responded.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that they would present a report
this summer about the shrunken project but gave no details.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argued that A-LP Lite is the first step in an attempt
to construct the original $754 million project, and that taxpayers
will foot a large part of the bill. In addition, they said that the
project will be exempt from environmental laws, and that it will
dewater a trout fishery and inundate winter range for the state's
second-largest elk herd.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are alternatives to a big reservoir 500 feet up on a
mesa, evaporating, with no pipelines to anywhere,'' said Lori
Potter, a Denver attorney who represented the Sierra Club at the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents told Congress that denying the project would mean
turning its back on water rights obligations to the Ute tribes.
This would lead to legal chaos, said Gale Norton, Colorado's
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   If A-LP Lite is not enacted, ``the State of Colorado, the United
States, the Ute Tribes and southwest Colorado water users appear
destined for years of expensive and acrimonious litigation,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Knight Frank, chairperson of the Ute Mountain Ute Tribal
Council, told the committee that litigation might be the only
choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all really tired. I think we're ready to go to court and
take our chances there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
