</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADEMOISELLE-CLAIBORNE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIZ CLAIBORNE WINS CASE IN TRADEMARK INFRINGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Liz Claiborne Inc. won a trademark infringement case Wednesday
against Mademoiselle Knitwear Inc., a New York sweater factory that
is involved in a tangle of litigation with Claiborne and Unite, the
garment workers union.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Robert Sweet ruled that Mademoiselle
repeatedly violated Claiborne's trademarks in 1995 by selling
thousands of sweaters made exclusively for Claiborne through other
outlets. Mademoiselle was ordered to pay damages of $582,000, its
estimated profits on the illegal sales.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge rejected Claiborne's request for triple damages
and lawyers' fees, citing the uncertainty about the actual volume
of illegal sales. ``Moreover, the complicated business relationship
between the parties, and the poor documentation of that
relationship on both sides, distinguishes this case from more
egregious cases of intentional trademark infringement,'' the judge
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the ruling is an important victory for Claiborne, which once
boasted of dealing with Mademoiselle's showcase unionized factory.
As Claiborne sent more of its manufacturing abroad, it tried to
reduce its dealings with Mademoiselle, but was blocked by a union
arbitrator in 1996. A second arbitration case was pending when
Claiborne and Unite settled last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's ruling represents a triumph of overwhelming evidence
against Mademoiselle's baseless allegations,'' said Roberta Karp,
the general counsel for Claiborne. ``The court has rejected the
false charges Mademoiselle publicized and tried to use to defend
its illegal actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweet's decision is a serious setback for Mademoiselle, which is
operating under federal bankruptcy protection. In a separate suit,
Mademoiselle has accused Claiborne of conspiring with Unite to drop
the arbitration claims in exchange for a payment of $13 million in
``liquidated damages.'' Such damages, an important source of income
for the union, are assessed against manufacturers that fail to use
unionized factories. The payments have recently become a focus of a
congressional subcommittee that is examining current labor laws.
</P>
<P>
   John Schryber, Mademoiselle's lawyer in the trademark case, said
Sweet's decision would be appealed. He added that the ruling should
not affect Mademoiselle's case against Claiborne and the union.
</P>
<P>
   That case is one of three remaining in the long-running dispute.
In addition, workers at Mademoiselle sued Claiborne and their union
late last year over the settlement of the arbitration claims. And
the National Labor Relations Board is scheduled to hold hearings in
the fall on various complaints of unfair labor practices that the
union has filed against Mademoiselle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0439 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5421 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATT-TCI-ANALYSIS-COX     06-24 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-TCI-ANALYSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A direct line into the home
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- AT&AMP;T's blockbuster bid to buy the nation's largest
cable company may be a huge gamble, but it is a loud confirmation
of the fact every communications company is now either hunter or
game.
</P>
<P>
   The deal to buy Tele-Communications Inc. in a stock swap worth
about $48 billion will give AT&AMP;T a direct link to consumer homes,
even as it pushes rivals to find their own partners and accelerate
their own competing connections. The long-distance giant, which has
floundered in several efforts at entering the $110 billion market
for local service, finally has a strategy that detours around the
lines controlled by the regional phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the move we have been waiting for,'' said analyst
Brian Adamik of the Yankee Group. ``There are only two lines to the
home, and AT&AMP;T is aligning itself with that other wire.''
</P>
<P>
   More than two years after passage of the Telecommunications Act,
most consumers have no choice in local service and no new choices
in long-distance. The law, touted as a way for industries to invade
each other's territories, has instead spurred only a spate of
mergers that did not cross industry lines _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike San Antonio-based SBC Communications, which has purchased
three other local phone companies, AT&AMP;T cannot simply add lines to
grow. While it has more than 70 million consumer customers, AT&AMP;T
does not own any lines into their homes. To compete in local
service, AT&AMP;T has been forced to choose between reselling service _
which is not profitable _ and constructing its own network _ which
is stunningly expensive. AT&AMP;T recently spent $11 billion to buy
Teleport Communications Group to beef up its ability to sell
services to businesses. But owning a cable company gives AT&AMP;T a
path to consumers. TCI has systems reaching 11 million homes and
owns parts of companies that reach 10 million more. In Georgia, TCI
serves 23 communities, including Columbus and Albany.
</P>
<P>
   When complete, a high-speed cable connection can offer a
lightning-quick link to the Internet, along with television and
phone service. Using its huge customer base and world-renowned
brand name, AT&AMP;T should be able to market the new service to
millions.
</P>
<P>
   But that path is studded with both cost and risk.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the awesome expense of the purchase, success depends on
a multibillion-dollar upgrade of TCI's lines to permit phone calls
and high-speed data transmission. Between 10 percent and 15 percent
of the nation's cable lines have been upgraded to handle
interactive traffic, high-speed data and phone conversations, and
analysts believe TCI is below average in making that transition. A
similar effort in metro Atlanta by MediaOne, projected to cost $350
million, has already taken several years and is only about 20
percent complete.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Bell Atlantic agreed to a merger with TCI intended to
do much of what AT&AMP;T now plans. That deal collapsed under the
weight of corporate egos, financial haggling and industry doubt.
But that was then. Now, the technology for improving networks is
greatly improved. More importantly, the Internet is a vibrant
reality with the promise of still more lucrative growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling is that it won't be as expensive as it would have
been before, that the payoff is better than it would have been and
AT&AMP;T has lots of bucks,'' said Dwight Allen, director of global
telecommunications for Deloitte Research.
</P>
<P>
   For months, AT&AMP;T has been seen as the helpless giant, watching
events swirl past.
</P>
<P>
   The company's share of long-distance, once dominant, has faded
to about half. Meanwhile, it has been outflanked by WorldCom, which
after finishing the purchase of MCI and MFS, will be a major player
in long-distance, Internet and local service to business. SBC
Communications has purchased two other Bells, while Bell Atlantic
bought Nynex.
</P>
<P>
   On the cable front, cable companies have been building
high-speed lines that will give customers quick access to the
Internet along with phone service. Bells have been planning to
offer DSL, a high-speed service over phone lines, while Internet
companies tinker with techniques for carrying voice.
</P>
<P>
   And while AT&AMP;T's purchase of TCI is bold, AT&AMP;T has stumbled
before making grand gestures. For example, the disastrous purchase
of NCR, later reversed, which looked so promising on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the payoff from TCI is years away. By the time those
upgrades are made, other technologies _ such as wireless _ could
eclipse cable. Still, AT&AMP;T could not afford to wait, Allen said.
``You just don't know what's going to come crashing onto the scene,
but you've got to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bells need to do something, too. They already face
competition for their more lucrative business customers. The
prospect of mighty AT&AMP;T stomping into residential neighborhoods
offering a full range of telecommunications services is not taken
lightly. But first the Bells hope the TCI deal can be good news,
providing a reason for federal regulators to permit them into
long-distance.
</P>
<P>
   U S West, the smallest of the remaining Bells, released a
statement Wednesday arguing just that. ``All of us should be
allowed to compete, now that the biggest kid on the block just got
bigger. A combined AT&AMP;T and TCI would have a market value of about
$125 billion. WorldCom and MCI together would be valued at about
$82 billion. The thought that these big companies continue to need
protection from U S West is ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, at $22 billion a year in revenue, has during the
recent industry consolidation gone from the largest Bell to the
second-smallest. So the Atlanta-based company also hopes to have
long-distance as an offering when AT&AMP;T enters consumer markets. But
the thought of competing with a cable-owning behemoth could
accelerate BellSouth's efforts to roll out its own high-speed
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Any major player in telecommunications must soon provide a
high-speed digital mix of voice, data and video, said BellSouth
Executive Officer C. Sidney Boren. ``This will stimulate our
efforts, no doubt. It stimulates everybody's research and
development into how to get broadband closer to the home.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth plans to start offering DSL in metro Atlanta starting
Aug. 31. While DSL is not quite as fast as a cable modem and cannot
be used too far from a central office switch, phone companies
should be capable of getting it to market much faster than cable
companies can install upgraded lines.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sadler, analyst at Robinson Humphrey, said BellSouth should
feel pressure to push DSL into the market. ``No more trials. No
more messing around. They have got to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's announcement evokes the specter of trouble on BellSouth's
home turf, he said. ``This is a flashing green light with a klaxon.
The potential is to hit BellSouth not only in local residential
service but also in business-to-business. This is a cold slap in
the face.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's huge purchase would be added to its long-distance
network, Teleport's local network for business and AT&AMP;T's business
in wireless phones _ the largest in the nation. But the deal is
almost certainly not the last of the industry mergers _ perhaps not
even for AT&AMP;T. It has a national presence in long-distance, and
would presumably want the same for its local business.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
