<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5422 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATT-TCI-CABLE-COX     06-24 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-TCI-CABLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deal viewed as milestone; stocks climb
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- AT&AMP;T's purchase of Tele-Communications Inc. is the
biggest in a series of big endorsements of the cable TV pipeline as
the new standard in communications.
</P>
<P>
   In the past several years, Microsoft, Bell Canada and U S West
have all invested in cable TV with varying degrees of success. But
AT&AMP;T's $48 billion deal raises that investment to a new level,
driving the industry's soaring stock prices even higher Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the Microsoft investment in Comcast last year, this
transaction is a strong endorsement of the cable's broadband
plant,'' said Jim Robbins, president of Atlanta-based cable TV
operator Cox Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is fairly significant for other cable players, but
you have to remember that the industry has already experienced
consolidation,'' said Andy Grossman, deputy editor of influential
industry trade weekly Multichannel News. ``This is part of a
trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Will it continue? ``It's hard to tell whether AT&AMP;T will create a
rush by outsiders to buy other cable operators,'' said Bruce
Leitchman, a media analyst at Boston-based consultant Yankee Group.
``MCI and Sprint, for example, have shown no interest so far in the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides soaring stock prices, though, industry observers doubted
the merger would have much impact on other cable TV companies. The
top operators such as Cox Communications and MediaOne have already
embarked on billion-dollar programs to rebuild their systems to
handle two-way traffic such as high-speed access to the Internet
and telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal doesn't change the video angle of the business one
iota,'' said Leitchman.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, though, could greatly change TCI. With 10 million
subscribers, the Denver-based operator is the industry's
second-largest. Most of its systems, which include Chicago, Denver,
Seattle and San Francisco, are west of the Mississippi. It does
have some 100,000 subscribers spread out over 23 systems in South
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   TCI ranks low within the industry in terms of both customer
service and facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has very, very few systems that are two-way digital,'' said
Leitchman. ``The company faces one heck of a challenge to finish
rebuilding all its systems as two-way by the year 2000 as promised
by Malone (TCI Chairman John C. Malone).''
</P>
<P>
   That upgrade is critical if AT&AMP;T is going to successfully use
TCI's systems to deliver local telephone service and high-speed
Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Also critical is TCI's ability to improve customer service. If
unhappy with their cable TV, subscribers are unlikely to buy other
services from TCI such as local telephone and cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   Since hiring Leo Hindry Jr. as its second-in-command two years
ago, TCI has worked to improve service and its systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company has been pretty successful where it has upgraded
service,'' said Grossman. ``But they still have problems in pockets
where the company has not upgraded.''
</P>
<P>
   The purchase is expected to bolster TCI's upgrade. ``Its cash
flow should greatly help TCI deliver on its promise of
next-generation services,'' said Grossman.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers wonder, though, whether Malone was really
interested in building a better TCI. There have been rumors for the
past six months that he was rebuilding to get ready for a sale.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Malone is renown for his financial acumen. He cobbled
together small cable TV systems into what once was the country's
largest operator. And he's continually restructuring TCI, spinning
off and then re-buying parts of his company.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's portfolio includes more than cable systems. He controls
stakes in a variety of programmers, including Time Warner. He
holds, through TCI, a nonvoting 9.2 percent stake in the New
York-based media conglomerate, which in turn owns Atlanta-based
Turner Broadcasting Systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malone has done a masterful job of inspiring confidence with
Wall Street,'' said Leitchman. ``In a sense, this is just his
biggest deal yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
