<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5423 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENDICOTT-COX     06-24 1627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENDICOTT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How do we heal the strife in Asia?
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Given President Clinton's trip this week to China and
the recent testing of nuclear weapons by India and Pakistan, it
seemed a good time to discuss Asian security issues with John
Endicott.
</P>
<P>
   Endicott is an expert on Asian security matters, an author and
the director of the Center for International Strategy, Technology
and Policy, a think tank at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   But if that makes his career sound a tad dry, guess again.
Endicott worked in 1958 as a U.S. Air Force intelligence officer in
Japan, where he interrogated Japanese prisoners of war still
straggling out of Siberian prisons. In 1962, during the Cuban
Missile Crisis, he was in the Strategic Air Command's underground
headquarters in Nebraska when it was sealed for the first and only
time.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'60s, the Air Force sent him to Vietnam, where he
became intelligence adviser to Prime Minister Nguyen Cao Ky.
</P>
<P>
   After another stint in Japan, Endicott worked in strategic
planning in Washington, D.C. _ going through the Cold War as, he
says, ``a strategic nuclear weaponeer.''
</P>
<P>
   He retired from the Air Force in 1986 and became director of the
Institute for National Strategic Studies, which gave policy advice
to the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and the secretary of
defense. He came to Georgia Tech in 1990 to create the School of
International Affairs and the policy study group.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts from a conversation with him this week:
</P>
<P>
   Q:The prime ministers of Pakistan and India have said they're
going to talk face-to-face next month. What can we realistically
expect out of that?
</P>
<P>
   A:Not too much, I don't think. But I would like to see them
really start to get serious about maybe a fissile manufacturing
cut-off proposal. They've already got enough stuff to probably make
60 weapons as far as the Indians are concerned, and maybe 25 or 30
as far as the (Pakistanis) are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately the real problem is the Indians and the
Pakistanis really don't know enough about what each country is
doing. (America) could do two things, I think that would really
make a difference. One is to offer immediately, to the Indians and
the Pakistanis, the latest PAL technology to both states. P-A-L,
permissive action link technology. This is the technology that
complicates unauthorized use of nuclear weapons. Prohibits it,
basically.
</P>
<P>
   But secondly, we're not really sure and they're not really sure
of each other's actions. They almost went to war in '96 by rumor
alone. So there's a lot of satellite intelligence that we could
make available to them and tell the Indians and tell the
(Pakistanis) that we're going to make this information available to
both sides in an honest broker kind of maneuver so that there can't
be any sneak attack.
</P>
<P>
   Q:The U.S. wants Pakistan and India to sign on to nuclear
proliferation and test ban treaties, but not as nuclear states.
Isn't that asking them to put the genie back in the bottle?
</P>
<P>
   A:Exactly.
</P>
<P>
   This brings another issue up that's really bothersome. And it's
the way we, in our current international system, welcome latecomers
on the international system. We went to war with Germany in World
War I because we couldn't adapt to what they were trying to do,
that happened to be about 30 or 40 years behind what the Brits and
the rest of the world had done _ the French, etc. We went to World
War II because the Japanese were trying to do the same thing as far
as colonies, etc., that was the norm 40 years prior.
</P>
<P>
   Well, now we get to the same kind of situation, only the norm
now is non-proliferation. And the international system really
demands that these two countries forgo the right to nuclear weapons
when they ascertain by their own processes that their national
security is in danger. Well, if we had those same kind of
circumstances, you know the kind of answer that we would find.
</P>
<P>
   Q:With regard to India and Pakistan, what can China do to help?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, China has already stated that it was very disappointed
in the Pakistan explosions. And it is generally, I think,
acknowledged that there was up until several years ago quite a bit
of Chinese assistance to the (Pakistanis) in the development of the
nuclear capability and missiles. This has supposedly stopped now,
so certainly China can play a role in this situation of a good
adviser toward Pakistan, but they don't have very much credibility
with the Indians, and that's a real major problem. And of course
the Indians see China as their number one threat.
</P>
<P>
   So, in this case, the United States cannot back away from this
kind of responsibility for being a senior counsel in this
relationship. Russia also has a real opportunity here to play a
major role as a responsible international power. The Russians do
have a much better relationship with India, of course, than we do.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What's the best that you think, in terms of U.S.-China
security, that Clinton can achieve there?
</P>
<P>
   A:Well, if we do get a de-targeting situation, that would be
very good. De-alerting would also be very good. De-alerting would
be the separation of warheads from the missiles themselves, so it's
very, very difficult to marry them again without showing your hand.
</P>
<P>
   Q:How committed should the United States be to the protection of
Taiwan, and what do you think the U.S. response ought to be if
Taiwan were to declare its independence?
</P>
<P>
   A:I agree with the U.S. current policy that recognizes that
there is one China, and that China and Taiwan are both claimants to
that real title. We (should) tolerate any outcome as long as it's
an outcome that is viable between both parties. We will be very
unhappy, in fact under the Taiwan act we should use force, if the
PRC (People's Republic of China) intervenes with force in an
outright aggressive way.
</P>
<P>
   But I think if Taiwan declares its own independence, then it
takes its chances and it takes its consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In your assessment, how dangerous is North Korea to security
in East Asia?
</P>
<P>
   A:Extremely dangerous. It's sort of the danger represented by a
person who is starving, desperate and willing to hold on to an
ideology that they have spent their lives saying was the right way.
Knowing how the Russians feel about the collapse of Communism and
Marxism, etc., and what sort of real problems that's caused, it's
by a factor of 10 as far as the North Koreans are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   So it's a very dangerous situation, and it's a danger from
weakness, not a danger from strength. Often we talk about the
forward-deployed North Korean forces _ and of their million-man
military, about 60 percent are forward-deployed, therefore in
positions that could be very critical and very dangerous to a South
Korean defense.
</P>
<P>
   This is really a deployment, though, not of strength and threat;
it's a deployment of weakness, I believe. Because the North
Koreans, I don't think, have the petroleum, the communications, the
training to carry off a forward deployment after the fact, when the
situation becomes tense. I don't think they're ready to execute a
forward deployment because they don't have enough money to exercise
their forces now in large groups, their communication technology is
antiquated, and certainly where they're sitting gives them a chance
to maximize politically the threat and not look so weak.
</P>
<P>
   So it's a very dangerous situation in the sense that if Kim
Jong-il and his group get into factional fighting and a coup is
attempted, and then in order to put down the coup they launch _ you
know, you can write all sorts of scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   I think, having said that, we're now in a period where common
strife, both South Korean and North Korean, and a new political
leadership in the South, brings the whole peninsula closer to a
rational settlement than we've seen in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Both Kim Dae-jung and a task force headed by former Ambassador
James Laney haverecommended that sanctions against North Korea be
lifted. What's your view?
</P>
<P>
   A:Definitely, they should be lifted. I think what we need to do
is everything that we can to reduce those items that make the North
Koreans feel we're threatening and constraining and conspiring
against them. And it doesn't take many kinds of good works to
reduce their fear. It's fear that drove them toward nuclear
weapons, and they were surprised, I think, at the international
willingness to really work this problem out and come up with the
1994 agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What kind of role should Japan be encouraged to play in Asian
security matters in the future?
</P>
<P>
   A: Japan has got security _ writ large _ responsibilities, in
this case economic security as well as military security.
Everybody's on them: ``Do something outstanding, forward-looking as
far as getting the Japanese economy out of neutral.'' It's almost
in reverse. And the problem, of course, is that Japan is also going
through a restructuring of its economic system. (And) the western
European Union is forming a monolith that's going to be a very,
very difficult thing to compete with.
</P>
<P>
   Having said this, there's also an area where Japan should be
actively a leader in the region. And this is in the
non-proliferation area. Japan, of all the countries in Asia _ of
all the countries in the world _ has the charter, basically, to
lead against proliferation of nuclear weapons. Japan could become a
leader in non-proliferation, could become a leader in an area where
it doesn't threaten anyone. And this is an action where China would
be reassured, North and South Korea would be reassured, even the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
