<HEADER>
A5424 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATT-TCI-IMPACT-COX     06-24 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-TCI-IMPACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deal makes phone giant major force in broadband
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- AT&AMP;T's acquisition of Tele-Communications Inc. and
its broadband service (at)Home may have forced the Internet
industry to take a long, hard look at broadband development.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, how far and how fast broadband can reach into U.S.
homes and abroad will impact the future development of America
Online, the world's largest proprietary online service.
</P>
<P>
   After numerous false starts, AT&AMP;T's acquisition of
Tele-Communications finally gives AT&AMP;T the power to emerge as a
serious Internet player.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the TCI acquisition, AT&AMP;T's failed forays into
electronic commerce and online services such as AT&AMP;T Interchange
left analysts shaking their heads, wondering why AT&AMP;T couldn't
leverage its telecommunications prowess into a successful Internet
venture.
</P>
<P>
   Now, AT&AMP;T seems to have looked into the future and saw what
analysts like to call the ``big pipes'' of broadband. Broadband is
delivered to subscribers through a set-top box and offers its users
Net access up to 100 times faster than the standard dial-up modem
connections.
</P>
<P>
   Along with local phone service possibilities, the merger with
TCI enables AT&AMP;T to take a leap of faith into the world of
broadband communications. In addition to some 10 million cable
subscribers, AT&AMP;T also would acquire a controlling interest in the
(at)Home Network (http://www.home.net/home/), a leading provider of
high-speed Internet access and content services. The service
currently has roughly 110,000 subscribers who pay between $30 and
$50 for the service.
</P>
<P>
   TCI has controlling stake in the venture, whose other primary
partners are Comcast and Cox Communications, a public company
controlled by Cox Enterprises. Wednesday, (at)Home shares closed at
$51.12 1/2 up $11.87 1/2, a 30 percent increase. The company also
reached its all-time high of $54 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of just following Internet trends, AT&AMP;T has a
chance to lead the way into broadband Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Its closest competitor is Time Warner and MediaOne's Road
Runner. That company plans to build out its service with a $425
million investment from Microsoft and Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   TCI's deals with other cable systems already give (at)Home
access to 67 million homes, but there is still a long way to go
before the world embraces broadband. Of those 67 million homes,
(at)Home is only available in 6 million, and of those 6 million,
only 100,000 are (at)Home subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   However, AT&AMP;T also gains (at)Home's expertise at developing
content for the high-speed broadband connections. High-speed access
allows content developers to employ streaming audio, video and
Shockwave enhancements that aren't feasible on dial-up connections
because of long download times and limited dial-up bandwidth. With
cable modems, there are no such limitations.
</P>
<P>
   But this sudden flurry of interest in cable modems and broadband
technology leaves America Online at a technological crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   For now, AOL says it wants to remain independent but form
``alliances'' with other companies. But the decision facing AOL in
the long term is whether to bet on cable and broadband, or the
phone companies and their high-speed DSL technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``America Online has to stop and develop its broadband
strategy,'' says Robert Seidman, editor and publisher of Online
Insider (http://www.onlineinsider.com).
</P>
<P>
   According to Seidman, America Online isn't ready to compete in
the broadband arena or partner with a major cable operator. ``They
are boxed out of cable access right now,'' he says, adding that
(at)Home already has spent several years developing content for the
high-speed arena, putting it at an advantage over AOL in the short
term.
</P>
<P>
   Even though AT&AMP;T may have forced the broadband issue, Seidman
says AOL can take its time developing the next generation of its
service. ``Next year and the year after that and the year after
that, dial up at 28.8k bps or 56K bps is still going to be the
dominant method of access,'' he says. ``That gives Steve Case some
breathing room.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
