<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5425 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-POOLS-COX     06-24 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-POOLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parents questioned the safety of public pools
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Armed with a season pass, Joan Yesner has taken her
three children to White Water park almost every day this month.
</P>
<P>
   But after trying to reach officials at the Cobb County water
park and talking to public health workers Wednesday, Yesner said
she can't go back _ not until she knows more details about how
public pools are cleaned and inspected in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just devastated by the whole thing,'' said Yesner, a
Marietta resident who filed a complaint about White Water with the
Cobb County health department Wednesday. ``But what really bothers
me is the seeming lack of information about how pools are to be
monitored.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most public pool facilities _ including White Water _
have been deemed safe by public health workers, there are no
statewide regulations regarding swimming pool maintenance or water
quality.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Georgia Department of Human Resources allows
individual counties to develop their own codes of conduct, although
most are based on a set of guidelines that were issued almost three
decades ago by the state's Environmental Health Division.
</P>
<P>
   Those guidelines, 20 pages worth, outline standards for
everything from filtration systems to cleanliness of bathhouse
buildings. But they do not spell out how facilities should respond
to specific incidents, such as the case of a child defecating in a
pool, which is believed to be the cause of an E coli outbreak at
White Water park.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 25 counties _ including most metro Atlanta counties _
have enacted some portion of those recommendations into ordinances,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But how diligently the counties follow or enforce their codes
varies. That factor, along with the need to make sure Olympic
swimming venues were safe for the 1996 Games, prompted Georgia to
start developing a new set of uniform statewide regulations. But
those laws are not slated for release until this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started looking at writing rules and regulations about
three years ago,'' said Ken Dickson, assistant director of
environmental health with the state division of public health.
``There was no single incident that sparked this, but we wanted to
avert any potential problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Public health officials say the White Water outbreak is
extremely unusual. E. coli is most often passed through food
contaminated with fecal bacteria. The White Water case is only the
second known incident where a chlorinated pool was the route of
transmission for E. coli. The first also occurred in Georgia, in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, chlorine is highly effective in keeping pools safe _
even from the unpredictable potty habits of children. Chemically
speaking, chlorine _ often used in cleaning supplies_ is a strong
oxidant that releases free radicals that attack and destroy
bacteria by invading the cell walls and internal structure,
according to Laren Tolbert, chairman of Georgia Institute of
Technology's school of chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   But he said when chlorine is used to protect people from
bacteria in pools, ``the hard part is controlling the level of
chlorine so it's sufficient to kill the bacteria without being
uncomfortable for the swimmers.''
</P>
<P>
   And if there has been a case of someone defecating in the pool,
chlorine has to have a time to work, he said. ``It doesn't work
instantly,'' Tolbert said. That's why it's recommended that pool
owners place a higher dose of chlorine in a pool at night _ ``to
give it time to kill everything that shouldn't be there.''
</P>
<P>
   John Gormley, who oversees the safety and water quality of 1,200
community pools in subdivisions and public facilities in Fulton
County, said he believes the best policy when someone has had an
accident is to close the pool, remove the bulk of the matter, and
``shock'' the pool _ or over-chlorinate the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, a pool should have a chlorine level of at least 1.5
parts per million, with between 2 and 5 parts per million being
optimal, said Gormley, manager of Fulton County Health and Wellness
Department's environmental health service division. But when owners
shock a pool, the level should rise to at least 12 parts per
million.
</P>
<P>
   Then, pool owners should wait 24 hours until the chlorine
returns to a normal level, said Gormley.
</P>
<P>
   However, owners don't want to have a pool with too much chlorine
either. Tolbert points out that it's such a powerful agent it was
used as a poison gas against soldiers during World War I.
</P>
<P>
   And even when chlorine hits 8 to 10 parts per million , it's
enough to bleach bathing suits, tint dyed hair green, irritate eyes
and even cause respiratory problems for asthmatics.
</P>
<P>
   The key to having a safe pool has more to do with consistent
maintenance that just taking care of a crisis, experts say. Gormley
and others who run pool stores say routinely testing the water is
the only way to make sure bacteria can't ruin a summer pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   Going by a strong chlorine smell, for example, is one of the
worst ways to determine whether there's enough chlorine. In fact,
when a pool smells heavily like chlorine, it might mean its level
is too low _ because it indicates that the chlorine has bonded with
the bacteria and has formed a new chemical compound which puts off
a stronger smell.
</P>
<P>
   Test kits typically cost between $6 and $26, said Cheryl Lanuza,
office manager of Atlas Pools and Spas on Peachtree Industrial
Boulevard. ``You need to make sure your pool is in balance, and you
need to shock your pool every seven to 10 days, depending on the
number of swimmers you have.''
</P>
<P>
   Filters are also important, public health workers and pool
salespeople say. And if there's been an accident, owners need to
make sure they scrub the filter traps and skimmers that might have
trapped fecal matter.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley said homeowners in subdivisionshave the right to set
their own standards for community pools. In some cases, it might be
helpful to bar children under 3 years old _ or until they are
potty-trained. If parents don't want to block a child's access to a
pool, the subdivision should require that the babies wear diapers
that are rubberized or tight enough to contain any accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do have some control over this issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So, in light of the White Water outbreak, would it be better to
return to nature?
</P>
<P>
   No, say public health experts.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ocean does offer some protection against bacteria
because it has such a high concentration of salt, and natural
scrubbers, it is not clean. Neither are lakes and rivers, which
often contain bacteria from septic tanks and run-off from sewers
and pasture lands.
</P>
<P>
   For Yesner, the lawn sprinkler is going to see more action in
the days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I get some answers, we can't go back,'' said Yesner,
mother of a 9-year-old, a 7-year-old and a 20-month-old. ``I'm not
going to take the risk.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
