<HEADER>
A5426 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OZONE-COX     06-24 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Metro's smog is worse than you thought
 &HT;    By David Goldberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- As metro Atlanta faces its third consecutive ozone
pollution alert today, some commuters are bemoaning the frequency
of these requests to leave their cars at home in the name of
cleaner air.
</P>
<P>
   But Rhonda Hill knows it's worse than they think, because the
air is even more unhealthy than they've been told. Long before
ozone smog hits the level at which the state Enviornmental
Protection Division triggers an ozone warning, kids like Hill's son
Kellan Bolden, a severe asthmatic, need to leave the yard or the
pool and head indoors. Failure to do so risks a life-threatening
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very scary,'' Hill said. ``I can't let him play outside
when ozone is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult for parents like Hill to get adequate warning,
however. The EPD issues pollution forecasts geared toward meeting
an ozone standard now declared out-of-date by the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after controversy-ridden debate, the EPA set a new
health standard acknowledging that for children like Kellan, and
even for healthy people who are active outdoors, prolonged exposure
at lower levels is more dangerous than brief spikes.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is stark: Under the new standard, based on levels
averaged over eight hours rather than one hour, metro Atlanta in
May alone had twice as many ``bad air'' days than the five EPD
reported. Using the new standard, EPD officials say the region will
likely register three or more times the current average of 11
violation days.
</P>
<P>
   But the EPD is not yet required to use the new standard in
issuing its alerts. Consequently, if forecasters call an alert
based on the older standard, the EPD's Web site says confidently,
if not altogether accurately, ``ozone conditions are not
unhealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   State air experts issued warnings for Tuesday, Wednesday and
today. While neither Tuesday nor Wednesday exceeded the older
standard, both days saw ozone levels above the new one, according
to information on the EPD web site.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot is that metro Atlanta's air pollution problem is more
intractable, and possibly more dangerous to health, than the EPD is
acknowledging with its current program. The EPD hopes to make a
serious dent in the pollution problem by asking resi-dents to leave
cars at home, put off mowing and take othermeasures on ozone alert
days.
</P>
<P>
   Under the updated standard, however, almost every other day
could be an alert day. Skeptics have suggested that indicates a
need to switch habits for the entire May-September ozone season,
rather than only on ``action days.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the sheer number of likely alert days is one reason the
EPD decided not to issue warnings based on the new health standard,
said Ron Methier, EPD's chief of air protection.
</P>
<P>
   EPD was worried that it's so-called Voluntary Ozone Action
Program would be doomed from the start if action days came too
fast, Methier said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of 10 or 20 action alerts a summer we may be issuing
40 or 50 under the 8-hour standard,'' Methier said. ``We wanted to
ease into this and get people to understand there's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Methier also noted that federal regulators are allowing problem
cities like Atlanta to wait until after they have met the existing
standard to start working toward the new one. The EPD doesn't plan
to meet the old standard until close to 2005.
</P>
<P>
   That's not acceptable to Dr. Leroy Graham, the
cardiopulmonologist who treats Kellan Bolden.
</P>
<P>
   ``To wait is foolish and dangerous,'' Graham said. ``We
shouldn't get caught up in thinking that compliance with
regulations is all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents are getting an unrealistic picture of the
healthfulness of Atlanta's air and what it will take to fix it, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kellan's mom, too, hopes they get the picture sooner, rather
than later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts to hear him ask, `Why can't I play football and
baseball? Why do I have to take all this medication?'' she said.
``It's not just the air pollution, but that's a lot of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
