<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT JUSTICES TO MEET EUROPEAN COUNTERPARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Texas, Conn.)  (nk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four Supreme Court justices will lead a delegation
in meetings next month with judges in four European countries, the
court announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The four justices, Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony Kennedy, Ruth
Bader Ginsburg and Stephen Breyer, will present papers and exchange
views on court procedures and topics such as religious freedom,
federalism, discrimination in the work place, human rights and the
rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation includes two other judges, Richard Arnold of the
8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Little Rock, Ark., and Texas
Supreme Court Chief Justice Thomas Phillips. The group will also
include Thomas Susman, a Washington lawyer representing the
American Bar Association, and two law professors, Paul Verkuil,
dean of the Benjamin Cardozo Law School in New York, and Paul
Gewirtz of Yale Law School.
</P>
<P>
   The four justices have all spent part of past summers teaching
in Europe or meeting with European judges, and they have expressed
interest in various ways in drawing on other countries' legal
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the justices' individual interests, a joint project on
this scale is unusual for the court. The trip, July 5 to 15, will
include visits to the European Court of Justice in Luxembourg; the
European Commission in Brussels; the German constitutional court in
Karlsruhe; the European Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg,
France; and three French appellate courts in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The trip is being underwritten by the State Department, the U.S.
Information Agency and a private foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
