<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5439 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-ANIMAS-NAT     06-24 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-ANIMAS-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  CLINTON ADMINISTRATION OPPOSES ANIMAS LA PLATA -- TRIBAL
LEADERS SAY SEE YOU IN COURT
</P>
<P>
   By Elliot Zaret
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 24 -- In a move that Ute tribal leaders say may
force them to sue the federal government for their water rights,
the Clinton administration Wednesday announced strong opposition to
the Animas-La Plata water settlement and called for the bill to be
re-written.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, as chairman of the Southern Ute Tribe, will climb upon my
war pony and spread to all the Indian nations across the country
that the administration has broken its promise,'' said Clement
Frost, chairman of the Southern Ute Tribal Council, one of the two
tribes involved in the water settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., said that until
Wednesday, the administration had been supportive of the bill,
which would have resolved water rights issues remaining from an
1868 treaty with the Ute tribes. The plan to divert the Animas and
La Plata Rivers in southwestern Colorado and northern New Mexico to
bring water to the tribes has been the subject of numerous bills
over the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our last time to sit down and negotiate -- we've gone
as far as we can go,'' Frost said. ``We'll go to court if we need
to. We don't have anything else to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who blasted the administration for ``backstabbing''
and ``pulling the rug out from under the tribes'' said the
administration's opposition effectively kills the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've encouraged the tribes that maybe they should go back to
court and sue,'' said Campbell, who had co-authored the bill with
Sen. Wayne Allard, R-Colo. ``It's going to be long, litigious and
expensive for the taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's bill, the Colorado Ute Settlement Act Amendments of
1998, would build a reservoir and pumping plant on the Animas River
near Durango, along with other features for municipal and
industrial water supplies, to serve Ute tribes and other
communities in southern Colorado and northern New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The scaled-down version of Animas-La Plata -- known as ``Animas
La Plata Lite'' -- would cost approximately $300 million, far less
than the original $754 million project which Congress passed in
1988. But environmental groups have attacked the plan as just the
first step in an attempt to reinstate the original, larger plan.
</P>
<P>
   Eluid Martinez, commissioner of the Department of the Interior's
Bureau of Reclamation, told a Senate panel that ``the modified
Animas-La Plata project raises renewed concerns over the same
unanswered, critical environmental, fiscal, financial, economic and
legal issues that have kept the project from coming to fruition for
a decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Richardon, director of policy for the Bureau of
Reclamation, said the administration had three concerns: that the
current plan lacks a mechanism to actually deliver water to the
tribes, that the bill waives environmental laws, and that the bill
waives an law that would require the tribes to pay for the parts of
the plan that don't affect their land.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who refused to say whether Clinton would veto the
bill if it were passed by Congress, said the administration plans
to release an alternative package sometime this summer.
</P>
<P>
   And though the administration ``strongly opposes'' the bill,
Martinez said, ``it is committed to continue a dialogue with the
Tribes and others in pursuit of the best means to obtain a just and
final settlement for the Tribes.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Knight-Frank, Chairperson of the Ute Mountain Ute Tribal
Council, said the opportunity for that dialogue has come and gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have spent many hours and many nights and many years trying
to work with them, and they say they want a dialogue,'' said
Knight-Frank. ``If they want to talk to us they've had every
opportunity and the opportunities have been there for over 100
years to fulfill their trust obligation -- and they have not done
that. I think that it's too late. I know that it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit by the Ute tribes would put into question many issues
of water rights in southwest Colorado, said Colorado Attorney
General Gale Norton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such litigation would involve virtually all water users in the
Animas and La Plata basins, take many years of trial and appeals,
cost millions of federal, state, and local taxpayer dollars, and
undo decades of cooperation between Indians and non-Indians in
southwest Colorado,'' Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   To the tribes, however, the issue runs deeper than the money --
or the rivers, Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we are treated like strangers in our own nation, we are
treated like aliens,'' said Frost. ``It's saddening that many
things (the administration says) are not true. They do not keep
their word.''
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
