<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5441 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-ART-2TAK     06-24 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S.-CHINESE TENSIONS LINGER ON EVE OF SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: CHINA-GOALS, CHINA-ZHAO, CHINA-LAW,
CHINA-PEONY, CHINA-PEONY-FRANCE, CHINA-RELICS-FEUD) 
(ART ADV: Graphic map on Clinton's itinerary and graphic on history
of U.S.-Chinese relations are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIAN, China _ President Clinton's aerial caravan arrives here
Thursday for a visit eagerly sought by his Chinese hosts as
long-overdue recognition of China's status as a major global power.
But Clinton leaves behind an America deeply uneasy about the
conduct and intentions of a rising China.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to the summit talks, the friction in the
relationship has been evident in the two countries' failure to
reach agreement on a number of agenda items the United States
considers important, including human rights, trade, military
cooperation, and a largely symbolic gesture to announce that
neither country would aim its nuclear missiles at the other.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of these problems, the White House has been trying to make
the case that the success of the visit ought to be measured not in
the number of agreements reached or documents signed _ they will be
relatively few and modest _ but in whether Clinton and President
Jiang Zemin can subtly redefine the relationship between the two
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's nine-day voyage to China is the longest presidential
visit to a single country since Harry Truman attended the Potsdam
peace conference in Germany after the end of World War II in
Europe. It is the first to China since President George Bush was
here in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The president intends to devote the majority of his schedule and
his public appearances to addressing China's people, not its
leaders. He will visit a small village that has conducted its first
open election, attend services at an officially registered
Protestant church in Beijing, speak to students at Beijing
University, and engage in a roundtable discussion with young
entrepreneurs in Shanghai. The official part of his schedule is
essentially limited to a half-day of meetings with Jiang and two
elaborate dinners.
</P>
<P>
   The hope, Clinton and his advisers say, is to show the American
people a dynamic and diverse China that could become the U.S.
economy's biggest customer and an important ally in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   The message is simple: China is too big to be ignored and the
U.S.-China relationship too important to fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``That relationship,'' Clinton said in an address 10 days ago
outlining the goals for his trip, ``will in large measure help to
determine whether the new century is one of security, peace and
prosperity for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's schedule is also an answer to critics in
Congress and elsewhere, who object to the warming of relations with
a government that still jails dissidents, threatens Taiwan,
oppresses Tibet, forces abortions and imposes stiff tariffs on U.S.
goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   The political goal of the president's journey, as formed by
White House strategists, can best be understood as a long defense
of his policy of engaging China, which is the focus of
congressional investigations into political contributions and the
possible transfer of U.S. technology to the development of Chinese
nuclear missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the visit will be heavily symbolic, beginning with his
arrival in Xian, the ancient Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
   The official welcoming ceremony will be held Saturday morning in
Tiananmen Square, a place where the Chinese have celebrated triumph
and witnessed tragedy repeatedly over the decades since the
communist revolution of 1949. Clinton has already come under
criticism in the United States for agreeing to appear at the
square, the symbol of the bloody crackdown on pro-democracy
demonstrators in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The trip ends in Hong Kong, which Clinton will portray as the
hoped-for future of all China.
</P>
<P>
   The images Clinton wants his domestic American audience to
remember are his contacts with ordinary Chinese _ villagers,
students, business people, first-time homeowners, churchgoers.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton makes his progress from historic Xian to imperial
Beijing to bustling Shanghai to picturesque Guilin, he will be
following the standard tourist itinerary. Each stop has a policy
component, but it the risk for the White House is that Americans
will see only the pictures and find few concrete benefits to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a highly risky summit for the president,'' said David
Shambaugh, director of the Sigur Center at George Washington
University and a former China policy adviser at the National
Security Council and the State Department. ``It's the longest trip
of his presidency and he is spending most of it sightseeing.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has tried to win Chinese concessions in some
important areas as part of the president's visit. But senior
officials said Clinton left for China with little prospect of
agreement on major parts of that agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had hoped that China would sign the
International Convention on Civil and Political Rights, as Beijing
promised to do this spring, when Clinton chose not to sponsor a
resolution condemning China's human rights practices. But Jiang
announced that China would only sign the convention this autumn.
</P>
<P>
   China also has thus far rejected U.S. efforts on Tibet, by
refusing the idea of a visit, by an internationally known person or
organization, to the young Panchen Lama designated by the Dalai
Lama. China has appointed its own Panchen Lama, the second-ranking
spiritual leader of Tibetan Buddhists. The 9-year-old Panchen Lama
and his parents, Beijing says, are under the state's protection in
an unidentified location.
</P>
<P>
   China has also resisted U.S. requests to stop the re-education
of monks and nuns in Tibetan monasteries, and has thus far not
released any well-known Tibetan prisoners of conscience. Nor has
China yet released any of the dissidents on list given to Beijing
by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   China has also rejected the idea of any sweeping review of the
cases of nearly 2,500 prisoners convicted under a
counter-revolutionary offense now scrapped from Chinese law,
including some dating from the Tiananmen demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And officials in Washington were pessimistic about the
possibility of an agreement under which China would stop targeting
its nuclear missiles at the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the White House said there was still hope for the
gesture and sent Deputy National Security Adviser James Steinberg
to to China ahead of Clinton for a last round of talks.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the State Department and Pentagon, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said it was unlikely a deal could be
reached. China has insisted it would not ``detarget'' its nuclear
weapons until the United States pledges never to use nuclear
weapons first in a crisis. ``We're absolutely deadlocked,'' one
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Against this political backdrop, Clinton hopes to assuage
domestic critics of engagement with the Chinese with frank talk on
China's continuing human rights abuses. He will remind China's
leaders that attempts to meddle in U.S. politics by secret campaign
contributions are illegal and unacceptable. He will praise China
for its role in trying to restrain an arms race between India and
Pakistan. He will urge it to open its markets. And he will say that
China must take painful steps to reduce pollution that is damaging
the health of its people and contributing to global warming.
</P>
<P>
   On each of these areas the president has come under attack from
critics across the political spectrum in the United States, who
complain that he is turning a blind eye to Chinese misbehavior in
the interest of advancing America's commercial ties to the world's
most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is his real policy? Engaging them by money?'' asked Harry
Wu, a Chinese dissident now living in the United States. ``Only in
giving them money, it means an appeasement policy. If your policy,
foreign policy, doesn't contain a moral basis, this is a typical,
hypocritical appeasement policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Other human rights advocates, in Congress and in
non-governmental groups, say that by agreeing to visit China
without solid pledges of internal reform the president is
squandering an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has created many of his own problems, some of his
critics argue, by shifting his views and his rhetoric on China
repeatedly during his five years in office. As a candidate in 1992,
he criticized Bush for ``coddling'' the leaders who later mowed
down demonstrators in Tiananmen Square. As president, he linked
normal trading relations to progress on human rights, then reversed
himself and de-linked them.
</P>
<P>
   He sent aircraft carriers to the Taiwan Strait in March 1996
after China conducted a series of provocative missile tests near
Taiwan. A year later he invited Jiang to the White House for the
first state visit by a Chinese leader in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration spent the first five years trying to
develop a China policy that satisfied its many objectives,'' said
Robert Ross, a China scholar at Boston College. ``It went through
at least five or six phases, then settled on the new China policy
of working toward a strategic partnership.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
