<SLUG> BC-CHINA-PEONY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA CANCELS OPERA AT LINCOLN CENTER
</HEADLINE>
   (Duplicaation warning: also moved in `e' category; with
CHINA-PEONY-FRANCE) 
(bl) 
 By SETH FAISON   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ After a final round of negotiations failed to
yield a workable compromise, Shanghai's Bureau of Culture refused
Wednesday night to let a classic Chinese opera be staged as
scheduled next month at the Lincoln Center Festival in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Festival director Nigel Redden, director of the festival, said
late Wednesday night that Shanghai officials maintained that the
production of the opera, ``The Peony Pavilion,'' would have to be
extensively revised to better reflect Chinese tradition before it
would be allowed to travel to the festival.
</P>
<P>
   Although Redden was willing to accept a staging with minor
changes, the officials insisted on a new set of rehearsals that
would make it impossible for the opera, a 20-hour production that
was to have been presented in several segments, to open July 7 as
planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have effectively canceled the project,'' said Redden, who
flew to China on Monday to try to negotiate a way out of the
impasse. ``This is a tremendous loss for us, but it's even worse
for people in the company, who worked day and night for so long to
pull this together.''
</P>
<P>
   Redden said he planned to leave Shanghai on Thursday night. Yet
he still expressed the hope that President Clinton or Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, who are to arrive in China that evening,
would intervene and persuade Shanghai officials to reverse their
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Ma Bomin, the director of Shanghai's Bureau of Culture, said she
blocked ``The Peony Pavilion'' because it was a national treasure
that needed to be protected from unorthodox interpretations like
the one Lincoln Center wanted to perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a precious piece of Chinese culture,'' Ms. Ma, a
former opera singer, said in an interview. ``If we are going to
show it to the world, it must be presented in line with Chinese
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking publicly about ``The Peony Pavilion'' for the first
time since its staging was suddenly thrown into doubt last week,
Ms. Ma defended her bureau's right to be the arbiter of what is
consistent with Chinese tradition. Her comments reflected the
doggedness with which opera buffs in China can try to guard their
turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the power to decide how an opera is performed,'' Ms.
Ma said. ``You must understand, our standards for Kunqu Opera and
Peking Opera are not the same as for other arts. I am an artist,
and I have a responsibility to see it done properly.''
</P>
<P>
   (At Lincoln Center, Beverly Sills, the chairman, and Nathan
Leventhal, the president, issued a statement saying that the Bureau
of Culture's position ``makes it physically impossible for Lincoln
Center to receive the production in time to mount and present it as
scheduled.'' They praised ``the superb artistry of the Shanghai
Kunqu Opera Company,'' which was to have performed the work, and
congratulated the director of the production, Chen Shi-Zheng, ``for
his brilliant and evocative conception.''
</P>
<P>
   (Lincoln Center will explore legal steps, Leventhal said. ``We
own the production,'' he said, referring to Lincoln Center and its
partners in the commissioning consortium. ``They don't.'')
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ma brushed aside arguments that the opera be judged by
Lincoln Center, which is financing the production with co-producers
in France, Australia and Hong Kong, where the opera is also
scheduled to appear. She also discounted the importance of a
contract that she approved last year granting Chen full artistic
freedom in its staging.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed to the contract, and we thought the production was a
good idea,'' Ms. Ma said. ``But now we find that it includes
elements that cannot be allowed, unhealthy elements that violate
China's cultural exchange regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton arriving for a nine-day visit to China on Thursday,
Redden expressed hope that Chinese and U.S. officials would be
eager to resolve a dispute involving a cultural exchange,
especially since Shanghai is now trying to present itself as a
vibrant financial and cultural center.
</P>
<P>
   Unless some senior official intervenes, Ms. Ma is having her
way. ``I don't see what this has to do with President Clinton's
visit,'' she said. ``This is about art, and the debate should
remain about art.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ma cites three artistic objections to the modern staging of
``The Peony Pavilion'': that the production violates the spirit of
the author Tang Xianzu, who wrote the opera in 1598; it violates
the specific rules of Kunqu Opera, one of China's most refined and
classic strands of traditional opera; and it introduces what she
called ``unhealthy elements,'' which she defines as ``feudal,''
``superstitious'' and ``pornographic.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Ms. Ma spoke, it became clear that her biggest problem
was with Chen, a native of China who moved to the United States in
1987 and became a U.S. citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's innovative staging of the opera uses an elaborate set _
complete with a duck pond, water wheel and singing birds _ in what
he described as an effort to recreate the atmosphere of daily life
in China for ordinary people in the Ming Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ma and other elders of Shanghai's culture bureaucracy,
accustomed to simple staging and more stylized acting, are also
apparently accustomed to getting the changes they demand when they
preview a piece of theater. Ms. Ma expressed surprise and some
resentment when Chen resisted some changes she sought after seeing
a dress rehearsal this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand the director has the right to interpret the
opera, but the spirit must be true to the original,'' Ms. Ma said.
``When we made suggestions, he said he would accept some, but not
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrinkling her nose in disgust, she delivered what seemed to be
the most serious criticism she could make about a fellow artist of
classic opera: ``He lacks knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   A director like Chen _ with new ideas, a healthy American budget
and a firm artistic vision _ is almost inevitably going to raise
hackles or induce professional jealousy in a country like China.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has his own ideas and he is very stubborn,'' Ms. Ma said.
Asked why her bureau's objections to ``The Peony Pavilion'' were
raised only after the production had rehearsed in Shanghai for
eight months, she said concerns had been raised indirectly all year
long. Only after Chen staged the dress rehearsal, Ms. Ma said, did
she have a chance to fully explain what was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   When Chen wanted to go over the script with her, to ask which
points she specifically objected to, Ms. Ma seemed to rely on a
tactic common to Communist Party censors, insisting that he make
the changes himself and then let her judge the finished product.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him: `You're the director,''' Ms. Ma said. ``You have
to make the changes, and then let us see the rehearsal as it will
be performed. Then we will decide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
