<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5446 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WETLANDS-DEVELOP-NYT &LR;      06-24 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WETLANDS-DEVELOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED WETLAND RULES DRAW BROAD CRITICISM
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration is proposing changes to
a long-disputed system of wetland development permits, potentially
opening up more wetlands to builders but also creating new
restrictions that are intended to help minimize environmental
damage.
</P>
<P>
   The special permits allow developers to fill in several acres of
wetlands at a time without going through prolonged regulatory
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which was criticized as too lenient by
environmental advocates and too strict by developers, would allow
the permits for more types of wetlands and for larger construction
sites. At the same time, the plan would allow local authorities in
some parts of the country to put new conditions on development, and
would limit the extent of wetland destruction in some
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``nationwide permits,'' the special provisions
governing wetlands were established by Congress years ago to avoid
potentially lengthy reviews of relatively straightforward projects.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, the permits authorize thousands of residential,
commercial and other developments affecting wetlands of a few acres
or less. Developers are often required to offset the environmental
damage by preserving or protecting other wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are supposed to be used only where minimal
environmental harm is expected, the permits cumulatively account
for a significant portion of the estimated 70,000 to 80,000 acres
of wetlands that are lost each year.
</P>
<P>
   Because wetlands provide ecological services such as water
purification and wildlife habitat, the federal government is trying
to reduce annual net wetlands losses to zero.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Army Corps of Engineers, which regulates
wetlands, briefed industry and environmental groups on the proposal
on Wednesday. Officials said the rules would be published soon for
public comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think they are moving the program in the wrong direction,''
said Michael Luzier, assistant vice president at the National
Association of Home Builders. He said fewer developers would be
able to use the new permits, and that new, regional restrictions
would cause delays for builders.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Caputo, a lawyer at the Natural Resources Defense Council,
said the broad scope of the new permits was troubling and that the
limit on how many acres of wetlands could be destroyed was far too
high.
</P>
<P>
   One kind of permit would allow up to three acres of wetlands to
be destroyed in construction of residential subdivisions and
shopping malls, while another would allow up to ten acres to be
eliminated by larger developments.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed changes come at a time when wetlands regulations
are under broad attack by industry groups, which have won a series
of court cases.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia upheld a lower court's ruling that the Corps of Engineers
overstepped its authority by regulating developers whenever they
drained wetlands by dredging. The court's decision invalidated a
1993 regulation, known as the Tulloch rule, that had greatly
expanded Army Corps jurisdiction over development in wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   Court decisions have put such pressure on federal regulators
that they now must consider asking Congress to rewrite the portions
of the Clean Water Act that govern wetlands, a request that
environmental agencies are loath to make because many members of
Congress are hostile to wetlands regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
