<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5447 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-PREKI-LADN     06-24 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-PREKI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREKI READY TO TAKE ON YUGOSLAVIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France --- Like Thomas Dooley before him, Predrag
Radosavljevic is ready to take on his native land in a World Cup
clash. Whether he'll get that opportunity, only Steve Sampson
knows.
</P>
<P>
   Radosavljevic --- known to all as ``Preki'' --- would love to
celebrate his 35th birthday with a goal to beat Yugoslavia tonight
at Stade de La Beaujoire, but he's not anticipating it will happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like I'm starting, and that's very
disappointing for me, especially since this game means very little
for us,'' he said following training on Wednesday. ``I knew coming
in I would not be a starter, but I thought I'd get more playing
time, maybe one or two starts. I'm being overlooked every day.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory over the Yugoslavs would do nothing but bolster Yankee
pride --- the Americans are heading home afterwards regardless of
the result --- and the match offers Sampson an opportunity to
reward the Belgrade-born forward, whose spectacular goals off the
bench notched back-to-back wins over Costa Rica and Brazil in
February.
</P>
<P>
   But Preki, who played the final 33 minutes of Sunday's 2-1 loss
to Iran, doesn't think he'll be on the field, at least not
initially.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke with Steve for two minutes after the Germany match (on
June 15), and he was trying to assure me that he still believed in
me,'' he said. ``I don't think that's the case. It would be nice to
start my first World Cup match, but it doesn't look like it's going
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've not played so well offensively, and everyone's getting a
shot but me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson won't say one way or another if Preki, whose birthday
was Wednesday, would be in his lineup. Asked why Preki wouldn't be
starting, he replied: ``Who says Preki won't start. I didn't say
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson has used Preki almost exclusively off the bench,
questioning his ability to go a full 90 minutes. Preki has done so
repeatedly with the Kansas City Wizards, with whom he won Major
League Soccer's scoring title and MVP award last season, but he
carries far more defensive responsibilities when playing for the
national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Sampson is) just trying to find a reason not to play
me,'' Preki said. ``It's certainly not the case'' that he can't
play the full game.
</P>
<P>
   Preki came to the United States in 1984, leaving Red Star
Belgrade for an indoor soccer career. He was an indoor star most of
the next 12 years --- with brief stints outdoors in Portugal and
England --- then became one of MLS's biggest stars when the league
kicked off in 1996. He gained U.S. citizenship in October 1996 and
has been in and out of the U.S. squad since; he was left out of the
team for a time after sulking over playing time, but Sampson
brought him back after an attitude adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he's been the Americans' 12th man, a player of
superb skill and a great left foot, which he proved most notably in
that 1-0 stunner over the Brazilians at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   He'd love the chance to show Yugoslavia --- the ``Brazilians of
Europe'' --- what he can do, in great part because it is where he
was born, bred and learned to love the game. But his feelings
mirror those of Dooley, the German-born U.S. captain who led the
Yanks against Germany in their World Cup opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought it would be very emotional (to play against
the Yugoslavs), but I really haven't thought about it yet,'' he
said. ``I'm sure it will be even more emotional as the game gets
closer, and more so if I play.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as soon as the game starts, it's just a game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
