NYT-06-24-98 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESTUDY-COX     06-24 2193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTUDY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. Army Corps of Engineers wants to redesign drainage system
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- A half-century ago, weary from an
unending cycle of flood, drought and fire, South Florida residents
asked Washington to build them a barrier against the extremes of
nature.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. All too well.
</P>
<P>
   Federal engineers constructed a 1,600-mile-long bulwark of
canals, levees, pumps and floodgates to ensure that people would
always have enough water _ but never too much. That let the
region's farms prosper. Suburbs and strip malls swarmed, faster
than anyone had imagined, toward the gravel-covered dikes that
marked the Everglades' new boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond those walls, the Everglades strangled in its man-made
straitjacket.
</P>
<P>
   Now the engineers say it's time to start over. They want to
redesign the entire drainage system.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists call it the Everglades' last chance.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers and water managers say it will cost more than $7.5
billion, making it the biggest environmental restoration ever. The
project would spend decades restoring the Everglades' life-giving
pulses of water. The engineers say it's also needed to serve a
region whose population is expected to more than double during the
next 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   It will mean transforming the landscape once again, creating a
network of reservoirs occupying enough territory for a good-size
city. Imagine water covering eight Miamis or two Philadelphias.
Water managers will use so-far-untested methods to store hundreds
of billions of gallons more than 1,000 feet underground, hoping to
retrieve the water years later.
</P>
<P>
   It likely will mean higher taxes or water bills. No one has
decided how to divide the costs, although Washington is expected to
pay half.
</P>
<P>
   All this can happen only if Congress OKs the proposal sometime
after mid-1999. But first, the plan's creators have to sell it to
the people of South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and the South Florida Water
Management District say their plan wouldn't just rescue the
Everglades. They say it's also the key to making South and Central
Florida livable for the next half-century as its population doubles
to 12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, residents can expect more frequent water shortages,
greater floods and repeats of this winter's pounding of the St.
Lucie and Indian rivers by Lake Okeechobee's overflow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a cost to doing nothing,'' said Stuart Appelbaum, the
corps' restoration chief in Jacksonville. ``These problems won't go
away. They'll get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet parts of the plan have drawn skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar growers say it would cripple their industry to give up
tens of thousands of acres of productive farmland for some of the
reservoirs. Water utilities fear relying on unproven storage wells
that might not be able to get federal permits.
</P>
<P>
   Even environmentalists, eager to see the long-promised
restoration become reality, want assurances that this time the
Everglades will come first.
</P>
<P>
   This is more than the old fight between environmentalists and
sugar growers. Everyone has a stake in this debate _ even
suburbanites who wouldn't know saw grass from crab grass. A more
natural Everglades
</P>
<P>
   In corps-speak, the plan is the Central and Southern Florida
Restudy, ordered by Congress in 1992. It's the update of the 1947
federal blueprint that led to the creation of today's South
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   That project, which the corps built largely in the 1950s and
'60s, began by erecting a 100-mile-long wall to separate the
Everglades from the populated coast.
</P>
<P>
   To provide a reliable water supply, the corps divided what
remained of the central and northern Everglades into a series of
bathtub-like basins. The engineers straightened the Kissimmee
River, widened drainage canals and created the 700,000-acre
Everglades Agricultural Area.
</P>
<P>
   The new proposal would leave that structure largely intact. But
it would overlay it with a complex web of pumps, canals, dikes,
100-foot-deep underground ``curtain'' walls, well fields and every
conceivable type of reservoir, from shallow marshes to steep pits
left over from rock mining.
</P>
<P>
   The main idea is to find new places to store water until it's
needed _ especially the estimated 600 billion gallons that drain
unused into the sea each year.
</P>
<P>
   The cities and farms would get all the water they need, with
plenty left over for the Everglades, engineers say.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, the Everglades could return to natural
cycles, no longer dependent on humans' leftover water. The corps'
advisers say the plan would help birds, crocodiles, deer and fish.
</P>
<P>
   The plan rests on a paradox: Man-made dikes and pumps have
trashed the Everglades. To rescue it, the engineers would add more.
</P>
<P>
   That has worried some scientists and environmentalists, who said
the plan could amount to a $7.5 billion water supply project that
helps the Everglades only slightly. They have pressed the corps to
be more aggressive in dismantling canals and dikes to restore the
features that the Everglades' plants and wildlife need: the wide
stretches of slow-trickling water with a mix of shallow and deep
marshes.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone can agree on what's natural.
</P>
<P>
   When the engineers looked at removing part of the levee around
the Arthur R. Marshall Loxahatchee National Wildlife Refuge,
scientists there objected. They said the Palm Beach County refuge
would dry out if the levee didn't hold the water inside.
</P>
<P>
   In the plan, the levee stays.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the latest version of the plan, unveiled last week, would
remove 228 miles of canals and levees, including most of the Miami
Canal and the entire east-west levee that runs north of Everglades
National Park along Tamiami Trail. The corps would add bridges or
culverts to the road to let water flow south into the park.
</P>
<P>
   Appelbaum calls truly natural flow an impossible goal for an
Everglades that has lost half its territory to development.
</P>
<P>
   Park researcher Robert Doren agreed but said the current plan
goes further toward that goal than any earlier proposal. He said he
still questions whether the plan would restore enough water to the
heart of the park, but the rest of the proposal seems likely to
help the environment a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're never going to get back the way the Everglades used to
be,'' Doren said, noting that early explorers found the marsh so
wet that they could ride sailboats from hammock to hammock. ``It's
not that way today, and it will probably never be that way again.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal's supporters say scientists don't know enough about
how much water, at what places, at what times, will do the most
good _ at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to learn a lot as we implement this plan over the
next 20 years,'' said Dan Cary, the water district's planning
director. ``What I want is the most tools in the toolbox.''
</P>
<P>
   Another possible sticking point is the project's price.
Florida's half of the $7.5 billion cost would be more than the
water district could handle by itself so some mix of state, county
and local money would be needed.
</P>
<P>
   The corps and district have given too little thought to the
price tag, argued Palm Beach County Utilities Director Gary
Dernlan, although he said he supports the project and thinks it
will work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing they can do is price themselves out of the
market,'' Dernlan said. ``Then the project goes down the tubes, and
everyone loses.''
</P>
<P>
   But Florida Audubon Society lobbyist Charles Lee said the price,
paid out over decades and helping more than 12 million people,
isn't that expensive compared with other big-budget projects. He
cited the estimated $4 billion cost for expanding Miami
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're really talking about is a couple of airport runways
or an expressway somewhere,'' he said. Fooling with nature
</P>
<P>
   The proposal follows a century-old tradition of carving up South
Florida to fit the prevailing ideas of progress.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1800s, when most saw the Everglades as a
vermin-ridden swamp in need of draining, a Philadelphia millionaire
named Hamilton Disston(cq) dug a canal linking the Caloosahatchee
River to Lake Okeechobee.
</P>
<P>
   By 1917, his successors had dynamited riverbeds and scraped four
major drainage canals from the lake to the east coast. Later they
linked the lake to the St. Lucie River, still another outlet for
Okeechobee's excess.
</P>
<P>
   But those primitive efforts backfired in the 1940s, when fires
raged across the dried Everglades, and salt from the ocean invaded
the canals and coastal wells. Then two hurricanes and a tropical
storm struck in the fall of 1947, spreading a blanket of water
across 4,700 square miles from Kissimmee to Florida Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Things got dangerous quickly.
</P>
<P>
   In the farming towns around Lake Okeechobee, schoolboys and
prisoners packed sandbags atop canal dikes. In Canal Point, a dike
collapsed, and 4 feet of water flooded the community.
</P>
<P>
   In West Palm Beach, health officials evacuated 400 families from
their homes in neighborhoods where flood waters mixed with sewage.
Loxahatchee Slough sloshed across Okeechobee Road (cq) when a dike
just west of Military Trail gave way.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to make a cow cry. Or so the state implied in its
official plea to Congress, which bore a drawing of a cow bawling
its eyes out as water rose to its neck.
</P>
<P>
   The corps had a drainage plan ready, and public sentiment was in
no mood to wait.
</P>
<P>
   On July 1, 1948, the day after President Harry Truman signed the
bill giving the go-ahead, the front page of The Palm Beach Post
carried a cartoon of a big equipment crane labeled ``Flood
Control.'' The man at the controls was shouting, ``Let's go!''
</P>
<P>
   For the Everglades, the results were deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Canals offered a conduit to foreign plants and fish while drying
out vast stretches of saw-grass marsh, allowing melaleuca trees to
invade. Other areas have drowned in too much water, causing
island-dwelling trees to wilt. The levees destroyed the fringe
marshes that give wading birds a place to feed.
</P>
<P>
   Water often arrives at the wrong time, scattering the prey of
nesting wood storks and other wading birds. In a cruel ritual, baby
birds routinely starve to death when rising water forces their
parents to flee.
</P>
<P>
   Little surprise, then, that the Everglades' wading bird
population has declined about 90 percent since the corps began its
work.
</P>
<P>
   North of the Everglades, the drainage system failed miserably
this year as El Nio-driven rains filled Lake Okeechobee and sprang
leaks in the Herbert Hoover Dike. The corps released billions of
gallons of lake water down the St. Lucie Canal, devastating fish,
sea grass and tourism-based businesses downstream.
</P>
<P>
   No such misgivings seemed to matter 50 years ago, said Johnny
Jones, retired former chairman of the Florida Wildlife Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they could think of in those days was how do you get rid
of all that damn water,'' said Jones, who used to hunt ducks near
where the Palm Beach Mall was later built. ``It was simply land
reclamation.'' What's next
</P>
<P>
   The corps and the district plan to revise their proposal during
the summer, then unveil it to the public in mid-October. After
holding public hearings in November, they'll ship a final version
to Congress in July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Even congressional approval won't end the story. The engineers
and water managers would spend the next 20 years or so designing
each step of the project and lining up the money. What they have
now, the district's Cary said, is ``just a skeleton.''
</P>
<P>
   But parts of the project already are under way. Aided by $200
million from Congress, the corps and district have bought tens of
thousands of acres for future reservoirs south of Lake Okeechobee
and along the Everglades' fringes.
</P>
<P>
   The land will be crucial. In a flat region like Florida, most
above-ground reservoirs have to be shallow _ which means they have
to be broad. Water managers are in a race to buy the land,
especially just east of the Everglades, before developers snatch it
up.
</P>
<P>
   Some think it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the coast there's nothing left,'' said Herb Zebuth, a
coordinator for the state Department of Environmental Protection,
who thinks the plan calls for too little storage. ``What are you
going to do in downtown West Palm Beach? Are you going to tear up
all the streets, replace the buildings with treatment areas?''
</P>
<P>
   Questions remain, but supporters say the plan represents a great
leap forward. Twenty-five years ago, most politicians called even
the idea of Everglades restoration a pipe dream, and engineers and
water managers relied on piecemeal fixes that created their own
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember, even as recently as the '80s, really becoming
discouraged at how unwilling, how unprepared we were to take a
big-picture look,'' said John Ogden, a water district biologist and
Everglades expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all turned around just remarkably.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff researchers Barbara Gellis Shapiro, Xiao Kai Chen and
Lynne Palombo contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
