<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5453 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-URBAN-COX     06-24 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    City attempts to capture new water sources
 &HT;    By Joel Engelhardt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Palm beach gardens relies on wells when
we flood the slough, this will replenish your wells we're not sure
about that we need the overland flow of water put in a pump we
flood the slough, but who does it really help? at heart, that's the
question _ because it affects who pay for it jupiter _ half wells,
half treated salt water may help me, but we've secured a source of
water independent from your system west palm beach _ where do we
get water to fill the catchment area. had been coming from lake O,
now how about acreage stormwater jupiter and gardens afraid water
management district will tax their wells. fine _ tax our wells but
show us a benefit $34 million _ pumps, wells, canals does this
include buying rock quarry?
</P>
<P>
   A plan to assure a future water supply for residents of northern
Palm Beach County is shaping into a turf battle, with wary
governments positioning themselves to keep the spigot on and the
flow of new taxes off.
</P>
<P>
   _ For West Palm Beach, the revision of the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers' 1947 plan puts the city in a strong position to capture
new sources of water, store it and sell it to neighboring
communities.
</P>
<P>
   _ For The Acreage, it's an opportunity to unleash torrents
during heavy rains that otherwise would blanket yards and driveways
for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ For Palm Beach County, the plan offers a mechanism to reflood
the 10,000-acre Loxahatchee Slough, recreating lost wildlife
habitat while replenishing freshwater sources in Jupiter and Palm
Beach Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   _ But for communities north of West Palm Beach, the proposal
raises concerns about new charges for improvements they say they
don't need.
</P>
<P>
   The total cost of the portion that covers northern Palm Beach
County is estimated at $34 million. And West Palm Beach, which
benefits the most, says the money can be found without new taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a mosaic,'' said Erik Olson, who heads West Palm
Beach's water and sewer department. ``It is true that the city will
no doubt have a better water supply. But so will The Acreage and so
will the areas to the north of us. We've all got to be together, or
otherwise it doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, togetherness has been hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   The portion for northern Palm Beach County would enhance West
Palm Beach's water supply by offering a new source: storm water
from the flood-prone Acreage.
</P>
<P>
   The city would get enough water to meet growth demands and still
market water to other cities _ even perhaps The Acreage. It also
could pump excess water northward into the 10,000-acre Loxahatchee
Slough, which water managers wish to restore to a more natural
flooded state.
</P>
<P>
   A flooded slough would help replenish underground water sources
in Palm Beach Gardens and Jupiter, water managers say.
</P>
<P>
   Yet utilities officials in Jupiter and Palm Beach Gardens say
their water supply is fine, and there's no assurance flooding the
slough will make it better. In fact, officials of Seacoast
Utilities, which supplies Palm Beach Gardens, North Palm Beach and
Lake Park, argue the changes would interrupt an overland water
source they rely upon.
</P>
<P>
   The move is great for the environment and like other
environmental improvements should be paid for on a regional basis,
not by local rate payers, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The utilities' biggest scare came last year, when water
management district Executive Director Sam Poole broached the idea
of applying a tax on utilities' wells to help pay for the plan for
northern Palm Beach County. He later backed away from the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The Loxahatchee Council of Governments, a group of 11 north
county cities and special districts, sent Poole its objections and
produced a resolution for its members to sign. So far, Jupiter and
Juno Beach have signed. Seacoast votes later this month.
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach officials, trying to avoid conflict, are putting
together grant requests to find the money without tapping local
sources. They believe they can get $20 million from Congress and
$12 million from the South Florida Water Management District.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
