<HEADER>
A5461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-MARKETPLACE-NYT     06-24 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: U.S. STEPS UP PRESSURE FOR JAPANESE ECONOMIC REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A week after the Clinton administration signed off
on a multibillion-dollar intervention in the foreign-exchange
markets to support the Japanese yen, American authorities stepped
up the pressure on the Japanese government Wednesday to make good
on its promises of economic reform and avoid another decline in the
currency's value.
</P>
<P>
   ``The steps we can take _ currency intervention _ can have an
effect, but they can have an effect primarily through what they
signal,'' Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers told the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee Wednesday, hours after returning
from a trip to Japan and Indonesia. ``What is crucial is the pace
of action,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, investors seem to have been unimpressed with the speed
of Japan's efforts to clean up $600 billion in bad bank debts, spur
the economy and accelerate the deregulation of its financial
markets. Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto told President Clinton
last week that he would accelerate those efforts, a promise that
led to the joint intervention in the currency markets last
Wednesday. That sent the yen's value up sharply though briefly _ it
lingered at a rate around 136 to the dollar for a day or so.
</P>
<P>
   But the yen has slipped ever since, as Japanese leaders reverted
to talking about the difficulties inherent in moving quickly. Late
Wednesday, the yen settled in New York trading at 141.25 to the
dollar, compared with 139.15 on Tuesday, and not far below the
level when the United States agreed to step in.
</P>
<P>
   Investors appeared to interpret Summers' comments as suggesting
that Washington would not intervene again any time soon. But they
have been burned once before: When Summers' boss, Secretary of the
Treasury Robert E. Rubin, told Congress earlier this month that
interventions only worked temporarily, traders saw that as a green
light to bet against the Japanese currency. Their rush to sell yen
at that time gave Rubin an opportunity to take the markets by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Summers also told the Senate committee he had
received additional assurances from Chinese officials that they
were ``committed to maintain exchange-rate stability,'' despite
growing pressure to devalue their currency, the yuan.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials fear that a devaluation, while intended to keep
Chinese exports competitively priced with the goods of other Asian
nations, would greatly worsen the Asian financial crisis _ setting
off another round of currency devaluations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to raise these matters directly when he
meets with Chinese leaders in Beijing this weekend. But already the
administration is praising China for its restraint, and the Chinese
are hoping to parlay their resolve not to devalue into some kind of
diplomatic advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said further Wednesday that the International Monetary
Fund was on the verge of another economic agreement with Indonesia
_ its fourth, but the first since President Suharto's resignation.
While details of the accord are skimpy, it will enable the IMF to
resume aid to Jakarta at a time when economic projections for the
country are growing considerably more dire.
</P>
<P>
   The country is suffering what U.S. officials call a food crisis,
with increasing reports of malnutrition in outlying islands, after
years in which Indonesia boasted of self-sufficiency in food
production. The number of Indonesians living below the poverty line
may increase by almost 80 million this year, or nearly 40 percent
of the population, the World Bank warned several days ago.
</P>
<P>
   American officials fear that such distress would worsen attacks
on ethnic Chinese in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Summers made an oblique reference to such attacks Wednesday. He
said that when he met with Indonesia's new president, B.J. Habibie,
in Jakarta on Monday, he told him ``it is essential that all of
Indonesia's people, rich and poor alike, enjoy a sense of security
that their homes, their businesses and their futures in the country
are secure.''
</P>
<P>
   The focus of Summers' testimony Wednesday, though, was on Japan,
and he repeated the theme that the Japanese had only a brief
``window of opportunity'' to act.
</P>
<P>
   But in private, many at the Treasury and the White House are
skeptical about how much Japanese leaders will be able to deliver
before Hashimoto visits Washington on July 22 _ a visit that was
intended in part to keep pressure on Japan and in part to appease
it after Clinton's lengthy visit to China, which begins in Xian on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation in Japan is a source of very considerable
concern,'' Summers said Wednesday. ``Growth has turned negative;
the banking system is increasingly stressed. While the passage last
week of a significant stimulus package is a welcome step, we remain
very concerned about Japan's economic and financial situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pivotal moment for Asia and the global economy,'' he
added. The weakness in Japan is now having a clear impact on the
other troubled economies in Asia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
