A5465 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-ZHAO-1     06-24 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ZHAO-1,280(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PARTY CHIEF URGES LEADERS TO ADMIT TIANANMEN WAS BLUNDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-GOALS, CHINA-LAW,
CHINA-PEONY, CHINA-PEONY-FRANCE, CHINA-RELICS-FEUD) 
(ps) 
 By SETH FAISON 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Zhao Ziyang, who was ousted as Communist Party
chief at the time of the crackdown in Tiananmen Square in 1989, has
challenged the nation's leaders to admit that the incident was not
only reprehensible, but also an immense political blunder.
</P>
<P>
   Zhao, who has been under house arrest for nine years, made his
case in a letter to the party's Central Committee by arguing that
President Clinton's visit to China, which begins on Thursday,
offered a chance to reverse the official verdict on the massacre
that bloodied the streets of Beijing and deeply scarred the
nation's conscience. The Communist Party has insisted that the
government had to use the military to quell a
``counter-revolutionary rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   For a former Communist Party leader to confront the leadership
so openly, and on such a sensitive political issue, is
extraordinary in China. Yet it may reflect Zhao's confidence that
the party's position is squarely on the wrong side of history, and
that the vast majority of Chinese people agree with him.
</P>
<P>
   By trying to provoke debate within the party on the events of
June 4, 1989, when the military killed hundreds of demonstrators
who had been protesting in Tiananmen Square for seven weeks, Zhao
has also risked further punishment. Two ex-officials who know Zhao,
and who attested to the letter's authenticity, said he intended
that it both be read by party leaders and circulated in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are facing the arrival of a new open, democratic and
information-age era,'' Zhao wrote in the letter, which was
published on Wednesday by the Reuters news agency. ``What reason do
we have to reject the will of the people, cling to the June 4
problem and block our road to democratic politics? The trend of
democracy cannot be blocked.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In contrast with previous fallen leaders in China, Zhao has
steadfastly refused to admit wrongdoing, apparently calculating
that creating some distance between himself and his successors can
leave the door open to a possible return to power, should the
current leadership falter in a future crisis.
</P>
<P>
   No liberal when in power, Zhao was fast losing influence when
student protests erupted in the spring of 1989, and he painted
himself as sympathetic to their cause as a way to try to save his
own career.
</P>
<P>
   Whether a pragmatic politician or a cynical one, Zhao now uses
his opposition to the crackdown of June 4, 1989, as his greatest
weapon. His supporters make the case with eloquent simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resolving the June 4 question is a common desire of all
Chinese people,'' said Bao Tong, Zhao's chief aide for many years,
who spent seven years in prison after 1989. ``Political reform is
the biggest issue in China today. It begins with June 4.''
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton arrives in China, landing in Xian Thursday evening
and then proceeding to Beijing on Friday, he will follow an
itinerary designed to accentuate the nonpolitical side of life in
China. Meeting teachers, lawyers and entrepreneurs, Clinton is
expecting to celebrate the ever-greater degree of personal freedom
that is thriving in the private affairs of ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Zhao's letter, and even the mere mention of his name, is a
pointed reminder of the authoritarian and secretive system that
still reigns, sharply restricting political freedom in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   Zhao's case is not a typical one. Held under tight security for
nine years, he has never been charged with a crime. His real
offense was to lose in the high-stakes poker of Communist Party
politics at a time of crisis in 1989, and to refuse to go quietly.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Zhao's rival and predecessor as Communist Party
chief, Hu Yaobang, took a much more conciliatory stance after he
was dumped in January 1987. By accepting criticism, and promising
obediance to his successor, Hu retained a seat on the Politburo
until he died in April 1989, an event that sparked the
demonstrations that led to the Tiananmen confrontation as students
used his death as an excuse to protest government shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Zhao has also retained his membership in the Communist
Party, and under the sometimes arcane rules that guide China's
ruling elite, that allows him certain privileges, such as access to
internal documents, even as he is deprived of other more basic
rights, like freedom of speech and movement.
</P>
<P>
   Zhao lives with his wife in a spacious home on a small alley
near the Forbidden City in Beijing, and not far from Zhongnanhai,
the compound where China's leaders live and work. Zhao can receive
select, pre-approved visitors, and often sees his daughter and two
sons.
</P>
<P>
   Said to suffer from mild heart trouble, Zhao has occasionally
been allowed to play golf, a sport he became passionate about
during his rise to power on the coattails of Deng Xiaoping during
the 1980s. Every time Zhao wants to leave Beijing, he must apply
directly to President Jiang Zemin, who personally decides.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Zhao has spent many winter months in the resort
city of Hangzhou, where he is believed to have been in February,
1997, when Deng died. Zhao applied to Jiang for permission to
return immediately to Beijing and attend Deng's memorial service,
but Jiang turned down the request, eager to establish himself as
the sole heir to Deng and evidently still threatened by Zhao's
reputation as a capable economic reformer. As prime minister, Zhao
pioneered early stages of China's shift to a market economy.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang, who replaced Zhao in 1987as head of the Communist Party,
is judged by political scientists to be vulnerable on the question
of the massacre of June 4, 1989. Even though Jiang was not named as
party General Secretary until three weeks later, emerging as a
complete surprise and compromise candidate, he was physically in
Beijing as a member of the Politburo during the crackdown and is
tainted by association with the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chinese leaders generally try to avoid public
discussion of the Tiananmen incident, it is an issue that weighs
heavily on top-level party politics and that has been repeatedly
been debated at internal meetings, as Prime Minister Zhu Rongji
recently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference that was nationally televised when he took
his new job in March, Zhu was asked about the Tiananmen incident.
He appeared to offer the party line in response.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent years, every major meeting of our party and
government has drawn a correct conclusion regarding that matter,
and that conclusion can not be changed,'' Zhu said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Yet careful listeners noticed that, inadvertently or not, Zhu's
comment revealed that at ``every major meeting,'' the Tiananmen
incident had to reaffirmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my experience, only if an issue is raised will it be
reaffirmed,'' said Bao. ``That means there are different views.
Otherwise there would be no need to discuss it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Zhao's letter, he uses the issue of China-U.S. relations to
call for a reappraisal of the June 4 issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton's visit to China marks a turn for the better
in Sino-U.S. relations,'' Zhao wrote. ``But the United States and
the whole of the West have again and again raised the issue of June
4 and the issue of human rights in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than let it become an obstacle to international
relations, it would be better to resolve the issue of June 4
ourselves, voluntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   He calls the Tiananmen crackdown ``one of the biggest human
rights issues in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Bao, speaking in a telephone interview from his home in Beijing
late Wednesday night, said, ``I have not seen the letter, but it
sounds like it would be in line with Zhao's thinking.''
 &UR; STORY MAY TRIM HERE &QL; 
 &LR;  Bao is a telling case of political persecution himself. As Zhao's
chief aide and secretary to the Politburo, Bao was one of the most
powerful people in China's leadership before his boss fell from
favor and he was suddenly taken into custody on May 28, 1989, just
days before the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Bao was found guilty of subversion for leaking information about
internal party debates in the days leading up to the crackdown,
apparently in a desperate attempt to stop it and save his boss'
career, and his own.
</P>
<P>
   By an odd quirk of China's legal system, Bao recovered his
rights to speak freely on May 28, nine years to the day after his
detention. After granting a few interviews to international
reporters, Bao was again silenced by public security officers who
warned him that in the sensitve days before the June 4 anniversary
this year, keeping quiet would be ``healthy and safe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't know exactly what they meant by that,'' Bao
said, chuckling. ``But today I am speaking to you because I feel
strongly that Chinese people should show President Clinton during
his visit that we have respect for a constitution that guarantees
freedom of speech.''
</P>
</TEXT>
