A5468 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-E!-ENTERTAINMENT-2     06-24 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-E!-ENTERTAINMENT-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT'S E! FOR ENTERTAINMENT _ AND EROTICA?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WARREN BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to be disgraced or disrobed to get a starring
role on E! Entertainment Television. But lately it does seem to
help.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, E! has been steadily churning out sordid tales
of young Hollywood stars _ Christian Slater, Charlie Sheen, Robert
Downey Jr. et al. _ plagued by sex scandals, drug addiction and
other misfortunes.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, E! has begun recycling old tales of Hollywood
murder, mayhem and sexual deviance as part of its new ``Mysteries
and Scandals'' series.
</P>
<P>
   But a channel can't live by mug shots alone. For more uplifting
fare, E! has taken to presenting specials like ``Women of the
Net,'' profiling pornographic-film actresses who've set up their
own X-rated Web sites, and presenting ``Playmates of the '90s,''
which probably requires no plot explication.
</P>
<P>
   Is this any way for a basic cable channel _ one partly owned by
the Walt Disney Co., incidentally _ to carry on? How did the
channel stray from its mission to cover the entertainment industry
better than anyone else? Has someone let Jerry Springer sneak into
the programming booth?
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the latter question is no (though Springer is a
formidable presence on E!, which runs many clips of his show and
recently produced a curiously positive behind-the-scenes special
about it).
</P>
<P>
   E!'s actual program director, Fran Shea, a senior vice
president, maintains that the channel _ heretofore known for
showing movie trailers, fawning celebrity interviews, exhaustive
movie-award-show coverage and the quirky roundup of talk show
highlights (or lowlights) called ``Talk Soup'' _ is simply
broadening its definition of entertainment and giving viewers what
E!'s focus groups say they crave. That seems to be either scandal
or skin, with a thin layer of fashion in between.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the channel has escaped the kind of criticism recently
leveled at Springer's syndicated talk show and Comedy Central's
``South Park,'' which have been accused of being lurid or coarse.
(The relative silence regarding E!'s racy shows raises questions
that are perhaps more troubling for the channel: Is anybody
watching? Does anyone care?).
</P>
<P>
   Still, a perusal of E!'s evening fare over the last couple of
weeks suggests that there is now not just a show but an entire
channel dedicated to pushing the boundaries of good taste.
Watchdogs of television decency (and the rest of us voyeurs) may
want to take note.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of E!'s new programming strategy seems to be the
newly expanded ``E! True Hollywood Story,'' a series best described
as ``Biography'' meets The National Enquirer. With a portentous
voice-over, it chronicles the rise and fall of stars who, in some
cases, hardly ever rose to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   (One recent episode told the life story _ including a battle
against drug addiction _ of the obscure and irritating teen-age
actor Corey Feldman, whose past films include ``Stepmonster'' and
``Meatballs 4''). Presumably because there aren't enough
scandalized current stars available, the channel has begun
searching decades into the past for old scandals that can be
presented anew.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, on E!'s ``Mysteries and Scandals,'' the 1940s murder
of the woman known as the Black Dahlia was recounted one more time,
with repeated flashings of old photographs of the Dahlia's severed
nude torso, along with some cheesy ``re-enactment'' footage
involving what looked like a department-store mannequin sawed into
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   It gets uglier. Earlier this month, a gaunt-looking Charlie
Sheen was caught in E!'s harsh spotlight. For some reason, Sheen
agreed to participate in a documentary that was essentially about
his own demise; he squeezed in a studio interview between a recent
court appearance and a more recent trip to a hospital emergency
room.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to discuss his spate of personal problems, Sheen only
made things worse. He explained, in a bit too much detail, the
reasons he enjoyed the company of prostitutes. And he complained
about the press because, as Sheen blurted, ``They take the fun
stuff _ the drugs, the whores _ and boom, it's, like, headlines.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheen may not have been particularly impressive in his E!
appearance, but at least he was fully clothed. That is more than
can be said for the stars of recent E! original-programming
specials like ``Playmates of the '90s,'' ``Sex on the Riviera,''
``Secrets of Victoria's Secret'' and ``The Girls of Hawaiian
Tropic.''
</P>
<P>
   These one-hour shows, complete with innuendo-drenched narration,
travel to various locales (the South of France, Hugh Hefner's
mansion, the X-rated corners of the Internet, assorted dressing
rooms) to examine the hopes, the dreams and primarily the anatomies
of topless sunbathers, beauty pageant contestants, adult movie
stars, cheerleaders and lingerie models.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   E!'s cheesecake specials may be the closest thing to soft-core
pornography on basic cable. However, unlike Showtime, the Playboy
Channel and other premium channels, E! technically abides by
certain basic-cable practices; for example, it does not show
nudity. But by employing state-of-the-art film technique in which
blurred-image patches are placed in just the right spots, E! is
able to achieve an effect that could be described as 98 percent
nude.
</P>
<P>
   The naughty bits may be covered up, but the promotional plugs
can be painfully obvious on some of these shows. ``The Girls of
Hawaiian Tropic,'' ostensibly a beauty pageant, also serves as an
hourlong promotion for a suntan oil company.
</P>
<P>
   The channel has produced a couple of shows involving the
Victoria's Secret lingerie company, and in each case the scenes of
underwear models are interspersed with self-serving comments by
marketing and publicity executives from the company (which also
happens to be an E! advertiser).
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps worst of all is ``Playmates of the '90s'' (a special so
nice they made it five times, one for each decade since the '50s),
which comes off like a Hefner training film for future centerfolds.
The special is full of boosterism by Hefner and his models, one of
whom points out that posing in the magazine ``has helped launch a
lot of careers, and it's definitely a vehicle to get to where you
want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Shea defends the channel's more risque shows, saying they
are ``in the same category as what the nightly news does during
sweeps where there's always a bikini story and a supermodel.'' The
sexy shows, she says, are ``a small piece of what we do here.''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Women of the Net' is not necessarily all sex-oriented,'' she
added. ``What we're doing is just covering women who are on the
Net, and there's been a lot of interest in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Arriving just as E! was being reintroduced in 1990 (the channel
had earlier been known as Movietime and showed mostly film
trailers), Ms. Shea presided over the channel's early forays into
original production, which included the introduction of ``E! News
Daily,'' a half-hour news program that continues to provide some of
the most in-depth coverage of Hollywood found on television.
</P>
<P>
   The channel also scored its first breakout hit with ``Talk
Soup,'' the series that mixes video clips from talk shows with wry
commentary from the host (originally Greg Kinnear, now John
Henson). E! has drawn solid ratings with its exhaustive coverage of
movie-awards shows, including exclusive live coverage of the Cannes
Film Festival, as well as offbeat features like Joan Rivers'
acerbic critique of the clothing worn by stars at the Academy
Awards. And the channel still shows trailers in its weekly ``Coming
Attractions'' show. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the channel has tried to expand its niche beyond Hollywood
coverage. Beginning a few years ago, it began to develop a slate of
fashion series like ``Fashion Emergency'' and ``Model.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Stern's often crude and sexually explicit late-night talk
show, which made its debut in 1994, quickly became E!'s
highest-rated series and may have provided the impetus for the
channel's subsequent movement toward more sensational and
occasionally lurid programming. (Although Stern will soon have a
weekly series on CBS, he will continue to do his daily show on E!.)
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the formula seems to be working. Ms. Shea notes
that ``The E! True Hollywood Story'' is doing particularly well in
the ratings, as are most of the sexy specials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're following what the audience is interested in,'' she
said, ``and we're expanding the genre of entertainment
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is always the possibility that the channel's
increasingly provocative programming will eventually catch the eye,
and raise the ire, of media watchdogs or perhaps worried Disney
executives. And if that happens, the channel may find itself in a
similar position to some of its ``True Story'' subjects: red-faced
and in need of detoxification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
