<HEADER>
A5470 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-ART-2     06-24 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS UNVEIL PATIENTS` RIGHTS PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Rep. Dennis Hastert, R.-Ill., is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ps) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans unveiled a long-awaited proposal
on Wednesday to define patients' rights and set uniform nationwide
standards for health insurance, especially health maintenance
organizations. The insurance industry immediately denounced the
proposal, saying it would increase costs for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the House Republicans, who have been working behind closed
doors for four months on legislation to address voters' anger at
the constraints of managed health care, found themselves in the
same position as President Clinton four years ago: in the
cross-hairs of the insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican proposals would guarantee coverage of
emergency medical care, assure open communication between doctors
and patients, and allow women in an HMO to go directly to
obstetricians and gynecologists, without getting prior approval.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders in the Senate and House said the House
Republican plan did not do nearly enough to protect consumers, but
the reaction from the White House was upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Rahm Emanuel, a senior adviser to President Clinton, said, ``The
House Republican proposal is a pleasant surprise coming from the
very people who said just six months ago that we'd get a patients'
bill of rights over their dead body.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Labor Secretary Alexis Herman said, ``We are pleased
that the Republican leadership has recognized the need for federal
action,'' though she added that Democratic bills were superior.
</P>
<P>
   No one can say for sure whether any of the proposals will become
law. But there is plenty of common ground if members of the two
parties want to strike a compromise. More and more Republicans say
they want to be able to respond in some way to the concerns of
voters, and to the daily attacks by Democrats on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Hastert, R.-Ill., chairman of the 15-member group
that drafted the House Republican proposal, said, ``It was pretty
evident in listening to our constituents collectively that there
was concern.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, interest in legislation to regulate HMOs has been
bubbling for months in both parties. But conservatives like Sen.
Don Nickles, R.-Okla., the party's assistant leader, express grave
doubts about new federal requirements of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican plan would also enable consumers to
challenge the denial of medical services by filing appeals with an
an independent panel of medical experts. Patients could not
necessarily sue an HMO for damages, but they could get quick
assistance from the courts _ much more than is now available _ if
an HMO or an insurance company improperly denied benefits that had
been promised to subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Health plans would have to pay a monetary penalty for each day
they refused to pay a claim or provide a service to which consumers
were entitled under the terms of their insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers and lawmakers of both parties are clamoring for
federal standards to protect patients. But Bill Gradison, a former
Republican congressman who is president of the Health Insurance
Association of America, said on Wednesday, ``The public would be
better served by no congressional action.''
</P>
<P>
   Gradison described the House Republican proposals as ``a
mishmash of cobbled-together ideas that are guaranteed to raise
consumers' costs, reduce choice and generate more federal
bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a surprising statement, Gradison said ``we are equally
opposed'' to the three major patient-protection bills: the House
Republican measure; a Democratic bill written by Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy of Massachusetts and Rep. John Dingell of Michigan, and a
bipartisan measure drafted by Rep. Charlie Norwood, a Republican
from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood endorsed Hastert's bill, saying he had gotten 75 percent
of what he sought. Norwood, like many Democrats, wanted to do more
to let consumers sue HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignagni, president of the American Association of Health
Plans, which represents HMOs, offered a more nuanced assessment
than Gradison. She said the House Republican plan ``moves in a
better direction than what has been discussed thus far on Capitol
Hill'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``While less onerous than the Kennedy-Dingell proposal or the
Norwood bill, this proposal still tilts toward a reliance on
government mandates,'' she said of the House Republican plan.
</P>
<P>
   Gradison said that the insurance industry was not planning
anything like the $15 million ``Harry and Louise'' television
advertisements that helped kill Clinton's plan to guarantee
coverage for all Americans in 1994. But Gradison said, ``I would
not accept the idea that there will be legislation enacted this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nancy Dickey, president of the American Medical Association,
said, ``The Hastert task force represents a step in the right
direction, but it does not go far enough'' in making HMOs
accountable for the clinical decisions they make.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Court, director of Consumers for Quality Care in Santa
Monica, Calif., said patients would not be fully protected until
they could sue HMOs and recover damages for injuries caused by the
denial of medically necessary care. Another consumer advocate,
Ronald F. Pollack, executive director of Families USA, said the
Republican proposal was ``an election-year stunt, a ploy to enable
some members of Congress to claim they did something on managed
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, the chief deputy whip for House Republicans, said he
was not worried by such negative reaction. ``We tried not to pander
to any one group,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans provided a detailed description of their
proposals on Wednesday and said they would introduce a bill soon
after the Fourth of July recess.
</P>
<P>
   HMO lobbyists, while not thrilled with the prospect of federal
regulation, are pragmatic. They said they were willing to negotiate
with Congress, to fend off what they see as the most onerous
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republican initiative includes these elements:
</P>
<P>
   _ HMOs and other health plans would have to pay for emergency
care in any situation that a ``prudent lay person'' would regard as
an emergency. Democrats agree on this.
</P>
<P>
   _ HMOs could not interfere with doctors' ability to tell
patients about any treatment option, regardless of whether the
health plan offers or pays for such services. Democrats support
this idea.
</P>
<P>
   _ Parents could choose pediatricians, rather than family
doctors, to coordinate care for children in an HMO.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consumers could, for an extra premium, buy coverage allowing
them to use doctors outside the network of physicians formed by an
HMO. Democrats say they too want to expand choices for consumers,
but would do it differently.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans are also proposing several devices to expand
the number of people with health insurance. Under one proposal,
small businesses and self-employed people could band together and
buy insurance through trade associations and professional
organizations. Another proposal would create regional supermarkets,
or ``health marts,'' where families could shop for insurance.
</P>
<P>
   State officials generally oppose such purchasing pools because
the new arrangements would be exempt from many state laws and
regulations, including requirement to cover of specific conditions
like maternity care or cancer screenings. Moreover, Glenn Pomeroy
of North Dakota, president of the National Association of Insurance
Commissioners, said the health marts could recruit healthy people
and avoid sick people by operating in certain geographic areas or
by refusing to cover services needed by people with costly
illnesses like AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said they could not accept a
House Republican proposal to set a $250,000 limit on damages for
pain and suffering in medical malpractice lawsuits. The House has
passed several bills to set such limits, but the Senate has
repeatedly refused to go along.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
