<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5473 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-GOALS-450-2TAKE     06-24 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-GOALS-450-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S MAIN GOAL: RECOGNITION AS A MAJOR PLAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China would love President Clinton to announce here
this week that Taiwan, which China considers a renegade province,
will get no more U.S. weapons, that China's application to join the
World Trade Organization is near approval and that the economic and
military sanctions the United States imposed after the 1989
crackdown on student-led demonstrations in Tiananmen Square will be
lifted.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, as the Chinese leaders already know, China will get
few if any of the policy changes it wants during the state visit
that begins Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, China's leaders and people are ecstatic about the
visit, the first by an U.S. president in nine years and one that is
already being hailed in China as a great step forward in diplomatic
relations.
</P>
<P>
   This summit meeting is important to China for both symbolic and
practical reasons. Symbolic, because the Chinese clearly feel that,
by his very presence, Clinton, leader of the world's foremost
economic and military power, will confer new status on China as a
major international player.
</P>
<P>
   Practical, because China's leaders are convinced that friendly
ties with the United States are crucial to their ambitious goal of
creating a more market-oriented and prosperous economy.
</P>
<P>
   What China seeks most right now, one senses here, is not so much
the things that get discussed at meetings, like trade or security
or even a cave-in on Taiwan. It is, in a word, respect.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese wear their country's painful history on their
sleeves and invariably bring it up in discussions of foreign
policy. After the humiliating foreign incursions of the 19th and
early 20th century, decades of terrible civil war and then the
destructive chaos of Mao's political campaigns, culminating in the
1966-76 Cultural Revolution, China feels it is finally on its feet.
Its economy has surged, its leadership is stable and China is more
than ready to take what it believes to be its rightful place.
</P>
<P>
   ``This visit means that China finally has been noticed by the
world,'' said Xiong Zhiyong, dean of the Foreign Affairs College in
Beijing. ``The American administration is recognizing the
importance of China.''
</P>
<P>
   This is also the first visit by a U.S. president since 1989, and
the leaders here hope that it will mark, if not an end to world
disapproval of that year's massacre of hundreds of civilians around
Tiananmen Square, at least tacit agreement to push the lingering
ghosts to the side.
</P>
<P>
   For Chinese President Jiang Zemin personally, to again stand
beside the U.S. president, following his touted tour of America
last year, may cement his stature as a statesman able to take up
where the late Deng Xiaoping left off.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At a more practical level, friendly ties with the United States
are seen as vital to Beijing's domestic aims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paramount goal of China is to modernize, and to do that we
need a durable, peaceful environment,'' said Yan Xuetong, a foreign
policy expert at the Chinese Institute of Contemporary
International Relations. ``If we get on bad terms with the United
States, we'll never get the right environment.''
</P>
<P>
   China has embarked on two major, precarious transitions, said
Jia Qingguo, a professor of international studies at Beijing
University: a shift in politics from personal, charismatic
leadership toward more bureaucratic and technocratic rule and a
shift in the economy from rigid socialism toward a market economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need stability to carry out these reforms,'' Jia said.
``And we need all the support we can get to help China through this
difficult period.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Chinese scholars said that while the outside pressures and
criticisms that come with deeper contacts will be controversial
here, China badly needs more foreign trade, more foreign
investment, more advanced technologies as well as more cooperation
in developing energy sources, fighting air and water pollution and
other technical areas. For all these things, leaders here believe,
the United States is the primary source.
</P>
<P>
   China, though its military power is growing, wants to avoid
costly confrontations in Asia. It has an almost willful naivete
about the fear its rising military capability inspires among its
neighbors. China, despite its past support for Pakistan, is working
with the United States to contain a nuclear arms race in South Asia
and peacefully resolve tensions on the Korean peninsula. It is also
wary of the recently affirmed Japanese-U.S. security alliance and
suggestions that even Japan could support the defense of Taiwan in
a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan, as officials in Beijing never tire of saying, remains
the ``core issue'' in Chinese-U.S. relations. There seems little
doubt here that in the event of a serious step toward independence
by Taiwan, China would risk all its gains by resorting to military
force if necessary, possibly forcing America's hand in turn.
</P>
<P>
   But many Chinese foreign policy experts also recognize that
Clinton has little political space to maneuver on Taiwan. So long
as he strongly reiterates U.S. support for ``one China,'' the
Chinese leaders seem ready to let the matter ride for now, though
they maintain the right to use force and harshly criticize U.S.
sales of advanced weapons to Taiwan. They also know that closer
Chinese-U.S. ties implicitly pressure Taiwan to tread carefully in
any moves toward formal independence.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The post-1989 sanctions barring U.S. government export loans and
restricting exports of arms and certain high-technology items, such
as satellites and advanced computers, definitely rankle Chinese
pride and they also impede the high-priority quest for superior
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Still, recent comments by Chinese officials on the sanctions
have sounded more resigned than angry.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the minister for foreign trade and economic cooperation,
Shi Guangsheng, was asked whether a case-by-case rather than
general easing of sanctions would do. ``China welcomes any action
that will result in the relaxation of export restrictions,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Acceptance into the World Trade Organization, in which all the
Western countries and Japan as well as many developing countries
set trade rules, has been a prime political and economic goal. .
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Chinese leaders have swallowed their pRide as U.S.
negotiators declared that the country is far from satisfying
requirements for access to China's markets. Monday, Shi, instead of
lashing out, noted that ``we don't have any timetable,'' and
expressed the hope of further progress this week.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Clinton visit, and more generally ties with the
United States, have been invested with so much meaning here, some
Chinese who know both countries well fear that dangerously
unrealistic expectations are being created, with the potential to
create a backlash.
</P>
<P>
   A leading Chinese specialist in American affairs, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, worried that China underestimates the force
and staying power of issues like human rights or the concerns in
Washington about transfer of sensitive technologies and possible
illegal political donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most disastrous misperception of the United States is that
Americans are purely pragmatic, practical people who only care for
money, and don't have strong inner political and spiritual
values,'' the scholar said.
</P>
<P>
   If the two countries can weave mutually advantageous strategic
and economic ties, the scholar said many Chinese mistakenly think,
then irritating U.S. concerns like human rights or the status of
Tibet will recede.
</P>
<P>
   Suisheng Zhao, a Chinese-born political expert at Colby College
in Maine, who recently visited Beijing, expressed concern that the
Chinese are reading too much into the U.S. relationship _ some
businessmen even predict it will boost China's stock market _ and
will be in for a rude surprise once things turn sour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weight of this summit is very different on the two sides
of the Pacific,'' Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
   But Xiong, the dean of the Foreign Affairs College, felt a more
realistic view was spreading _ that more Chinese realize that
relations between major powers will have ups and downs, that
countries are not all friend or enemy. ``We know it won't always go
smoothly,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
