<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-URIS-GIFTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING OUT WITH A BANG: FOUNDATION GIVING AWAY $30 MILLION BEFORE
DISBANDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A foundation set up by two brothers four decades ago
will go out of business in a blaze of glory by giving away $30
million to six New York City institutions, including the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Central Park Conservancy and the
New York Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   Uris Brothers Foundation will announce the gifts Thursday. The
Metropolitan and the Central Park Conservancy will each receive $10
million, and the Public Library $3 million. The foundation will
also give $3 million to Thirteen-WNET, $2.5 million to Carnegie
Hall and $1.5 million to the New School for Social Research.
</P>
<P>
   The gift is believed to be one of the largest to support the
operations of institutions in New York City. The $30 million total
exceeds the $18 million given earlier this year to Baruch College
of the City University of New York by Lawrence and Carol Zicklin,
the $25 million given last year to the Columbia University School
of Engineering and Applied Science by the Fu Foundation, and the
$20 million in 1990 from the estate of actress Paulette Goddard to
endow professorships at New York University.
</P>
<P>
   ``In size, it's a significant event,'' said Barbara Bryan,
president of the New York Regional Association of Grantmakers, a
nonprofit consortium in Manhattan. ``That's a lot of money for a
small foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, the Uris Brothers Foundation has given away
more than $35 million to recipients in the New York metropolitan
area. It was created in 1957 by two real estate developers, Percy
and Harold Uris.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 million given to the Metropolitan is the largest the
museum has ever received exclusively for educational programs,
``and will strengthen dramatically the museum's outreach to the
young people of this region, and their families,'' said Philippe de
Montebello, the museum's director.
</P>
<P>
   The grant will enable the Met to spend about $550,000 a year to
finance three major new efforts to bring visual arts programs and
activities to 25,000 children each year. They include family
workshops, the distribution of written museum guides and online
information for families on the museum's Web site,
www.Metmuseum.org.
</P>
<P>
   Since the deaths of the two brothers, Harold Uris' three
daughters have managed the foundation. They are Susan Halpern,
president, and Jane Bayard and Dr. Linda Sanger, vice presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a low visibility foundation that doesn't seek to
publicize its grants,'' said Ms. Bryan of the grantmakers
association. ``The foundation has a history of doing things that
need to be done, not necessarily with their name attached.''
</P>
<P>
   The $30 million is the foundation's final gift before it
disbands. ``We're going public now because we want this final gift
to be a celebration of the Uris brothers,'' said Ms. Halpern.
</P>
<P>
   The large grants come as institutions are finding it more
difficult to raise money for mundane needs, from security to worthy
but unglamorous educational programs. In its focus on such
operations, the Uris grant is unusual ``in that it is doing the
gritty things that other givers might not be interested in,'' Ms.
Bryan said.
</P>
<P>
   The three Uris daughters said they would continue charitable
giving by starting foundations of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 million gift to the Central Park Conservatory will
create an endowment for the maintenance of the 1.58-mile running
track at the reservoir, which is being renovated through a $500,000
gift from another donor. The Uris grant will also pay for
renovation and preservation of the landscapes surrounding the
reservoir, as well as provide funding for outreach programs at the
Central Park Visitor Centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The breadth of the gift's impact will reach all park users,''
said Karen Putnam, president of the conservancy, ``from weekend
strollers out to enjoy the park's esthetic beauty, to the
schoolchildren learning about the park's wildlife habitats.''
</P>
<P>
   The $3 million gift to the New York Public Library will create
an endowment to purchase about 12,000 children's books a year for
85 library branches in Manhattan, the Bronx and Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   At Thirteen/WNET, the $3 million gift will provide educational
materials and videos and finance programs that train day care
workers and parents to make better use of the television station's
programming for preschool children.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.5 million gift to Carnegie Hall will support the New
Theater project, which will add educational programs and performing
space to the hall.
</P>
<P>
   At the New School, the $1.5 million grant will create an endowed
professorship in urban policy and management at the Milano Graduate
School of Management and Urban Policy. The chair will be named in
honor of Henry Cohen, who founded the school and served as its dean
for 15 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
