<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5481 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-PARAGUAY-HNS &LR;      06-24 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-PARAGUAY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Paraguay extends ride 
with win over Nigeria
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAINT-ETIENNE, France _ The Bulldog growled and snarled and barked.
</P>
<P>
   He raged from sideline to sideline. He practically frothed at
the mouth at the incredible opportunity facing his small,
overshadowed and economically torn nation.
</P>
<P>
   He was kicked and pushed. He jumped and dived at all angles. He
wagged his tongue and his arms wildly, sometimes to get the crowd
going, sometimes to get his teammates rolling.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, Paraguayan goalkeeper Jose Luis Chilavert, the
mad bulldog of a personality, clamped his jaws around this World
Cup tournament with authority.
</P>
<P>
   After another stunning effort by Chilavert in a 3-1 win over
explosive Nigeria on Wednesday, the only question is, How far can
Chilavert and inspired Paraguay take this wild world ride?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having a sensational time of it,'' Paraguay coach Paolo
Carpeggiani said. ``This is a great party we didn't fully expect.
We worked for it and dreamed of it, but we didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Paraguay can celebrate its team's berth in the second round
of the World Cup and a date Sunday against France in Lens. But what
Paraguay's berth means for Spain is a quick exit for one of the
tournament favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Spain whipped Bulgaria 6-1 in what proved to be a meaningless
match in Lens, while Paraguay and Nigeria battled in Toulouse.
Earlier, France beat Denmark 2-1, setting up Sunday's game against
Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, most experts will favor France in the elimination game.
But then, most believed Paraguay would get an early ticket home out
of Group D _ the so-called ``Group of Death.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't. And the spectacular Chilavert was the biggest reason,
shutting out Spain and Bulgaria and turning back numerous
point-blank shots by Nigeria in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted this game very much,'' Chilavert said. ``We wanted
it for Paraguay.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Chilavert is the player of the tournament thus far and
Paraguay is the most surprising team.
</P>
<P>
   The win also came thanks to a suddenly wide-open offense
stepping up the attack and getting several shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria, which won its first two games, had clinched the top
spot in the group before Wednesday's games. But the Super Eagles
conceded nothing in the entertaining match with Paraguay, trying
all night to beat Chilavert but converting only once.
</P>
<P>
   Chilavert turned aside four scoring chances by Nigeria in the
first half, when the game was tied at 1 after an early header by
Paraguay's Celso Ayala and Wilson Oruma's 11th-minute equalizer
Chilavert barely missed.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest plays offensively for Paraguay came midway through
the second half, when it pressed the ball forward and finally
converted on a booming, curving 25-yard kick by Miguel Benitez in
the 59th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was one of the more spectacular of the tournament, with
Benitez freeing himself from Nigerian stopper Taribo West,
spinning, then firing a rocket past keeper Peter Rufai.
</P>
<P>
   The terrific shot typified play on this hot, humid night, when
the Nigerians turned on the offense with slick moves and lightning
runs and Paraguay answered with its most wide-open effort in the
must-win game.
</P>
<P>
   There were bicycle kicks, 40-yard crossing passes, quick shots
from all angles and the ever-present Chilavert even roaming out of
the box to start attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed that we can be dynamic and have speed in the
attack,'' Carpeggiani said. ``We were outstanding with our
forwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Paraguay sealed the game and set the celebration in motion for
its fans when defender Jose Cordoza came up with his team's third
goal on a low shot that beat a diving Rufai inside the far post.
</P>
<P>
   At the final whistle, the Paraguayans' jubilation was clear,
many players dropping to their knees, some screaming and hugging,
others crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great day for Paraguay,'' Carpeggiani said. ``Now, we
have to face the French. We're going to need this same kind of
game, or a better one. You never know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
