<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-MENS-CHORUS-ART-N     06-24 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MENS-CHORUS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTOR OF GAY MEN'S CHORUS STEPS DOWN AFTER 18 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(ja) 
 By JOYCE WADLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was a time, during the worst of the AIDS
epidemic, when Gary Miller, a founder of the New York City Gay
Men's Chorus, would begin rehearsals by asking if anyone needed a
stool to get through. This was at Carnegie Hall. There were a lot
of musicians' stools there, and still there were never enough for
everyone who was sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choir was divided into four sections,'' Miller says.
``From where I was standing, as conductor, half of the bass section
was decimated. There was a weekend I'll never forget. We did three
memorial services in two days. Two Saturday, one Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   It's morning in the dark, walnut-paneled living room of Miller's
small apartment on the Upper West Side. There are leaded-glass
windows, a fireplace, a dozen pink roses on the little Wurlitzer
piano. The roses are tribute: Monday evening was Miller's farewell
concert in New York. He will resign as music director after a
European tour. It's time for a change, he says. There are floral
gifts all around the room. Miller, who is 51 and wears a wedding
band, talks about death.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we lost someone, at the next rehearsal we would always
sing a song for that person,'' Miller says. ``Sometimes it would be
a song that was special to the person, a lot of the time it was a
song called `Love Lives On.'''
</P>
<P>
   Miller plays a recording of the song. ``The truth of love will
never die, our spirits will shine strong long after we're gone, and
so our love lives on. ''
</P>
<P>
   In the 18 years Miller has worked with the Gay Men's Chorus, 90
members have died. Miller himself is HIV positive. Hearing the
song, he gets up from the sofa, fusses with papers at the back of
the room and cries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This piece, believe it or not, is from an awful movie, `Harry
and the Hendersons,''' he says. ``It came out in '87. But clearly
the lyrics touched us. The person who brought this song to me was
the arranger, Mark Riese, a dear, dear friend of mine and a member
of the chorus. This was the last piece he arranged for us before he
died of AIDS in 1989. As you can observe, this has been a very
emotional week.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how it started for Miller: growing up in York, Pa., ;
fighting with his father, a maintenance machinist, who couldn't
understand a son who loved music and had no interest in sports;
dating a girl he planned to marry in college at the same time he
was sleeping with a boyfriend; unaware there could ever be a
community of men like himself. Miller received a bachelor's degree
in music education from Lebanon Valley College and a master's
degree in choral conducting from the University of Michigan, moved
to New York and taught in public school.
</P>
<P>
   At 33, Miller discovered the fledgling New York City Gay Men's
Choir.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventeen of the chattiest young men,'' Miller says, laughing.
``But so welcoming, so funny. We sang, `Standing on the Corner' _
our version, `watching all the boys go by' _ and `Stouthearted Men'
_ all that glorious trash. Three weeks after I started, the poor
man who tried to lead us threw in the towel. He was a very serious
young man _ this will sound like I'm not _ and as I was the only
one who knew how to wave my arms around in front of this group,
they promoted me. ''
</P>
<P>
   In August 1980, the group merged with the Big Apple Gay Men's
Chorus
</P>
<P>
   Was there a political goal?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes, a mission statement,'' Miller says. ``I used to be
able to quote it. As gay men we wanted to make music for the
education and enrichment of the community. It was to be equal parts
music, social and political.''
</P>
<P>
   One month before the group's first concert, a former transit
policeman opened fire on a gay club called the Ramrod in Greenwich
Village, killing two men. The chorus performed at a memorial
service, singing, ``He's Not Heavy, He's My Brother'' and ``We Kiss
in the Shadows.'' It was not difficult for Miller to relate to the
victims _ he had been beat up twice by men who called him a fag.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ramrod galvanized us,'' Miller says. ``Not just as a
choral group, as a family. It was apparent we had a role in the
healing process that had not existed before. Two years later, with
AIDS, it was the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Working full time as an artist's manager and later as a music
teacher, Miller worked for the chorus for a salary he cheerfully
characterizes as ``a pittance.'' When the American Choral Directors
Association refused to mention the name of the group in their
program in the early '80s because they did not care to include the
word ``gay,'' Miller brought in the American Civil Liberties Union
and mounted a successful suit. He commissioned 40 pieces. Under his
direction, the New York City Gay Men's Chorus became the first gay
musical ensemble to receive a recording contract.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Miller teaches music at the Ethical Culture School and
lives with the man with whom he exchanged wedding rings, Daniel
Starr, the chief librarian at the Museum of Modern Art. There was
no marriage ceremony; the men exchanged rings as Christmas gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The changes Miller sees in the chorus since the bad times in the
'80s?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a baby boom,'' Miller says happily. ``There are a
number of fathers in our chorus. Two men just adopted their second
child.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
