u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-UNION-NYT &LR;      06-24 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM ACCUSES AUTO WORKERS OF STRIKING ILLEGALLY
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ General Motors said Wednesday that two strikes in
Michigan that have crippled its car and truck production were
illegal, taking an unusually hard stance against its national union
over local walkouts.
</P>
<P>
   The company said in a statement that it would seek to take the
United Automobile Workers to expedited arbitration and wanted a
response from the union within 48 hours. The company also plans to
block payments of unemployment benefits to idled workers. GM tried
a similar tactic in a 1996 strike in Dayton, Ohio, but almost all
states granted unemployment benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not have to support a strike against ourselves,''
said Gerald Knechtel, vice president of GM in charge of personnel
for the company's North American operations. ``We will vigorously
pursue this action in all of the states in which we have affected
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's latest stance was communicated in a letter to
Richard Shoemaker, the union's point man in negotiations with GM,
and was disclosed as UAW leaders at a convention here continued to
forecast a long summer of heated labor battles with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker said Wednesday that the letter accused union
negotiators of thwarting management efforts to settle the local
issues that set off strikes by 9,200 workers at two parts factories
in Flint, Mich., and also accused them of essentially waging a
national strike. The two strikes have idled more than 140,000 GM
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker dismissed the letter's accusations as ``theatrics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve and I met with Jack Smith and other GM executives. If
their charges were valid, that would have been the time to bring
them up, not while we're trying to have serious negotiations,'' he
said in an interview. ``Someday they're going to have to start
taking this strike seriously and begin to work toward a solution
instead of wasting time twisting perception.''
</P>
<P>
   The UAW has maintained that its members are on a strike because
of hundreds of health and safety grievances, including hazardous
leaking fluids and dangerous noise levels, issues that UAW locals
are allowed to strike over. But many striking workers have openly
focused their anger at a series of broken commitments concerning
investment at the plants. The two sides will have to meet with an
arbitrator before going before a judge. Shoemaker said he saw
little chance that the letter would end the work stoppage or deter
future strikes by union locals in Dayton, Indianapolis and at a
Flint car factory scheduled to be closed next year. A strike at the
brake factories in Dayton alone would cripple GM, just as one did
for 17 days in 1996. And all the local skirmishes could ignite an
even larger showdown during next year's national contract talks
with GM.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Knechtel of GM said, ``Our contention is that
the strikeable issues identified by the union are contrived and
that the real issues that led to these costly disputes are ones
that the unions have agreed to be nonstrikeable issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Buck, a Cleveland lawyer who represents the management of
many auto parts companies during labor disputes, said that GM could
seek a court injunction demanding that the union return to work or
even ask that the UAW cover GM's losses during the strike, which
analysts estimate at close to $1 billion. ``It's pressure General
Motors can bring to bear,'' he said. But federal laws limit when
courts can intervene in labor disputes, making it likely that GM's
latest action is aimed mainly at forcing a settlement with the
union.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Brickner, professor emeritus of labor and industrial
relations at Michigan State University, views the legal fight as a
risky strategy for both sides. He said GM would have to explain why
it was challenging the Flint strikes as a national dispute while it
did not do so in more than a dozen similar local strikes over the
last three years. The union, meanwhile, would have to prove that
its fight is truly based on health and safety issues at the
striking plants.
</P>
<P>
   GM's latest action was largely overshadowed here Wednesday by
the re- election of Stephen P. Yokich to his second and final term
as president of the 61-year-old union. Yokich did not even comment
on the letter, though people close to him say it has intensified
the union's resolve not to capitulate to GM, which employs 220,000
of its 750,00 members.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the 62-year-old Yokich has more important issues to
deal with regarding the union's future. He wants to be known as the
president who expanded the union's power base outside the nation's
Big Three auto makers. The UAW has been under pressure for decades
to stem a precipitous decline in membership, which has dropped to
750,000 from a peak of 1.5 million in 1979, and to bring small
parts shops and foreign auto giants such as Honda, Toyota and
Nissan into the UAW fold.
</P>
<P>
   As for GM, Yokich has largely left the tedious negotiations to
Shoemaker, a savvy negotiator who has drafted some of the union's
most complex agreements. He said further labor strife with GM was
almost assured because the auto maker was in such a race to expand
its global presence that it was disregarding input from workers and
overlooking the long-term effects of breaking investment
commitments in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Globalization is a fact of life, and we recognize that General
Motors just like every other auto maker has to be a player in that
worldwide market,'' Shoemaker said. ``But that doesn't mean GM can
forget the agreements it's made here in America with local unions.
If we can't convince them to address these issues in a rational and
honest manner, then these kinds of confrontations will continue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
