<HEADER>
A5492 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-SLEEP-NAT     06-24 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SLEEP-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        RESETTING CLOCKS IN THE NAME OF EDUCATION
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Anita Thakkar  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 24 -- Zzzzzz. That's the sound of students
snoring during their classes. And that sound is what prompted Rep.
Zoe Lofgren, D-San Jose, to introduce legislation Wednesday which
would change school schedules -- to accommodate the natural sleep
cycles of teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing a study in the newspaper that reported biological
clock changes in children during puberty, and noticing that she had
a hard time waking up her own kids before school every morning,
Lofgren came up with a plan to deal with the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to know why the school day got earlier and earlier,''
Lofgren said. ``When as kids get older, they need more and more
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Lofgren said she was relieved to read the study results, and
said: ``Thank God my kids are not lazy!''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, the ``Z's to A's Act'' aims to increase academic
performance and safety, and decrease after school crime.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would urge school districts to move up their starting
time to at least 9 a.m., allowing students to get adequate sleep at
night in order to be fully alert during their school day. The bill
would provide $25,000 federal grants to schools will be a big
incentive for the schools to change their hours to be in sync with
teenagers' body clocks.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is also supported by the National Sleep Foundation
(NSF), a nonprofit organization that supports sleep-related
education, research and advocacy to improve public health and
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Lofgren added that the bill would help working parents because
``when school starts later, it also ends later.'' Under her plan,
kids would still be in school between three and six p.m. -- the
time when the juvenile crime rate is at its peak.
</P>
<P>
   William Dement, a sleep researcher at Stanford University, said
that lack of sleep affects mood, ability to learn, and motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation officially recognizes what parents and
teachers have known for years,'' Dement said. ``That students in
our nation's schools are walking zombies trying to cope with the
stresses of school, work and social activities that may literally
be putting their lives in peril.'' He also noted that the average
ten year-old needs ten hours of sleep each night. Contrary to
popular belief, however, the hours of sleep needed does not
decrease as kids get older. This creates a problem because most
teenagers don't get to bed by 9 p.m. every night.
</P>
<P>
   Lofgren bill, however, lacks provisions for after-school
activities, such as sports, music and academic clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Lofgren said ``there's no magic'' to the after-school activities
problem. She said that activities like tennis matches and football
games should simply be played before school. But she added that
``there is nothing more important for students than to be
successful academically.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0484 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5493 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATT-TCI-MAIN-COX     06-24 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-TCI-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High-wire act: AT&AMP;T cable move is perilous
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- There's $48 billion at stake in this roll of the
dice.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling that it can conquer Internet and local telephone
service, AT&AMP;T has agreed to pay that price to buy cable TV operator
Tele-Communications Inc. It's a move that promises to shake up the
online and local telephone industries.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, AT&AMP;T will combine its consumer
long distance, wireless and Internet services with TCI's cable,
telecommunications and high-speed Internet business to create a new
subsidiary _ AT&AMP;T Consumer Services.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said the unit will significantly accelerate its
cable infrastructure to provide digital phone and data services, as
well as digital video services, to consumers by the end of 1999.
TCI has 10 million cable TV subscribers. In Georgia it serves 23
communities, including Columbus and Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase, in stock and assumption of debt, confirms again
what the cable TV industry already believes: that its growing fiber
optic network is the telecommunications superhighway of the future.
AT&AMP;T joins Atlanta-based Cox Communications and other cable TV
operators attempting to bring consumers a range of services.
</P>
<P>
   For AT&AMP;T, the deal, which is expected to close in the first half
of 1999, is a move boldly out of character. The country's leading
long distance carrier has sought a new identity since it was forced
to divest local telephone service to the Baby Bells more than a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a move fraught with danger. There is no guarantee
consumers will flock to cable as their primary ramp to the
Internet. Only about 200,000 of the country's 68 million cable
subscribers have cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Bells such as Atlanta-based BellSouth Corp. aren't going to
let this new market go uncontested. They will likely accelerate
their plans to offer high-speed Internet access over phone lines.
For TCI, the country's second largest cable operator, the deal,
which came together in eight days, is a bonanza.It will help the
Denver-based company catch up with the other operators that have
taken the lead in building two-way digital systems.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
