<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-FCC-NYT &LR;      06-24 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-FCC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY REVIEWS LOOK POSITIVE; CLOSE SCRUTINY IS A CERTAINTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: AT&AMP;T-TCI, AT&AMP;T-ASSESS, AT&AMP;T-EXECS) 
(th) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While federal regulatory officials expressed
initially favorable views of AT&AMP;T Corp.'s proposed acquisition of
cable television giant Tele-Communications Inc., they said
Wednesday that they would closely examine the impact the deal would
have on creating competition in local phone markets and increasing
home access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to learning more about this transaction,''
William Kennard, chairman of the Federal Communications Commission,
said in a speech Wednesday afternoon. ``But if it means that these
companies will make a real commitment to building facilities to
bring residential voice and high-speed Internet service to
America's homes, then this merger is eminently thinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   FCC officials said the commission could be expected to grant
approval if the two companies showed that their merger increased
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and Federal Trade Commission, the two
agencies that share responsibility for enforcing antitrust laws,
have not yet decided among themselves which agency will handle this
case. But both generally apply the same test: If competition is
harmed, the merger receives critical scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Most mergers, by their very nature, reduce competition. But in
some ways, the officials said, this one could be different. Through
TCI, AT&AMP;T intends to introduce significant new competition in the
telephone and Internet service markets.
</P>
<P>
   In a few small markets, cable companies have been offering local
telephone service. But once it acquires TCI, AT&AMP;T plans to move
aggressively into that business, giving the local telephone
companies their first significant competition since the breakup of
AT&AMP;T. Kennard indicated he would like to see that happen.
</P>
<P>
   Greater competition in local telephone service could also open
up long-distance competition. The regional Baby Bell telephone
companies have tried to move into the long-distance market but have
been rebuffed because they face so little competition locally.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all of this happens as is being discussed,'' a senior FCC
official said, ``this could take some of the issues off the table
that have prevented the Baby Bells from moving into long-distance
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the cable-television industry has been slow to offer
Internet services, even though using cable modems gives customers
far faster access to the Internet. But AT&AMP;T is a major Internet
server and is expected to ramp up TCI's presence in that market _
bringing a significant new competitor into that business too.
</P>
<P>
   Senior members of Congress with responsibility in this area said
they were grappling with the same questions. Ken Johnson, an aide
to Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., chairman of the House
Telecommunications subcommittee, said, ``We're going to take a good
hard look, but I think a lot of good could come from this. It will
give consumers one-stop shopping for the Internet, cable and
telephone services. But we do have to see what impact this will
have on cable TV competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is chairman of the Senate
Commerce Committee, complained that the 1996 Telecommunications Act
was supposed to increase competition, thereby reducing the need for
mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This approach ignores marketplace realities and forces
companies that are forestalled from competing to take the simpler
route of merging,'' McCain said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
