<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-EXECS-NYT &LR;      06-24 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-EXECS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG AND MALONE: EXECUTIVES WITH DIFFERING CAREER GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: AT&AMP;T-TCI, AT&AMP;T-ASSESS, AT&AMP;T-FCC) 
(th) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   C. Michael Armstrong and John Malone have arranged a very modern
marriage. In the proposed $48 billion merger of AT&AMP;T Corp., the
nation's biggest long-distance phone company, and
Tele-Communications Inc., the second-largest cable-television
company, theirs will be a partnership of equals pursuing starkly
different career goals.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's chief executive since last November, will
throw all his energies into integrating AT&AMP;T's telephone services
with TCI's cable wires in a drive to offer local phone service to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, who built TCI from a scrappy West Coast cable company
into an industry behemoth, will hardly be a passive partner in that
endeavor. Indeed, he will become one of AT&AMP;T's biggest individual
shareholders and will sit on its board.
</P>
<P>
   But he will spend most of his time doing what he enjoys most _
cable deals. By retaining control over Liberty Media, TCI's
separately traded programming unit with stakes in such properties
as QVC Inc., Home Shopping Network, TV Guide, the Discovery
Channel, Encore Media and Liberty Fox Sports, Malone will in effect
have his own sandbox to play in.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, both men stand to make a lot of money from the
deal. Armstrong could get rich and Malone a whole lot richer than
his current $2.4 billion net worth.
</P>
<P>
   At a joint press conference Wednesday, the 58-year-old Malone
said he thought his ownership of some 25 million TCI shares was
worth about $1.2 billion, though he added that he was so optimistic
about the ramifications of the merger that earlier in the day he
had bought another $240 million in TCI stock at market prices _ or
roughly five million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of his wealth is mostly tied up in Liberty and a third
company, TCI Ventures, that will be folded into Liberty. He will
ultimately be able to swap the TCI stock for AT&AMP;T shares, tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have John's problem,'' Armstrong joked Wednesday,
referring to Malone's wealth and his seeming uncertainty about its
value.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not, but he isn't doing too badly. According to an AT&AMP;T
proxy filed in March, he received a $14.9 million stock package
when he left Hughes Electronics Corp. to join the phone company. He
also got a $1.4 million salary, a comparable bonus and
performance-related stock designed to match his salary this year
and next.
</P>
<P>
   If Armstrong can make this merger work, of course, he is likely
to benefit from huge option grants that could push his long-term
compensation into the stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Ted Turner, the Time Warner vice chairman, who sold his
Turner Broadcasting System to Time Warner and did not retain a
separate power base, John Malone will continue to run his own
fiefdom at Liberty Media.
</P>
<P>
   He has always been an avid dealmaker, and in overseeing Liberty,
which will have relatively little debt, he will have ample
opportunity to buy and sell and negotiate. ``He wants to build
asset value,'' said Christopher Dixon, an analyst at Painewebber
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   That role should suit Malone's impatient personality well. Since
Liberty is generally a minority investor or partner in
cable-programming holdings, he will not be required to get involved
in day-to-day operating duties, a task that has never particularly
interested him.
</P>
<P>
   Given the complexity of the deal, however, it is not yet clear
what the final structure of AT&AMP;T will be. Armstrong and Malone said
Wednesday that while the first step is for AT&AMP;T to acquire TCI, a
second step is to spin off AT&AMP;T's consumer businesses together with
TCI's cable systems into an AT&AMP;T ``tracking stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracking stocks represent ownership in certain, specific assets
of publicly held companies and rise or fall with the fortunes of
those assets. Investors in such stocks have no voting rights,
however.
</P>
<P>
   The advantages of a tracking stock for the issuing company are
twofold: It retains full control of the underlying assets, and it
is subject to fewer tax consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Malone is already taking advantage of the tracking-stock
structure to sell back shares of AT&AMP;T that TCI received when it
sold a stake in Teleport, a company that provides local phone and
data services to businesses, thereby pumping up Liberty's cash
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   TCI will also sell its shares in At Home, an Internet access and
information services company that operates over cable networks, to
AT&AMP;T for cash. Those shares are held by Liberty and TCI Ventures
respectively, both of which are tracking companies of TCI.
</P>
<P>
   Malone sees the new Liberty as a sort of General Electric
Capital Corp., he said Wednesday, because it will have the capital
to make leasing investments in such technologies as digital cable
set top boxes, which could help AT&AMP;T grow.
</P>
<P>
   But before any of that can happen, Liberty said Wednesday that
it would merge with TCI Ventures, which has a wide range of
holdings, in a stock deal with Liberty offering 0.52 shares for
each share of TCI Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   The merged Liberty-TCI Ventures _ which will retain the Liberty
name _ will be an unusual form of tracking stock because AT&AMP;T,
though it will swap a new class of its shares for the Liberty
shares, will not have a direct financial interest in Liberty.
Liberty will be owned by Malone, other TCI and Liberty executives
and the public. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
