<HEADLINE>
NASA OFFICIAL CONCEDES FUTURE DELAYS, COST OVERRUNS MAY HIT SPACE
STATION 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NASA administrator Dan Goldin told a congressional
committee Wednesday that his agency is preparing contingency plans
to expand its role in launching and assembling the orbiting
laboratory, if the space agency's Russian partners cannot meet
their commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin conceded the project _ already over budget and behind
schedule _ probably faces future delays and cost overruns, but he
brushed aside sharp criticism from committee members and offered
few specifics about how much additional funding the agency might
need.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA does not want and does not need a blank check from
Congress,'' Goldin told the House space subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency chief said the Russian government is about $240
million behind in its commitment to the space station and has until
July 1 to fulfill its obligations. At that point, Goldin said, he
will make a recommendation to the White House and Congress based on
alternative measures being considered by NASA planners.
</P>
<P>
   A key concern is whether Russia will complete, as planned, a
propulsion module to keep the space station in proper orbit. Among
the options being considered, Goldin said, is use of the space
shuttle to essentially push the station into the correct orbit
during resupply mission. Also under consideration by NASA is
building a propulsion module largely from parts that might
otherwise be used to build another space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is in big, deep trouble and we need to have some
alternatives to keep the program going,'' Goldin said. Sixteen
countries are participating in the space station, and Goldin said
all but Russia are meeting their obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by committee members, the NASA chief conceded that if
Russia falls short of its goal he might have to ask the White House
and Congress to increase the NASA budget for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. share of the space station, as currently designed, was
to cost an estimated $17 billion and be completed by June 2002.
NASA has revised that cost figure to $21.7 billion. An independent
task force early this year estimated the cost would top $25 billion
and the orbiting lab would not be operational until 2005.
</P>
<P>
   When urged by space station supporters in Congress to help find
the money to cover the overruns, the White House responded recently
that NASA should get no money above the $13.5 billion in the
president's 1999 budget request. Any additional money, the White
House said, should be shifted from other NASA projects such as the
space shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   That suggestion drew an angry response Wednesday from members of
the House space subcommittee and renewed a call by some members to
scrap the space station project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your bosses are letting you down big time,'' Rep. David
Weldon, R-Fla., told Goldin. ``What is it going to take to get the
administration to concede that this (partnership with Russia) isn't
working out and we need to put resources behind making it happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tim Roemer, an Indiana Democrat and leader in efforts to
scrap the international project, renewed his call to pull the plug
``before the slow, bloated and out-of-control space station
cannibalizes the rest of the worthwhile, admirable projects at
NASA.''
</P>
<P>
   In comments supported by Texas Democratic Reps. Sheila Jackson
Lee and Nick Lampson, Goldin said canceling the space station would
be ``devastating'' and essentially end the United States' human
space flight program.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a question from Lampson, whose district includes
the Johnson Space Center in far south Houston, Goldin said the
project is ``the future of our space program'' and without it the
space shuttle has ``no place ... to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the shuttle to spend another 17 years going up and down
for 7 days to 14 days at a time makes no sense,'' Goldin said. ``If
we cancel the program, we will be a second-class power and there
would be international repercussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee said dipping into other NASA accounts to keep the
project moving is ill-advised. ``We need a plan that solidly speaks
to the needs of the space station,'' Jackson Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
