<SLUG> BC-WHEAT-WASHINGTON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE EXEMPTS WHEAT SALES FROM SANCTIONS AGAINST PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The sale of Northwest wheat would be exempt from
sanctions imposed on Pakistan under a $56 billion agriculture
spending bill approved overwhelmingly by the House Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The exemption can not come soon enough for Washington state
wheat growers, whose largest market is Pakistan. Wheat farmers were
already reeling from low prices and an overabundant harvest when
India and Pakistan tested nuclear weapons last month, triggering
automatic sanctions that included a ban on the agricultural credits
Pakistan uses to buy about 37 percent of the wheat grown in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Washington state's congressional delegation, led by Rep. George
Nethercutt, R-Wash., and Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., has been
pushing to change the sanctions law to exempt agricultural export
credits from the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is insane that our country would impose unilateral
sanctions on the industry that is there to provide food and fiber
and assistance to people who are hungry, not only in our country
but in all countries of the world,'' Nethercutt said in debate on
the House floor. ``(Pakistan) is a huge market for us, and for the
law to impose unilateral sanctions seems to me wrongheaded.''
</P>
<P>
   The annual agriculture appropriations bill, which passed 373-48,
increases spending by $6.1 billion over last year. The bill
contains money for the Department of Agriculture, tobacco support
programs, food safety inspections and farm loans.
</P>
<P>
   The House defeated an effort to reduce the subsidy for sugar
processors and approved an amendment that bars the FDA from using
any funds to study, develop or approve for manufacture any
abortion-inducing pill. The Senate, which has not yet taken up the
farm bill, often defeats or softens anti-abortion measures backed
in the more militant House.
</P>
<P>
   The wheat exemption was controversial when it was first
introduced in a subcommittee by Nethercutt, because it became
ensnared in a larger debate over the wisdom of U.S. sanctions
policy. But no opposition was voiced during two days of debate over
agriculture programs on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the gentleman from Washington (Nethercutt) brought up the
proposal that is now incorporated in the bill that dealt with
lifting agriculture from the sanctions mandate in Pakistan, there
was give-and-take on the committee,'' said Rep. Marcy Kaptur of
Ohio, the ranking Democrat on the agriculture appropriations
subcommittee. ``Members did not agree, but ultimately, by the time
we got to the floor, we were able to work out our concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Several members expressed support for the wheat farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The resolution of this issue is vitally important to American
wheat farmers since Pakistan is the third largest wheat market in
the world, accounts for 10 percent of all U.S. wheat exports, and
relies on the (export credit) program for nearly all of its U.S.
wheat imports,'' said Rep. Earl Pomeroy, D-N.D. ``Farmers on the
Upper Great Plains are already struggling with miserably low market
prices, adverse growing conditions, and devastating crop disease.
... At a minimum, we should not surrender hard-fought and hard-won
foreign markets through unilateral sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is not expected to take up its version of the
agriculture budget until it returns from the July 4 recess, and
then any differences between the two budgets must be reconciled.
But thus far, the change sought by wheat farmers has not been
controversial in the Senate, and it was unanimously added to the
bill by the Senate Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton several times has voiced his support for
changing the sanctions law to help wheat farmers. Clinton has said
that without a change in the law, he has no choice but to ban
Pakistan from using agricultural export credits under the Arms
Export Control Act, which requires sanctions on countries that test
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must protect our exports by passing the legislation ... to
allow our farmers to continue to export wheat to Pakistan and
India,'' he said Tuesday. ``It was never intended, I don't believe,
to use food as a weapon in foreign policy even in this extreme
circumstance. And I strongly support that legislation and believe
we have big bipartisan support for doing something about it
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The wheat industry welcomed the House action. Wheat prices in
Portland have fallen from $3.37 a bushel to $2.93 a bushel since
Pakistan detonated its weapons last month. Wheat experts attributed
some of that price drop to the expectation that sanctions would
eliminate a major market for Northwest white wheat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great news that the House passed it, but now we have to
see whether it will get through the Senate, and whether so many
things get attached that it gets killed,'' said Glen Squires, an
analyst at the Washington Wheat Commission. ``And hopefully the
other impacts (of sanctions) won't cause Pakistan's
creditworthiness to be lessened and negate the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan imports about $500 million worth of wheat annually,
about half of which comes from the Northwest. The main competitor
for the Northwest is Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The budget was approved by the House after two days of debate
over various subsidies. Rep. Linda Smith, R-Wash., has been trying
for several years to eliminate tobacco subsidies, but Wednesday she
agreed to withdraw her proposal in exchange for a promise by
Republican leaders to include such a ban in the tobacco bill they
intend to propose this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year, tobacco interests muscled their way to defeat the
amendments by less than 12 votes,'' Smith said. ``Today, with this
agreement, tobacco subsidies and big tobacco interests are on their
way out.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospects of the House tobacco bill, which is expected to be
much more restrained than the sweeping measure rejected by the
Senate last week, remain uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes wire service material.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
