<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-TCI-STRATEGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ATT, A QUICK ENTRY INTO 22 MILLION HOUSEHOLDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They call it ``the last mile,'' the biggest
challenge to telecommunications companies hoping to capture a piece
of the billions up for grabs in the new information era.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies have already crisscrossed the country with
sophisticated networks that for the first time can carry phone,
cable television and new high-tech services over a single wire. But
running those lines from operations centers to the nation's 100
million homes is proving to be hugely expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, as AT&AMP;T Corp. confirmed its $31.9 billion acquisition
of Tele-Communications Inc., the nation's No. 2 cable operator, it
said a major factor driving the deal was the need to travel that
last mile to connect to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T does not own any wires into homes now, but TCI's cable
lines now reach 22 million households. Together, the two companies
promised to upgrade TCI's cable system to offer an array of
information services, including speedy Internet access and
movies-on-demand.
</P>
<P>
   But more important, the companies said they would offer local
telephone service, entering a market where competition is slim, the
Baby Bell monopolies still rule and prices are higher than many
critics say they should be. Phone service ``is probably a year to
18 months away,'' John Malone, chairman and chief executive of TCI,
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of local phone competition was enough to cheer some
consumer advocates who had condemned many of the other
billion-dollar mergers sweeping the phone and cable industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Color us `tentatively optimistic.' We like what we've heard,''
said the Media Access Project, a Washington public interest group.
US Representative Edward Markey, the Massachusetts Democrat who
specializes in telecommunications issues, said the deal might
``jump-start'' local phone competition nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also prompted speculation that other phone companies
would sell cable partners to keep pace with AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T dominates the $75 billion-a-year long-distance industry but
has been locked out of the $110 billion market for local phone
service. The main reason is that the government forced AT&AMP;T in 1984
to give up its wires into US homes, along with switching equipment
that makes local phone service possible. Those assets formed the
core of the local Baby Bell phone companies, such as Bell Atlantic
Corp. in New England.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; It would cost AT&AMP;T billions of dollars to lay new wires, as
much $2,000 per home by some estimates. AT&AMP;T had considered renting
existing lines controlled by the Baby Bells but said it could not
reach acceptable terms.
</P>
<P>
   That is why AT&AMP;T turned to TCI, which has made a huge investment
in wiring homes and businesses. By adapting TCI's cable lines, AT&AMP;T
can cut the cost of establishing local phone service to $400 or
$500 per home, AT&AMP;T chairman C. Michael Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we are beginning to answer a big part of the question
about how we will provide local service to US consumers,'' said
Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   But huge technical and financial hurdles remain. The combined
company's goal isn't just to own a wire into businsses and
residences. It is to build a ``full-service network'' that can
handle voice, video, e-mail and other data with ease.
</P>
<P>
   That requires the company _ and every other cable and local
phone company _ to spend huge amounts to upgrade networks, said
William Bane, a vice president and telecommunications specialist
with Mercer Mangement Consulting in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of copper phone wires or coaxial cable used to deliver
cable TV, the new networks will use fiber-optic lines, which are
less vulnerable to rain, lightning, hungry squirrels, and other
types of interference, and which can carry vastly greater amounts
of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and TCI have a long way to go to build this kind of
network, said Jim Wahl of the Yankee Group, a Boston research and
consulting concern. ``They've got the least-updated plant of the
big cable operators,'' he said of TCI.
</P>
<P>
   The poor condition of TCI's network was one of the
less-publicized reasons that a proposed 1993 merger with Bell
Atlantic collapsed, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   TCI had annoucned plans to fully upgrade its network by the year
2001, ``but from our perspective, that was extremely aggressive,
and we were skeptical that they could meet that goal,'' Wahl said.
Now, with AT&AMP;T's cash and expertise, ``it is more likely they can
meet their goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts Wednesday questioned the cost that AT&AMP;T would
incur. ``I'm really worried about AT&AMP;T funding the upgrade of those
networks,'' analyst Blake Bath of Lehman Brothers told Bloomberg
Business News. ``It's going to take a number of years to get these
networks up to date.''
</P>
<P>
   But for AT&AMP;T, moving into local phone service could be a matter
of survival.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1996, when Congress approved a sweeping overhaul of
telephone and cable laws, long-distance firms and the Baby Bells
were barred from entering each other's businesses. Now those
barriers are gone. But for legal and technical reasons, the Baby
Bells are likely to start selling long-distance service before
carriers like AT&AMP;T move into local service.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's share of the long-distance market, which is already
eroding under pressure from MCI and Sprint, is likley to fall
further before the company generates new revenues from the local
telephone business. The deal with TCI could cut the time that it
remains vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the TCI deal will not bring local phone competition fast
enough for some consumer advocates, including Mark Cooper,
economist for the Consumer Federation of America. ``In five years
or 10 years they'll get it ... I need an effective way for someone
new to get into local service in the next year or two. This ain't
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the only effective way to bring competition to the local
phone market is to force Bell Atlantic and the other Baby Bells to
share their networks on fair terms. Congress attempted to set those
terms in the 1996 legislation, but the Baby Bells have challenged
them in court.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Some consumer advocates who praised the deal for its possible
impact on local phone service cautioned that it could dampen
competition in other arenas.
</P>
<P>
   The Media Access Project warned that TCI could use AT&AMP;T's cash
and clout to ``destroy'' the satellite TV industry, a burgeoning
competitor to cable. And Markey warned that the deal could help TCI
skirt rules that require it to sell its TV programs to other cable
operators, which would be a setback to companies setting up rival
cable service in TCI service areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
