<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-TCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T INTENSIFIES LOCAL PHONE BATTLE WITH PLAN TO BUY TCI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking direct aim at the local telephone monopolies of Bell
Atlantic and the other Bell companies, AT&AMP;T Corp. Wednesday
unveiled plans to acquire cable television giant
Tele-Communications Inc. for $31.9 billion in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would allow AT&AMP;T, the nation's largest long distance
phone carrier, to eventually offer local phone service and
high-speed Internet access to millions of Americans using TCI's
cable lines. As a result, AT&AMP;T, with long-distance and cellular
phone services already, would take a giant step toward providing
consumers one-stop shopping for telecommunications services.
</P>
<P>
   The buyout would also permit AT&AMP;T to bypass local phone
companies _ and the ``access'' fees they charge _ when providing
long-distance services.
</P>
<P>
   News of the deal sent tremors throughout the communications
industry. Shares of local phone companies fell as investors worried
that AT&AMP;T would steal their customers. Shares of cable TV companies
rose on speculation that ATT&AMP;T-TCI combination would trigger
similar deals. And the blockbuster announcement also raised
questions about the local phone strategies of MCI and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   With a flurry of multibillion-dollar telecommunications deals
ushering in an era of sophisticated communications services, AT&AMP;T
had been searching for a master stroke to move it closer to the
goal of offering all-in-one services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Demand for broadband (cable and Internet services) is apparent
and the time was closing in on us,'' explained C. Michael
Armstrong, the 59-year old AT&AMP;T chairman who had expressed
frustration in trying to enter the local phone market that the Bell
companies dominate.
</P>
<P>
   However, AT&AMP;T is entering a large but geographically limited
market. TCI, based in Englewood, Colo., and its affiliates have
about 22 million cable customers. Those customers, plus another 11
million with potential access to TCI networks, represent about
one-third of the nation's households with access to cable.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the move was major gamble by Armstrong, who joined
the company last year from Hughes Electronics. By acquiring TCI,
AT&AMP;T is betting that it can crack the $100 billion local phone
market using cable technology rather than phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big gamble. This was a necessary yet desperate move
by AT&AMP;T,'' said Mark R. Bruneau, president of global communications
and computing at Renaissance Worldwide Inc. of Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T shares fell 5 3/8 to close at 60, while TCI class A stock
rose 1 1/6 to close at 39 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, AT&AMP;T will buy TCI's cable operations with
$26.4 billion in newly issued AT&AMP;T stock. It will also spend $5.5
billion in cash to buy back TCI's stake in Teleport Communications
Group, a local phone provider to businesses that AT&AMP;T agreed to
acquire earlier this year, and TCI's share of AtHome Corp., a
provider of high-speed Internet access. In addition, AT&AMP;T will
assume $11 billion of TCI debt.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Media Group, a programming company spun off from TCI, is
not part of the deal and will continue to be operated independently
by John C. Malone, TCI chief exeuctive.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed deal, which would rank among the top 10 in history,
will create a behemoth with projected revenues of $69 billion a
year.
</P>
<P>
   After the deal, AT&AMP;T will be split into two companies, each with
its own stock. The parent company, AT&AMP;T, will focus on business
customers, the long distance phone system and a wholesale phone
business. It will have 90,000 employees and $36 billion in annual
revenue. The other company, AT&AMP;T Consumer Services Co. will include
local, wireless and long distance phone services to residential
customers as well as cable television and Internet services to
homes. The second company will have &UR;  &LR; annual revenue of $33 billion
and 60,000 employees. Some antitrust experts predicted the deal
would clear regulatory review. But the deal is sure to receive
intense government scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``If AT&AMP;T and TCI make a strong commitment to bring residential
consumers more choice in local telephone and high-speed Internet
access services, then this proposed merger is eminently
thinkable,'' said William Kennard, Federal Communications
Commission chairman, in a statement.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Attorney General Janet Reno made clear that the government
will review the merger, but she said no final decision has been
made whether it would be handled by the Justice Department or the
Federal Trade Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders of both companies must also approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The merger announcement gave some regional Bell operating
companies ammunition to press for quicker government approval to
enter long distance markets. Under the 1996 Telecommunications
Act, &UR;  &LR; the regional phone companies will be allowed to start
offering long distance service only after AT&AMP;T and other
competitors get access to local phone markets.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement, Bell Atlantic said the AT&AMP;T-TCI deal is a
``wake-up call that markets are open.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the AT&AMP;T-TCI deal is an example of
Armstrong's frustration in dealing with the Baby Bells. AT&AMP;T, which
already has been trying to enter the local phone markets, currently
must pay the Baby Bells access fees to connect long distance calls
to local networks. But AT&AMP;T has complained that the access fees are
too high and that the Baby Bells are foot-dragging in lowering
them.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also is expected to boost the cable industry's fortunes
and legitimize cable as a conduit for phone service. The stock
prices of leading cable companies rose Wednesday. ``This deal is a
harbinger of things to come. Cable will provide real competition to
local phone companies,'' said Paul Cianelli, president of the New
England Cable Television Association in Braintree, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
