<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUEENS-FIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEENS FIRE DISRUPTS NEIGHBORHOOD OF SMALL SHOPS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ralph Palmiotto stood outside his water-damaged
insurance agency with worry etched into his face _ not for his own
losses but for those of the six shopkeepers to the south whose
livelihoods were destroyed by fire early Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problems are minor by comparison,'' he said, almost
embarrassed by his relative good fortune. ``These people are my
family,'' he said of his neighbors. ``I get goose bumps just
thinking about what they're going through right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-alarm fire destroyed the six stores and caused heavy
water damage in Palmiotto's shop and two other businesses along the
retail strip at the intersection of Francis Lewis Boulevard and
26th Avenue in Whitestone, Queens. It took four hours and more than
200 firefighters to put out the fire, which began at about 3 a.m.
and left seven firefighters with minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The only fatality was Ziggy, a parrot at the Pet Doctor, a
grooming and boarding shop for pets, but the fire did immeasurable
damage to a small but bustling strip where the atmosphere is more
small town than big city.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the Miracle Mile,'' Palmiotti said. ``This is
working people and these are our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials were unsure where or how the fire started, but
they said it raced quickly up the street through the one-story
shops' cocklofts _ the space between the ceiling and the roof _
until a fire wall on the north side of the local Chinese takeout
restaurant stopped it from spreading further.
</P>
<P>
   The businesses that were destroyed were the Chinese takeout
restaurant, run by a man everybody knew as Mr. Wong; Murder Ink, a
tattoo parlor that opened just six months ago; a baseball card
shop; the pet grooming store; Egizia Tile, which moved to the block
from another spot in Whitestone just about a year ago, and Il
Mercantino, a corner grocery, the sort of convenient focal point of
neighborhood traffic where folks would stop to pick up a quart of
milk on the way home.
</P>
<P>
   The three businesses that suffered water damage were Palmiotti's
insurance business; D'Elar Jewelers, which has been in the
neighborhood as long as anyone can remember, and the Candy Store,
which is actually a store that serves other neighborhood needs _
children run in for a candy bar, and adults with hopes of someday
hitting it big pick up their daily lottery tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll have to go somewhere else to get my numbers,''
said an elderly man who would give his name only as Nicky.
</P>
<P>
   Last names are often an afterthought in the neighborhood strip,
a place where everybody is known only by a first name. Paul at the
paint store on the other side of the street offered space in his
store to anybody who needed to make phone calls. Grace Ann at the
beauty parlor across the street took people in for coffee. And
everybody was worried about Maria Nicolosi, the tile store
operator, who is practically an institution in Whitestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Maria for many, many years,'' said Anita Deklich, a
Whitestone resident who was on her way to Il Mercantino Wednesday
morning for groceries when she saw the fire's devastation.
``Everybody knows her. I got all my tile for my kitchen and my
bathrooms, and all my friends did, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Staring at the empty shell of Mrs. Nicolosi's tile store, Mrs.
Deklich was saddened. ``It gives you a real sad feeling to see
because it's not just about rebuilding, it's about people out of
work,'' she said. ``How is she going to pay her bills?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Nicolosi's daughter, Maria Rosa Nicolosi, said her mother
has had the tile business for more than 21 years. Sitting in her
own shop, Total Impact, a cellular phone and pager store in the
next block, she said she, too, was concerned about her mother.
``We've kept her home because it's going to be devastating to
her,'' she said. ``We're not letting her see the damage, not until
she's ready.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she was also worried about Richard Belner, the operator
of the Pet Doctor. ``I love Richie,'' she said. ``He's always been
there for my mother, helping her open the gates in the morning. Any
time he could he'd lend a hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Belner was visibly shaken by the loss of his business and the
death of Ziggy. ``He was an African gray parrot and he had a
200-word vocabulary and he would give commands to a pet Rottweiler
that he used to sleep on.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the landlord, who owns the entire strip of stores and
carried insurance, had already promised to rebuild. ``Hopefully,
everything will be replaced in six months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of neighbors stopped by to check on Concetta Insalata,
an 85-year-old Italian immigrant who has lived in the two-story
home next to Il Mercantino since 1948. Mrs. Insalata was fine, but
smoke permeated her home, and water had poured into her house and
was still coming out her light fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little upset,'' she said, because she will have to move
in with her 67-year-old son who lives across the street. But she
was even more concerned that she wouldn't be able to shop at the
corner store for a while and instead would have to rely on her son
to drive her to a supermarket a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very bad, what do you think?'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
