<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5534 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPEC-OIL-OUTPUT-265&AMP;A     06-24 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-OIL-OUTPUT-265&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEC AGREES TO CURB OIL OUTPUT TO FORCE PRICES UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By YOUSSEF M. IBRAHIM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria _ Overcoming a serious political dispute that
split the Iranian delegation and threatened the final agreement,
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries announced late
Wednesday that it planned to reduce its oil production by more than
1.3 million barrels a day, or nearly 5 percent, in the latest
attempt to push up prices.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 members of OPEC and other producers have been facing a
severe crisis since oil prices began a sharp decline in November,
falling below $12 a barrel last week to the lowest level in more
than a decade. Two earlier moves to reduce production, including
sharp cutbacks pledged in March, have failed to keep prices from
dropping.
</P>
<P>
   The much-anticipated agreement was announced at the meeting of
OPEC oil ministers here near the close of the oil markets in New
York on Wednesday. The dispute involving Iran had sent oil prices
dropping during the day, wiping out an early rally in European
markets after reports that a deal was imminent. But prices ended
the day little changed, with crude oil for August delivery settling
up 8 cents, at $14.60 a barrel, on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The split among the the Iranians, as well as OPEC's reputation
for being unable to maintain production cutbacks, left some experts
questioning how long the agreement would hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a fragile agreement by its very nature, as it depends on
the pledge of each country to cut its production,'' said Fadhil
Chalabi, a former undersecretary of OPEC. He added that some
countries might once again be tempted to increase production if
prices rise.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The deal was nearly scuttled early Wednesday evening, shortly
before it was first to have been announced, when Iranian Oil
Minister Bijan Zanganeh, who represents the moderate views of
President Mohammad Khatami, engaged in a public dispute with
Kazempour Ardebilli, a senior figure in the Iranian government who
tends to reflect the views of the Revolutionary Guards and other
hard-liners.
</P>
<P>
   The two officials argued loudly over who had the authority to
speak for Iran during the final negotiations over the
oil-production accord. Several OPEC oil ministers who attended that
meeting said privately afterward that they feared the dispute would
deflate any rally in oil prices the agreement might otherwise have
brought.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the session, according to several officials
who were present, Nigerian Oil Minister Don Etete raised his
walking stick in anger at the two Iranian officials, proclaiming
`'this is no way to do business.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the two Iranians and several oil ministers stormed
out of the closed-door meeting, and OPEC was forced to delay the
announcement of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a senior member of the Iranian delegation disagrees with
his minister publicly, it poses a big question mark about what is
happening there,'' a senior Arab delegate said, speaking on
condition of anonymity. ``Can you imagine what it would be like if
in our delegation the minister and the deputy minister argued over
who speaks for the country?''
</P>
<P>
   But other officials said there were some benefits from bringing
the Iranian political dispute out into the open. ``It is good that
a misunderstanding has been aired here because last time when we
here in March, we left with two different Iranian interpretations
of a deal,'' said former Algerian Oil Minister Nordine
Ait-Laoussine, who is a senior adviser to his country's OPEC
delegation. ``This time, we are all clear as to where Iran
stands.''
</P>
<P>
   By agreeing this time to cut their daily oil output by 1.3
million barrels, the 11 members of OPEC have pledged since March to
remove a total of about 2.6 million barrels a day from the market.
</P>
<P>
   If OPEC, which controls about 40 percent of the world's oil
production, can live up to those commitments, it could
significantly reduce the excess supplies of crude oil that have
sent prices plunging. But too often, oil producers both in and
outside OPEC have failed to meet all their pledges.
</P>
<P>
   Late in March, for instance, Saudi Arabia and Venezuela, with
Mexico helping as an intermediary, led a coalition of oil exporters
that agreed to cut oil output by 1.7 million barrels a day. But
less than 1 million barrels is estimated to have actually been
taken out of production, and oil prices, which initially rallied,
resumed their decline.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a number of these countries have agreed to
cut a further total of 740,000 barrels, starting on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   The production cutbacks announced by OPEC on Wednesday will
expand on the reductions planned for July 1 by more than 600,000
barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest sacrifice in production is to come from Saudi
Arabia, which plans to reduce its output by 425,000 barrels a day,
beginning July 1. Venezuela promised to cut its oil output by
325,000 barrels, and the United Arab Emirates, by 100,000 barrels a
day.
</P>
<P>
   After much negotiation, Iran agreed to cut back production
65,000 barrels a day instead of OPEC's request for a 95,000-barrel
cutback.
</P>
<P>
   Ardebilli, who is an adviser to Iran's foreign minister and the
oil minister as well as Iran's governor on the OPEC board, insisted
on the smaller cut, saying this quantity was what his government
had authorized. But Zanganeh, the Iranian oil minister, said he
would agree to a larger cut.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Arab official said the differences in these Iranian
positions reflected concerns over the rising production of oil by
Iraq, Iran's rival and wartime enemy in the 1980s. Over the last
year, the Iraqi government of President Saddam Hussein has raised
its production of oil with United Nations permission to 2.2 million
barrels a day, of which it exports 1.7 million barrels, crowding
Iranian and Saudi oil sales.
</P>
<P>
   It does so under a food-for-oil agreement worked out by its
representatives with the United Nations, and if that production
should continue to expand, Iraq might reclaim its position as
OPEC's second-largest oil producer after Saudi Arabia, passing the
Iranians.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the hard-liners in Tehran have insisted on
giving as little as possible. But Khatami's government, which is
eager to improve ties with the rest of the world, insisted on more
cooperation. Both tendencies are represented in Iran's OPEC
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   A number of non-OPEC countries that attended the meeting as
observers, including representatives of Mexico, Russia, Norway and
Oman, have made some production cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, a non-OPEC member that reduced its output by 100,000
barrels a day at the beginning of April, plans to cut another
100,000 in July.
</P>
<P>
   But Norway, which has cut 100,000 barrels a day, has no plans
for further reductions. Russia pledged reductions this year of
80,000 barrels a day, and Oman offered a 50,000 barrel-a-day cut.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC officials acknowledged that it would take a while for the
market to verify that these pledges had ben fulfilled. And, there
is concern here that the Asian economic crisis, which has removed
about 1 million barrels a day of oil in demand, could grow worse,
making further production cuts necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
