<HEADER>
A5538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-NYT &LR;      06-24 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS SELECT OLOWOKANDI WITH FIRST PICK IN NBA DRAFT  
 (JT )
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ His skill was hard to gauge
because he has played less than 55 games in his life. But his size
_ 7 feet 1 inch, 265 pounds _ made it impossible for the Los
Angeles Clippers to stubbornly choose a small point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Amid trade speculation that he might be dealt, Michael
Olowokandi of the University of Pacific was selected No. 1 by the
Clippers in the National Basketball Association draft at G.M. Place
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my hat on,'' the Nigerian-born Olowokandi said,
donning his Clippers cap. ``But it's on a little loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi becomes the first player drafted from Pacific since
John Gianelli, who played on the Knicks' 1973 championship team,
was taken by the Houston Rockets in the second round of the 1972
draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Vancouver Grizzlies took Mike Bibby with the No. 2 pick and
were also said to be entertaining offers for the 6-1 guard. Denver
became one of several teams to pass on Kansas swingman Paul Pierce,
who fell to No. 10 into the laps of the Boston Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Nuggets took his teammate, power forward Raef
LaFrentz at No. 3. The Toronto Raptors selected North Carolina's
Antawn Jamison with the fourth pick and the Golden State Warriors
chose his Tar Heel teammate Vince Carter with the fifth pick. But
the Raptors, knowing the Warriors wanted Jamison all along, then
traded Jamison for Carter plus cash considerations to Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   Robert (Tractor) Traylor, Michigan's trimmed down 6-7, 284-pound
forward, was taken sixth by the Dallas Mavericks and the Florida
point guard Jason Williams was selected seventh by the Sacramento
Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia took 19-year-old St. Louis shooting guard Larry
Hughes with the eighth pick and Milwaukee chose the German 6-11
forward Dirk Nowitzki at No. 9. Another rumored deal involved the
Bucks sending Nowitzki and their 19th pick to the Mavericks for
Traylor, but no announcements were made midway through the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   While Pierce tumbling out of the top five was surprising,
nothing was more intriguing than who would go No. 1 and why leading
up to the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby was projected as the first pick for the last month until
the Clippers' phone began ringing incessantly about Olowokandi, who
learned the game in relative obscurity the past three years at
little-known University of the Pacific in Stockton, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby's agent, David Falk, was so confident his client would go
No. 1 he only had the Arizona guard work out for the Clippers. But
Falk began to sweat on Tuesday, flying to Los Angeles to meet with
Clippers owner Donald Sterling with the notion of pleading Bibby's
case as No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   He was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to give my opinion I think it would be because
Vancouver got a lot of offers from veteran teams who wanted to
trade up and get me, and they figured they could keep me and get
something better later on,'' Olowokandi said, reasoning why he was
taken No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Elgin Baylor said,'' he added of the Clippers' general
manager, ``there is a lack of available centers in the league right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi is the second straight center and college senior to
be taken with No. 1 overall pick, following Tim Duncan's selection
by San Antonio last season.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby, meanwhile, got a rousing ovation from the Vancouver fans
as he stepped to the podium. Asked how he felt to be drafted by a
team he never worked out for, he smiled and said, ``It makes me
feel wanted, at least.''
</P>
<P>
   Through trades, Orlando and Houston controlled the middle of the
draft. The Magic and Rockets had three picks apiece between Nos. 12
through 18. Orlando used its first two picks on big men - Utah's
6-11 Michael Doleac and Nevada Las-Vegas' Keon Clark, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first 13 picks, not a single high school player was
chosen. Al Harrington, the 6-9 center from St. Patrick's High
School in Elizabeth, N.J., was expected to be chosen near the end
of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Parade Magazine's National Player of the Year, Rashard Lewis of
Alief Elsik High School in Alief, Texas, was also expected to be
taken in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   There was a rumor that Olowokandi would be dealt to Phoenix in a
three-way deal involving Minnesota's Stephon Marbury and the Suns'
Steve Nash. In such a scenario, the London-bred post prodigy would
go to the Suns. Phoenix would send Nash to Minnesota, who would
move Marbury to the Clippers to complete a deal and add spice to
what began as one of the blandest draft days in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   The Timberwolves shot down the deal, and there was no immediate
indications from the Clippers that they would trade Olowokandi.
Marbury would be a free agent next season, and the thinking was
that Minnesota would not be able to pay the point guard a contract
worth more than $100 million after committing $126 million to Kevin
Garnett.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
