<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5539 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT&AMP;T-STOCK-2TAKES-NYT     06-24 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-STOCK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HITCH IN THE AT&AMP;T-TCI HITCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related stories: AT&AMP;T-TCI, AT&AMP;T-ASSESS, AT&AMP;T-FCC, AT&AMP;T-EXECS) 
(th) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Widows and orphans, hold onto your hats.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the merger between AT&AMP;T and Tele-Communications Inc.,
millions of AT&AMP;T shareholders, many of them individual investors
who own the stock for its relative safety and high dividend yield,
are about to become holders of one of Wall Street's sexiest and
most complex inventions, so-called tracking stock.
</P>
<P>
   True, AT&AMP;T's stock _ which was divided into long-distance and
local operating companies in the 1984 breakup and then split three
ways more than two years ago o create separate equipment, phone
and computer companies _ is no longer held mostly by the proverbial
widows and orphans of old. But its shareholders, even the most
sophisticated among them, will be puzzling over this latest deal
for a while.
</P>
<P>
   What is a tracking stock? It is a security typically issued by a
large conglomerate with interests in a wide variety of businesses.
Because the security is designed to track a narrow segment of the
company's far-flung operations, issuing it is a good way for a
company to put a discrete market value on those operations alone.
The stocks are likewise bought by investors interested in whatever
aspect of the business the stock tracks.
</P>
<P>
   There is a big difference between common stocks and tracking
stocks, however. In most cases, ownership of tracking shares does
not represent direct ownership of the business' underlying assets,
as common stock ownership does.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying assets are still owned by the issuing company,
but in a tracking stock the issuing company agrees to parcel out
the economics of the business, as it were, giving its shareholders
a stake in the entire operation while its tracking stockholders can
concentrate their bet.
</P>
<P>
   Although tracking stocks have been around for about 15 years,
only about 15 companies in the United States have issued them.
These companies range from household names such as General Motors,
USX and Georgia-Pacific to smaller companies like Seagull Energy,
the electronics retailer Circuit City and Genzyme Corp., a
biotechnology concern.
</P>
<P>
   Why is staid AT&AMP;T going the tracking stock route? The heads of
both companies are big believers in the concept. John Malone,
chairman of TCI, has a tracking stock, called Liberty Media Group,
that represents the performance of the company's cable programming.
And C. Michael Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's chief executive, came from GM's
Hughes Electronics division and is comfortable with the idea.
</P>
<P>
   By issuing a tracking stock, AT&AMP;T can accomplish objectives
generally achieved in a corporate spinoff without incurring any of
the negatives, such as having to meet some fairly stringent tax law
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   To make a spinoff tax-free to shareholders, for instance, the
parent company would be prohibited by the Internal Revenue Service
from having dealings with the new company once a spinoff had taken
place.
</P>
<P>
   But the company also gives up some of the advantages of a clean
spinoff, which means investors are not likely to place as much
value on the tracking stock as they would on a new spinoff owning
the same assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``People recognize that a tracking stock is not the same as
outright ownership, so they do trade at some discount'' to what
they would have fetched in a spinoff, said Robert Willens, a tax
and accounting analyst at Lehman Brothers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the company gains a lot from issuing a tracking stock.
Once a company has issued one, it can count on being able to raise
capital at the higher valuations that it expects investors to
assign to that particular aspect of the company's business. It can
use that money for either acquisitions or capital investments in
the operation.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, for example, was the first company to float a
tracking stock. It issued two, one to cover its now-divested
Electronic Data Systems subsidiary (so-called ``E'' shares) and
another (``H'' shares) to track its Hughes Electronics division.
</P>
<P>
   Both were higher-growth businesses than GM's more predominant
automotive operations, and so investors were more eager to own
them. GM's ``H'' stock, for example, now trades at around 36 times
what Hughes Electronics earned over the last 12 months, while GM
trades at a price/earnings multiple of 8.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the AT&AMP;T merger, the company will offer
0.7757 share of its common stock for each share of TCI Group series
A and 0.8533 share of AT&AMP;T for each share of TCI's series B stock.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T expects to issue 440 million shares in the transaction. The
existing TCI tracking stock, in a modified form, will be reissued
by AT&AMP;T and therefore will remain as a separate, publicly traded
security after the merger. Malone holds a controlling interest in
Liberty Media Group.
</P>
<P>
   Although AT&AMP;T will acquire title to Liberty Media Group in the
deal, it has agreed to pass along all the benefits of ownership to
the holders of the tracking stock. If Liberty Media Group were to
be sold, for example, all the proceeds would go to its tracking
shareholders, none to AT&AMP;T. Shareholders of AT&AMP;T will not receive
shares of Liberty Media Group as part of the merger.
</P>
<P>
   But AT&AMP;T didn't stop there. The company will also issue a new
tracking stock of its own in the merger. This stock will represent
the activities of AT&AMP;T Consumer Services, a new subsidiary that
will result from the merger.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidiary will include AT&AMP;T's interests in residential
long-distance, wireless and Internet services and TCI's cable and
telecommunications businesses. The company expects AT&AMP;T Consumer
Services to have revenue in 1999 of $33 billion and earnings before
interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization of around $7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Not included in the new AT&AMP;T tracking stock will be the products
and services AT&AMP;T offers to business customers, including Internet
access, long-distance and wireless services and high-speed data
offerings. These operations are expected to generate revenue in
1999 of at least $29 billion and earnings before interest, taxes,
depreciation and amortization of $12 billion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Those who own AT&AMP;T common stock will have a claim on both AT&AMP;T's
business and consumer operations, while the tracking stockholders
will trade exclusively in a piece of paper focused on the consumer
side of the business. Also excluded from the tracking stock will be
the assets of the AT&AMP;T network and AT&AMP;T's wholesale business, in
which the company generates revenue of about $2 billion selling
long-distance time on its lines in bulk.
</P>
<P>
   All this makes for one complicated deal. Indeed, confusion
surrounding the merger may have contributed to the 8 percent
decline in AT&AMP;T stock Wednesday. Tepid action in TCI Group's
shares, up $1.0625, to $39.75, also seemed to indicate investor
confusion and doubt about whether or not the deal will go through.
</P>
<P>
   The merger poses two major risks that may contribute to the
doubt. One is that federal regulators will not approve it. Another
is that TCI's chairman, Malone, will change his mind and walk away
from the proposed merger as he did five years ago when Bell
Atlantic offered almost $17 billion for TCI.
</P>
<P>
   Are tracking stocks riskier than investing in the parent
company? Only in the sense that their lack of diversification makes
a bet that much more narrowly placed.
</P>
<P>
   For example, CMS Energy Group, a gas and electric utility and
energy concern in Dearborn, Mich., has a tracking stock, CPG, that
reflects the performance of its gas distribution subsidiary. If gas
prices plunged, the tracking shares would probably be hurt more
than the shares of the more diversified parent.
</P>
<P>
   What about the fact that tracking stocks have no assets
underlying them? This has not presented a problem to shareholders
because none of the companies that have issued these shares have
experienced financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   When can AT&AMP;T shareholders expect to get their new tracking
shares? That is unclear. According to Willens, the tax and
accounting analyst, tracking stocks are typically issued to
shareholders either in the form of a stock dividend alone or
combined with an initial public offering of the subsidiary's
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Connolly, an AT&AMP;T spokeswoman, said the company had not
decided how it would get the Consumer Services tracking stock into
investors' hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said that a portion will be held by the public,'' she
said, ``but we have not said how that will be achieved.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
