<HEADLINE>
YESHIVA UNIVERSITY ACCUSED OF DENYING HOUSING TO GAY STUDENTS WITH
PARTNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Canada)  (nk) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The American Civil Liberties Union filed a
discrimination lawsuit Wednesday against Yeshiva University for
allegedly denying campus housing to lesbian and gay graduate
students who want to live with their domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed in state court by the ACLU's Lesbian and
Gay Rights Project on behalf of two medical students, Sara Levin
and Maggie Jones, and the Einstein Association of Gays, Lesbians
and Bisexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Levin, 26, a third-year medical student from San Francisco,
and Ms. Jones, 23, a first-year medical student from Halifax, Nova
Scotia, both attend Yeshiva's Albert Einstein College of Medicine
in the Bronx. Each was denied shared housing with her nonstudent
partner because they are not married.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk each day among families who fill the playground and the
courtyard in the late afternoons knowing that my family is not
entitled to the same respect,'' said Ms. Levin, speaking at a news
conference Wednesday at the ACLU's headquarters in lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Adams, the ACLU's lead lawyer, said: ``New York City and
state law simply does not allow this type of discrimination against
lesbian and gay couples.''
</P>
<P>
   The medical school denied discriminating against gay and lesbian
students in a terse statement, saying ``our housing policy is
applied equally to all applicants for student housing without
regard to their sexual orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU's lawsuit seeks a reversal of Yeshiva's housing policy
and damages for emotional distress and the extra cost of housing
and commuting.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones said that she had been fortunate to find a studio
apartment in Brooklyn for $825 a month but that comparable living
space at the university costs only $300 to $400 per month. ``In
addition,'' she said, ``I have a three-hour commute.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeshiva University provides housing for all undergraduates. Of
the university's six graduate schools, only the medical school
offers students housing.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, several colleges and universities, including
Stanford University and Columbia University, have granted same-sex
couples benefits already available to married students. The
University of Chicago adopted such a policy in 1993 after being
challenged by the Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund, a New
York-based national gay rights legal organization.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Scott Emmons, a professor of molecular genetics at Einstein,
said that the medical school's faculty senate has for years
supported equal access to housing and other benefits for same-sex
domestic partners but that the administration has ignored them.
</P>
<P>
   When, as a member of the Einstein Association of Gays, Lesbians
and Bisexuals, he met with the Yeshiva president, Norman Lamm, to
discuss the issue, Emmons said Lamm told him that Yeshiva ``will
not be on the cutting edge of this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamm said Wednesday he would have no comment about that meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
