<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GRADE-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS 61 STUDENTS GOT DIPLOMAS IMPROPERLY
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nearly a quarter of the 277 students who graduated
from a Brooklyn alternative high school in 1996 and 1997 failed at
least one state test or took too few courses but received their
diplomas anyway through an elaborate extra-credit system overseen
by the school's acting principal, according to a report released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them even received credit for running personal errands
for administrators, trading baseball players in a rotisserie league
and answering phones at a travel agency, according to the report by
Edward Stancik, special investigator of the city schools.
</P>
<P>
   The students, all of them graduates of Senior Academy, a
mini-school within the former Eastern District High School, have
since had their diplomas rescinded and their high school
transcripts invalidated, Stancik said.
</P>
<P>
   School officials are now trying to reach the 61 affected
students, some of them already in college, urging them to complete
their courses and retake tests. But so far only 14 have done so.
</P>
<P>
   Stancik said that the acting principal at the school, Marcia
Brevot, had permitted the students to satisfy their outstanding
requirements through questionable internships (one student who
worked as a secretary at a travel agency for 12 weeks received
credits in English, social studies, health and music) and specially
designed courses (one course, titled ornamental horticulture,
involved the creation of centerpieces to satisfy requirements in
English, math and health).
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, Stancik said, Ms. Brevot granted a diploma to a
39-year-old former Eastern District student who had dropped out in
the 1970s, six credits shy of a diploma. Though the former student
had done no additional work, Ms. Brevot acted after the man's
sister-in-law, a leader of the parents' association at the school,
intervened on his behalf, Stancik said.
</P>
<P>
   Through her lawyer, Ms. Brevot said Wednesday night that she had
done nothing wrong and that she was being singled out only to
weaken the alternative school movement, which Schools Chancellor
Rudy Crew has sometimes criticized.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a political hit,'' said Ms. Brevot's lawyer, Richard
Bellman.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brevot, a retired Manhattan high school principal who was
working at Senior Academy as a consultant, left the school system
after her contract expired last summer. Chiara Coletti, a
spokeswoman for Crew, said that officials had decided not to renew
Ms. Brevot's contract in the spring of 1997 after questions about
student credits first surfaced. Because Ms. Brevot is no longer a
school employee, Stancik said, it does not appear she can be
disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said they began their investigation in the
spring of 1997 and eventually determined that Ms. Brevot had set up
what was effectively an alternative credit system. The goal, they
said, was clear: to get as many students as possible at the failing
school to graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Under the state-ordered reorganization of Eastern District,
which was among the state's lowest-performing schools, Senior
Academy had already been designated to close at the end of the
current school year, and Ms. Brevot was hired as a consultant to
preside over its dismantling.
</P>
<P>
   Stancik contended that Ms. Brevot had ``relaxed the curriculum
and restructured the system of awarding credits in a manner that
made it easier for students.'' Stancik said, for example, that
students in so-called interdisciplinary courses _ like one that
replicated a sports rotisserie league, in which students bought and
sold professional players in a simulated free agent market _ could
gain credits in math and social studies, depending on their need.
</P>
<P>
   Bellman, Ms. Brevot's lawyer, said that some of the students had
been passed as a result of a ``clerical error'' and that Ms. Brevot
had written them letters instructing them that they would have to
take the regents test after all.
</P>
<P>
   Of the courses questioned by Stancik, Bellman said that the
investigator had not sought to go below the surface of the work
done. A course on how to repair and build a bicycle, for example,
which gave students credit in English, science and art, involved
the writing of reports and travel logs, as well as a cross-country
trip, Bellman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing at all wrong with that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
