<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves Notebook
 &HT;    By Tom Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- John Schuerholz has heard what you've heard. The
Braves are haggling with Toronto to acquire closer Randy Myers,
with Baltimore for second baseman Roberto Alomar, with Montreal for
handyman Mark Grudzielanek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throw them in the toilet with the rest of them,'' Schuerholz
says of the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Russ Springer to the bullpen might not be the
last adjustment the Braves make to their roster this summer, but
their general manager said Wednesday that no other deal will be
forthcoming immediately. Keep in mind that four of the six
relievers the team broke spring camp with _ Adam Butler, Brian
Edmondson, Alan Embree and Mark Wohlers _ are not with the team
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our bullpen for now. Learn to love it,'' Schuerholz
said. ``These are our guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Springer deal came together gradually, after a series of
scouting reports all corroborated that Springer was pitching as
effectively as he ever had in his career. His arrival, in addition
to the eventual return of Wohlers, is all the club has planned for
the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised between now and the end of the season
(that) we made a couple more moves to strengthen the club,''
Schuerholz said. ``I have no idea what they'd be.''
</P>
<P>
   Relief for Smoltz?
</P>
<P>
   Although John Smoltz was receptive to the suggestion that he
move to the bullpen with the possibility of closing, management is
not exploring the idea. In fact, management doesn't think much of
the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Schuerholz said. ``(Smoltz) is a very
valuable starter, and who knows how any of us think if it becomes
an emergency situation? I know John would be willing to do
something like that, but would it make sense to diminish a strong
starting staff to end up with a strong closer? I don't think so. I
don't think it would make sense, especially when we think Mark
Wohlers can come back. There's no reason to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The club receives daily reports on Wohlers from special
assistant Guy Hansen, who is working at the club's training complex
in Orlando with Wohlers. He is working on altering his windup, has
yet to face any hitters and might not do so until he is sent to
Class AAA Richmond at a date not yet determined.
</P>
<P>
   Relief for Capitol Avenue
</P>
<P>
   Pregame traffic was predictably thick, but access to the Braves
parking lots was somewhat smoother after the Braves and Atlanta
police reached an agreement. Police restored the two-lane turn
policy into the color-coded lots after meeting with team officials
Tuesday. Over the previous homestand, access to the lots had been
restricted to one lane, causing tie-ups of 30 minuter or more just
to park.
</P>
<P>
   Now starting
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga was a late scratch from the lineup because of a
stiff back, and was replaced by Ryan Klesko, who made his first
start of the year at first base. Galarraga, who went hitless in
eight at-bats in New York, missed his first start as a Brave.
Klesko, whose last start at first base came July 23 last season in
Chicago (0-for-4), now has logged 43 games at first and entered the
game with two errors in 160 total chances. Taking Klesko's place in
left field was Curtis Pride, making his eighth start.
</P>
<P>
   Etc. ...
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle, originally set to appear in this afternoon's
Braves Foundation luncheon at the Hard Rock Cafe, has had to
cancel, because he is the team's starter tonight. Scheduled to
appear in his place are Klesko, Andruw Jones, Michael Tucker and
Gerald Williams. Tickets are $20, and all proceeds benefit the
Braves Foundation. ... Scott Boras, the most controversial agent in
baseball, will be Fastball's guest, today from 3-4 p.m. He will
appear at Fastball's Dugout Chatter. ... The Braves sold ticket No.
3 million this week. The team drew nearly 3.5 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
