<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Springer could get call to close
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Russ Springer wants to make one thing clear. He's no
miracle worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at myself as a setup guy,'' said the newest edition
to the Braves bullpen. ``I think every reliever at some point of
his career wants to be a closer. I think I can close games, but the
optimum thing for this club would be for Mark Wohlers to come back
and be at his best.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no guarantee that will happen, and Springer is the
freshest arm in what has been a erratic bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will get right in the thick of things,'' said pitching
coach Leo Mazzone of Springer.
</P>
<P>
   Traded for left-hander Alan Embree, the 29-year-old right-hander
comes to the Braves from expansion Arizona with a career 14-26
record and 5.24 ERA in 199 games. He was 4-3 with a 4.13 ERA with
the Diamondbacks this season. But he struck out 37 in 32 2/3
innings and the Braves desperately need a reliever that can come in
with runners in scoring position and get a strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a very live arm,'' Mazzone said. ``This could turn out
to be real good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager John Schuerholz said, ``I had three different
scouts recommend Russ after they saw him.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Braves are unsure what role Springer will have.
With Wohlers down in the rookie league trying to find his control,
the Braves are going bullpen by committee and, for now, Springer
could find himself in a few save situations. Last year when he was
with Houston, Springer found himself closing games in September
when closer Paul Wagner was struggling. He responded with three
saves in four opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby (Cox) told me to be ready any time the phone rings down
in the pen,'' Springer said. ``It could be to come in and get (out)
batter in the sixth, or in the seventh, eighth or ninth. I'm not
looking to come in here and become the big guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer throws four pitches _ fastball, curve, a cut fastball
and forkball, using the latter two pitches mainly against
left-handed hitters. Interestingly, his first appearance in a
Braves uniform might come against the team he started with, having
been a seventh-round pick of the Yankees in the 1989 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough getting traded during the middle of the season,''
he said. ``I liked Arizona. They are a class organization. But
other than that, you take care of your family first and then your
second priority is to win. I will get that chance here.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wohlers works out in Orlando and may pitch in an
intersquad this weekend. ``He's just pitching on the side right now
and trying to get his mechanics sound,'' Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
