</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Safety Is Independence Day Message
 &HT;    By Harry Thomas
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ With the impending arrival of Independence Day set
against a backdrop of continued drought, a parched Central Texas
istaking precautions to celebrate safely. Fire control officials at
the city and county levels are on high alert as the traditionally
fireworks-laden holiday in the baked-dry area approaches. Fireworks
bans are being strictly enforced, officials said. ``We understand
that fireworks are a traditional part of the Fourth of July
holiday, but the danger is simply too great,'' said Austin Fire
Chief Gary Warren. ``The fun. . .is not worth the risk to yourself,
your home or your neighbor's home.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, sparklers are the one exception to the city's ban on
fireworks, but this year even sparklers are off limits. Anyone
possessing or using any type of fireworks within the city limits
faces a $248 fine.
</P>
<P>
   County fireworks merchants are echoing Warren's calls for
caution. The dry conditions in Bastrop and Travis Counties have
caused county officials to team up with fireworks wholesalers and
distributors to encourage a voluntary no-sale, no-use ordinance on
aerial and missile style fireworks. ``They're a good portion of our
business,'' said Chester Davis, owner of American Fireworks in
Bastrop. ``But we know it's dry. We just want people to have a safe
and happy Fourth _ without fires.'' Missiles and aerials are the
most common causes of fireworks-related grass fires because they
launch after ignition, said Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The Round Rock Fire Department battled a fire early Tuesday
night off of McNeil Road in the Robinson Ranch area that was caused
by a bottle rocket, the department said. Between 2 1/2 and 3 acres
burned.
</P>
<P>
   Vendors appeared to be complying with the voluntary ban
Wednesday. Several fireworks booths located at Austin's city limits
did not have aerials or missiles on display.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the voluntary ban and officials urging caution,
fireworks merchants remained enthusiastic about seasonal sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fourth is on a Saturday this year and we're planning on
making up sales because of that,'' said Buddy Stratton, the
operator of an American Fireworks Factory Outlet just outside the
city limits on U.S. 290 West. ``Lots of people are off all weekend,
so they buy more of the bigger fireworks.''
</P>
<P>
   Stratton said that between 10 and 20 percent of his business
typically comes from sales of aerials and missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks from a passing Union Pacific train caused at least eight
grass fires Wednesday afternoon along the train tracks on the
eastern side of Mo-Pac from south of Northland Drive to Steck
Avenue, said Klint Cummings, a battalion chief for the Austin Fire
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke from the fires billowed onto the highway and caused a
collision between an 18-wheeler and a car on the northbound Mo-Pac
overpass at Northland Drive, Cummings said. No injuries were
reported. The fire department was notified about the fires at 4:34
p.m. and had them under control in about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   A southeast wind kept the flames from spreading to nearby
houses, Cummings said.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service has recorded over 3,000 fires in the state
from May 1 to June 20. Approximately 250 homes were threatened by
fires in Jeff Davis County last weekend. Five wildfires have
charred at least about 5,000 acres in the Panhandle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
