<SLUG> BC-SAKS-FOR-SALE-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAKS FIFTH AVENUE SAID TO BE FOR SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: This was budgeted earlier as RETAIL-ACQUIRE)  
(lb) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saks Fifth Avenue, one of New York's oldest and most
esteemed names in retailing, is on the selling block, executives
who have been briefed on the effort said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The majority owner of the 97-store Saks, Investcorp
International, a Bahrain-based investment bank, has richly profited
from investing in other luxury retailers like Tiffany and Gucci and
selling them to the public. The company has been seeking a similar
way to profit from Saks.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers tend to fetch one to 1.5 times revenue, which would
mean Saks could be priced at between $2 billion and $2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Saks was bought by Investcorp in 1990 for $1.6 billion, and the
company sold 20 percent of Saks to the public in 1995 for $25 a
share, or $425 million. Although the stock soared in its early days
of trading, it has since failed to post the kinds of returns that
Investcorp enjoyed with Tiffany &AMP; Co. and that Gucci Group rewarded
Investcorp with. On Wednesday, shares of Saks closed at $24.825,
down 43.75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Investcorp has a longstanding practice of acquiring companies,
providing capital and other resources for growth and then selling
them in the public marketplace or to private investors. But the
decision to sell Saks was initiated by the retailer's board, the
executives who have been briefed on the matter said. The board has
retained outside investment bankers to assist with a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Saks and Investcorp declined to comment Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   By many measures, Saks has performed well. The company's
earnings rose 95 percent in its last fiscal year, to $55.8 million
on sales of $2.2 billion. Sales have been growing at a compound
rate of 15.6 percent since 1994. And sales at stores open at least
one year, the best measure of a retailer's health, rose 3.8 percent
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The company has significantly reduced its debt load, which was a
terrible drag on it in the early part of the decade. Its most
recent quarter was especially stellar.
</P>
<P>
   But it has been stymied by inconsistent sales, especially in its
Off Fifth division, its outlet shops, where same-store sales fell
6.5 percent last year. Those weak sales, and a weakness in the
market for lower-priced apparel, known as bridge wear, pushed the
cost of goods sold up 13.8 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the company has a merchandising management
problem. Last fall, Rose Marie Bravo, the company's president,
resigned to become chief executive officer of Burberrys Worldwide.
The company was unable to find an adequate replacement, and chose
instead to appoint an executive vice president of merchandising,
Jeanne Daniel, from Tiffany.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Saks has one of the most famous names in the universe of
retailing, and a strong crop of managers, most notably Brian
Kendrick, the company's chief operating officer, who has earned
much respect on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The question, however, is: Is there a retailer left to make the
purchase? The industry has consolidated greatly over the last
decade, leaving few independent luxury chains looking to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Among its competitors, Neiman Marcus, a unit of Harcourt
General, is an obvious candidate, as are LVMH Moet Hennessy-Louis
Vuitton, the luxury holding company based in Paris that owns a
number of the high-end brands found on the store's floors, and
Dickson Poon, which is looking to have a presence in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Both of those companies, however, have been badly hurt by Asia's
economic crisis. The closest thing Federated Department Stores has
to a Saks is Bloomingdale's; it is considerably less fancy than
Saks, which has courted an even wealthier customer base in the last
few years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, retailers are always looking for new ways to gain
economies of scale; indeed, last year Saks made a bid for Barneys
New York, which is operating under Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection, for $290 million for the company. The offer was
rebuffed by Barney's creditors, and Saks later said it would offer
no more. LVMH and Dickson Poon also looked at Barneys last year.
</P>
<P>
   Saks was founded in 1867, and as a privately held company
operated as a division of Gimbel Bros. Inc., the now defunct
department store. In September 1924, Horace Saks and Bernard Gimbel
opened the landmark Fifth Avenue store, which today accounts for
roughly 20 percent of the entire company's sales.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, Saks &AMP; Co. was acquired by BAT Industries PLC through
its acquisition of Gimbel Bros. Investcorp bought the company in
1990 from BAT.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Saks Holdings, the holding company for the retailer,
operates 41 full-line stores, five main-street stores in smaller
cities and eight small stores catering to resort regions. Its
off-price store, Off Fifth, is in 43 locations.
</P>
<P>
   In its 131 years, Saks has seen its competitors fade away. In
New York City, the retail capital of the world, there is no B.
Altman anymore. There is no Bonwit Teller. And Henri Bendel is a
shadow of its former self. Saks is in many ways in a rarefied class
by itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
