<SLUG> BC-CHINA-MISSILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE CITES `MINIMAL' DAMAGE IN LOSS OF CODED CHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (th) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House on Wednesday tried to clarify an
intelligence assessment of damage to national security from the
disappearance of a sensitive, encoded circuit board after a failed
launch of an American communications satellite in China in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials Wednesday sought to play down the
episode, saying that the Pentagon concluded that the loss of the
encoded chips would pose only ``minimal impact'' to national
security.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Pentagon official said Tuesday that the Defense
Department suspected that Chinese officials may have stolen the
militarily sensitive device, which would be a violation of an
agreement between Beijing and Washington on technology safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials said Wednesday they still could not
determine if the United States had ever demanded or received an
accounting from China about the missing circuit board, which tells
an orbiting satellite which way to point to receive and transmit
signals.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Pentagon official said Wednesday that military
authorities responsible for preventing the transfer of sensitive
satellite technology were not alerted by military technical experts
that the circuit board was missing from control box recovered from
the wreckage until ``many months'' after the failed launch on Feb.
15, 1996. Chinese authorities barred American monitors from the
crash site for five hours, purportedly for their own safety.
</P>
<P>
   At issue now is a statement provided last week to Rep. Curt
Weldon, R-Pa., a senior member on the House National Security
Committee, by the Pentagon's National Security Agency.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing last week, three senior officials from the Defense,
State and Commerce departments could not answer some of the
questions Weldon asked about the failed launch, which destroyed a
$200 million satellite built by Loral Space &AMP; Communications and
Hughes Electronics. Weldon later put the questions directly to the
NSA.
</P>
<P>
   In a three-sentence response, to which Weldon referred at
another hearing of the National Security and International
Relations committees on Tuesday, the agency concluded: ``If the
encryption board was reversed-engineered, the knowledge gained
could be used to strengthen adversaries' knowledge'' of the devices
the United States uses to safeguard its communications systems.
</P>
<P>
   But after The New York Times reported this and other aspects of
the hearing in a front-page article Wednesday, the White House's
National Security Council asked the NSA and other government
agencies to provide a more detailed accounting of the missing
circuit board's significance.
</P>
<P>
   In the resulting two-page statement, which the White House
provided to reporters Wednesday, the government qualified its
original damage assessment: ``If the encryption board was
reverse-engineered at the chip level (a difficult process), one
could determine the state of our research and development
sophistication 20 years ago, and the knowledge gained could be used
to strengthen one's knowledge of communications security
principles.''
</P>
<P>
   The original statement given to Weldon also said that since the
failed February 1996 launch, the NSA had ``adopted new space
encryption algorithms.'' Algorithms are the encoded set of
instructions in the circuit board.
</P>
<P>
   The revised statement added the following detail: ``The
technology and algorithms on satellites now being launched is no
longer the same as a result of the normal process of technology
upgrades. These upgrades are unrelated to the loss of the devices''
on the failed February 1996 launch.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the NSA said the agency decided in October
1995 to adopt new encryption codes as part of a regular, 20-year
upgrade schedule. The spokeswoman said new codes were not installed
on the satellite that was destroyed in February 1996, and she did
not know when the new codes were actually employed.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials blamed the super-secret National Security Agency,
the government's codemakers and codebreakers, for lacking the
political savvy to provide the more detailed answer to Weldon in
first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you great confidence, doesn't it?'' said one senior
administration official, who complained that the NSA did not tell
other government agencies about the statement to Weldon.
</P>
<P>
   Weldon expressed exasperation Wednesday at the administration's
response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wasn't this information made available yesterday?'' Weldon
said in an interview. ``This is a joke.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
