<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYFIELD, WALTRIP AMONG RIVETING NASCAR TALES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two of the more compelling ``people stories'' in NASCAR Winston
Cup racing have roots in Owensboro, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   Which rates as the bigger tear-jerker?
</P>
<P>
   Points leader Jeremy Mayfield's breakthrough victory Sunday at
Pocono Raceway? Or the recent resurgence of three-time series
champion Darrell Waltrip?
</P>
<P>
   There is no wrong answer here, whether you live in Owensboro or
merely appreciate the latest twists of fate emanating from NASCAR's
50th anniversary season.
</P>
<P>
   En route to the first victory of his Winston Cup career,
Mayfield drove around his homegrown Owensboro hero, Waltrip, who
was leading the Pocono 500 with 21 laps remaining. Waltrip, who has
not won a Cup race since 1992, hung on for a proud sixth-place
finish after leading nine late laps.
</P>
<P>
   The sport's elder statesman at 51, Waltrip graciously joined
those congratulating Mayfield. Waltrip gave the 29-year-old
Mayfield his official blessing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel confident he'll be the Winston Cup champion this
year,'' Waltrip declared, a vote that should drive reigning
champion and Waltrip favorite Jeff Gordon to distraction. ``I'm
also going to pass the torch to Jeremy. He can carry the Owensboro
torch for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip has been hauling the torch since 1972, the second year
of NASCAR's ``modern era.'' His Cup championships in 1981, 1982 and
1985 and 84 career victories _ the most during the modern era and
tied for third all-time with Bobby Allison _ earned Waltrip a spot
among NASCAR's 50 greatest drivers this season.
</P>
<P>
   That honor was one of the few bright recent moments for Waltrip
until he opted to sell his struggling team to Texas businessman Tim
Beverley. The deal was announced during a double-barreled news
conference at Bristol Motor Speedway in March. In addition to the
sale of his Cup and NASCAR Craftsman Truck teams to Beverley,
Waltrip and seven-time Cup champion Dale Earnhardt spelled out
details of their relationship as teammates until the return of
injured rookie Steve Park in August.
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip said then that removing the burdens of ownership would
free him to drive the wheels off of Earnhardt's Chevrolet. It would
allow the new team assembled for Park to learn various tracks and
chassis setups from an experienced driver. And the downtime would
also allow the No. 17 team owned by Beverley to assemble personnel
while hunting for almighty sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of mounting criticism from fans and news media,
Waltrip promised a win-win-win scenario. And all parties have
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``My racing was terrible, and I knew it was terrible,'' said
Waltrip, who lost face with major sponsors Western Auto and Sears
DieHard in 1997. ``I felt defeated. I felt I was a loser. I came to
the conclusion the only way I could get out of this was to sell my
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see it work out and be the way I thought it would, it's
just great. Because when I walked in the door \Rat Earnhardt's
shop\S the first time, I was very skeptical what we could or could
not accomplish. I looked at it as a job. But it's been a great
relationship, a great opportunity to go out and do my thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Waltrip has recorded six top-20 finishes in the past seven races
_ not awesome, but decent. Before climbing into the No. 1 Pennzoil
Monte Carlo, Waltrip had not finished better than 30th in his
Chevys. He has moved from 40th in Cup points to 24th during that
span, silencing a number of skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   Or those whose memories date to about 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people don't appreciate what you've accomplished, or
don't know what you've accomplished _ and when people say or write
bad things about you _ it hurts,'' Waltrip said. ``I realize my
career is short. I don't have much time left. And I don't want to
live off of my past. I think I still bring an awful lot to the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   And as they say in Owensboro _ just bring it on.
THE BUZZ NASCAR
</P>
<P>
   First-time Winston Cup winner Jeremy Mayfield figures he will be
walking about a foot off the ground in the garage area at Sears
Point Raceway beginning tomorrow. ``It feels really nice walking
into the garage as the points leader, so I imagine it's going to
feel pretty good walking in as a race winner,'' said Mayfield, who
won the Pocono 500 and will be the prerace focus for the Save
Mart/Kragen 350K. ``People have been great. You wouldn't believe
the telephone calls and stuff we've gotten. The Pocono race ended
about 6:30 \REDT\S Sunday night and we got home \Rto Davidson,
N.C.\S about 12:30 that same night. There were 71 messages on the
answering machine at home _ 71 messages. We're not sure if we got
more, because I think the thing got filled up. The phone rang off
the hook Monday, people calling to congratulate us.'' ... Mayfield
said that before Sunday he was getting a little tired of reading
headlines proclaiming that he was the Cup points-leader, but had
yet to win a race. ``I wanted to do something so the story was
going to have to change,'' said Mayfield, who made his 125th career
start at Pocono. ``Then I had a newspaper guy joke after the race
Sunday that the headline was going to be, `When's Jeremy going to
win again?' '' ...
</P>
<P>
   Cup regular Ken Schrader has spent the week resting in the wake
of his crash in Turn 3 at Pocono, after he was tagged by Dale
Earnhardt. Schrader reported soreness in his neck and some bruising
of his arm. He has been fitted with an electro-therapy device that
minimizes pain. Meanwhile, car owner Andy Petree, who dissed
Earnhardt's post-wreck apology, has been forced to retire the No.
33 Skoal Bandit Chevy named ``Jesse James'' because of severe
left-side damage. ...
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Jet Motorsports and new team owner Tim Beverley are
scheduled to make their Cup debut this weekend at Sonoma, Calif.
Former NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series champion Ron Hornaday Jr., a
three-time winner in that series this year, will drive the No. 17
NAPA Auto Parts Monte Carlo. Hornaday will work with crew chief
Phil Hammer, formerly of Hendrick Motorsports. Meanwhile, the
team's No. 17 Chevy truck will again be driven by Toby Porter in
the DieHard 200 at The Milwaukee Mile on July 4. Porter finished
23rd in the truck during the Pronto Auto Parts 400K at Texas Motor
Speedway on June 5 in Fort Worth. ...
</P>
<P>
   Former Cup regular Robby Gordon is scheduled to drive the No. 96
Caterpillar Chevrolet owned by Buz McCall at Sears Point Raceway's
road course this weekend. ``I told the team to bring a few extra
sets of wheels, because I plan to drive them off the car,'' said
Gordon, who was a bust as a rookie Cup driver for Sabco Racing last
year. ...
</P>
<P>
   Sears Point Raceway, which like TMS is owned by Speedway
Motorsports Inc., has undergone a reconfiguration since last year.
The biggest change on the course is ``The Chute,'' an 890-foot,
high-speed straightaway that connects existing turns 4 and 7 on the
road course. The reconfiguration has trimmed the course length from
2.52 miles to 1.95. But it has also increased the lap-count from 74
to 112. The race distance, which had been 300 kilometers since its
inception in 1989, has increased to 350 kilometers. Speeds from 110
mph to 120 mph were recorded in ``The Chute'' during Cup testing
May 4-6.
CART
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Championship Auto Racing Teams stars launched a
three-day Goodyear tire test _ with an aerodynamic twist _
yesterday at Michigan Speedway. Newman/Haas Racing teammates
Michael Andretti and Christian Fittipaldi, Marlboro Team Penske's
Al Unser Jr. and Gil de Ferran of Walker Racing are scheduled to
test the new Hanford Device adopted by CART to help reduce the
speeds of its Champ Cars on superspeedways. Designed by Mark
Hanford of Swift Engineering, the device is a winglike aerodynamic
piece fitted to the rear of the car with the intention of creating
drag and reducing downforce. ``We feel that by slowing the cars
down a bit we increase safety, as well as enhance our drivers'
ability to race and race comfortably,'' said J. Kirk Russell,
CART's vice president of competition. The Hanford Device is
scheduled to be used for the first time during the U.S. 500 at the
2-mile Michigan track July 26. It will also be utilized in the
FedEx Championship Series season-ending Marlboro 500 at the
California Speedway on Nov. 1. Testing of the Hanford Device by
Unser and Bryan Herta at California this month resulted in a
reduction of 17 mph to 23 mph from the world-record 240.942-mph
qualifying lap rung up by Mauricio Gugelmin last year.
FAST LAPS Ray takes a `holiday'
</P>
<P>
   Direct from his runner-up finish at Texas Motor Speedway, Greg
Ray of Plano will attend the Pep Boys Indy Racing League's New
England 200 this weekend as a spectator.
</P>
<P>
   Ray and team owner Thomas Knapp, still without a full-time
primary sponsor, have opted to sit out Sunday's race on the
1.058-mile New Hampshire International Speedway in Loudon, N.H.
Ray's sponsorship deal with AT&AMP;T Wireless Services was only for the
True Value 500K night race June 6 in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Ray finished second to Billy Boat at TMS by 0.928-seconds, but
failed to cash in with a corporate backer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable with going to New Hampshire and not driving
right now because we're looking at the big picture _ to put myself
in position to win races and championships next year and the year
after that,'' said Ray, driver of the No. 97 Dallara/Aurora.
``There's a little bit of sacrifice. Because we had such a good run
at Fort Worth and such a good run at Indy \Rqualified No. 2
overall\S more people have taken notice.''
Nuts and bolts
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup points leader Jeremy Mayfield is the only driver to
finish in the top 25 in every race this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cup rookie Steve Park tested the No. 1 Pennzoil Chevy at
Greenville (S.C.) Pickens Speedway on Monday, 109 days after
suffering multiple injuries in a crash at Atlanta Motor Speedway.
Park plans to return to the series for the Brickyard 400 at
Indianapolis on Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Reigning Sports Car Club of America Trans-Am champion Tommy
Kendall is scheduled to drive the No. 46 First Union Chevy at Sears
Point this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell Wilson has been named vice president of racing
operations for Mattei Motorsports and driver Geoff Bodine.
</P>
<P>
   Indy Racing League rookie Jack Hewitt is scheduled to compete in
the IRL's New England 200 with PDM Racing this weekend. The team
skipped the True Value 500K in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone has won 19 of the past 20 Championship Auto Racing
Teams events, including eight consecutive.
</P>
<P>
   Top Fuel driver Larry Dixon will unveil new graphics on the
Miller Lite Dragster this weekend at the National Hot Rod
Association Sears Craftsman Nationals at Gateway International
Raceway in Madison, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Stevie Smith won the 30-lap main event Tuesday at the Oklahoma
City Fairgrounds Speedway, closing the gap on a tight Pennzoil
World of Outlaws points battle. It was Smith's series-leading
seventh victory of the year and second in five days.
Last words
</P>
<P>
   ``The FedEx Championship Series is not made for figure-eight
racing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Wally Dallenbach Sr. CART chief steward on the probation
handed to Greg Moore after a multicar, opening-lap crash at
Portland International Raceway.
</P>
</TEXT>
