<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REGENTS-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE OFFICIALS UNVEIL TOUGHER SCHOOL EXAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Offering the first glimpse into how dramatically they
plan to raise high school standards, state education officials
Wednesday made public new, harder exams in English and math being
phased in for all students.
</P>
<P>
   In English, the new exam, which students now in the 10th grade
and below must take beginning next June, replaces a three-hour
minimal skills test. It will take six hours and be administered
over two days, making it the longest and most comprehensive high
school English test requirement of any state in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never heard of one that long,'' said Chris Pipho, a
spokesman for the Education Commission of the States, a Denver
group that tracks academic trends. Most states that have competency
exams for graduation require one or two essays, Pipho said; the
test in Georgia, for instance, allots 75 minutes for a writing
test, while Ohio allots two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The tests are part of the state's effort to phase out the
minimal standards tests, called Regents Competency Tests, and
establish one bar for all. Students who do not pass the harder
tests, called regents exams, will still be able to get a
equivalency diploma by taking the less-stringent exams for a
general equivalency diploma.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not to be measured against some low average,'' said the
state's education commissioner, Richard Mills. ``New York, in every
field, plays against the world's best. I believe, and the regents
believe, that these are the basics.''
</P>
<P>
   The new English Regents exam will ask students to write three
comparative essays based on several passages of text, and one essay
based on two works of literature that they read in class or at
home. The test also contains multiple-choice questions testing
grammar, punctuation and vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   State education officials have also revamped the math regents
test, to be required for all public school students beginning with
this year's ninth graders, to include more advanced algebra and
geometry as well as some trigonometry.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, only those students bound for college take
college-preparatory regents examinations, and the state awards
regents diplomas to those who pass eight or more exams. Everyone
else can earn a local diploma by passing five Regents Competency
Tests.
</P>
<P>
   Under new rules passed by the Board of Regents last year, all
students will have to pass at least five regents exams, in English,
math, American history, global studies and science. The tests will
be phased in over the next five years, beginning with English in
June 1999. To pass, students will ultimately have to score at least
65 percent, but for the first four years, school districts can set
the passing grade at 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, officials at New York City public schools welcomed
the tougher tests, while some education advocates worried about the
lack of resources to train teachers to teach for the higher
standards. Last year, about two-thirds of the state's high school
students took the English Regents exam, and only 56 percent passed
with at least a 65 percent mark; 63 percent scored 55 percent or
above.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, when high school seniors in New York City
took a pilot exam, it became clear to city school officials that
many students, especially those with limited English skills, had
trouble writing the essays. All students who have been in a U.S.
school for at least three years will be required to pass the
English exam, though the state will offer the other tests in the
four most common languages spoken by immigrant students: Spanish,
Chinese, Russian and Haitian Creole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found out we have work to do, obviously,'' said Dr.
Margaret Harrington, chief executive of school programs and student
support services at the Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Starting this fall, Harrington said, the board will provide
funds to reduce class size in all 11th-grade English courses to 25
students; currently, she said, most high school classes have 34
students.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
