<SLUG> BC-GLOBE-COLUMNIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBE URGES RESCINDING OF COLUMNIST'S AWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston Globe editor Matthew V. Storin has asked the American
Society of Newspaper Editors to rescind its 1998 Distinguished
Writing Award to Globe columnist Patricia Smith, after she admitted
fabricating parts of her columns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although her entry of five columns in the ASNE Writing Awards
is apparently free of any fabrications, we feel that Ms. Smith's
admission of fabrications in other pieces makes reconsideration of
the ASNE award appropriate,'' Storin wrote in a letter to the
society dated Wednesday. ``While we recognize that the decision is
not ours to reverse, we urge the ASNE board to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   ASNE executive director Lee Stinnett said he had received
Storin's request and was polling the 20-member board about how to
respond. The voting is made more difficult by the fact that four of
the board members are in Europe, Stinnett said, ``but we're hoping
for an answer soon.''
</P>
<P>
   He said ASNE has not withdrawn any awards since it began
granting them in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Storin said Smith was notified of the Globe's action Wednesday
through her lawyer and agent, John ``Ike'' Williams, at the Boston
firm of Palmer &AMP; Dodge. Smith did not return a call to her home.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 43, had written a twice-weekly Metro column for the Globe
since 1994. She resigned at the Globe's request last Thursday,
after admitting that she had invented quotes and characters in four
columns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
