r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-USSOCCER-LADN     06-24 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-USSOCCER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PLAYS FOR PRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France --- They are playing exclusively for pride, but
that's not all on the minds of the United States' players as they
head into their final World Cup clash.
</P>
<P>
   As much as they declare otherwise, at least for the record, the
American camp is rocked with dissension over Steve Sampson's
personnel decisions and tactics, and it threatens to boil over
after tonight's finale against Yugoslavia at Stade de La Beaujoire.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the U.S. players apparently plan to voice their
dissatisfaction with Sampson and his decisions, which they blame
for the U.S. failure in the Cup, after the final whistle has blown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's ready to explode,'' defender Alexi Lalas told the
Washington Post. ``You can get ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The players evidently are angered over Sampson's lineup and
formation changes the past two months, which have sent several
veteran players --- including Lalas and Cerritos' Marcelo Balboa
--- to the bench; his fielding an inexperienced team in the 2-0
loss to Germany in the U.S. cup opener, then radically changing
players and tactics for the 2-1 loss Sunday to Iran; his decision
to drop captain John Harkes, a two-time World Cup veteran, from the
roster in April; and his criticism in the press of certain players,
primarily striker Eric Wynalda.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of dissension were sown two months ago with Harkes'
ouster and the switch to a 3-6-1 alignment using several
inexperienced players --- midfielders Frankie Hejduk, Chad Deering
and Brian Maisonneuve --- solely on the basis of a 3-0 rout of
Austria on April 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rather nave to think that a team that has gone through so
much together can basically be rearranged and be expected to play
with any consistency and cohesiveness,'' Lalas told the Post. ``It
just doesn't happen, especially in soccer. ... The reality is
consistency comes from playing under a system for an extended
period of time and understanding the role you play in that system.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this was the master plan, good god, it was pretty
masterful. (Sampson's) got a weird definition of a master plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda, the all-time U.S. scoring leader, was left on the bench
throughout the loss to Iran, then instructed by U.S. Soccer not to
speak to the media. He made his feelings known by slamming the door
to the ``mixed zone'' on his departure. Neither he nor Balboa would
talk to the media on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Soccer source told the Washington Post that Sampson
threatened, through assistant coaches, to send home Lalas, Wynalda,
Balboa and Ernie Stewart because of attitude problems following the
game against Germany. Of the quartet, only Stewart played against
Iran, as a second-half substitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players came here to play, they didn't come here to sit on the
bench,'' Sampson, who may be coaching his final U.S. game tonight,
said Wednesday when asked about the players' criticism. ``It's
normal for players that don't see playing time to voice their
frustration. My opinion is this: Players have to be mature and
professional ad they have a choice whether to be mature and
professional or not. I've always been professional with them. ... I
will never criticize my players to the press, never communicate to
my players through the press. I hope they have the same approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson did criticize Wynalda following the Germany match but
wouldn't provide his reasons for not including him in the Iran
game, even when the Americans were desperately seeking goals in the
final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The loss to Iran eliminated the United States from second-round
contention, but the players, for the most part, have decided to
hold their tongues until tonight's game is done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people have a lot of things to say once this
is over. I think I'll be one of those guys,'' said midfielder Tab
Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   One player was willing to lash out, but only under a veil of
anonymity, according to the Post. He said the U.S. squad's failure
had ``nothing to do with the ability of the players here. The team
lost chemistry months ago. The reason we're upset is we got
(Sampson) his job. He talks about trust and sacrifice ... and he's
taking credit for all the things we accomplished as a group. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we worked for, everything we accomplished, is
thrown away not because of talent but because he wanted it to be
his show.''
</P>
<P>
   SCOUTING REPORT
</P>
<P>
   Today: United States vs. Yugoslavia
</P>
<P>
   Site/kickoff: Stade de La Beaujoire (Nantes), noon PDT
</P>
<P>
   TV: Channel 7. Radio: None.
</P>
<P>
   Probable U.S. (0-2) lineup: Goalkeeper Brad Friedel; defenders
Thomas Dooley, Eddie Pope and David Regis; midfielders Chad
Deering, Brian Maisonneuve, Cobi Jones, Frankie Hejduk, Claudio
Reyna and Tab Ramos; forward Brian McBride.
</P>
<P>
   Probable Yugoslavia (1-0-1) lineup: Goalkeeper Ivica Kralj;
defenders Slobodan Komljenovic, Nisa Saveljic, Sinisa Mihajlovic
and Goran Djorovic; midfielders Vladimir Jugovic, Slavisa
Jokanovic, Dragan Stojkovic and Dejan Stankovic; forwards Predrag
Mijatovic and Savo Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. outlook: The Americans are playing for pride in what might
be Steve Sampson's final game as head coach, but with no chance to
reach the second round, they may find it tough to get emotionally
prepared for the match. ``Is it difficult? Yeah, it's difficult,
but we have to go on,'' says Ramos. ``This is the World Cup ---
this is something we've worked four years for. Hopefully we can
leave with a good showing.'' Sampson has offered no clues as to who
will start, except that Friedel will step in for Kasey Keller in
the nets, but the demeanor of Eric Wynalda, Alexi Lalas and Marcelo
Balboa following Wednesday's practice at La Beaujoire suggest
they'll remain on the bench. McBride, who has scored the Yanks'
only goal in the Cup, brings a solid air game, but the Yugos are
strong everywhere on the field, and the key to U.S. success is
whether Reyna and, probably, Ramos can connect with the other
attacking players.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia outlook: The Yugoslavs have been going through a bit
of an injury crisis, not that it matters all that much. There is so
much talent here --- more than any other World Cup team's --- that
plugging one player in for another is fairly simple. Five players
are sidelined, including two regulars, defenders Zoran Mirkovic and
Zeljko Petrovic. Dejan Savicevic, who hasn't yet seen action, is
still out with what it being called a knee injury, although there
is great speculation in the Yugoslav press as to what is really
wrong. They key figures are defender Sinisa Mihajlovic, the best
free-kick specialist in the tournament; midfielders Dragan
Stojkovic, the captain, and Vladimir Jugovic, a Cup MVP candidate;
and forward Predrag Mijatovic, one of the world's top strikers. A
victory will send Yugoslavia to the second round, and it would get
through with a loss as long as Germany tops Iran. The real battle
is for the group title, with the Yugoslavs even with the Germans on
points but trailing by a goal on differential.
</P>
<P>
   --- Scott French
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
