<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COLUMNIST'S APOLOGY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attempts at sarcasm and wit are a part of a sports columnist's
repertoire. Sometimes, they backfire loudly.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, a short wire story noted that a downhill
skateboarder preparing for the X Games in San Diego had been hit by
a dump truck. In full sarcastic mode, I wrote that I thought that
was one of the X Games' events.
</P>
<P>
   The wire story did not mention anyone being hurt. But it turns
out that Mark Golter, the 28-year-old skateboarder from Laguna
Beach, was seriously hurt. The dump truck that hit him rolled over
his right arm and hand, breaking his femur and severely damaging
all of the bones in his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Mark's mother, Lindsay Golter, said surgeons initially were
concerned that he might lose the use of his right hand. ``The
accident almost severed his hand,'' she said. ``But they were able
to reset the bones.''
</P>
<P>
   There are not enough words available to express my regret over
the flippant comment. I certainly would not have written it if I
had known someone had been hurt so severely.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the incident definitely draws more attention to
the nature of Mark Golter's sport and the way some people react.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Golter said her son was taking a practice run down
Soledad Canyon Drive. He was in the bike lane when a small truck
came up behind him, followed by a white dump truck.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the dump truck, she says, laid on his horn. Her
son grabbed the wheel well of his skateboard to slow down and
stayed in the bike lane.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the road expanded to two lanes, she said the driver
of the dump truck passed the other car on the right, swerved to get
in front of her son, and then hit his brakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark hit the center divide of the street, flipped over and his
arm was ran over by the truck,'' she said. ``He got up right away,
but with his arm just hanging there.''
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the dump truck never stopped. The San Diego police
are still looking for him. If he is caught, he will face charges of
assault with a deadly weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how people think about skateboards,'' said Lindsay
Golter. ``I've been dealing with it since the day he started. It is
what it is, an extreme sport. But my son wears the best gear there
is to protect himself and always is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son has spoken to the Laguna Beach City Council in support
of the city building a skateboard park to accommodate the sport and
its athletes, and take some elements of it off city streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this will make people think twice the next time they see
someone on a skateboard,'' said Ms. Golter.
</P>
<P>
   I know one person who will. My deepest apology goes out to Mark
Golter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0521 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5565 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-CHILE-LADN     06-24 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-CHILE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING LIKE CHILE RECEPTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BENNETT J. MINTZ  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FUTALEUFU, Chile _ The Montero was loaded down with two
fly-fishermen and their gear _ enough rods and reels to target the
trout they had long envisioned finning at the end of the earth in
Patagonia.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Carlos was at the wheel, careful to get his passengers,
their luggage and supplies from town to the fishing lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Juan Carlos the driver is like calling the Taj Mahal a
building. Juan Carlos is the John Elway of the blacktop. The road
from Futaleufu is jokingly called the Evel Knievel Memorial
Highway. About three-fourths of the way to camp it is so dangerous
that passengers are required to get out and walk around paso
suicida for about 50 yards.
</P>
<P>
   We already had flown from Los Angeles and Chile's Santiago and
Puerto Montt. Navigating a few more narrows along the ``highway''
seemed a minor hardship considering how far we had come and the
proximity of our goal _ the Futaleufu River.
</P>
<P>
   The Futaleufu begins in Argentina as the Rio Grande and comes
out of a huge dam not far from the Chilean border. It travels in a
southerly direction until it rolls into the Pacific a few hundred
miles away. There are sea trout and chinook and coho salmon in the
lower end. But it was the rainbow and brown trout in a 20-mile
mountainous stretch that we had come to tackle.
</P>
<P>
   After checking into the Futaleufu Lodge, Juan Carlos backed the
trailer and the rubber raft it carried down the launching ramp. He
called it a ramp. I called it a small cliff.
</P>
<P>
   We swung the craft into the current and began casting our 5- and
6-weight fly rods to some of the clearest water we'd ever seen. We
would hold the boat 30 feet or so from the bank and flip our flies
under the trees; other times we'd toss them into the many riffles
and runs. For bait we used a size No.10 grasshopper with green
beadhead caddis larvae on a dropper or a beetle pattern or
sometimes size 18 flying black ants.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the grasshopper would disappear in a silvery swirl
and the fight would begin. ``Keep his head up,'' cautioned our
host, Juan Carlos. ``Don't let him get into that fast water.''
</P>
<P>
   The trout ran from a foot to 25 inches. Most were in the 15- to
17-inch slot, brilliantly colored and tremendous fighters. It takes
good eyes, sunglasses that cut through the water's glare and
unwavering attention to the fly to hook them with any degree of
regularity.
</P>
<P>
   During their stay at the lodge, anglers explore different
sections of the river each day. If one is to float from the
Argentina border, he or she must drive that awful road back into
town, then another five miles to the so-called boat ramp. Other
destinations are accessed by horseback. One trip takes you down
river through neighboring ranches to a swinging suspension bridge
with rusted cables that is a symbol of ``the Futa.''
</P>
<P>
   I was in the boat's bow seat when Matt Henderson _ who guides
anglers out of Missoula, Montana, by summer and Chile by winter _
spotted a fat fish flush against a rock outcropping.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll only get one shot at that baby, so make it good,''
Henderson whispered. I cast a grasshopper imitation 45 feet and was
rewarded with a drag-free drift that enabled the fly pattern to
make a natural-looking run downstream. The big rainbow gulped down
the 'hopper without hesitation. It looked like an 18-inch trout,
but when it took off downstream I knew it was bigger.
</P>
<P>
   We headed into a cove and soon the brute came to the net. It was
my first 20-inch fish of the journey. Later that afternoon, I cast
to a much larger trout that again took a grasshopper, bolted
through a tangle of roots and fortunately headed for open river. It
was 25-inches _ Henderson's largest client-caught rainbow of the
season _ and made both of our days.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it was the talk of the lodge.
</P>
<P>
   Futaleufu Lodge is nestled along the Andes in Chile's Region Los
Lagos, some 750 miles south of Santiago and 20 miles southwest of
Esquel, Argentina. Operators Jim and Sonia Repine come from a
background as diverse as the lakes, rivers and volcanoes that dot
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Jim is from Richmond, Va., with stops in the Marine Corps and in
Alaska for 20 years as a fishing guide, author, outfitter and
outdoors television-show host. Sonia is the widow of a Chilean Air
Force jet pilot.
</P>
<P>
   They've had the ``lodge'' about eight years. It is really a
compound consisting of a main house, stables, various buildings
containing laundry and other services, staff housing and equipment
sheds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I searched most of the trout world for the perfect location,
from Alaska to Tierra del Fuego, and when I got to the Futa, I
stopped. This is it,'' bragged Jim Repine.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't wrong.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Futaleufu Lodge, write to the
proprietors at Casilla 1238, Vina del Mar, Chile, phone or fax them
at 011-56-32-812-659 or inquire with a travel agent who specializes
in fishing trips.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
