<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHINA-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DEMOCRATS IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 25:
</P>
<P>
   We would feel more confident about the lasting value of
President Clinton's trip to China, which begins Thursday, if we
knew that someone had included among his briefing papers a summary
of Ronald Reagan's extraordinary visit to the Soviet Union in 1988.
Reagan used that trip to meet with prominent dissidents and speak
directly to Soviet audiences about fundamental freedoms and the
advantages of democracy, and there was little that his host,
Mikhail Gorbachev, could do about it but grumble. Reagan knew that
one of the important powers of a traveling president is the right
to speak plainly in lands unaccustomed to open debate. Bill Clinton
has the same luxury. The cause of human rights will be poorer if he
squanders it.
</P>
<P>
   His aides have said he will address the issue in some way, and
there is no shortage of promising venues. His itinerary includes a
small village that has just conducted its first open election, an
ecumenical church and a classroom at Beijing University. But there
is one obvious setting in which Clinton can seize the moment,
politely but firmly, to assert American values. That is Tiananmen
Square, which he will visit Saturday, and where hundreds of
peaceful pro-democracy demonstrators were slaughtered on June 4,
1989.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese, of course, prefer to see Clinton's visit to
Tiananmen Square not as a reminder of that tragedy but as a form of
closure, a way of saying farewell to a relationship strained by
that memory and moving quickly to the ``constructive strategic
partnership'' celebrated in last fall's meeting in Washington
between Clinton and China's president, Jiang Zemin. But why accept
Beijing's definition of what the Tiananmen visit means? More than
700 people were arrested there nine years ago, and many are still
in prison. Clinton can honor their memory by describing their
sacrifice as a reminder of how much further China and its leaders
must travel.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the points the president's Republican critics
have been trying to make on Capitol Hill. On Tuesday they tried
unsuccessfully to ram through a series of amendments that, among
other things, would have denied visas to Chinese officials involved
in religious persecution or forced abortions, and put new
restrictions on some forms of economic aid to Beijing. Senate
Democrats said the entire exercise was an attempt to embarrass the
president. ``I'm not going to allow one single vote on China this
week,'' said Sen. Thomas Daschle, the Democratic leader. But there
are also plenty of liberal Democrats who believe that in pursuing
his policy of engagement Clinton has looked squishy on human
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Of course China cannot be viewed through a single lens, and of
course there will be other important issues on the president's
agenda in the next nine days. But the Chinese leadership has
already profited greatly from his visit. His very presence is an
affirmation of Beijing's growing power. The Chinese are certainly
strong enough to hear straight talk on American values and a
presidential statement of solidarity with the democrats in Chinese
society. A show of presidential will would not disrupt the trip. It
might even make it memorable. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
