<HEADER>
A5567 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMITHBARNEY-DISCRIMIN     06-24 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITHBARNEY-DISCRIMINATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE REJECTS PROPOSED PACT IN SEX HARASSMENT CASE
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal court judge in Manhattan unexpectedly
rejected a proposed settlement of a sex discrimination case against
Smith Barney Inc. Wednesday, criticizing it for vagueness and
questioning whether it would have sufficient financial backing.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Judge Constance Baker Motley does not mean Smith
Barney and the female plaintiffs in the case must start over, and
both sides said they thought the judge's criticisms could be
swiftly addressed. But the proposed settlement, which had been
agreed to by lawyers for both sides after several months of
negotiation, had been widely expected to win the court's approval.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark case, brought by 23 past and present female
employees of Smith Barney as a class-action suit on behalf of
thousands of current and former women employees of the big
brokerage firm, had shone a rare light on some of the seamier
aspects of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which had attracted considerable media attention,
detailed male brokerage executives' frequent discrimination against
female employees, and several instances of sexual harassment
including an infamous ``boom boom room'' at Smith Barney's office
in Garden City, N.Y., where carousing male bosses would grope and
harass their female subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   In a 48-page ruling filed in Federal District Court in Manhattan
Wednesday, Motley declined to approve the proposed settlement,
saying that it ``leaves unclear both what new programs it will fund
and to what extent existing Smith Barney expenditures can qualify
under the vague definition of `diversity-related expenditure.'''
She said, ``The proposed programs are nowhere delineated or
defined.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Motley wrote, ``It is possible to envision that $15
million over four years for a company as large as Smith Barney is
grossly inadequate if personnel training, for example, is
included.'' The judge also criticized the settlement because it did
not allow for continued court oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Both lawyers for Smith Barney and for the plaintiffs sought
Wednesday to play down the rejection, calling it a setback that
could be addressed quickly. They maintained that they would now
work together to adjust the proposed settlement to address Judge
Motley's concerns. Smith Barney Inc. is now Salomon Smith Barney,
the brokerage subsidiary of the Travelers Group. Travelers itself
is now merging with Citicorp to form Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working with the Smith Barney lawyers'' on modifying
the settlement, said Mary Stowell of Stowell &AMP; Friedman, the
Chicago law firm that represented the plaintiffs. After further
work, the two sides intend to submit some suggested modifications
``perhaps as early as next week,'' she said. ``We are hopeful that
we will be able to address the court's concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Belnick, a partner at Paul Weiss Rifkind Wharton &AMP; Garrison
and lead counsel for Smith Barney, said Wednesday that although
``all of us would have preferred final approval at this time it is
nonetheless heartening that the court has approved all the core
provisions of this settlement relating to the dispute resolution
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Belnick added: ``Smith Barney and class counsel intend to submit
to the court as quickly as possible an amendment which responds to
the one specific concern the court raised _ which all of us take
very seriously _ regarding the specifics of the diversity programs
on which Smith Barney will spend its $15 million. On the basis of
that submission, Smith Barney and class counsel hope to secure the
approval of the court.''
</P>
<P>
   In a memo distributed Wednesday to all employees at Salomon
Smith Barney, John Donelly, the brokerage firm's head of human
resources, played down the court's rejection. The memo, entitled
`Proposed settlement still awaiting final approval,' characterized
the judge's ruling as a ``temporary setback,'' and said that the
firm was pleased that the court had ``endorsed all features of the
settlement relating to establishment of a dispute resolution
process for handling all gender based and other employment
claims.'' The court's primary concern, the memo said, ``related to
the lack of specificity of the diversity programs which Salomon
Smith Barney has committed to create and fund prospectively.'' The
firm, the memo said, remained hopeful that its ``proposed amendment
will lead to final approval.''
</P>
<P>
   In their response to the judge's rejection of the proposed
settlement, the plaintiffs and Smith Barney were expected to allow
for continued court oversight of the proposed settlement, and to
offer more specific information about the diversity programs that
Smith Barney plans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
