<HEADER>
A5568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANTAVIRUS-420&AMP;ADD-NY     06-24 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANTAVIRUS-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETHAL VIRUS BORNE BY MICE MAKES RETURN IN THE WEST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., N.M., Ariz.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOLCOTT, Colo. _ Carried by a surging population of deer mice,
hantavirus has returned to the Southwest this spring, killing a boy
and a woman in Colorado and a man in New Mexico. Nonfatal cases
have been recorded in Arizona, New Mexico and, on Tuesday, this
western Colorado town.
</P>
<P>
   For Colorado and New Mexico, the hantavirus deaths are the first
since an outbreak receded in the mid-1990s. The mouse-borne virus,
which can kill swiftly, claimed this year's three fatal victims
within hours of hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can go from mildly ill to fatally ill in a couple of
hours,'' John Pape, an epidemiologist with the Colorado health
department, said from the town of Durango, where he was
investigating the death last week of Cheri Newbold, a mother of
three. ``It is a nasty virus and can hit people pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   With revived memories of the earlier outbreak, which killed 15
people in the Four Corners area of Colorado and New Mexico in 1993,
residents of southwestern Colorado have started buying cats to kill
mice and work masks to filter out dust contaminated by deer-mouse
droppings and urine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't keep cats in here,'' said Jackie Lee, director of the
La Plata County Humane Society Animal Shelter in Durango. ``People
come in to adopt because they are afraid of hantavirus. We had a
cattery that was 100 percent full, and now we don't have any.''
</P>
<P>
   At a hardware store nearby, disposable masks are selling at a
brisk pace. ``People come in,'' said Joel Krueger, the manager,
``and ask if we have anything for cleaning up mouse areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The hantavirus _ so called because a strain of it infected about
3,000 U.S. soldiers along the Hantaan River during the Korean War _
has probably killed people in the American West for centuries. But
it was not identified until 1993, after the mysterious outbreak had
started taking lives on the Navajo Reservation. By studying old
blood samples, scientists identified cases in the region dating
from 1959.
</P>
<P>
   As in the outbreak five years ago, the culprit now appears to be
El Nino. A mild, wet winter has given an enormous boost to the deer
mouse, a brown rodent with a white belly that was already
considered North America's most common mammal. (America's common
gray ``house mouse'' does not appear to carry the virus.) The warm,
moist weather provided extra plant cover for mouse shelter, and
extra fruits, seeds and insects for mouse nourishment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mouse monitoring sites, set up in Arizona, New Mexico and
Colorado after the 1993 outbreak, indicate that the deer-mouse
populations this spring are as much as 20 times those of a year
ago. A trap left for three days in Mesa County, west of here,
captured 59 deer mice in late May. One year ago a trap at the same
site captured only eight.
</P>
<P>
   In years when the number of deer mice per acre drops below one,
hantavirus infects about 10 to 15 percent of them. This spring,
with as many as 10 mice per acre, infection rates can hit 40
percent. Male mice seem to spread the virus, which does them no
harm, by fighting over food and females, inflicting wounds on one
another, said Dr. Brian Hjelle, associate professor of pathology at
the University of New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Hjelle said the mice might also transmit the virus among
themselves through sex, by walking in infected droppings or by
urinating on one another. A team led by him is using a $1.35
million grant from the National Institutes of Health to study the
mice's transmission methods and to search for a vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Although deer mice are found across the country, 95 percent of
the 185 hantavirus cases identified in the United States, dating
from 1959, have occurred west of the Mississippi. Scientists do not
know why.
</P>
<P>
   Humans contract the virus by inhaling dust contaminated by mouse
droppings or urine. There are no known cases of transmission
between humans in the United States, although a different
hantavirus strain was transmitted from person to person in
Argentina two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   With 75 percent of hantavirus cases occurring in the rural West,
towns like this one are getting the word out through posters and
fliers.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that mice can wriggle through openings the size of a
button, health officials urge rural residents to seal their houses
by plugging holes and girdling foundations with metal flashing.
When people open barns, trailers or cabins for spring cleaning,
they should leave doors and windows open for 30 minutes before they
enter to work, to insure good ventilation. Masks should be worn
when mouse-infested areas are swept, and campers should use tents
with floors and not pitch tents in areas with mouse burrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are living in a rural area of the western U.S.,'' said
Pape of the Colorado health department, ``you are always going to
be at risk of hantavirus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
