<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-TCI DEAL TO ALTER COMMUNICATIONS INDUSTRY
</P>
<P>
   The telephone giant AT&AMP;T has agreed to acquire
Tele-Communications Inc., the No. 2 cable television provider, for
$31.8 billion in stock in a deal that is the most ambitious product
yet of Congress' 1996 deregulation of the telecommunications
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will probably change the way consumers buy and use
communications services. The companies said they wanted to jointly
market each other's services as soon as possible after the deal
closed.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT HELPED BY RULING
</P>
<P>
   Although the Justice Department and 20 states suing Microsoft
say the federal appeals court ruling in the company's favor is only
a minor bump in their broader antitrust case, legal experts called
the decision a big victory for the leading software maker.
Microsoft's stock surged a second day to a record in the aftermath
of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 officially went on sale Thursday, minus the hype and
publicity Microsoft used to promote Windows 95 when it introduced
the personal-computer operating software three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   GM CALLS FOR EXPEDITED ARBITRATION
</P>
<P>
   General Motors called the two strikes against its car and truck
production illegal and said it would seek to take the United
Automobile Workers to expedited arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO kicked off a campaign to highlight labor's argument
that the right of workers to join unions is being unfairly undercut
by fierce employer hostility and by laws that labor leaders say do
little to protect workers seeking to unionize.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE REJECTS PROPOSED SETTLEMENT
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge unexpectedly rejected a proposed settlement of a
sex discrimination case against Smith Barney, &UR;  &LR;  criticizing it for
vagueness and questioning whether it would have sufficient
financial backing.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. TO PUT PATENT DATA ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is expected to announce that it will
make the database of the United States' patents since 1976 and
trademark text and images starting from the late 1800s available on
the World Wide Web beginning in August.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS RALLY ON AT&AMP;T MERGER NEWS
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index soared 13.39 points, to a
record 1,132.88. The increase came as the stock market rose sharply
on demand for shares in telecommunications-equipment makers and
cable companies as a result of AT&AMP;T's announcement that it would
buy Tele-Communications Inc. The Dow climbed 95.41 points, to
8,923.87, and the Nasdaq composite index rose 33.19, to 1,877.76.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year Treasury bond fell, but its yield rose to 5.66
percent, from 5.64 percent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   DURABLE-GOODS ORDERS FELL IN MAY
</P>
<P>
   Orders for durable goods fell 2.6 percent, to $184.305 billion,
in May as the economic crisis in Asia reduced orders for
transportation- and electronics-related goods.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE APPROVES TAX-BREAK BILL
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved a bill that would provide tax breaks for
parents who save for education costs, including private school
tuition. President Clinton has said he will veto the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   LIZ CLAIBORNE WINS TRADEMARK CASE
</P>
<P>
   Liz Claiborne won a trademark-infringement case against
Mademoiselle Knitwear, a New York sweater factory involved in a
tangle of litigation with the clothing maker and Unite, the garment
workers' union.
</P>
<P>
   A MOBILE-PHONE SOFTWARE VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   A British palmtop-computer company, Psion, is forming a venture
with Motorola, Nokia of Finland, and Ericsson of Sweden to develop
software for mobile phones that behave more like computers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
