<SLUG> BC-SILVER-PLAYWRIGHT-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOONY LANDMARK THAT INSPIRED A SEVENTH-GRADER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By NICKY SILVER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dinosaurs, creeping walls of ice, hunger, wars _ these are among
the ingredients of the play ``The Skin of Our Teeth,'' Thornton
Wilder's condensed (three acts) history of the human race. Wilder
had already won a Pulitzer Prize for ``Our Town,'' when, five years
later, in 1943, he won again for ``The Skin of Our Teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   His main characters, Mr. and Mrs. George Antrobus of Excelsior,
N.J., their two children, Gladys and Henry, and the family maid,
Sabina, live in a surreal place, a combination commuters' suburb
and prehistoric wasteland. Survival is paramount.
</P>
<P>
   The initial production, directed by Elia Kazan, opened on
Broadway in 1942 starring Fredric March and Florence Eldridge as
the parents and Tallulah Bankhead as Sabina, with Montgomery Clift
as Henry.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, the New York Shakespeare Festival opens its
43rd season of theater in Central Park with a revival of the play
at the Delacorte Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes John Goodman as Antrobus, Frances Conroy as
his wife and Kristen Johnston as Sabina, under the direction of
Irene Lewis, the artistic chief of the Center Stage in Baltimore.
The set designer is John Conklin.
</P>
<P>
   In a preface to a collection of his plays, Wilder said about
this one:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was wrtten on the eve of our entrance into the war and
under strong emotion and I think it mostly comes alive under
conditions of crisis. It has been often charged with being a
bookish fantasia about history, full of rather bloodless
schoolmasterish jokes. But to have seen it in Germany soon after
the war, in the shattered churches and beer halls that were serving
as theaters ... was an experience that was not so cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The play, he noted, ``is deeply indebted to James Joyce's
`Finnegans Wake.' I should be very happy if, in the future, some
author should feel similarly indebted to any work of mine.
Literature has always more resembled a torch race than a furious
dispute among heirs.''
</P>
<P>
   In this essay, the playwright Nicky Silver, author of ``Raised
in Captivity,'' ``The Food Chain'' and ``The Maiden's Prayer,''
among others, talks about Wilder's effect on his own writing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I am occasionally asked what writers have influenced my work.
This happens most frequently on foreign soil, when I've dragged
myself over an ocean and am groggy with jet lag. Desperate for
sleep, I answer by rote. I say Joe Orton, John Guare, Chris Durang
and Stephen Sondheim, whom I consider a playwright who happens to
rhyme a lot. Were I really thinking, I'd have to include Thornton
Wilder, whose play ``The Skin of Our Teeth'' woke me up from a
dreary adolescence of ``Arsenic and Old Lace.''
</P>
<P>
   While I've seldom thought about Wilder's loony epic, its
influence has been profound on me. You see, my play
``Pterodactyls'' was called the flip side of ``The Skin of Our
Teeth'' by the critic from this very paper _ and for obvious
reasons. While both plays feature ice ages and dinosaurs, mine is,
frankly, a cautionary tale, while Wilder's masterwork is a love
letter to the human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   I guess he hasn't made my list because I never cared for ``Our
Town,'' a lovely play soured forever, for me, by the fact that I
was not cast in my summer camp production (Mark Segal got the part
I wanted) and when, as a child, I saw the film of ``The
Matchmaker,'' it upset me to see Hazel in those period costumes.
I've been unfair.
</P>
<P>
   I read ``The Skin of Our Teeth'' when I was in the seventh
grade. I checked an anthology out from my junior high school
library (I don't think I ever returned it, oops), one of those
massive hardback volumes containing musty ``important'' works. I
tried to struggle through ``The Wild Duck'' and ``The Voice of the
Turtle'' but gave up midway and returned to ``Dark Shadows'' on
television.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Then I read ``The Skin of Our Teeth'' in one sitting, smiling
the whole time. And the reason was simple: it's a riot! Wilder's
play chronicles the adventures of an archetypal family struggling
to be virtuous as they face the Ice Age, the Great Flood and the
destruction of war. I had not yet, at that young age, ever read a
play that so blithely combined broad comedy and big ideas. I had
not read a play in which the characters addressed the audience to
complain about the material. And I had certainly not read a play
that featured quotes by Plato and Spinoza as well as talking
dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if I understood what I was reading, but I knew what
made, and still makes, me laugh. Early in Act I, Sabina, the maid,
is forced to stall alone on stage as another character is late for
an entrance. Rather than improvise, she complains:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't invent any words for this play, and I'm glad I can't.
I hate this play and every word in it. As for me, I don't
understand a single word of it anyway _ all about the troubles the
human race has gone through, there's a subject for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly I wasn't reading a play about a family, set in a living
room. I was reading a play about actors set on a stage. This
predates my studying at the Experimental Theater Wing at NYU, where
I learned the phrase ``site-specific,'' meaning a play set in a
bathroom, performed in a bathroom. And while, ultimately, Orton may
have spoken more clearly to me, his jaundiced view of mankind
matching mine more closely, Wilder was where I first saw politics
mixed so adroitly with jokes.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't yet read Guare or Durang. So it was surprising to me
that venomously funny repartee could be juxtaposed with serious and
emotional politics. But there they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children are a thing only a parent can stand'' in the same
play with ``You and I want the same thing; but until you think of
it as something that everyone has a right to, you are my deadly
enemy and I will destroy you.'' I don't know, I wasn't born, but I
can only imagine that this was stylistically shocking in its day. I
base this conclusion on the fact that it's stylistically shocking
now.
</P>
<P>
   And ``The Skin of Our Teeth'' offers no simplistic solutions.
Evil, in the personification of the Antrobus son, Henry, evolves
from a happy family struggling nobly to continue. There is no
explanation for why he goes astray while his sister, Gladys, does
not (although she does wear red stockings in the second act, a
fashion faux pas so severe, her mother feels it borders on evil).
No. Wilder is saying that the world is complicated, scary and
beyond our understanding. But he also sees mankind's honor. He sees
us as a species in love with life and infatuated with hope. These
were important messages at the height of World War II. Everyone saw
the world as treacherous _ the enemy was at the door and America
was frightened of tomorrow. We needed to hear Sabina tell us that
the archetypal characters will prevail, as she does at the end:
</P>
<P>
   ``The end of this play isn't written yet. Mr. and Mrs. Antrobus!
Their heads are full of plans and they're confident as the first
day they began __ ''
</P>
<P>
   Who wouldn't leave the theater feeling good about themselves and
tomorrow? Who doesn't enjoy being congratulated on their strength
and dignity?
</P>
<P>
   But we live in a different era now and everything is wonderful.
Or so we like to believe. With no obvious enemies, we drive through
life, enjoying the sunny view. The predators are hidden; they're
subtler and we don't see them. While ``The Skin of Our Teeth''
offers us hope for better times, we're busy wallowing in the good
times of today. Frankly, I'm not so sure the time is right for a
``love letter to the human spirit.'' But hell, the time is always
right for a good laugh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
