<HEADER>
A5579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CONSTITUTION-NYT     06-24 0300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CONSTITUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AMENDMENT FEVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, June 25:
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution is the nation's bedrock charter, and lawmakers
sworn to uphold it should resist the temptation to push for
pandering amendments every time an election year rolls around. But
such resistance requires more principle and self-restraint than the
Senate Judiciary Committee seems able to muster.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, by a mostly party-line vote, the committee approved
narrowing the Bill of Rights to combat the rare instance of flag
desecration. In doing so, the committee blessed what would be the
first exemption ever to the constitutional guarantee of freedom of
speech. The committee's Democrats, with the glaring exception of
Sen. Dianne Feinstein of California, tried to stop this repressive
move but failed. Few politicians want to risk being seen as voting
against the Stars and Stripes. But poking a hole in the First
Amendment to punish people who burn or otherwise physically abuse a
flag in the exercise of their free-speech rights is an act of
desecration, not patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday the committee will take up the so-called victims'
rights amendment allowing victims to participate in criminal
proceedings. No one disagrees that victims of crime deserve
sympathy and respectful treatment. But state legislatures and
courts are already experimenting with ways to inject greater
sensitivity for victims into the justice system without tampering
with defendants' rights or inadvertently harming prosecutions, as
the lengthy, complex amendment is destined to do.
</P>
<P>
   In little more than a week, the nation will mark another
Independence Day. Messing with the Constitution is no way to
celebrate. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
