<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)   Lam Firing Up to 25% Of Staff  
   
 By Julia Angwin  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
In yet another sign of troubles in the computer chip industry, Lam
Research of Fremont said yesterday that it will lay off 20 to 25
percent of its workforce.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lam said it will trim 1,000 to 1,200 workers _ in its second
round of layoffs this year _ mainly because of slowing sales and
financial turmoil in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, chip equipment sales are slow in the summer, said
Lam chief executive Jim Bagley. But, he said, ``the situation today
is a dramatic slowdown ... with no improvements likely for fall
quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   The company refused to say where the layoffs would occur, but
the Bay Area is home to almost three-quarters of the firm's 4,400
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Lam said it will take a charge of up to $65 million related to
the restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   The company also expects to report a fourth-quarter loss of 5
cents a share before the restructuring charge, in line with
analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Lam's troubles are only the latest ripples in the wave of bad
news that hit the chip sector, which is in its third consecutive
year of slowing growth.
</P>
<P>
   Lam's biggest rival, Applied Materials of Santa Clara, shed 15
percent of its workforce last month.
</P>
<P>
   And Bay Area chipmakers Intel, National Semiconductor and
Cypress Semiconductor all have announced significant job reductions
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a sign of the times,'' said Mark FitzGerald,
semiconductor analyst at Merrill Lynch in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Like those companies, Lam blames the cuts on slowing PC sales,
an oversupply of computer memory and the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Lam said it expects chip companies to spend 30 percent less this
year on chip equipment than they did last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on this view of the industry, we have made the decision
to realign the company's cost structure,'' said Bagley, Lam's CEO.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say Lam has internal problems, too. It is in the
midst of a turnaround after several years of losing market share to
Applied Materials and a Japanese firm called TEL.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Lam laid off 700 workers worldwide because of
similar problems _ a dramatic slowdown in the chip industry, and
its attempt to turn the company around.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Lam officials told analysts that they are likely to
shut down the Chemical Vapor Deposition division _ an area Lam had
unsuccessfully sought to penetrate for a few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been struggling for a while,'' said Gus Richard,
semiconductor analyst at Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in San Francisco. ``Now,
they're going to shut it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the troubles in the chip equipment industry,
however, Richard said he thinks that the industry soon may rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is going through what I consider to be the bottom
of a cycle,'' Richard said. ``I don't believe it's going to get
much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made after the market closed. Lam shares
closed at $22.06 yesterday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
