<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Insurers Can't Use ZIP Codes To Gauge Rates   By Arthur M. Louis  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
A superior court judge ruled yesterday that the state's automobile
insurers cannot use ZIP codes as a major factor to determine
premium rates.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge Henry E. Needham Jr. of Alameda County reversed a policy
adopted last March by state Insurance Commissioner Chuck
Quackenbush. The policy had been appealed by San Francisco,
Oakland, Los Angeles and various consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   The cities and consumer groups argued that the use of ZIP codes
violated Proposition 103. They said Quackenbush allowed insurers to
discriminate against drivers in the inner cities, where premiums
tend to be highest.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance Department spokeswoman Dana Spurrier said the
department won't comment on yesterday's ruling ``until we have
thoroughly reviewed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal sources said the department has several weeks to consider
an appeal and that the ruling won't take effect before then.
</P>
<P>
   If the ruling goes unchallenged, inner-city auto-insurance rates
likely would come down while those who live in the suburbs would
see their rates rise.
</P>
<P>
   The judge agreed with the plaintiffs that Quackenbush
circumvented Proposition 103, which mandates that auto rates be
based primarily on three factors: a driver's safety record, miles
driven annually and years of driving experience.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush, citing an opinion by an administrative law judge
within the Insurance Department, had provided the insurers with a
loophole.
</P>
<P>
   He permitted the insurers to use other factors in determining
rates as long as the average weighting for the other factors was
less than the weighting for any of the three Prop. 103 criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Public Advocates, one of the groups that appealed Quackenbush's
decision, pointed out that the policy allowed the insurers to give
geography the greatest weight of all.
</P>
<P>
   They could do this by introducing numerous other criteria.
Although the average weight for these criteria might be low,
certain criteria could have substantial weight.
</P>
<P>
   Public Advocates pointed to a filing by Allstate, the
second-largest auto insurer in California. The firm gave driver
safety a 20.65 percent weighting, but geography had a 34.6 percent
weighting.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies say they need to use geography in setting
rates because there are many more auto thefts in some parts of the
state than in others. They also note that medical costs and costs
of auto repairs are exceptionally high in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco city attorney Louise Renne was pleased with the
ruling. ``The insurance companies set rates that are
discriminatory,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
