r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOORE-SFCHRON &LR;      06-24 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOORE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Silicon Valley's Word Wizard   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Chasms, tornadoes and gorillas may sound like good subjects for
National Geographic specials. But they're also terms used to
describe marketing strategies for technology companies.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man who popularized this decidedly nontech vocabulary is
Geoffrey Moore, a 51-year-old author/consultant who is emerging as
the heir-apparent to Silicon Valley's pioneer marketing guru, Regis
McKenna.
</P>
<P>
   In three best-selling books _ ``Crossing the Chasm,'' ``Inside
the Tornado'' and ``The Gorilla Game,'' Moore has used catchy
metaphors to describe the life cycles of companies and markets in
the turbulent world of high tech.
</P>
<P>
   According to (Geoffrey) Moore's law, a chasm is the gulf that
must be crossed as a company goes from a small market of customers
who embrace new technology to the larger mainstream market.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado is a ``hypergrowth'' market that many companies
encounter once they cross the chasm.
</P>
<P>
   The gorilla is the company that dominates a technology, such as
Microsoft, Intel and Cisco. They are the equivalent of the
600-pound gorilla that sleeps any where it wants to, Moore says.
Everybody else in the sector is either a monkey, trying to copy the
gorilla, or a chimp pushing a different kind of technology.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Moore cites the semiconductor industry, where
Intel is the gorilla with its Pentium chips. Motorola and Digital
Equipment Corp., which have chips based on alternative technology,
are the chimps, while AMD and Cyrix, with their Pentium clones, are
the monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   Like Moore's previous efforts, ``The Gorilla Game'' is riding
high on business best-seller lists. Published in March, it was
third on the Business Week list this month.
</P>
<P>
   But while the first two books focused on marketing strategies,
``The Gorilla Game'' examines the way technology companies perform
in the stock market _ and how investors can spot the hottest
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Moore enlisted two co-authors who provided investment expertise
to go with his marketing acumen _ Tom Kippula, a partner in Moore's
consulting firm, the Chasm Group; and Paul Johnson, managing
director of equity research at BancAmerica Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   The result of their collaboration is a common-sense primer with
straightforward advice:
</P>
<P>
   _Find markets making a transition into hypergrowth.
</P>
<P>
   _Buy a basket of stocks that represents all the companies that
have a clear shot at being the gorilla.
</P>
<P>
   _As the gorilla emerges, sell off the rest of the basket and
consolidate your holdings in the gorilla.
</P>
<P>
   _Plan to hold the gorilla for the long-term.
</P>
<P>
   _Sell the gorilla only when a new category, based on an
alternative technology, threatens to eradicate its power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gorilla Game'' is aimed at individual investors, says
Moore. ``The audience is people who want to use the stock market as
part of their personal financial plan. The book offers a safe and
sane way to play in high-tech markets assuming you don't have very
much money and can't afford to lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, a burly fellow with a ready smile, has risen above the
crowd of high-tech strategists and consultants largely because he's
a clear communicator. That requires a solid grounding in language,
which he has, having received degrees in English literature from
Stanford University and the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ```Renaissance man' is an overused term, but if I were going to
label somebody that, out of all the people I know in Silicon
Valley, it would be Geoff,'' says Tom Byers, who teaches
entrepreneurship at Stanford and has known Moore for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Moore started out as an English professor at Olivet College in
Michigan. After four years of that, however, he and his wife,
Marie, decided they'd rather live in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 years starting in 1978, Moore worked in marketing for
three technology companies, none of which exist today. In 1987 he
started consulting, and shortly thereafter joined McKenna's
company, the leading public relations firm in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an exciting intellectual time,'' he says. ``There was
an enormous demand for high-tech strategy consulting, Regis had a
very good reputation and we got a lot of great clients and problems
to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, HarperBusiness, which has since published all of
Moore's books, released ``Crossing the Chasm.'' That created enough
interest in Moore to let him start his own consulting firm the
following year.
</P>
<P>
   Based in San Mateo, the Chasm Group today is six people strong
and has worked for many of the big names in technology, including
IBM, Netscape, Intel, Sun Microsystems and 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   Moore earlier this year joined the board of Documentum, a
Pleasanton tech company that modeled its marketing strategy on his
tactics. He also recently joined venture capital firm Mohr, Davidow
Ventures as a venture partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us (at the Chasm Group) are joining boards and getting
involved with venture firms,'' he says. ``We're sharing this huge
wave of excitement in high tech. I don't know when it will crest,
but it hasn't yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
