r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON &LR;      06-24 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Another Day, Another Merger _ Welcome to the New Economy   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
The phone rang at 3 a.m. yesterday, rousting PR guy Andrew Johnson
from his bed in Antioch.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was TCI corporate in Colorado, telling him to get dressed and
drive to Walnut Creek, because AT&AMP;T was buying its way into the
cable business and it was Johnson's job to inform TCI's Bay Area
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to another day in the New Economy, where the megamergers
just keep on coming.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson arrived at TCI's offices at 4:10 a.m. and relayed an
e-mail from TCI President Leo Hindery to the general managers at
all 128 TCI franchises in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   The managers were supposed to reassure TCI's 4,000 local
employees that no ``downsizing'' was expected if and when AT&AMP;T
became their boss.
</P>
<P>
   Hindery, The Chronicle's former chief finance officer, was still
on the phone late last night, explaining the deal from New York,
where he's spent the last 12 days cloistered with his negotiating
counterpart, AT&AMP;T Chief Financial Officer Dan Somers.
</P>
<P>
   Hindery said the seeds of the current merger were planted in
January, when TCI sold AT&AMP;T its share of the Teleport
Communications Group, a large-scale Internet service provider.
Meeting the AT&AMP;T brass for that and other deals forged the personal
relationships that led to the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is you date around, you date around, and after a
while, you say, `What the heck, let's get married,''' Hindery said.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Self-fulfilling prophecy? &LR;  It's no accident that deals like
this occur in spurts. Morgan Stanley investment banker Rex Golding
told me recently that whenever a big merger occurs, bankers pay
discrete calls on other firms in the same industry, trying to match
them with potential partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good for us to claim credit but our role is to
precipitate the mergers,'' Golding said.
</P>
<P>
   So you can bet dealmakers are out there now, pitching the
WorldComs and Sprints as well as the Comcasts and Cox Cables on the
virtues of telco-cable matchups _ and the dangers of staying
single.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  _ &UR; Whither goest antitrust? &LR;  While the merger wave continues
to surge, the political winds seem to have shifted against the
Justice Department and Federal Trade Commission, each of which has
tackled one-half of the Wintel monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's appellate court ruling in favor of Microsoft was a
slap at the antitrust case Joel Klein's DOJ lawyers have brought
against the software giant.
</P>
<P>
   Adding insult to injury, lawyers in the Beltway are buzzing
about a recent op-ed piece in the Chicago Tribune that ripped Klein
for pursuing a ``weak'' case against Microsoft while approving huge
mergers like the $70 billion Citicorp-Travelers deal. It wasn't the
opinion that caused the stir, but the fact that op-ed writer Steve
Frank is an attorney in the DOJ's civil appellate division.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Intel was sounding aggrieved yesterday, after the
Washington Post reported that the FTC had indirectly tried to win
over public opinion, by sending a pro-government briefing paper to
antitrust experts likely to get quoted by reporters. (You can find
the paper at  &LR; www.ljx.com &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is against the FTC's rules,'' said Intel
spokesman Chuck Mulloy.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Klein and his FTC counterpart Robert Pitofsky may
feel like the legendary King Canute who drowned trying to halt the
tides. Lawrence Sullivan, emeritus professor of antitrust law at UC
Berkeley, said despite their legal and PR setbacks, the antitrust
duo are right to buck the merger wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Klein is not a crazy, neither is Pitofsky,'' Sullivan said.
``They're thoughtful, cautious people who deserve support and
encouragement'' as they try to figure out how 19th century
antitrust plays in 21st century industries.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Magic words: &LR;  Personally, I say to heck with Sullivan and his
fellow travelers in D.C. It's the New Economy, stupid. Antitrust
drools. One-stop shopping rules.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that one rationale for the AT&AMP;T-TCI deal, the notion that
synergies and efficiencies result when consumers can get everything
from Seinfeld reruns to Web pages to phone calls from one
brand-name corporation.
</P>
<P>
   In fact once the dust settles, AT&AMP;T should acquire Domino's,
Costco and Sears, then merge the whole shebang into Citicorp, so we
can order everything from pizzas to microwaves, and debit the
transaction to our AT&AMP;T tele-banking account.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's one-stop shopping! Accept no substitutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail ( &LR; abate(at &LR; 
sig &LR; n)sfgate.com &LR; ). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
