<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Mylan Fleshing Out Deal for Penederm   By Carl T. Hall  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Penederm Inc., a Bay Area skin-products and drug-delivery company,
is being acquired by generic-drug giant Mylan Laboratories Inc. in
a stock deal worth about $205 million .
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mylan, the largest producer of off-patent drugs in the United
States, has been trying to jump into the market for higher-profit,
brand-name drugs. Foster City-based Penederm gives Mylan three
dermatology products on the market and several more in development,
including two in the final stages of clinical testing.
</P>
<P>
   Mylan is paying nearly a third more than Penederm's recent
market value. Analysts said the price did not seem out of line
given premiums paid in other recent drug-industry takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really paying for a future product stream here,''
said Eugene Melnitchenko, a stock analyst at Sutro &AMP; Co. in Los
Angeles. ``Mylan has been trying to diversify away from purely
generic products, and Penederm does have a decent pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   Mylan said it planned no layoffs and intended to beef up
Penederm's clinical research efforts. Penederm's delivery
technology may be incorporated in some Mylan product candidates now
in development.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Malchow, chief executive at Penederm, said the deal ``will
enhance significantly Penederm's ability to pursue its
product-development and marketing plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal has been approved by directors of both companies.
Penederm shareholder approval also is required before it can take
effect, expected by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Penederm stockholders would get 0.68 shares of Mylan for every
Penederm share. That made the deal worth about $205 million, or
$21.89 a share, based on stock prices Tuesday, when the terms were
made final.
</P>
<P>
   Mylan stock edged down 44 cents yesterday to close at $31.75,
while Penederm rose $4.75, or 30.2 percent, to close at $20.50.
</P>
<P>
   Penederm's existing products are Avita, a topical medicine for
acne; Mentax, for fungal infections; and Acticin, for scabies.
Mentax has been marketed through a partnership between Penederm and
Mylan's Bertek Pharmaceuticals Inc. subsidiary, which plans to take
over marketing all Penederm products once the deal closes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
