<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WITI-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Conference Focuses on Women in Tech   By Amy Doan  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
One small but telling sign of the growing influence of women in
technology: The Santa Clara Convention Center placed Boston ferns
in the men's urinals this week.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The convention center had to turn the men's rooms into women's
rooms for the fourth annual Women in Technology International
conference this week. The ferns were designed to cover up the fact
that the convention center didn't have enough rest rooms for the
4,500 women who will attend the three-day conference, which ends
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WITI's mission is to get women into technical fields and keep
them there. And that's still a daunting task.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this year's record attendance at WITI _ only 2,500
attended last year _ the percentage of U.S. electrical engineers
and computer analysts/scientists who are women has barely budged in
the past decade. The majority of women at the conference were in
fields such as marketing, sales and communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to encourage young girls,'' said Carolyn Leighton,
founder and director of WITI, &UR;  &LR; which is based in Sherman Oaks.
``The only messages they get from the media are about how women can
balance career and family; they rarely see women talking about
computer products or something purely technical.''
</P>
<P>
   Leighton founded the nonprofit group in 1989 as an e-mail
network for women technologists. Today it is a professional
association with 6,000 members worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   At the conference, which had sessions on Java and e-commerce as
well as career development tracks, speaker after speaker emphasized
the need for women in technology to find and serve as role models.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In her keynote speech, Autodesk Inc. chief executive Carol
Bartz described watching her grandmother whack the head off of a
rattlesnake in a Wisconsin barn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky to have someone to show me how to do something
difficult and move on,''said Bartz, who worked for Digital
Equipment Corp. and Sun Microsystems Inc. before moving to
Autodesk.
</P>
<P>
   Bartz said the women in the audience should be encouraged by the
prevalence of technology in the 90s.
</P>
<P>
   Images like the computer-generated ``dancing baby'' on the Fox
television show ``Ally McBeal'' (which is created with Autodesk
software) have made technology accessible to everyone, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her upbeat focus, Bartz said she sometimes gets
``depressed'' about how underrepresented women are in science and
engineering.
</P>
<P>
   One attendee said that while events like WITI can cut down on
female engineers' sense of isolation, the real problem starts in
grade school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so trite now to say that girls are discouraged in math
classes, but it's true.'' said Stacey Blaschke, an engineer and
owner of Computer Matters, a Laguna Beach consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Blaschke, who has a computer science degree from California
Polytechnic University, said one of her good friends was told by
her calculus professor to switch majors, ``just for asking a few
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   That story is a familiar one to researchers who are trying to
pinpoint reasons for the relative lack of women in technical jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Two main causes are the fact that fewer women enter technical
fields than men, and they also drop out at a greater rate,
according to New York research firm Catalyst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a long time to make a scientist,''said Jennifer
Allyn, an associate with Catalyst who is working on a study of
women in technology.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is also attracting attention in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The House has passed the Women in Science, Engineering and
Technology Development Act and it heads to the education and
workforce committee this week. The so-called Wisetech bill would
allocate $750,000 for a commission to study barriers that women
face in technical fields and make recommendations on recruiting and
retaining women scientists and engineers.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is the brainchild of Representative Constance Morella,
R-Md., who said she wrote it when she learned about the dearth of
women in technical fields.
</P>
<P>
   One way to get more girls interested in technology is to give
them more hands-on experience.
</P>
<P>
   The WITI conference spotlighted two such programs: Advocates for
Women in Science, Engineering and Mathematics, a Portland,
Ore.-based science and math advocacy program for girls aged 11-18;
and Design Your Future, an Autodesk initiative that sponsors
computer-assisted design contests for girls.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, a dozen girls from Bay Area middle schools showed
what they had learned through the Design Your Future program.
</P>
<P>
   As she created a software model of an intricate LEGO truck,
14-year-old Naomi Duben of San Rafael said, ``I really like
computers. I don't see why I couldn't do this as a job.'' &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
