<SLUG> BC-BOX-KING-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING'S REPRESENTATIVES SECRETLY TAPED MEETINGS, LAWYER TESTIFIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A lawyer for a Lloyd's of London syndicate testified
Wednesday in Don King's insurance fraud trial that the promoter's
defense team secretly taped meetings last year aimed at settling a
related civil case.
</P>
<P>
   King and his company are being tried in federal court in
Manhattan, accused of filing a fraudulent insurance claim after a
Julio Cesar Chavez-Harold Brazier bout was canceled in 1991, and
the Lloyd's syndicate is suing to recover the $671,000 payment it
made.
</P>
<P>
   What the lawyer, Donald Cayea, and another syndicate lawyer,
William Dunnegan, said during the settlement meetings is a matter
of dispute. King's defense claims that Cayea and Dunnegan tried to
broker a settlement in the civil suit by offering to provide
evidence that could exculpate Don King Productions for repayment of
the $671,000 claim.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination by Baruch Weiss, an assistant U.S.
attorney for the Southern District, Cayea testified that no tape
recorder was visible at two meetings that were recorded, and that
none of King's lawyers said that the meetings were being taped.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you learned you were taped, you were upset?'' Weiss
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an ethical violation,'' Cayea said.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss said that although the tapes are a year old, King's
lawyers did not disclose their existence to the U.S. attorney's
office until last week.
</P>
<P>
   Cayea testified that during settlement meetings, the Lloyd's of
London syndicate merely offered _ in the event of a settlement of
the civil case _ to give King's lawyers access to witnesses who
might help develop defense strategies for the criminal trial. Cayea
said it was standard procedure in settlement talks.
</P>
<P>
   Cayea said he warned King's lawyers that the help that was
offered would not necessarily lead to an acquittal for King's
company.
</P>
<P>
   Closing statements in the case could be heard Thursday or
Friday. King's first trial on the charges in 1995 ended in a hung
jury. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
