<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHEN CHARTER PLUS BASEBALL EQUALS POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is constitutional reform the way Rube Goldberg
would have liked it.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, after many impassioned words and stirring
pronouncements _ one member compared the event to the Boston Tea
Party _ the New York City Council voted to place a referendum on
the future of Yankee Stadium on November's ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum would ask voters whether the City Charter should
be amended to prevent public funds from being used to move the
stadium from the Bronx to Manhattan. If New Yorkers voted ``yes,''
it would mean no public funds could be used, while if they voted
``no,'' it would mean yes, public funds could be used.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of the vote, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, speaking at
a news conference Wednesday in Manhattan, denounced the proposed
referendum, calling it ``very, very bad government'' as well as
``an indication of a total lack of willingness to make difficult
decisions.'' Giuliani has made it clear that he will do everything
in his power, which turns out to be quite a bit, to keep the
council's referendum from coming to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday he reiterated his position that proposals made by a
commission he has appointed to revise the City Charter will bump
the council's proposal on amending it off the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a much better chance in court than they do,''
he said, anticipating where the dispute will end up.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the city's public advocate, Mark Green, at a news
conference of his own, denounced the mayor for forming a Charter
Revision Commission to foil the City Council's charter amendment.
Members of the mayor's commission have already stated that one of
the charter changes they will consider is eliminating his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``This abuse of power won't stand up in a court of law or in the
court of public opinion,'' Green declared.
</P>
<P>
   With his job suddenly on the line, Green perhaps has the most
pressing reason to lament the bizarre connection between baseball
and charter revision. But everyone should be embarrassed by it.
</P>
<P>
   The council complains, with good reason, that the whole fight is
a result of the mayor's stubbornness. Giuliani, it contends, is not
acting in the public interest but rather on behalf of powerful
interests who would benefit from moving the stadium. The whole
point of the referendum, council members suggest, is to show how
unenthusiastic most New Yorkers are about the mayor's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an issue in which the people have the right to be
heard,'' the City Council speaker, Peter Vallone, said Wednesday,
defending the stadium referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, also with good reason, blames the City Council, and
in particular Vallone and his political ambitions. Giuliani has
frequently said he thinks Vallone is pushing the stadium referendum
simply as a way to raise Democratic voter turnout in November, when
the council speaker hopes to be the party's candidate for governor.
The mayor portrays himself and his Charter Revision Commission as a
necessary brake on this kind of legislative irresponsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise,'' he said, ``everything then would be decided by
referendum and the deliberative process of executive and
legislative branch would end.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, both sides are much more persuasive when hammering each
other than when trying to justify their own actions. Both were
astonishingly ready to escalate the argument over Yankee Stadium
into an argument over charter revision. And both had plenty of more
reasonable alternatives available.
</P>
<P>
   If the City Council does not want a new stadium to be built in
Manhattan, there are several points at which it could stop such a
plan. Most significant, it could just refuse to appropriate the
funds to finance it.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, if the mayor does not want to see voters turn down
a new stadium in a referendum, he could try to convince them that a
new stadium is actually a good idea. Instead, having pointed out
that the future of the stadium is a bogus excuse for a referendum,
he has turned around and supported an even more bogus proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he has offered rationales for charter revision, he has
never seriously tried to disguise the fact that his goal is to beat
the council at its own game.
</P>
<P>
   As Giuliani observed Wednesday, the issue of the stadium will be
resolved one day. But, as he also correctly noted, ``it's going to
take a little more thinking to figure out how to move to a more
responsible level of leadership.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
