<HEADLINE>
BAN ON MONO COUNTY NIGHT FISHING REINSTATED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Calif. _ Officials concerned that night-fishing in
Mono County is unsafe have won a reversal of the recent action
permitting 24-hour angling in the popular Eastern Sierra
destination.
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting Thursday in Bridgeport, the state Fish and Game
Commission approved emergency action to reinstate a ban on
nighttime fishing. The request was made by the Mono County Board of
Supervisors and was not opposed by the Department of Fish and Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that this has been a tradition in Mono County
for some years and one that the community wants to see
maintained,'' said Tim Farley, chief of the DFG's Inland Fisheries
Division.
</P>
<P>
   The order was unanimously passed by the commission. It is
expected to receive approval by the state Office of Administrative
Law _ the next step in the process _ and take effect July 1. If
approved, Mono County will once again be the only Sierra Fishing
District where angling is allowed only from one hour before sunrise
to one hour after sunset. (Night-fishing in Mono went on the books
March 1.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The night-fishing issue is not a biological issue,'' Farley
said. ``Objections to it in Mono County appear to be based
primarily on local safety and security concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at issue was the integrity of the customary flare that is
shot over Crowley Lake each last Saturday of April at 5 a.m. to
signify the start of trout season in the Eastern Sierra. Now that
tradition is preserved.
</P>
</TEXT>
