<HEADLINE>
BOSTON TURNS TO REALITY AFTER DNC VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Now that the Democratic Convention site committee has
moved on to inspect other contenders, Boston can focus on what it
needs to do if it should actually land the 2000 convention.
</P>
<P>
   What began last year as a glimmer in the eye of Mayor Thomas M.
Menino after a tour of Atlanta, has blossomed into a viable
possibility, according to the committee.
</P>
<P>
   For months, city officials have been sweating the details of
hotel rooms and transportation, telecommunications, and computer
plugs. But as far as the visitors were concerned, Boston seems to
be able to &UR;  &LR; handle all that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many things you can't put on an Excel spread
sheet, like how much is the city willing to go the extra mile,''
said Joseph Andrew, chairman of the site panel. Boston showed
marathon potential, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that Tommy's town couldn't be better, and Tommy's
tour is tops,'' said the Indiana state party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor himself could not sound more confident. ``We are one
team and we are ready,'' he said at a farewell breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the stellar showing of these past few days, the
reality is that Boston still has two high hurdles to conquer in
order to host a successful convention of that scale: Raising $30
million in private funds for the four-day party, and overcoming a
political deck that has always been stacked against this Democratic
stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   No Democrat has ever won the presidency without carrying
Massachusetts, so the traditional wisdom has directed the
convention to swing states and regions where the party needs a
boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure it's the wisest place for them to have the
convention for the ticket,'' said Ron Kaufman, Massachusetts native
and Republican National Committee member. ``If the Democrats are in
the position of having to drum up support in Massachusetts, they're
in deep trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   But New York and Chicago have won the convention several times,
neither of them offering strategic advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big political picture still has to play itself out,'' said
Chuck Campion, a former Democratic campaign operative now with the
Dewey Square Group. ``They went to New York twice for the Democrats
and there wasn't a political argument to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the mountain of money to be raised, Kaufman said the
business community has to be convinced it's worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Campion agreed that Boston would have to change its style in
that regard. ``We're not a city that usually jumps up and down to
get in on things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff for the city dwarfs that contribution, with an
estimated $150 million in direct spending and twice that amount in
long-term benefits that would come from publicity. While
Massachusetts consistently tops the fund-raising charts for
Democratic candidates, the business community here has little
practice with huge outlays for marketing the city for conventions.
The financial services industry, which is sizable here, has been
slow to reach for its wallet, according to city sources.
</P>
<P>
   So far, BankBoston, Fleet Bank, and John Hancock have been
generous in supporting the city's bid with checks and by sponsoring
events like Tuesday's breakfast in the John Hancock Tower.
Companies large and small were ready with donations of food and
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Others gave their time _ Bobby Orr mixed drinks in the Reebok
box at Fenway; M.L. Carr greeted the group in the Celtics locker
room at the Fleet Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get it, we need to start the fund-raising that day,''
said Kelley Quinn, spokeswoman for the Boston Redevelopment
Authority. ``All the people on the fray will have to step up to the
plate.''
</P>
<P>
   As the city has emerged as a contender for the convention,
business support has mushroomed, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visit-bounce will probably be better than the
(presidential) candidate will get'' after the national convention,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Boston has passed the technical test, with
21,000 hotel rooms. In fact, the executive housing at Harvard
University turned out to be the site panel's favorite. Wowed by the
computer hookups, fax machines, and conference tables available for
each of the Harvard rooms, the panelists urged the city to ask some
of the other top academic institutions in the area to see if they
have similar space available, Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fleet Center turned out to be the darling of the committee
as well. Plans need to be made for moving 100 buses full of people
away from the arena in rapid succession, however, and parking
supplies in the neighborhood have to be assessed, Quinn said. Other
details remain, but they are manageable, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We demonstrated far and above that we have the ability and
enthusiasm to do this,'' said Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   Donald R. Sweitzer, former finance and political director for
the DNC, has been watching Boston from Washington, remembering how
his site panel shocked everyone by choosing Atlanta over Houston
because Mayor Andrew Young was so enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Boston's chances are pretty good,'' he said. But the
decision in many ways is out of the city's hands, Sweitzer said.
``It's one part technical, one part political, and one part rub
your belly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
