<SLUG> BC-MA-TOBACCO-ATTACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE AD CAMPAIGN TO ATTACK TOBACCO INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In an unusual use of taxpayers' money, the
Massachusetts public health department is launching a $280,000 ad
campaign to counterattack the tobacco industry media blitz that
critics say led to the collapse of the recent national tobacco
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Using excerpts from the cigarette industry's own internal
documents, the three TV ads and two newspaper ads will begin
appearing locally Thursday and will be made available to public
officials in any other states, said Dr. Gregory Connolly, director
of the state's $36 million Tobacco Control Program.
</P>
<P>
   Connolly said the ads are intended to offset the $40 million
worth of advertising which cigarette makers sponsored over the past
three weeks to undermine an attempt in Congress to raise cigarette
taxes. State public health officials estimate that close to $1
million was spent by the tobacco industry in Massachusetts alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an attempt to put an infusion of truth into the
debate,'' said US Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts
Democrat and the co-chair of the Task Force on Tobacco and Health
in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, which contain images of youngsters smoking, display
quotes taken from confidential industry documents that appear to
show cigarette makers targeted teens in the past. The damaging
documents recently emerged from the suit filed by Minnesota
officials against the industry.
</P>
<P>
   One cites a 1976 R.J. Reynolds document that said ``the 14- to
18-year-old group is an increasing segment of the smoking
population. RJR must soon establish a successful new brand in this
market.''
</P>
<P>
   In another, a excerpt from a 1972 document is shown that says:
``Happily for the tobacco industry, nicotine is both habituating
and unique in its variety of physiological actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The tag line on each of the ads states: ``They knew. They always
knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Connolly Wednesday said the public health department feels it is
proper to use public funds to weigh in on the political debate in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the advertising the industry conducted over the past
few weeks has undermined the reality that the tobacco companies are
targeting kids,'' Connolly said. His program spends about $12
million a year on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The state is prohibited from using tax revenue for political
purposes, but Connolly said the real intent is to discourage
smoking, not influence politicians. The money for the ad campaign
comes from the 25-cent sales tax increase on cigarettes approved by
voters in 1992 to create a state anti-smoking program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not lobbying for or against any national settlement,''
Connolly said. ``We are just trying to bring the issue back home
and letting people know that the industry is after their
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting Governor Paul Cellucci, who authorized the two-week ad
campaign, said the ads put to rest the cigarette makers' claims
that they did not intentionally market to young people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secret documents, recently released, tell a different story
and this campaign reveals the truth that the tobacco industry has
been going after our children with an addictive product that can
kill them,'' Cellucci said. ``In private, Big Tobacco `knew, they
always knew.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, however, stood against the 1992 cigarette tax hike
that created the Massachusetts Tobacco Control Program which pays
for the anti-smoking ads. Furthermore, Cellucci recently expressed
opposition to the Washington-led effort to raise federal cigarette
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Lauria, a spokesman for the Tobacco Institute in
Washington, declined to comment on Massachusetts' new ad campaign,
saying he and his colleagues had not seen them or the industry
documents used. He also declined to offer any industry reaction to
the comments made by Cellucci, Meehan, and other officials.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said the tobacco industry media blitz was instrumental in
helping defeat the McCain bill in the Senate last week, a near
fatal blow to the efforts to pass the legislation. The McCain bill
would have raised cigarette taxes $1.20, created anti-smoking
campaigns to protect children, and paid for health care initiatives
promoted by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The state's use of its tax revenue to attack the industry is
also being hailed by national anti-smoking leaders. Bill Novelli,
president of the Campaign for Tobacco Free Kids in Washington, said
Massachusetts' decision to launch the ads is first major boost to
efforts to combat the industry's aggressive ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has basically set out to correct the most recent record
and that's why this Massachusetts program is unique and
important,'' Novelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Novelli said national anti-smoking leaders are concerned that
the industry has been bolstered by the success of its media blitz,
feeling it has helped its public image. He said he hears from
industry sources that the manufacturers plan to use similar ad
campaigns to further shape their image and influence the public
debate in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Novelli said his group is considering using the Massachusetts
ads in the Washington media market to combat the tobacco industry's
media strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the debate on Capitol Hill is expected to continue.
Sensing an opportunity to blame Republicans for the collapse of the
bill, President Clinton and the Democrats have vowed to try to
revive the national tobacco bill.
</P>
<P>
   While the Senate version of the tobacco bill died last week when
advocates could not marshall the necessary 60 votes to bring the
issue to a vote, the effort has been kept alive in the House.
Meehan and Rep. James P. Hansen, a Republican from Montana, have
offered a revised version of the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
