<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BKN-DRAFT-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE THING WASN'T ON THE BOARD _ LOGIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We all figured it was going to be a wild, wacky night. It was.
</P>
<P>
   There was no scenario in which the Celtics had Paul Pierce
tumbling to No. 10. That was one of many stunners, which, of
course, were all predestined because the Clippers were in control.
</P>
<P>
   You could have made a lot of money had you placed a wager that
Jason Williams, the point guard from Florida, would go ahead of
Pierce. He did, by three spots. Dirk Nowitzki, the German
star-in-waiting, was on the Celtics' wish list and, according to
Rick Pitino, was prepared to accept some Uncle Sam Benjamins
instead of Italian lire.
</P>
<P>
   (That was another curveball. Both Pitino and Chris Wallace had
said they weren't all that interested in anyone who couldn't put on
a uniform right away. And that Pitino had never had any foreign
kids in his programs. And that foreign kids generally present some
kind of problem, usually contractual.
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki appeared to be one of those fellows, having reportedly
agreed to play the next two years in Bologna. Pitino worked him out
in Rome and said he was as certain as he could be that Nowitzki
would have played in Boston next year.)
</P>
<P>
   It all started at the top, which, with the Clippers making the
first pick, guaranteed a night of craziness. Los Angeles hemmed and
hawed between Pacific big man Michael Olowokandi and Arizona point
guard Mike Bibby.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby was the logical choice if you went by Donald Sterling's
logic: fame and pedigree. He's also pretty good. But the Clips
instead took Olowokandi, who may not be ready right away but could
be one of the better centers in the league in the next five years.
And when the dust settles from this summer's lockout, the rookies
almost assuredly will be signed to five-year deals.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver was next. Last year the Grizzlies took Antonio Daniels
as their point guard of the future with the fourth pick. He flamed
out and at the end of the season was on the bench, watching Bobby
Hurley and Lee Mayberry.
</P>
<P>
   Would Grizzlies general manager Stu Jackson, who already has
three point guards, add a fourth? Would he do so knowing the choice
would all but invalidate the selection of Daniels? To his credit,
Jackson went with Bibby. If he delivers as promised, Big Country
Reeves and Sharif Abdur-Rahim will be much happier fellows. Who
knows, Rahim may even decide to re-sign.
</P>
<P>
   Denver had needs everywhere. The Nuggets went with Raef
LaFrentz, who would have been the No. 3 pick last year had he come
out early. He had started out high on everyone's list, tumbled a
bit, then risen again. But he's a skilled player who also happens
to be 6 feet 11 inches. Denver has needs up front and took him,
even though it was assumed the Nuggets would go with either Pierce
or Vince Carter.
</P>
<P>
   There was subterfuge everywhere in the next three picks. Golden
State felt comfortable that Antawn Jamison would be available at
No. 5 but then got wind that Dallas was trying to move up to take
the College Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   So Garry St. Jean, the Warriors' general manager, upstaged
former boss Don Nelson and made a cash deal with Toronto. The
Raptors took Jamison, the Warriors took Carter, the two lads
swapped caps at NBA Draft Central in Vancouver, and some ``carrying
charges,'' as Sidney Greenstreet might say, followed.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas then took Robert Traylor. Why? The Mavericks already have
A.C. Green and Samaki Walker at power forward. The answer became
apparent soon enough. Dallas was drafting for Milwaukee, which
agreed to send picks No. 9 and 19 to the Mavs in exchange for the
No. 6. Implicit in that transaction was that Milwaukee would take
Nowitzki at No. 9. The German was Nellie's favorite all along.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas wasn't through. The Mavericks worked out a deal with
Phoenix which brought them Steve Nash as well. That gave them
Nowitzki and Nash. In return for Nash, they sent the Suns their
unprotected first-round pick next season and two salary cap
throw-ins, Martin Muursepp and Bubba Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was a real shocker. No one had the Florida guard going
that high. He was an undeniable talent, the second-best point guard
(after Bibby), but had some behavioral problems at Florida. It was
a gutsy choice.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings didn't need Pierce; their forward spots are all
filled. They might have used Larry Hughes, but his age (19) may
have scared them away. They definitely needed a point guard, and he
was high on everyone's list in terms of pure ability.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia could have put a dent in Pitino's plans by picking
Pierce. But the 76ers are committed to Tim Thomas at small forward
and have no one to play shooting guard. Hughes, a shooting guard,
was there and had looked good in workouts. So they went with the
6-4 guard, an outstanding talent who played only one season of
college ball.
</P>
<P>
   That left Pierce to the Celtics and completed a top 10 which no
personnel man or GM could have envisioned. The Celtics certainly
didn't. And as the first round moved well into the 20s, there were
still such names as Nazr Mohammed, Rashard Lewis, Corey Benjamin,
Vladimir Stepania, and Ruben Patterson available for the picking.
Mohammed was supposed to be a top 15 pick; then again, he was
coming out of Kentucky because he was going to lose playing time to
people like Mike Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Sound crazy? It is. But it was fitting for the night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
