   (NYT22) XIAN, China -- June 24, 1998 -- CHINA-RELICS-FEUD-1,
6-24 -- Yang Quanyi, 70, insists that it was he who first unearthed
replicas of Xian's terra-cotta soldiers. ``Don't believe what other
people tell you,'' says Yang, shown signing books in the tourist
gift shop where he works. ``I found the soldiers.'' (Seth
Faison/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- June 24, 1998 -- CONGRESS-HEALTH, 6-24 --
House Republicans unveiled a long-awaited proposal Wednesday to
define patients' rights and set uniform nationwide standards for
health insurance, especially health maintenance organizations. Rep.
Dennis Hastert of Illinois, a leader of the Republican initiative
on health care, confers with Rep. John Boehner of Ohio, chairman of
the House Republican Conference. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- June 24, 1998 -- AT&AMP;T-TCI, 6-24 -- AT&AMP;T, the
nation's largest telephone company, agreed Wednesday to acquire
Tele-Communications Inc., the second biggest cable television
provider, for $31.8 billion in stock in a deal that is the most
ambitious product yet of the 1996 deregulation of the
telecommunications industry by Congress. From left, C. Michael
Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's chief executive, John Malone, chairman of TCI,
John Zeglis, AT&AMP;T's president, and Leo Hindery, Jr., president of
TCI. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- June 24, 1998 -- TV-BEDSTUY-REVISITED, 6-24
-- Charles Hobson returns to the brownstone in Bedford-Stuyvesant
where he grew up. Hobson, 62, chronicled the neighborhood from1968
until 1970 in a pioneering television program for local station
WNEW. ``This was a way for blacks to hear their voices,'' he says.
``Here's a community of about 400,000 people at that time, with all
of their culture and churches, and no coverage.'' (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) DENVER -- June 24, 1998 -- HANTAVIRUS, 6-24 -- Carried
by a surging population of deer mice, hantavirus has returned to
the Southwest this spring, killing a boy and a woman in Colorado
and a man in New Mexico. Flor Dabola, a scientist at the Colorado
Health Department, runs a test for the virus on a blood sample in a
Denver laboratory. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- June 24, 1998 -- GAY-MENS-CHORUS, 6-24 --
Gary Miller, the music director of the New York City Gay Men's
Chorus. In the 18 years Miller has worked with the chorus, 90
members have died, and Miller himself is HIV positive. ``After we
lost someone, at the next rehearsal we would always sing a song for
that person,'' he says. ``Sometimes it would be a song that was
special to the person; a lot of the time it was a song called 'Love
Lives On.' `` (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
