<HEADER>
A5615 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     06-24 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMBILL PERSISTS AND IT PAYS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ What kind of tennis tournament is this, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Weird. Nothing like Jan-Michael Gambill of the Spokane, Wash.,
Gambills had ever experienced. But then, he's only a 21-year-old
Wimbledon new boy, and you wouldn't exactly call Spokane a tennis
breeding ground. His was the longest, strangest debut at the
121-year-old Big W, which, he said, ``isn't like the Wimbledon I've
watched on TV. Coming here was sort of like stepping into a movie _
except the court I played on was never in the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. Jan-Michael Gambill, a tall, polite,
peroxide-headed kid, has the looks to be in the movies himself, but
if you're No. 60 in the world playing No. 53, Sjeng Schalken,
they're not going to put you in the Palace. You go to the back lots
where the B movies are made. In fact, Diane Gambill named her boy
for the B movie star she adored, Jan-Michael Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   Court 7 was the location. What happened out there, a paddock on
the wrong side of the concourse, well away from Centre Court _ over
and over and over _ was more a miniseries than a match. The feeling
was that some director with a megaphone kept yelling at Schalken
and Gambill, ``Cut! Cut! Let's do another take, fellows, until we
get it right.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a while and a lot of takes. Why not? When you go to work
at Wimbledon on Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday, are you supposed to
play the same guy on the same court every time? That could get
monotonous. But that's what Gambill _ the winner _ and Schalken
did. Again and again and again, until Gambill, who'd never played
more than three sets or one day against any opponent, got it
righter: 7-6 (8-6), 6-4, 6-7 (5-7), 4-6, 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   The suspenseful miniseries in three episodes went like this:
</P>
<P>
   Monday _ ``Gambill Gambols But Gambles.'' Jan-Michael, baffling
his foe with wacky, powerful two-handed shots from both sides, has
done enough to win any prior match in his life. He takes two of
three sets _ and comes within two points of victory (5-5) in the
tie-breaker _ but tries ``a shot I shouldn't have'' to lose the
breaker. The curtain comes down in the form of darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday _ ``Schalken's Shakin'!'' Sjeng, the lanky Dutchman,
victor over Marcelo Rios to win the MFS Pro last August in Boston,
turns up the heat, seizes the fourth set, and breaks Gambill to
start the fifth. Gambill's coach _ his father, Chuck Gambill _
groans, but the kid is saved by the curtain descending in the form
of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday _ ``Gambillation!'' Jan-Michael and Sjeng, rewarded by
sunshine, slug away nervelessly, surely leaving their footprints on
Court 7 forever. Gambill retrieves the break after trailing, 2-4,
and keeps pushing Schalken to the edge of the cliff. Time after
time. Match-point take after match-point take _ only to have to
repeat the scene. Schalken serves to 5-5 from 15-40, escaping four
match points. He does the same, from 0-40, to 6-6, rescuing five
more match points. ``I keep thinking I'll get one. Can't worry
about it,'' Gambill says. Schalken wriggles out of a 10th match
point, but on Take 11, his forehand fails and over the cliff he
falls, with the curtain.
</P>
<P>
   Out go the Dutchman's lights, and Jan-Michael wants to sing,
``The Night the Lights Went Out in Georgia,'' his favorite song by
his favorite singer, Reba McEntire, who, he says, follows his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first night,'' Gambill recalls that intermission, ``I was
really mad. I should have won the tie-breaker, the match.'' He was
``madder'' the second, ``falling behind after leading the whole
way. But Dad and I talked it over, made some adjustments, and being
mad made me determined not to let this chance get away.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this wasn't the Wimbledon I've seen on TV.'' Nope. Too
weird. No network is going to broadcast a three-day match.
Miniseries are strictly for sex and gore.
</P>
<P>
   So now the kid who won the championship of Spokane at age 15 and
16 _ ``I loved that huge cup; you could take it home for a year'' _
is in the second round against Byron Black. He hopes that doesn't
last until Sunday. But it will be weird, too, because Black also
hangs on with both hands for backhand and forehand _ a duel of
freaks.
</P>
<P>
   Gambill, proclaiming, ``Steffi Graf is my hero,'' knew the drill
from watching her on TV (until arriving here for a gratifying
personal look). ``You go hard all the time to win any match.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it takes three days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
