<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRADUATION AISLE IS CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 ANOTHER BOROUGH NOW HER OWN  
 HISS AND TELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ MARK GREEN, the city's public advocate, did something
Wednesday that only a politician would do: He gave three
commencement speeches.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, he faced fifth-graders graduating from Public
School 33 in Jamaica, Queens. Then he was off to Madison Square
Garden for the Bronx High School of Science commencement. Later, he
went back to Queens for the Grover Cleveland High School
graduation, held at Queens College.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a record, at least not for Green, a candidate for the
Senate. ``I've done five in a day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he did it without prepared texts. ``I have to speak without
notes because otherwise you have all the dynamism of an Al Gore
inaugural address,'' he said. ``Obviously you have set ideas and
language that you occasionally repeat.''
</P>
<P>
   He custom-tailored each talk, though his basic theme was: ``In a
world where Michael Jordan was cut from his JV basketball team and
we have a one-armed pitcher in major-league baseball, nobody's
smart enough to be a pessimist and nobody can tell you you can't
reach your dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one listener was paying attention. At the Bronx Science
graduation, Green ad-libbed a line about the defeat of the tobacco
bill in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``One kid yelled, `Great,''' he said. ``Some other kids laughed.
I said, `Me, I don't think it's a good idea that tobacco merchants
can seduce 14-year-olds the age of my son with deceptive ads and
lure them into a lifelong, life-ending addiction.' I didn't want to
put him down, but I didn't want him to be the dissenting voice
confused for the majority, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Borough, Now Her Own
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In chronicling the exotic demimonde of Manhattan in
her 1986 book ``Slaves of New York,'' TAMA JANOWITZ included
characters who were slaves to their apartments in Manhattan
(couldn't pay for them, couldn't hang on to them or couldn't stand
living in them).
</P>
<P>
   She is no longer among them, if she ever was. She and her
husband, TIM HUNT, the chief curator of the Warhol Foundation, are
bound for Brooklyn. He said that they had signed a contract on a
co-op. But there is a but. ``We haven't yet met with the co-op
board,'' he said. ``That happens shortly, so we can't celebrate
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brooklyn?
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no intention of looking in Brooklyn,'' he said, ``but
we saw an ad that looked very tempting and interesting. I ran out
to see it one evening. Tama followed the next morning and we made
an offer that afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiss and Tell
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The rock-music producer PHIL SPECTOR and his former
wife and former Ronette RONNIE SPECTOR GREENFIELD found themselves
in the same room for the first time in at least a decade.
</P>
<P>
   A courtroom, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't seem to get rid of her,'' said Spector, who is the
defendant in a civil suit in state Supreme Court in Manhattan filed
by the Ronettes, who maintain that he cheated them out of millions
in record royalties and licensing fees.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Greenfield testified earlier in the month, but Spector was
not in court that day. On Wednesday, she watched as he was
cross-examined by the Ronettes' lawyer, ALEXANDER PELTZ.
</P>
<P>
   Spector said later he believed that he had not encountered her
since their divorce in 1974. ``I have difficulty in dealing with
people whose future is the past,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Greenfield had her say outside the courtroom. ``Like so
many of those people back then,'' she said, ``he cheated the
performers and thought he could get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Spector got away without even a hallway encounter: He
left the courtroom through a back door.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
