<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5620 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-DRUGSTORES-FINED-B     06-24 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-DRUGSTORES-FINED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUGSTORES FINED FOR IMPROPER TOXICS DISPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hoping to prove they can be friendly to business and
tough on pollution at the same time, Massachusetts environmental
officials Wednesday fined CVS and Walgreen a total of $55,000 for
violations discovered when the drugstore chains volunteered for a
new program aimed at cutting red tape.
</P>
<P>
   The fines _ for improper disposal of toxic silver at the stores'
photoprocessing shops _ mark the first penalties under a nationally
watched program that allows companies to self-report their
environmental performance instead of going through elaborate permit
approvals.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists had feared that the ``Environmental Results
Program'' would allow businesses to get away with polluting when
former Governor William Weld unveiled it 1996 &UR;  &LR; by tearing up
permits. But Environmental Protection Commissioner David Struhs
said the fines send the message that enforcement, if anything, will
increase under the new system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's critically important that (businesses) know that
we take these self-certifications very, very seriously,'' said
Struhs, noting that Walgreen and CVS got caught because Department
of Environmental Protection officials checked to see if the
certificates were accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists cheered the fines, which Jim Gomes, president
of the Environmental League of Massachusetts, called ``a true Kodak
moment.'' Silver from photo processors travels through sewers to
discharge sites such as Boston Harbor where it can poison marine
life.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Results Program, expected to cover 15,000
Massachusetts businesses by 2000, is part of a national effort to
get away from old-style regulation where regulators write detailed
permits that tell businesses what to do. The process is so time
consuming that Department of Environmental Protection regulators
have little left over to make sure businesses are following the
permits.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders complain that the arcana of permitting slows
them down, while environmentalists say firms don't follow the
permits. The Department of Environmental Protection estimates that
60 to 70 percent of businesses are violating at least one
environmental permit.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Environmental Results Program, which now applies only
to photo processors, dry cleaners, and printers, companies can
throw away most permits.But they must also file an annual statement
saying they meet environmental standards for the industry or
outlining ways they intend to correct violations.
</P>
<P>
   The new system got off to a bumpy start in 1996 when it was
revealed that state inspectors immediately found violations at 14
of the 23 companies that volunteered to try self-reporting,
including one firm that was illegally shipping hazardous waste to
Kazakhstan. Even Struhs called the findings ``alarming.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the firms have improved compliance so much since 1996 _
only four of the volunteers still have violations _ that a US
General Accounting Office report this week held up the
Massachusetts program as a potential national model. In addition,
silver discharges among photo processors in the program have
dropped 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists and some Department of Environmental
Protection employees were waiting to see if the agency would punish
any of the volunteer companies that don't follow the rules, making
CVS and Walgreen test cases.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island-based CVS and Walgreen of Illinois both said they
were obeying state limits on discharges of silver to the sewer
system in their first self-certifications, filed last September.
But the Department of Environmental Protection found violations at
50 CVS and 35 Walgreens photo-processing shops around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the violations centered on the two chains' failure to
test the discharge from the photo-processing machines to determine
silver levels and their lack of proof that employees regularly
changed special filters that remove silver from the
photo-processing waste water.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave generic answers that did not meet the reality,''
said Steven DeGabriele, the Department of Environmental
Protection's director of business compliance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the chains were cited for 12 violations each for
not filing certification forms for new stores.
</P>
<P>
   However, because CVS and Walgreen were among the first group of
volunteers to test the Environmental Results Program, the
Department of Environmental Protection levied relatively light
penalties. CVS agreed to pay $32,500 and Walgreen will pay $22,500
under separate consent agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Struhs said the penalties, while modest, probably would not have
been levied at all under the old system because the Department of
Environmental Protection doesn't have enough inspectors to check
out small discharge violations at 85 far-flung photo-processing
shops. Now, he said, the burden is on executives to take
responsibility even for small sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
