<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0566 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5631 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-FAMILIES-COX     06-24 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-FAMILIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `It has to run its course,' E. coli survivors say
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- In Laura Day's first semester in college, she took a
science class the hard way: in a hospital bed for seven weeks. The
University of Alabama student developed hemolytic uremic syndrome
after eating a hamburger from a fast-food place on the Tuscaloosa,
Ala., campus. The cause: E. coli O157:H7, a sinister bacteria she
knew little about.
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a bad case of the runs turned into near
death. Her parents drove up from Florida and never left her side
from early November until Dec. 27, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came into the hospital with complete kidney failure,'' said
Day, now 22 and living in Fort Walton Beach, Fla., with her college
degree in hand. ``I was unconscious in the ICU for four to five
days. My lungs filled with fluid, I had respiratory failure, needed
a respirator and at one time, completely stopped breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   Intravenous feeding, dialysis machines and a last-ditch
treatment that completely replaced her poisoned plasma kept her
alive. She also endured surgery to remove her spleen, chemotherapy
to cleanse her blood, constant steroids and the exhaustion of
constant dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Hope and wait. And then hope and wait some more. That's all the
doctors _ and her family _ could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing they can do to fight the bacteria. It has to
run its course. They treat the symptoms; they can't treat the
bacteria because nothing kills it,'' said Day, who would like
Atlanta to be the first stop in her career in international
marketing or public relations.
</P>
<P>
   She's already getting a start in publicity as a member of
S.T.O.P., Safe Tables Our Priority, a grassroots group of E. coil
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about any of this before, and certainly not
when I went to eat a hamburger because I used to eat a lot of
them,'' said Day, who no longer eats red meat. ``But my case proves
it can happen to anyone. I was a healthy 18-year-old collgee
student. I'd been on the dance team and been very active. Then all
of a sudden I had E. coli and I was dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it can happen to anyone. People need to realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   Damion Heersink of Dothan, Ala., was 11 years old when E. coli
O157:H7 almost killed him. It came from eating a tiny piece of
hamburger he innocently nibbled off a tray during a Boy Scout
cookout.
</P>
<P>
   Heersink also was hospitalized for seven weeks. Day by day,
another organ failed, another threat loomed. He came out OK and
today, at age 18, has become an advocate for safer meat practices,
along with his mother, Mary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a roller coaster ride of panic and dread, relief, then
panic again when something else goes wrong,'' she said. ``That's
what these Atlanta parents are going through right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine what these little kids are going through,''
Damion added. ``I understood what was going on. These little ones
have no comprehension.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those in public health are not immune from the E. coli
O157:H7 that's estimated annually in the United States to sicken
20,000 people a year, although activists say the toll is greater.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Howard, a communications specialist with the U.S. Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention, became a statistic of the
infectious disease before he became a collecter of such statistics
at Atlanta's national office.
</P>
<P>
   A quick stop at a roadside cafe driving to Sacramento, Calif.,
left Howard with a memorable New Year's Eve 1991. He spent it _ and
the next three days _ running in circles from the couch to the
bathroom. In the U.S. Army at the time, Howard learned it was E.
coli after a military doctor decided to conduct a test for it and
got back a positive result.
</P>
<P>
   Howard spent the next three days in misery but gradually
regained his strength and appetite, a typical course the strain
sets off in milder cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine what it must be like for a child to go through
the advanced form of E. coli,'' Howard said. ``I was 40 years old
then and it was hell. The amount of fluids I lost in 48 hours was
just incredible. But I wasn't really that sick in comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
