<HEADER>
A5632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-MAIN-COX     06-24 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More cases of E. coli showing up
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The E. coli outbreak that has severely sickened
several area children has grown to a potential 20 cases in Georgia
and up to 10 in six other states, authorities said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But because very few have been confirmed by laboratory analysis,
and not all have links to White Water park in Cobb County where at
least some of the children are believed to have been infected, the
scope of the outbreak may not be known for days.
</P>
<P>
   The state Division of Public Health said seven Georgia cases of
infection by the E. coli O157:H7 strain have been confirmed by lab
culture. Six of them are known to have visited White Water, and
five are hospitalized with hemolytic uremic syndrome, a potentially
life-threatening complication.
</P>
<P>
   An eighth child has been diagnosed with the syndrome, but has
not been proved to be infected with O157:H7, a bacterium that
releases a toxin capable of destroying blood cells and kidney
function. And 12 to 15 additional cases with symptoms likely to be
caused by the particular strain of bacteria _ chiefly bloody
diarrhea _ have been reported by hospitals or private doctors and
have test results pending.
</P>
<P>
   Outside state borders, the health agency has learned of seven
children in four states it would not identify who have the
symptoms; all of them visited White Water recently, but none has
been tested.
</P>
<P>
   And in a demonstration of how complicated the investigation has
become, the health department also learned Wednesday that test
results on two sick children in Tennessee who visited White Water
were not sent to the agency, but relayed via phone by a parent. In
addition, they discovered that a South Carolina child whose
infection had been thought to be lab-confirmed had not in fact been
tested _ and might never have visited the White Water park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many leads, and the numbers are changing very
rapidly,'' said Joyce Goldberg, director of communications for the
Division of Public Health. ``As we finish with suspected cases, we
find that there are more links.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the problem, health workers said, is that some
children who were infected may not have exhibited symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Among them: Bo Weiss, youngest son of Atlanta Braves shortstop
Walt Weiss. The baseball player said Wednesday that while
11-month-old Bo has tested positive for E. coli, he has shown no
symptoms. Meanwhile, Weiss's 3-year-old son, Brody, remains
hospitalized from severe symptoms of E. coli infection.
</P>
<P>
   Blood work performed Wednesday confirmed Bo had not developed
the hemolytic uremic syndrome that has left Brody in serious
condition and is being treated with dialysis.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be some more blood work (Thursday). If that's OK,
he's pretty much out of the woods,'' Weiss said of the younger
child.
</P>
<P>
   The family spent most of June 11 at White Water, but only the
two youngest boys spent any significant amount of time in the
Captain Kid's Cove kiddie pool area, where health officials believe
the E. coli cases were spread. Oldest son Blake, 11, did not test
positive for E. coli; neither did the boys' parents.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials said Wednesday that -- ome children in the
initial cluster _ believed to all have been infected in one kiddie
pool on June 11 and 12 _ may subsequently have infected others in a
``second generation'' of cases. That may be the explanation for one
of the out-of-state cases reported Wednesday _ a 3-year-old who did
visit White Water, but not until June 17. The toddler has Georgia
relatives who might have been infected earlier, the health agency
said. They have shown mild symptoms, but are in transit to another
set of out-of-state relatives and could not be reached immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The detective work was being conducted in an atmosphere of
intense concern, with the state's E. coli hotline logging more than
80 calls an hour. Most of them came from worried parents; none
produced any additional cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are legitimate calls for the people who are calling,''
said Dr. Scott Kellerman an epidemiologist from the U.S. Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention on long-term loan to the state
health agency. ``It's a scary disease. But when we talk to them, it
turns out that the majority are folks who took their kids to White
Water at some point, and then heard about some connection between
the disease and White Water, but whose kids were never exposed.''
</P>
<P>
   State health officials said they may never prove absolutely
White Water was the source of the infection, though the
epidemiologic evidence is overwhelming. The Cobb County water park
``is the only common characteristic,'' said Mel Ralstona CDC public
health adviser working with the state. A handful of Georgia
children remained in Atlanta hospitals Wednesday with symptoms of
E. coli infection, though it wasn't clear whether they all belonged
to the White Water outbreak. Two children, a 5-year-old boy and a
4-year-old girl, were admitted Tuesday night to Scottish Rite
Hospital, spokeswoman Staci Flaxer said Wednesday. She would not
give any information on their condition or whether they had been to
White Water Park.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish Rite is treating three other children for E. coli. In
addition to Brody Weiss, two girls, ages 2 and 4, are in critical
condition in the intensive care unit. All three children entered
the hospital between June 15 and June 20, Flaxer said.
</P>
<P>
   Egleston Children's Hospital is treating three children,
including a 3-year-old boy in fair condition and two sisters, ages
2 and 6, who are in good condition.
</P>
<P>
   Neither hospital would release patient names, hometowns or any
other information. They said the parents did not wish to talk about
their children at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Kurylo contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
