<HEADER>
A5633 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BAD100-TEX     06-24 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BAD100-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GREATEST MOVIES' LIST LEFT OFF BLACKS AND A WHOLE LOT MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one should be surprised that last week's list of the 100
greatest movies, as announced by the American Film Institute, is
overtly middlebrow and sentimental. Burt Reynolds wept when
discussing ``To Kill a Mockingbird'' _ tears he may have been
saving up since losing the Best Supporting Actor Oscar to Robin
Williams. And poor Dustin Hoffman was so narcissistic that he cried
about ``Tootsie.'' But more unfortunately, the program _ and the
list _ seems racist as well.
</P>
<P>
   The only movie starring an African-American, the rapidly
mildewing ``Guess Who's Coming to Dinner,'' is No. 99, several
notches behind the homeboy-wannabe atmosphere of ``Pulp Fiction.''
And it is well below the racist classics ``Birth of a Nation,'' and
``Gone With the Wind,'' which was edged out of the No. 1 slot by,
thank God, ``Citizen Kane.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been less than 30 years since the first African-American
directed a major studio picture _ Gordon Parks' ``The Learning
Tree'' _ and I was appalled to not hear any mention of the
exclusionary nature of the film selections, especially after
Reynolds' sobbing about the nature of race relations. I should
mention here that I'm an African-American, and after the horrible
ad hoc hate killing that took place in this state not long ago, I
think it's time for art to take a stand about the important brand
of omission.
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to say that the elegant Poitier's best work was
``Guess Who's Coming to Dinner,'' in which he was engaged to a
woman so unworthy of him that some joked that his character was a
gay African trying to get a green card. The list of 400 movies
eligible for inclusion includes a picture that was the best
showcase of Poitier's work: ``In the Heat of the Night,'' where
Poitier's elongated, innate superiority is the butt of the joke. By
foisting ``The Joy Luck Club'' onto the voters _ mercifully, it
didn't make the final selection either _ the AFI made evident how
little diversity exists in the American cinema.
</P>
<P>
   The list is a belated effort to celebrate the 100th anniversary
of film and was promulgated by the American Film Institute, which
advances and preserves American film. The films were chosen by
1,500 filmmakers, film critics, randomly selected filmgoers and
prominent citizens to represent the 100 ``definitive'' American
movies made between 1896 and 1996. And the announcement special was
merely part of the hoopla: Now comes a 10-part TNT series that will
explore in depth the selected films. Later, a Turner Classic Movies
festival will showcase the films; video companies will release
winners in deluxe box sets.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest-movies special, however, was the first splash of
the effort. Unfortunately, it often felt just like an infomercial,
although with a much more horrifying group of commentators,
including such film scholars as Larry King and Brooke Shields.
Hearing King growl about why he hated Louise Fletcher in ``One Flew
Over the Cuckoo's Nest'' had about as much cultural weight as
listening to a 6-year-old go on about the relative merits of Power
Rangers Beetleborgs vs. original-recipe Power Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably understandable that the American Film Institute
put itself on the corner and did the stroll, since its federal
funding has been drying up and there are rumors that AFI is in
danger of closing. I'm not sure that excused Tommy Lasorda missing
the point of ``Patton,'' which he said represents the best of
America. Does that mean he misses the days of slapping rookie
centerfielders after they dropped pop-up flies? It seemed that
Lasorda's appearance, and that of Susan Lucci and her hair as well
_ Susan Lucci! _ was to legitimize Larry King. At least King has
been in a movie.
</P>
<P>
   And imagine the howls of laughter at Newt Gingrich's house as
President William Jefferson Clinton murmured rapturously about
``High Noon,'' and Gary Cooper's insistence on doing what was
right. At this point, hearing Clinton lecture on moral courage is
about like having Ronald McDonald criticize your taste in clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The original list of 1,500 films is almost as horrifying as the
100 that the participants selected. For example, the films culled
from 1979 include ``Kramer vs. Kramer,'' but leave out ``Richard
Pryor Live in Concert,'' which features one of the greatest
performances in the history of film. Not to mention the omission of
the wonderful comedies of Buster Keaton and director Ernst
Lubitsch.
</P>
<P>
   If the top-100 list was created to provoke controversy, then
it's one of the few successes the AFI has had this decade. No one
seems to be sure if the list was supposed to include only American
films _ remember what the AFI is an acronym for. If so, how to
explain the inclusion of ``The Third Man'' _ one of the few great
films to make the cut _ or ``Bridge on the River Kwai?'' Or
``Lawrence of Arabia,'' which has hardly any Americans in it?
</P>
<P>
   Among the films that also merited inclusion are ``On the
Waterfront'' and ``A Streetcar Named Desire,'' which has made even
more noticeable the omission of director Elia Kazan from the list
of movie pioneers to have received the American Film Institute's
Lifetime Achievement Award. This is an organization that has given
the Lifetime Achievement Award to the man who starred in ``Every
Which Way But Loose'' _ Clint Eastwood.
</P>
<P>
   It's been said that the AFI hasn't honored Kazan because he
named names to the House Un-American Activities Committee, an act
that he has spent a length of time equal to Eastwood's career
apologizing for. It's a little juvenile to rule out a compromise,
especially after hurling this list at the wall to see if it'll
stick. Eastwood supported George Bush, a president who had to be
browbeaten into extending the expired Civil Rights Acts of 1964, a
gesture surely as cowardly as being stalked by the FBI and giving
up friends' names.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this will make the organization rethink its stance on
Kazan. If so, at least one good thing will have come out of it.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
