<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0569 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5634 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-RESEARCH-COX     06-24 0356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-RESEARCH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia researchers study arsenal of bacteria killers
 &HT;    By J. Matthew Aldag
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- As E. coli outbreaks become increasingly common,
Georgia researchers are experimenting with a variety of new
techniques _ using everything from lasers to ``beneficial''
bacteria _ to detect and combat the deadly bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Although none of the experimental methods are currently in use,
food safety experts believe they could lead to better ways to head
off or contain E. coli 0157:H7 infections, which sicken up to
20,000 Americans and kill 200 each year.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech researchers have developed a laser that can
instantly detect the presence of E. coli in suspect foods, like
ground beef. This device, called a ``biosensor,''could one day be
part of a food processing plant and be tailored to look for ``any
bacterial organism,'' said Georgia Tech researcher Craig Wyvill.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, similar to the laser beam on a CD player, passes
a laser through meat or other foods. If E. coli is present, it
alters the beam, marking the food as contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working on detection sensitivity,'' said Wyvill, who
said researchers believe the technique could be refined to provide
readings within minutes. Current E. coli detection methods, which
use laboratory cultures, take up to eight hours. The technology is
still years from commercial release, but current estimates say a
single system could cost less than $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Doyle, director of the Center for Food Safety and
Quality Enhancement at the University of Georgia, has experimented
with another technique using strains of a naturally occurring
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked for beneficial bacteria that prevent the bad
bacteria from being carried in the intestinal tract of cattle,'' he
said in UGA's Research Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle's research found that E. coli was eliminated from infected
animals in less than three weeks after they were given a solution
containing the bacteria that neutralize E. coli.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
