A5639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-FAILING-SCHOOLS-NY     06-24 0272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FAILING-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS FAILING SCHOOLS ARE SCANTED BY DISTRICT ADMINISTRATORS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A two-year study released Wednesday by New York
University has found that officials at community school districts
in New York City treat persistently failing schools like orphans,
staffing them with poorly trained teachers and shuttling some
students in the districts to failing schools at all levels, from
elementary to high school.
</P>
<P>
   The NYU study of the Schools Under Registration Review _ the
state's list of schools with persistently low reading and math test
scores _ called on education officials in Albany to exert greater
pressure on the city's community school district superintendents.
</P>
<P>
   District officials, for instance, have the power to remove
principals and reassign teachers, and can redistribute students in
the district so that children who graduate from one low-performing
school do not end up in another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The districts knew for years they were failing and they turned
their attention elsewhere,'' said Norm Fruchter, the director of
the NYU Institute on Education and Social Policy and a co-author of
the report.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the report, which was commissioned by the state,
the education commissioner, Richard Mills, announced several
changes.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said, the state's review teams would provide
school staff members with more timely feedback on what they need to
do to lift themselves off of the SURR list and craft teacher
training programs to address the shortcomings identified by the
state review team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0574 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ZODIAC-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      06-24 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ZODIAC-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY FINDS BROOKLYN MAN GUILTY IN 3 ZODIAC KILLINGS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Heriberto Seda, a 30-year-old high school dropout and
loner from Brooklyn, was convicted Wednesday of being the Zodiac
killer, a mysterious gunman who terrorized the city and taunted the
police during two shooting sprees in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a six-week trial and after less than five hours of
deliberation, an emotional and visibly shaken jury filed into the
courtroom in state Supreme Court in Queens to announce that it had
found Seda guilty of killing three people and wounding one person
in Queens between 1990 and 1993. He faces a maximum penalty of 83
1/3 years to life in prison when he is sentenced on July 22.
</P>
<P>
   At least five jurors wept as the jury was polled.
</P>
<P>
   Seda, who had lashed out angrily on the first day of the trial,
stood impassively throughout Wednesday's short proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers said he was unemotional because he had been prepared
to hear the guilty verdict. They said they planned to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Seda's mother sat quietly in the last row of the courtroom as
the verdict was read against her son, who prosecutors said chose
his victims at random, looking for vulnerable people who could not
fight back.
</P>
<P>
   Seda, who is known as Eddie, has yet to stand trial in Brooklyn
for three Zodiac shootings and the shooting of his half-sister. He
has not yet been charged in the shooting of a homeless man in
Central Park for which the Zodiac killer also claimed credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was two years ago last Sunday that Eddie Seda was arrested
and I said at that time that the people of the city could heave a
sigh of relief that the Zodiac killer was in custody,'' the Queens
district attorney, Richard Brown, said. ``Today's verdict means he
will finally be brought to account for his evil deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he would ask the court ``to require him to spend the
rest of his life in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   The `Zodiac killer' name stemmed from the killer's letters to
the media and the police in which he said he would kill one person
for each sign of the zodiac.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Masters, the assistant district attorney who argued the
case, said that Wednesday's emotional outpouring by the jury was
probably due to a great sense of relief. ``But I think the jurors
also were very absorbed in the sadness of the victims,'' he said,
``and I think it was a very difficult thing for them to call a
human being just about the worst thing that you can call him _ a
serial killer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zodiac killer's victims were primarily from the margins of
society, many of them homeless and physically and mentally weak.
</P>
<P>
   Seda, who had eluded the police for six years, was convicted of
17 crimes involving the four victims, including murder, assault and
criminal possession of a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Seda's other lawyer, John Wallenstein, said that as the lawyers
in the case spoke to the jurors after the hearing, ``the jurors
indicated that they really analyzed everything and essentially
looked for ways to find reasonable doubt and to find him innocent
if they could, but they were obviously unable to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Scheer, the other assistant district attorney who tried
the case, spoke of the mountain of evidence that was presented to
the jury during the trial _ including the testimony of 45 witnesses
and 150 pieces of evidence. ``I think, like the police officers who
were involved in the case, the jurors are somehow going to be
affected by this case for the rest of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallenstein, said he was not surprised by the verdict. ``We felt
that the jury took the time to analyze everything, but there was so
much evidence,'' he said. ``They had everything but an eyewitness.
And in the end, there's only so much you can do with that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
