<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5642 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-DAVIES-NYT &LR;      06-24 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DAVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISE DAVIES, 98, SAN FRANCISCO BENEFACTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Louise Davies, the San Francisco benefactor who gave the city
she loved a $5 million concert hall in 1980, died on Monday at a
retirement home in Portola Valley, Calif. She was 98.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Davies, whose husband, Ralph Davies, an oil millionaire,
died in 1971, bestowed millions of dollars on many cultural,
educational and medical charities in the Bay Area, including the
Exploratorium, the World Affairs Council, the Conservatory of
Music, the University of San Francisco, Stanford University and the
San Francisco Opera.
</P>
<P>
   But she will no doubt be best remembered as the benefactor of
the 3,000-seat, modern concert hall on Van Ness Avenue that bears
her name, the home of the San Francisco Symphony. Before the hall
was built, the orchestra had to share the War Memorial building
with the San Francisco Opera.
</P>
<P>
   The completion of Davies Symphony Hall, next door to the opera
house, allowed the orchestra to expand to a full 52-week season and
add additional players. After the hall opened, she gave another $3
million as a fund to attract leading guest conductors. One of the
first to come was Michael Tilson Thomas, who became the orchestra's
music director three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   When asked by an interviewer in 1990 why she had financed the
building, Mrs. Davies, a down-to-earth woman, said simply,
``Because I had the money, and we certainly needed the hall.'' In
that same interview, she added: ``I'm just learning after all these
years that I have quite a lot of money. Isn't that something?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Davies was born fairly poor, on a remote cattle ranch in
Plumas County. When her parents divorced, her mother moved with
Louise and her three other daughters, eventually settling in
Oakland, Calif., where Louise attended a Catholic boarding school.
As a young woman, she held a $25-per-week job as a stenographer in
Oakland for seven years, then moved to Los Angeles to try her
chances at film acting. There she met her future husband, a young
executive with Standard Oil. They married in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Davies rose to the rank of vice president of Standard Oil. But
when the presidency eluded him, he left and formed his own oil
company. He also ran American President Lines and Natomas Co. In
1934 the couple bought 20 acres in Woodside, Calif., where in 1940
they built a magnificent house, which Mrs. Davies lived in until
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by her daughter, Maryon Davies Lewis of San
Francisco, five grandchildren and five great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Mrs. Davies on Monday, Nancy Bechtle, the president
of the San Francisco Symphony Board, said, ``The crowning glory of
her life was that hall, and every time she walked in, she was just
thrilled to be there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0576 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5644 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CA-SMOKEBAN-LADN     06-24 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CA-SMOKEBAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE SENATOR'S BILL LOOKS TO REVISE SMOKING BAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY PAUL HEFNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ State Sen. W.J. ``Pete'' Knight has reignited the
smoldering debate over California's smoking ban by agreeing to
carry legislation to allow some bars to exempt themselves from the
law.
</P>
<P>
   The bill by Knight, R-Palmdale, would let smoking resume in
bars, taverns and card clubs if employees consent to working amid
cigarette smoke or if bar owners install state-approved ventilation
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the legislation that is in place is too
restrictive on small business,'' Knight said Wednesday. ``I believe
small businesses should be allowed to determine what kind of
business they have. If their clientele says we don't want a smoking
bar, they won't have one.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's workplace ban on smoking went into effect Jan. 1 for
bars, taverns and card rooms. Though anti-smoking groups hailed the
move, the ban has been under attack by smokers, some bar owners,
the tobacco industry and organizations they support, including the
National Smokers Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance, partially funded by three tobacco companies, is
sponsoring Knight's measure, SB 1513, which is scheduled to be
heard Monday in an Assembly committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly earlier passed its own version of a bill to repeal
the ban, but the measure has languished in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Knight's bill, originally introduced as a measure on horse
racing, passed the Senate before it was rewritten to address the
smoking ban.
</P>
<P>
   The wholesale changes to the measure had anti-smoking groups
crying foul, claiming that Knight had used a legislative sleight of
hand to put the issue on a fast track through the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that a legislator would try to do an end run
around the normal legislative process in order to enact
special-interest legislation that will harm California workers,''
said Alan Henderson, president of the state chapter of the American
Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   But Knight defended his tactics, noting that the Assembly
measure repealing the ban was never allowed to come up for a Senate
committee vote.
</P>
<P>
   If the Assembly passes Knight's bill, a final vote on
concurrence would be required in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm perfectly within the process,'' he said. ``I don't know
that I'm bypassing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of a new attempt to repeal the smoking ban came as the
state Department of Health Services announced that a March survey
found that 66 percent of bar patrons believe it's important to have
smoke-free bars. Alliance officials said the survey was dated and
claimed the department hadn't disclosed all its findings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
