u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAPALM-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      06-24 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAPALM-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FIRMS VYING FOR RAIL CARS FILLED WITH NAPALM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Filed in ``a'' and ``w'' categories) 
 
By T.J. MILLING 
and GREG MCDONALD 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Rail cars filled with 22,000 gallons of napalm may be
headed for a Houston-area storage facility in as little as two
weeks, sparking protests from some politicians unhappy about being
notified only days ago.
</P>
<P>
   GNI Group Inc. of Deer Park, an industrial city of 30,000 about
15 miles east of downtown Houston, is vying with Waste Control
Specialists, a West Texas company, for the contract to temporarily
store the jellied gasoline, according to a government memo.
</P>
<P>
   The winner may gain the inside track for a $2.5 million deal to
recycle 3.3 million gallons of the toxic substance that has been
stored at a Navy weapons station near San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Three other Texas firms, based in San Leon, El Paso and Port
Arthur, are seeking the recycling contract in competition with
companies in Utah and Wisconsin, the memo said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the public reaction to the Navy's efforts to recycle the
34,000 aluminum canisters of napalm _ and the 22,000 gallons in
rail tankers _ has been less than kind.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy was forced to scrap its plans earlier this year to
begin recycling the chemical in East Chicago, Ind., after negative
public reaction prompted the company that won the contract to turn
away a 12,000-gallon rail shipment.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy brought the napalm back to its facility in Fallbrook,
Calif., where another 10,000 gallons had been drawn for shipment.
</P>
<P>
   Once the napalm was placed in the tanker cars, environmental
regulations gave the Navy only 90 days to move it to a licensed
storage facility. For the 12,000 gallons, that deadline is July 8;
for the 10,000, July 15, according to the government memo.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Yocum, spokesman for Battelle Memorial Institute, an Ohio
company that holds the main napalm recycling contract, acknowledged
the time crunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would hope to get it done in the next several weeks,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas emerged as a likely home for the napalm when a number of
state-based companies that store and process chemicals showed
interest in the Navy contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush expressed concern about the toxic chemical
coming to Texas after being briefed by a high-level Navy official
Tuesday, spokeswoman Karen Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, GNI officials notified Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Houston,
that they were a serious candidate for the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first time we heard anything about it,'' said
Bentsen, whose office then contacted the Navy. Officials then set
about trying to brief members of the Texas congressional
delegation, claiming that they had already begun ``a public
outreach program.''
</P>
<P>
   But the program had not reached Rep. Nick Lampson, D-Beaumont,
by late Wednesday afternoon. Two of the companies bidding on the
recycling contracts are located in his southeast Texas district.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me the issue is not necessarily the napalm, but the manner
in which (the Navy) has handled it,'' Lampson said. ``I'm sure
opposed to moving so quickly that we don't know the answers to a
bunch of questions that ought to be asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen said he was ``somewhat perturbed that the Navy has just
dropped this in everybody's lap like it's no big deal,'' noting
that napalm is a mixture of gasoline, highly toxic benzene and
polystyrene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be concerned about the movement of it, and the
public needs to be adequately notified about it,'' Bentsen said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to contacting the governor and congressional
delegation, GNI notified, the mayor of Deer Park and Houston Mayor
Lee Brown, who will meet with company officials Thursday, spokesman
Don Payne said. The Houston Fire Department Hazardous Materials
team has also been notified.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the images of death and destruction that napalm evokes,
once detonators are removed from the canisters, it is a more stable
substance than gasoline, hazardous waste experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no new or overbearing safety issues,'' said Bill
Reeves, GNI's vice president of regulatory affairs. ``Once they
take that cordex explosive out of the canister, it's neutered. The
bark is off the dog.''
</P>
<P>
   University of Houston organic chemistry professor Randall Lee
confirmed that napalm is as safe as gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   GNI's Reeves said the public outcry in Indiana was caused by
inflammatory media accounts complete with Vietnam-era footage of
napalm exploding.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lack of communication, and there was some
politics, and all of a sudden everything was inflamed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But worries about safety persist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has not been handled well at all,'' said Bentsen. ``They
need to come out and make a statement about how they are proposing
to do this and give the public a chance to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporter Greg McDonald contributed to this story from
Washington, D.C. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
