<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0578 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5647 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-GUNSBERG-NYT &LR;      06-24 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GUNSBERG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHELDON GUNSBERG, 78, FILM DISTRIBUTOR  
 (ATTN: N.J.) 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sheldon Gunsberg, a film producer and distributor who
later headed the Walter Reade chain of movie theaters in New York,
died last Thursday of a heart attack at his home in Manhattan. He
was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Jersey City, N.J., Gunsberg served in the U.S. Merchant
Marine during World War II, and then entered the film industry,
promoting the 1945 version of ``Henry V,'' starring Laurence
Olivier, for United Artists. He joined Universal Pictures as a
publicist in 1948, where he directed advertising and marketing for
films including ``The Lavender Hill Mob'' and ``Kind Hearts and
Coronets.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, he joined the Walter Reade Organization, whose
principal Manhattan theaters included the Ziegfeld, the Coronet and
the Baronet. He was named chief operating officer in 1971. In 1973,
Walter Reade Jr., the chain's president, was killed in a skiing
accident in Switzerland and Gunsberg succeeded him.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Walter Reade Organization was a nationwide
theater chain with about 80 movie houses, but it was plagued by
financial losses. The company filed for federal bankruptcy
protection in 1977, and its holdings were whittled down to 10
theaters in the New York area before it emerged from bankruptcy in
1981.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the executors of Reade's estate, Gunsberg was charged
with finding a buyer for his 31 percent stake in the company.
Columbia Pictures bought it in 1981. But a year later, Gunsberg
said he regretted that deal, because Columbia backed an attempted
takeover of the company. Columbia eventually acquired the Walter
Reade chain outright in 1985, then sold it to Cineplex Odeon in
1987. Gunsberg retired as chief executive just before the Cineplex
Odeon deal.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure with the Walter Reade company, Gunsberg also
headed its Continental Distributing subsidiary, which distributed
and often financed or produced many notable foreign films. Among
them were the British ``Saturday Night and Sunday Morning,'' the
French ``Mon Oncle,'' and ``War and Peace,'' from the Soviet Union.
It also produced and distributed the American films ``Ulysses'' and
``A View From the Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   At his death, Gunsberg was chairman of the Walter Reade
Foundation and vice chairman of the Film Society of Lincoln Center,
whose Walter Reade Theater he was instrumental in creating.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 53 years, Lois; two daughters,
Mayra Bloom of Nyack and Donna Lerner of Manhattan, and two
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0579 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5660 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-CURRY-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-24 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CURRY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TOP BRAVES, FOR NOW ANYWAY
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ David Cone has been too politically correct while
discussing Recent baseball history this week, nodding his head
robotically while speculating that the Braves might have been
better than the Yankees in 1996. Maybe the Yankees were simply a
team of destiny two years ago, Cone theorized. Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Cone is too savvy to gloat about the diamond-filled
World Series ring that he slips on and off, the pitcher surely
believes that the Yankees were the better club in 1996 and, right
now, they are the better club again. Obviously, it is only June,
but what the mighty Braves and the mightier Yankees have
accomplished so far is the best and freshest evidence available for
making a comparison. And the Yankees prevail today.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever edge the Braves have with their formidable starting
rotation, which is the same advantage they supposedly had in 1996,
is eclipsed by the Yankees' superior bullpen, their superior depth,
their slightly superior offense and, one more time for emphasis,
their superior bullpen. If Ramiro Mendoza wandered into Atlanta's
bullpen tonight, the Braves would make him the closer. It would be
a shrewd decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen is something they've got to get together,'' Cone
said. ``That's big.''
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the reasons why, regardless of what happens in the
final two games of this interleague matchup between the two best
teams in the major leagues, I still think Joe Torre will awaken on
Friday feeling more secure about his team than Bobby Cox will feel
about his bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I need to find out about my club,'' Torre
said. ``I'm not trying to be smart. I really feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cox, who desperately needs Mark Wohlers to emerge
from his funk and right a relief corps that has botched eight save
opportunities, countered by saying, ``I know my team. We're not
going to find out anything by playing the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Cone imitates Pataki or Giuliani by uttering what he
thinks is safe to say about 1996, instead of what he actually
thinks, it is the 35-year-old pitcher churning into PC overdrive.
Does anyone believe Cone felt the 1996 Braves were better than the
Yankees? Then, today or in 2016? Absolutely not. The Yankees may
even have a psychological edge over the Braves, who might wonder if
this special team is destined.
</P>
<P>
   All it would take to challenge Cone's words _ and perhaps get
him to show that sly smile _ would be some quick reminders. More
baseball history. Flash back to the World Series and remember how
the Yankees trailed, 2-0, with Cone starting Game 3 in Atlanta. One
more defeat would have been like losing twice since no team had
ever rallied from a 3-0 deficit to win a four-of-seven-game Series.
New York's hopes rested with Cone, who was not thinking about
destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Cone was ornery that night, ornery that the Braves had seemed a
little too cocky and a little too comfortable while walloping the
Yankees by a combined score of 16-1 at Yankee Stadium. Sure, the
Braves had the right to feel cozy, but Cone seized upon it and used
it as his edge, his motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the mindset of the team was we were a little
embarrassed in New York,'' Cone said at the time. ``I think
everyone in the city was into the Series and we didn't give them
anything to cheer about.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Atlanta. Until Cone began showing why the Yankees were the
better team. The Braves filled the bases with one out in the sixth
and New York's 2-0 spread suddenly looked puny. But Cone got Fred
McGriff to pop out to shortstop before Torre visited him. Ryan
Klesko was the batter and Mariano Rivera, the super setup man, was
ready. Torre's dark brown eyes studied Cone's fiery brown eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me do this,'' Cone pleaded. ``I can get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone later admitted, ``I lied, but I had to get him through the
sixth.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone walked Klesko with a 3-2 pitch that strayed inches out of
the strike zone. The score was sliced to 2-1. But Cone rebounded.
No destiny, just better pitching. Just Javier Lopez popping up to
Joe Girardi in foul territory. To that point, it was the most
important out in the Series as the Yankees won, 5-2, to begin a
dramatic comeback that would show everyone they were indeed better.
</P>
<P>
   Without it, who knows if Jim Leyritz goes deep off Mark Wohlers
in Game 4, if Paul O'Neill makes a lunging, game-ending catch in
Game 5 or if Charlie Hayes squeezes the popout to climax Game 6?
Or, who knows if these plays would have been as critical. Leyritz's
homer is not so devastating if it helps make the Series 3-1, not
2-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the Leyritz homer, we go home,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   Let Cone keep appeasing his PC instincts. Let him throw the
Braves a 2-year-old bone about wondering if they were better. Let
him do this while the Yankees pursue their second title in three
years. Let him be. Just don't believe every word you hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were they the better team?'' Cone asked once more. ``Maybe.''
</P>
<P>
   Not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980624.0580 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-24 23:03 </DATE_TIME>
