A5836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BADILLO-NYT &LR;      06-24 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BADILLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC LEADER HERMAN BADILLO TO SWITCH TO REPUBLICAN PARTY  
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Herman Badillo, a former U.S. representative, deputy
mayor and mayoral candidate, and a fixture in Hispanic politics in
New York for more than 40 years, has decided to quit the Democratic
Party and become a Republican, associates familiar with his
decision said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They said Badillo, 68, would announce his political shift
Thursday at a press conference attended by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
a Republican and his most visible political ally in recent years.
The announcement will also be attended by representatives of the
Republican National Committee, the associated said. Their presence
suggests the symbolic importance Republicans will try to attach to
Badillo's switch at a time the party has sought to make inroads in
a voting group once viewed as solidly Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, Badillo's announcement is no surprise. His
alliance with Giuliani and his increasing advocacy of Republican
positions on issues from education to welfare have strained his
relations with Democratic leaders over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, for many New Yorkers, the announcement will come
as a shock and an indication of the changing face of ethnic
politics in this and other cities. Badillo has been one of the most
visible faces of the Hispanic advance in mainstream politics since
he was elected Bronx borough president in 1965, and then a
congressman from the South Bronx in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, his switch in party allegiance is the latest
evidence that as a group, Hispanic voters in New York and across
the country are very much up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Badillo did not return phone calls seeking comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, and the way it is being presented, seemed to
have as much to do with the political fortunes of Giuliani as they
do for Badillo. Giuliani has sought in recent months to present
himself as a candidate with national potential. His ability to
boast that he brought a prominent Hispanic politician into
Republican ranks would permit him to argue that this is another way
he could expand the party's reach.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any obvious political gain to Badillo, it would be
if he were to try yet again to run for mayor. He could do it in
2000, when Giuliani is not eligible to run again, in the much less
crowded Republican field.
</P>
<P>
   Although Badillo is expected to say Thursday that he is
supporting the candidacies of both major Republicans, Gov. George
Pataki and Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, seeking re-election this year,
only Giuliani is scheduled to appear with him as he makes his
announcement, Badillo's associates said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has extensive ties to Badillo. The two ran on what
Giuliani called a fusion ticket in 1993. Badillo ran as a
Republican candidate for comptroller. Giuliani was supposed to
officiate at Badillo's second marriage two years ago (a delayed
helicopter flight forced him to miss it). And Badillo is a partner
in the politically connected law firm of Raymond B. Harding, the
Liberal Party leader, and one of the mayor's closest advisers.
</P>
<P>
   He is also vice chairman of the board of the City University of
New York, where he was one of the mayor's allies in his
controversial though successful bid to eliminate remedial courses
at the system's senior colleges. He was one of the most insistent
advocates of Giuliani's proposals, which drew a furious response
from many quarters, including Hispanic groups, which argued that it
would hurt disadvantaged students trying to make their mark in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Democrats were quick to minimize the significance
of the defection. ``This announcement merely confirms what we
already know,'' said Matthew Hiltzik, the press secretary for the
state Democratic Party. ``Mr. Badillo has a long-standing
relationship with the mayor and the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic community in New York, though overwhelmingly
Democratic, is nonetheless far from unified in its political and
cultural beliefs. Giuliani, with his emphasis on anticrime measures
and social conservatism, has struck a chord with many Hispanic
voters.
</P>
<P>
   And Badillo, associates said, had been moved by Giuliani's
political success and by the mayor's denunciation of Democratic
policies that he says have failed to address urban problems.
</P>
<P>
   Badillo is clearly a figure of huge stature in New York's
Hispanic community, especially among Puerto Ricans like himself. He
is regularly afforded a hero's reception at the annual Puerto Rican
Day Parade, especially by the older attendees, who remember him as
the vibrant Bronx borough president and then congressman. He was
also a deputy mayor under Edward Koch.
</P>
<P>
   His announcement comes as, in New York City and across the
country, there have been indications of some political shifts among
Hispanic voters, and as that vote has become increasingly
influential, Giuliani enjoys strong support among Latino voters,
recent polls have shown.
</P>
<P>
   And while Democrats remain the overwhelming party of choice
among this group, there are some signs of small changes that
several analysts suggested could only be advanced by Badillo's
decision. Douglas Muzzio, director of the Baruch College, which has
conducted regular polls for the Hispanic Federation of New York
City, said he has seen regular evidence of some drifting away from
the Democratic Party, particularly among Latinos who are younger
and not of Puerto Rican descent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a major shift, but you can see some shifting
ground,'' Muzzio said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
