A5818 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARPRING25-COX     06-24 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARPRING25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harpring must have the magic
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For nearly three months, Georgia Tech small forward Matt
Harpring heard the rumors from doubters. Critics claimed he was too
slow and not athletic enough to excel in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, Harpring's undeniable determination and
tenacity, which often carried the young Yellow Jackets in his final
two collegiate seasons, paid off. After pre-draft speculation
placed him near the end of the first round of Wednesday night's NBA
Draft -- perhaps to No. 20 to the Atlanta Hawks -- Harpring was
selected with the 15th pick by the Orlando Magic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was a little surprised,'' Harpring said. ''I knew I had a
chance to go in the teens, but a lot of people had me going at No.
20 to Atlanta. A lot of people thought I was a ''tweener'' for the
NBA, but I don't think I am. I think I proved that playing in the
ACC for four years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Magic chose the Dunwoody native with their third first-round
pick. Orlando took Utah center Michael Doleac and UNLV power
forward Keon Clark with the Nos. 12 and 13 picks, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Harpring's pre-draft anxiety began after he injured his left
foot toward the end of his senior season at Georgia Tech. He
continued to play on the foot, which became progressively worse as
he attempted to remain sharp for NBA workouts. After missing the
pre-draft camps, Harpring finally worked out for Houston on June
16th; Orlando on June 18th and Minnesota on June 22nd.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would have loved to work out for 12 teams like everyone else
did,'' Harpring said. ''Unfortunately, my foot was injured and I
wasn't able to do it. My foot needed rest and I didn't do it. I
always play with pain and I thought it would go away. But my agent
(Atlanta-based Richard Howell) told me I had to start working out
with some teams because they were forgetting about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando coach Chuck Daly had eyed several forwards for his final
pick in the opening round. Besides Harpring, Orlando also had Notre
Dame's Pat Garrity and high-school phenoms Al Harrington of New
Jersey and Rashard Lewis of Texas in for workouts. Following
Harpring's visit, Magic general manager John Gabriel said the Tech
star had a ''Dan Majerle quality about him.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I was pleased,'' Howell said. ''I knew Orlando was seriously
considering him, along with Minnesota and Atlanta. What worried me
was him not being able to work out. He was able to work out for
Orlando, but he was limping badly. It wasn't the same Matt
Harpring.''
</P>
<P>
   Harpring, a 6-foot-6, 231-pound sharpshooter, produced one of
the most memorable careers in Georgia Tech history. He finished as
the Yellow Jackets' second-leading all-time scorer and rebounder,
falling only eight points short of Rick Yunkus' scoring record of
2,232 points.
</P>
<P>
   As a senior, Harpring averaged 21.6 points and 9.4 rebounds,
finishing second in the ACC in both categories behind North
Carolina's Antawn Jaminson. A first-team All-ACC selection and
third-team All-American in his final campaign, Harpring was only
the sixth Yellow Jacket to have his jersey retired.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
