<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACING-NOTEBOOK </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panoz urging peace between rival bodies
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Road Atlanta owner Don Panoz put more heat on the
feuding sanctioning bodies, U.S. Road Racing Championships and
Professional Sports Car Racing, during a press conference Sunday
about his American Le Mans Series.
</P>
<P>
   Asked who would sanction the series, Panoz said, ``We wish the
two organizations would get together. If it doesn't happen, I'll
assign the sanctioning body unilaterally. It may or may not be
them. The ball is in their court. I'm offering them a chance, not
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the CART-IRL fight, the USRRC-PSCR feud hasn't helped
either side.
</P>
<P>
   Venues for the proposed 11-event series include Sebring, Road
Atlanta, Lime Rock, Road America, Mosport, Portland and Laguna
Seca. What about Daytona, which hosts the 24 Hours of Daytona?
</P>
<P>
   ``They said we need to talk,'' Panoz said. It seems unlikely
that NASCAR czar Bill France, who owns Daytona, would give up
control.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Car Grand Prix
</P>
<P>
   It took only one lap for fans to know that Sunday's WSC/GT
Sports Car Grand Prix would be exciting. The Panoz No. 4 car,
fastest of a trio entered, started the race with four wheels, but
had only three when it came back around and made an early pit stop.
It played catch-up, a lap behind, until being knocked off the track
and slammed into a tire retaining wall. Tony Dow, managing director
of Panoz Motor Sports, said the team is still looking into the lost
wheel, which was one of several unlikely events _ No. 45 out with
gear box problems, No. 5 out of contention because of a broken prop
shaft _ that left the three strongest GT-1 cars in America out of
the money.
</P>
<P>
   Bazemore moves
</P>
<P>
   Whit Bazemore will join Team Chevrolet in the Nitro Funny Car
ranks, beginning with the Sears Craftsman Nationals this weekend.
Bazemore, 35, an Atlantan, who heads Bazemore Racing out of
Indianapolis, will switch from a Ford Mustang to a Camaro Z28 Funny
Car. ... Less than a month after he finished 11th in the
Indianapolis 500 as a rookie, Jimmy Kite of Stockbridge was back at
the Indianapolis Motor Speedway last week testing a stock car. Andy
Evans, owner of Team Scandia, decided to switch from the Indy
Racing League to stock car racing and hopes to debut in the NASCAR
Winston Cup Brickyard 400 on Aug. 1 at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
