<HEADER>
A5821 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LILITH-AZR &LR;      06-24 1695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILITH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTIFUL VOICES STRIKE CHORD WITH LILITH FAIR FANS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore _ Lollapalooza is dead. George Strait and company
already have passed through town. Now in its second year, Lilith
Fair stands as the music festival of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah McLachlan's brainchild opened last Friday in Portland. It
will hit 57 cities this summer, stopping Sunday at Blockbuster
Desert Sky Pavilion in Phoenix. And after critics carped about the
lack of diversity among last year's acts, McLachlan strived to meet
that question by offering a different mix of performers this year.
</P>
<P>
   Then again maybe the mix of artists isn't that important. It
didn't seem to be for the nearly 20,000 fans who showed up at the
Portland Civic Stadium, a baseball field oddly planted in the
middle of the city's bustling downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   No matter who was performing onstage, women of all ages, shapes
and sizes would stand off to the side of the mammoth stage and
dance. And it wasn't couples swaying romantically. Rather it
reflected people struggling to express them selves through
movement.
</P>
<P>
   The constant fluttering of arms and legs began right when Sinead
O'Connor took the stage under an uncommonly broiling sun. It contin
ued as dusk fell and a gentle breeze cooled off the crowd, which
failed to fill the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The rhythms and melodies in O'Connor's 35-minute opening set
were hardly danceable, but it didn't stop the throng to the side of
the stage. Rather unintentionally, O'Connor's performance _ Liz
Phair fills her spot in the Phoenix show _ illustrated what works
and what doesn't with the Lilith Fair concept.
</P>
<P>
   As opposed to most other music festivals, the emphasis here is
on pure, beautiful voices. It's not a guitar fest or a dance-off.
It's not a spectacle; the stage set was mini mal, save for two huge
banners that draped both sides of the stage, depicting Lilith and a
pair of angels.
</P>
<P>
   But with thousands of tipsy fans thrown into the mix, some occa
sional spectacle might not be a bad thing. O'Connor's introspective
six-song set showed off her lovely, if brittle, tones but seemed
more suited to a small cabaret setting than an overheated baseball
field mas querading as a concert venue.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful that onlookers in the bleachers could pick up on
the subtle touches in O'Connor's songs. In hushed moments, noise
from vendors and people waiting for bathrooms to open up leaked to
the stage, killing the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The sensitive nature of her songs was offset by her playful
mood. The Irish singer thanked the audience after each song,
affecting a different accent each time. She sounded like a fruity
English dame one minute; the next, she was a hick Minnie Pearl. It
was goofy but vaguely endearing.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in deference to the end less barbs about whining women
with guitars, McLachlan added R&AMP;B siren Erykah Badu to this year's
lineup. And in her striking head wrap and bold African garb, Badu
certainly was not as tradition ally Lilithesque as past headliners
Mary Chapin Carpenter and Paula Cole.
</P>
<P>
   That also goes to show you the impact that the festival has had:
Terms like Lilithesque have slipped into the vernacular. Already
stereo types about who and what make up the Lilith Fair crowd are
out there.
</P>
<P>
   Badu came close to greatness, at least in terms of her vocal
ability. She's got a sharp, tangy voice, which she placed over some
sinu ous, jazzy rhythms. She said on stage that Chaka Khan was one
of her heroes, but there are touches of Nancy Wilson and Sarah
Vaughan in her style as well.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying herself with the fluid movements of a dancer, Badu was
captivating to watch. On the other hand, her spacey, ethereal
patter seemed to go right over the heads of the crowd. She was
better when she stuck to vocalizing, particularly on Ye Yo, a
lovely lullaby to her son, Seven.
</P>
<P>
   She was followed by the Indigo Girls, perhaps the archetypal
Lilith act. The silk-and-sandpaper harmonies of Emily Saliers and
Amy Ray got a boost when McLachlan made a surprise appearance to
join voices on the hymn The Water Is Wide. Belgian group K's Choice
also turned up for one song, the closest the night ever came to a
jam session involving all the artists.
</P>
<P>
   That was a disappointment about the entire festival. There were
few surprises to be had. McLachlan had mentioned the artists
participating in loosely organized jam sessions, but apparently
those are held back stage, away from the eyes of the fans.
</P>
<P>
   The audience didn't need any guest stars to warm up to Natalie
Merchant. They greeted the ex-10,000 Maniacs front woman with a
rapturous cheer the moment she seemingly floated onstage in her
billowing outfit.
</P>
<P>
   The good mood continued, though the diminutive singer seemed
dwarfed by the large size of the stadium and the event. The gently
whimsical touches in her set _ a little box she stood on that was
painted with stars, or the red scarf that she twirled with abandon
_ were lost to the night.
</P>
<P>
   By the time McLachlan took the stage at 9:30, it was clear she
was the favorite. At one point, fans pushed down a barrier to get
closer to their heroine, causing a momen tary panic for concert
security.
</P>
<P>
   Her set was brief _ no one played for more than an hour _
featuring seven numbers. But the mix of her graceful soprano and
her smartly crafted songs was enticing.
</P>
<P>
   She offered a new song, Black and White, but it was the radio
hits that people responded to. The dis turbing Possession throbbed
with its dark undercurrents. Building a Mys tery and Sweet
Surrender also seemed punchier than on disc, thanks to a tight
six-piece band and McLachlan's arresting delivery.
</P>
<P>
   If McLachlan seemed sure-footed onstage, she was equally in com
mand at a press conference held earlier in the day. The women
fielded some puffball questions with relatively good humor, each
demon strating the kind of personality they later would exhibit
onstage.
</P>
<P>
   The waiflike McLachlan was sen sible and patient, seeming
comfort able in her newfound role as boss. Ray and Saliers were
upbeat cheer leaders, smiling and listening raptly when the other
artists talked.
</P>
<P>
   A subdued Merchant came off as shy and obviously brainy, the
smart girl who sat behind you in algebra but never said a word. A
goddess for all intelligent geeks, she also managed to work in
references to Swedish immigrants and use the word suffragette in
her conversation.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, wearing a shirt that said ``Jesus is coming,'' was re
served and cynical. O'Connor, who will miss the Phoenix show, had
the best quip when asked what she brought to the tour:
``Estrogen.''
</P>
<P>
   No one brought up any of the negative comments that have been
hurled at Lilith Fair: the lineup's lack of diversity or the
stereotypical perceptions that plague the festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys at work were all on me about this,'' said Craig
Russillo, a Portland attorney at the show. ``Like, why would you
want to go see a bunch of lesbians? But it's not like that. It's
about hearing some great music.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Indigo Girls being the only ``out'' headlining act,
that misconception should finally be put to rest. As for the
diversity of the bill, the acts that played the two smaller stages
_ only K's Choice will show up in Phoenix _ were a bit more
adventurous and colorful.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Billie Myers, of Jamaican/English descent, was kinetic,
climbing high on the stage rigging at one point, waving to the fans
in the bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   She opened the set by saying ``I'm so happy to be here at
Lilith.'' But when organizers told her she had to end her set after
three songs, she said ``this is bull (expletive)'' before launching
into a ferocious version of her hit Kiss the Rain.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the enchanting Lhasa sang in Spanish, backed only by
drums, guitar and accordion. Her voice, as rich as a cup of
Brazilian coffee, was exotic and intoxicating. It also led one
listener to gripe, ``Why is she singing in French?''
</P>
<P>
   That also pointed out the general slant of the event. Lhasa,
Myers and Badu may be used to shake up the mix a little bit, but
it's not clear the fans want to be shaken up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Erykah Badu kind of fit but not really,'' said Shelley
Goentzen, a Portland apartment manager. ``It has to be a certain
kind of music, more natural, more flowing, not like hip-hop bands.
I don't think that's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   What is it all about?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sarah,'' she said. ``That type of music. I don't want to see
every kind of music that's out there. How could you do that? A
little '70s, a little country, a little R&AMP;B _ it wouldn't work. You
need a focus.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who weren't completely enthralled by the songs, there
were plenty of booths in the Lilith Village to make the time go
faster. They ranged from the educational (Planned Parenthood) to
the usual (Lilith merchandise) to the oddball (www.excite.com).
</P>
<P>
   Tower Records erected a little shop that not only sold
merchandise from the featured acts but also basically from all
women in music. You could find artists who should be added to
Lilith (Canada's fine singer-songwriter Jann Arden) and those who
never will be (the late Sandy Denny). Throw in discs by the likes
of Doris Day, Ella Fitzger ald, Loretta Lynn and, yes, even the
Spice Girls, and it illustrated the diversity of women in music far
better than the Lilith Fair itself.
</P>
<P>
   When it all finally wrapped up, a fan exiting in a Lilith
T-shirt remarked, ``I could listen to them forever.'' After eight
hours under the unusually fierce sun, it felt like we had been
listening to them forever.
</P>
<P>
   Eight hours of any kind of music is pushing it. But a few less
heartfelt confessionals, a little more energy and some more diverse
sounds would make the day a little more memorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, if Jewel were here, that would have been so cool,'' said
Sarah Lindquist, a veteran of last year's festival. ``And that Ally
McBeal woman, she would have fit in perfectly. And Janet Jackson!
Oh, and that country woman, Shania whatever. And Madonna _ if she
would do something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's a Lilith Fair bill. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
