<HEADLINE>
DISABLED BOY TURNED AWAY FROM CHARTER SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHRYN CRENO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ If anyone needs a school that caters to the needs of
disabled kids, Onyx Teasley does.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the mother of the 8-year-old boy with acquired
immune deficiency syndrome concluded last spring, after he missed a
third of the school year because of health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Onyx is a very bright, inquisitive kid,'' Melissa Teasely
said. ``I want to keep him going, even in the face of death.''
</P>
<P>
   So in April, she decided to enroll her son in a 180-student
charter school near her home that had mailed out brochures touting
programs for children ``with special needs.''
</P>
<P>
   But the wheelchair Onyx frequently uses never got through the
front door of Children's Academy of Arizona's school at 1875 N.
Central Ave.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I wonder how many other kids like Onyx schools turn
away,'' Melissa Teasley said.
</P>
<P>
   The non-profit Arizona Center for Disability Law, which has
received about 200 complaints about charter schools' treatment of
disabled kids since last October, agreed to take on the case.
</P>
<P>
   To attorney Jerri Katzerman, the issue is clear cut:
</P>
<P>
   The suit she filed in U.S. District Court on Wednesday says Onyx
was turned away from Children's Academy because he has AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue isn't so clear in the minds of Children's Academy
director Reginald Barr, who is a former member of the state Board
of Education, or state Department of Education staffers.
</P>
<P>
   Barr vehemently denies that Onyx was not admitted to the school
because of his disease.
</P>
<P>
   Barr said his Central Avenue campus has a 60-child waiting list
and no elevator to haul a wheelchair to the second floor. He said
when Onyx was offered a space at a wheelchair accessible Children's
Academy site on west Camelback Road, his mother turned that down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally speaking, if a school receives federal funds, they
must provide access'' for the disabled, Arizona Department of
Education spokeswoman Patricia Likens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this particular case, we are investigating whether that
regulation pertains to the program or to the building itself. We
need to look into that before we have a clear answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Teasley said that during her initial visit, Barr's staff
said nothing about a waiting list. In fact, she said, the school
had a large ``Open Enrollment'' sign on the side of the building.
</P>
<P>
   She said one staffer told her ``We don't have the money'' when
she toured the Central Avenue site and pointed out that structural
changes would have to be made to accommodate her son's wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   Later on, she said, a staff member told her that teachers would
be unwilling to ``handle'' Onyx and that his presence might upset
parents of other children.
</P>
<P>
   She said she found the comment about the parents particularly
offensive because she and her son believe he has nothing to hide.
</P>
<P>
   Born with AIDS, Onyx was not expected to live past 2, Melissa
Teasley said.
</P>
<P>
   She said he is still alive because of special medications he has
received as a participant in a National Institutes of Health study
of children with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Onyx sometimes is in a wheelchair because he is too
weak to walk.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the last three years, he has attended Longview
Elementary in central Phoenix with a medical assistant who gives
him five different kinds of medicine and a continual supply of
water to prevent him from dehydrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be lacking in some areas but he more than makes up for
it in other ways,'' Melissa Teasley said.
</P>
<P>
   Onyx, for instance, has told classmates at Longview about his
disease during show-and-tell. He brought a toy ``doctors kit'' that
includes latex gloves, syringes minus the needles and other
equipment to demonstrate safety precautions health workers use when
they drawing blood and treating him in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kids were really surprised that I have AIDS,'' Onyx said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But some didn't think it was a very big deal. I told them that
when I get a cut, I tell someone right away and make sure I don't
touch anyone who also has a cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr denies that his staff would not welcome Onyx.
</P>
<P>
   But he does question whether federal law actually requires him
to remodel his Central Avenue school _ or simply teach Onyx and any
other children somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure this young boy receives the right kind of
care and I have no problem spending money to do that,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But do I need to shortchange other students by spending money
to remodel a school when I can accommodate him at another
facility?''
</P>
<P>
   Katzerman says the answer is simple. All public schools _
including charter schools _ must be 100 percent accessible to the
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Separate but equal is against the law,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if a grandparent of a child is in a wheelchair and wants
to visit the school? A public building must be accessible to the
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzerman said while her center also takes complaints about
special education issues in district schools, it has received about
200 calls about problems in Arizona's estimated 250 charter schools
since last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most frequent thing we hear is that parents of disabled
kids are discouraged from applying to charter schools,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are told that the schools probably aren't the best place
for their child,'' she said. ``They are told `You have become a
consumer _ is our school the best way you can spend your
educational dollar?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Lund, director of exceptional student services at the
Department of Education, agrees that many charter school operators
have had difficulty grasping that special education laws require
them to accommodate the needs of any student _ regardless of how
complex the child's problems.
</P>
<P>
   Her staff recently put together ``Charter Starter'' packets
explaining regulations that obligate all public schools to educate
disabled kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many, it's an eye opener,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The responsibilities are a lot more than they thought they
were getting into.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathryn Creno can be reached at 444-8056 or via the Internet at
education &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
