<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD CUT FEE FOR CROSS-BORDER CARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Business people and mayors of Arizona border towns are keeping
their fingers crossed that Congress will adopt more realistic fees
and deadlines for replacing 5.5 million Mexican border-crossing
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Some feared that many Mexicans cannot afford the $45 fee being
charged for the new ``laser visas'' and would stop crossing the
border to spend money.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they are applauding a proposed amendment to the law by Sen.
Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., and Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., that would waive the
fee for children under 15 and give the U.S. State Department an
extra four years to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been very apprehensive,'' said Fred Johnson, former
president of the Nogales-Santa Cruz Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the border towns depend on Mexican customers, and
that ``Everything we do to make it more difficult for the border
customer to come across has a serious impact on border economies.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress ordered the replacement of old, easily counterfeited
border-crossing cards in an effort to control illegal immigration,
but did not consider the unintended consequences, an aide to Kolbe
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The laser visa system was intended to encourage, not inhibit
legitimate and lawful cross-border commerce,'' Kolbe said. ``This
bill introduces a more realistic fee policy and timetable for the
transition to a new system.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, the State Department began replacing the outdated
documents with state-of-the-art ``laser visas'' that include an
individual's photograph, fingerprint and biographical data stored
with the use of compact disc technology.
</P>
<P>
   Congress had initially set an October 1999 deadline to complete
the switch, but State Department officials said the deadline was
impossible to meet.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Kyl-Kolbe plan, U.S. consulates in Mexico will have
until October 2003 to replace the old cards with laser visas.
</P>
<P>
   Among those cheering the proposed amendment is Ray Borane, mayor
of Douglas, who says his city relies on Mexican shoppers for 40
percent of its retail revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased with it,'' he said. ``Douglas and Agua
Prieta (Sonora) are really one bicultural community. We not only
depend on one another economically, but there are many social and
family ties on both sides . . . that would be stifled if people
couldn't come across.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix-based Border Trade Alliance, representing businesses
on both sides of the border, and Gov. Jane Hull have also been
seeking changes in the laser visa law.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's ``biggest concern is that those people who wanted to come
across legally and couldn't afford to replace their cards would
just not come across anymore,'' said Margie Emmermann, the
governor's policy adviser on Mexico. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
