<SLUG> BC-ATT-TCI-DEAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T,   TCI DEAL ALL ABOUT LINE ACCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The $48 billion merger of AT&AMP;T Corp. and
Tele-Communications Inc. creates a powerhouse communications
company that will put customers a click away from a vast array of
entertainment and information products, plus provide telephone
service around the world and around the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   When completed, the deal will give AT&AMP;T access to 13.5 million
subscribers across the nation that get television programming via
TCI and its affiliates. AT&AMP;T can use that cable network to provide
phone service and Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   A new subsidiary, AT&AMP;T Consumer Service, will market the product
lines, including TCI's cable service. AT&AMP;T said the new unit will
accelerate improvements to TCI's cable infrastructure and begin
offering digital telephone, video and data services to consumers by
the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Upgrading cable lines for two-way transmission of digital
signals should be completed by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The products, which could include up to 500 television channels,
will be offered under the AT&AMP;T brand name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers will pretty much get one-stop shopping for a wide
range of services. TCI has got a pretty substantial customer base
and they have already laid the groundwork for an existing cable
system to reach a lot more homes,'' said Timothy K. Horan, an
analyst at BancAmerica Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   TCI serves about 95,000 households in Los Angeles' San Fernando
Valley area and 26,000 in Ventura County. All told the company is
in roughly 400,000 Southern California homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   However, for consumers, change will come later rather than
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very early to speculate on what changes consumers will
see and in what order,'' said Ellen Zundl, an AT&AMP;T spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The deal weds the nation's top telecommunications company and
one of the biggest cable providers.
</P>
<P>
   It benefits AT&AMP;T because the company is able to circumvent local
phone lines and to gain a foothold in the local phone market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we're beginning to answer a big part of the question
about how we will provide local service to U.S. consumers,'' AT&AMP;T
Chairman C. Michael Armstrong told reporters in announcing the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is expected to be completed in the first half of
1999. Within three years, it will help the companies save about $2
billion annually through reduced costs, such as advertising,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   TCI benefits because AT&AMP;T has the cash to upgrade the cable
infrastructure more quickly than it could have done by itself.
</P>
<P>
   A critical component of the new unit's strategy is TCI's plan to
distribute about 10 million advance cable boxes over the next three
years. These devices will deliver hundreds of television channels
and Internet access. AT&AMP;T could then sell telephone services via
those cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   Prepping this kind of market will cost about $500 per home, but
the cost to consumers for connection and usage fees has not been
established.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest benefits for consumers would be speed. Cable
lines can carry information more than 1,000 times faster than
telephone companies' copper lines and 100 times faster than
integrated services digital networks, or ISDN, lines.
</P>
<P>
   A file that would take 5 minutes to download over a standard
computer-and-phone-line modem would take about one second via a
cable modem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be quite different than what people see today or
are expecting,'' said Berge Ayvazian, an industry analyst with the
Yankee Group, a Boston-based research firm. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
