<HEADLINE>
KNICKS TRADE OAKLEY FOR CAMBY ON DRAFT DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Updates and expands earlier story.)  (lb) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ On the night the National
Basketball Association held its draft, the New York Knicks severed
their decade-long relationship with Charles Oakley, considered the
heart and soul of the team, in a trade that will send him to the
Toronto Raptors for Marcus Camby, according to two Raptor team
officials.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Knicks gave their second pick in the draft, the
44th over all, and cash to the financially strapped Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley was noted for his aggressive rebounding and head-first
plays for loose balls since he arrived in 1988. He was offered to
the Raptors for a chance at a young shot-blocker and scorer like
the 6-foot-11-inch Camby.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 24-year-old Camby has been fragile in his first two
pro seasons, the Knicks are in need of a more active front-court
player than the 35-year old Oakley. This need was magnified when
they watched Indiana's Antonio Davis and Dale Davis block shots,
grab rebounds and put down dunks as they eliminated the Knicks in
the second-round of the playoffs this year.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley was attractive to the cash-strapped Raptors because he
has one year left on his deal, even though he is scheduled to make
$10 million in the balloon year of his contract next season. One
league official speculated that the Knicks could pay part of
Oakley's contract. Although the Raptors believe in Camby, they fear
losing him next summer when he is eligible to become a free agent.
Oakley might not fit in with the Raptors' high-flying style, but he
could be used for a future trade.
</P>
<P>
   With their first pick, No. 38 over all, the Knicks selected
DeMarco Johnson, a 6-8 forward from North Carolina-Charlotte. His
skill is hard to gauge because he has played fewer than 55 games in
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Olowokandi of Pacific University was selected at No. 1
by the Clippers in the National Basketball Association draft at GM
Place Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Vancouver Grizzlies took Mike Bibby, a 6-1 guard, with the
No. 2 pick and were said to be entertaining offers for him.
</P>
<P>
   Though neither the Knicks nor the Nets had one of the first 29
picks, the New York metropolitan area was represented in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   Al Harrington, the 6-9 phenom from St. Patrick's High School in
Elizabeth, N.J., was taken 25th by the Indiana Pacers. He was the
first high school player taken, ahead of Parade Magazine's national
player of the year, Rashard Griffin, who was not taken until the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   Felipe Lopez took a much more circuitous path. Lopez, whose
development at St. John's was always overshadowed by expectations
and hyperbole born out of his schoolboy legend days in Queens,
finally made it to the NBA Wednesday night. He was taken 24th by
the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Denver became one of several teams to pass on Kansas swingman
Paul Pierce, who fell to No. 10 into the laps of the Boston
Celtics. Instead, the Nuggets took his teammate, power forward Raef
LaFrentz at No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little disappointing,'' said Pierce, who averaged 20.4
points last season. ``I have to move on and use it as motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto Raptors selected North Carolina's Antawn Jamison
with the fourth pick and the Golden State Warriors chose his Tar
Heel teammate Vince Carter with the fifth pick. But the Raptors,
knowing the Warriors wanted Jamison all along, then traded Jamison
to Golden State for Carter plus cash.
</P>
<P>
   Robert ``Tractor'' Traylor, Michigan's trimmed-down, 6-7,
284-pound forward, was taken sixth by the Dallas Mavericks. Dallas
traded him to Milwaukee for the rights to Milwaukee's two
first-round picks: the German forward Dirk Nowitzki, chosen No. 9,
and Pat Garrity, picked at No. 19. Dallas then sent Garrity,
forward Martin Muursepp, Charles Wells and a 1999 draft pick to
Phoenix for point guard Steve Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Florida point guard Jason Williams was selected seventh by the
Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia took a 19-year-old, St. Louis shooting guard Larry
Hughes, with the eighth pick.
</P>
<P>
   Bonzi Wells went to the Detroit Pistons with the 11th pick,
giving them a scorer to replace the free agent Jerry Stackhouse.
Wells averaged 21.4 points and 7.3 rebounds in four years at Ball
State, breaking Ron Harper's school scoring record.
</P>
<P>
   While Pierce tumbling out of the top five was surprising,
nothing was more intriguing than who would go No. 1 and why,
leading up to the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby was projected as the first pick for the last month until
the Clippers' phone began ringing incessantly about Olowokandi, who
learned the game in relative obscurity the past three years at
little-known Pacific in Stockton, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby's agent, David Falk, was so confident his client would go
No. 1 that he had him work out only for the Clippers. But Falk
began to sweat on Tuesday, flying to Los Angeles to meet with the
Clippers' owner, Donald Sterling, with the notion of pleading
Bibby's case as No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   He was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to give my opinion, I think it would be because
Vancouver got a lot of offers from veteran teams who wanted to
trade up and get me, and they figured they could keep me and get
something better later on,'' Olowokandi said, reasoning why he was
taken No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Elgin Baylor said,'' he added of the Clipper general
manager, ``there is a lack of available centers in the league right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi is the second straight center and college senior to
be taken with the No. 1 overall pick, following Tim Duncan's
selection by San Antonio last season.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi, 23, averaged 22.2 points, 11.2 rebounds and 2.9
blocked shots as a senior with the Tigers, earning Big West
Conference player of the year honors.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi becomes the first player drafted from Pacific since
John Gianelli, who played on the Knicks' 1973 championship team,
was taken by the Houston Rockets in the second round of the 1972
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby, meanwhile, got a rousing ovation from the Vancouver fans
as he stepped to the podium. Asked how he felt to be drafted by a
team he never worked out for, he smiled and said, ``It makes me
feel wanted, at least.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Through trades, Orlando and Houston controlled the middle of the
draft. The Magic and Rockets had three picks apiece between Nos. 12
and 18. Orlando used its first two picks on big men: Utah's 6-11
Michael Doleac and Nevada Las-Vegas' Keon Clark.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, took small forward Michael Dickerson of Arizona at
No. 14 before Orlando made its third selection, forward Matt
Harpring of Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets also took shooting guard Bryce Drew of Valparaiso
with the 16th pick.
</P>
<P>
   With the 24th pick, the San Antonio Spurs selected Felipe Lopez,
the St. John's guard. Lopez was a highly-touted player coming out
of high school, but had a disappointing four years with the Red
Storm.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks do not have a first-round pick, and the New Jersey
Nets have no pick in either the first or second round. With the
38th and 44th picks in the second round, the Knicks were hoping to
move up and acquire a young frontline player or a point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first 24 picks, no high school player was chosen. Al
Harrington, the 6-9 center from St. Patrick's High School in
Elizabeth, N.J., was chosen at No. 25 by the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Parade Magazine's national player of the year, Rashard Lewis of
Alief Elsik High School in Alief, Texas, was taken by the Seattle
SuperSonics with the third pick in the second round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
