<SLUG> BC-NY-PSEUDO-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVE INTERNET PROGRAM DRAWS COMPLAINTS FROM NEIGHBORS, CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Josh Harris has made a name for himself in New York
City's Silicon Alley _ first by founding a new-media consulting
company, then by holding large parties in a SoHo loft that evoked
comparisons to Andy Warhol's Factory. Most recently, he's known for
producing video programming for the Internet through a company
called Pseudo Programs.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who said he employs 45 people and provides an outlet for
independent producers, would like the city to offer incentives for
start-up Internet ventures like his. Instead, he said, he has been
awakened in the middle of the night by gun-toting fire marshals in
bulletproof vests over complaints, mostly from neighbors, that he
stages his Internet programming in front of live audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole tone and tenor of them showing up that way is to
intimidate us from holding the events,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   As city fire officials see it, however, Harris is violating fire
codes required of social clubs and other places where more than 75
people congregate.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving 11 complaints about Pseudo Programs, the Fire
Department's Social Club Task Force inspected its studio six times
and ultimately issued a summons against Harris in January for
failing to provide lighted exit signs, maintain his sprinkler
system and meet other fire codes, said Louis F. Garcia, the chief
of fire investigations. He added that fire marshals are required by
law to wear bulletproof vests and carry firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he's being persecuted,'' the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the summons, Harris faces a $10,000 fine or six months in
jail or both. Harris said he had already spent $50,000 to bring his
studio up to code. A hearing is set for July 28.
</P>
<P>
   Pseudo Programs was established in May 1994 as a content
provider for the Internet service Prodigy. At the same time, Harris
said, he began throwing huge parties, often attracting as many as
2,000 performance artists, musicians and other creative people.
</P>
<P>
   From these events, Harris said, he developed the contacts and
ideas for the niche programming that the company began producing
about a year ago. Today, Pseudo offers 45 one-hour programs a week
on subjects from hip-hop music to skateboarding.
</P>
<P>
   But Pseudo has also annoyed some neighbors by regularly inviting
what Harris describes as 75 ``movers and shakers in the hip-hop
business'' to his Wednesday night Webcast.
</P>
<P>
   As he acknowledges, some of his guests hang around afterward in
front of a Pottery Barn store at street level and occasionally
leave graffiti behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our storefront is covered with graffiti,'' said Susanna
Somogyi, a manager of the Pottery Barn in SoHo. She said that a few
times _ most recently, last week _ people believed to be guests of
Pseudo have also tried to break into the store.
</P>
<P>
   Both Harris and his lawyer, John Johnson, said they felt that
Pseudo was targeted by the city's Multi-Agency Nightclub
Enforcement Task Force, formed in 1996 to address noise and illegal
activities at bars and nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   But Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's office said that the nightclub
task force had not been involved in the case against Pseudo. The
social club task force, which sometimes participates in
investigations by the nightclub task force, operates independently
under the Fire Department. It was formed after a 1990 fire killed
87 people at the Happy Land Social Club in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said that an Internet company with a live studio audience
has the same obligation to conform to fire codes as, say, David
Letterman does with his ``Late Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to wind up with another fire in another
unprotected location and wind up with a lot of people dead,''
Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson said that since Pseudo did not have the resources of
CBS, the city should help the company meet the fire codes. ``My big
bone of contention with the city is that they should tell them what
they need to get done and try to help them with interim measures so
they could still operate and be within the law,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
