<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSEUM-FLOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURST PIPE FLOODS MODERN ART MUSEUM'S SUB-BASEMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By DAVID ROHDE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A burst water main in midtown Manhattan flooded the
sub-basement of the Museum of Modern Art Wednesday, endangering two
dozen crates of artwork awaiting shipment, museum officials said.
No art was damaged because the crates were stored 6 to 10 inches
off the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Two to three inches of water filled the building's sub-basement,
which is not open to the public, after a truck ran over a six-inch
water main supplying a midtown Manhattan hydrant, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our conservators immediately evacuated everything that was
down there and double-checked to make sure everything did not get
wet,'' Glenn Lowry, the museum's director, said. ``The range of
objects that were down there did not include anything of
extraordinary importance.'' He said that he could not name the
specific works, but that the sub-basement was generally used only
for less valuable items.
</P>
<P>
   But Lowry, citing fears of another such break, said the museum
would study whether to build a protective wall _ he called it a box
within a box _ to seal off its basement from future water main
breaks. ``We've been here since 1929 and to the best of my
knowledge this has never happened before,'' he said. ``After this,
we're increasingly aware of how fragile and vulnerable we are to
these kind of crises.''
</P>
<P>
   The rupturing of the pipe on West 53rd Street between Fifth and
Sixth avenues was the third highly publicized water main break in
the city this year. In January, a 48-inch water main burst,
creating a huge, car-swallowing sinkhole and a flame of natural gas
two stories high on Fifth Avenue. In March, a sprinkler line burst,
nearly drowning a 22-year-old woman and her terrier trapped in
their Upper East Side apartment building elevator.
</P>
<P>
   But city officials say that despite appearances, manmade deluges
are not growing more common. Charles Sturcken, chief of staff in
the Department of Environmental Protection, said that a recent
analysis by the department found that the number of water main
breaks in New York has remained the same since the 1970s, about 550
a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average has not increased,'' he said. ``The vast majority
are small breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowry said that employees working in a nearby brownstone, which
had been converted into an office by the museum, heard the sound of
running water coming from the basement just before 1 p.m. An
employee opened a storage room door to find a funnel of water
pouring out of the wall. ``Imagine a fire hydrant with a valve
open,'' Lowry said.
</P>
<P>
   The basement of that brownstone, at 41 W. 53rd St., eventually
filled with 10 feet of water, Fire Department officials said. Water
then flooded the basements of two adjoining brownstones to the
east, at 37 and 39 W. 53rd. Finally, water burst through the wall
of a stairwell leading to the museum building's sub-basement, its
lowest level, at 11 W. 53rd St., and flowed downstairs to where the
crated artwork was stored.
</P>
<P>
   Sturcken said local residents told city officials that a truck
had run over the hydrant two weeks ago. Another truck ran over what
was left of the hydrant Wednesday, ramming a protruding section of
pipe into the ground and causing the pipe below the street to burst
from the pressure. City officials said they had no record of
anyone's having previously reported the initial hydrant damage to
city agencies.
</P>
<P>
   As the fire trucks left Wednesday, Lowry tried to be
philosophical about the flood. ``These are the kinds of things that
an old system is going to suffer,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
