u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STADIUM-VOTE-545&AMP;A     06-24 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STADIUM-VOTE-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFIANCE REIGNS AS COUNCIL KEEPS SWINGING AT MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By MIKE ALLEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a new act in a streak of defiance that began last
week, the City Council stiff-armed Mayor Rudolph Giuliani three
times Wednesday and used its harshest oratory for a measure giving
voters a say in the future of Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Council members invoked the Boston Tea Party as they voted 39-7
to authorize a referendum in November intended to prevent the use
of city money to help the New York Yankees move from the Bronx to
Manhattan. ``We're talking about the Bronx Bombers _ not the West
Side Wallopers,'' said City Councilman Gifford Miller, D-Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The vote sets up a likely court fight with the mayor, who has
extolled the advantages of a Manhattan stadium and has vowed to
knock the council's measure off the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   In two other jabs at Giuliani, the council added so many
conditions to a bill making the Department of Homeless Services a
separate city agency that the mayor said he would veto it, and it
also refused to start work on the mayor's bill to deny contracting
licenses to companies with ties to organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the council's decisions amounted to another tear
in the quickly fraying relationship between the Republican mayor
and the Democratic-dominated council. Last week, in a vote also
influenced by the debate over Yankee Stadium, the council overrode
his vetoes of items for next year's budget, prompting a vow by the
mayor to block spending.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the friction, the two sides agreed Wednesday on a
bill, championed as historic by gay-rights groups, to give domestic
partners the same rights as married couples under city law. The
bill means that domestic partners, if they register with the city,
will receive the same benefits as spouses in future contracts with
unions of city workers.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also grants domestic partners visitation rights in
city hospitals and succession rights to rent-controlled apartments.
It also give bereavement leave to city employees who register as
domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was proposed by Giuliani despite the risk to his
prospects for national advancement in a party where conservatives
control most nominations. The council gallery was packed with
gay-rights advocates, who hissed when opponents spoke. Brendan Fay,
a leader of a group of gay and lesbian Catholics, called the
measure ``a tiny step for our community, but a gigantic leap for
our conservative mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Margarita Lopez, a Democrat from Manhattan who is
one of three openly gay and lesbian members of the council, flew
the rainbow-striped gay flag from her microphone on the floor of
the council chamber. In arguing for the bill, she read words of
Thomas Jefferson that are painted on the ceiling, promising ``equal
and exact justice to all men of whatever state or persuasion.''
</P>
<P>
   The stadium measure produced a more raucous debate, with some
council members sporting Yankee lapel pins or baseball caps. ``This
bill,'' said Councilwoman Mary Pinkett, a Brooklyn Democrat,
``assures the right of the people of New York City to carry on the
legacy that began with the throwing of the tea over the side of the
ship _ that no one could create for them a country in which they
could not have a voice.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The council speaker, Peter Vallone, said a vote could prevent
``a billion-dollar rip-off'' resulting from ``secret negotiations
that are going on just between a few people.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Randy Mastro said the mayor would veto the
referendum bill, which he called ``a hollow political gesture''
that will never appear on the ballot because a referendum favored
by the mayor _ proposed revisions to the City Charter _ would
supersede it under city law. Mastro said the stadium referendum
exists only to enhance the political fortunes of Vallone, who is
running for governor.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Vallone vowed to go to court to ensure that his
proposal makes the ballot. He said his ground for a lawsuit would
be that the charter revisions were being proposed only to block a
vote on the Yankees. ``It's contrary to the purposes of the
charter,'' he said. ``It's a sham.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Rubenstein, the spokesman for the team's principal owner,
George Steinbrenner III, said a referendum would be ``very
disruptive'' as he decides among three options: staying in the
Bronx, or moving to the West Side of Manhattan or New Jersey. He
has said he will not pick until after this season.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was also upset over the council's handling of a bill
that would make the Department of Homeless Services an independent
agency. Although he favored the concept, he did not approve of all
the conditions the council added before passing it, 41-6. Giuliani
had said earlier in the day that he expected to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they tried to do is load it down with so many terms,
conditions and burdens that they would have destroyed it,'' the
mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   The conditions included adding beds and cribs to a center in the
Bronx where families apply for emergency shelter; limiting the
number of beds in new adult shelters to 200, and requiring the
submission of sanitation, health and fire protection records to the
council.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's veto would essentially dissolve the agency on June
30, and homeless services would once again be managed by the city's
Human Resources Administration. Vallone has vowed that the council
will override the veto. But both sides have indicated they are
willing to compromise to save the agency, which has been held up as
a national model for improving services to homeless single adults
and families in the shelters.
</P>
<P>
   The council and the mayor's office also clashed over the future
of legislation that would give the city the power to impose
stricter regulations on whether certain companies are fit to work
on public or private construction projects in the city. In an
effort to get organized crime out of the construction industry,
Giuliani is pressing for legislation that would deny licenses to
contractors if they were found to ``lack good character, honesty
and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office had asked the council to introduce the
legislation at Wednesday's meeting, the first step in a series of
hearings and votes that lead to a bill's becoming law. But council
officials said the mayor's office submitted the legislation too
late. Council rules say legislation must be submitted to the
council by 1 p.m. on Friday to be introduced at a meeting the next
Wednesday. The mayor's bill did not arrive until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's above the law,'' said Bruce Bender, Vallone's chief
of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Mastro said that in the past, the council has routinely
introduced bills that had been submitted on Mondays. He added,
``Score one for organized crime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
