<SLUG> BC-RAC-GOLDCUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVER CHARM OUT OF GOLD CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Silver Charm, the heartbreak colt, is out of
Sunday's Hollywood Gold Cup, leaving Hollywood Park with the
notable matchup of Skip Away and Gentlemen but not the ``Race of
the Decade'' it advertised.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm was withdrawn Wednesday morning after trainer Bob
Baffert reported he developed a temperature of 102 degrees, one or
two degrees above normal for a thoroughbred. After a blood test
later in the day, the 1997 Kentucky Derby winner seemed to be
fighting a virus, Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got something there, so we can't afford to take a
chance,'' Baffert said. ``If I ran him and he got pneumonia or
something like that, I couldn't live with myself.''
</P>
<P>
   It's reminiscent of the Santa Anita Handicap in March. Silver
Charm was scratched the day before that race after returning from a
gallop with a bruised foot, leaving Santa Anita with thousands of
T-shirts ballyhooing his ``Showdown'' with Gentlemen. Capping a
beautiful week in the racetrack marketing world, Gentlemen bled
internally during the race and finished last at 1-20 odds.
</P>
<P>
   Since Silver Charm recovered quickly to win the $4 million Dubai
World Cup three weeks later, cynics charged that the foot bruise
was trumped up because the colt's handlers never wanted to run in
Santa Anita's little $1 million affair.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood Park general manager Eual Wyatt Jr., asked Wednesday
if he was suspicious of Silver Charm's latest withdrawal, answered
with an emphatic, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm owner Bob Lewis said it was simply a matter of
protecting the health of the popular gray horse who came within
half a length of sweeping the 1997 Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a great day Sunday anyway,'' Lewis said.
``It's just unfortunate we won't be able to come to the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert speculated that the illness is the result of the stress
of Silver Charm's second-place finish to Awesome Again in the
Stephen Foster Handicap at Churchill Downs on June 13 and the
flight home. Because he had raced so recently, it had been a
surprise when Baffert announced last week that Silver Charm would
try the Gold Cup, for which entries will be taken this morning.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm performed well in a 5-furlong workout Tuesday at
Santa Anita, recording a :58 3/5 clocking, fastest of the morning.
Baffert said his staff takes the temperatures of all the horses in
the barn each morning, and first thing on Wednesday Silver Charm
was normal.
</P>
<P>
   But Baffert said he didn't attack the feed tub as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``(His groom) said he went to the corner and just put his head
down,'' the trainer said. ``We took his temperature again, and he
had a fever of 102. We brought every thermometer in the barn to
take his temperature, and they all had the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The $1 million Gold Cup would have marked 4-year-old Silver
Charm's first meeting with 6-year-old Gentlemen, the top handicap
horse in California for more than a year, or with 5-year-old Skip
Away, the nation's champion older horse of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Gold Cup features a rematch of the other two
horses, who met in the '97 Pimlico Special, Gentlemen holding off
Skip Away by half a length. Each ran one of his sharpest races at
Hollywood Park _ Gentlemen winning the '97 Gold Cup by four lengths
to lead a 1-2-3 sweep by trainer Richard Mandella, and Skip Away
winning by six lengths in the '97 Breeders' Cup Classic.
</P>
<P>
   With Silver Charm's departure, jockey Gary Stevens is free to
jump back to Gentlemen, knocking Corey Nakatani out of the saddle.
The horses and riders expected to be entered: Gentlemen, Skip Away
(Jerry Bailey), Puerto Madero (Kent Desormeaux), Budroyale (Matt
Garcia), Bagshot (Alex Solis) and Don't Blame Rio. Listed as
``possible'' are Mud Route (Chris McCarron) and Anet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
