<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCAA-MOVES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10, BIG TEN AIM TO ALTER NCAA RULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two top Division I-A conferences want changes in the NCAA's
governance structure, which is less than a year old.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific-10 Conference is sponsoring legislation to change
the membership makeup of NCAA committees. And Big Ten Conference
commissioner Jim Delany has circulated memos expressing his
league's displeasure with the setup.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of Delany's memos to Division I-A commissioners said,
`This isn't the house we built and we're not happy living in it,'
'' said a source who had seen a copy of the memo.
</P>
<P>
   The discord centers on a power struggle. Division I-A schools
want more control and input on legislation that affects them. And
the most powerful conferences aren't shy about flexing their
political muscle to gain support on the committee issue.
</P>
<P>
   The bowl championship series agreed last year to distribute
money to I-AA schools, and Division I-A pushed for legislation that
would allow games with I-AA schools to count toward I-A teams
becoming bowl-eligible. Division I-A leaders could be waiting to
cash in, quid pro quo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's something that will be mentioned,'' Pacific-10
Conference commissioner Tom Hansen said. ``There's a political
aspect to all of this. That rule about I-AA games counting toward
bowl eligibility, that could go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Division I-A comprises schools with major football programs;
I-AA is made up of schools with midmajor football programs. I-AAA
comprises Division I schools that don't play football.
</P>
<P>
   Although there appears to be a rift in Division I pitting I-A
against I-AA and I-AAA schools, there is also discord in Division
I-A.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 is sponsoring legislation that would move conference
championship games from the first Saturday in December to the last
Saturday of November.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeastern Conference, which staged the first conference
title game in 1992 and is one of four conferences with a
championship game, has expressed displeasure with the proposal and
asked the Pac-10 to withdraw it.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10's legislative proposal on committee membership could
lead to a full vote of Division I members. However, a subcommittee
is looking at a compromise that would not require a vote of all
Division I members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that our peers should be involved in selecting the
teams in basketball and baseball, and we should be judged by our
peers on the infractions committees,'' Hansen said. ``We tried to
reach a compromise, but we've come to an impasse.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA's revised structure took effect in August and was
designed to streamline the legislative process. In Division I, a
board of directors (presidents) oversees a management council
(athletic directors and faculty representatives), which oversees
four cabinet and eight committees.
</P>
<P>
   The new structure calls for no division to have a majority on
committees. For example, on committees such as men's basketball and
baseball, four of the nine members can be from Division I-A
conferences. (On the board of directors and the management council,
however, Division I-A has majority representation).
</P>
<P>
   In April, the Big Ten sought a waiver that would permit Michigan
State to play in the Black Coaches Association preseason football
game in August. Rules prohibit more than one team from a conference
playing in a preseason game in one season, and Purdue is to play in
the Pigskin Classic on Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Although the board of directors approved the waiver that allowed
Michigan State to play Colorado State on Aug. 29, Delany was irked
by the management council's original decision that upheld the rule.
Delany believed that I-AA and I-AAA should not have voted on this
issue. (Division I-A representatives from the Pac-10 and Conference
USA voted against the Big Ten request).
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee issue is one that Division I-A cares about,''
said Big South Conference commissioner Kyle Kallander, whose league
is made up of I-AA and I-AAA schools. ``I think there needs to be
some fine-tuning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't categorize it as class or division warfare. I
believe there's room for compromise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-98 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
