</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LIVOTI-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTION: OFFICERS PLANNED TO LIE TO PROTECT ACCUSED COLLEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Arguing that police officers tried to cover up a
colleague's role in the 1994 choking death of a Bronx man, a
prosecutor said Wednesday that the officers had prepared an
elaborate lie to place the blame on a fictitious black man who
disappeared from the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Mark Pomerantz, speaking out of the jury's presence,
told a federal judge in Manhattan that Officer Daisy Boria was
prepared to testify that ``in the formative stages, the story was
going to be a mysterious stranger with black hands choked'' the
victim, Anthony Baez.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Shira Scheindlin refused to allow that testimony into
the trial of Francis Livoti. She did not explain why she considered
it inadmissible.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office declined to comment
on the judge's action, but Livoti's lawyer, Stuart London, said of
Boria's planned testimony: ``It was hearsay that was neither
reliable nor trustworthy.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution had told the judge that Boria was told of the
cover story by her partner, who was at the scene with her that
night.
</P>
<P>
   Scheindlin did allow other testimony by Boria about what
Pomerantz said was ``in the nature of a police cover-up.`` Boria
testified that she declined an invitation to meet with other
officers to discuss the case.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Livoti was acquitted of state charges of criminally
negligent homicide in the death of Baez on Dec. 22, 1994. He was
later dismissed by the police force.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation between Livoti and Baez was sparked by a
late-night touch football game outside the Baez family home in the
Bronx in which a football hit police cruisers.
</P>
<P>
   Livoti's acquittal led to street protests in the Bronx and
further fueled the debate about how the police treat minorities in
New York. Baez was Hispanic and Livoti is white.
</P>
<P>
   With both sides resting their cases in the week-old federal case
Wednesday, Judge Scheindlin told the jurors that closing arguments
would begin Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   In another case stemming from Baez's death, a judge in the Bronx
unsealed additional parts of a deposition Wednesday in a wrongful
death lawsuit filed by the Baez family against the Police
Department. The newly released parts show that Louis Anemone, now
chief of department, rejected a 1991 recommendation _ three years
before Baez's death _ to transfer Livoti because of the number of
police brutality complaints against him.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation was made by Livoti's commander at the time,
William Casey, now a deputy chief, who said in the deposition that
there were 12 civilian complaints against Livoti by 1991, of which
nine alleged excessive force.
</P>
<P>
   A police official, speaking on the condition of anonymity on
Tuesday night, said that Anemone had rejected the transfer because
the complaints against Livoti were unsubstantiated. Continuing to
demand anonymity last night, the same police official broadened
those reasons, saying that Anemone also countermanded the transfer
because of Livoti's status as a union delegate.
</P>
<P>
   A police spokesman, Deputy Inspector Michael Collins, reiterated
Wednesday night that the department would have no comment on the
trial or the pending civil suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
